(function(){const unit5Selections={"selections":[{"selection_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth","grade":4,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":5,"week":1,"title":"Planet Earth","author":"Christine Taylor-Butler","genre":"Informational Text","essential_question":"How do Earth\u0027s systems shape the planet?","weekly_question":"What makes Earth able to sustain life?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["molten","mantle","crust","tectonic plates","atmosphere"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Planet Earth. What makes Earth able to sustain life?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027molten\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options: A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027molten\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q002","read_aloud":"How many main layers is Earth made of? Options: A. Two, B. Three, C. Four, D. Five","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\"","stem":"How many main layers is Earth made of? Options:","choices":{"A":"Two,","B":"Three,","C":"Four,","D":"Five"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that our planet is composed of four main layers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What are the sections of Earth\u0027s crust called? Options: A. Mantles, B. Cores, C. Tectonic plates, D. Oceans","excerpt":"\"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\"","stem":"What are the sections of Earth\u0027s crust called? Options:","choices":{"A":"Mantles,","B":"Cores,","C":"Tectonic plates,","D":"Oceans"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text identifies the sections of the crust and upper mantle as tectonic plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q004","read_aloud":"What is the name of Earth\u0027s outer surface? Options: A. Inner core, B. Mantle, C. Atmosphere, D. Crust","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust.\"","stem":"What is the name of Earth\u0027s outer surface? Options:","choices":{"A":"Inner core,","B":"Mantle,","C":"Atmosphere,","D":"Crust"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Paragraph 1 states that the outer surface of the planet is called the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q005","read_aloud":"What circles overhead and is made of gases? Options: A. The atmosphere, B. The inner core, C. The ocean, D. A tectonic plate","excerpt":"\"Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere. Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life.\"","stem":"What circles overhead and is made of gases? Options:","choices":{"A":"The atmosphere,","B":"The inner core,","C":"The ocean,","D":"A tectonic plate"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that the atmosphere is the layer of gases circling Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere. Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"mantle\" mean in this sentence? A. the outer surface of Earth B. the layer of Earth between the crust and the core C. the innermost part of Earth D. the air around Earth","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\"","stem":"What does \"mantle\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"the outer surface of Earth","B":"the layer of Earth between the crust and the core","C":"the innermost part of Earth","D":"the air around Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists Earth\u0027s layers: crust, mantle, outer core, and inner core. The mantle is between the crust and the core.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is this section mostly about? A. how to dig into Earth B. the different layers that make up Earth C. why Earth is the only planet with water D. how animals live on Earth","excerpt":"\"Above and Below. Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core. Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere.\"","stem":"What is this section mostly about?","choices":{"A":"how to dig into Earth","B":"the different layers that make up Earth","C":"why Earth is the only planet with water","D":"how animals live on Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The section describes Earth\u0027s layers below the surface and the atmosphere above. It gives an overview of how Earth is structured.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Above and Below. Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core. Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What makes Earth special compared to other planets? A. It has the most moons. B. It is the biggest planet. C. It has water as solid, liquid, and gas at its surface. D. It has no atmosphere.","excerpt":"\"Earth is the only planet in our solar system where water exists as a solid, liquid, and gas at its surface.\"","stem":"What makes Earth special compared to other planets?","choices":{"A":"It has the most moons.","B":"It is the biggest planet.","C":"It has water as solid, liquid, and gas at its surface.","D":"It has no atmosphere."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly states that Earth is the only planet in our solar system where water exists as a solid, liquid, and gas at its surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth is the only planet in our solar system where water exists as a solid, liquid, and gas at its surface.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What are tectonic plates? A. pieces of Earth\u0027s crust and upper mantle B. types of ocean waves C. tools used by scientists D. parts of the atmosphere","excerpt":"\"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates.\"","stem":"What are tectonic plates?","choices":{"A":"pieces of Earth\u0027s crust and upper mantle","B":"types of ocean waves","C":"tools used by scientists","D":"parts of the atmosphere"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text tells us that tectonic plates are sections of Earth\u0027s crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why are Earth\u0027s layers important? A. They help Earth support life. B. They make Earth look pretty. C. They keep Earth far from the sun. D. They block all the water.","excerpt":"\"Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life. For example, plants and animals depend on liquid water on Earth\u0027s surface to drink.\"","stem":"Why are Earth\u0027s layers important?","choices":{"A":"They help Earth support life.","B":"They make Earth look pretty.","C":"They keep Earth far from the sun.","D":"They block all the water."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says each layer helps Earth sustain life. Plants and animals need water on the surface, which is part of Earth\u0027s structure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life. For example, plants and animals depend on liquid water on Earth\u0027s surface to drink.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does the word \"mantle\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. the layer of Earth between the crust and the core B. a type of rock found on the surface C. the hottest part of Earth\u0027s center D. the air that surrounds our planet","excerpt":"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.","stem":"What does the word \"mantle\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"the layer of Earth between the crust and the core","B":"a type of rock found on the surface","C":"the hottest part of Earth\u0027s center","D":"the air that surrounds our planet"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mantle means the layer of Earth between the crust and the core. The text lists it as one of Earth\u0027s main layers beneath the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this sentence? A. Feathers are a natural part of birds B. Birds need trees to live C. The sky is full of stars D. Leaves grow on trees","excerpt":"Birds and feathers go together, like trees and leaves, like stars and the sky.","stem":"What is the main idea of this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Feathers are a natural part of birds","B":"Birds need trees to live","C":"The sky is full of stars","D":"Leaves grow on trees"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The comparison shows that feathers belong to birds just as leaves belong to trees, emphasizing that feathers are naturally part of birds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Birds and feathers go together, like trees and leaves, like stars and the sky."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What does this sentence tell us about feathers? A. Only birds have feathers B. All animals have feathers C. Feathers are found on mammals D. Feathers help birds fly","excerpt":"All birds have feathers, but no other animals do.","stem":"What does this sentence tell us about feathers?","choices":{"A":"Only birds have feathers","B":"All animals have feathers","C":"Feathers are found on mammals","D":"Feathers help birds fly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states that all birds have feathers and no other animals do, meaning only birds have feathers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: All birds have feathers, but no other animals do."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q014","read_aloud":"Why do birds have different kinds of feathers? A. Feathers do different jobs for birds B. All feathers look the same C. Birds only need one type of feather D. Feathers are only for flying","excerpt":"Most birds have thousands of feathers, but those feathers aren\u0027t all the same. That\u0027s because feathers have so many different jobs to do.","stem":"Why do birds have different kinds of feathers?","choices":{"A":"Feathers do different jobs for birds","B":"All feathers look the same","C":"Birds only need one type of feather","D":"Feathers are only for flying"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that feathers have many different jobs to do, which is why birds have different kinds of feathers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most birds have thousands of feathers, but those feathers aren\u0027t all the same. That\u0027s because feathers have so many different jobs to do."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q015","read_aloud":"How do feathers help a blue jay stay warm? A. They trap warm air near the bird\u0027s skin B. They make the bird fly faster C. They help the bird find food D. They make the bird look bigger","excerpt":"On cold, damp days a blue jay stays warm by fluffing up its feathers and trapping a layer of warm air next to its skin.","stem":"How do feathers help a blue jay stay warm?","choices":{"A":"They trap warm air near the bird\u0027s skin","B":"They make the bird fly faster","C":"They help the bird find food","D":"They make the bird look bigger"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that fluffing feathers traps warm air next to the skin, which helps the blue jay stay warm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: On cold, damp days a blue jay stays warm by fluffing up its feathers and trapping a layer of warm air next to its skin."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What is the layer of gases that circles Earth called? A. The core B. The mantle C. The atmosphere D. The crust","excerpt":"\"Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere. Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life.\"","stem":"What is the layer of gases that circles Earth called?","choices":{"A":"The core","B":"The mantle","C":"The atmosphere","D":"The crust"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere. Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What was the single landmass called that scientists believe once held all the continents together? A. Pangaea B. Eurasia C. Gondwana D. Atlantis","excerpt":"\"Tectonic plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving. Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea.\"","stem":"What was the single landmass called that scientists believe once held all the continents together?","choices":{"A":"Pangaea","B":"Eurasia","C":"Gondwana","D":"Atlantis"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says \"a single landmass called Pangaea.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tectonic plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving. Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What caused Pangaea to break apart? A. Earthquakes under the ocean B. The shifting of tectonic plates C. Volcanoes erupting D. The sun\u0027s heat","excerpt":"\"Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted. This caused Pangaea to break into sections. The sections drifted apart and formed the continents we know today.\"","stem":"What caused Pangaea to break apart?","choices":{"A":"Earthquakes under the ocean","B":"The shifting of tectonic plates","C":"Volcanoes erupting","D":"The sun\u0027s heat"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says tectonic plates shifted and caused Pangaea to break.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted. This caused Pangaea to break into sections. The sections drifted apart and formed the continents we know today.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What is the mantle? A. The outer layer of Earth B. The layer between the crust and the core C. The center of the Earth D. The layer of gases around Earth","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that is the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\"","stem":"What is the mantle?","choices":{"A":"The outer layer of Earth","B":"The layer between the crust and the core","C":"The center of the Earth","D":"The layer of gases around Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists the layers as crust, mantle, outer core, and inner core. The mantle is below the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that is the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q020","read_aloud":"What can tectonic plates create? A. New oceans B. Mountain ranges C. The moon D. The atmosphere","excerpt":"\"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\"","stem":"What can tectonic plates create?","choices":{"A":"New oceans","B":"Mountain ranges","C":"The moon","D":"The atmosphere"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that the pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What happens to liquid water when the sun heats it? A. It freezes into ice. B. It turns into a gas called water vapor. C. It sinks into the soil. D. It becomes part of the core.","excerpt":"\"Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere.\"","stem":"What happens to liquid water when the sun heats it?","choices":{"A":"It freezes into ice.","B":"It turns into a gas called water vapor.","C":"It sinks into the soil.","D":"It becomes part of the core."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that liquid water turns into a gas called water vapor when heated by the sun.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What is the outer core mostly made of? A. Water and air B. Rocks and soil C. Iron and nickel D. Lava and magma","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s core has two layers. The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick.\"","stem":"What is the outer core mostly made of?","choices":{"A":"Water and air","B":"Rocks and soil","C":"Iron and nickel","D":"Lava and magma"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly says the outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s core has two layers. The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q023","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \u0027abundant\u0027? Options:? A. Rare, B. Plentiful, C. Small, D. Hidden","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \u0027abundant\u0027? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Rare,","B":"Plentiful,","C":"Small,","D":"Hidden"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abundant means there is a lot of something, or it is plentiful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q024","read_aloud":"What happens to water after it falls to the ground? Options:? A. It disappears forever, B. It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil, C. It turns into solid rock, D. It stops moving","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. ... It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil. Then it starts the process over again.\"","stem":"What happens to water after it falls to the ground? Options:?","choices":{"A":"It disappears forever,","B":"It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil,","C":"It turns into solid rock,","D":"It stops moving"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says water collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil before starting the cycle again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. ... It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil. Then it starts the process over again.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What is the outer core mostly made of? Options:? A. Water and air, B. Rock and dirt, C. Iron and nickel, D. Gold and silver","excerpt":"\"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\"","stem":"What is the outer core mostly made of? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Water and air,","B":"Rock and dirt,","C":"Iron and nickel,","D":"Gold and silver"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text specifically identifies iron and nickel as the materials that make up the outer core.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q001","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \u0027abundant\u0027? Options: A. Rare, B. Plentiful, C. Small, D. Hidden","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \u0027abundant\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"Rare,","B":"Plentiful,","C":"Small,","D":"Hidden"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abundant means there is a lot of something, or it is plentiful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What happens to water after it falls to the ground? Options: A. It disappears forever, B. It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil, C. It turns into solid rock, D. It stops moving","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. ... It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil. Then it starts the process over again.\"","stem":"What happens to water after it falls to the ground? Options:","choices":{"A":"It disappears forever,","B":"It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil,","C":"It turns into solid rock,","D":"It stops moving"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says water collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil before starting the cycle again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. ... It collects in bodies of water or soaks into the soil. Then it starts the process over again.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What is the outer core mostly made of? Options: A. Water and air, B. Rock and dirt, C. Iron and nickel, D. Gold and silver","excerpt":"\"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\"","stem":"What is the outer core mostly made of? Options:","choices":{"A":"Water and air,","B":"Rock and dirt,","C":"Iron and nickel,","D":"Gold and silver"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text specifically identifies iron and nickel as the materials that make up the outer core.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q004","read_aloud":"What kind of material is the inner core? Options: A. Liquid water, B. Gas, C. Solid iron, D. Moving plates","excerpt":"\"The inner core is solid iron. It may spin faster than Earth\u0027s other layers.\"","stem":"What kind of material is the inner core? Options:","choices":{"A":"Liquid water,","B":"Gas,","C":"Solid iron,","D":"Moving plates"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Paragraph 8 clearly states that the inner core is solid iron.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The inner core is solid iron. It may spin faster than Earth\u0027s other layers.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What does \"circulates\" mean in this sentence? A. stays in one place B. moves through a system C. disappears forever D. turns into rock","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.\"","stem":"What does \"circulates\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"stays in one place","B":"moves through a system","C":"disappears forever","D":"turns into rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows water moving through a cycle: heating, turning to gas, rising, forming clouds, and falling back. \"Circulates\" means moving through a system.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What happens first in the water cycle? A. Water falls as rain. B. Water is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. C. Water gathers into clouds. D. Water soaks into the soil.","excerpt":"\"Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere. It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation.\"","stem":"What happens first in the water cycle?","choices":{"A":"Water falls as rain.","B":"Water is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.","C":"Water gathers into clouds.","D":"Water soaks into the soil."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes the water cycle step by step. First, liquid water is heated by the sun and turns into a gas called water vapor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere. It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What can happen when tectonic plates move? A. The sun gets hotter. B. An earthquake can occur. C. Plants stop growing. D. The atmosphere disappears.","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans.\"","stem":"What can happen when tectonic plates move?","choices":{"A":"The sun gets hotter.","B":"An earthquake can occur.","C":"Plants stop growing.","D":"The atmosphere disappears."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that when tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What was Pangaea? A. a type of animal B. a single landmass with all continents joined together C. a tool for studying Earth D. a layer of the atmosphere","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted.\"","stem":"What was Pangaea?","choices":{"A":"a type of animal","B":"a single landmass with all continents joined together","C":"a tool for studying Earth","D":"a layer of the atmosphere"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text tells us that Pangaea was a single landmass where all of Earth\u0027s continents were once joined together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q009","read_aloud":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller? A. because of wind and rain B. because tectonic plates are pushing against each other C. because people are building them D. because the ocean is rising","excerpt":"\"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\"","stem":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller?","choices":{"A":"because of wind and rain","B":"because tectonic plates are pushing against each other","C":"because people are building them","D":"because the ocean is rising"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the collision or pressure of tectonic plates can create mountains. The Himalayas grow taller because of this constant pressure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"circulates\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. moves through a system B. stays in one place C. disappears into the ground D. turns into ice","excerpt":"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.","stem":"What does \"circulates\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"moves through a system","B":"stays in one place","C":"disappears into the ground","D":"turns into ice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Circulates means moves through a system. The text describes water moving through the water cycle, not staying still.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What is the effect of thick feathers on red-tailed hawks? A. Their skin is protected from the sun B. They can fly higher in the sky C. They can catch more prey D. They stay warmer in winter","excerpt":"Their thick feathers protect their delicate skin from the sun\u0027s harmful rays.","stem":"What is the effect of thick feathers on red-tailed hawks?","choices":{"A":"Their skin is protected from the sun","B":"They can fly higher in the sky","C":"They can catch more prey","D":"They stay warmer in winter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that thick feathers protect the hawks\u0027 delicate skin from harmful sun rays.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Their thick feathers protect their delicate skin from the sun\u0027s harmful rays."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What does the wood duck use her feathers for? A. To cushion and warm her eggs B. To help her fly faster C. To attract a mate D. To build a bigger nest","excerpt":"A female wood duck lines her nest with feathers she plucks from her own body. These feathers cushion the duck\u0027s eggs and keep them warm.","stem":"What does the wood duck use her feathers for?","choices":{"A":"To cushion and warm her eggs","B":"To help her fly faster","C":"To attract a mate","D":"To build a bigger nest"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states the feathers cushion the eggs and keep them warm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A female wood duck lines her nest with feathers she plucks from her own body. These feathers cushion the duck\u0027s eggs and keep them warm."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q013","read_aloud":"How do feathers help the heron find food? A. They block reflections so the heron can see fish better B. They make the heron swim faster C. They help the heron catch frogs with its beak D. They keep the heron dry while hunting","excerpt":"As a hungry tricolored heron wades through the water in search of food, it raises its wings high over its head. The feathers block out reflections from the sky and shade the water. This makes it easier to spot tasty fish and frogs.","stem":"How do feathers help the heron find food?","choices":{"A":"They block reflections so the heron can see fish better","B":"They make the heron swim faster","C":"They help the heron catch frogs with its beak","D":"They keep the heron dry while hunting"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text explains that feathers block sky reflections and shade the water, making it easier for the heron to spot fish and frogs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As a hungry tricolored heron wades through the water in search of food, it raises its wings high over its head. The feathers block out reflections from the sky and shade the water. This makes it easier to spot tasty fish and frogs."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What happens right after water vapor rises into the atmosphere? A. It turns into ice. B. It gathers into clouds. C. It falls as snow. D. It soaks into the soil.","excerpt":"\"Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere. It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation.\"","stem":"What happens right after water vapor rises into the atmosphere?","choices":{"A":"It turns into ice.","B":"It gathers into clouds.","C":"It falls as snow.","D":"It soaks into the soil."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it rises, gathers into clouds, then falls as precipitation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere. It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q015","read_aloud":"What can happen if a strong earthquake occurs under the ocean? A. A volcano forms. B. A tsunami can develop. C. The ocean freezes. D. The water turns to steam.","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans. If the ocean earthquake is strong enough, waves can develop into a deadly tsunami.\"","stem":"What can happen if a strong earthquake occurs under the ocean?","choices":{"A":"A volcano forms.","B":"A tsunami can develop.","C":"The ocean freezes.","D":"The water turns to steam."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says strong ocean earthquakes can cause deadly tsunamis.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans. If the ocean earthquake is strong enough, waves can develop into a deadly tsunami.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q016","read_aloud":"How were the Hawaiian Islands formed? A. By earthquakes pushing up land B. By molten rock rising from the mantle through the ocean crust C. By glaciers melting D. By rivers carrying soil","excerpt":"\"Islands such as the Hawaiian Islands were created as molten rock rose up from the mantle through the crust beneath the ocean.\"","stem":"How were the Hawaiian Islands formed?","choices":{"A":"By earthquakes pushing up land","B":"By molten rock rising from the mantle through the ocean crust","C":"By glaciers melting","D":"By rivers carrying soil"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says molten rock rose from the mantle and created the islands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Islands such as the Hawaiian Islands were created as molten rock rose up from the mantle through the crust beneath the ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q017","read_aloud":"If you climbed a mountain that is 6 miles high, which layer of the atmosphere would you still be in? A. The stratosphere B. The troposphere C. The mesosphere D. The thermosphere","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\"","stem":"If you climbed a mountain that is 6 miles high, which layer of the atmosphere would you still be in?","choices":{"A":"The stratosphere","B":"The troposphere","C":"The mesosphere","D":"The thermosphere"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The troposphere is about 7 miles high, so 6 miles is still inside it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What does the word circulates mean in this sentence? A. Stays in one place B. Moves through a system C. Stops moving D. Freezes into ice","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\"","stem":"What does the word circulates mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Stays in one place","B":"Moves through a system","C":"Stops moving","D":"Freezes into ice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To circulate means to move through a closed system, like the water cycle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q019","read_aloud":"How hot is Earth\u0027s core estimated to be? A. 100 degrees Fahrenheit B. 1,000 degrees Fahrenheit C. 11,000 degrees Fahrenheit D. 100,000 degrees Fahrenheit","excerpt":"\"The inner core is solid iron. It may spin faster than Earth\u0027s other layers. The whole core is estimated to be 11,000 degrees Fahrenheit (6,000 degrees Celsius).\"","stem":"How hot is Earth\u0027s core estimated to be?","choices":{"A":"100 degrees Fahrenheit","B":"1,000 degrees Fahrenheit","C":"11,000 degrees Fahrenheit","D":"100,000 degrees Fahrenheit"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text gives the specific number 11,000 degrees Fahrenheit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The inner core is solid iron. It may spin faster than Earth\u0027s other layers. The whole core is estimated to be 11,000 degrees Fahrenheit (6,000 degrees Celsius).\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q020","read_aloud":"Which gas makes up most of the air we breathe? A. Oxygen B. Nitrogen C. Other gases D. Carbon dioxide","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\"","stem":"Which gas makes up most of the air we breathe?","choices":{"A":"Oxygen","B":"Nitrogen","C":"Other gases","D":"Carbon dioxide"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the air is 78 percent nitrogen, which is more than oxygen (21 percent).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q021","read_aloud":"Where does a compass needle point? A. The geographic North Pole B. The South Pole C. The magnetic north pole D. The equator","excerpt":"\"A compass needle points to Earth\u0027s magnetic north pole. But did you know that the magnetic north pole is not located at the geographic North Pole?\"","stem":"Where does a compass needle point?","choices":{"A":"The geographic North Pole","B":"The South Pole","C":"The magnetic north pole","D":"The equator"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that a compass needle points to Earth\u0027s magnetic north pole.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A compass needle points to Earth\u0027s magnetic north pole. But did you know that the magnetic north pole is not located at the geographic North Pole?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q022","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027molten\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027molten\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q023","read_aloud":"How many main layers is Earth made of? Options:? A. Two, B. Three, C. Four, D. Five","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\"","stem":"How many main layers is Earth made of? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Two,","B":"Three,","C":"Four,","D":"Five"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that our planet is composed of four main layers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What are the sections of Earth\u0027s crust called? Options:? A. Mantles, B. Cores, C. Tectonic plates, D. Oceans","excerpt":"\"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\"","stem":"What are the sections of Earth\u0027s crust called? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Mantles,","B":"Cores,","C":"Tectonic plates,","D":"Oceans"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text identifies the sections of the crust and upper mantle as tectonic plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What is the name of Earth\u0027s outer surface? Options:? A. Inner core, B. Mantle, C. Atmosphere, D. Crust","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust.\"","stem":"What is the name of Earth\u0027s outer surface? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Inner core,","B":"Mantle,","C":"Atmosphere,","D":"Crust"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Paragraph 1 states that the outer surface of the planet is called the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q001","read_aloud":"What does \u0027circulates\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options: A. Moves through a system, B. Stops moving, C. Gets hot, D. Turns into ice","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. ... It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation.\"","stem":"What does \u0027circulates\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Moves through a system,","B":"Stops moving,","C":"Gets hot,","D":"Turns into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Circulates means to move around through a system, which is what water does in the water cycle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. ... It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q002","read_aloud":"Why is ozone important? Options: A. It creates rain, B. It blocks harmful sun rays, C. It helps us breathe, D. It makes the air cold","excerpt":"\"The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere. Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\"","stem":"Why is ozone important? Options:","choices":{"A":"It creates rain,","B":"It blocks harmful sun rays,","C":"It helps us breathe,","D":"It makes the air cold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun to protect us.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere. Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What does a compass needle point to? Options: A. The geographic South Pole, B. Earth\u0027s magnetic north pole, C. The center of the sun, D. The nearest city","excerpt":"\"A compass needle points to Earth\u0027s magnetic north pole. But did you know that the magnetic north pole is not located at the geographic North Pole?\"","stem":"What does a compass needle point to? Options:","choices":{"A":"The geographic South Pole,","B":"Earth\u0027s magnetic north pole,","C":"The center of the sun,","D":"The nearest city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that a compass needle points to the magnetic north pole.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A compass needle points to Earth\u0027s magnetic north pole. But did you know that the magnetic north pole is not located at the geographic North Pole?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What is the troposphere mostly made of? Options: A. Nitrogen and oxygen, B. Water and ice, C. Iron and nickel, D. Melted rock","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\"","stem":"What is the troposphere mostly made of? Options:","choices":{"A":"Nitrogen and oxygen,","B":"Water and ice,","C":"Iron and nickel,","D":"Melted rock"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text lists nitrogen and oxygen as the main gases in the troposphere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Where does most of Earth\u0027s weather happen? Options: A. In the outer core, B. In the stratosphere, C. In the troposphere, D. On the ocean floor","excerpt":"\"Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\"","stem":"Where does most of Earth\u0027s weather happen? Options:","choices":{"A":"In the outer core,","B":"In the stratosphere,","C":"In the troposphere,","D":"On the ocean floor"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says that nearly all weather occurs in the troposphere layer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What is Earth\u0027s mantle made of? A. water and ice B. silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium, and aluminum C. air and clouds D. wood and plastic","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium, and aluminum.\"","stem":"What is Earth\u0027s mantle made of?","choices":{"A":"water and ice","B":"silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium, and aluminum","C":"air and clouds","D":"wood and plastic"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists the materials that make up the mantle: silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium, and aluminum.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium, and aluminum.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the mantle from this sentence? A. It is completely solid and never moves. B. It can get hot enough to melt and rise through the crust. C. It is always below the ocean. D. It has no effect on Earth\u0027s surface.","excerpt":"\"Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the mantle from this sentence?","choices":{"A":"It is completely solid and never moves.","B":"It can get hot enough to melt and rise through the crust.","C":"It is always below the ocean.","D":"It has no effect on Earth\u0027s surface."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says substance from the mantle rises and surfaces as molten rock in volcanoes. This means the mantle can get hot enough to melt and push through the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q008","read_aloud":"What is the outer core made of? A. mostly iron and nickel B. mostly water and sand C. mostly oxygen and nitrogen D. mostly wood and stone","excerpt":"\"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\"","stem":"What is the outer core made of?","choices":{"A":"mostly iron and nickel","B":"mostly water and sand","C":"mostly oxygen and nitrogen","D":"mostly wood and stone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text directly states that the liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field? A. the movement of the outer core around the inner core B. the water in the oceans C. the air in the atmosphere D. the plants on the surface","excerpt":"\"Its movement around the inner core creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field. Enormous pressure and radiation keep this layer hot.\"","stem":"What creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field?","choices":{"A":"the movement of the outer core around the inner core","B":"the water in the oceans","C":"the air in the atmosphere","D":"the plants on the surface"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the movement of the liquid outer core around the inner core creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Its movement around the inner core creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field. Enormous pressure and radiation keep this layer hot.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"adopted\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. started to use a selected idea or method B. refused to accept something new C. changed the rules completely D. forgot about the old way","excerpt":"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions.","stem":"What does \"adopted\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"started to use a selected idea or method","B":"refused to accept something new","C":"changed the rules completely","D":"forgot about the old way"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Adopted means started to use a selected idea or method. The text says most areas started using standard time zones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What can you infer about earthquakes from this passage? A. Earthquakes can cause different types of dangers B. Earthquakes only happen in the ocean C. Earthquakes are always deadly D. Earthquakes cannot be predicted","excerpt":"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans. If the ocean earthquake is strong enough, waves can develop into a deadly tsunami.","stem":"What can you infer about earthquakes from this passage?","choices":{"A":"Earthquakes can cause different types of dangers","B":"Earthquakes only happen in the ocean","C":"Earthquakes are always deadly","D":"Earthquakes cannot be predicted"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows earthquakes can cause land movement, ocean shifts, and tsunamis, suggesting they create various dangers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans. If the ocean earthquake is strong enough, waves can develop into a deadly tsunami."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q012","read_aloud":"How does the junco use its tail feathers? A. To distract enemies and escape B. To attract a mate C. To keep warm in winter D. To help it fly faster","excerpt":"A dark-eyed junco distracts its enemies by flashing the bright white feathers on the outside of its tail. Then it quickly covers the feathers and darts off in the other direction.","stem":"How does the junco use its tail feathers?","choices":{"A":"To distract enemies and escape","B":"To attract a mate","C":"To keep warm in winter","D":"To help it fly faster"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text describes how the junco flashes white tail feathers to distract enemies, then escapes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A dark-eyed junco distracts its enemies by flashing the bright white feathers on the outside of its tail. Then it quickly covers the feathers and darts off in the other direction."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q013","read_aloud":"Why do male peacocks have colorful tail feathers? A. To attract female peacocks during mating time B. To hide from predators in the forest C. To keep warm during cold weather D. To help them fly long distances","excerpt":"A peacock\u0027s bright, beautiful tail feathers make him easy to spot. At mating time a female is attracted to the male with the biggest, most colorful fan of feathers.","stem":"Why do male peacocks have colorful tail feathers?","choices":{"A":"To attract female peacocks during mating time","B":"To hide from predators in the forest","C":"To keep warm during cold weather","D":"To help them fly long distances"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that at mating time, females are attracted to males with the biggest, most colorful feathers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A peacock\u0027s bright, beautiful tail feathers make him easy to spot. At mating time a female is attracted to the male with the biggest, most colorful fan of feathers."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q014","read_aloud":"How do feathers help swans float on water? A. Air trapped in feathers helps them stay on the surface B. Feathers make them swim faster underwater C. Feathers keep them warm while swimming D. Feathers help them dive deep for food","excerpt":"Mute swans glide smoothly across the water\u0027s surface. Pockets of air trapped between their feathers help these graceful birds stay afloat.","stem":"How do feathers help swans float on water?","choices":{"A":"Air trapped in feathers helps them stay on the surface","B":"Feathers make them swim faster underwater","C":"Feathers keep them warm while swimming","D":"Feathers help them dive deep for food"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that air pockets trapped between feathers help swans stay afloat on water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mute swans glide smoothly across the water\u0027s surface. Pockets of air trapped between their feathers help these graceful birds stay afloat."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q015","read_aloud":"(The page also includes a map of time zones.) What text feature helps you see how time zones are arranged around the world? A. A diagram of Earth\u0027s layers B. A map of standard time zones C. A photograph of a compass D. A caption about Pangaea","excerpt":"Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it.","stem":"(The page also includes a map of time zones.) What text feature helps you see how time zones are arranged around the world?","choices":{"A":"A diagram of Earth\u0027s layers","B":"A map of standard time zones","C":"A photograph of a compass","D":"A caption about Pangaea"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The map shows the time zones visually.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What does ozone in the stratosphere do? A. It creates rain. B. It blocks harmful rays from the sun. C. It makes the air thicker. D. It causes wind.","excerpt":"\"The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere. Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\"","stem":"What does ozone in the stratosphere do?","choices":{"A":"It creates rain.","B":"It blocks harmful rays from the sun.","C":"It makes the air thicker.","D":"It causes wind."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere. Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q017","read_aloud":"What happens to the magnetic field when the poles switch places? A. It becomes stronger. B. It becomes twisted and scrambled. C. It disappears completely. D. It turns into electricity.","excerpt":"\"The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places. When this happens, Earth\u0027s magnetic field temporarily becomes twisted and scrambled.\"","stem":"What happens to the magnetic field when the poles switch places?","choices":{"A":"It becomes stronger.","B":"It becomes twisted and scrambled.","C":"It disappears completely.","D":"It turns into electricity."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it becomes twisted and scrambled.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places. When this happens, Earth\u0027s magnetic field temporarily becomes twisted and scrambled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q018","read_aloud":"What does molten mean? A. Frozen solid B. Melted into liquid C. Broken into pieces D. Very cold","excerpt":"\"Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What does molten mean?","choices":{"A":"Frozen solid","B":"Melted into liquid","C":"Broken into pieces","D":"Very cold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means melted or hot enough to be in liquid form, like rock in a volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q019","read_aloud":"How many standard time zones does Earth have? A. 12 B. 24 C. 7 D. 4","excerpt":"\"Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it.\"","stem":"How many standard time zones does Earth have?","choices":{"A":"12","B":"24","C":"7","D":"4"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states clearly that Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Why is China an exception to time zones? A. It has no time zones. B. It uses 24 time zones. C. It uses only one time zone for the whole country. D. It does not use clocks.","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions. China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\"","stem":"Why is China an exception to time zones?","choices":{"A":"It has no time zones.","B":"It uses 24 time zones.","C":"It uses only one time zone for the whole country.","D":"It does not use clocks."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that China decided to have only one time zone even though it crosses three.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions. China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q021","read_aloud":"According to the text, what do GPS satellites help us do? A. Study the stars B. Navigate the planet C. Drill into the mantle D. Predict the weather","excerpt":"\"Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars.\"","stem":"According to the text, what do GPS satellites help us do?","choices":{"A":"Study the stars","B":"Navigate the planet","C":"Drill into the mantle","D":"Predict the weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"GPS satellites allow people to find their way around the planet easily.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does technology help scientists during natural disasters? A. It stops the disasters from happening. B. It helps them spot problems and react quickly. C. It moves people to different planets. D. It creates more disasters.","excerpt":"\"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\"","stem":"How does technology help scientists during natural disasters?","choices":{"A":"It stops the disasters from happening.","B":"It helps them spot problems and react quickly.","C":"It moves people to different planets.","D":"It creates more disasters."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says technology helps scientists spot problems and react quickly to reduce devastation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q023","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q024","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l03-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. By flying satellites over it B. By drilling into it and taking samples C. By using GPS D. By studying the moon","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"By flying satellites over it","B":"By drilling into it and taking samples","C":"By using GPS","D":"By studying the moon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists plan to drill through the ocean floor to get samples from the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q001","read_aloud":"If you move from one time zone to the one east of it, what happens to the time? Options: A. It stays the same, B. It goes back an hour, C. It goes forward an hour, D. It becomes midnight","excerpt":"\"Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it.\"","stem":"If you move from one time zone to the one east of it, what happens to the time? Options:","choices":{"A":"It stays the same,","B":"It goes back an hour,","C":"It goes forward an hour,","D":"It becomes midnight"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says each zone is one hour ahead of the one to the west.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Why are GPS satellites helpful? Options: A. They study the stars, B. They help us navigate without studying stars, C. They monitor the core, D. They stop volcanoes from erupting","excerpt":"\"Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space. ... Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars.\"","stem":"Why are GPS satellites helpful? Options:","choices":{"A":"They study the stars,","B":"They help us navigate without studying stars,","C":"They monitor the core,","D":"They stop volcanoes from erupting"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that GPS satellites allow us to navigate the planet easily.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space. ... Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q003","read_aloud":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller? Options: A. Because of rain, B. Because of tectonic plate pressure, C. Because they are made of ice, D. Because the sun hits them","excerpt":"\"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\"","stem":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because of rain,","B":"Because of tectonic plate pressure,","C":"Because they are made of ice,","D":"Because the sun hits them"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The collision or pressure of tectonic plates causes the mountains to rise and grow taller.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q004","read_aloud":"What is the first thing that happens in the water cycle? Options: A. Rain falls to the ground, B. Water soaks into the soil, C. The sun heats the water, D. Clouds form","excerpt":"\"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram. ... Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.\"","stem":"What is the first thing that happens in the water cycle? Options:","choices":{"A":"Rain falls to the ground,","B":"Water soaks into the soil,","C":"The sun heats the water,","D":"Clouds form"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The process begins when the sun heats the water on the surface, causing it to turn into gas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram. ... Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q005","read_aloud":"What does \"abundant\" mean in this sentence? A. very rare and hard to find B. plentiful and commonly occurring C. small and hidden D. dangerous and scary","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"What does \"abundant\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"very rare and hard to find","B":"plentiful and commonly occurring","C":"small and hidden","D":"dangerous and scary"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. \"Abundant\" means there is plenty of something, or it is commonly occurring.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q006","read_aloud":"How is the stratosphere different from the troposphere? A. The stratosphere has less water and more ozone. B. The stratosphere is where we breathe. C. The stratosphere is only 7 miles high. D. The stratosphere has no purpose.","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe... The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere.\"","stem":"How is the stratosphere different from the troposphere?","choices":{"A":"The stratosphere has less water and more ozone.","B":"The stratosphere is where we breathe.","C":"The stratosphere is only 7 miles high.","D":"The stratosphere has no purpose."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text compares the two layers. The stratosphere contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere. The troposphere is where we breathe and is only 7 miles high.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe... The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q007","read_aloud":"Why do meteoroids usually burn up? A. because they are made of fire B. because friction from moving through the atmosphere heats them up C. because they hit the ocean D. because they are afraid of Earth","excerpt":"\"A meteoroid creates friction as it moves rapidly through the atmosphere. This usually causes the object to burn up.\"","stem":"Why do meteoroids usually burn up?","choices":{"A":"because they are made of fire","B":"because friction from moving through the atmosphere heats them up","C":"because they hit the ocean","D":"because they are afraid of Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says meteoroids create friction as they move rapidly through the atmosphere. This friction causes them to burn up before reaching the ground.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A meteoroid creates friction as it moves rapidly through the atmosphere. This usually causes the object to burn up.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q008","read_aloud":"If you took a breath right now, which layer of the atmosphere are you using? A. the stratosphere B. the troposphere C. the mesosphere D. the outer core","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\"","stem":"If you took a breath right now, which layer of the atmosphere are you using?","choices":{"A":"the stratosphere","B":"the troposphere","C":"the mesosphere","D":"the outer core"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the troposphere contains the air we breathe. Since we live on Earth\u0027s surface, we are breathing air from the troposphere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q009","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the number 170 times in 80 million years? A. to show that magnetic pole switches are very rare B. to prove that compasses never work C. to show that they happen every day D. to make the paragraph longer","excerpt":"\"The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places. When this happens, Earth\u0027s magnetic field temporarily becomes twisted and scrambled. But this has only happened 170 times in the last 80 million years.\"","stem":"Why does the author include the number 170 times in 80 million years?","choices":{"A":"to show that magnetic pole switches are very rare","B":"to prove that compasses never work","C":"to show that they happen every day","D":"to make the paragraph longer"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"170 times in 80 million years is not very often. The author uses this number to show that magnetic pole switches are rare events, even though they do happen.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places. When this happens, Earth\u0027s magnetic field temporarily becomes twisted and scrambled. But this has only happened 170 times in the last 80 million years.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"abundant\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. plentiful; commonly occurring B. rare and hard to find C. dangerous to explore D. expensive to study","excerpt":"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.","stem":"What does \"abundant\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"plentiful; commonly occurring","B":"rare and hard to find","C":"dangerous to explore","D":"expensive to study"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abundant means plentiful or commonly occurring. The text describes oceans as one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this passage? A. Tectonic plate movement can form mountains B. Mountains are found only in Asia C. The Himalayas are the tallest mountains D. Tectonic plates never stop moving","excerpt":"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.","stem":"What is the main idea of this passage?","choices":{"A":"Tectonic plate movement can form mountains","B":"Mountains are found only in Asia","C":"The Himalayas are the tallest mountains","D":"Tectonic plates never stop moving"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The passage explains that tectonic plate collisions and pressure create mountain ranges, using the Himalayas as an example.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q012","read_aloud":"What is the effect of the cardinal\u0027s feather colors? A. She can hide from enemies while protecting her nest B. She can fly faster than other birds C. She can find more food in the forest D. She can attract more mates","excerpt":"A female cardinal\u0027s dull, grayish-tan body and feathers blend in with her forest home. They help her hide and protect her nest from enemies while she sits on her eggs.","stem":"What is the effect of the cardinal\u0027s feather colors?","choices":{"A":"She can hide from enemies while protecting her nest","B":"She can fly faster than other birds","C":"She can find more food in the forest","D":"She can attract more mates"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text states that the dull colors help the female cardinal blend in and hide from enemies while protecting her nest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A female cardinal\u0027s dull, grayish-tan body and feathers blend in with her forest home. They help her hide and protect her nest from enemies while she sits on her eggs."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q013","read_aloud":"If you were a baby sandgrouse, how would you get water on a hot day? A. By sucking on my father\u0027s wet feathers B. By flying to a watering hole myself C. By waiting for rain to fall D. By drinking dew from leaves","excerpt":"On sizzling summer days a male sandgrouse cools off by soaking his belly feathers in a watering hole. Then the proud papa flies to his nest. While dad guards his chicks, the little ones suck on his feathers to quench their thirst.","stem":"If you were a baby sandgrouse, how would you get water on a hot day?","choices":{"A":"By sucking on my father\u0027s wet feathers","B":"By flying to a watering hole myself","C":"By waiting for rain to fall","D":"By drinking dew from leaves"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes how baby sandgrouse suck on their father\u0027s wet belly feathers to get water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: On sizzling summer days a male sandgrouse cools off by soaking his belly feathers in a watering hole. Then the proud papa flies to his nest. While dad guards his chicks, the little ones suck on his feathers to quench their thirst."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q014","read_aloud":"How does the bittern\u0027s feather structure help it survive? A. The brittle tips create cleaning powder to remove dirt and oil B. The feathers help it fly faster to catch prey C. The powder attracts more fish to hunt D. The brittle feathers make it easier to hide","excerpt":"An American bittern always cleans up after it eats. Its feathers have brittle tips that crumble into a dusty powder. The powder is perfect for scouring away the dirt and slimy fish oil that sticks to its feathers.","stem":"How does the bittern\u0027s feather structure help it survive?","choices":{"A":"The brittle tips create cleaning powder to remove dirt and oil","B":"The feathers help it fly faster to catch prey","C":"The powder attracts more fish to hunt","D":"The brittle feathers make it easier to hide"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that brittle feather tips crumble into powder that cleans dirt and fish oil, helping the bittern maintain clean feathers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: An American bittern always cleans up after it eats. Its feathers have brittle tips that crumble into a dusty powder. The powder is perfect for scouring away the dirt and slimy fish oil that sticks to its feathers."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What could happen if polar caps melt too much? A. Ocean currents could shift and temperatures could drop. B. The oceans would become frozen. C. The mantle would cool down. D. Time zones would change.","excerpt":"\"The Aqua satellite uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle. For example, water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge.\"","stem":"What could happen if polar caps melt too much?","choices":{"A":"Ocean currents could shift and temperatures could drop.","B":"The oceans would become frozen.","C":"The mantle would cool down.","D":"Time zones would change."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says ocean currents could shift and temperatures could plunge.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Aqua satellite uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle. For example, water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q016","read_aloud":"Why is the depth of the mantle only an estimate? A. Scientists have not been able to drill that deep yet. B. The mantle is too cold to measure. C. The mantle is made of gas. D. The core is in the way.","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean or 8 miles (13 km) on land.\"","stem":"Why is the depth of the mantle only an estimate?","choices":{"A":"Scientists have not been able to drill that deep yet.","B":"The mantle is too cold to measure.","C":"The mantle is made of gas.","D":"The core is in the way."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"No one has drilled deep enough to reach the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean or 8 miles (13 km) on land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q017","read_aloud":"If you lived in China and traveled from the east side to the west side, would the time on your watch change? Why? A. Yes, because China crosses time zones. B. No, because China uses only one time zone for the whole country. C. Yes, because every country changes time. D. No, because China has no time zones.","excerpt":"\"China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\"","stem":"If you lived in China and traveled from the east side to the west side, would the time on your watch change? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because China crosses time zones.","B":"No, because China uses only one time zone for the whole country.","C":"Yes, because every country changes time.","D":"No, because China has no time zones."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"China decided to have only one time zone despite crossing three.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q018","read_aloud":"What does adopted mean in this sentence? A. Refused to use B. Started to use C. Forgotten about D. Broken","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\"","stem":"What does adopted mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Refused to use","B":"Started to use","C":"Forgotten about","D":"Broken"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Adopted means to accept or start using a selected idea or method, like time zones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q019","read_aloud":"What is the cause of earthquakes according to the text? A. The ocean waves crashing B. Tectonic plates sliding over or past each other C. Heavy rain storms D. The moon\u0027s gravity","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur.\"","stem":"What is the cause of earthquakes according to the text?","choices":{"A":"The ocean waves crashing","B":"Tectonic plates sliding over or past each other","C":"Heavy rain storms","D":"The moon\u0027s gravity"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that sliding tectonic plates cause earthquakes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q020","read_aloud":"What helps the reader understand the movement of water? A. A map of China B. A diagram with blue arrows C. A picture of a volcano D. A list of time zones","excerpt":"\"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram.\"","stem":"What helps the reader understand the movement of water?","choices":{"A":"A map of China","B":"A diagram with blue arrows","C":"A picture of a volcano","D":"A list of time zones"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions a diagram where blue arrows show water movement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q021","read_aloud":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller each year? A. Because of the constant pressure of tectonic plates B. Because people build them higher C. Because of heavy rains D. Because the core is cooling down","excerpt":"\"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\"","stem":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller each year?","choices":{"A":"Because of the constant pressure of tectonic plates","B":"Because people build them higher","C":"Because of heavy rains","D":"Because the core is cooling down"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text links the growth of mountains to the collision or pressure of tectonic plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main job of ozone in the atmosphere? A. To create wind B. To block harmful rays from the sun C. To make the air cold D. To create rain clouds","excerpt":"\"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\"","stem":"What is the main job of ozone in the atmosphere?","choices":{"A":"To create wind","B":"To block harmful rays from the sun","C":"To make the air cold","D":"To create rain clouds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q023","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q024","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l04-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. By flying satellites over it B. By drilling into it and taking samples C. By using GPS D. By studying the moon","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"By flying satellites over it","B":"By drilling into it and taking samples","C":"By using GPS","D":"By studying the moon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists plan to drill through the ocean floor to get samples from the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q001","read_aloud":"Why are special drills needed for the ocean floor? Options: A. Because the ocean is too cold, B. To drill through hard oceanic crust, C. Because the ship is too large, D. To find fish","excerpt":"\"The Japanese vessel Chikyu holds the world\u0027s record for deep ocean drilling. ... Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\"","stem":"Why are special drills needed for the ocean floor? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because the ocean is too cold,","B":"To drill through hard oceanic crust,","C":"Because the ship is too large,","D":"To find fish"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that drills must be strong to handle the stress of boring through hard oceanic crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Japanese vessel Chikyu holds the world\u0027s record for deep ocean drilling. ... Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q002","read_aloud":"How are earthquakes and mountain ranges similar? Options: A. They both need rain, B. They are both caused by moving tectonic plates, C. They both happen in the atmosphere, D. They are both caused by the sun","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. ... The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\"","stem":"How are earthquakes and mountain ranges similar? Options:","choices":{"A":"They both need rain,","B":"They are both caused by moving tectonic plates,","C":"They both happen in the atmosphere,","D":"They are both caused by the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both of these phenomena are results of tectonic plates moving and pressing against each other.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. ... The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q003","read_aloud":"Why do meteoroids usually not hit the ground? Options: A. They are too heavy, B. They burn up from friction in the atmosphere, C. They move too slowly, D. The ozone layer pushes them away","excerpt":"\"The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids. ... However, a meteoroid creates friction as it moves rapidly through the atmosphere. This usually causes the object to burn up.\"","stem":"Why do meteoroids usually not hit the ground? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are too heavy,","B":"They burn up from friction in the atmosphere,","C":"They move too slowly,","D":"The ozone layer pushes them away"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The friction caused by moving fast through the atmosphere makes them burn up before reaching the surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids. ... However, a meteoroid creates friction as it moves rapidly through the atmosphere. This usually causes the object to burn up.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q004","read_aloud":"What can you infer about studying the mantle? A. It is easy to reach and study directly. B. It is very difficult to study because it is too deep to drill into. C. Scientists have already drilled all the way through it. D. The mantle is not important to study.","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean or 8 miles (13 km) on land.\"","stem":"What can you infer about studying the mantle?","choices":{"A":"It is easy to reach and study directly.","B":"It is very difficult to study because it is too deep to drill into.","C":"Scientists have already drilled all the way through it.","D":"The mantle is not important to study."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The mantle is 1,860 miles deep, but the deepest drill is only 8 miles. This huge difference shows scientists cannot yet reach the mantle directly. It is very difficult to study.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean or 8 miles (13 km) on land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q005","read_aloud":"[Caption with diagram] How does the diagram help readers understand the atmosphere? A. by showing a story about animals B. by giving a visual picture of the layers and their order C. by listing only the names without any pictures D. by hiding information from readers","excerpt":"This illustration shows the five layers of Earth\u0027s atmosphere.","stem":"[Caption with diagram] How does the diagram help readers understand the atmosphere?","choices":{"A":"by showing a story about animals","B":"by giving a visual picture of the layers and their order","C":"by listing only the names without any pictures","D":"by hiding information from readers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A diagram of the five layers helps readers see what each layer looks like and how they are arranged from lowest to highest. Visual features make information easier to understand.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: This illustration shows the five layers of Earth\u0027s atmosphere."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q006","read_aloud":"Why might China choose to have only one time zone? A. because China is very small B. to make time simpler for everyone in the country C. because China has no clocks D. to confuse travelers","excerpt":"\"China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\"","stem":"Why might China choose to have only one time zone?","choices":{"A":"because China is very small","B":"to make time simpler for everyone in the country","C":"because China has no clocks","D":"to confuse travelers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Having one time zone for a whole country makes life simpler. People do not have to change clocks when they travel within the country. Businesses and schools can use the same time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q007","read_aloud":"Why is it important that Aqua can see through clouds? A. because clouds are pretty to look at B. because clouds often block the view of Earth from regular satellites C. because Aqua needs to collect clouds D. because clouds are dangerous to satellites","excerpt":"\"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"Why is it important that Aqua can see through clouds?","choices":{"A":"because clouds are pretty to look at","B":"because clouds often block the view of Earth from regular satellites","C":"because Aqua needs to collect clouds","D":"because clouds are dangerous to satellites"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Regular cameras cannot see through clouds. If Aqua can see through clouds using microwave technology, it can monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle even when it is cloudy. This gives scientists better data.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q008","read_aloud":"What does \"molten\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. melted; hot enough to be in liquid form B. frozen; cold enough to be solid C. dry; without any water content D. soft; easy to shape by hand","excerpt":"Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.","stem":"What does \"molten\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"melted; hot enough to be in liquid form","B":"frozen; cold enough to be solid","C":"dry; without any water content","D":"soft; easy to shape by hand"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Molten means melted or hot enough to be in liquid form. The text describes rock that rises and erupts from volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q009","read_aloud":"What does the male bank swallow do first when making a home? A. He digs a tunnel using his bill and leg feathers B. He builds a nest at the tunnel\u0027s end C. He pushes dirt out with his wings D. He finds straw and grasses for the nest","excerpt":"First the male uses his bill and the tough feathers on his lower legs to dig a two-foot-long tunnel in a stream bank. He pushes the dirt out with his wings. Then the female builds a nest of straw, grasses, and leaves at the end of the tunnel.","stem":"What does the male bank swallow do first when making a home?","choices":{"A":"He digs a tunnel using his bill and leg feathers","B":"He builds a nest at the tunnel\u0027s end","C":"He pushes dirt out with his wings","D":"He finds straw and grasses for the nest"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text describes the sequence: first the male digs the tunnel, then pushes out dirt, then the female builds the nest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: First the male uses his bill and the tough feathers on his lower legs to dig a two-foot-long tunnel in a stream bank. He pushes the dirt out with his wings. Then the female builds a nest of straw, grasses, and leaves at the end of the tunnel."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q010","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Wesley\u0027s preferences from this passage? A. He prefers comfortable, practical clothing over heavy, uncomfortable items B. He likes expensive clothing that costs a lot of money C. He prefers clothing that is made from denim material D. He likes clothing that has very few pockets","excerpt":"Unlike jeans, which he found scratchy and heavy, the robe was comfortable, reflected the sun, and offered myriad opportunities for pockets.","stem":"What can you infer about Wesley\u0027s preferences from this passage?","choices":{"A":"He prefers comfortable, practical clothing over heavy, uncomfortable items","B":"He likes expensive clothing that costs a lot of money","C":"He prefers clothing that is made from denim material","D":"He likes clothing that has very few pockets"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts jeans (scratchy, heavy) with the robe (comfortable, sun-reflecting, many pockets), suggesting Wesley values comfort and practicality.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Unlike jeans, which he found scratchy and heavy, the robe was comfortable, reflected the sun, and offered myriad opportunities for pockets."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q011","read_aloud":"If you were designing a new bird species, how might it carry nesting materials differently? A. By storing materials in a special pouch on its back B. By always carrying materials in its beak like most birds C. By dropping materials and flying back to get them D. By asking other birds to carry materials for it","excerpt":"Most birds carry nesting materials in their beaks. But not the female rosy-faced lovebird. When she finds grass, leaves, or strips of bark, she tucks them under her rump feathers and flies back to her nest.","stem":"If you were designing a new bird species, how might it carry nesting materials differently?","choices":{"A":"By storing materials in a special pouch on its back","B":"By always carrying materials in its beak like most birds","C":"By dropping materials and flying back to get them","D":"By asking other birds to carry materials for it"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This question asks students to apply knowledge of bird adaptations to imagine a new carrying method, building on the lovebird\u0027s unique feather-tucking adaptation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most birds carry nesting materials in their beaks. But not the female rosy-faced lovebird. When she finds grass, leaves, or strips of bark, she tucks them under her rump feathers and flies back to her nest."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q012","read_aloud":"How does the manakin\u0027s feather structure create sound? A. Ridge feathers rubbing against curved-tip feathers produces chirping sounds B. The feathers vibrate when the bird flies through the air C. The feathers trap air that makes noise when released D. The feathers change color to create visual sounds","excerpt":"When a male club-winged manakin wants to get a female\u0027s attention, he leans forward, raises his wings over his back, and rapidly shakes them. As feathers with ridges rub against feathers with stiff, curved tips, a squeaky chirping sound trills through the air.","stem":"How does the manakin\u0027s feather structure create sound?","choices":{"A":"Ridge feathers rubbing against curved-tip feathers produces chirping sounds","B":"The feathers vibrate when the bird flies through the air","C":"The feathers trap air that makes noise when released","D":"The feathers change color to create visual sounds"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text explains that ridged feathers rubbing against stiff, curved-tip feathers creates the squeaky chirping sound used to attract females.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When a male club-winged manakin wants to get a female\u0027s attention, he leans forward, raises his wings over his back, and rapidly shakes them. As feathers with ridges rub against feathers with stiff, curved tips, a squeaky chirping sound trills through the air."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q013","read_aloud":"How is the text organized? A. In time order B. By comparing Earth to other planets C. By describing Earth\u0027s different parts (layers) D. As a story with characters","excerpt":"The text has headings such as \"The Crust,\" \"The Mantle,\" \"The Core,\" and \"The Atmosphere.\"","stem":"How is the text organized?","choices":{"A":"In time order","B":"By comparing Earth to other planets","C":"By describing Earth\u0027s different parts (layers)","D":"As a story with characters"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The headings show a descriptive structure about Earth\u0027s layers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text has headings such as \"The Crust,\" \"The Mantle,\" \"The Core,\" and \"The Atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q014","read_aloud":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller each year? A. Because of wind and rain B. Because tectonic plates are still colliding and pushing the mountains up C. Because glaciers are melting D. Because people add rocks","excerpt":"\"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\"","stem":"Why do the Himalayan mountains grow taller each year?","choices":{"A":"Because of wind and rain","B":"Because tectonic plates are still colliding and pushing the mountains up","C":"Because glaciers are melting","D":"Because people add rocks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Colliding plates push the mountains higher.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q015","read_aloud":"Do you think it is important to explore more of the ocean floor? Why? A. No, because the ocean is not interesting. B. Yes, because we might discover new species and learn more about Earth\u0027s processes. C. No, because it costs too much money. D. Yes, because we need more fish.","excerpt":"\"Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Do you think it is important to explore more of the ocean floor? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because the ocean is not interesting.","B":"Yes, because we might discover new species and learn more about Earth\u0027s processes.","C":"No, because it costs too much money.","D":"Yes, because we need more fish."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says exploring helps explain Earth\u0027s geologic processes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q016","read_aloud":"How do scientists plan to solve the mystery of the mantle? A. By flying satellites over it B. By drilling into it and taking samples C. By using GPS D. By studying the moon","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"How do scientists plan to solve the mystery of the mantle?","choices":{"A":"By flying satellites over it","B":"By drilling into it and taking samples","C":"By using GPS","D":"By studying the moon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists plan to drill through the ocean floor to get samples from the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q017","read_aloud":"What can the Aqua satellite do? A. Drill into the Earth B. See through clouds C. Stop earthquakes D. Change the weather","excerpt":"\"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"What can the Aqua satellite do?","choices":{"A":"Drill into the Earth","B":"See through clouds","C":"Stop earthquakes","D":"Change the weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Aqua uses technology to see through clouds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Why do scientists need special drills for this project? A. The ocean water is too cold. B. The oceanic crust is very hard. C. They want to drill into a volcano. D. The fish are in the way.","excerpt":"\"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\"","stem":"Why do scientists need special drills for this project?","choices":{"A":"The ocean water is too cold.","B":"The oceanic crust is very hard.","C":"They want to drill into a volcano.","D":"The fish are in the way."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says special drills are needed to handle the stress of boring through hard crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q019","read_aloud":"How does studying Mount Erebus help scientists? A. It helps them predict rain. B. It helps them understand how and why volcanoes erupt. C. It helps them find gold. D. It helps them measure time zones.","excerpt":"\"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\"","stem":"How does studying Mount Erebus help scientists?","choices":{"A":"It helps them predict rain.","B":"It helps them understand how and why volcanoes erupt.","C":"It helps them find gold.","D":"It helps them measure time zones."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the data explains how and why volcanoes erupt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. By flying satellites over it B. By drilling into it and taking samples C. By using GPS D. By studying the moon","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"By flying satellites over it","B":"By drilling into it and taking samples","C":"By using GPS","D":"By studying the moon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists plan to drill through the ocean floor to get samples from the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q023","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Drill into the Earth B. See through clouds C. Stop earthquakes D. Change the weather","excerpt":"\"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Drill into the Earth","B":"See through clouds","C":"Stop earthquakes","D":"Change the weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Aqua uses technology to see through clouds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q024","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. The ocean water is too cold. B. The oceanic crust is very hard. C. They want to drill into a volcano. D. The fish are in the way.","excerpt":"\"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"The ocean water is too cold.","B":"The oceanic crust is very hard.","C":"They want to drill into a volcano.","D":"The fish are in the way."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says special drills are needed to handle the stress of boring through hard crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l05-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. It helps them predict rain. B. It helps them understand how and why volcanoes erupt. C. It helps them find gold. D. It helps them measure time zones.","excerpt":"\"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"It helps them predict rain.","B":"It helps them understand how and why volcanoes erupt.","C":"It helps them find gold.","D":"It helps them measure time zones."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the data explains how and why volcanoes erupt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q001","read_aloud":"In this text, what does \u0027fluid\u0027 mean? Options: A. Hard like a rock, B. Able to flow or move easily, C. Very dry, D. Made of gas","excerpt":"\"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\"","stem":"In this text, what does \u0027fluid\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Hard like a rock,","B":"Able to flow or move easily,","C":"Very dry,","D":"Made of gas"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A fluid layer is one that can move or flow, which allows the tectonic plates to drift.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main purpose of the International Space Station (ISS)? Options: A. To watch the sun, B. To help scientists conduct experiments in weightless environments, C. To drill for oil, D. To map the ocean floor","excerpt":"\"ISS welcomed its first astronauts on November 2, 2000. ... ISS completed more than 57,000 orbits around Earth.\"","stem":"What is the main purpose of the International Space Station (ISS)? Options:","choices":{"A":"To watch the sun,","B":"To help scientists conduct experiments in weightless environments,","C":"To drill for oil,","D":"To map the ocean floor"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The station was designed to help scientists learn how things work in a weightless environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"ISS welcomed its first astronauts on November 2, 2000. ... ISS completed more than 57,000 orbits around Earth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q003","read_aloud":"How many satellites does a GPS need to work correctly? Options: A. One, B. Two, C. Four or more, D. Ten","excerpt":"\"Signals from four or more satellites are needed to accurately determine your position. Digital maps are built into the receiver. They use the satellites\u0027 information to help you navigate.\"","stem":"How many satellites does a GPS need to work correctly? Options:","choices":{"A":"One,","B":"Two,","C":"Four or more,","D":"Ten"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that a receiver needs signals from four or more satellites to work accurately.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Signals from four or more satellites are needed to accurately determine your position. Digital maps are built into the receiver. They use the satellites\u0027 information to help you navigate.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q004","read_aloud":"What does the shifting of tectonic plates tell us about Earth\u0027s history? Options: A. Earth never changes, B. Earth\u0027s landmasses have moved over time, C. There were always seven continents, D. Pangaea is still together","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted. This caused Pangaea to break into sections.\"","stem":"What does the shifting of tectonic plates tell us about Earth\u0027s history? Options:","choices":{"A":"Earth never changes,","B":"Earth\u0027s landmasses have moved over time,","C":"There were always seven continents,","D":"Pangaea is still together"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The movement of plates explains how one big landmass broke apart over time to form our current continents.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted. This caused Pangaea to break into sections.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q005","read_aloud":"What is the main role of the atmosphere\u0027s layers? Options: A. To create wind, B. To protect Earth from harmful things like sun rays and meteoroids, C. To keep the ocean water warm, D. To help satellites move","excerpt":"\"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun. The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space.\"","stem":"What is the main role of the atmosphere\u0027s layers? Options:","choices":{"A":"To create wind,","B":"To protect Earth from harmful things like sun rays and meteoroids,","C":"To keep the ocean water warm,","D":"To help satellites move"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The layers act like a blanket of protection against space objects and harmful radiation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun. The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q006","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"abundant\"? A. rare B. plentiful C. tiny D. empty","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"abundant\"?","choices":{"A":"rare","B":"plentiful","C":"tiny","D":"empty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Abundant\" means plentiful or commonly occurring. Oceans cover most of Earth, so they are plentiful. \"Plentiful\" is the closest synonym.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q007","read_aloud":"Why do scientists choose to drill in the Pacific Ocean? A. because the ocean floor there is thinner than other places B. because they like swimming C. because the Pacific is the smallest ocean D. because there are no fish there","excerpt":"\"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\"","stem":"Why do scientists choose to drill in the Pacific Ocean?","choices":{"A":"because the ocean floor there is thinner than other places","B":"because they like swimming","C":"because the Pacific is the smallest ocean","D":"because there are no fish there"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the Pacific Ocean floor is less than 4 miles thick. This is thinner than land crust, which goes down 8 miles. Thinner crust means they can get closer to the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author start this section by talking about technology? A. to tell a funny story B. to show how new tools help us learn about Earth C. to describe ancient astronomy in detail D. to complain about old technology","excerpt":"\"Technology has come a long way since the days of ancient astronomy. Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space.\"","stem":"Why does the author start this section by talking about technology?","choices":{"A":"to tell a funny story","B":"to show how new tools help us learn about Earth","C":"to describe ancient astronomy in detail","D":"to complain about old technology"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author wants to show that modern technology like satellites helps scientists study Earth better than in the past. This sets up the rest of the section about tools like GPS and ROVs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Technology has come a long way since the days of ancient astronomy. Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q009","read_aloud":"How does technology help during natural disasters? A. by causing more disasters B. by letting scientists see problems early and respond faster C. by making disasters invisible D. by stopping all earthquakes","excerpt":"\"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\"","stem":"How does technology help during natural disasters?","choices":{"A":"by causing more disasters","B":"by letting scientists see problems early and respond faster","C":"by making disasters invisible","D":"by stopping all earthquakes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists can spot problems and react quickly. This means they can warn people and prepare before disasters get worse. Technology helps reduce the damage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q010","read_aloud":"Why is the mantle still a mystery even though scientists know a lot about Earth? A. because scientists do not care about the mantle B. because it is too deep to reach and study directly C. because the mantle does not exist D. because the mantle is made of water","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"Why is the mantle still a mystery even though scientists know a lot about Earth?","choices":{"A":"because scientists do not care about the mantle","B":"because it is too deep to reach and study directly","C":"because the mantle does not exist","D":"because the mantle is made of water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the mantle is about 1,860 miles deep, but the deepest drill is only 8 miles. Scientists cannot yet reach it directly. That is why its exact nature is still unknown.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"system\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. set of connected things or methods for organizing information B. a single bird species that scientists study C. a type of feather found on all birds D. a machine used to catch birds for study","excerpt":"Many scientists study birds, and they are learning new information every day. Right now not all scientists agree about the best way to classify types of feathers. Here is one system that many scientists use...","stem":"What does \"system\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"set of connected things or methods for organizing information","B":"a single bird species that scientists study","C":"a type of feather found on all birds","D":"a machine used to catch birds for study"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"System means a set of connected things or methods for organizing information. The text describes a classification system for feather types.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many scientists study birds, and they are learning new information every day. Right now not all scientists agree about the best way to classify types of feathers. Here is one system that many scientists use..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about filoplume feathers? A. They help birds sense their environment and feather position B. They are the largest feathers on a bird\u0027s body C. They help birds fly faster and farther D. They are only found on young birds","excerpt":"Tiny filoplume feathers are attached to nerves. They help a bird sense its surroundings, and they let the bird know that its feathers are in place.","stem":"What is the main idea about filoplume feathers?","choices":{"A":"They help birds sense their environment and feather position","B":"They are the largest feathers on a bird\u0027s body","C":"They help birds fly faster and farther","D":"They are only found on young birds"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The passage explains that filoplume feathers connect to nerves and help birds sense surroundings and feather placement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Tiny filoplume feathers are attached to nerves. They help a bird sense its surroundings, and they let the bird know that its feathers are in place."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q013","read_aloud":"What are two functions of bristle feathers? A. Protecting eyes like eyelashes and helping locate food B. Helping birds fly and keeping them warm C. Attracting mates and building nests D. Making sounds and storing water","excerpt":"Stiff bristle feathers around a bird\u0027s eyes act like eyelashes. Some birds use bristle feathers around their mouths to locate food.","stem":"What are two functions of bristle feathers?","choices":{"A":"Protecting eyes like eyelashes and helping locate food","B":"Helping birds fly and keeping them warm","C":"Attracting mates and building nests","D":"Making sounds and storing water"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states bristle feathers around eyes act like eyelashes, and those around mouths help locate food.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Stiff bristle feathers around a bird\u0027s eyes act like eyelashes. Some birds use bristle feathers around their mouths to locate food."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q014","read_aloud":"If you were designing winter clothing for humans, how might you use the principle of down feathers? A. By creating layers that trap body heat close to the skin B. By making clothing that reflects all heat away from the body C. By using only one thick layer of material D. By designing clothing that lets heat escape easily","excerpt":"Soft, fluffy down feathers keep a bird warm by trapping body heat next to its skin.","stem":"If you were designing winter clothing for humans, how might you use the principle of down feathers?","choices":{"A":"By creating layers that trap body heat close to the skin","B":"By making clothing that reflects all heat away from the body","C":"By using only one thick layer of material","D":"By designing clothing that lets heat escape easily"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This asks students to apply the principle of down feathers trapping heat to human clothing design.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Soft, fluffy down feathers keep a bird warm by trapping body heat next to its skin."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q015","read_aloud":"How do contour feathers serve multiple purposes for birds? A. They provide both physical shape and visual coloration for the bird B. They only help birds fly and do not affect appearance C. They keep birds warm but do not affect how they look D. They help birds find food but do not cover their bodies","excerpt":"Contour feathers cover most of a bird\u0027s body. They give a bird its shape and colors.","stem":"How do contour feathers serve multiple purposes for birds?","choices":{"A":"They provide both physical shape and visual coloration for the bird","B":"They only help birds fly and do not affect appearance","C":"They keep birds warm but do not affect how they look","D":"They help birds find food but do not cover their bodies"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains contour feathers cover the body and serve dual functions: giving shape and providing colors.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Contour feathers cover most of a bird\u0027s body. They give a bird its shape and colors."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for abundant? A. scarce B. plentiful C. small D. empty","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for abundant?","choices":{"A":"scarce","B":"plentiful","C":"small","D":"empty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abundant means plentiful or commonly occurring.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q017","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose for writing Planet Earth? A. To tell a story about a scientist B. To inform readers about Earth\u0027s features and processes C. To persuade readers to become astronauts D. To entertain with jokes about the planet","excerpt":"The text includes facts about Earth\u0027s layers, tectonic plates, the water cycle, the atmosphere, time zones, and exploration.","stem":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose for writing Planet Earth?","choices":{"A":"To tell a story about a scientist","B":"To inform readers about Earth\u0027s features and processes","C":"To persuade readers to become astronauts","D":"To entertain with jokes about the planet"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text is informational, full of facts about Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes facts about Earth\u0027s layers, tectonic plates, the water cycle, the atmosphere, time zones, and exploration."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how satellites help people? A. They only take pictures of space. B. They help predict weather and warn of natural disasters. C. They cause earthquakes. D. They replace scientists.","excerpt":"\"Human-made satellites also help us study Earth. … Satellites can track storms or changes in Earth\u0027s climate.\"","stem":"What can you infer about how satellites help people?","choices":{"A":"They only take pictures of space.","B":"They help predict weather and warn of natural disasters.","C":"They cause earthquakes.","D":"They replace scientists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Tracking storms and climate helps with prediction and warnings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Human-made satellites also help us study Earth. … Satellites can track storms or changes in Earth\u0027s climate.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Why do scientists want to drill into the mantle? A. To find gold B. To take samples and learn more about its composition C. To create a new volcano D. To reach the core","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. … Geologists plan to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"Why do scientists want to drill into the mantle?","choices":{"A":"To find gold","B":"To take samples and learn more about its composition","C":"To create a new volcano","D":"To reach the core"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They want to take samples to learn about the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. … Geologists plan to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Why is it important that scientists can react quickly to natural disasters? A. So they can take photos B. To save lives and reduce damage C. To study the disasters later D. To make the disasters worse","excerpt":"\"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\"","stem":"Why is it important that scientists can react quickly to natural disasters?","choices":{"A":"So they can take photos","B":"To save lives and reduce damage","C":"To study the disasters later","D":"To make the disasters worse"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Quick reaction helps reduce devastation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as circulates? A. Stops B. Flows C. Freezes D. Sinks","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as circulates?","choices":{"A":"Stops","B":"Flows","C":"Freezes","D":"Sinks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Circulates means moves through a system, which is similar to flows.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What does the theory of Pangaea suggest? A. Earth has always had the same continents. B. Continents were once joined together in a single landmass. C. There were no oceans in the past. D. The Earth is flat.","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted.\"","stem":"What does the theory of Pangaea suggest?","choices":{"A":"Earth has always had the same continents.","B":"Continents were once joined together in a single landmass.","C":"There were no oceans in the past.","D":"The Earth is flat."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists believe continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q023","read_aloud":"Why are there five backup satellites? A. To replace active ones if needed B. To make the GPS faster C. To take photos of the moon D. To watch the weather","excerpt":"\"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twenty-four satellites are active. The other five are backups.\"","stem":"Why are there five backup satellites?","choices":{"A":"To replace active ones if needed","B":"To make the GPS faster","C":"To take photos of the moon","D":"To watch the weather"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Backup satellites are kept to replace active ones if they stop working.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twenty-four satellites are active. The other five are backups.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q024","read_aloud":"What might happen if polar caps melt? A. Ocean currents might shift and weather could change. B. The Earth would become a desert. C. The core would stop spinning. D. Time zones would disappear.","excerpt":"\"Water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge.\"","stem":"What might happen if polar caps melt?","choices":{"A":"Ocean currents might shift and weather could change.","B":"The Earth would become a desert.","C":"The core would stop spinning.","D":"Time zones would disappear."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text connects melting polar caps to shifting currents and weather changes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l06-q025","read_aloud":"Why was the ISS built? A. To study weightless environments B. To drill for oil C. To track hurricanes D. To store water","excerpt":"\"To learn how things work in a weightless environment, world scientists designed the International Space Station (ISS).\"","stem":"Why was the ISS built?","choices":{"A":"To study weightless environments","B":"To drill for oil","C":"To track hurricanes","D":"To store water"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states the ISS was designed to learn how things work in a weightless environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To learn how things work in a weightless environment, world scientists designed the International Space Station (ISS).\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q001","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \u0027contains\u0027 mean? Options: A. To hold or have inside, B. To throw away, C. To hide, D. To change","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \u0027contains\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"To hold or have inside,","B":"To throw away,","C":"To hide,","D":"To change"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To contain something means it is inside of it, like the gases held inside the troposphere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q002","read_aloud":"Why do scientists have to estimate the depth of the mantle? Options: A. They do not want to know, B. They cannot drill deep enough to see it directly, C. The mantle is too hot to measure, D. The mantle moves too fast","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean.\"","stem":"Why do scientists have to estimate the depth of the mantle? Options:","choices":{"A":"They do not want to know,","B":"They cannot drill deep enough to see it directly,","C":"The mantle is too hot to measure,","D":"The mantle moves too fast"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists estimate it because they haven\u0027t been able to drill down that far to measure it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q003","read_aloud":"How do satellites help people stay safe? Options: A. By preventing all natural disasters, B. By tracking storms and signaling natural disasters, C. By cleaning up the ocean, D. By moving the tectonic plates","excerpt":"\"Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge. Other satellites look for activity signaling earthquakes, tsunamis, or other natural disasters.\"","stem":"How do satellites help people stay safe? Options:","choices":{"A":"By preventing all natural disasters,","B":"By tracking storms and signaling natural disasters,","C":"By cleaning up the ocean,","D":"By moving the tectonic plates"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Satellites can watch for danger and signal natural disasters so people can react quickly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge. Other satellites look for activity signaling earthquakes, tsunamis, or other natural disasters.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q004","read_aloud":"If the sun did not heat Earth\u0027s water, what would happen to the water cycle? Options: A. It would speed up, B. It would stop working because water wouldn\u0027t turn into gas, C. It would create more rain, D. It would stay the same","excerpt":"\"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram. ... Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere.\"","stem":"If the sun did not heat Earth\u0027s water, what would happen to the water cycle? Options:","choices":{"A":"It would speed up,","B":"It would stop working because water wouldn\u0027t turn into gas,","C":"It would create more rain,","D":"It would stay the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Heat is needed to turn the water into vapor, so without it, the cycle could not continue.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram. ... Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q005","read_aloud":"How are the magnetic field and the compass related? Options: A. The compass points to the magnetic pole created by the core, B. They are not related, C. The magnetic field makes the compass stop working, D. The compass creates the magnetic field","excerpt":"\"Its movement around the inner core creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field. ... But did you know that the magnetic north pole is not located at the geographic North Pole?\"","stem":"How are the magnetic field and the compass related? Options:","choices":{"A":"The compass points to the magnetic pole created by the core,","B":"They are not related,","C":"The magnetic field makes the compass stop working,","D":"The compass creates the magnetic field"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The movement of the core creates the field, and the compass needle uses that field to point toward the magnetic north.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Its movement around the inner core creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field. ... But did you know that the magnetic north pole is not located at the geographic North Pole?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q006","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"circulates\" the same way as the excerpt? A. The blood circulates through the body, moving oxygen to all parts. B. The circulates dog ran around the yard. C. She circulates the cake by eating it all. D. The circulates book sat on the shelf.","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"circulates\" the same way as the excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The blood circulates through the body, moving oxygen to all parts.","B":"The circulates dog ran around the yard.","C":"She circulates the cake by eating it all.","D":"The circulates book sat on the shelf."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"In the excerpt, \"circulates\" means moving through a system. Blood moving through the body is also moving through a system. The other choices do not use \"circulates\" correctly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q007","read_aloud":"How is the inner core different from the outer core? A. The inner core is solid, and the outer core is liquid. B. They are exactly the same. C. The inner core is cooler than the outer core. D. The inner core is made of water.","excerpt":"\"The inner core is solid iron. It may spin faster than Earth\u0027s other layers. The whole core is estimated to be 11,000 degrees Fahrenheit.\"","stem":"How is the inner core different from the outer core?","choices":{"A":"The inner core is solid, and the outer core is liquid.","B":"They are exactly the same.","C":"The inner core is cooler than the outer core.","D":"The inner core is made of water."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the inner core is solid iron. Earlier, it says the outer core is liquid. This is a key difference between the two layers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The inner core is solid iron. It may spin faster than Earth\u0027s other layers. The whole core is estimated to be 11,000 degrees Fahrenheit.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author mention meteoroids in the section about the atmosphere? A. to show that the atmosphere protects us from space objects B. to tell a scary story C. to prove that meteoroids never exist D. to describe how to catch meteoroids","excerpt":"\"The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids.\"","stem":"Why does the author mention meteoroids in the section about the atmosphere?","choices":{"A":"to show that the atmosphere protects us from space objects","B":"to tell a scary story","C":"to prove that meteoroids never exist","D":"to describe how to catch meteoroids"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author wants to show one important job of the atmosphere: protecting Earth. Meteoroids burn up in the atmosphere, so they rarely hit the surface. This shows why the atmosphere matters.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q009","read_aloud":"Why are five GPS satellites kept as backups? A. because they are broken B. so that if an active satellite fails, a backup can take its place C. because they are too old to use D. because there are too many satellites","excerpt":"\"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twenty-four satellites are active. The other five are backups.\"","stem":"Why are five GPS satellites kept as backups?","choices":{"A":"because they are broken","B":"so that if an active satellite fails, a backup can take its place","C":"because they are too old to use","D":"because there are too many satellites"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Backups are extra resources kept ready in case something goes wrong. If one of the 24 active satellites stops working, a backup can be used so GPS still functions properly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twenty-four satellites are active. The other five are backups.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the author explain time zones using Anchorage and Los Angeles as examples? A. because those cities are the only ones with time zones B. to give a clear, real example that helps readers understand the idea C. because the author lives in those cities D. to show that time zones do not matter","excerpt":"\"Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it.\"","stem":"Why does the author explain time zones using Anchorage and Los Angeles as examples?","choices":{"A":"because those cities are the only ones with time zones","B":"to give a clear, real example that helps readers understand the idea","C":"because the author lives in those cities","D":"to show that time zones do not matter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Using real cities makes an abstract idea concrete. Readers can picture Anchorage and Los Angeles and understand that when it is noon in one place, it is 1 p.m. just one zone to the east.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones. Each time zone is one hour ahead of the zone to the west of it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"bristle\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. short and rough B. long and smooth C. soft and fluffy D. colorful and bright","excerpt":"Stiff bristle feathers around a bird\u0027s eyes act like eyelashes.","stem":"What does \"bristle\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"short and rough","B":"long and smooth","C":"soft and fluffy","D":"colorful and bright"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Bristle means short and rough. The text describes these feathers as stiff and acting like eyelashes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Stiff bristle feathers around a bird\u0027s eyes act like eyelashes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q012","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the importance of flight feathers? A. They are essential for controlled flight and movement B. They are only important for decoration C. They help birds but are not necessary for flying D. They are only found on young birds learning to fly","excerpt":"The flight feathers on a bird\u0027s wings lift it up and move it forward. Flight feathers on the tail help a bird steer and keep its balance.","stem":"What can you infer about the importance of flight feathers?","choices":{"A":"They are essential for controlled flight and movement","B":"They are only important for decoration","C":"They help birds but are not necessary for flying","D":"They are only found on young birds learning to fly"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes flight feathers as providing lift, forward motion, steering, and balance, suggesting they\u0027re essential for controlled flight.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The flight feathers on a bird\u0027s wings lift it up and move it forward. Flight feathers on the tail help a bird steer and keep its balance."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q013","read_aloud":"What is the effect of the anhinga not waterproofing its feathers? A. Wet feathers help it dive deep to hunt underwater prey B. It can fly higher than other water birds C. It stays warmer in cold water D. It can catch prey on land more easily","excerpt":"Most birds make a special oil to waterproof their feathers, but not the anhinga. The weight of its wet feathers helps the hungry hunter dive deep down in search of fish, crayfish, and shrimp.","stem":"What is the effect of the anhinga not waterproofing its feathers?","choices":{"A":"Wet feathers help it dive deep to hunt underwater prey","B":"It can fly higher than other water birds","C":"It stays warmer in cold water","D":"It can catch prey on land more easily"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text explains that the anhinga\u0027s wet, heavy feathers help it dive deep to hunt aquatic prey.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most birds make a special oil to waterproof their feathers, but not the anhinga. The weight of its wet feathers helps the hungry hunter dive deep down in search of fish, crayfish, and shrimp."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q014","read_aloud":"If you were designing boots for walking on snow, what feature might you add based on the ptarmigan\u0027s adaptation? A. Wide, flat soles that spread weight like snowshoes B. Sharp spikes to dig into the snow C. Thin soles to feel the ground better D. Heavy weights to help you sink into the snow","excerpt":"Each autumn, willow ptarmigans grow a thick layer of feathers on top of their toes. Like snowshoes the feathers increase the size of the birds\u0027 feet, so they can shuffle across the snow instead of sinking in.","stem":"If you were designing boots for walking on snow, what feature might you add based on the ptarmigan\u0027s adaptation?","choices":{"A":"Wide, flat soles that spread weight like snowshoes","B":"Sharp spikes to dig into the snow","C":"Thin soles to feel the ground better","D":"Heavy weights to help you sink into the snow"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the ptarmigan\u0027s snowshoe-like toe feathers to human boot design for snow walking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Each autumn, willow ptarmigans grow a thick layer of feathers on top of their toes. Like snowshoes the feathers increase the size of the birds\u0027 feet, so they can shuffle across the snow instead of sinking in."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q015","read_aloud":"How does the structure of penguin belly feathers relate to their function? A. Tightly packed feathers create a slick surface for sliding on ice B. Loose feathers trap more air for warmth while swimming C. Colorful feathers help them attract mates on ice D. Long feathers help them fly over ice formations","excerpt":"Emperor penguins have tightly packed belly feathers that form firm, slick surfaces. The feathers make it easy for these birds to slide across ice and snow.","stem":"How does the structure of penguin belly feathers relate to their function?","choices":{"A":"Tightly packed feathers create a slick surface for sliding on ice","B":"Loose feathers trap more air for warmth while swimming","C":"Colorful feathers help them attract mates on ice","D":"Long feathers help them fly over ice formations"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text connects the tightly packed feather structure to the function of creating a slick surface for sliding on ice and snow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Emperor penguins have tightly packed belly feathers that form firm, slick surfaces. The feathers make it easy for these birds to slide across ice and snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q016","read_aloud":"How does the word circulates help you understand the water cycle? A. It shows water stays in one place. B. It shows water moves around in a repeating loop. C. It shows water disappears. D. It shows water only goes up.","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water cycle. … Then it starts the process over again.\"","stem":"How does the word circulates help you understand the water cycle?","choices":{"A":"It shows water stays in one place.","B":"It shows water moves around in a repeating loop.","C":"It shows water disappears.","D":"It shows water only goes up."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Circulates means moves through a system, like a cycle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water cycle. … Then it starts the process over again.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What effect does the Aqua satellite have on our understanding of Earth? A. It helps scientists see through clouds and monitor the water cycle. B. It causes rain. C. It blocks the sun. D. It creates earthquakes.","excerpt":"\"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"What effect does the Aqua satellite have on our understanding of Earth?","choices":{"A":"It helps scientists see through clouds and monitor the water cycle.","B":"It causes rain.","C":"It blocks the sun.","D":"It creates earthquakes."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The satellite helps scientists monitor the water cycle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q018","read_aloud":"Which layer is more important for protecting us from the sun\u0027s harmful rays? A. The troposphere B. The stratosphere C. The crust D. The mantle","excerpt":"\"The troposphere contains the air we breathe. The stratosphere contains ozone that blocks harmful rays.\"","stem":"Which layer is more important for protecting us from the sun\u0027s harmful rays?","choices":{"A":"The troposphere","B":"The stratosphere","C":"The crust","D":"The mantle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The stratosphere contains ozone that blocks harmful rays.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere contains the air we breathe. The stratosphere contains ozone that blocks harmful rays.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this comparison to the sun? A. To show the core is cold B. To help readers understand how extremely hot the core is C. To say Earth is a star D. To confuse the reader","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s core may be as hot as the surface of the sun.\"","stem":"Why does the author include this comparison to the sun?","choices":{"A":"To show the core is cold","B":"To help readers understand how extremely hot the core is","C":"To say Earth is a star","D":"To confuse the reader"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing to the sun emphasizes the extreme heat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s core may be as hot as the surface of the sun.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Do you think GPS is a reliable way to navigate? Why? A. No, because satellites often fail. B. Yes, because many satellites work together to give accurate information. C. No, because it uses too much power. D. Yes, because it is free.","excerpt":"\"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twentyfour satellites are active. … Signals from four or more satellites are needed to accurately determine your position.\"","stem":"Do you think GPS is a reliable way to navigate? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because satellites often fail.","B":"Yes, because many satellites work together to give accurate information.","C":"No, because it uses too much power.","D":"Yes, because it is free."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Multiple satellites work together for accuracy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twentyfour satellites are active. … Signals from four or more satellites are needed to accurately determine your position.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q021","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for abundant? A. Plentiful B. Scarce C. Full D. Rich","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for abundant?","choices":{"A":"Plentiful","B":"Scarce","C":"Full","D":"Rich"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abundant means plentiful. Scarce means there is very little, which is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q022","read_aloud":"What creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field? A. The movement of the liquid outer core B. The solid inner core C. The wind in the atmosphere D. The ocean tides","excerpt":"\"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\"","stem":"What creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field?","choices":{"A":"The movement of the liquid outer core","B":"The solid inner core","C":"The wind in the atmosphere","D":"The ocean tides"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the movement (flowing) of the outer core around the inner core creates the magnetic field.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q023","read_aloud":"What unusual event happens to the magnetic poles? A. They never move. B. They sometimes switch places. C. They disappear. D. They become bigger.","excerpt":"\"The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places. When this happens, Earth\u0027s magnetic field temporarily becomes twisted and scrambled.\"","stem":"What unusual event happens to the magnetic poles?","choices":{"A":"They never move.","B":"They sometimes switch places.","C":"They disappear.","D":"They become bigger."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions that the north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places. When this happens, Earth\u0027s magnetic field temporarily becomes twisted and scrambled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How are the troposphere and stratosphere different? A. The troposphere has weather; the stratosphere has ozone. B. The troposphere is hot; the stratosphere is cold. C. The troposphere is near space; the stratosphere is on the ground. D. There is no difference between them.","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\"","stem":"How are the troposphere and stratosphere different?","choices":{"A":"The troposphere has weather; the stratosphere has ozone.","B":"The troposphere is hot; the stratosphere is cold.","C":"The troposphere is near space; the stratosphere is on the ground.","D":"There is no difference between them."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says weather happens in the troposphere, while the stratosphere contains ozone to block sun rays.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l07-q025","read_aloud":"Why is ocean exploration important? A. It helps us understand Earth\u0027s geologic processes. B. It helps us find new time zones. C. It allows us to live underwater. D. It stops tsunamis from happening.","excerpt":"\"But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored. That is changing. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration is studying deepwater canyons...\"","stem":"Why is ocean exploration important?","choices":{"A":"It helps us understand Earth\u0027s geologic processes.","B":"It helps us find new time zones.","C":"It allows us to live underwater.","D":"It stops tsunamis from happening."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says missions help explain Earth\u0027s geologic processes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored. That is changing. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration is studying deepwater canyons...\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What does \u0027boring\u0027 mean in this context? Options: A. To be uninterested, B. To drill a hole, C. To move slowly, D. To break something by hand","excerpt":"\"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\"","stem":"What does \u0027boring\u0027 mean in this context? Options:","choices":{"A":"To be uninterested,","B":"To drill a hole,","C":"To move slowly,","D":"To break something by hand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Boring refers to the action of drilling deep into something, such as the earth\u0027s crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q002","read_aloud":"Why is this project important to scientists? Options: A. They want to build a house there, B. It will help solve the mystery of what the mantle is made of, C. They want to break the world record, D. They want to make the ocean deeper","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"Why is this project important to scientists? Options:","choices":{"A":"They want to build a house there,","B":"It will help solve the mystery of what the mantle is made of,","C":"They want to break the world record,","D":"They want to make the ocean deeper"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Getting physical samples would allow them to finally understand the mantle\u0027s composition.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q003","read_aloud":"Why might it be useful for a country to use a half-hour time zone instead of a full hour? Options: A. It makes clocks cheaper, B. It fits better with their specific location or needs, C. It makes the day longer, D. It stops time from moving","excerpt":"\"Some regions divide time zones by half hours. Iran, Newfoundland in Canada, and parts of Australia are examples.\"","stem":"Why might it be useful for a country to use a half-hour time zone instead of a full hour? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes clocks cheaper,","B":"It fits better with their specific location or needs,","C":"It makes the day longer,","D":"It stops time from moving"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Countries choose exceptions like half-hour zones to better organize time based on their local needs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some regions divide time zones by half hours. Iran, Newfoundland in Canada, and parts of Australia are examples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author ask \"What will we discover next?\" at the end of the section? Options: A. Because the author forgot the answer, B. To encourage readers to think about future discoveries, C. To show that scientists have stopped learning, D. To show that space is empty","excerpt":"\"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\"","stem":"Why does the author ask \"What will we discover next?\" at the end of the section? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because the author forgot the answer,","B":"To encourage readers to think about future discoveries,","C":"To show that scientists have stopped learning,","D":"To show that space is empty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This question makes the reader think about how much more there is to learn and explore on Earth and in space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Based on this, is technology more important for preventing disasters or for helping people after they happen? Options: A. Only preventing, B. Only helping, C. Both are important for reducing harm, D. Neither is important","excerpt":"\"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\"","stem":"Based on this, is technology more important for preventing disasters or for helping people after they happen? Options:","choices":{"A":"Only preventing,","B":"Only helping,","C":"Both are important for reducing harm,","D":"Neither is important"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Technology is helpful for spotting problems before they happen and for managing the response, which both reduce the total damage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q006","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"adopted\"? A. accepted B. rejected C. started D. used","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"adopted\"?","choices":{"A":"accepted","B":"rejected","C":"started","D":"used"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Adopted\" means started to use or accepted. The opposite would be rejected, which means refused to use. The text mentions exceptions, which are areas that did not adopt the standard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the exact number 57,000 orbits? A. to make the paragraph longer B. to show that the ISS has been working hard for a long time C. to prove that 2013 was the best year D. to describe what an orbit is","excerpt":"\"As of 2013, ISS completed more than 57,000 orbits around Earth. Exploration continues to expand.\"","stem":"Why does the author include the exact number 57,000 orbits?","choices":{"A":"to make the paragraph longer","B":"to show that the ISS has been working hard for a long time","C":"to prove that 2013 was the best year","D":"to describe what an orbit is"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"57,000 orbits is a very large number. It shows readers that the ISS has been orbiting Earth many times over many years. This proves that space exploration is active and ongoing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As of 2013, ISS completed more than 57,000 orbits around Earth. Exploration continues to expand.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q008","read_aloud":"[Diagram with labels] How does the caption help readers understand the diagram? A. It tells readers what the diagram is about. B. It makes the diagram more confusing. C. It hides the important information. D. It replaces the need for the diagram.","excerpt":"This illustration shows the five layers of Earth\u0027s atmosphere.","stem":"[Diagram with labels] How does the caption help readers understand the diagram?","choices":{"A":"It tells readers what the diagram is about.","B":"It makes the diagram more confusing.","C":"It hides the important information.","D":"It replaces the need for the diagram."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"A caption explains what a visual feature shows. The caption tells readers that the diagram illustrates the five layers of Earth\u0027s atmosphere. This helps readers know what to look for in the picture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: This illustration shows the five layers of Earth\u0027s atmosphere."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think spending $1 billion to drill into the mantle is worth it? Why or why not? A. No, because money should never be spent on science. B. Yes, because learning about the mantle could help us understand volcanoes, earthquakes, and how Earth works. C. No, because scientists already know everything about Earth. D. Yes, because drilling is fun.","excerpt":"\"To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples. This $1 billion project is planned to start drilling in 2020.\"","stem":"Do you think spending $1 billion to drill into the mantle is worth it? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because money should never be spent on science.","B":"Yes, because learning about the mantle could help us understand volcanoes, earthquakes, and how Earth works.","C":"No, because scientists already know everything about Earth.","D":"Yes, because drilling is fun."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The mantle affects volcanoes, earthquakes, and Earth\u0027s structure. Understanding it better could help predict natural disasters and protect people. The text shows this knowledge is still missing, so the project has real value.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples. This $1 billion project is planned to start drilling in 2020.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the author end with a question? A. because the author does not know the answer B. to make readers curious and excited about future discoveries C. because the book is finished D. to confuse readers","excerpt":"\"People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\"","stem":"Why does the author end with a question?","choices":{"A":"because the author does not know the answer","B":"to make readers curious and excited about future discoveries","C":"because the book is finished","D":"to confuse readers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ending with a question invites readers to think about the future. It makes them curious about what scientists will discover next. This is a good way to end an informational text because it keeps readers interested in learning more.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"contour\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. related to the shape or outline of something B. related to the color or pattern of something C. related to the size or weight of something D. related to the sound or movement of something","excerpt":"Contour feathers cover most of a bird\u0027s body. They give a bird its shape and colors.","stem":"What does \"contour\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"related to the shape or outline of something","B":"related to the color or pattern of something","C":"related to the size or weight of something","D":"related to the sound or movement of something"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Contour means related to the shape or outline. The text states these feathers give birds their shape and colors.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Contour feathers cover most of a bird\u0027s body. They give a bird its shape and colors."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about semiplume feathers? A. They work together with down feathers for insulation and water protection B. They are the most colorful feathers on a bird C. They help birds fly faster than other feather types D. They are only found on water birds","excerpt":"Semiplume feathers work with down feathers to keep birds warm and dry.","stem":"What is the main idea about semiplume feathers?","choices":{"A":"They work together with down feathers for insulation and water protection","B":"They are the most colorful feathers on a bird","C":"They help birds fly faster than other feather types","D":"They are only found on water birds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The passage explains semiplume feathers collaborate with down feathers to provide warmth and dryness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Semiplume feathers work with down feathers to keep birds warm and dry."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the echidna\u0027s hunting ability? A. It can find prey using senses beyond sight, hearing, or touch B. It must see its prey before it can catch it C. It only hunts during the day when it can see well D. It needs to touch prey with its beak to find it","excerpt":"The most amazing thing about the echidna\u0027s beak is something you can\u0027t see. The beak has sensors inside it. The sensors detect electrical signals given off by living creatures. That means an echidna can locate prey without seeing, hearing, or touching it.","stem":"What can you infer about the echidna\u0027s hunting ability?","choices":{"A":"It can find prey using senses beyond sight, hearing, or touch","B":"It must see its prey before it can catch it","C":"It only hunts during the day when it can see well","D":"It needs to touch prey with its beak to find it"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes electrical sensors in the beak that detect prey signals, suggesting the echidna can hunt using this unique sense.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The most amazing thing about the echidna\u0027s beak is something you can\u0027t see. The beak has sensors inside it. The sensors detect electrical signals given off by living creatures. That means an echidna can locate prey without seeing, hearing, or touching it."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Do you think the echidna\u0027s defense strategy is effective? Why or why not? A. Yes, because rolling into a spiny ball deters most predators from attacking B. No, because predators can still bite through the spines easily C. Yes, but only if the echidna is in a forest environment D. No, because the echidna cannot move when rolled up","excerpt":"When a predator approaches, an echidna rolls itself up into a ball. The ball appears to be nothing but spines. Predators usually think twice before chomping down.","stem":"Do you think the echidna\u0027s defense strategy is effective? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because rolling into a spiny ball deters most predators from attacking","B":"No, because predators can still bite through the spines easily","C":"Yes, but only if the echidna is in a forest environment","D":"No, because the echidna cannot move when rolled up"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text states predators \"think twice before chomping down,\" suggesting the spiny ball defense is effective at deterring attacks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When a predator approaches, an echidna rolls itself up into a ball. The ball appears to be nothing but spines. Predators usually think twice before chomping down."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q015","read_aloud":"If you could design a new animal adaptation based on the echidna\u0027s temperature control, what might it do? A. Allow animals to slow their body functions to survive with less food during hard times B. Help animals run faster by increasing their body temperature C. Make animals change color to match their environment D. Help animals grow bigger by speeding up their digestion","excerpt":"The echidna has one more unique feature. The echidna\u0027s body temperature is about 85 to 89 degrees Fahrenheit... When they need to, echidnas can turn down their body temperature even lower than normal. When they do this, all their body functions, such as breathing, heart rate, and digestion, slow down too.","stem":"If you could design a new animal adaptation based on the echidna\u0027s temperature control, what might it do?","choices":{"A":"Allow animals to slow their body functions to survive with less food during hard times","B":"Help animals run faster by increasing their body temperature","C":"Make animals change color to match their environment","D":"Help animals grow bigger by speeding up their digestion"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to create a new adaptation based on the echidna\u0027s ability to lower body temperature and slow functions to conserve energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The echidna has one more unique feature. The echidna\u0027s body temperature is about 85 to 89 degrees Fahrenheit... When they need to, echidnas can turn down their body temperature even lower than normal. When they do this, all their body functions, such as breathing, heart rate, and digestion, slow down too."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q016","read_aloud":"What does it mean that China adopted only one time zone? A. China rejected all time zones. B. China chose to use only one time zone even though it crosses three. C. China has no time zones. D. China adopted all three time zones.","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions. China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\"","stem":"What does it mean that China adopted only one time zone?","choices":{"A":"China rejected all time zones.","B":"China chose to use only one time zone even though it crosses three.","C":"China has no time zones.","D":"China adopted all three time zones."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Adopted means started using; China chose one zone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions. China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q017","read_aloud":"How does the water cycle diagram help you understand the text? A. It shows the colors of water. B. It visually explains how water moves from the ground to the sky and back. C. It replaces the need to read. D. It shows only rain.","excerpt":"The page includes a diagram showing the water cycle with arrows for evaporation, condensation, and precipitation.","stem":"How does the water cycle diagram help you understand the text?","choices":{"A":"It shows the colors of water.","B":"It visually explains how water moves from the ground to the sky and back.","C":"It replaces the need to read.","D":"It shows only rain."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Diagrams make processes easier to understand visually.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The page includes a diagram showing the water cycle with arrows for evaporation, condensation, and precipitation."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q018","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about how scientists study Earth\u0027s interior? A. They use only one method. B. They use many methods, including volcanoes, drilling, and satellites. C. They never study the interior. D. They only guess.","excerpt":"Scientists study the mantle through volcanoes (Mount Erebus), through drilling projects, and through satellites.","stem":"What can you conclude about how scientists study Earth\u0027s interior?","choices":{"A":"They use only one method.","B":"They use many methods, including volcanoes, drilling, and satellites.","C":"They never study the interior.","D":"They only guess."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes multiple methods.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists study the mantle through volcanoes (Mount Erebus), through drilling projects, and through satellites."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q019","read_aloud":"∗∗ ∗∗Doyouthinkspending1billionprojectisplannedtostartdrillingin2020.\"∗∗ ∗∗Doyouthinkspending1 billion to drill into the mantle is a good use of money? Why? A. No, because the money could be used for other things. B. Yes, because learning about Earth\u0027s interior could help us understand earthquakes and volcanoes. C. No, because we already know everything. D. Yes, because it would be fun.","excerpt":"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles thick. This 1billionprojectisplannedtostartdrillingin2020.","stem":"∗∗ ∗∗Doyouthinkspending1billionprojectisplannedtostartdrillingin2020.\"∗∗ ∗∗Doyouthinkspending1 billion to drill into the mantle is a good use of money? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because the money could be used for other things.","B":"Yes, because learning about Earth\u0027s interior could help us understand earthquakes and volcanoes.","C":"No, because we already know everything.","D":"Yes, because it would be fun."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The knowledge could have practical benefits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles thick. This 1billionprojectisplannedtostartdrillingin2020."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Write one question that you would like scientists to answer about the unexplored ocean floor. A. \"Are there new animals down there?\" B. \"What is the color of the water?\" C. \"How many ships have sunk?\" D. \"Is it cold?\"","excerpt":"\"Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Write one question that you would like scientists to answer about the unexplored ocean floor.","choices":{"A":"\"Are there new animals down there?\"","B":"\"What is the color of the water?\"","C":"\"How many ships have sunk?\"","D":"\"Is it cold?\""},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Exploring the unknown raises many scientific questions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q021","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses adopted correctly? A. The cat adopted a new home. B. The boy adopted a different route to school. C. The teacher adopted the chalk. D. The dog adopted a loud bark.","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses adopted correctly?","choices":{"A":"The cat adopted a new home.","B":"The boy adopted a different route to school.","C":"The teacher adopted the chalk.","D":"The dog adopted a loud bark."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Adopted means to choose or start using a new method or path. Choosing a new route fits this meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q022","read_aloud":"What does the word \"Its\" refer to in this sentence? A. The crust B. The liquid outer core C. The atmosphere D. The satellite","excerpt":"\"Its movement around the inner core creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field. Enormous pressure and radiation keep this layer hot.\"","stem":"What does the word \"Its\" refer to in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"The crust","B":"The liquid outer core","C":"The atmosphere","D":"The satellite"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph is about the liquid outer core. \"Its movement\" refers to the movement of that liquid outer core.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Its movement around the inner core creates Earth\u0027s magnetic field. Enormous pressure and radiation keep this layer hot.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q023","read_aloud":"What is the main purpose of the Aqua satellite? A. To monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle B. To drill into the mantle C. To study the magnetic poles D. To send astronauts to space","excerpt":"\"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"What is the main purpose of the Aqua satellite?","choices":{"A":"To monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle","B":"To drill into the mantle","C":"To study the magnetic poles","D":"To send astronauts to space"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Aqua monitors Earth\u0027s water cycle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q024","read_aloud":"Why do meteoroids usually burn up in the atmosphere? A. The air is very cold. B. Friction with the air creates heat. C. They hit birds in the sky. D. The ozone layer eats them.","excerpt":"\"A meteoroid creates friction as it moves rapidly through the atmosphere. This usually causes the object to burn up.\"","stem":"Why do meteoroids usually burn up in the atmosphere?","choices":{"A":"The air is very cold.","B":"Friction with the air creates heat.","C":"They hit birds in the sky.","D":"The ozone layer eats them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that friction causes the object to burn up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A meteoroid creates friction as it moves rapidly through the atmosphere. This usually causes the object to burn up.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l08-q025","read_aloud":"Why are four or more satellites needed for GPS? A. One satellite is too slow. B. Four satellites are needed to accurately find a position. C. The government requires it. D. Satellites often break.","excerpt":"\"Signals from four or more satellites are needed to accurately determine your position.\"","stem":"Why are four or more satellites needed for GPS?","choices":{"A":"One satellite is too slow.","B":"Four satellites are needed to accurately find a position.","C":"The government requires it.","D":"Satellites often break."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that signals from four or more satellites are needed for accuracy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Signals from four or more satellites are needed to accurately determine your position.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q001","read_aloud":"If the troposphere \u0027contains\u0027 the air, what is a synonym for this word? Options: A. Holds, B. Hides, C. Removes, D. Lacks","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. ... Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\"","stem":"If the troposphere \u0027contains\u0027 the air, what is a synonym for this word? Options:","choices":{"A":"Holds,","B":"Hides,","C":"Removes,","D":"Lacks"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To hold inside is what it means to contain, making \u0027holds\u0027 a perfect synonym.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. ... Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q002","read_aloud":"What can you infer about time zones? Options: A. They are strictly the same everywhere, B. They are flexible and can be changed to fit human needs, C. They were created by nature, D. They never change","excerpt":"\"Some regions divide time zones by half hours. ... Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions.\"","stem":"What can you infer about time zones? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are strictly the same everywhere,","B":"They are flexible and can be changed to fit human needs,","C":"They were created by nature,","D":"They never change"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The existence of exceptions shows that humans organize time zones in ways that are convenient for their specific countries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some regions divide time zones by half hours. ... Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q003","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is the main benefit of satellites? Options: A. They take nice photos, B. They help us understand and protect our planet, C. They make satellites more expensive, D. They tell us where to go on vacation","excerpt":"\"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. ... For example, water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. ... Other satellites look for activity signaling earthquakes, tsunamis, or other natural disasters.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is the main benefit of satellites? Options:","choices":{"A":"They take nice photos,","B":"They help us understand and protect our planet,","C":"They make satellites more expensive,","D":"They tell us where to go on vacation"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Satellites collect data to monitor the planet\u0027s health and warn us about dangerous changes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. ... For example, water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. ... Other satellites look for activity signaling earthquakes, tsunamis, or other natural disasters.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q004","read_aloud":"If we could control tectonic plates, would we? Why? Options: A. Yes, to stop earthquakes and tsunamis, B. No, because it is boring, C. Yes, to make more mountains, D. No, because it is too hard","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. ... The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\"","stem":"If we could control tectonic plates, would we? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"Yes, to stop earthquakes and tsunamis,","B":"No, because it is boring,","C":"Yes, to make more mountains,","D":"No, because it is too hard"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Since plates cause disasters, controlling them could prevent harm to people, though in reality, it is impossible.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. ... The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q005","read_aloud":"Is spending $1 billion on this project a good idea? Why? Options: A. No, it costs too much money, B. Yes, because learning about Earth\u0027s structure is important for science, C. Yes, just for fun, D. No, because we already know everything","excerpt":"\"To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples. ... This $1 billion project is planned to start drilling in 2020.\"","stem":"Is spending $1 billion on this project a good idea? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, it costs too much money,","B":"Yes, because learning about Earth\u0027s structure is important for science,","C":"Yes, just for fun,","D":"No, because we already know everything"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This is a subjective question based on the text\u0027s importance of science; a good answer considers the scientific value of discovering new knowledge about Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples. ... This $1 billion project is planned to start drilling in 2020.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q006","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"molten\" correctly? A. The molten chocolate was warm and liquid. B. The molten ice cube was frozen solid. C. She molten her shoes before walking. D. The molten book had many pages.","excerpt":"\"Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"molten\" correctly?","choices":{"A":"The molten chocolate was warm and liquid.","B":"The molten ice cube was frozen solid.","C":"She molten her shoes before walking.","D":"The molten book had many pages."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Molten\" means melted and hot enough to be liquid. Warm, liquid chocolate fits this meaning. An ice cube is frozen, not molten. The other choices do not use \"molten\" correctly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q007","read_aloud":"How does the example of the Himalayas support the author\u0027s point? A. It proves that mountains never change. B. It gives a real, current example that shows tectonic plates are still working today. C. It shows that mountains are getting smaller. D. It describes a place to visit on vacation.","excerpt":"\"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\"","stem":"How does the example of the Himalayas support the author\u0027s point?","choices":{"A":"It proves that mountains never change.","B":"It gives a real, current example that shows tectonic plates are still working today.","C":"It shows that mountains are getting smaller.","D":"It describes a place to visit on vacation."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The Himalayas growing taller right now proves that tectonic plate pressure is not just something from the past. It is still happening today. This real example makes the author\u0027s point stronger and more believable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q008","read_aloud":"Which layer of the atmosphere do you think is most important for protecting life, and why? A. The troposphere, because it has the air we breathe. B. The stratosphere, because it blocks harmful sun rays and space objects. C. Both are important for different reasons. D. Neither layer matters at all.","excerpt":"\"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun. The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids.\"","stem":"Which layer of the atmosphere do you think is most important for protecting life, and why?","choices":{"A":"The troposphere, because it has the air we breathe.","B":"The stratosphere, because it blocks harmful sun rays and space objects.","C":"Both are important for different reasons.","D":"Neither layer matters at all."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The troposphere gives us air to breathe, which is essential for life. The stratosphere protects us from harmful rays and meteoroids. Both layers do different but equally important jobs. Choosing just one ignores the other vital role.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun. The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q009","read_aloud":"If scientists could not use underwater machines, how would our understanding of the ocean change? A. We would know more about the ocean. B. We would know much less because humans cannot dive deep enough without machines. C. The ocean would disappear. D. Fish would stop swimming.","excerpt":"\"Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution uses a human occupied vehicle and other underwater machines to explore and map even deeper waters.\"","stem":"If scientists could not use underwater machines, how would our understanding of the ocean change?","choices":{"A":"We would know more about the ocean.","B":"We would know much less because humans cannot dive deep enough without machines.","C":"The ocean would disappear.","D":"Fish would stop swimming."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The ocean is very deep and dangerous for humans. Machines like ROVs let scientists explore places people cannot go. Without these machines, we would have much less information about the deep ocean.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution uses a human occupied vehicle and other underwater machines to explore and map even deeper waters.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"brittle\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. very easily broken B. very strong and durable C. soft and flexible D. colorful and bright","excerpt":"Its feathers have brittle tips that crumble into a dusty powder.","stem":"What does \"brittle\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"very easily broken","B":"very strong and durable","C":"soft and flexible","D":"colorful and bright"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Brittle means very easily broken. The text describes feather tips that crumble into powder, showing they break easily.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Its feathers have brittle tips that crumble into a dusty powder."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about echidna body temperature? A. A cooler body temperature may contribute to the echidna\u0027s long lifespan B. All small mammals have the same body temperature C. Echidnas live shorter lives than other mammals D. Body temperature does not affect how long animals live","excerpt":"Scientists think that a cool body temperature might help the echidna live longer. Surprisingly, echidnas live as long as 45 years in the wild. Other small mammals don\u0027t live nearly as long.","stem":"What is the main idea about echidna body temperature?","choices":{"A":"A cooler body temperature may contribute to the echidna\u0027s long lifespan","B":"All small mammals have the same body temperature","C":"Echidnas live shorter lives than other mammals","D":"Body temperature does not affect how long animals live"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The passage connects the echidna\u0027s cool body temperature to its surprisingly long lifespan compared to other small mammals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists think that a cool body temperature might help the echidna live longer. Surprisingly, echidnas live as long as 45 years in the wild. Other small mammals don\u0027t live nearly as long."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q012","read_aloud":"What can you infer about torpor as a survival strategy? A. It helps animals conserve energy when food is scarce or conditions are difficult B. It makes animals more active and able to find more food C. It only works during summer months when food is plentiful D. It is dangerous and should be avoided by all animals","excerpt":"When in torpor, the echidna uses less energy. So it needs less food. This is useful during the winter, when prey is harder to find. It\u0027s also helpful during times of crisis, such as when a forest fire occurs.","stem":"What can you infer about torpor as a survival strategy?","choices":{"A":"It helps animals conserve energy when food is scarce or conditions are difficult","B":"It makes animals more active and able to find more food","C":"It only works during summer months when food is plentiful","D":"It is dangerous and should be avoided by all animals"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text explains torpor reduces energy needs, helping echidnas survive winter food scarcity and crises like fires.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When in torpor, the echidna uses less energy. So it needs less food. This is useful during the winter, when prey is harder to find. It\u0027s also helpful during times of crisis, such as when a forest fire occurs."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think the author\u0027s conclusion about echidnas is well-supported? Why or why not? A. Yes, because the text provides multiple examples of unique adaptations that aid survival B. No, because the text only mentions one adaptation C. Yes, but only for echidnas living in Australia D. No, because other small mammals have similar adaptations","excerpt":"Scientists think this trait is one reason that the echidna has managed to survive. But it\u0027s just one of the adaptations that makes the tiny, spiny echidna one of the most amazing creatures on Earth.","stem":"Do you think the author\u0027s conclusion about echidnas is well-supported? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because the text provides multiple examples of unique adaptations that aid survival","B":"No, because the text only mentions one adaptation","C":"Yes, but only for echidnas living in Australia","D":"No, because other small mammals have similar adaptations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes multiple adaptations (beak sensors, spines, digging ability, temperature control, torpor) supporting the conclusion that echidnas have many amazing survival traits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists think this trait is one reason that the echidna has managed to survive. But it\u0027s just one of the adaptations that makes the tiny, spiny echidna one of the most amazing creatures on Earth."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q014","read_aloud":"If you were creating a new animal for a story, how might you adapt the echidna\u0027s spine defense for a different environment? A. Give it spines that can change color to blend with surroundings while still providing protection B. Make the spines soft and fluffy to attract friends instead of deterring predators C. Remove the spines entirely to make the animal faster D. Make the spines only appear when the animal is sleeping","excerpt":"The echidna\u0027s spines are like a coat of armor. They protect the echidna from predators such as the dingo, a kind of wild dog.","stem":"If you were creating a new animal for a story, how might you adapt the echidna\u0027s spine defense for a different environment?","choices":{"A":"Give it spines that can change color to blend with surroundings while still providing protection","B":"Make the spines soft and fluffy to attract friends instead of deterring predators","C":"Remove the spines entirely to make the animal faster","D":"Make the spines only appear when the animal is sleeping"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This asks students to creatively adapt the spine defense concept to serve both protection and camouflage functions in a new environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The echidna\u0027s spines are like a coat of armor. They protect the echidna from predators such as the dingo, a kind of wild dog."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of molten? A. melted B. frozen C. hot D. liquid","excerpt":"\"Antarctica\u0027s Mount Erebus is one of Earth\u0027s most unusual volcanoes. … It contains a lake of molten hot lava deep inside its crater.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym of molten?","choices":{"A":"melted","B":"frozen","C":"hot","D":"liquid"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means melted and hot; frozen is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Antarctica\u0027s Mount Erebus is one of Earth\u0027s most unusual volcanoes. … It contains a lake of molten hot lava deep inside its crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author use headings in this text? A. To make the text look pretty B. To organize information and help readers find topics easily C. To hide information D. To tell a story","excerpt":"The author uses headings like \"The Crust,\" \"The Mantle,\" \"The Core,\" and \"Which Way Is North?\"","stem":"Why does the author use headings in this text?","choices":{"A":"To make the text look pretty","B":"To organize information and help readers find topics easily","C":"To hide information","D":"To tell a story"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Headings organize and guide the reader.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The author uses headings like \"The Crust,\" \"The Mantle,\" \"The Core,\" and \"Which Way Is North?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q017","read_aloud":"How has technology changed the way people navigate? A. People still only use stars. B. People now use GPS satellites instead of only relying on stars. C. People never navigate anymore. D. People use maps only.","excerpt":"\"Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space. … Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars.\"","stem":"How has technology changed the way people navigate?","choices":{"A":"People still only use stars.","B":"People now use GPS satellites instead of only relying on stars.","C":"People never navigate anymore.","D":"People use maps only."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"GPS has replaced star navigation for many.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space. … Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q018","read_aloud":"If you were designing a new compass, what feature might you add to account for the moving magnetic pole? A. A way to update the compass for the current pole location B. A button to turn off the compass C. A light for nighttime D. A builtin clock","excerpt":"\"The magnetic pole drifts about 6 to 25 miles (10 to 40 km) each year. The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places.\"","stem":"If you were designing a new compass, what feature might you add to account for the moving magnetic pole?","choices":{"A":"A way to update the compass for the current pole location","B":"A button to turn off the compass","C":"A light for nighttime","D":"A builtin clock"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The pole moves, so a compass might need updates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The magnetic pole drifts about 6 to 25 miles (10 to 40 km) each year. The north and south magnetic poles sometimes switch places.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Write one new question that scientists might still have about volcanoes. A. \"Do volcanoes exist on other planets?\" B. \"What is the temperature of lava?\" C. \"Can we predict exactly when a volcano will erupt?\" D. \"How many volcanoes are there?\"","excerpt":"\"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\"","stem":"Write one new question that scientists might still have about volcanoes.","choices":{"A":"\"Do volcanoes exist on other planets?\"","B":"\"What is the temperature of lava?\"","C":"\"Can we predict exactly when a volcano will erupt?\"","D":"\"How many volcanoes are there?\""},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Prediction is still difficult.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q020","read_aloud":"Which situation describes something that is molten? A. Ice cream melting in a bowl B. Metal heated until it turns to liquid C. Water freezing in a tray D. Wood burning in a fire","excerpt":"\"It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which situation describes something that is molten?","choices":{"A":"Ice cream melting in a bowl","B":"Metal heated until it turns to liquid","C":"Water freezing in a tray","D":"Wood burning in a fire"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten usually refers to rock or metal that is melted by great heat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q021","read_aloud":"How does the author organize the section \"The Undiscovered Deep\"? A. By listing facts about the moon B. By describing a problem and how scientists are solving it C. By telling a story about a fish D. By comparing land and water","excerpt":"\"These missions help explain Earth\u0027s geologic processes.\"","stem":"How does the author organize the section \"The Undiscovered Deep\"?","choices":{"A":"By listing facts about the moon","B":"By describing a problem and how scientists are solving it","C":"By telling a story about a fish","D":"By comparing land and water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text identifies that much of the ocean is unexplored (problem) and explains how ROVs and sonar are used to explore it (solution).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These missions help explain Earth\u0027s geologic processes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q022","read_aloud":"Why did the author include a diagram of the water movement? A. To show where the oceans are located B. To visually explain how water circulates C. To show pictures of fish D. To list the names of clouds","excerpt":"\"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram.\"","stem":"Why did the author include a diagram of the water movement?","choices":{"A":"To show where the oceans are located","B":"To visually explain how water circulates","C":"To show pictures of fish","D":"To list the names of clouds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Diagrams are used to visually explain a process, like the circulation of water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q023","read_aloud":"Do you think the atmosphere is important for human survival? A. No, humans can survive without it. B. Yes, because it provides oxygen and protection. C. No, it blocks too much sun. D. Yes, but only for the ocean.","excerpt":"\"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun. The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids.\"","stem":"Do you think the atmosphere is important for human survival?","choices":{"A":"No, humans can survive without it.","B":"Yes, because it provides oxygen and protection.","C":"No, it blocks too much sun.","D":"Yes, but only for the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists several ways the atmosphere protects us (ozone, blocking meteors) and provides air to breathe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun. The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q024","read_aloud":"Why does the author end the text with a question? A. To show that we know everything about Earth. B. To encourage readers to think about future discoveries. C. To ask for money. D. To confuse the reader.","excerpt":"\"People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\"","stem":"Why does the author end the text with a question?","choices":{"A":"To show that we know everything about Earth.","B":"To encourage readers to think about future discoveries.","C":"To ask for money.","D":"To confuse the reader."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Authors often end with a question to make readers think about what might happen in the future.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l09-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q001","read_aloud":"What does \u0027monitor\u0027 mean here? Options: A. To watch and keep track of something, B. To hide something, C. To change something, D. To break something","excerpt":"\"Technology has come a long way since the days of ancient astronomy. ... Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space. Probes deep inside the earth and in the ocean monitor the health of the planet.\"","stem":"What does \u0027monitor\u0027 mean here? Options:","choices":{"A":"To watch and keep track of something,","B":"To hide something,","C":"To change something,","D":"To break something"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To monitor means to keep a close watch on something over time to see how it is doing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Technology has come a long way since the days of ancient astronomy. ... Satellites create detailed images of Earth from space. Probes deep inside the earth and in the ocean monitor the health of the planet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q002","read_aloud":"What main idea does this paragraph explain? Options: A. How to become an astronaut, B. How the atmosphere protects Earth from space objects, C. Why meteoroids are made of rock, D. What the troposphere is","excerpt":"\"The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids. These objects sometimes threaten to crash into Earth.\"","stem":"What main idea does this paragraph explain? Options:","choices":{"A":"How to become an astronaut,","B":"How the atmosphere protects Earth from space objects,","C":"Why meteoroids are made of rock,","D":"What the troposphere is"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph focuses on how the upper layers of the atmosphere help keep Earth safe from space debris.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The stratosphere and the layers above it also help protect us from objects in space, such as meteoroids. These objects sometimes threaten to crash into Earth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Why might China have chosen only one time zone? Options: A. To make it simpler for the whole country, B. Because they don\u0027t believe in time, C. Because it is a small country, D. Because the sun never sets there","excerpt":"\"China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\"","stem":"Why might China have chosen only one time zone? Options:","choices":{"A":"To make it simpler for the whole country,","B":"Because they don\u0027t believe in time,","C":"Because it is a small country,","D":"Because the sun never sets there"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Having a single time zone, even across a large area, can make communication and planning easier across the nation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"China crosses three standard time zones. But the country decided to have only one time zone.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Does the author think we know everything about Earth? Options: A. Yes, because we have satellites, B. No, because the author encourages future discovery, C. Yes, because we have traveled everywhere, D. No, because Earth is shrinking","excerpt":"\"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\"","stem":"Does the author think we know everything about Earth? Options:","choices":{"A":"Yes, because we have satellites,","B":"No, because the author encourages future discovery,","C":"Yes, because we have traveled everywhere,","D":"No, because Earth is shrinking"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By ending with a question about what comes next, the author shows that there is always more to learn.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q005","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"adopted\" in the same way as the excerpt? A. The school adopted a new rule about homework. B. The cat adopted a mouse as a pet. C. She adopted a sunny day for her picnic. D. The car adopted a new color.","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"adopted\" in the same way as the excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The school adopted a new rule about homework.","B":"The cat adopted a mouse as a pet.","C":"She adopted a sunny day for her picnic.","D":"The car adopted a new color."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"In the excerpt, \"adopted\" means started to use a selected idea or method. A school starting to use a new rule is similar. The other choices use \"adopted\" in ways that do not fit the meaning of accepting or starting to use something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones. But there are some exceptions.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q006","read_aloud":"What message does the author want readers to take away from this text? A. We already know everything about Earth. B. Science and exploration help us understand our planet better, and there is always more to learn. C. Earth is not important to study. D. Ancient people were always right about science.","excerpt":"\"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\"","stem":"What message does the author want readers to take away from this text?","choices":{"A":"We already know everything about Earth.","B":"Science and exploration help us understand our planet better, and there is always more to learn.","C":"Earth is not important to study.","D":"Ancient people were always right about science."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author shows how much we have learned about Earth using new technology. But the ending question suggests there is still more to discover. The message is that exploration is ongoing and valuable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Is it better to study Earth from space or from the ground? Use evidence from the text. A. Space is always better because satellites can see the whole planet at once. B. Ground studies are always better because you can touch things directly. C. Both methods are needed because they give different but important information. D. Neither method works at all.","excerpt":"\"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"Is it better to study Earth from space or from the ground? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"Space is always better because satellites can see the whole planet at once.","B":"Ground studies are always better because you can touch things directly.","C":"Both methods are needed because they give different but important information.","D":"Neither method works at all."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Satellites like Aqua can monitor the whole water cycle and see through clouds. But drills and ROVs let scientists study deep places satellites cannot reach. The text uses both methods, showing that each has value. Scientists need multiple tools to fully understand Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q008","read_aloud":"What does \"unique\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. unusual; unlike anything else B. common; found in many places C. dangerous; harmful to humans D. small; smaller than other animals","excerpt":"Australia is home to some of the most unique animals on Earth.","stem":"What does \"unique\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"unusual; unlike anything else","B":"common; found in many places","C":"dangerous; harmful to humans","D":"small; smaller than other animals"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Unique means unusual or unlike anything else. The text describes Australian animals as unique, suggesting they\u0027re unlike animals elsewhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Australia is home to some of the most unique animals on Earth."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q009","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about monotremes? A. They are the only egg-laying mammals, with just two species existing today B. They are the most common type of mammal on Earth C. They can fly and swim better than other mammals D. They live only in Australia and nowhere else","excerpt":"The echidna belongs to a group of mammals known as monotremes. They are the only mammals on Earth that lay eggs. There are only two kinds of monotremes. One is the echidna, and the other is the platypus.","stem":"What is the main idea about monotremes?","choices":{"A":"They are the only egg-laying mammals, with just two species existing today","B":"They are the most common type of mammal on Earth","C":"They can fly and swim better than other mammals","D":"They live only in Australia and nowhere else"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The passage explains monotremes are unique egg-laying mammals with only two species: echidna and platypus.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The echidna belongs to a group of mammals known as monotremes. They are the only mammals on Earth that lay eggs. There are only two kinds of monotremes. One is the echidna, and the other is the platypus."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q010","read_aloud":"What can you infer about monotreme adaptations? A. Their adaptations have allowed them to survive for a very long time B. They have not changed at all since they first appeared C. They are less successful than other mammal groups D. They will soon become extinct because of their age","excerpt":"Monotremes have lived on Earth longer than any other mammals. Several adaptations have helped them to thrive.","stem":"What can you infer about monotreme adaptations?","choices":{"A":"Their adaptations have allowed them to survive for a very long time","B":"They have not changed at all since they first appeared","C":"They are less successful than other mammal groups","D":"They will soon become extinct because of their age"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states monotremes have lived longer than other mammals and that adaptations helped them thrive, suggesting their adaptations contributed to long-term survival.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Monotremes have lived on Earth longer than any other mammals. Several adaptations have helped them to thrive."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q011","read_aloud":"Do you think the echidna\u0027s digging ability is more important than its spines for survival? Why or why not? A. Both are important; spines deter predators while digging provides escape, showing multiple defense strategies B. Spines are more important because they work without the echidna needing to move C. Digging is more important because it helps the echidna find food underground D. Neither is important because echidnas have no natural predators","excerpt":"When it comes to predators, the echidna has another secret weapon: its claws. When an echidna is startled or attacked, it hides by doing something no other mammal in the world can do. It digs itself straight down into the ground.","stem":"Do you think the echidna\u0027s digging ability is more important than its spines for survival? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Both are important; spines deter predators while digging provides escape, showing multiple defense strategies","B":"Spines are more important because they work without the echidna needing to move","C":"Digging is more important because it helps the echidna find food underground","D":"Neither is important because echidnas have no natural predators"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes both spines (deterrent) and digging (escape) as defense mechanisms, suggesting multiple strategies work together for survival.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When it comes to predators, the echidna has another secret weapon: its claws. When an echidna is startled or attacked, it hides by doing something no other mammal in the world can do. It digs itself straight down into the ground."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q012","read_aloud":"If scientists could apply the echidna\u0027s temperature regulation to help humans, what might be one beneficial use? A. Helping astronauts conserve energy and resources during long space missions by slowing body functions B. Making humans run faster by increasing body temperature during sports C. Helping people stay awake longer by preventing the body from cooling down D. Making humans grow taller by speeding up metabolism","excerpt":"Scientists think that a cool body temperature might help the echidna live longer... When they need to, echidnas can turn down their body temperature even lower than normal.","stem":"If scientists could apply the echidna\u0027s temperature regulation to help humans, what might be one beneficial use?","choices":{"A":"Helping astronauts conserve energy and resources during long space missions by slowing body functions","B":"Making humans run faster by increasing body temperature during sports","C":"Helping people stay awake longer by preventing the body from cooling down","D":"Making humans grow taller by speeding up metabolism"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This asks students to creatively apply the echidna\u0027s temperature control to human space travel, where conserving resources during long missions would be valuable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists think that a cool body temperature might help the echidna live longer... When they need to, echidnas can turn down their body temperature even lower than normal."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q013","read_aloud":"How does the word abundant help you understand Earth\u0027s resources? A. It shows some resources are plentiful. B. It shows resources are scarce. C. It shows resources are only in the ocean. D. It shows resources are dangerous.","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. … The troposphere contains abundant nitrogen and oxygen.\"","stem":"How does the word abundant help you understand Earth\u0027s resources?","choices":{"A":"It shows some resources are plentiful.","B":"It shows resources are scarce.","C":"It shows resources are only in the ocean.","D":"It shows resources are dangerous."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Abundant means plentiful; Earth has many resources.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. … The troposphere contains abundant nitrogen and oxygen.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Why is a diagram more helpful than text alone for showing Earth\u0027s layers? A. A diagram shows the layers visually and how they fit together. B. A diagram is shorter. C. A diagram replaces all words. D. A diagram is more colorful.","excerpt":"The text includes a diagram of Earth\u0027s layers with labels for crust, mantle, outer core, and inner core.","stem":"Why is a diagram more helpful than text alone for showing Earth\u0027s layers?","choices":{"A":"A diagram shows the layers visually and how they fit together.","B":"A diagram is shorter.","C":"A diagram replaces all words.","D":"A diagram is more colorful."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Visual diagrams show relationships clearly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes a diagram of Earth\u0027s layers with labels for crust, mantle, outer core, and inner core."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q015","read_aloud":"How are the outer core and inner core different? A. One is gas; one is solid. B. The outer core is liquid; the inner core is solid. C. Both are solid. D. Both are liquid.","excerpt":"The crust is solid and thin. The mantle is semisolid and moves. The outer core is liquid iron and nickel. The inner core is solid iron.","stem":"How are the outer core and inner core different?","choices":{"A":"One is gas; one is solid.","B":"The outer core is liquid; the inner core is solid.","C":"Both are solid.","D":"Both are liquid."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states the outer core is liquid and the inner core is solid.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The crust is solid and thin. The mantle is semisolid and moves. The outer core is liquid iron and nickel. The inner core is solid iron."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q016","read_aloud":"Do you think early warning systems are worth the cost? Why? A. No, because disasters will happen anyway. B. Yes, because they save lives and reduce damage. C. No, because they are not reliable. D. Yes, because they are fun to watch.","excerpt":"\"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\"","stem":"Do you think early warning systems are worth the cost? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because disasters will happen anyway.","B":"Yes, because they save lives and reduce damage.","C":"No, because they are not reliable.","D":"Yes, because they are fun to watch."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Saving lives and reducing damage is a great benefit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q017","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for molten? A. Solid B. Frozen C. Melted D. Broken","excerpt":"\"It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for molten?","choices":{"A":"Solid","B":"Frozen","C":"Melted","D":"Broken"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Molten means melted, usually by heat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q018","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the section \"To the Center of the Earth\"? A. Drilling into the mantle is easy. B. Scientists have a plan to sample the mantle to learn more about it. C. The mantle is made of water. D. Scientists have already finished drilling.","excerpt":"\"To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of the section \"To the Center of the Earth\"?","choices":{"A":"Drilling into the mantle is easy.","B":"Scientists have a plan to sample the mantle to learn more about it.","C":"The mantle is made of water.","D":"Scientists have already finished drilling."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The section describes the plan and the expensive project to drill into the mantle to solve the mystery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q019","read_aloud":"What can the reader infer about exploring the ocean? A. It is a finished project. B. It is difficult and expensive but important. C. It is more dangerous than space travel. D. It is not useful.","excerpt":"\"But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored. That is changing. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration is studying deepwater canyons...\"","stem":"What can the reader infer about exploring the ocean?","choices":{"A":"It is a finished project.","B":"It is difficult and expensive but important.","C":"It is more dangerous than space travel.","D":"It is not useful."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since only 5 percent is explored and they need special vehicles like ROVs, the reader can infer it is hard work but worth doing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored. That is changing. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration is studying deepwater canyons...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q020","read_aloud":"Why is the project to drill into the mantle considered a big deal? A. It costs a lot of money and requires new technology. B. It will take only one day. C. It will happen in the desert. D. It is the first time people have drilled.","excerpt":"\"Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust. This $1 billion project is planned to start drilling in 2020.\"","stem":"Why is the project to drill into the mantle considered a big deal?","choices":{"A":"It costs a lot of money and requires new technology.","B":"It will take only one day.","C":"It will happen in the desert.","D":"It is the first time people have drilled."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text mentions the $1 billion cost and the need for special drills, showing it is a major project.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust. This $1 billion project is planned to start drilling in 2020.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q021","read_aloud":"If you could ask the author one question about Earth, what would be the best question to ask based on the text? A. What is your favorite color? B. How do scientists know the core is hot if they cannot go there? C. Do you like to swim? D. What time is it?","excerpt":"(Referring to the whole text)","stem":"If you could ask the author one question about Earth, what would be the best question to ask based on the text?","choices":{"A":"What is your favorite color?","B":"How do scientists know the core is hot if they cannot go there?","C":"Do you like to swim?","D":"What time is it?"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that no one has drilled to the core. Asking how they know the temperature is a good scientific question based on the reading.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: (Referring to the whole text)"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q022","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q023","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q024","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. By flying satellites over it B. By drilling into it and taking samples C. By using GPS D. By studying the moon","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"By flying satellites over it","B":"By drilling into it and taking samples","C":"By using GPS","D":"By studying the moon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists plan to drill through the ocean floor to get samples from the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-l10-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Drill into the Earth B. See through clouds C. Stop earthquakes D. Change the weather","excerpt":"\"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Drill into the Earth","B":"See through clouds","C":"Stop earthquakes","D":"Change the weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Aqua uses technology to see through clouds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q001","read_aloud":"What is the mantle? A. the air around Earth B. the layer between Earth\u0027s crust and core C. the outer surface of Earth D. the deepest part of the ocean","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\"","stem":"What is the mantle?","choices":{"A":"the air around Earth","B":"the layer between Earth\u0027s crust and core","C":"the outer surface of Earth","D":"the deepest part of the ocean"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists Earth\u0027s layers in order: crust, mantle, outer core, and inner core. The mantle is between the crust and the core.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q002","read_aloud":"What does \"circulates\" mean? A. stays in one place B. moves through a system C. turns into ice D. disappears completely","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.\"","stem":"What does \"circulates\" mean?","choices":{"A":"stays in one place","B":"moves through a system","C":"turns into ice","D":"disappears completely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The water cycle shows water moving through different stages: heating, rising, forming clouds, and falling back. \"Circulates\" means moving through a system.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q003","read_aloud":"What does \"molten\" mean? A. frozen solid B. melted and hot enough to be liquid C. cold and hard D. dry and cracked","excerpt":"\"Antarctica\u0027s Mount Erebus is one of Earth\u0027s most unusual volcanoes. It contains a lake of molten hot lava deep inside its crater.\"","stem":"What does \"molten\" mean?","choices":{"A":"frozen solid","B":"melted and hot enough to be liquid","C":"cold and hard","D":"dry and cracked"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes molten hot lava inside a volcano. \"Molten\" means melted and hot enough to be in liquid form.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Antarctica\u0027s Mount Erebus is one of Earth\u0027s most unusual volcanoes. It contains a lake of molten hot lava deep inside its crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this section? A. Earth has layers below the surface and gases above. B. Earth is the smallest planet. C. Earth has no atmosphere. D. Only scientists can understand Earth.","excerpt":"\"Above and Below. Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core. Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this section?","choices":{"A":"Earth has layers below the surface and gases above.","B":"Earth is the smallest planet.","C":"Earth has no atmosphere.","D":"Only scientists can understand Earth."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The section describes what is below us (crust, mantle, core) and what is above us (atmosphere). The main idea is that Earth has layers both below and above its surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Above and Below. Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core. Circling overhead is a layer of gases that forms our atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q005","read_aloud":"What can happen when tectonic plates move? A. The sun gets darker. B. Earthquakes and ocean shifts can occur. C. Plants grow faster. D. The atmosphere gets thicker.","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans.\"","stem":"What can happen when tectonic plates move?","choices":{"A":"The sun gets darker.","B":"Earthquakes and ocean shifts can occur.","C":"Plants grow faster.","D":"The atmosphere gets thicker."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that sliding tectonic plates can cause earthquakes and shifts in the oceans. These are natural results of plate movement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q006","read_aloud":"Why is the mantle still mysterious? A. because scientists are not interested B. because it is too deep for current drilling technology to reach C. because the mantle is made of water D. because there is no mantle","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean or 8 miles (13 km) on land.\"","stem":"Why is the mantle still mysterious?","choices":{"A":"because scientists are not interested","B":"because it is too deep for current drilling technology to reach","C":"because the mantle is made of water","D":"because there is no mantle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The mantle is 1,860 miles deep, but the deepest drill is only 8 miles. The huge gap shows that current technology cannot reach the mantle. That is why it remains mysterious.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles (2,993 km) deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles (2.3 km) beneath the ocean or 8 miles (13 km) on land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q007","read_aloud":"What is the air we breathe mostly made of? A. oxygen and nitrogen B. only oxygen C. carbon dioxide and helium D. water vapor and smoke","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\"","stem":"What is the air we breathe mostly made of?","choices":{"A":"oxygen and nitrogen","B":"only oxygen","C":"carbon dioxide and helium","D":"water vapor and smoke"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the troposphere is 78 percent nitrogen and 21 percent oxygen. Together, these two gases make up 99 percent of the air we breathe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. It is 78 percent nitrogen, 21 percent oxygen, and 1 percent other gases.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q008","read_aloud":"Why is ozone important? A. because it makes the sky blue B. because it blocks harmful rays from the sun C. because it causes rain D. because it makes air smell good","excerpt":"\"The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere. Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\"","stem":"Why is ozone important?","choices":{"A":"because it makes the sky blue","B":"because it blocks harmful rays from the sun","C":"because it causes rain","D":"because it makes air smell good"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun. This protects living things on Earth from dangerous radiation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere. Ozone blocks harmful rays from the sun.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q009","read_aloud":"How does technology help people during natural disasters? A. by causing more disasters B. by letting scientists see problems early and respond faster to save lives C. by hiding information from people D. by stopping all earthquakes forever","excerpt":"\"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\"","stem":"How does technology help people during natural disasters?","choices":{"A":"by causing more disasters","B":"by letting scientists see problems early and respond faster to save lives","C":"by hiding information from people","D":"by stopping all earthquakes forever"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Technology like satellites and GPS lets scientists spot problems early. When they react quickly, they can warn people and prepare. This reduces the damage and saves lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q010","read_aloud":"What does this ending suggest about science and learning? A. We already know everything. B. Science keeps changing as we learn more, and there is always more to discover. C. Ancient people were right about everything. D. We should stop exploring Earth.","excerpt":"\"People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\"","stem":"What does this ending suggest about science and learning?","choices":{"A":"We already know everything.","B":"Science keeps changing as we learn more, and there is always more to discover.","C":"Ancient people were right about everything.","D":"We should stop exploring Earth."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author reminds us that old ideas were wrong and asks what we will discover next. This suggests that science is always growing. New tools and exploration lead to new knowledge. There is always more to learn about our planet. Section A - Text Information Title: Planet EarthAuthor: Christine Taylor-ButlerText Type: Informational TextPreview Vocabulary Words: mantle, circulates, adopted, abundant, molten","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"mantle\" mean in this sentence? A. the layer of Earth between the crust and the core B. a type of rock found on the surface C. the hottest part of Earth\u0027s center D. the air that surrounds our planet","excerpt":"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core.","stem":"What does \"mantle\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"the layer of Earth between the crust and the core","B":"a type of rock found on the surface","C":"the hottest part of Earth\u0027s center","D":"the air that surrounds our planet"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mantle refers to Earth\u0027s layer between crust and core, as described in the text\u0027s layer listing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that are the mantle, outer core, and inner core."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q012","read_aloud":"What does \"circulates\" mean here? A. moves through a system B. stays in one place C. disappears into the ground D. turns into ice","excerpt":"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.","stem":"What does \"circulates\" mean here?","choices":{"A":"moves through a system","B":"stays in one place","C":"disappears into the ground","D":"turns into ice"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Circulates means moves through a system, describing water\u0027s continuous movement in the hydrologic cycle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"abundant\" mean in this context? A. plentiful; commonly occurring B. rare and hard to find C. dangerous to explore D. expensive to study","excerpt":"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.","stem":"What does \"abundant\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"plentiful; commonly occurring","B":"rare and hard to find","C":"dangerous to explore","D":"expensive to study"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Abundant means plentiful or commonly occurring, describing oceans as a widespread Earth resource.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about birds and feathers? A. Feathers are a defining characteristic found only on birds B. All animals have feathers but birds have the most C. Feathers help birds but are not unique to them D. Trees and stars also have feather-like parts","excerpt":"Birds and feathers go together, like trees and leaves, like stars and the sky. All birds have feathers, but no other animals do.","stem":"What is the main idea about birds and feathers?","choices":{"A":"Feathers are a defining characteristic found only on birds","B":"All animals have feathers but birds have the most","C":"Feathers help birds but are not unique to them","D":"Trees and stars also have feather-like parts"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text establishes that all birds have feathers while no other animals do, making feathers a unique bird characteristic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Birds and feathers go together, like trees and leaves, like stars and the sky. All birds have feathers, but no other animals do."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q015","read_aloud":"What is the effect of tectonic plates sliding past each other? A. An earthquake can occur B. Mountains immediately form C. Oceans dry up completely D. Volcanoes stop erupting","excerpt":"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur.","stem":"What is the effect of tectonic plates sliding past each other?","choices":{"A":"An earthquake can occur","B":"Mountains immediately form","C":"Oceans dry up completely","D":"Volcanoes stop erupting"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that plate movement can cause earthquakes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q016","read_aloud":"What happens after water vapor rises into the atmosphere? A. It gathers into clouds and falls as precipitation B. It freezes into ice crystals immediately C. It disappears and never returns to Earth D. It turns back into liquid water on the ground","excerpt":"Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere. It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation, such as rain or snow.","stem":"What happens after water vapor rises into the atmosphere?","choices":{"A":"It gathers into clouds and falls as precipitation","B":"It freezes into ice crystals immediately","C":"It disappears and never returns to Earth","D":"It turns back into liquid water on the ground"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The water cycle sequence shows vapor rising, gathering into clouds, then falling as precipitation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas. This gas, called water vapor, rises into the atmosphere. It gathers into clouds and falls back to the ground as precipitation, such as rain or snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q017","read_aloud":"What two purposes do the wood duck\u0027s feathers serve in her nest? A. They cushion and warm the eggs B. They help the duck fly to find food C. They attract a mate to the nest D. They keep predators away from the nest","excerpt":"A female wood duck lines her nest with feathers she plucks from her own body. These feathers cushion the duck\u0027s eggs and keep them warm.","stem":"What two purposes do the wood duck\u0027s feathers serve in her nest?","choices":{"A":"They cushion and warm the eggs","B":"They help the duck fly to find food","C":"They attract a mate to the nest","D":"They keep predators away from the nest"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text clearly states the feathers cushion eggs and keep them warm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A female wood duck lines her nest with feathers she plucks from her own body. These feathers cushion the duck\u0027s eggs and keep them warm."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q018","read_aloud":"How does the junco\u0027s tail feather behavior help it survive? A. It distracts predators so the junco can escape B. It helps the junco find food more easily C. It attracts other juncos to form a group D. It keeps the junco warm during cold weather","excerpt":"A dark-eyed junco distracts its enemies by flashing the bright white feathers on the outside of its tail. Then it quickly covers the feathers and darts off in the other direction.","stem":"How does the junco\u0027s tail feather behavior help it survive?","choices":{"A":"It distracts predators so the junco can escape","B":"It helps the junco find food more easily","C":"It attracts other juncos to form a group","D":"It keeps the junco warm during cold weather"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes the flashing feathers as a distraction technique that allows the junco to escape from enemies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A dark-eyed junco distracts its enemies by flashing the bright white feathers on the outside of its tail. Then it quickly covers the feathers and darts off in the other direction."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q019","read_aloud":"How do contour feathers demonstrate the relationship between structure and function in birds? A. Their structure provides both physical form and visual characteristics that serve different functions B. They only serve one function of making birds look attractive C. They help birds fly but do not affect their appearance D. They are only important for keeping birds warm","excerpt":"Contour feathers cover most of a bird\u0027s body. They give a bird its shape and colors.","stem":"How do contour feathers demonstrate the relationship between structure and function in birds?","choices":{"A":"Their structure provides both physical form and visual characteristics that serve different functions","B":"They only serve one function of making birds look attractive","C":"They help birds fly but do not affect their appearance","D":"They are only important for keeping birds warm"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows contour feathers have dual functions: providing body shape (structural function) and colors (visual function), demonstrating how structure serves multiple purposes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Contour feathers cover most of a bird\u0027s body. They give a bird its shape and colors."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q020","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why might the echidna be considered \"one of the most amazing creatures on Earth\"? A. It has multiple unique adaptations that work together to help it survive in challenging environments B. It is the largest mammal in Australia C. It can fly and swim better than any other animal D. It is the only animal that can change its body temperature","excerpt":"Scientists think this trait is one reason that the echidna has managed to survive. But it\u0027s just one of the adaptations that makes the tiny, spiny echidna one of the most amazing creatures on Earth.","stem":"Based on the text, why might the echidna be considered \"one of the most amazing creatures on Earth\"?","choices":{"A":"It has multiple unique adaptations that work together to help it survive in challenging environments","B":"It is the largest mammal in Australia","C":"It can fly and swim better than any other animal","D":"It is the only animal that can change its body temperature"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes multiple adaptations (egg-laying, spines, digging, temperature control, electrical sensing) that work together, supporting the evaluation that these combined traits make the echidna amazing. Section A - Text Information Title: Planet Earth (excerpt)Author: Christine TaylorButler","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists think this trait is one reason that the echidna has managed to survive. But it\u0027s just one of the adaptations that makes the tiny, spiny echidna one of the most amazing creatures on Earth."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q021","read_aloud":"What does adopted mean? A. started to use B. rejected C. forgot D. changed","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\"","stem":"What does adopted mean?","choices":{"A":"started to use","B":"rejected","C":"forgot","D":"changed"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Adopted means started to use a selected idea or method.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this passage? A. Earth\u0027s layers are all the same. B. Earth\u0027s layers help sustain life. C. The core is the most important layer. D. The crust is the thickest layer.","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this passage?","choices":{"A":"Earth\u0027s layers are all the same.","B":"Earth\u0027s layers help sustain life.","C":"The core is the most important layer.","D":"The crust is the thickest layer."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states each layer plays an important part in sustaining life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. Each layer plays an important part in Earth\u0027s ability to sustain life.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q023","read_aloud":"Where does nearly all weather occur? A. In the stratosphere B. In the troposphere C. In the core D. In the mantle","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\"","stem":"Where does nearly all weather occur?","choices":{"A":"In the stratosphere","B":"In the troposphere","C":"In the core","D":"In the mantle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says nearly all weather occurs in the troposphere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe. Nearly all of the weather we experience on Earth occurs in the troposphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q024","read_aloud":"Why is the depth of the mantle only an estimate? A. Scientists cannot drill deep enough to measure it exactly. B. The mantle moves too much. C. The core is in the way. D. The crust is too hard.","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles beneath the ocean.\"","stem":"Why is the depth of the mantle only an estimate?","choices":{"A":"Scientists cannot drill deep enough to measure it exactly.","B":"The mantle moves too much.","C":"The core is in the way.","D":"The crust is too hard."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"No one has drilled deep enough to know for sure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe the mantle is about 1,860 miles deep. This calculation is an estimate. No one has ever drilled deeper than 1.4 miles beneath the ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q025","read_aloud":"What is the inner core made of? A. Liquid iron and nickel B. Solid iron C. Molten rock D. Silicon and oxygen","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s core has two layers. The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel. … The inner core is solid iron.\"","stem":"What is the inner core made of?","choices":{"A":"Liquid iron and nickel","B":"Solid iron","C":"Molten rock","D":"Silicon and oxygen"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the inner core is solid iron.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s core has two layers. The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel. … The inner core is solid iron.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q026","read_aloud":"How are earthquakes and mountain ranges related? A. Both are caused by the movement of tectonic plates. B. Earthquakes create mountains instantly. C. Mountains prevent earthquakes. D. They are not related.","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. … The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\"","stem":"How are earthquakes and mountain ranges related?","choices":{"A":"Both are caused by the movement of tectonic plates.","B":"Earthquakes create mountains instantly.","C":"Mountains prevent earthquakes.","D":"They are not related."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Both result from tectonic plate movement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. … The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q027","read_aloud":"Why is it important to explore the ocean floor? A. To find new species and understand Earth\u0027s processes B. To find buried treasure C. To build underwater cities D. To prove the ocean is small","excerpt":"\"Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Why is it important to explore the ocean floor?","choices":{"A":"To find new species and understand Earth\u0027s processes","B":"To find buried treasure","C":"To build underwater cities","D":"To prove the ocean is small"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says exploring helps explain Earth\u0027s geologic processes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q028","read_aloud":"Write one sentence predicting what scientists might learn about Earth in the future. A. \"Scientists will stop exploring Earth.\" B. \"Scientists might discover new facts about the mantle and deep ocean life.\" C. \"Scientists will find that Earth has no core.\" D. \"Scientists will prove the earth is flat.\"","excerpt":"\"What will we discover next?\"","stem":"Write one sentence predicting what scientists might learn about Earth in the future.","choices":{"A":"\"Scientists will stop exploring Earth.\"","B":"\"Scientists might discover new facts about the mantle and deep ocean life.\"","C":"\"Scientists will find that Earth has no core.\"","D":"\"Scientists will prove the earth is flat.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Exploration continues to bring new knowledge. Section A - Text information Title: Planet Earth Author: Christine Taylor-Butler","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What will we discover next?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q029","read_aloud":"Where is the mantle located? A. Above the crust B. Inside the core C. Between the crust and the core D. In the atmosphere","excerpt":"\"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that is the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\"","stem":"Where is the mantle located?","choices":{"A":"Above the crust","B":"Inside the core","C":"Between the crust and the core","D":"In the atmosphere"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The mantle is the layer beneath the crust and above the core.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Below us, our planet is composed of four main layers. The outer surface is called the crust. Beneath that is the mantle, outer core, and inner core.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q030","read_aloud":"What does adopted mean in the text? A. Created B. Started to use C. Destroyed D. Ignored","excerpt":"\"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\"","stem":"What does adopted mean in the text?","choices":{"A":"Created","B":"Started to use","C":"Destroyed","D":"Ignored"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Adopted means the areas started to use the time zones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most areas have adopted these standard time zones.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q031","read_aloud":"What does abundant mean? A. Rare B. Plentiful C. Small D. Deep","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.\"","stem":"What does abundant mean?","choices":{"A":"Rare","B":"Plentiful","C":"Small","D":"Deep"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abundant means there is a large amount or plenty of something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q032","read_aloud":"What causes the tectonic plates to move? A. The wind blowing B. The ocean tides C. The fluid layer of mantle they rest on D. The satellites in space","excerpt":"\"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\"","stem":"What causes the tectonic plates to move?","choices":{"A":"The wind blowing","B":"The ocean tides","C":"The fluid layer of mantle they rest on","D":"The satellites in space"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states the plates rest on a fluid layer and are constantly moving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The crust and the uppermost layer of the mantle are broken into sections called tectonic plates. The plates rest on top of a more fluid layer of mantle and are constantly moving.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q033","read_aloud":"What is the relationship between earthquakes and tsunamis? A. Earthquakes stop tsunamis. B. Strong ocean earthquakes can cause tsunamis. C. Tsunamis cause earthquakes. D. They are not related.","excerpt":"\"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans. If the ocean earthquake is strong enough, waves can develop into a deadly tsunami.\"","stem":"What is the relationship between earthquakes and tsunamis?","choices":{"A":"Earthquakes stop tsunamis.","B":"Strong ocean earthquakes can cause tsunamis.","C":"Tsunamis cause earthquakes.","D":"They are not related."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says shifts in the ocean from earthquakes can develop into a tsunami.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When tectonic plates slide over or past each other, an earthquake can occur. Sometimes the pressure causes shifts in the oceans. If the ocean earthquake is strong enough, waves can develop into a deadly tsunami.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q034","read_aloud":"Why is the Japanese vessel Chikyu mentioned in the text? A. It is a fishing boat. B. It holds the record for deep-ocean drilling. C. It is a satellite. D. It studies the weather.","excerpt":"\"The Japanese vessel Chikyu holds the world\u0027s record for deep-ocean drilling.\"","stem":"Why is the Japanese vessel Chikyu mentioned in the text?","choices":{"A":"It is a fishing boat.","B":"It holds the record for deep-ocean drilling.","C":"It is a satellite.","D":"It studies the weather."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The caption and text highlight Chikyu\u0027s record for drilling deep into the ocean.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Japanese vessel Chikyu holds the world\u0027s record for deep-ocean drilling.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q035","read_aloud":"How are the troposphere and stratosphere different? A. The troposphere is higher than the stratosphere. B. The stratosphere contains ozone; the troposphere has the air we breathe. C. The stratosphere is where planes fly. D. The troposphere blocks the sun.","excerpt":"\"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe... The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere.\"","stem":"How are the troposphere and stratosphere different?","choices":{"A":"The troposphere is higher than the stratosphere.","B":"The stratosphere contains ozone; the troposphere has the air we breathe.","C":"The stratosphere is where planes fly.","D":"The troposphere blocks the sun."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text distinguishes them by their contents: the troposphere has air to breathe, and the stratosphere has ozone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The troposphere is about 7 miles (11 km) high. It contains the air we breathe... The stratosphere is about 30 miles (48 km) high. It contains less water and more ozone than the troposphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q036","read_aloud":"Why is it important to use technology to spot natural disasters? A. To watch them for fun B. To reduce the damage they cause C. To stop the Earth from spinning D. To create more jobs","excerpt":"\"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\"","stem":"Why is it important to use technology to spot natural disasters?","choices":{"A":"To watch them for fun","B":"To reduce the damage they cause","C":"To stop the Earth from spinning","D":"To create more jobs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says quick reaction helps reduce devastation, meaning it saves lives and property.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q037","read_aloud":"Do you think scientists should spend money exploring the ocean? A. No, we know enough already. B. Yes, because learning about the ocean helps us understand Earth. C. No, the ocean is not important. D. Yes, but only for fishing.","excerpt":"\"But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\"","stem":"Do you think scientists should spend money exploring the ocean?","choices":{"A":"No, we know enough already.","B":"Yes, because learning about the ocean helps us understand Earth.","C":"No, the ocean is not important.","D":"Yes, but only for fishing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text implies that exploration helps explain geologic processes, which is valuable for understanding our planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q038","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q039","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. Very cold, B. Melted and hot, C. Made of wood, D. Hard as a rock","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"Very cold,","B":"Melted and hot,","C":"Made of wood,","D":"Hard as a rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means something is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how lava acts during an eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s mantle is a semisolid and movable layer of rock. It is composed of silicon, oxygen, iron, magnesium and aluminum. Sometimes this substance rises through the crust above. It surfaces as a volcanic eruption of molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q040","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. By flying satellites over it B. By drilling into it and taking samples C. By using GPS D. By studying the moon","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"By flying satellites over it","B":"By drilling into it and taking samples","C":"By using GPS","D":"By studying the moon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists plan to drill through the ocean floor to get samples from the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q041","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Drill into the Earth B. See through clouds C. Stop earthquakes D. Change the weather","excerpt":"\"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Drill into the Earth","B":"See through clouds","C":"Stop earthquakes","D":"Change the weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Aqua uses technology to see through clouds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q042","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. The ocean water is too cold. B. The oceanic crust is very hard. C. They want to drill into a volcano. D. The fish are in the way.","excerpt":"\"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"The ocean water is too cold.","B":"The oceanic crust is very hard.","C":"They want to drill into a volcano.","D":"The fish are in the way."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says special drills are needed to handle the stress of boring through hard crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles (6.4 km) thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q043","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. It helps them predict rain. B. It helps them understand how and why volcanoes erupt. C. It helps them find gold. D. It helps them measure time zones.","excerpt":"\"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"It helps them predict rain.","B":"It helps them understand how and why volcanoes erupt.","C":"It helps them find gold.","D":"It helps them measure time zones."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the data explains how and why volcanoes erupt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists at the McMurdo Station research facility analyze the gas and lava produced by Mount Erebus. The data helps explain how and why volcanoes erupt.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q044","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Stops B. Flows C. Freezes D. Sinks","excerpt":"\"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Stops","B":"Flows","C":"Freezes","D":"Sinks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Circulates means moves through a system, which is similar to flows.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q045","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Earth has always had the same continents. B. Continents were once joined together in a single landmass. C. There were no oceans in the past. D. The Earth is flat.","excerpt":"\"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Earth has always had the same continents.","B":"Continents were once joined together in a single landmass.","C":"There were no oceans in the past.","D":"The Earth is flat."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists believe continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists believe Earth\u0027s continents were once joined as a single landmass called Pangaea. Over millions of years, the tectonic plates shifted.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q046","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. To replace active ones if needed B. To make the GPS faster C. To take photos of the moon D. To watch the weather","excerpt":"\"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twenty-four satellites are active. The other five are backups.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"To replace active ones if needed","B":"To make the GPS faster","C":"To take photos of the moon","D":"To watch the weather"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Backup satellites are kept to replace active ones if they stop working.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The U.S. Air Force maintains these satellites. Twenty-four satellites are active. The other five are backups.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q047","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. Ocean currents might shift and weather could change. B. The Earth would become a desert. C. The core would stop spinning. D. Time zones would disappear.","excerpt":"\"Water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"Ocean currents might shift and weather could change.","B":"The Earth would become a desert.","C":"The core would stop spinning.","D":"Time zones would disappear."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text connects melting polar caps to shifting currents and weather changes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water and ice from melting polar caps could shift ocean currents. Weather would change, and Earth\u0027s temperatures could plunge.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q048","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. To study weightless environments B. To drill for oil C. To track hurricanes D. To store water","excerpt":"\"To learn how things work in a weightless environment, world scientists designed the International Space Station (ISS).\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"To study weightless environments","B":"To drill for oil","C":"To track hurricanes","D":"To store water"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states the ISS was designed to learn how things work in a weightless environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To learn how things work in a weightless environment, world scientists designed the International Space Station (ISS).\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q049","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Plentiful B. Scarce C. Full D. Rich","excerpt":"\"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Plentiful","B":"Scarce","C":"Full","D":"Rich"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Abundant means plentiful. Scarce means there is very little, which is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w1-planet-earth-std-q050","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. The movement of the liquid outer core B. The solid inner core C. The wind in the atmosphere D. The ocean tides","excerpt":"\"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"The movement of the liquid outer core","B":"The solid inner core","C":"The wind in the atmosphere","D":"The ocean tides"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the movement (flowing) of the outer core around the inner core creates the magnetic field.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The liquid outer core is composed mostly of iron and nickel, and is about 1,400 miles (2,250 km) thick. It is constantly flowing.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes","grade":4,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":5,"week":2,"title":"Volcanoes","author":"Seymour Simon","genre":"Informational Text","essential_question":"How do forces inside Earth change its surface?","weekly_question":"What happens when volcanoes erupt?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["erupt","crater","dormant","active","lava"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Volcanoes. What happens when volcanoes erupt?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027erupt\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options: A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027erupt\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q002","read_aloud":"What is a volcano? Options: A. A type of lake, B. A forest with many trees, C. A mountain or hill with a vent, D. A flat piece of land","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"What is a volcano? Options:","choices":{"A":"A type of lake,","B":"A forest with many trees,","C":"A mountain or hill with a vent,","D":"A flat piece of land"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text defines a volcano as a mountain or hill that has a crater or vent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What is another word for dormant? Options: A. Awake, B. Asleep, C. Active, D. Gone","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are called dormant, or asleep, when they are quiet but could erupt in the future.\"","stem":"What is another word for dormant? Options:","choices":{"A":"Awake,","B":"Asleep,","C":"Active,","D":"Gone"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says volcanoes are called dormant, or asleep, when they are quiet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are called dormant, or asleep, when they are quiet but could erupt in the future.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q004","read_aloud":"What is an active volcano? Options: A. One that is gone forever, B. One that is quiet and sleeping, C. One that can still erupt, D. One that has no heat","excerpt":"\"An active volcano is one that still has the ability to erupt.\"","stem":"What is an active volcano? Options:","choices":{"A":"One that is gone forever,","B":"One that is quiet and sleeping,","C":"One that can still erupt,","D":"One that has no heat"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that an active volcano is one that still has the ability to erupt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"An active volcano is one that still has the ability to erupt.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q005","read_aloud":"Can a dormant volcano erupt again? Options: A. No, never, B. Yes, it could erupt, C. Only if it is extinct, D. Only in the past","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are called dormant, or asleep, when they are quiet but could erupt in the future.\"","stem":"Can a dormant volcano erupt again? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, never,","B":"Yes, it could erupt,","C":"Only if it is extinct,","D":"Only in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that dormant volcanoes are quiet now but could erupt in the future.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are called dormant, or asleep, when they are quiet but could erupt in the future.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What is \"magma\"? A. solid rock on Earth\u0027s surface B. liquid rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface C. water in the ocean D. air in the atmosphere","excerpt":"\"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\"","stem":"What is \"magma\"?","choices":{"A":"solid rock on Earth\u0027s surface","B":"liquid rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface","C":"water in the ocean","D":"air in the atmosphere"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines magma as melted rock. It forms deep beneath the crust where it is very hot. Magma is liquid rock under Earth\u0027s surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is this paragraph mostly about? A. how volcanoes erupt B. stories people told about volcanoes long ago C. where volcanoes are found D. why volcanoes are dangerous","excerpt":"\"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire.\"","stem":"What is this paragraph mostly about?","choices":{"A":"how volcanoes erupt","B":"stories people told about volcanoes long ago","C":"where volcanoes are found","D":"why volcanoes are dangerous"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph tells about stories and beliefs from history. It mentions the Roman god Vulcan and Hawaiian legends about Pele.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q008","read_aloud":"Who was Pele? A. a Roman god of fire B. a Hawaiian goddess of fire C. a scientist who studied volcanoes D. a mountain in Hawaii","excerpt":"\"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. Pele was chased from her homes by her sister Namaka, goddess of the sea.\"","stem":"Who was Pele?","choices":{"A":"a Roman god of fire","B":"a Hawaiian goddess of fire","C":"a scientist who studied volcanoes","D":"a mountain in Hawaii"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that Pele was the Hawaiian goddess of fire. She was chased by her sister Namaka, goddess of the sea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. Pele was chased from her homes by her sister Namaka, goddess of the sea.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What is the top layer of solid rock called? A. the mantle B. the crust C. the core D. the magma","excerpt":"\"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust. Deep beneath the crust is the mantle.\"","stem":"What is the top layer of solid rock called?","choices":{"A":"the mantle","B":"the crust","C":"the core","D":"the magma"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text tells us that the top layers of solid rock are called the crust. The mantle is deep beneath the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust. Deep beneath the crust is the mantle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q010","read_aloud":"What causes a volcanic eruption? A. water freezing in the ocean B. magma pushing up through cracks in Earth\u0027s crust C. wind blowing over mountains D. plants growing on hills","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. This is called a volcanic eruption.\"","stem":"What causes a volcanic eruption?","choices":{"A":"water freezing in the ocean","B":"magma pushing up through cracks in Earth\u0027s crust","C":"wind blowing over mountains","D":"plants growing on hills"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. This process is called a volcanic eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. This is called a volcanic eruption.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does the word \"magma\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. melted rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface B. hard rock found on mountain tops C. water that flows through volcanoes D. gas that comes from volcanic eruptions","excerpt":"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.","stem":"What does the word \"magma\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"melted rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface","B":"hard rock found on mountain tops","C":"water that flows through volcanoes","D":"gas that comes from volcanic eruptions"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magma means melted rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface. The text says rock melts in the mantle and is called magma.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q012","read_aloud":"(Correcting to Volcanoes excerpt) What did early Romans believe about volcanoes? A. they were created by a fire god named Vulcan B. they were formed by earthquakes under the sea C. they were mountains made by giant animals D. they were holes that led to another world","excerpt":"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire.","stem":"(Correcting to Volcanoes excerpt) What did early Romans believe about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"they were created by a fire god named Vulcan","B":"they were formed by earthquakes under the sea","C":"they were mountains made by giant animals","D":"they were holes that led to another world"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire, who worked at a forge making swords and armor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What is the top layer of Earth called? A. the crust B. the mantle C. the outer core D. the inner core","excerpt":"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust.","stem":"What is the top layer of Earth called?","choices":{"A":"the crust","B":"the mantle","C":"the outer core","D":"the inner core"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states that the top layers of solid rock are called the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What is magma called when it reaches Earth\u0027s surface? A. lava B. ash C. steam D. rock","excerpt":"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.","stem":"What is magma called when it reaches Earth\u0027s surface?","choices":{"A":"lava","B":"ash","C":"steam","D":"rock"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says when magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q015","read_aloud":"How is a volcano formed? A. erupted material piles up around a vent B. water flows down and carves a mountain C. wind blows sand into a tall hill D. ice builds up layer by layer over time","excerpt":"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.","stem":"How is a volcano formed?","choices":{"A":"erupted material piles up around a vent","B":"water flows down and carves a mountain","C":"wind blows sand into a tall hill","D":"ice builds up layer by layer over time"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that a volcano is formed when erupted material piles up around the vent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. Volcanoes are dangerous. B. Ancient cultures created stories and gods to explain volcanoes. C. Volcanoes only erupt in Hawaii. D. Romans hated volcanoes.","excerpt":"\"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire. … The early Hawaiians told legends of … Pele, their goddess of fire.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes are dangerous.","B":"Ancient cultures created stories and gods to explain volcanoes.","C":"Volcanoes only erupt in Hawaii.","D":"Romans hated volcanoes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives examples of Roman and Hawaiian stories about volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire. … The early Hawaiians told legends of … Pele, their goddess of fire.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What forms a volcano? A. Wind blowing sand B. Erupted material piling up around a vent C. Glaciers melting D. Rivers carving rock","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"What forms a volcano?","choices":{"A":"Wind blowing sand","B":"Erupted material piling up around a vent","C":"Glaciers melting","D":"Rivers carving rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines a volcano as a hill formed by erupted material piling up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q018","read_aloud":"Who did the Romans believe was the god of fire? A. Pele B. Vulcan C. Namaka D. Surtsey","excerpt":"\"The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire. They thought that Vulcan worked at a hot forge, striking sparks as he made swords and armor for the other gods.\"","stem":"Who did the Romans believe was the god of fire?","choices":{"A":"Pele","B":"Vulcan","C":"Namaka","D":"Surtsey"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire. They thought that Vulcan worked at a hot forge, striking sparks as he made swords and armor for the other gods.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q019","read_aloud":"Who chased Pele from her homes? A. Her brother Vulcan B. Her sister Namaka C. The Romans D. The scientists","excerpt":"\"Pele was chased from her homes by her sister Namaka, goddess of the sea.\"","stem":"Who chased Pele from her homes?","choices":{"A":"Her brother Vulcan","B":"Her sister Namaka","C":"The Romans","D":"The scientists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that Namaka, her sister, chased Pele.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Pele was chased from her homes by her sister Namaka, goddess of the sea.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q020","read_aloud":"What is Kilauea? A. An extinct volcano B. A dormant volcano C. An active volcano D. A cold mountain","excerpt":"\"Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years. Kilauea is still an active volcano.\"","stem":"What is Kilauea?","choices":{"A":"An extinct volcano","B":"A dormant volcano","C":"An active volcano","D":"A cold mountain"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly states that Kilauea is still an active volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years. Kilauea is still an active volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q021","read_aloud":"According to the text, what pushes up through the cracks to form a volcano? A. Water B. Magma C. Trees D. Wind","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust.\"","stem":"According to the text, what pushes up through the cracks to form a volcano?","choices":{"A":"Water","B":"Magma","C":"Trees","D":"Wind"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that magma pushing up through cracks forms volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q022","read_aloud":"Based on the sentence, what does \u0027gushes\u0027 mean? Options:? A. To stop completely, B. To flow quickly, C. To move like ice, D. To become solid","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\"","stem":"Based on the sentence, what does \u0027gushes\u0027 mean? Options:?","choices":{"A":"To stop completely,","B":"To flow quickly,","C":"To move like ice,","D":"To become solid"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gushes means to spout or flow out quickly, which describes how the lava moves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What is the top layer of Earth called? Options:? A. The mantle, B. The core, C. The crust, D. The lava","excerpt":"\"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust. Deep beneath the crust is the mantle.\"","stem":"What is the top layer of Earth called? Options:?","choices":{"A":"The mantle,","B":"The core,","C":"The crust,","D":"The lava"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that the top layers of solid rock are called the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust. Deep beneath the crust is the mantle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q024","read_aloud":"What causes a volcanic eruption? Options:? A. Magma pushing through cracks, B. Too much water, C. Cold wind, D. People building houses","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. This is called a volcanic eruption.\"","stem":"What causes a volcanic eruption? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Magma pushing through cracks,","B":"Too much water,","C":"Cold wind,","D":"People building houses"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Volcanoes form and erupt when magma pushes up through cracks in the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. This is called a volcanic eruption.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What is magma? Options:? A. Frozen water, B. Solid rock on the surface, C. Melted rock beneath the crust, D. Cold air","excerpt":"\"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\"","stem":"What is magma? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Frozen water,","B":"Solid rock on the surface,","C":"Melted rock beneath the crust,","D":"Cold air"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Magma is the name given to the melted, or molten, rock found in the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the sentence, what does \u0027gushes\u0027 mean? Options: A. To stop completely, B. To flow quickly, C. To move like ice, D. To become solid","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\"","stem":"Based on the sentence, what does \u0027gushes\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"To stop completely,","B":"To flow quickly,","C":"To move like ice,","D":"To become solid"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gushes means to spout or flow out quickly, which describes how the lava moves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What is the top layer of Earth called? Options: A. The mantle, B. The core, C. The crust, D. The lava","excerpt":"\"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust. Deep beneath the crust is the mantle.\"","stem":"What is the top layer of Earth called? Options:","choices":{"A":"The mantle,","B":"The core,","C":"The crust,","D":"The lava"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that the top layers of solid rock are called the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. The top layers of solid rock are called the crust. Deep beneath the crust is the mantle.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What causes a volcanic eruption? Options: A. Magma pushing through cracks, B. Too much water, C. Cold wind, D. People building houses","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. This is called a volcanic eruption.\"","stem":"What causes a volcanic eruption? Options:","choices":{"A":"Magma pushing through cracks,","B":"Too much water,","C":"Cold wind,","D":"People building houses"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Volcanoes form and erupt when magma pushes up through cracks in the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. This is called a volcanic eruption.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q004","read_aloud":"What is magma? Options: A. Frozen water, B. Solid rock on the surface, C. Melted rock beneath the crust, D. Cold air","excerpt":"\"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\"","stem":"What is magma? Options:","choices":{"A":"Frozen water,","B":"Solid rock on the surface,","C":"Melted rock beneath the crust,","D":"Cold air"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Magma is the name given to the melted, or molten, rock found in the mantle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What is lava? Options: A. Magma that is on the surface, B. Hard rock underground, C. Gas in the sky, D. A type of mountain","excerpt":"\"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.\"","stem":"What is lava? Options:","choices":{"A":"Magma that is on the surface,","B":"Hard rock underground,","C":"Gas in the sky,","D":"A type of mountain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that magma becomes lava when it pours onto the surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"face\" mean in this sentence? A. the front part of a person\u0027s head B. the surface or front part of the mountain C. a clock showing the time D. a game with cards","excerpt":"\"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away. In its place is a huge volcanic crater.\"","stem":"What does \"face\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"the front part of a person\u0027s head","B":"the surface or front part of the mountain","C":"a clock showing the time","D":"a game with cards"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text is talking about a mountain. The \"north face\" means the north side or surface of the mountain. \"Face\" here means the outer surface or front part.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away. In its place is a huge volcanic crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What happened first before Mount St. Helens erupted? A. The mountain exploded immediately. B. Small earthquakes shook the mountain. C. Ash fell over 75,000 square miles. D. The mountain became a national monument.","excerpt":"\"First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain. Then, on March 27, Mount St. Helens began to spout ashes and steam. Each day brought further earthquakes.\"","stem":"What happened first before Mount St. Helens erupted?","choices":{"A":"The mountain exploded immediately.","B":"Small earthquakes shook the mountain.","C":"Ash fell over 75,000 square miles.","D":"The mountain became a national monument."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes events in order. First, there were small earthquakes. Then the mountain began to spout ashes and steam. The big eruption came later.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain. Then, on March 27, Mount St. Helens began to spout ashes and steam. Each day brought further earthquakes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What happens when magma reaches Earth\u0027s surface? A. It turns into ice. B. It is called lava. C. It disappears completely. D. It becomes part of the crust.","excerpt":"\"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava. In this photograph of an eruption, you can see great fountains of boiling lava forming fiery rivers and lakes.\"","stem":"What happens when magma reaches Earth\u0027s surface?","choices":{"A":"It turns into ice.","B":"It is called lava.","C":"It disappears completely.","D":"It becomes part of the crust."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that when magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava. Magma and lava are the same material, just in different locations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava. In this photograph of an eruption, you can see great fountains of boiling lava forming fiery rivers and lakes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q009","read_aloud":"What is a volcano? A. a type of ocean wave B. a hill or mountain formed by erupted material around a vent C. a kind of cloud in the sky D. a tool used by scientists","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"What is a volcano?","choices":{"A":"a type of ocean wave","B":"a hill or mountain formed by erupted material around a vent","C":"a kind of cloud in the sky","D":"a tool used by scientists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives a clear definition. A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by material that erupts and piles up around the vent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q010","read_aloud":"When did Mount Rainier last erupt? A. in the 1980s B. in the nineteenth century C. last year D. it has never erupted","excerpt":"\"Mount Rainier in the state of Washington is an ice-covered volcano that last erupted in the nineteenth century.\"","stem":"When did Mount Rainier last erupt?","choices":{"A":"in the 1980s","B":"in the nineteenth century","C":"last year","D":"it has never erupted"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that Mount Rainier last erupted in the nineteenth century. That was more than 100 years ago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mount Rainier in the state of Washington is an ice-covered volcano that last erupted in the nineteenth century.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q011","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"face\" in this sentence? A. front or outer part of something B. the expression on a person\u0027s head C. the bottom layer of a mountain D. the inside of a volcanic crater","excerpt":"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"face\" in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"front or outer part of something","B":"the expression on a person\u0027s head","C":"the bottom layer of a mountain","D":"the inside of a volcanic crater"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Face means the front or outer part of something. The text describes the north face of the volcano sliding away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What happened first when Mount St. Helens awakened? A. there were small earthquakes B. lava poured out of the crater C. ash fell over a huge area D. the mountain grew taller","excerpt":"In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain.","stem":"What happened first when Mount St. Helens awakened?","choices":{"A":"there were small earthquakes","B":"lava poured out of the crater","C":"ash fell over a huge area","D":"the mountain grew taller"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says first there were small earthquakes that shook the mountain when it awakened.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What time did Mount St. Helens erupt? A. 8:32 A.M. B. 9:15 A.M. C. 7:45 A.M. D. 10:00 A.M.","excerpt":"Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force.","stem":"What time did Mount St. Helens erupt?","choices":{"A":"8:32 A.M.","B":"9:15 A.M.","C":"7:45 A.M.","D":"10:00 A.M."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states the eruption happened at 8:32 A.M.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q014","read_aloud":"How powerful was the Mount St. Helens eruption? A. equal to ten million tons of dynamite B. equal to one million tons of coal C. equal to five thousand tons of gas D. equal to a small earthquake","excerpt":"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.","stem":"How powerful was the Mount St. Helens eruption?","choices":{"A":"equal to ten million tons of dynamite","B":"equal to one million tons of coal","C":"equal to five thousand tons of gas","D":"equal to a small earthquake"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states the energy released was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q015","read_aloud":"Why was the Mount St. Helens eruption so important? A. it was the most destructive in U.S. history B. it was the first volcano to erupt in America C. it created a new island in the ocean D. it was the smallest eruption ever recorded","excerpt":"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States.","stem":"Why was the Mount St. Helens eruption so important?","choices":{"A":"it was the most destructive in U.S. history","B":"it was the first volcano to erupt in America","C":"it created a new island in the ocean","D":"it was the smallest eruption ever recorded"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says this eruption was the most destructive in the history of the United States.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What happened right after the small earthquakes? A. The mountain exploded. B. The mountain began to spout ashes and steam. C. People left their homes. D. The mountain became quiet.","excerpt":"\"In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain. Then, on March 27, Mount St. Helens began to spout ashes and steam.\"","stem":"What happened right after the small earthquakes?","choices":{"A":"The mountain exploded.","B":"The mountain began to spout ashes and steam.","C":"People left their homes.","D":"The mountain became quiet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"First there were earthquakes. Then … it began to spout ashes and steam.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain. Then, on March 27, Mount St. Helens began to spout ashes and steam.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q017","read_aloud":"What effect did the eruption\u0027s force have on the surrounding area? A. It created new islands. B. It destroyed forests, houses, and roads, and people lost their lives. C. It made the mountain grow taller. D. It caused no damage.","excerpt":"\"Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force. The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\"","stem":"What effect did the eruption\u0027s force have on the surrounding area?","choices":{"A":"It created new islands.","B":"It destroyed forests, houses, and roads, and people lost their lives.","C":"It made the mountain grow taller.","D":"It caused no damage."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Later paragraphs describe destruction of forests, houses, roads, and loss of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force. The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q018","read_aloud":"How many people died in the Mount St. Helens eruption? A. 10 B. 60 C. 100 D. 1,000","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives.\"","stem":"How many people died in the Mount St. Helens eruption?","choices":{"A":"10","B":"60","C":"100","D":"1,000"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"Sixty people lost their lives.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q019","read_aloud":"Why might people want to visit the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument? A. To see the damage and learn about volcanoes B. To swim in the crater C. To climb the mountain without danger D. To find buried treasure","excerpt":"\"In 1982, the mountain and the area around it were dedicated as the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument. Visitor centers allow people to view the actively growing lava dome.\"","stem":"Why might people want to visit the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument?","choices":{"A":"To see the damage and learn about volcanoes","B":"To swim in the crater","C":"To climb the mountain without danger","D":"To find buried treasure"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The monument lets people see the volcano and learn about eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1982, the mountain and the area around it were dedicated as the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument. Visitor centers allow people to view the actively growing lava dome.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What does the word face mean in this sentence? A. The front or surface of the mountain B. A person\u0027s expression C. A clock D. The bottom of the ocean","excerpt":"\"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\"","stem":"What does the word face mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"The front or surface of the mountain","B":"A person\u0027s expression","C":"A clock","D":"The bottom of the ocean"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Here, face refers to the outer surface or side of the volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q021","read_aloud":"What is magma called when it reaches the surface? A. Crust B. Magma C. Lava D. Ash","excerpt":"\"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.\"","stem":"What is magma called when it reaches the surface?","choices":{"A":"Crust","B":"Magma","C":"Lava","D":"Ash"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that melted rock on the surface is called lava.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q022","read_aloud":"What happens when lava cools? A. It melts. B. It becomes gas. C. It hardens into rock. D. It turns into water.","excerpt":"\"As lava cools, it hardens to form rock that is also called lava.\"","stem":"What happens when lava cools?","choices":{"A":"It melts.","B":"It becomes gas.","C":"It hardens into rock.","D":"It turns into water."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says that cooling lava hardens to form rock.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As lava cools, it hardens to form rock that is also called lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q023","read_aloud":"How is a volcano hill or mountain formed? A. By water washing up sand B. By erupted material piling up C. By trees growing tall D. By wind blowing dirt","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"How is a volcano hill or mountain formed?","choices":{"A":"By water washing up sand","B":"By erupted material piling up","C":"By trees growing tall","D":"By wind blowing dirt"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that erupted material piles up to form the hill or mountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What covers Mount Rainier? A. Sand B. Trees C. Ice D. Lava","excerpt":"\"Mount Rainier in the state of Washington is an ice-covered volcano that last erupted in the nineteenth century.\"","stem":"What covers Mount Rainier?","choices":{"A":"Sand","B":"Trees","C":"Ice","D":"Lava"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes Mount Rainier as an ice-covered volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mount Rainier in the state of Washington is an ice-covered volcano that last erupted in the nineteenth century.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027erupt\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027erupt\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q001","read_aloud":"What does \u0027threatened\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options: A. To be helped, B. To be in danger, C. To be very strong, D. To be made of wood","excerpt":"\"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava. Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\"","stem":"What does \u0027threatened\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"To be helped,","B":"To be in danger,","C":"To be very strong,","D":"To be made of wood"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To be threatened means you are in a risky position or in danger from something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava. Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q002","read_aloud":"Why are scientists studying volcanoes now? Options: A. To build a new volcano, B. Because they want to know how volcanoes work, C. To hide the lava, D. To stop all mountains from growing","excerpt":"\"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes.\"","stem":"Why are scientists studying volcanoes now? Options:","choices":{"A":"To build a new volcano,","B":"Because they want to know how volcanoes work,","C":"To hide the lava,","D":"To stop all mountains from growing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Scientists study them to understand how they work, since people in early times did not know.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q003","read_aloud":"How does a volcano grow into a mountain or hill? Options: A. By piling up erupted material, B. By shrinking the crust, C. By freezing the ocean, D. By planting trees","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"How does a volcano grow into a mountain or hill? Options:","choices":{"A":"By piling up erupted material,","B":"By shrinking the crust,","C":"By freezing the ocean,","D":"By planting trees"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The mountain forms because material from eruptions piles up around the vent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q004","read_aloud":"Which is the largest Hawaiian volcano mentioned? Options: A. Mount Rainier, B. Mount St. Helens, C. Mauna Loa, D. Surtsey","excerpt":"\"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.\"","stem":"Which is the largest Hawaiian volcano mentioned? Options:","choices":{"A":"Mount Rainier,","B":"Mount St. Helens,","C":"Mauna Loa,","D":"Surtsey"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly identifies Mauna Loa as the largest Hawaiian volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q005","read_aloud":"What is another name for a composite volcano? Options: A. Shield volcano, B. Stratovolcano, C. Dome volcano, D. Cinder cone","excerpt":"\"Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions.\"","stem":"What is another name for a composite volcano? Options:","choices":{"A":"Shield volcano,","B":"Stratovolcano,","C":"Dome volcano,","D":"Cinder cone"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text notes that composite volcanoes are also called stratovolcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"reclaim\" mean in this sentence? A. to give away B. to take back C. to destroy completely D. to ignore forever","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot mountain of lava.\"","stem":"What does \"reclaim\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"to give away","B":"to take back","C":"to destroy completely","D":"to ignore forever"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The people left the island because of the volcano. After a year, they came back to reclaim it, which means they came back to take back their island and live there again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot mountain of lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q007","read_aloud":"How many people lost their lives in the Mount St. Helens eruption? A. six people B. sixty people C. six hundred people D. no people","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives. Measurable ash fell over a huge area of more than 75,000 square miles.\"","stem":"How many people lost their lives in the Mount St. Helens eruption?","choices":{"A":"six people","B":"sixty people","C":"six hundred people","D":"no people"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that sixty people lost their lives in the eruption of Mount St. Helens.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives. Measurable ash fell over a huge area of more than 75,000 square miles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q008","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Mount St. Helens before 1980? A. It had never erupted before. B. It had erupted long ago but seemed quiet for over 100 years. C. It was constantly erupting. D. It was not a real volcano.","excerpt":"\"Native Americans and early settlers in the Northwest had seen Mount St. Helens puff out some ash, steam, and lava in the mid-1800s. Yet for more than a century, the mountain seemed quiet and peaceful.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Mount St. Helens before 1980?","choices":{"A":"It had never erupted before.","B":"It had erupted long ago but seemed quiet for over 100 years.","C":"It was constantly erupting.","D":"It was not a real volcano."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says people saw it erupt in the mid-1800s. Then for more than a century, it seemed quiet. This means it had erupted before but had been calm for a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Native Americans and early settlers in the Northwest had seen Mount St. Helens puff out some ash, steam, and lava in the mid-1800s. Yet for more than a century, the mountain seemed quiet and peaceful.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q009","read_aloud":"How powerful was the Mount St. Helens eruption? A. as weak as a firecracker B. equal to ten million tons of dynamite C. stronger than any explosion ever D. too weak to measure","excerpt":"\"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\"","stem":"How powerful was the Mount St. Helens eruption?","choices":{"A":"as weak as a firecracker","B":"equal to ten million tons of dynamite","C":"stronger than any explosion ever","D":"too weak to measure"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly compares the eruption\u0027s energy to ten million tons of dynamite. This shows how incredibly powerful the eruption was.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q010","read_aloud":"What happened to Mount St. Helens after the eruption? A. It was destroyed completely. B. It became a national volcanic monument. C. It was turned into a city. D. It was forgotten by everyone.","excerpt":"\"In 1982, the mountain and the area around it were dedicated as the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument.\"","stem":"What happened to Mount St. Helens after the eruption?","choices":{"A":"It was destroyed completely.","B":"It became a national volcanic monument.","C":"It was turned into a city.","D":"It was forgotten by everyone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the mountain and area around it were dedicated as a national volcanic monument in 1982. This means it was protected as an important place for people to visit and learn.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1982, the mountain and the area around it were dedicated as the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"reclaim\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. take back or return to a place B. build something new on land C. leave a place forever D. study something very carefully","excerpt":"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.","stem":"What does \"reclaim\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"take back or return to a place","B":"build something new on land","C":"leave a place forever","D":"study something very carefully"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Reclaim means take back or return to. The text says people came back to reclaim their island after the eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What was one effect of the Mount St. Helens eruption? A. ash fell over more than 75,000 square miles B. new islands formed in the Pacific Ocean C. earthquakes stopped happening worldwide D. all volcanoes became inactive","excerpt":"Sixty people lost their lives. Measurable ash fell over a huge area of more than 75,000 square miles.","stem":"What was one effect of the Mount St. Helens eruption?","choices":{"A":"ash fell over more than 75,000 square miles","B":"new islands formed in the Pacific Ocean","C":"earthquakes stopped happening worldwide","D":"all volcanoes became inactive"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that measurable ash fell over a huge area of more than 75,000 square miles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sixty people lost their lives. Measurable ash fell over a huge area of more than 75,000 square miles."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What is Earth\u0027s crust compared to in this sentence? A. a giant cracked eggshell B. a smooth glass window C. a thick blanket of snow D. a solid block of stone","excerpt":"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell.","stem":"What is Earth\u0027s crust compared to in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a giant cracked eggshell","B":"a smooth glass window","C":"a thick blanket of snow","D":"a solid block of stone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text compares Earth\u0027s crust to a giant cracked eggshell to help readers picture the tectonic plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What are the pieces of Earth\u0027s crust called? A. plates B. layers C. shells D. rings","excerpt":"The pieces of the crust are called plates.","stem":"What are the pieces of Earth\u0027s crust called?","choices":{"A":"plates","B":"layers","C":"shells","D":"rings"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states that the pieces of the crust are called plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The pieces of the crust are called plates."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q015","read_aloud":"Where do most volcanoes erupt? A. where two tectonic plates meet B. in the middle of large oceans C. on top of the highest mountains D. in desert areas with little rain","excerpt":"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.","stem":"Where do most volcanoes erupt?","choices":{"A":"where two tectonic plates meet","B":"in the middle of large oceans","C":"on top of the highest mountains","D":"in desert areas with little rain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that most volcanoes erupt where two tectonic plates meet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What can you infer about where volcanoes are likely to form? A. In the middle of continents B. Where tectonic plates meet or move apart C. Only on land D. Only in deserts","excerpt":"\"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet. … Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them.\"","stem":"What can you infer about where volcanoes are likely to form?","choices":{"A":"In the middle of continents","B":"Where tectonic plates meet or move apart","C":"Only on land","D":"Only in deserts"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says most volcanoes erupt where two plates meet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet. … Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q017","read_aloud":"How does the photograph help you understand the text? A. It shows how the mountain changed dramatically after the eruption. B. It shows what people wore in 1980. C. It shows the inside of the volcano. D. It shows animals that live on the mountain.","excerpt":"The page includes a photograph of Mount St. Helens before and after the eruption.","stem":"How does the photograph help you understand the text?","choices":{"A":"It shows how the mountain changed dramatically after the eruption.","B":"It shows what people wore in 1980.","C":"It shows the inside of the volcano.","D":"It shows animals that live on the mountain."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The beforeandafter photos show the destruction.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The page includes a photograph of Mount St. Helens before and after the eruption."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q018","read_aloud":"How many people were evacuated from Heimaey? A. 500 B. 1,000 C. 5,000 D. 10,000","excerpt":"\"Ten years after the explosion that formed Surtsey, another volcano erupted off the south coast of Iceland on the island of Heimaey. Within six hours of the eruption, more than 5,000 people were taken off the island to safety.\"","stem":"How many people were evacuated from Heimaey?","choices":{"A":"500","B":"1,000","C":"5,000","D":"10,000"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"more than 5,000 people were taken off the island.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ten years after the explosion that formed Surtsey, another volcano erupted off the south coast of Iceland on the island of Heimaey. Within six hours of the eruption, more than 5,000 people were taken off the island to safety.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What happens after an eruption? A. Nothing ever grows again. B. Life slowly renews itself. C. The area becomes a desert forever. D. Only animals return.","excerpt":"\"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself. Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks.\"","stem":"What happens after an eruption?","choices":{"A":"Nothing ever grows again.","B":"Life slowly renews itself.","C":"The area becomes a desert forever.","D":"Only animals return."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says life renews itself in a few months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself. Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q020","read_aloud":"What time did Mount St. Helens erupt on May 18? A. 7:00 A.M. B. 8:32 A.M. C. 12:00 P.M. D. 5:00 P.M.","excerpt":"\"Sunday, May 18, dawned bright and clear. The mountain seemed much the same as it had been for the past month. Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force.\"","stem":"What time did Mount St. Helens erupt on May 18?","choices":{"A":"7:00 A.M.","B":"8:32 A.M.","C":"12:00 P.M.","D":"5:00 P.M."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives the specific time of the eruption as 8:32 A.M.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sunday, May 18, dawned bright and clear. The mountain seemed much the same as it had been for the past month. Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What does the author compare the energy to? A. Ten million tons of dynamite B. A small firecracker C. A lightning bolt D. A nuclear bomb","excerpt":"\"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\"","stem":"What does the author compare the energy to?","choices":{"A":"Ten million tons of dynamite","B":"A small firecracker","C":"A lightning bolt","D":"A nuclear bomb"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author uses the comparison of ten million tons of dynamite to describe the force.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q022","read_aloud":"What happened first when the volcano woke up? A. Lava flowed down the street. B. Ash fell on the houses. C. Small earthquakes shook the mountain. D. The top of the mountain fell off.","excerpt":"\"In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain.\"","stem":"What happened first when the volcano woke up?","choices":{"A":"Lava flowed down the street.","B":"Ash fell on the houses.","C":"Small earthquakes shook the mountain.","D":"The top of the mountain fell off."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists small earthquakes as the first sign that the volcano was waking up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q023","read_aloud":"Why does the author call the eruption \"most destructive\"? A. It was the biggest noise ever. B. It caused the most damage and loss. C. It lasted the longest time. D. It was the first eruption ever.","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States.\"","stem":"Why does the author call the eruption \"most destructive\"?","choices":{"A":"It was the biggest noise ever.","B":"It caused the most damage and loss.","C":"It lasted the longest time.","D":"It was the first eruption ever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Destructive means causing much damage. The text lists lives lost, houses destroyed, and forests blown down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l03-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What does \u0027reclaim\u0027 mean? Options: A. To build something new, B. To take back or get something again, C. To move away forever, D. To watch from afar","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.\"","stem":"What does \u0027reclaim\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"To build something new,","B":"To take back or get something again,","C":"To move away forever,","D":"To watch from afar"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To reclaim means to get something back that you once had.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q002","read_aloud":"How powerful was the eruption of Mount St. Helens? Options: A. Like a small fire, B. Like a few rocks falling, C. Like ten million tons of dynamite, D. Like a quiet breeze","excerpt":"\"Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. ... The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\"","stem":"How powerful was the eruption of Mount St. Helens? Options:","choices":{"A":"Like a small fire,","B":"Like a few rocks falling,","C":"Like ten million tons of dynamite,","D":"Like a quiet breeze"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text compares the massive energy of the eruption to ten million tons of dynamite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. ... The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author describe Earth\u0027s crust? Options: A. Like a smooth ball, B. Like a giant cracked eggshell, C. Like a flat table, D. Like a piece of cloth","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\"","stem":"How does the author describe Earth\u0027s crust? Options:","choices":{"A":"Like a smooth ball,","B":"Like a giant cracked eggshell,","C":"Like a flat table,","D":"Like a piece of cloth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses the comparison of a cracked eggshell to help explain how the crust is broken into plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the phrase \"like rows of matchsticks\" to describe the trees? Options: A. To show that the trees were made of wood, B. To show how easily and completely the force destroyed the forest, C. To show that the trees were burning, D. To show that the trees were very small","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. ... The force of the eruption was so great that entire forests were blown down like rows of matchsticks.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the phrase \"like rows of matchsticks\" to describe the trees? Options:","choices":{"A":"To show that the trees were made of wood,","B":"To show how easily and completely the force destroyed the forest,","C":"To show that the trees were burning,","D":"To show that the trees were very small"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing them to matchsticks shows that the eruption\u0027s force was powerful enough to knock down large trees as if they were tiny objects.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. ... The force of the eruption was so great that entire forests were blown down like rows of matchsticks.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q005","read_aloud":"Why do dome volcanoes explode? Options: A. Because they are too cold, B. Because pressure builds up when the lava is plugged, C. Because they are at the bottom of the sea, D. Because the wind is too strong","excerpt":"\"As the pressure builds up, the volcano eventually explodes, as Mount St. Helens did.\"","stem":"Why do dome volcanoes explode? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they are too cold,","B":"Because pressure builds up when the lava is plugged,","C":"Because they are at the bottom of the sea,","D":"Because the wind is too strong"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"When hardened lava plugs the vent, it traps gases and causes pressure to build until an explosion occurs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As the pressure builds up, the volcano eventually explodes, as Mount St. Helens did.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"gushes\" mean in this sentence? A. drips slowly B. spouts or flows quickly C. freezes solid D. disappears underground","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\"","stem":"What does \"gushes\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"drips slowly","B":"spouts or flows quickly","C":"freezes solid","D":"disappears underground"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes lava coming out in fountains. \"Gushes\" means spouts or flows quickly, like water shooting out of a fountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q007","read_aloud":"How is aa lava different from pahoehoe lava? A. They are exactly the same. B. Aa is thick and slow, while pahoehoe is thin and quick. C. Aa is smooth, while pahoehoe is rough. D. Aa comes from the sky, while pahoehoe comes from the ocean.","excerpt":"\"Thick, slow-moving lava called aa hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks. Thin, hot, quick-moving lava called pahoehoe forms a smooth, billowy surface.\"","stem":"How is aa lava different from pahoehoe lava?","choices":{"A":"They are exactly the same.","B":"Aa is thick and slow, while pahoehoe is thin and quick.","C":"Aa is smooth, while pahoehoe is rough.","D":"Aa comes from the sky, while pahoehoe comes from the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text compares the two types. Aa is thick and slow-moving. Pahoehoe is thin, hot, and quick-moving. They harden into different surfaces.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Thick, slow-moving lava called aa hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks. Thin, hot, quick-moving lava called pahoehoe forms a smooth, billowy surface.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q008","read_aloud":"Why don\u0027t volcanoes happen just anywhere? A. because they only happen where tectonic plates meet B. because volcanoes are random C. because the Earth is flat D. because volcanoes need snow","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\"","stem":"Why don\u0027t volcanoes happen just anywhere?","choices":{"A":"because they only happen where tectonic plates meet","B":"because volcanoes are random","C":"because the Earth is flat","D":"because volcanoes need snow"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that Earth\u0027s crust is broken into plates. Most volcanoes erupt where two plates meet. This is why volcanoes do not happen just anywhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q009","read_aloud":"If you wanted to find a volcano, where should you look? A. in the middle of a desert far from any plate edge B. near the edges where two tectonic plates meet C. at the North Pole only D. underwater in the deepest ocean only","excerpt":"\"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\"","stem":"If you wanted to find a volcano, where should you look?","choices":{"A":"in the middle of a desert far from any plate edge","B":"near the edges where two tectonic plates meet","C":"at the North Pole only","D":"underwater in the deepest ocean only"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says most volcanoes erupt where two plates meet. If you want to find a volcano, you should look near plate boundaries or edges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q010","read_aloud":"How do underwater volcanoes become islands? A. They grow tall enough to rise above sea level. B. They are built by people. C. They float up from the bottom. D. They are carried by ships.","excerpt":"\"Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them. A chain of underwater volcanoes runs along the line where the two plates meet.\"","stem":"How do underwater volcanoes become islands?","choices":{"A":"They grow tall enough to rise above sea level.","B":"They are built by people.","C":"They float up from the bottom.","D":"They are carried by ships."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says some underwater volcanoes have grown so high that they rise from the ocean floor to above sea level as islands. Lava keeps piling up until the volcano breaks through the water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them. A chain of underwater volcanoes runs along the line where the two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"gushes\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. flows out quickly and forcefully B. freezes into hard ice crystals C. disappears into the ground slowly D. turns into gas and rises upward","excerpt":"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.","stem":"What does \"gushes\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"flows out quickly and forcefully","B":"freezes into hard ice crystals","C":"disappears into the ground slowly","D":"turns into gas and rises upward"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Gushes means flows out quickly and forcefully. The text describes lava shooting out in fountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q012","read_aloud":"What happens when tectonic plates move apart? A. hot magma pushes up between them B. the ocean water freezes into ice C. mountains form on the ocean floor D. volcanoes stop erupting completely","excerpt":"Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them.","stem":"What happens when tectonic plates move apart?","choices":{"A":"hot magma pushes up between them","B":"the ocean water freezes into ice","C":"mountains form on the ocean floor","D":"volcanoes stop erupting completely"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says when plates move apart, hot magma pushes up between them, forming underwater volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What happened near Iceland in 1963? A. an undersea volcano erupted and formed a new island B. a large earthquake shook the island C. the ocean water turned into steam D. a glacier melted and flooded the coast","excerpt":"Iceland is a volcanic island in the North Atlantic. In 1963, an area of the sea near Iceland began to boil and churn.","stem":"What happened near Iceland in 1963?","choices":{"A":"an undersea volcano erupted and formed a new island","B":"a large earthquake shook the island","C":"the ocean water turned into steam","D":"a glacier melted and flooded the coast"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes how an undersea volcano erupted near Iceland and formed a new island called Surtsey.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Iceland is a volcanic island in the North Atlantic. In 1963, an area of the sea near Iceland began to boil and churn."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q014","read_aloud":"If you were solving a problem about volcanoes, what might you learn from this idea? A. use both technology and human thinking to find solutions B. only trust computers to solve science problems C. never use computers for any scientific work D. ignore what scientists have already discovered","excerpt":"A computer can calculate numbers faster than the human brain; but people bring creativity and common sense to a problem, something a computer cannot do.","stem":"If you were solving a problem about volcanoes, what might you learn from this idea?","choices":{"A":"use both technology and human thinking to find solutions","B":"only trust computers to solve science problems","C":"never use computers for any scientific work","D":"ignore what scientists have already discovered"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This question asks students to apply the idea that combining technology with human creativity leads to better problem-solving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A computer can calculate numbers faster than the human brain; but people bring creativity and common sense to a problem, something a computer cannot do."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q015","read_aloud":"How does this detail show the relationship between volcanoes and mountains? A. plate movements can create both volcanoes and mountains B. mountains are always formed by volcanic eruptions C. volcanoes only form in flat areas, not mountains D. mountains prevent volcanoes from erupting","excerpt":"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.","stem":"How does this detail show the relationship between volcanoes and mountains?","choices":{"A":"plate movements can create both volcanoes and mountains","B":"mountains are always formed by volcanic eruptions","C":"volcanoes only form in flat areas, not mountains","D":"mountains prevent volcanoes from erupting"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that tectonic plate movements cause both volcanic activity and mountain formation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q016","read_aloud":"How are Hawaiian volcanoes different from Mount St. Helens? A. Hawaiian volcanoes are more violent. B. Hawaiian volcanoes are much less violent. C. Hawaiian volcanoes never erupt. D. Both are equally violent.","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens. Only rarely does a Hawaiian volcano throw out rock and high clouds of ash.\"","stem":"How are Hawaiian volcanoes different from Mount St. Helens?","choices":{"A":"Hawaiian volcanoes are more violent.","B":"Hawaiian volcanoes are much less violent.","C":"Hawaiian volcanoes never erupt.","D":"Both are equally violent."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly says Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens. Only rarely does a Hawaiian volcano throw out rock and high clouds of ash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Why were houses threatened in 1986? A. Because the lava moved very quickly. B. Because people built too close. C. Because there was no warning. D. Because the lava was slow.","excerpt":"\"In some lava rivers, speeds as high as thirtyfive miles per hour have been measured. In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quickmoving lava.\"","stem":"Why were houses threatened in 1986?","choices":{"A":"Because the lava moved very quickly.","B":"Because people built too close.","C":"Because there was no warning.","D":"Because the lava was slow."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The fast speed of the lava caused the threat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In some lava rivers, speeds as high as thirtyfive miles per hour have been measured. In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quickmoving lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q018","read_aloud":"What can scientists learn from the types of volcanic rock? A. The age of the volcano B. The kind of eruption that happened C. The color of the lava D. The height of the volcano","excerpt":"\"The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption. The two main kinds in Hawaii have Hawaiian names. Thick, slowmoving lava called aa hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks. Thin, hot, quickmoving lava called pahoehoe forms a smooth, billowy surface.\"","stem":"What can scientists learn from the types of volcanic rock?","choices":{"A":"The age of the volcano","B":"The kind of eruption that happened","C":"The color of the lava","D":"The height of the volcano"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The rocks are clues to the kind of eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption. The two main kinds in Hawaii have Hawaiian names. Thick, slowmoving lava called aa hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks. Thin, hot, quickmoving lava called pahoehoe forms a smooth, billowy surface.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q019","read_aloud":"If you were a firefighter facing fast lava, why would you spray water on it? A. To make the lava hotter B. To cool it and slow it down C. To turn it into gas D. To make it flow faster","excerpt":"\"Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\"","stem":"If you were a firefighter facing fast lava, why would you spray water on it?","choices":{"A":"To make the lava hotter","B":"To cool it and slow it down","C":"To turn it into gas","D":"To make it flow faster"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Cooling lava slows its movement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for face (surface/front)? A. Back B. Hide C. Side D. Cover","excerpt":"\"The cinder cone on Pacaya volcano in Guatemala, Central America, has had frequent eruptions.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for face (surface/front)?","choices":{"A":"Back","B":"Hide","C":"Side","D":"Cover"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"A face of a mountain is often called a side. \"Side\" is a synonym for the surface or face of an object like a mountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The cinder cone on Pacaya volcano in Guatemala, Central America, has had frequent eruptions.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What are the pieces of Earth\u0027s crust called? A. Eggshells B. Plates C. Islands D. Magma","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\"","stem":"What are the pieces of Earth\u0027s crust called?","choices":{"A":"Eggshells","B":"Plates","C":"Islands","D":"Magma"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text compares the crust to an eggshell but names the pieces \"plates.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q022","read_aloud":"Where do most volcanoes erupt? A. In the middle of a plate B. Where two plates meet C. Under the ocean only D. On top of mountains","excerpt":"\"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\"","stem":"Where do most volcanoes erupt?","choices":{"A":"In the middle of a plate","B":"Where two plates meet","C":"Under the ocean only","D":"On top of mountains"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that most volcanoes erupt where plates meet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How was the island of Surtsey formed? A. People built it with rocks. B. An undersea volcano exploded and built it up. C. A ship sank and became an island. D. Earthquakes pushed land up.","excerpt":"\"In 1963, an area of the sea near Iceland began to boil and churn. An undersea volcano was exploding and a new island was being formed.\"","stem":"How was the island of Surtsey formed?","choices":{"A":"People built it with rocks.","B":"An undersea volcano exploded and built it up.","C":"A ship sank and became an island.","D":"Earthquakes pushed land up."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes an undersea volcano exploding and forming the new island.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1963, an area of the sea near Iceland began to boil and churn. An undersea volcano was exploding and a new island was being formed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q024","read_aloud":"Why was the island named Surtsey? A. It was named after a famous sailor. B. It was named after an ancient god of fire. C. It was named after the first person to see it. D. It was named after a fish.","excerpt":"\"The island was named Surtsey, after the ancient Norse god of fire.\"","stem":"Why was the island named Surtsey?","choices":{"A":"It was named after a famous sailor.","B":"It was named after an ancient god of fire.","C":"It was named after the first person to see it.","D":"It was named after a fish."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly says it was named after the ancient Norse god of fire.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The island was named Surtsey, after the ancient Norse god of fire.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l04-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does \u0027billow\u0027 mean? Options: A. To stay still, B. To rise or roll in large clouds, C. To turn into ice, D. To sink underwater","excerpt":"\"Steam clouds billow as a flow of hot lava enters the sea.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does \u0027billow\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"To stay still,","B":"To rise or roll in large clouds,","C":"To turn into ice,","D":"To sink underwater"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Billow describes how steam or clouds move and swell outward in large, rolling shapes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Steam clouds billow as a flow of hot lava enters the sea.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q002","read_aloud":"Where do most of the world\u0027s volcanoes happen? Options: A. In the middle of the ocean only, B. Where two plates meet, C. In the center of a continent, D. Only on cold islands","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. ... Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\"","stem":"Where do most of the world\u0027s volcanoes happen? Options:","choices":{"A":"In the middle of the ocean only,","B":"Where two plates meet,","C":"In the center of a continent,","D":"Only on cold islands"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that volcanoes are usually found where the plates of Earth\u0027s crust meet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. ... Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q003","read_aloud":"Why are they called shield volcanoes? Options: A. Because they are made of metal, B. Because they have broad, gentle slopes like a warrior\u0027s shield, C. Because they protect the Earth, D. Because they are very small","excerpt":"\"Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes shaped like an ancient warrior\u0027s shield.\"","stem":"Why are they called shield volcanoes? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they are made of metal,","B":"Because they have broad, gentle slopes like a warrior\u0027s shield,","C":"Because they protect the Earth,","D":"Because they are very small"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The name comes from their shape, which looks like a shield laid on the ground.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes shaped like an ancient warrior\u0027s shield.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q004","read_aloud":"Why is this area called the \"Ring of Fire\"? Options: A. Because it is always hot, B. Because there are many volcanoes and earthquakes there, C. Because people have campfires there, D. Because the sun hits it directly","excerpt":"\"Many volcanoes and earthquakes are located along the margins of the large Pacific plate. Volcanoes and earthquakes are so numerous that these margins are called the \u0027Ring of Fire.\u0027\"","stem":"Why is this area called the \"Ring of Fire\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because it is always hot,","B":"Because there are many volcanoes and earthquakes there,","C":"Because people have campfires there,","D":"Because the sun hits it directly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The high number of volcanic and earthquake activities in this region gives it its famous name.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many volcanoes and earthquakes are located along the margins of the large Pacific plate. Volcanoes and earthquakes are so numerous that these margins are called the \u0027Ring of Fire.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q005","read_aloud":"How does the author show that volcanoes are not just destructive? Options: A. By explaining that plants and animals return and soil is created, B. By saying that volcanoes are beautiful, C. By stating that volcanoes are good for homes, D. By saying that eruptions are quiet","excerpt":"\"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. ... But in a few short months, life renews itself.\"","stem":"How does the author show that volcanoes are not just destructive? Options:","choices":{"A":"By explaining that plants and animals return and soil is created,","B":"By saying that volcanoes are beautiful,","C":"By stating that volcanoes are good for homes,","D":"By saying that eruptions are quiet"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author points out that while destruction happens first, volcanoes also help create new land and new soil for life to return.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. ... But in a few short months, life renews itself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"threatened\" mean in this sentence? A. protected and safe B. endangered or put in a risky position C. decorated with flowers D. ignored completely","excerpt":"\"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava. Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\"","stem":"What does \"threatened\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"protected and safe","B":"endangered or put in a risky position","C":"decorated with flowers","D":"ignored completely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The houses were in danger from the quick-moving lava. Firefighters had to spray water to slow it down. \"Threatened\" means endangered or put in a risky position.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava. Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Hawaiian volcanoes? A. They are the most dangerous volcanoes in the world. B. They are usually less explosive than some other volcanoes. C. They never erupt at all. D. They only erupt underwater.","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens. Only rarely does a Hawaiian volcano throw out rock and high clouds of ash.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Hawaiian volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"They are the most dangerous volcanoes in the world.","B":"They are usually less explosive than some other volcanoes.","C":"They never erupt at all.","D":"They only erupt underwater."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than Surtsey or Mount St. Helens. They rarely throw out rock and ash. This means they are usually less explosive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens. Only rarely does a Hawaiian volcano throw out rock and high clouds of ash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q008","read_aloud":"How does the map help readers understand where volcanoes form? A. by showing that volcanoes only form in Hawaii B. by showing the locations of plate boundaries where volcanoes often erupt C. by hiding information from readers D. by showing only ocean locations","excerpt":"[Map showing tectonic plates with arrows indicating movement]","stem":"How does the map help readers understand where volcanoes form?","choices":{"A":"by showing that volcanoes only form in Hawaii","B":"by showing the locations of plate boundaries where volcanoes often erupt","C":"by hiding information from readers","D":"by showing only ocean locations"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The map shows tectonic plates and their boundaries. Since the text says most volcanoes erupt where plates meet, the map helps readers see those locations around the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: [Map showing tectonic plates with arrows indicating movement]"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q009","read_aloud":"How do volcanoes help Hawaii grow? A. by destroying old land B. by adding new land when lava flows into the sea and hardens C. by making the ocean deeper D. by moving the island to a new location","excerpt":"\"Hawaii is constantly changing as frequent eruptions of the Mauna Loa and Kilauea volcanoes add hundreds of acres of new land to the Big Island.\"","stem":"How do volcanoes help Hawaii grow?","choices":{"A":"by destroying old land","B":"by adding new land when lava flows into the sea and hardens","C":"by making the ocean deeper","D":"by moving the island to a new location"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says eruptions add hundreds of acres of new land. When lava flows into the sea and hardens, it becomes new land. This makes the Big Island grow larger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaii is constantly changing as frequent eruptions of the Mauna Loa and Kilauea volcanoes add hundreds of acres of new land to the Big Island.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the measurements of Mauna Loa? A. to show how small the volcano is B. to help readers understand how enormous Mauna Loa really is C. to prove that Mauna Loa is extinct D. to describe the weather in Hawaii","excerpt":"\"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.\"","stem":"Why does the author include the measurements of Mauna Loa?","choices":{"A":"to show how small the volcano is","B":"to help readers understand how enormous Mauna Loa really is","C":"to prove that Mauna Loa is extinct","D":"to describe the weather in Hawaii"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Seventy miles long and thirty thousand feet tall are huge numbers. The author uses these measurements to show readers that Mauna Loa is an enormous volcano. Numbers help readers imagine the size.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"threatened\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. put in danger or at risk of harm B. protected from all types of damage C. moved to a safer location quickly D. studied carefully by scientists","excerpt":"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava.","stem":"What does \"threatened\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"put in danger or at risk of harm","B":"protected from all types of damage","C":"moved to a safer location quickly","D":"studied carefully by scientists"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Threatened means put in danger. The text says houses were at risk from the fast-moving lava.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What makes Mauna Loa special among Hawaiian volcanoes? A. it is the largest and rises 30,000 feet from the ocean floor B. it erupts more often than any other volcano C. it is the only volcano that produces black lava D. it is located on a different tectonic plate","excerpt":"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.","stem":"What makes Mauna Loa special among Hawaiian volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"it is the largest and rises 30,000 feet from the ocean floor","B":"it erupts more often than any other volcano","C":"it is the only volcano that produces black lava","D":"it is located on a different tectonic plate"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states Mauna Loa is the largest Hawaiian volcano, rising thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q013","read_aloud":"How fast can Hawaiian lava rivers flow? A. as high as thirty-five miles per hour B. about five miles per hour C. slower than a person can walk D. faster than the speed of sound","excerpt":"Hawaiian lava is fluid and flows quickly. In some lava rivers, speeds as high as thirty-five miles per hour have been measured.","stem":"How fast can Hawaiian lava rivers flow?","choices":{"A":"as high as thirty-five miles per hour","B":"about five miles per hour","C":"slower than a person can walk","D":"faster than the speed of sound"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says some lava rivers have been measured flowing at speeds as high as thirty-five miles per hour.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Hawaiian lava is fluid and flows quickly. In some lava rivers, speeds as high as thirty-five miles per hour have been measured."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q014","read_aloud":"If you were trying to protect a town from lava, what strategy might you use based on this example? A. spray water on the lava to slow it down B. build walls of ice to block the lava flow C. move the town to a different location D. wait for the lava to cool on its own","excerpt":"Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.","stem":"If you were trying to protect a town from lava, what strategy might you use based on this example?","choices":{"A":"spray water on the lava to slow it down","B":"build walls of ice to block the lava flow","C":"move the town to a different location","D":"wait for the lava to cool on its own"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the strategy used by firefighters to slow lava with water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q015","read_aloud":"How does this detail help scientists study volcanoes? A. rock types provide clues about how a volcano erupted B. all volcanic rocks look exactly the same C. rocks can predict when the next eruption will happen D. volcanic rocks are only found near active volcanoes","excerpt":"When lava cools and hardens, it forms volcanic rocks. The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption.","stem":"How does this detail help scientists study volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"rock types provide clues about how a volcano erupted","B":"all volcanic rocks look exactly the same","C":"rocks can predict when the next eruption will happen","D":"volcanic rocks are only found near active volcanoes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that different rock formations help scientists understand the type of volcanic eruption that occurred.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When lava cools and hardens, it forms volcanic rocks. The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this section? A. All volcanoes look the same. B. Volcanoes can be classified into four types based on their shape and eruption style. C. Only shield volcanoes are dangerous. D. There is only one type of volcano.","excerpt":"\"Earth scientists have divided volcanoes into four groups. Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes … Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand … Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. … A fourth kind of volcano is called a dome volcano.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this section?","choices":{"A":"All volcanoes look the same.","B":"Volcanoes can be classified into four types based on their shape and eruption style.","C":"Only shield volcanoes are dangerous.","D":"There is only one type of volcano."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes four groups of volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth scientists have divided volcanoes into four groups. Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes … Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand … Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. … A fourth kind of volcano is called a dome volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q017","read_aloud":"Why do dome volcanoes sometimes explode violently? A. Because they have thin lava B. Because gases build up pressure behind a hardened plug C. Because they are underwater D. Because they are extinct","excerpt":"\"Dome volcanoes have thick, slowmoving lava that forms a steepsided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava. The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water. As the pressure builds up, the volcano eventually explodes, as Mount St. Helens did.\"","stem":"Why do dome volcanoes sometimes explode violently?","choices":{"A":"Because they have thin lava","B":"Because gases build up pressure behind a hardened plug","C":"Because they are underwater","D":"Because they are extinct"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The plug traps gases, building pressure until explosion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dome volcanoes have thick, slowmoving lava that forms a steepsided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava. The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water. As the pressure builds up, the volcano eventually explodes, as Mount St. Helens did.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q018","read_aloud":"How does a stratovolcano grow over time? A. It grows all at once in one eruption. B. It grows in layers from many eruptions, alternating ash and lava. C. It only grows from lava flows. D. It never grows.","excerpt":"\"Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions. An eruption can be initially explosive, when ash and cinders fall to the ground. Later the eruption becomes less violent and lava slowly flows out, covering the layer of ash and cinders.\"","stem":"How does a stratovolcano grow over time?","choices":{"A":"It grows all at once in one eruption.","B":"It grows in layers from many eruptions, alternating ash and lava.","C":"It only grows from lava flows.","D":"It never grows."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Layers of ash and lava build up from multiple eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions. An eruption can be initially explosive, when ash and cinders fall to the ground. Later the eruption becomes less violent and lava slowly flows out, covering the layer of ash and cinders.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Do you think volcanoes are more destructive or more beneficial overall? Why? A. More destructive, because they kill people and destroy homes. B. More beneficial, because they create new land and soil. C. Both; they cause destruction but also create new land over time. D. Neither; volcanoes have no effect.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\"","stem":"Do you think volcanoes are more destructive or more beneficial overall? Why?","choices":{"A":"More destructive, because they kill people and destroy homes.","B":"More beneficial, because they create new land and soil.","C":"Both; they cause destruction but also create new land over time.","D":"Neither; volcanoes have no effect."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states both destructive and beneficial effects.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q020","read_aloud":"What does gushes mean? A. Flows slowly B. Stops moving C. Flows quickly D. Freezes hard","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\"","stem":"What does gushes mean?","choices":{"A":"Flows slowly","B":"Stops moving","C":"Flows quickly","D":"Freezes hard"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"To gush means to flow out quickly and in large amounts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q021","read_aloud":"Why were people taken off the island of Heimaey? A. They were going on vacation. B. They were moving to a new country. C. A volcano had erupted nearby. D. They wanted to see the ocean.","excerpt":"\"Within six hours of the eruption, more than 5,000 people were taken off the island to safety.\"","stem":"Why were people taken off the island of Heimaey?","choices":{"A":"They were going on vacation.","B":"They were moving to a new country.","C":"A volcano had erupted nearby.","D":"They wanted to see the ocean."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says the volcano erupted on Heimaey, so people were taken to safety.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Within six hours of the eruption, more than 5,000 people were taken off the island to safety.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q022","read_aloud":"What is the \"Ring of Fire\"? A. A circle of volcanoes and earthquakes around the Pacific plate B. A forest fire in California C. A burning island in the Atlantic D. A line of volcanoes in Africa","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes and earthquakes are so numerous that these margins are called the \u0027Ring of Fire.\u0027\"","stem":"What is the \"Ring of Fire\"?","choices":{"A":"A circle of volcanoes and earthquakes around the Pacific plate","B":"A forest fire in California","C":"A burning island in the Atlantic","D":"A line of volcanoes in Africa"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines the Ring of Fire as the margins of the Pacific plate with many volcanoes and earthquakes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes and earthquakes are so numerous that these margins are called the \u0027Ring of Fire.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q023","read_aloud":"Why did firefighters spray water on the lava? A. To clean the streets B. To cool it down and slow it C. To make steam for energy D. To help the plants grow","excerpt":"\"Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\"","stem":"Why did firefighters spray water on the lava?","choices":{"A":"To clean the streets","B":"To cool it down and slow it","C":"To make steam for energy","D":"To help the plants grow"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Spraying water cools the lava, which helps slow its movement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How do Hawaiian eruptions compare to Mount St. Helens? A. They are more violent. B. They are less violent. C. They are exactly the same. D. They never happen.","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens.\"","stem":"How do Hawaiian eruptions compare to Mount St. Helens?","choices":{"A":"They are more violent.","B":"They are less violent.","C":"They are exactly the same.","D":"They never happen."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Hawaiian volcanoes erupt \"much less violently.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l05-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q001","read_aloud":"What does \u0027extinct\u0027 mean? Options: A. A volcano that will erupt tomorrow, B. A volcano that is no longer connected to magma, C. A volcano that is very active, D. A volcano that is made of water","excerpt":"\"A volcano that has not erupted in the last 10,000 years, or a volcano that is no longer connected to magma below the Earth\u0027s surface, is called extinct.\"","stem":"What does \u0027extinct\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"A volcano that will erupt tomorrow,","B":"A volcano that is no longer connected to magma,","C":"A volcano that is very active,","D":"A volcano that is made of water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Extinct means the volcano is dead and no longer has a connection to the magma supply.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano that has not erupted in the last 10,000 years, or a volcano that is no longer connected to magma below the Earth\u0027s surface, is called extinct.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q002","read_aloud":"Where does the word \"volcano\" come from? Options: A. The word for fire, B. The name of a Roman god, C. A type of rock, D. The word for mountain","excerpt":"\"The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire. ... It is from the Roman Vulcan that we get the word volcano.\"","stem":"Where does the word \"volcano\" come from? Options:","choices":{"A":"The word for fire,","B":"The name of a Roman god,","C":"A type of rock,","D":"The word for mountain"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the word comes from Vulcan, the Roman god of fire.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire. ... It is from the Roman Vulcan that we get the word volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q003","read_aloud":"What is the difference between aa and pahoehoe lava? Options: A. Aa is smooth and pahoehoe is rough, B. Aa is rough and sharp, while pahoehoe is smooth, C. They are the exact same thing, D. Aa is made of water","excerpt":"\"Thick, slow-moving lava called aa (AH-ah) hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks. Thin, hot, quick-moving lava called pahoeboe (pah-HO-ee-ho-ee) forms a smooth, billowy surface.\"","stem":"What is the difference between aa and pahoehoe lava? Options:","choices":{"A":"Aa is smooth and pahoehoe is rough,","B":"Aa is rough and sharp, while pahoehoe is smooth,","C":"They are the exact same thing,","D":"Aa is made of water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes aa as rough and sharp, while pahoehoe is described as smooth and billowy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Thick, slow-moving lava called aa (AH-ah) hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks. Thin, hot, quick-moving lava called pahoeboe (pah-HO-ee-ho-ee) forms a smooth, billowy surface.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q004","read_aloud":"How are magma and the mountain related? Options: A. Magma creates the mountain by piling up on the surface, B. The mountain is made of water and air, C. Magma cools and disappears underground, D. The mountain is built by the wind","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. ... A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"How are magma and the mountain related? Options:","choices":{"A":"Magma creates the mountain by piling up on the surface,","B":"The mountain is made of water and air,","C":"Magma cools and disappears underground,","D":"The mountain is built by the wind"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The magma erupts from the earth, cools, and piles up to create the shape of the volcano mountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. ... A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q005","read_aloud":"How did the eruption change the lives of people living nearby? Options: A. It made them richer, B. It destroyed homes and left people homeless, C. It gave them a new way to travel, D. It helped them grow more plants","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. ... Hundreds of houses and cabins were destroyed, leaving many people homeless.\"","stem":"How did the eruption change the lives of people living nearby? Options:","choices":{"A":"It made them richer,","B":"It destroyed homes and left people homeless,","C":"It gave them a new way to travel,","D":"It helped them grow more plants"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes the loss of life, homes, and roads, showing how it negatively impacted the people in that area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. ... Hundreds of houses and cabins were destroyed, leaving many people homeless.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q006","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"threatened\"? A. protected B. endangered C. decorated D. ignored","excerpt":"\"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"threatened\"?","choices":{"A":"protected","B":"endangered","C":"decorated","D":"ignored"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Threatened\" means put in a risky position or endangered. The houses were in danger from the lava. \"Endangered\" is the closest synonym.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q007","read_aloud":"Why might a dome volcano explode? A. because it is too cold B. because gases build up pressure behind the plug like a cork in a bottle C. because it is underwater D. because it has no lava","excerpt":"\"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava.\"","stem":"Why might a dome volcano explode?","choices":{"A":"because it is too cold","B":"because gases build up pressure behind the plug like a cork in a bottle","C":"because it is underwater","D":"because it has no lava"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text compares the plug to a cork in a bottle of soda. When gases cannot escape, pressure builds up. Eventually the volcano explodes, just like soda shooting out when you shake a bottle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare early times to modern times? A. to show that people have always been curious about volcanoes B. to prove that ancient people were smarter C. to make the text shorter D. to describe Roman gods","excerpt":"\"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes. They still don\u0027t know all the answers.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare early times to modern times?","choices":{"A":"to show that people have always been curious about volcanoes","B":"to prove that ancient people were smarter","C":"to make the text shorter","D":"to describe Roman gods"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author shows that people in early times had stories but no scientific knowledge. Modern scientists study volcanoes but still do not know everything. This comparison shows that understanding volcanoes has been a long process of learning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes. They still don\u0027t know all the answers.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q009","read_aloud":"If a volcano has not erupted in 100,000 years and scientists believe it will never erupt again, what type is it? A. active B. dormant C. extinct D. composite","excerpt":"\"Around the world there are many very old volcanoes that no longer erupt. Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct.\"","stem":"If a volcano has not erupted in 100,000 years and scientists believe it will never erupt again, what type is it?","choices":{"A":"active","B":"dormant","C":"extinct","D":"composite"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text defines extinct volcanoes as dead volcanoes that will not erupt again. A volcano that has not erupted in 100,000 years and never will again fits this definition.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world there are many very old volcanoes that no longer erupt. Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q010","read_aloud":"Why is Crater Lake called a \"caldera\"? A. because it is a small pond B. because the top of the volcano collapsed inward and filled with water C. because it is made of sand D. because it is the highest mountain in Oregon","excerpt":"\"Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again. Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash.\"","stem":"Why is Crater Lake called a \"caldera\"?","choices":{"A":"because it is a small pond","B":"because the top of the volcano collapsed inward and filled with water","C":"because it is made of sand","D":"because it is the highest mountain in Oregon"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the entire top of the volcano collapsed inward. A huge crater formed and was later filled with water. This type of crater is called a caldera. The water made it into a lake.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again. Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q011","read_aloud":"How does the word \"shield\" help readers understand this type of volcano? A. it compares the volcano\u0027s shape to a warrior\u0027s shield B. it suggests the volcano protects nearby towns C. it means the volcano is made of metal D. it indicates the volcano is very old","excerpt":"Earth scientists have divided volcanoes into four groups. Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes shaped like an ancient warrior\u0027s shield.","stem":"How does the word \"shield\" help readers understand this type of volcano?","choices":{"A":"it compares the volcano\u0027s shape to a warrior\u0027s shield","B":"it suggests the volcano protects nearby towns","C":"it means the volcano is made of metal","D":"it indicates the volcano is very old"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Shield describes the broad, gentle slope shape of these volcanoes, comparing them to ancient warriors\u0027 shields.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Earth scientists have divided volcanoes into four groups. Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes shaped like an ancient warrior\u0027s shield."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What is a key feature of cinder cone volcanoes? A. they erupt explosively with ash and cinders B. they have very gentle, broad slopes C. they only erupt underwater D. they never produce lava flows","excerpt":"Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand poured through an opening. They erupt explosively, blowing out burning red-hot ash and cinders.","stem":"What is a key feature of cinder cone volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"they erupt explosively with ash and cinders","B":"they have very gentle, broad slopes","C":"they only erupt underwater","D":"they never produce lava flows"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes cinder cone volcanoes as erupting explosively and blowing out ash and cinders.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand poured through an opening. They erupt explosively, blowing out burning red-hot ash and cinders."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q013","read_aloud":"How are stratovolcanoes different from other types? A. they are built from layers of lava, cinders, and ash B. they only erupt once and then become extinct C. they form only in the middle of tectonic plates D. they produce only gas, never solid material","excerpt":"Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions.","stem":"How are stratovolcanoes different from other types?","choices":{"A":"they are built from layers of lava, cinders, and ash","B":"they only erupt once and then become extinct","C":"they form only in the middle of tectonic plates","D":"they produce only gas, never solid material"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that stratovolcanoes form from layers of different materials from multiple eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q014","read_aloud":"If a volcano erupted near your community, what might you expect to happen over time based on this passage? A. life would return to the area after some time B. the area would stay empty forever C. only animals could return, not plants D. the soil would never support life again","excerpt":"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.","stem":"If a volcano erupted near your community, what might you expect to happen over time based on this passage?","choices":{"A":"life would return to the area after some time","B":"the area would stay empty forever","C":"only animals could return, not plants","D":"the soil would never support life again"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the idea that ecosystems can recover after volcanic eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q015","read_aloud":"How does the structure of a dome volcano affect its eruption style? A. thick lava can plug the vent, building pressure for explosive eruptions B. thin lava always flows gently without explosions C. dome volcanoes never erupt more than once D. the shape prevents any lava from escaping","excerpt":"A dome volcano has thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava.","stem":"How does the structure of a dome volcano affect its eruption style?","choices":{"A":"thick lava can plug the vent, building pressure for explosive eruptions","B":"thin lava always flows gently without explosions","C":"dome volcanoes never erupt more than once","D":"the shape prevents any lava from escaping"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that thick lava can plug the vent like a cork, building pressure that leads to explosive eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A dome volcano has thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Which word from the vocabulary list relates to where volcanoes occur? A. gushes B. threatened C. face D. magma","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates. Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\"","stem":"Which word from the vocabulary list relates to where volcanoes occur?","choices":{"A":"gushes","B":"threatened","C":"face","D":"magma"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Magma rises at plate boundaries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates. Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q017","read_aloud":"What is Seymour Simon\u0027s purpose in writing Volcanoes? A. To persuade readers to live near volcanoes B. To inform readers about how volcanoes work and their effects C. To tell a story about a fictional volcano D. To teach readers how to build a volcano model","excerpt":"The text includes facts, photographs, and descriptions of eruptions, volcano types, and locations.","stem":"What is Seymour Simon\u0027s purpose in writing Volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"To persuade readers to live near volcanoes","B":"To inform readers about how volcanoes work and their effects","C":"To tell a story about a fictional volcano","D":"To teach readers how to build a volcano model"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text is informational, giving facts about volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes facts, photographs, and descriptions of eruptions, volcano types, and locations."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q018","read_aloud":"How is this text organized? A. In time order from oldest to newest volcano B. By comparing volcanoes to mountains C. From general concepts to specific examples and types D. As a story with a beginning, middle, and end","excerpt":"The text moves from explaining what magma is, to how volcanoes form, to specific eruptions (Mount St. Helens, Heimaey, Hawaii), to types of volcanoes.","stem":"How is this text organized?","choices":{"A":"In time order from oldest to newest volcano","B":"By comparing volcanoes to mountains","C":"From general concepts to specific examples and types","D":"As a story with a beginning, middle, and end"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text starts with basics, then gives examples, then types.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text moves from explaining what magma is, to how volcanoes form, to specific eruptions (Mount St. Helens, Heimaey, Hawaii), to types of volcanoes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q019","read_aloud":"What does \"still growing\" mean in this context? A. People are adding rocks to it. B. Eruptions continue to add new lava to the mountain. C. It is getting taller because of earthquakes. D. Plants are growing on it.","excerpt":"\"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor. It is still growing and is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes.\"","stem":"What does \"still growing\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"People are adding rocks to it.","B":"Eruptions continue to add new lava to the mountain.","C":"It is getting taller because of earthquakes.","D":"Plants are growing on it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Active eruptions add new layers of lava.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor. It is still growing and is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as reclaim? A. Lose B. Regain C. Forget D. Break","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as reclaim?","choices":{"A":"Lose","B":"Regain","C":"Forget","D":"Break"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Reclaim means to take back or regain something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which statement is true about Mauna Loa? A. It is a small volcano. B. It is no longer growing. C. It is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes. D. It is located in Washington state.","excerpt":"\"Mauna Loa is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor. It is still growing and is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes.\"","stem":"Which statement is true about Mauna Loa?","choices":{"A":"It is a small volcano.","B":"It is no longer growing.","C":"It is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes.","D":"It is located in Washington state."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states Mauna Loa is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mauna Loa is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor. It is still growing and is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q022","read_aloud":"How tall is Mauna Loa from the ocean floor? A. Seven miles B. One thousand feet C. Thirty thousand feet D. One hundred miles","excerpt":"\"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.\"","stem":"How tall is Mauna Loa from the ocean floor?","choices":{"A":"Seven miles","B":"One thousand feet","C":"Thirty thousand feet","D":"One hundred miles"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says it rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. It is seventy miles long and rises thirty thousand feet from the ocean floor.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How is aa lava different from pahoehoe lava? A. Aa is smooth; pahoehoe is rough. B. Aa is thick and rough; pahoehoe is thin and smooth. C. Aa is fast; pahoehoe is slow. D. Aa is cold; pahoehoe is hot.","excerpt":"\"The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption. The two main kinds in Hawaii have Hawaiian names. Thick, slow-moving lava called aa (AH-ah) hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks.\"","stem":"How is aa lava different from pahoehoe lava?","choices":{"A":"Aa is smooth; pahoehoe is rough.","B":"Aa is thick and rough; pahoehoe is thin and smooth.","C":"Aa is fast; pahoehoe is slow.","D":"Aa is cold; pahoehoe is hot."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes aa as thick and rough, while pahoehoe is thin, hot, and smooth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption. The two main kinds in Hawaii have Hawaiian names. Thick, slow-moving lava called aa (AH-ah) hardens into a rough tangle of sharp rocks.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l06-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the sentence, what is \u0027molten\u0027 rock? Options: A. Cold and hard rock, B. Melted, hot liquid rock, C. Rock that is made of gas, D. Rock that is blue","excerpt":"\"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock.\"","stem":"Based on the sentence, what is \u0027molten\u0027 rock? Options:","choices":{"A":"Cold and hard rock,","B":"Melted, hot liquid rock,","C":"Rock that is made of gas,","D":"Rock that is blue"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Molten means the rock is heated until it becomes a liquid, which is how it behaves beneath the crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q002","read_aloud":"How are some islands formed in the ocean? Options: A. By underwater volcanoes growing high enough to reach the surface, B. By people building them, C. By big ships parking there, D. By the sea level dropping","excerpt":"\"Some of the underwater volcanoes have grown so high that they rise from the ocean floor to above sea level as islands.\"","stem":"How are some islands formed in the ocean? Options:","choices":{"A":"By underwater volcanoes growing high enough to reach the surface,","B":"By people building them,","C":"By big ships parking there,","D":"By the sea level dropping"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Volcanoes on the sea floor erupt and build up until they break the surface of the water as islands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some of the underwater volcanoes have grown so high that they rise from the ocean floor to above sea level as islands.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What happened to the shape of Mount St. Helens after it erupted? Options: A. It grew much taller, B. It turned into a flat plain, C. Its top and side slid away, D. It became a lake","excerpt":"\"Comparing the way Mount St. Helens looked before and after the eruption. The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\"","stem":"What happened to the shape of Mount St. Helens after it erupted? Options:","choices":{"A":"It grew much taller,","B":"It turned into a flat plain,","C":"Its top and side slid away,","D":"It became a lake"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The eruption was so violent that it physically removed a large portion of the volcano\u0027s structure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Comparing the way Mount St. Helens looked before and after the eruption. The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q004","read_aloud":"Why do scientists study the volcanic rocks? Options: A. To see if they are pretty, B. Because they give clues about how the volcano erupted, C. To build stronger houses, D. To sell them as jewelry","excerpt":"\"When lava cools and hardens, it forms volcanic rocks. The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption.\"","stem":"Why do scientists study the volcanic rocks? Options:","choices":{"A":"To see if they are pretty,","B":"Because they give clues about how the volcano erupted,","C":"To build stronger houses,","D":"To sell them as jewelry"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The rocks act like a record of the eruption, helping scientists understand the volcano\u0027s history.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When lava cools and hardens, it forms volcanic rocks. The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q005","read_aloud":"Why is the comparison to a \"cork in a bottle\" useful for understanding a dome volcano? Options: A. It shows that the lava is actually a liquid drink, B. It shows how a plug traps pressure inside, just like a bottle of soda, C. It shows that volcanoes are small, D. It shows that the volcano is not dangerous","excerpt":"\"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. ... The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water.\"","stem":"Why is the comparison to a \"cork in a bottle\" useful for understanding a dome volcano? Options:","choices":{"A":"It shows that the lava is actually a liquid drink,","B":"It shows how a plug traps pressure inside, just like a bottle of soda,","C":"It shows that volcanoes are small,","D":"It shows that the volcano is not dangerous"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Just as a cork keeps the gas in a soda bottle until it bursts out, the hardened lava plug keeps the pressure inside until the volcano explodes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. ... The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q006","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"gushes\" the same way as the excerpt? A. Water gushes from the fire hydrant, spraying everywhere. B. The turtle gushes slowly across the road. C. She gushes her homework before dinner. D. The book gushes with interesting pictures.","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"gushes\" the same way as the excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Water gushes from the fire hydrant, spraying everywhere.","B":"The turtle gushes slowly across the road.","C":"She gushes her homework before dinner.","D":"The book gushes with interesting pictures."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"In the excerpt, \"gushes\" means flows out quickly and forcefully. Water spraying from a fire hydrant also flows out quickly. The other choices do not use \"gushes\" correctly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q007","read_aloud":"Why are stratovolcanoes also called \"composite\" volcanoes? A. because they are made of many different materials and layers from many eruptions B. because they are very simple C. because they only erupt once D. because they are made of water","excerpt":"\"Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions. An eruption can be initially explosive, when ash and cinders fall to the ground. Later the eruption becomes less violent and lava slowly flows out.\"","stem":"Why are stratovolcanoes also called \"composite\" volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"because they are made of many different materials and layers from many eruptions","B":"because they are very simple","C":"because they only erupt once","D":"because they are made of water"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says stratovolcanoes are formed by lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions. Each eruption adds new layers. \"Composite\" means made of many different parts. These volcanoes are composed of many layers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions. An eruption can be initially explosive, when ash and cinders fall to the ground. Later the eruption becomes less violent and lava slowly flows out.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare forests to matchsticks? A. to show that trees are used to make matches B. to help readers imagine how easily the powerful eruption knocked down huge trees C. to describe how to start a fire D. to prove that matchsticks are dangerous","excerpt":"\"The force of the eruption was so great that entire forests were blown down like rows of matchsticks.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare forests to matchsticks?","choices":{"A":"to show that trees are used to make matches","B":"to help readers imagine how easily the powerful eruption knocked down huge trees","C":"to describe how to start a fire","D":"to prove that matchsticks are dangerous"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Matchsticks are small and light. They fall over very easily. By comparing forests to matchsticks, the author helps readers imagine how the enormous force of the eruption knocked down huge trees as if they were tiny and weightless.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The force of the eruption was so great that entire forests were blown down like rows of matchsticks.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q009","read_aloud":"What does \"extinct\" most likely mean for a volcano? A. no longer active and will not erupt again B. very young and just beginning to form C. erupting more frequently than before D. moving to a different location on Earth","excerpt":"Around the world there are many very old volcanoes that no longer erupt. Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct.","stem":"What does \"extinct\" most likely mean for a volcano?","choices":{"A":"no longer active and will not erupt again","B":"very young and just beginning to form","C":"erupting more frequently than before","D":"moving to a different location on Earth"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Extinct means no longer active. The text says extinct volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Around the world there are many very old volcanoes that no longer erupt. Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q010","read_aloud":"What is the difference between extinct and dormant volcanoes? A. dormant volcanoes can erupt again; extinct ones cannot B. extinct volcanoes erupt more often than dormant ones C. dormant volcanoes are always underwater D. extinct volcanoes are found only on islands","excerpt":"Others can be inactive for as long as 50,000 years and then reawaken. These are called dormant.","stem":"What is the difference between extinct and dormant volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"dormant volcanoes can erupt again; extinct ones cannot","B":"extinct volcanoes erupt more often than dormant ones","C":"dormant volcanoes are always underwater","D":"extinct volcanoes are found only on islands"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that dormant volcanoes can reawaken after long periods, while extinct ones will not erupt again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Others can be inactive for as long as 50,000 years and then reawaken. These are called dormant."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Crater Lake Volcano? A. it has not erupted recently but could in the future B. it has never erupted in Earth\u0027s history C. it erupts every year without fail D. it is the smallest volcano in Oregon","excerpt":"Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again.","stem":"What can you infer about Crater Lake Volcano?","choices":{"A":"it has not erupted recently but could in the future","B":"it has never erupted in Earth\u0027s history","C":"it erupts every year without fail","D":"it is the smallest volcano in Oregon"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Since Crater Lake is described as dormant, readers can infer it is inactive now but could erupt again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q012","read_aloud":"If you were planning to rebuild after a volcanic eruption, what positive outcomes might you consider? A. new soil can support new plant growth and ecosystems B. volcanic ash makes all land permanently unusable C. eruptions only cause harm with no benefits D. only animals can return, not plants or people","excerpt":"Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks. Insects and other animals return. Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.","stem":"If you were planning to rebuild after a volcanic eruption, what positive outcomes might you consider?","choices":{"A":"new soil can support new plant growth and ecosystems","B":"volcanic ash makes all land permanently unusable","C":"eruptions only cause harm with no benefits","D":"only animals can return, not plants or people"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the idea that volcanic eruptions can create new, fertile soil for life to return.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks. Insects and other animals return. Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q013","read_aloud":"How does this concluding statement change how readers might view volcanoes? A. it shows volcanoes have both destructive and creative powers B. it suggests volcanoes are only dangerous and harmful C. it means volcanoes should be avoided at all costs D. it indicates volcanoes only affect remote areas","excerpt":"Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.","stem":"How does this concluding statement change how readers might view volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"it shows volcanoes have both destructive and creative powers","B":"it suggests volcanoes are only dangerous and harmful","C":"it means volcanoes should be avoided at all costs","D":"it indicates volcanoes only affect remote areas"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text balances the destructive power of volcanoes with their role in creating new land and fertile soil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q014","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for reclaim? A. abandon B. take back C. destroy D. forget","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735foot volcano.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for reclaim?","choices":{"A":"abandon","B":"take back","C":"destroy","D":"forget"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Reclaim means to take back something that was lost.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735foot volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the danger of Hawaiian lava flows compared to thicker lava? A. It is less dangerous because it is slow. B. It can be very dangerous because it moves very fast. C. It is never dangerous. D. It only moves underground.","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava is fluid and flows quickly. In some lava rivers, speeds as high as thirtyfive miles per hour have been measured.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the danger of Hawaiian lava flows compared to thicker lava?","choices":{"A":"It is less dangerous because it is slow.","B":"It can be very dangerous because it moves very fast.","C":"It is never dangerous.","D":"It only moves underground."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Fastmoving lava can reach houses quickly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava is fluid and flows quickly. In some lava rivers, speeds as high as thirtyfive miles per hour have been measured.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q016","read_aloud":"How are shield volcanoes different from cinder cone volcanoes in shape? A. Shield volcanoes are steep; cinder cones are flat. B. Shield volcanoes have broad, gentle slopes; cinder cones look like piles of sand. C. Both have the same shape. D. Shield volcanoes are underwater.","excerpt":"Shield volcanoes (broad, gentle slopes) vs. cinder cone volcanoes (steep piles of ash and cinders).","stem":"How are shield volcanoes different from cinder cone volcanoes in shape?","choices":{"A":"Shield volcanoes are steep; cinder cones are flat.","B":"Shield volcanoes have broad, gentle slopes; cinder cones look like piles of sand.","C":"Both have the same shape.","D":"Shield volcanoes are underwater."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes each shape clearly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Shield volcanoes (broad, gentle slopes) vs. cinder cone volcanoes (steep piles of ash and cinders)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q017","read_aloud":"How does the ocean change old lava flows in Hawaii? A. It washes them away completely. B. It breaks them into rocks and black sand. C. It makes them grow larger. D. It turns them into soil.","excerpt":"\"Old lava flows are quickly weathered by the waves into rocks and black sand.\"","stem":"How does the ocean change old lava flows in Hawaii?","choices":{"A":"It washes them away completely.","B":"It breaks them into rocks and black sand.","C":"It makes them grow larger.","D":"It turns them into soil."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Waves weather lava into rocks and sand.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Old lava flows are quickly weathered by the waves into rocks and black sand.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q018","read_aloud":"Do you think people should build towns near a dormant volcano? Why? A. Yes, because it might not erupt for thousands of years. B. No, because even dormant volcanoes can erupt again. C. Yes, because the soil is good for farming. D. Both; there are advantages and risks.","excerpt":"\"Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again. Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash.\"","stem":"Do you think people should build towns near a dormant volcano? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it might not erupt for thousands of years.","B":"No, because even dormant volcanoes can erupt again.","C":"Yes, because the soil is good for farming.","D":"Both; there are advantages and risks."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text shows both benefits (soil) and risks (eruption).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again. Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q019","read_aloud":"What does threatened mean? A. Safe and sound B. Endangered or at risk C. Hidden underground D. Already destroyed","excerpt":"\"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava.\"","stem":"What does threatened mean?","choices":{"A":"Safe and sound","B":"Endangered or at risk","C":"Hidden underground","D":"Already destroyed"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Threatened means something is in danger or at risk of being harmed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Why are shield volcanoes named this way? A. They look like a warrior\u0027s shield. B. They protect people from fire. C. They are made of metal. D. They have sharp edges.","excerpt":"\"Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes shaped like an ancient warrior\u0027s shield.\"","stem":"Why are shield volcanoes named this way?","choices":{"A":"They look like a warrior\u0027s shield.","B":"They protect people from fire.","C":"They are made of metal.","D":"They have sharp edges."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says they have slopes shaped like an ancient warrior\u0027s shield.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Shield volcanoes, such as Mauna Loa and Kilauea, have broad, gentle slopes shaped like an ancient warrior\u0027s shield.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q021","read_aloud":"How are cinder cone volcanoes formed? A. By slow rivers of lava B. By explosive eruptions of ash and cinders C. By underwater earthquakes D. By plates pulling apart","excerpt":"\"Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand poured through an opening. They erupt explosively, blowing out burning red-hot ash and cinders.\"","stem":"How are cinder cone volcanoes formed?","choices":{"A":"By slow rivers of lava","B":"By explosive eruptions of ash and cinders","C":"By underwater earthquakes","D":"By plates pulling apart"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that ash and cinders build up to form the cone after explosive eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand poured through an opening. They erupt explosively, blowing out burning red-hot ash and cinders.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How is a composite (strato) volcano built? A. In one single eruption B. By layers of ash, cinders, and lava from many eruptions C. Only by flowing water D. By wind blowing sand","excerpt":"\"Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions. An eruption can be initially explosive... Later the eruption becomes less violent and lava slowly flows out...\"","stem":"How is a composite (strato) volcano built?","choices":{"A":"In one single eruption","B":"By layers of ash, cinders, and lava from many eruptions","C":"Only by flowing water","D":"By wind blowing sand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes layers of ash, cinders, and lava piling up over time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions. An eruption can be initially explosive... Later the eruption becomes less violent and lava slowly flows out...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q023","read_aloud":"Why are Mount Shasta and Mount Hood considered active? A. They are erupting right now. B. They have erupted recently. C. They have not erupted in 10,000 years. D. They are still active because they have not erupted for many years but could.","excerpt":"\"Mount Shasta in California and Mount Hood in Oregon are stratovolcanoes. They are still active even though they have not erupted for many years.\"","stem":"Why are Mount Shasta and Mount Hood considered active?","choices":{"A":"They are erupting right now.","B":"They have erupted recently.","C":"They have not erupted in 10,000 years.","D":"They are still active because they have not erupted for many years but could."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says they are still active despite not erupting for many years, implying they could erupt again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mount Shasta in California and Mount Hood in Oregon are stratovolcanoes. They are still active even though they have not erupted for many years.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l07-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What is the difference between \u0027extinct\u0027 and \u0027dormant\u0027? Options: A. Extinct is dead, dormant can wake up, B. Dormant is dead, extinct can wake up, C. They are the same thing, D. Neither can ever erupt again","excerpt":"\"Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct. Others can be inactive for as long as 50,000 years and then reawaken. These are called dormant.\"","stem":"What is the difference between \u0027extinct\u0027 and \u0027dormant\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"Extinct is dead, dormant can wake up,","B":"Dormant is dead, extinct can wake up,","C":"They are the same thing,","D":"Neither can ever erupt again"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Extinct means it will not erupt again, whereas dormant means it is currently inactive but could erupt in the future.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct. Others can be inactive for as long as 50,000 years and then reawaken. These are called dormant.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q002","read_aloud":"Why does magma push up in the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean? Options: A. Because the plates are moving apart, B. Because the water is pushing it, C. Because it is cold, D. Because the sea level is rising","excerpt":"\"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet. Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them.\"","stem":"Why does magma push up in the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because the plates are moving apart,","B":"Because the water is pushing it,","C":"Because it is cold,","D":"Because the sea level is rising"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"When plates move apart, the gap allows magma from below to push up, forming volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet. Down the middle of the North Atlantic Ocean, two plates are slowly moving apart. Hot magma pushes up between them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q003","read_aloud":"How did the Hawaiians explain the volcanoes in their legends? Options: A. They said it was just hot rock, B. They told stories of a goddess of fire named Pele, C. They said the Earth was breaking, D. They did not have an explanation","excerpt":"\"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. ... Pele moved constantly from one Hawaiian island to another. Finally, Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea.\"","stem":"How did the Hawaiians explain the volcanoes in their legends? Options:","choices":{"A":"They said it was just hot rock,","B":"They told stories of a goddess of fire named Pele,","C":"They said the Earth was breaking,","D":"They did not have an explanation"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The legends described the volcano activity as the actions of their goddess of fire, Pele.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. ... Pele moved constantly from one Hawaiian island to another. Finally, Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you agree with the author that volcanoes bring good things? Why? Options: A. No, because they only destroy, B. Yes, because they create new land and soil for life to return, C. No, because they are too loud, D. Yes, because they make the air warmer","excerpt":"\"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. ... But in a few short months, life renews itself. Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\"","stem":"Do you agree with the author that volcanoes bring good things? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, because they only destroy,","B":"Yes, because they create new land and soil for life to return,","C":"No, because they are too loud,","D":"Yes, because they make the air warmer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author argues that while destruction is the immediate result, the long-term impact includes creating new land and opportunities for life, which is a balanced judgment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. ... But in a few short months, life renews itself. Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what tools would be most helpful to study a volcano in the ocean? Options: A. A shovel and a bucket, B. Specialized ships and drills like the ones mentioned for deep ocean drilling, C. Only a pair of binoculars, D. A map of the city","excerpt":"\"If you were a scientist, how would you study a volcano that is in the middle of the ocean?\"","stem":"Based on the text, what tools would be most helpful to study a volcano in the ocean? Options:","choices":{"A":"A shovel and a bucket,","B":"Specialized ships and drills like the ones mentioned for deep ocean drilling,","C":"Only a pair of binoculars,","D":"A map of the city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Given the difficulty of reaching underwater sites, specialized technology like the ships used for deep ocean research is essential for gathering data.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you were a scientist, how would you study a volcano that is in the middle of the ocean?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q006","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"reclaim\"? A. abandon B. return C. recover D. restore","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot mountain of lava.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"reclaim\"?","choices":{"A":"abandon","B":"return","C":"recover","D":"restore"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Reclaim\" means to take back or return to something. The opposite would be to abandon, which means to leave something behind and not return. The people of Heimaey did the opposite of abandoning their island.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot mountain of lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author write in a \"direct, conversational approach\"? A. because he does not know science well B. to make science interesting and easy to understand for young readers C. because he only writes for adults D. to make the text more confusing","excerpt":"\"Seymour Simon wants to develop \u0027enthusiasm for exploring the world\u0027 in his readers. He attributes his direct, conversational approach to science topics to his twenty-three years as a science teacher.\"","stem":"Why does the author write in a \"direct, conversational approach\"?","choices":{"A":"because he does not know science well","B":"to make science interesting and easy to understand for young readers","C":"because he only writes for adults","D":"to make the text more confusing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Seymour Simon was a science teacher for 23 years. He wants to develop enthusiasm for exploring the world. A conversational approach makes science feel friendly and accessible, not boring or hard. This helps young readers stay interested.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Seymour Simon wants to develop \u0027enthusiasm for exploring the world\u0027 in his readers. He attributes his direct, conversational approach to science topics to his twenty-three years as a science teacher.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the legend of Pele at the beginning? A. to tell a fictional story instead of facts B. to show how people long ago tried to explain volcanoes before science could C. to prove that goddesses are real D. to make the text shorter","excerpt":"\"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire... Finally, Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea, on the big island of Hawaii. Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years. Kilauea is still an active volcano.\"","stem":"Why does the author include the legend of Pele at the beginning?","choices":{"A":"to tell a fictional story instead of facts","B":"to show how people long ago tried to explain volcanoes before science could","C":"to prove that goddesses are real","D":"to make the text shorter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes legends to show what people believed before scientists studied volcanoes. It helps readers understand how human understanding of volcanoes has changed over time. Legends were early attempts to explain natural events.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire... Finally, Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea, on the big island of Hawaii. Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years. Kilauea is still an active volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think it was important to protect Surtsey from visitors? Why or why not? A. No, because people should build hotels there immediately. B. Yes, because a brand-new island could teach scientists how life begins on new land. C. No, because the island is not interesting. D. Yes, because the island is too dangerous for scientists.","excerpt":"\"In 1963, an area of the sea near Iceland began to boil and churn. An undersea volcano was exploding and a new island was being formed. The island was named Surtsey.\"","stem":"Do you think it was important to protect Surtsey from visitors? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because people should build hotels there immediately.","B":"Yes, because a brand-new island could teach scientists how life begins on new land.","C":"No, because the island is not interesting.","D":"Yes, because the island is too dangerous for scientists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A brand-new island like Surtsey is rare and valuable for science. Scientists can study how plants and animals first arrive and grow on new land. Protecting it from visitors keeps it natural so scientists can learn from it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1963, an area of the sea near Iceland began to boil and churn. An undersea volcano was exploding and a new island was being formed. The island was named Surtsey.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q010","read_aloud":"If a dormant volcano reawakens after 50,000 years, what problems might scientists face in warning people? A. There would be no problems at all. B. People might not believe the volcano is dangerous because it has been quiet for so long. C. The volcano would be too small to see. D. Scientists would know exactly when it would erupt.","excerpt":"\"Others can be inactive for as long as 50,000 years and then reawaken. These are called dormant.\"","stem":"If a dormant volcano reawakens after 50,000 years, what problems might scientists face in warning people?","choices":{"A":"There would be no problems at all.","B":"People might not believe the volcano is dangerous because it has been quiet for so long.","C":"The volcano would be too small to see.","D":"Scientists would know exactly when it would erupt."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If a volcano has been quiet for 50,000 years, people living near it might think it is completely safe. They might not take warnings seriously. Scientists would have to work hard to convince people that the long-dormant volcano is now dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Others can be inactive for as long as 50,000 years and then reawaken. These are called dormant.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q011","read_aloud":"How does the word \"mystery\" affect how readers understand scientific study of volcanoes? A. it shows there is still much to learn about Earth\u0027s interior B. it suggests scientists have already solved all volcano questions C. it means volcanoes are too dangerous to study D. it indicates volcanoes are not important to study","excerpt":"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.","stem":"How does the word \"mystery\" affect how readers understand scientific study of volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"it shows there is still much to learn about Earth\u0027s interior","B":"it suggests scientists have already solved all volcano questions","C":"it means volcanoes are too dangerous to study","D":"it indicates volcanoes are not important to study"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mystery suggests there are still unanswered questions, showing that scientific exploration of volcanoes continues.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q012","read_aloud":"What challenge do scientists face in studying Earth\u0027s mantle? A. drilling through thick, hard oceanic crust requires special equipment B. the mantle is too hot for any equipment to survive C. volcanoes erupt too frequently to allow drilling D. the ocean water prevents all drilling attempts","excerpt":"Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust.","stem":"What challenge do scientists face in studying Earth\u0027s mantle?","choices":{"A":"drilling through thick, hard oceanic crust requires special equipment","B":"the mantle is too hot for any equipment to survive","C":"volcanoes erupt too frequently to allow drilling","D":"the ocean water prevents all drilling attempts"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that special drills are needed to handle the stress of drilling through hard oceanic crust.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Geologists plan to drill through a section of the Pacific Ocean floor estimated to be less than 4 miles thick. Special drills are being designed to handle the stress of boring through the hard oceanic crust."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q013","read_aloud":"How do satellites help scientists study Earth? A. they can monitor Earth\u0027s systems from space, even through clouds B. they can stop volcanoes from erupting C. they only work during daytime hours D. they replace the need for ground-based research","excerpt":"The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.","stem":"How do satellites help scientists study Earth?","choices":{"A":"they can monitor Earth\u0027s systems from space, even through clouds","B":"they can stop volcanoes from erupting","C":"they only work during daytime hours","D":"they replace the need for ground-based research"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes how satellites like Aqua use technology to monitor Earth\u0027s systems from space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Do you think investing in satellite technology to study volcanoes is worthwhile? Why or why not? A. yes, because early warning can save lives and reduce damage B. no, because volcanoes cannot be predicted accurately C. yes, but only for volcanoes near large cities D. no, because the technology is too expensive for any benefit","excerpt":"Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause.","stem":"Do you think investing in satellite technology to study volcanoes is worthwhile? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because early warning can save lives and reduce damage","B":"no, because volcanoes cannot be predicted accurately","C":"yes, but only for volcanoes near large cities","D":"no, because the technology is too expensive for any benefit"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text supports that technology helps scientists react quickly to disasters, reducing their impact.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Now scientists can spot problems and react quickly to natural disasters. This helps reduce the devastation the events could cause."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q015","read_aloud":"If you could design a new satellite to study volcanoes, what feature might you include? A. sensors that detect heat changes before eruptions occur B. cameras that only take black-and-white photos C. a system that stops volcanoes from erupting D. equipment that only works during nighttime","excerpt":"Human-made satellites also help us study Earth. The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle.","stem":"If you could design a new satellite to study volcanoes, what feature might you include?","choices":{"A":"sensors that detect heat changes before eruptions occur","B":"cameras that only take black-and-white photos","C":"a system that stops volcanoes from erupting","D":"equipment that only works during nighttime"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to create a new idea based on how current technology monitors Earth systems.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Human-made satellites also help us study Earth. The Aqua satellite was launched in 2002. Aqua uses microwave technology to see through clouds and monitor Earth\u0027s water cycle."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the simile \"like rows of matchsticks\"? A. To show the forests were planted in neat rows. B. To show how easily and completely the trees were knocked down. C. To show the forests were made of matchsticks. D. To show the trees were not damaged.","excerpt":"\"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite. … entire forests were blown down like rows of matchsticks.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the simile \"like rows of matchsticks\"?","choices":{"A":"To show the forests were planted in neat rows.","B":"To show how easily and completely the trees were knocked down.","C":"To show the forests were made of matchsticks.","D":"To show the trees were not damaged."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Matchsticks break easily; the simile emphasizes total destruction.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite. … entire forests were blown down like rows of matchsticks.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q017","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about volcanoes based on these examples? A. Volcanoes only destroy. B. Volcanoes both create and destroy land. C. Volcanoes never create land. D. Volcanoes only happen underwater.","excerpt":"Volcanoes can create new islands (Surtsey), destroy towns (Heimaey), and add new land to existing islands (Hawaii).","stem":"What can you conclude about volcanoes based on these examples?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes only destroy.","B":"Volcanoes both create and destroy land.","C":"Volcanoes never create land.","D":"Volcanoes only happen underwater."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Examples show creation (Surtsey) and destruction (Heimaey) and addition (Hawaii).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Volcanoes can create new islands (Surtsey), destroy towns (Heimaey), and add new land to existing islands (Hawaii)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Do you agree with the author that good things can come from volcanoes? Why? A. No, because they only kill and destroy. B. Yes, because they create new land, islands, and fertile soil. C. No, because the bad outweighs the good. D. Yes, but only underwater volcanoes.","excerpt":"\"Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\"","stem":"Do you agree with the author that good things can come from volcanoes? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because they only kill and destroy.","B":"Yes, because they create new land, islands, and fertile soil.","C":"No, because the bad outweighs the good.","D":"Yes, but only underwater volcanoes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists positive effects.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Write one question that a visitor might ask a park ranger at Mount St. Helens. A. \"When will the next eruption happen?\" B. \"What is the name of the nearest restaurant?\" C. \"How fast does a horse run?\" D. \"What color is the sky?\"","excerpt":"\"Visitor centers allow people to view the actively growing lava dome that now partially fills the crater.\"","stem":"Write one question that a visitor might ask a park ranger at Mount St. Helens.","choices":{"A":"\"When will the next eruption happen?\"","B":"\"What is the name of the nearest restaurant?\"","C":"\"How fast does a horse run?\"","D":"\"What color is the sky?\""},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Visitors would likely ask about future eruptions or science.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Visitor centers allow people to view the actively growing lava dome that now partially fills the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for gushes? A. Pours B. Trickles C. Rushes D. Flows","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high...\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for gushes?","choices":{"A":"Pours","B":"Trickles","C":"Rushes","D":"Flows"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To gush is to flow fast. To trickle is to flow slowly, making them opposites.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What happens when a dome volcano gets plugged? A. It stops erupting forever. B. Gases cannot escape, and pressure builds up. C. It becomes a shield volcano. D. Lava flows out faster.","excerpt":"\"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava.\"","stem":"What happens when a dome volcano gets plugged?","choices":{"A":"It stops erupting forever.","B":"Gases cannot escape, and pressure builds up.","C":"It becomes a shield volcano.","D":"Lava flows out faster."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text compares the plug to a cork in soda water, preventing gas from escaping and building pressure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q022","read_aloud":"What does it mean if a volcano is dormant? A. It is dead and will never erupt. B. It is sleeping but could erupt again. C. It is erupting right now. D. It is under the ocean.","excerpt":"\"Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again.\"","stem":"What does it mean if a volcano is dormant?","choices":{"A":"It is dead and will never erupt.","B":"It is sleeping but could erupt again.","C":"It is erupting right now.","D":"It is under the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that dormant means \"inactive\" but \"likely to erupt again.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Crater Lake Volcano in Oregon is currently considered dormant, but it is likely to erupt again.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q023","read_aloud":"Why is Lassen Peak a good example of a dome volcano? A. It is the tallest mountain. B. It has a smooth surface. C. It shows evidence of thick lava and violent eruption. D. It is located in Hawaii.","excerpt":"\"Lassen Peak in California is a dome volcano that erupted violently in 1915. You can see the huge chunks of volcanic dome rock near the summit.\"","stem":"Why is Lassen Peak a good example of a dome volcano?","choices":{"A":"It is the tallest mountain.","B":"It has a smooth surface.","C":"It shows evidence of thick lava and violent eruption.","D":"It is located in Hawaii."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes the thick, slow-moving lava and the violent explosion, which are traits of dome volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Lassen Peak in California is a dome volcano that erupted violently in 1915. You can see the huge chunks of volcanic dome rock near the summit.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the author help you understand the extent of the ash? A. By saying it covered the ground for thousands of miles. B. By showing a picture of the ash. C. By comparing it to snow. D. By measuring the weight.","excerpt":"\"Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash.\"","stem":"How does the author help you understand the extent of the ash?","choices":{"A":"By saying it covered the ground for thousands of miles.","B":"By showing a picture of the ash.","C":"By comparing it to snow.","D":"By measuring the weight."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author uses specific details like \"thousands of miles\" to explain how far the ash went.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l08-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for \u0027spouted\u0027 as used in this sentence? Options: A. Swallowed, B. Threw out, C. Kept inside, D. Turned into ice","excerpt":"\"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. ... Spouted; threw out.\"","stem":"What is a synonym for \u0027spouted\u0027 as used in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Swallowed,","B":"Threw out,","C":"Kept inside,","D":"Turned into ice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To spout means to throw something out with force, which is how volcanoes release molten rock.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. ... Spouted; threw out.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q002","read_aloud":"Why did the Hawaiians create the legends of Pele? Options: A. To explain why the volcano erupted, B. Because they were bored, C. To describe the ocean, D. Because they wanted to build a mountain","excerpt":"\"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. ... Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea, on the big island of Hawaii.\"","stem":"Why did the Hawaiians create the legends of Pele? Options:","choices":{"A":"To explain why the volcano erupted,","B":"Because they were bored,","C":"To describe the ocean,","D":"Because they wanted to build a mountain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ancient peoples used legends to make sense of natural events like volcanic eruptions that they did not scientifically understand yet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. ... Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea, on the big island of Hawaii.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q003","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about where volcanoes form? Options: A. They are random, B. They form along the edges where plates meet, C. They only form in the North Pole, D. They do not form on Earth","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. ... Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\"","stem":"What can you conclude about where volcanoes form? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are random,","B":"They form along the edges where plates meet,","C":"They only form in the North Pole,","D":"They do not form on Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The connection between the cracks in the crust (plates) and the location of volcanoes shows that they are not random, but occur at plate boundaries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. ... Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Why might it be important for people to learn more about volcanoes? Options: A. Just to have something to talk about, B. To help predict eruptions and stay safe from destruction, C. To make more volcanoes, D. To learn how to build wooden houses","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives. ... Hundreds of houses and cabins were destroyed.\"","stem":"Why might it be important for people to learn more about volcanoes? Options:","choices":{"A":"Just to have something to talk about,","B":"To help predict eruptions and stay safe from destruction,","C":"To make more volcanoes,","D":"To learn how to build wooden houses"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding how volcanoes work and monitoring them can save lives by helping people know when to evacuate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives. ... Hundreds of houses and cabins were destroyed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q005","read_aloud":"If you were an engineer planning a town near a volcano, what would you do to keep people safe? Options: A. Build houses right next to the vent, B. Make sure there are clear evacuation routes and warning systems, C. Ignore the volcano, D. Build houses only out of glass","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. ... The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\"","stem":"If you were an engineer planning a town near a volcano, what would you do to keep people safe? Options:","choices":{"A":"Build houses right next to the vent,","B":"Make sure there are clear evacuation routes and warning systems,","C":"Ignore the volcano,","D":"Build houses only out of glass"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A responsible plan must prioritize safety through warnings and paths for people to escape if the volcano shows signs of activity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust. ... The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q006","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"threatened\" correctly? A. The endangered animals were threatened by habitat loss. B. She threatened the book with a smile. C. The flower threatened to bloom beautifully. D. He threatened his dinner by eating it.","excerpt":"\"A number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava. Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"threatened\" correctly?","choices":{"A":"The endangered animals were threatened by habitat loss.","B":"She threatened the book with a smile.","C":"The flower threatened to bloom beautifully.","D":"He threatened his dinner by eating it."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Threatened\" means put in danger or at risk. Endangered animals facing habitat loss are in danger. The other choices use \"threatened\" in ways that do not match its meaning of being in a risky position.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava. Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author include so many numbers and details? A. to make the text boring B. to show readers the enormous scale of the destruction C. to prove that math is important D. to describe the weather","excerpt":"\"Measurable ash fell over a huge area of more than 75,000 square miles. Hundreds of houses and cabins were destroyed, leaving many people homeless.\"","stem":"Why does the author include so many numbers and details?","choices":{"A":"to make the text boring","B":"to show readers the enormous scale of the destruction","C":"to prove that math is important","D":"to describe the weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Numbers like 75,000 square miles and hundreds of houses help readers understand how widespread and serious the destruction was. Specific details make the event feel real and help readers grasp the magnitude of the disaster.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Measurable ash fell over a huge area of more than 75,000 square miles. Hundreds of houses and cabins were destroyed, leaving many people homeless.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q008","read_aloud":"How does this ending change the reader\u0027s view of volcanoes? A. It makes readers think volcanoes are only bad. B. It helps readers see that volcanoes have both harmful and helpful effects. C. It proves that volcanoes should all be stopped. D. It shows that volcanoes are not real.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\"","stem":"How does this ending change the reader\u0027s view of volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"It makes readers think volcanoes are only bad.","B":"It helps readers see that volcanoes have both harmful and helpful effects.","C":"It proves that volcanoes should all be stopped.","D":"It shows that volcanoes are not real."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Earlier in the text, the author describes destruction and danger. The ending reminds readers that volcanoes also create new land and soil. This balanced view helps readers understand that volcanoes are not just destructive-they also build and renew.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Was spraying water on lava a good idea? Use evidence from the text. A. No, because water cannot stop lava. B. Yes, because the text says it was done to slow the lava and save houses. C. No, because firefighters should not help during eruptions. D. Yes, because lava is made of water.","excerpt":"\"Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\"","stem":"Was spraying water on lava a good idea? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because water cannot stop lava.","B":"Yes, because the text says it was done to slow the lava and save houses.","C":"No, because firefighters should not help during eruptions.","D":"Yes, because lava is made of water."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says firefighters sprayed water to slow down the lava\u0027s advance. This suggests the action had a purpose: to protect houses and people. While water cannot stop lava completely, slowing it down can save property and lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Firefighters sprayed water on the lava to slow down its advance.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q010","read_aloud":"How does the word \"diagram\" help readers understand the water cycle? A. it provides a visual representation of a complex process B. it replaces the need for written explanations C. it shows only the final result, not the process D. it is only useful for scientists, not students","excerpt":"The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram.","stem":"How does the word \"diagram\" help readers understand the water cycle?","choices":{"A":"it provides a visual representation of a complex process","B":"it replaces the need for written explanations","C":"it shows only the final result, not the process","D":"it is only useful for scientists, not students"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Diagram means a visual drawing that helps explain complex information, making the water cycle easier to understand.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The movement of water is shown in blue arrows in this diagram."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about Earth\u0027s water? A. water constantly moves through a cycle powered by the sun B. water only exists in liquid form on Earth\u0027s surface C. water disappears after it evaporates into the air D. water cycles only happen near volcanoes","excerpt":"Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas.","stem":"What is the main idea about Earth\u0027s water?","choices":{"A":"water constantly moves through a cycle powered by the sun","B":"water only exists in liquid form on Earth\u0027s surface","C":"water disappears after it evaporates into the air","D":"water cycles only happen near volcanoes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The passage explains the continuous movement of water through evaporation, condensation, and precipitation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Water on Earth circulates constantly through the water, or hydrologic, cycle. Liquid water on the planet\u0027s surface is heated by the sun and turns into a gas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q012","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use to explain Earth\u0027s atmosphere? A. description that explains layers and their functions B. chronological order of atmospheric changes C. cause and effect of atmospheric pollution D. problem and solution for atmospheric issues","excerpt":"Earth\u0027s atmosphere wraps the planet like a blanket of insulation. Its two lowest layers are the troposphere and the stratosphere.","stem":"What text structure does the author use to explain Earth\u0027s atmosphere?","choices":{"A":"description that explains layers and their functions","B":"chronological order of atmospheric changes","C":"cause and effect of atmospheric pollution","D":"problem and solution for atmospheric issues"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author uses descriptive text structure to explain the layers of the atmosphere and what each layer does.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Earth\u0027s atmosphere wraps the planet like a blanket of insulation. Its two lowest layers are the troposphere and the stratosphere."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think it is important to explore more of the ocean floor? Why or why not? A. yes, because we may discover important resources or knowledge B. no, because the ocean floor is not important to humans C. yes, but only if it is very inexpensive to explore D. no, because we already know everything about oceans","excerpt":"Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored.","stem":"Do you think it is important to explore more of the ocean floor? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because we may discover important resources or knowledge","B":"no, because the ocean floor is not important to humans","C":"yes, but only if it is very inexpensive to explore","D":"no, because we already know everything about oceans"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text suggests there is much to learn about Earth\u0027s oceans, supporting the value of further exploration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Oceans are one of Earth\u0027s most abundant resources. But only 5 percent of the ocean floor has been explored."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Imagine you are a scientist studying volcanoes. What new question about Earth would you want to investigate? A. How do volcanic eruptions affect climate patterns worldwide? B. What color is the lava from every volcano? C. How many volcanoes erupted last Tuesday? D. Which volcano has the prettiest name?","excerpt":"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?","stem":"Imagine you are a scientist studying volcanoes. What new question about Earth would you want to investigate?","choices":{"A":"How do volcanic eruptions affect climate patterns worldwide?","B":"What color is the lava from every volcano?","C":"How many volcanoes erupted last Tuesday?","D":"Which volcano has the prettiest name?"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This question encourages students to think creatively about meaningful scientific questions related to volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q015","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of gushes? A. flows quickly B. trickles slowly C. explodes D. sprays","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in redhot fountains a few hundred feet high.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym of gushes?","choices":{"A":"flows quickly","B":"trickles slowly","C":"explodes","D":"sprays"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gushes means flows quickly; the opposite is slow, small flow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in redhot fountains a few hundred feet high.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q016","read_aloud":"What message is the author trying to send about volcanoes? A. Volcanoes are only dangerous. B. Volcanoes have both destructive and constructive effects. C. We should avoid all volcanoes. D. Volcanoes are not interesting.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\"","stem":"What message is the author trying to send about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes are only dangerous.","B":"Volcanoes have both destructive and constructive effects.","C":"We should avoid all volcanoes.","D":"Volcanoes are not interesting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author balances destruction with creation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about scientific knowledge of volcanoes? A. Scientists know everything about volcanoes. B. Knowledge has increased, but mysteries remain. C. No progress has been made. D. Only ancient people understood volcanoes.","excerpt":"\"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted redhot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes. They still don\u0027t know all the answers, but they know much about how a volcano works.\"","stem":"What can you infer about scientific knowledge of volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"Scientists know everything about volcanoes.","B":"Knowledge has increased, but mysteries remain.","C":"No progress has been made.","D":"Only ancient people understood volcanoes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists know much but not all.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted redhot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes. They still don\u0027t know all the answers, but they know much about how a volcano works.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q018","read_aloud":"Is the \"cork in a soda bottle\" a good comparison for a plugged volcano? Why? A. Yes, because both trap pressure until it releases suddenly. B. No, because soda bottles are not hot. C. Yes, because both are made of glass. D. No, because volcanoes are larger.","excerpt":"\"The volcano may be plugged with hardened lava. The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water. As the pressure builds up, the volcano eventually explodes.\"","stem":"Is the \"cork in a soda bottle\" a good comparison for a plugged volcano? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because both trap pressure until it releases suddenly.","B":"No, because soda bottles are not hot.","C":"Yes, because both are made of glass.","D":"No, because volcanoes are larger."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The comparison helps explain pressure buildup and explosion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The volcano may be plugged with hardened lava. The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water. As the pressure builds up, the volcano eventually explodes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Write a short headline for a newspaper reporting on this ancient eruption. A. \"Volcano Sleeps Peacefully\" B. \"Mountain Explodes, Leaves Giant Crater Behind\" C. \"New Restaurant Opens in Town\" D. \"Rain Expected Tomorrow\"","excerpt":"\"Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash. Toward the end of the eruption, the entire top of the volcano collapsed inward.\"","stem":"Write a short headline for a newspaper reporting on this ancient eruption.","choices":{"A":"\"Volcano Sleeps Peacefully\"","B":"\"Mountain Explodes, Leaves Giant Crater Behind\"","C":"\"New Restaurant Opens in Town\"","D":"\"Rain Expected Tomorrow\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The eruption caused a massive collapse.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost seven thousand years ago, its predecessor, Mount Mazama, erupted and covered the ground for thousands of miles around in a blanket of pumice and ash. Toward the end of the eruption, the entire top of the volcano collapsed inward.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q020","read_aloud":"How was Crater Lake formed? A. A dam was built by people. B. A meteor hit the ground. C. A volcano collapsed and filled with rain and water. D. A glacier melted.","excerpt":"\"Toward the end of the eruption, the entire top of the volcano collapsed inward. A huge crater, called a caldera, formed and was later filled with water.\"","stem":"How was Crater Lake formed?","choices":{"A":"A dam was built by people.","B":"A meteor hit the ground.","C":"A volcano collapsed and filled with rain and water.","D":"A glacier melted."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains the top collapsed (calder a) and later filled with water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Toward the end of the eruption, the entire top of the volcano collapsed inward. A huge crater, called a caldera, formed and was later filled with water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q021","read_aloud":"What makes Crater Lake special in North America? A. It is the widest lake. B. It is the saltiest lake. C. It is the deepest lake. D. It is the oldest lake.","excerpt":"\"Crater Lake reaches a depth of two thousand feet, the deepest lake in North America.\"","stem":"What makes Crater Lake special in North America?","choices":{"A":"It is the widest lake.","B":"It is the saltiest lake.","C":"It is the deepest lake.","D":"It is the oldest lake."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states it is the deepest lake in North America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Crater Lake reaches a depth of two thousand feet, the deepest lake in North America.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main difference between an extinct and a dormant volcano? A. Extinct volcanoes are sleeping; dormant ones are dead. B. Dormant volcanoes are sleeping; extinct ones are dead. C. Both types are actively erupting. D. Both types are found only in Hawaii.","excerpt":"\"Around the world there are many very old volcanoes that no longer erupt. Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct.\"","stem":"What is the main difference between an extinct and a dormant volcano?","choices":{"A":"Extinct volcanoes are sleeping; dormant ones are dead.","B":"Dormant volcanoes are sleeping; extinct ones are dead.","C":"Both types are actively erupting.","D":"Both types are found only in Hawaii."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text distinguishes that dormant means \"asleep\" while extinct means \"dead\" or will not erupt again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world there are many very old volcanoes that no longer erupt. Some of these volcanoes are dead and will not erupt again. These are called extinct.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q023","read_aloud":"Does life return after a volcano destroys an area? A. No, the land stays empty forever. B. Yes, plants and animals return slowly. C. Yes, but only fish return. D. No, people never come back.","excerpt":"\"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.\"","stem":"Does life return after a volcano destroys an area?","choices":{"A":"No, the land stays empty forever.","B":"Yes, plants and animals return slowly.","C":"Yes, but only fish return.","D":"No, people never come back."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says life \"renews itself\" with plants and insects returning in a few months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l09-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is a \u0027crater\u0027? Options: A. A large hole at the top of a volcano, B. A flat field, C. A type of rock, D. A small hill","excerpt":"\"In 1982, the mountain and the area around it were dedicated as the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument. Visitor centers allow people to view the actively growing lava dome that now partially fills the crater.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is a \u0027crater\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"A large hole at the top of a volcano,","B":"A flat field,","C":"A type of rock,","D":"A small hill"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that the lava dome fills the crater, which is the opening or hole at the volcano\u0027s summit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1982, the mountain and the area around it were dedicated as the Mount St. Helens National Volcanic Monument. Visitor centers allow people to view the actively growing lava dome that now partially fills the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q002","read_aloud":"How has our understanding of volcanoes changed over time? Options: A. It hasn\u0027t changed at all, B. We went from using stories to using science to explain them, C. We used to know everything, now we know nothing, D. People stopped caring about volcanoes","excerpt":"\"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. ... In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes.\"","stem":"How has our understanding of volcanoes changed over time? Options:","choices":{"A":"It hasn\u0027t changed at all,","B":"We went from using stories to using science to explain them,","C":"We used to know everything, now we know nothing,","D":"People stopped caring about volcanoes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text highlights a shift from early myths to modern scientific investigation and understanding.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. ... In early times, no one knew how volcanoes formed or why they spouted red-hot molten rock. In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Why are stratovolcanoes made of many different layers? Options: A. Because they have had many different eruptions over time, B. Because they are made of water, C. Because people built them that way, D. Because they are in the ocean","excerpt":"\"Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions.\"","stem":"Why are stratovolcanoes made of many different layers? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they have had many different eruptions over time,","B":"Because they are made of water,","C":"Because people built them that way,","D":"Because they are in the ocean"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Each eruption adds a new layer of ash, cinders, or lava, slowly building the composite shape.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the volcanoes in the world are composite or stratovolcanoes. Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash from many eruptions.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the phrase \"Volcanoes do not just destroy\" to start this section? Options: A. To make the reader feel sad, B. To challenge the idea that volcanoes are only bad by showing their positive effects, C. To say that volcanoes are actually not dangerous at all, D. To describe the sound of the explosion","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the phrase \"Volcanoes do not just destroy\" to start this section? Options:","choices":{"A":"To make the reader feel sad,","B":"To challenge the idea that volcanoes are only bad by showing their positive effects,","C":"To say that volcanoes are actually not dangerous at all,","D":"To describe the sound of the explosion"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This sentence introduces the positive aspects of volcanic activity, countering the common view that they are purely destructive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q005","read_aloud":"Do you think it is safer to live near a dome volcano or a shield volcano? Why? Options: A. Shield volcano, because their eruptions are generally less violent and have gentler slopes, B. Dome volcano, because they never explode, C. It does not matter, D. Neither, because both are safe","excerpt":"\"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava... The plug prevents the gases from escaping... Lassen Peak in California is a dome volcano that erupted violently in 1915.\"","stem":"Do you think it is safer to live near a dome volcano or a shield volcano? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"Shield volcano, because their eruptions are generally less violent and have gentler slopes,","B":"Dome volcano, because they never explode,","C":"It does not matter,","D":"Neither, because both are safe"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Shield volcanoes have gentler, predictable lava flows, whereas dome volcanoes are associated with violent, explosive pressure buildup, making shield volcanoes generally less dangerous for residents.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava... The plug prevents the gases from escaping... Lassen Peak in California is a dome volcano that erupted violently in 1915.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q006","read_aloud":"Which word could replace \"reclaim\" without changing the meaning much? A. abandon B. retake C. destroy D. forget","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot mountain of lava.\"","stem":"Which word could replace \"reclaim\" without changing the meaning much?","choices":{"A":"abandon","B":"retake","C":"destroy","D":"forget"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Reclaim\" means to take back something that was yours. \"Retake\" has a very similar meaning. The people of Heimaey came back to take back their island after the eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot mountain of lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q007","read_aloud":"What is the most important message the author wants readers to remember about volcanoes? A. Volcanoes are only destructive and should be feared. B. Volcanoes are powerful forces that both destroy and create, and nature can renew itself. C. Volcanoes are not dangerous at all. D. People should never live near volcanoes.","excerpt":"\"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.\"","stem":"What is the most important message the author wants readers to remember about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes are only destructive and should be feared.","B":"Volcanoes are powerful forces that both destroy and create, and nature can renew itself.","C":"Volcanoes are not dangerous at all.","D":"People should never live near volcanoes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author shows both sides of volcanoes: destruction and renewal. The message is that volcanoes are powerful natural forces with both harmful and helpful effects. Nature has the ability to recover and grow again after destruction.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Why might the author include the origin of the word \"volcano\"? A. to teach readers about Roman mythology B. to show the connection between human culture and natural events C. to prove that Roman gods are real D. to make the text longer without purpose","excerpt":"\"It is from the Roman god Vulcan that we get the word volcano.\"","stem":"Why might the author include the origin of the word \"volcano\"?","choices":{"A":"to teach readers about Roman mythology","B":"to show the connection between human culture and natural events","C":"to prove that Roman gods are real","D":"to make the text longer without purpose"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The word \"volcano\" comes from a Roman god of fire. This shows that humans have long connected fire and heat with volcanic activity. It helps readers see that volcanoes have been part of human culture and language for thousands of years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is from the Roman god Vulcan that we get the word volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q009","read_aloud":"Should scientists drill into Earth\u0027s mantle even if it is expensive and difficult? Why or why not? A. No, because learning about Earth is not important. B. Yes, because understanding the mantle could help predict eruptions and save lives. C. No, because drilling is too easy. D. Yes, because drilling is fun.","excerpt":"\"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\"","stem":"Should scientists drill into Earth\u0027s mantle even if it is expensive and difficult? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because learning about Earth is not important.","B":"Yes, because understanding the mantle could help predict eruptions and save lives.","C":"No, because drilling is too easy.","D":"Yes, because drilling is fun."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The mantle affects volcanoes, earthquakes, and Earth\u0027s structure. Understanding it better could help scientists predict natural disasters and protect people. The text shows that this knowledge is still missing, so the effort has real value.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The exact nature of Earth\u0027s mantle is still unknown. To solve this mystery, scientists are hoping to drill directly into the mantle and take samples.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q010","read_aloud":"How does understanding \"navigate\" deepen our view of how technology helps us study Earth? A. it shows technology helps us find locations and study Earth systematically B. it suggests navigation is only important for sailors C. it means technology replaces all traditional knowledge D. it indicates GPS only works near volcanoes","excerpt":"Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars.","stem":"How does understanding \"navigate\" deepen our view of how technology helps us study Earth?","choices":{"A":"it shows technology helps us find locations and study Earth systematically","B":"it suggests navigation is only important for sailors","C":"it means technology replaces all traditional knowledge","D":"it indicates GPS only works near volcanoes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Navigate means to find one\u0027s way. Understanding this shows how GPS technology helps scientists systematically study Earth\u0027s features.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Global Positioning System (GPS) satellites allow us to navigate the planet without having to study the stars."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q011","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the entire selection, supported by this opening? A. human understanding of volcanoes has evolved from myth to science B. volcanoes have always been understood through scientific methods C. ancient stories about volcanoes are more accurate than modern science D. volcanoes are only important in mythology, not in science","excerpt":"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire... In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes.","stem":"What is the main idea of the entire selection, supported by this opening?","choices":{"A":"human understanding of volcanoes has evolved from myth to science","B":"volcanoes have always been understood through scientific methods","C":"ancient stories about volcanoes are more accurate than modern science","D":"volcanoes are only important in mythology, not in science"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The opening contrasts ancient myths with modern science, and the full text shows how scientific understanding of volcanoes has developed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire... In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q012","read_aloud":"How does the repetition of \"life renews itself\" and details about returning plants and animals help readers understand the story\u0027s message? A. it emphasizes nature\u0027s ability to recover and adapt after disasters B. it suggests that volcanic eruptions are always harmful with no recovery C. it shows that only animals, not plants, can return after eruptions D. it argues that humans should prevent all volcanic eruptions","excerpt":"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself. Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks. Insects and other animals return.","stem":"How does the repetition of \"life renews itself\" and details about returning plants and animals help readers understand the story\u0027s message?","choices":{"A":"it emphasizes nature\u0027s ability to recover and adapt after disasters","B":"it suggests that volcanic eruptions are always harmful with no recovery","C":"it shows that only animals, not plants, can return after eruptions","D":"it argues that humans should prevent all volcanic eruptions"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Repeating ideas about life returning emphasizes the resilience of nature and the cyclical nature of destruction and renewal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself. Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks. Insects and other animals return."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think the author fairly presents both the dangers and benefits of volcanoes? Why or why not? A. yes, it shows both destructive power and creative potential of volcanoes B. no, it only focuses on the dangers without mentioning benefits C. yes, but only for scientists who study volcanoes D. no, because volcanoes are always harmful to humans","excerpt":"Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.","stem":"Do you think the author fairly presents both the dangers and benefits of volcanoes? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, it shows both destructive power and creative potential of volcanoes","B":"no, it only focuses on the dangers without mentioning benefits","C":"yes, but only for scientists who study volcanoes","D":"no, because volcanoes are always harmful to humans"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes both destructive eruptions and how volcanoes create new land and fertile soil, presenting a balanced view.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q014","read_aloud":"If Seymour Simon could send one message to young scientists today, what might it be based on his text? A. \"Stay curious, ask questions, and keep exploring our amazing planet.\" B. \"Only study volcanoes that are near your home.\" C. \"Believe only what ancient myths say about Earth.\" D. \"Wait for others to make discoveries before you try.\"","excerpt":"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?","stem":"If Seymour Simon could send one message to young scientists today, what might it be based on his text?","choices":{"A":"\"Stay curious, ask questions, and keep exploring our amazing planet.\"","B":"\"Only study volcanoes that are near your home.\"","C":"\"Believe only what ancient myths say about Earth.\"","D":"\"Wait for others to make discoveries before you try.\""},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Simon\u0027s text shows how scientific understanding grows through curiosity and exploration, making this message authentic to his work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q015","read_aloud":"Which vocabulary word best describes what Mauna Loa does regularly? A. reclaim B. gushes C. threatened D. face","excerpt":"\"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. … It is still growing and is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes. … Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens.\"","stem":"Which vocabulary word best describes what Mauna Loa does regularly?","choices":{"A":"reclaim","B":"gushes","C":"threatened","D":"face"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gushes means flows quickly; Mauna Loa erupts frequently.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa. … It is still growing and is one of Hawaii\u0027s most active volcanoes. … Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q016","read_aloud":"Why are photographs especially helpful in a book about volcanoes? A. They show the scale and power of eruptions that words alone cannot fully capture. B. They replace the need to read. C. They are only for decoration. D. They make the book heavier.","excerpt":"The text includes photographs of Mount St. Helens before and after, a photo of an eruption, and a photo of a lava flow entering the sea.","stem":"Why are photographs especially helpful in a book about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"They show the scale and power of eruptions that words alone cannot fully capture.","B":"They replace the need to read.","C":"They are only for decoration.","D":"They make the book heavier."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Photos show the dramatic effects of eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes photographs of Mount St. Helens before and after, a photo of an eruption, and a photo of a lava flow entering the sea."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q017","read_aloud":"What overall pattern does the author show about volcanoes? A. Volcanoes only create new land. B. Volcanoes are forces of both destruction and creation. C. Volcanoes have no effect on land. D. Volcanoes only destroy.","excerpt":"The text describes how volcanoes create new land (Hawaii, Surtsey) and also destroy property (Mount St. Helens, Heimaey).","stem":"What overall pattern does the author show about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes only create new land.","B":"Volcanoes are forces of both destruction and creation.","C":"Volcanoes have no effect on land.","D":"Volcanoes only destroy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author includes both creation and destruction.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text describes how volcanoes create new land (Hawaii, Surtsey) and also destroy property (Mount St. Helens, Heimaey)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q018","read_aloud":"Why do you think the author ends the text with this hopeful message about life renewing? A. To end on a positive note and show that nature recovers. B. To scare readers away from volcanoes. C. To make the text longer. D. To argue that volcanoes are not dangerous.","excerpt":"\"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. … But in a few short months, life renews itself.\"","stem":"Why do you think the author ends the text with this hopeful message about life renewing?","choices":{"A":"To end on a positive note and show that nature recovers.","B":"To scare readers away from volcanoes.","C":"To make the text longer.","D":"To argue that volcanoes are not dangerous."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The ending balances destruction with hope.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. … But in a few short months, life renews itself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q019","read_aloud":"Write a short new myth that explains why a volcano erupts. A. \"The volcano erupts when the mountain giants have a sneezing fit.\" B. \"The volcano erupts because the weather is bad.\" C. \"The volcano erupts when people play loud music.\" D. \"The volcano erupts because it is Tuesday.\"","excerpt":"\"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. … Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea.\"","stem":"Write a short new myth that explains why a volcano erupts.","choices":{"A":"\"The volcano erupts when the mountain giants have a sneezing fit.\"","B":"\"The volcano erupts because the weather is bad.\"","C":"\"The volcano erupts when people play loud music.\"","D":"\"The volcano erupts because it is Tuesday.\""},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Myths often personify natural events.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire. … Pele settled in a mountain called Kilauea.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q020","read_aloud":"Which sentence correctly uses the word magma? A. The magma flowed down the street outside my house. B. The magma is liquid rock deep inside the Earth. C. The magma turned into cold air. D. The magma is a type of cloud.","excerpt":"\"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\"","stem":"Which sentence correctly uses the word magma?","choices":{"A":"The magma flowed down the street outside my house.","B":"The magma is liquid rock deep inside the Earth.","C":"The magma turned into cold air.","D":"The magma is a type of cloud."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Magma is specifically liquid rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q021","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the final paragraph? A. Volcanoes are only dangerous. B. Volcanoes create new land and help life return. C. People should not live near volcanoes. D. Volcanoes are always exploding.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of the final paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes are only dangerous.","B":"Volcanoes create new land and help life return.","C":"People should not live near volcanoes.","D":"Volcanoes are always exploding."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author concludes by listing good things volcanoes bring, like new soil and islands.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q022","read_aloud":"Why did the early Hawaiians tell stories about Pele? A. To explain why volcanoes erupted B. To teach children how to swim C. To map the islands D. To describe the weather","excerpt":"\"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire... Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years.\"","stem":"Why did the early Hawaiians tell stories about Pele?","choices":{"A":"To explain why volcanoes erupted","B":"To teach children how to swim","C":"To map the islands","D":"To describe the weather"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"People used legends to explain natural events they didn\u0027t understand scientifically, like eruptions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The early Hawaiians told legends of the wanderings of Pele, their goddess of fire... Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q023","read_aloud":"If you were writing a headline for this text, which would be best? A. \"Volcanoes: Dangerous Killers\" B. \"Fire Mountains: The Story of Volcanoes\" C. \"How to Escape a Volcano\" D. \"The Legend of Vulcan\"","excerpt":"(The whole text)","stem":"If you were writing a headline for this text, which would be best?","choices":{"A":"\"Volcanoes: Dangerous Killers\"","B":"\"Fire Mountains: The Story of Volcanoes\"","C":"\"How to Escape a Volcano\"","D":"\"The Legend of Vulcan\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text covers legends, science, types of volcanoes, and their impact. \"Fire Mountains\" captures the broad topic best.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: (The whole text)"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q024","read_aloud":"Do you think volcanoes are helpful or harmful? A. They are only harmful because they destroy everything. B. They are only helpful because they make islands. C. They can be both harmful because they destroy and helpful because they create new land. D. They are neither helpful nor harmful.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\"","stem":"Do you think volcanoes are helpful or harmful?","choices":{"A":"They are only harmful because they destroy everything.","B":"They are only helpful because they make islands.","C":"They can be both harmful because they destroy and helpful because they create new land.","D":"They are neither helpful nor harmful."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes the destruction of St. Helens but also the creation of Surtsey and new soil, supporting the idea that they are both.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-l10-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q001","read_aloud":"What is magma? A. solid rock on the surface B. liquid rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface C. water in the ocean D. air we breathe","excerpt":"\"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\"","stem":"What is magma?","choices":{"A":"solid rock on the surface","B":"liquid rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface","C":"water in the ocean","D":"air we breathe"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines magma as melted rock that forms deep beneath the crust where it is very hot. It is liquid rock under Earth\u0027s surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q002","read_aloud":"What does \"gushes\" mean? A. drips slowly B. spouts or flows quickly C. freezes solid D. disappears underground","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\"","stem":"What does \"gushes\" mean?","choices":{"A":"drips slowly","B":"spouts or flows quickly","C":"freezes solid","D":"disappears underground"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes lava coming out in fountains. \"Gushes\" means flows out quickly and forcefully, like water from a fountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q003","read_aloud":"What does \"threatened\" mean? A. protected and safe B. endangered or put in a risky position C. decorated with paint D. ignored completely","excerpt":"\"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava.\"","stem":"What does \"threatened\" mean?","choices":{"A":"protected and safe","B":"endangered or put in a risky position","C":"decorated with paint","D":"ignored completely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The houses were in danger from quick-moving lava. \"Threatened\" means endangered or put in a risky position.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In an eruption in 1986, a number of houses were threatened by the quick-moving lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this section? A. Volcanoes can erupt anywhere on Earth. B. Most volcanoes form where tectonic plates meet. C. Earth\u0027s crust is made of eggshells. D. Plates are only found in the ocean.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates. Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this section?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes can erupt anywhere on Earth.","B":"Most volcanoes form where tectonic plates meet.","C":"Earth\u0027s crust is made of eggshells.","D":"Plates are only found in the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The section explains that Earth\u0027s crust is broken into plates and that most volcanoes erupt where two plates meet. This is the main idea about where volcanoes form.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates. Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q005","read_aloud":"What causes mountains to grow taller? A. wind and rain B. the collision and pressure of tectonic plates C. people building them D. plants growing on them","excerpt":"\"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\"","stem":"What causes mountains to grow taller?","choices":{"A":"wind and rain","B":"the collision and pressure of tectonic plates","C":"people building them","D":"plants growing on them"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that the collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. The Himalayas grow taller because of this plate pressure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The collision or constant pressure of tectonic plates can create mountain ranges. For example, the Himalayan mountains in Asia grow taller each year.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q006","read_aloud":"Why do dome volcanoes sometimes explode? A. because they are too cold B. because pressure builds up behind the plug of hardened lava C. because they are underwater D. because they have no gases","excerpt":"\"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava. The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water.\"","stem":"Why do dome volcanoes sometimes explode?","choices":{"A":"because they are too cold","B":"because pressure builds up behind the plug of hardened lava","C":"because they are underwater","D":"because they have no gases"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text compares the plug to a cork in a soda bottle. When gases cannot escape, pressure builds up. Eventually the pressure becomes too great, and the volcano explodes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava that forms a steep-sided dome shape. After an eruption, the volcano may be plugged with hardened lava. The plug prevents the gases from escaping, like a cork in a bottle of soda water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q007","read_aloud":"How many people died in the Mount St. Helens eruption? A. six people B. sixty people C. six hundred people D. no people","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives.\"","stem":"How many people died in the Mount St. Helens eruption?","choices":{"A":"six people","B":"sixty people","C":"six hundred people","D":"no people"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that sixty people lost their lives in the eruption of Mount St. Helens.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q008","read_aloud":"What happens after a volcano erupts? A. Life never returns. B. Plants and animals eventually return and life renews itself. C. The land stays bare forever. D. Only rocks can grow.","excerpt":"\"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.\"","stem":"What happens after a volcano erupts?","choices":{"A":"Life never returns.","B":"Plants and animals eventually return and life renews itself.","C":"The land stays bare forever.","D":"Only rocks can grow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says that after an eruption, everything is buried. But in a few short months, life renews itself. Plants grow in cracks, and animals return.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q009","read_aloud":"How does this ending affect the reader\u0027s understanding of volcanoes? A. It makes readers think volcanoes are only bad. B. It helps readers see that volcanoes have both harmful and helpful effects. C. It proves that volcanoes are not real. D. It shows that volcanoes should all be stopped.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\"","stem":"How does this ending affect the reader\u0027s understanding of volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"It makes readers think volcanoes are only bad.","B":"It helps readers see that volcanoes have both harmful and helpful effects.","C":"It proves that volcanoes are not real.","D":"It shows that volcanoes should all be stopped."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author balances the destruction with creation. Readers learn that volcanoes destroy but also build new land and soil. This gives readers a complete picture of volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land. Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q010","read_aloud":"Why do you think Seymour Simon chose to write about volcanoes for children? A. because volcanoes are boring B. because he wants children to feel excited about science and the natural world C. because he does not understand science D. because children do not like interesting topics","excerpt":"\"Seymour Simon wants to develop \u0027enthusiasm for exploring the world\u0027 in his readers. He attributes his direct, conversational approach to science topics to his twenty-three years as a science teacher.\"","stem":"Why do you think Seymour Simon chose to write about volcanoes for children?","choices":{"A":"because volcanoes are boring","B":"because he wants children to feel excited about science and the natural world","C":"because he does not understand science","D":"because children do not like interesting topics"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Simon wants to develop enthusiasm for exploring the world. His conversational approach makes science accessible. Writing about dramatic topics like volcanoes can spark children\u0027s curiosity and excitement about learning science. Section A - Text Information Title: VolcanoesAuthor: Seymour SimonText Type: Informational TextPreview Vocabulary Words: magma, face, reclaim, gushes, threatened","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Seymour Simon wants to develop \u0027enthusiasm for exploring the world\u0027 in his readers. He attributes his direct, conversational approach to science topics to his twenty-three years as a science teacher.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"magma\" mean in this sentence? A. melted rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface B. hard rock found on mountain tops C. water that flows through volcanoes D. gas that comes from volcanic eruptions","excerpt":"Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma.","stem":"What does \"magma\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"melted rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface","B":"hard rock found on mountain tops","C":"water that flows through volcanoes","D":"gas that comes from volcanic eruptions"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magma means melted rock beneath Earth\u0027s surface. The text says rock melts in the mantle and is called magma.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Deep beneath the crust is the mantle, where it is so hot that some rock melts. The melted, or molten, rock is called magma."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q012","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"face\" in this sentence? A. front or outer part of something B. the expression on a person\u0027s head C. the bottom layer of a mountain D. the inside of a volcanic crater","excerpt":"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"face\" in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"front or outer part of something","B":"the expression on a person\u0027s head","C":"the bottom layer of a mountain","D":"the inside of a volcanic crater"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Face means the front or outer part. The text describes the north face of the volcano sliding away during the eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"reclaim\" mean in this sentence? A. take back or return to a place B. build something new on land C. leave a place forever D. study something very carefully","excerpt":"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.","stem":"What does \"reclaim\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"take back or return to a place","B":"build something new on land","C":"leave a place forever","D":"study something very carefully"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Reclaim means take back or return to. The text says people came back to reclaim their island after the volcanic eruption.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q014","read_aloud":"What did early Romans believe about volcanoes? A. they were created by a fire god named Vulcan B. they were formed by earthquakes under the sea C. they were mountains made by giant animals D. they were holes that led to another world","excerpt":"Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire.","stem":"What did early Romans believe about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"they were created by a fire god named Vulcan","B":"they were formed by earthquakes under the sea","C":"they were mountains made by giant animals","D":"they were holes that led to another world"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire, who worked at a forge making swords and armor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Throughout history, people have told stories about volcanoes. The early Romans believed in Vulcan, their god of fire."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q015","read_aloud":"What is Earth\u0027s crust compared to in this sentence? A. a giant cracked eggshell B. a smooth glass window C. a thick blanket of snow D. a solid block of stone","excerpt":"Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell.","stem":"What is Earth\u0027s crust compared to in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a giant cracked eggshell","B":"a smooth glass window","C":"a thick blanket of snow","D":"a solid block of stone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text compares Earth\u0027s crust to a giant cracked eggshell to help readers picture the tectonic plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Volcanoes don\u0027t just happen anyplace. Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"gushes\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. flows out quickly and forcefully B. freezes into hard ice crystals C. disappears into the ground slowly D. turns into gas and rises upward","excerpt":"Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes.","stem":"What does \"gushes\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"flows out quickly and forcefully","B":"freezes into hard ice crystals","C":"disappears into the ground slowly","D":"turns into gas and rises upward"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Gushes means flows out quickly and forcefully. The text describes lava shooting out in fountains hundreds of feet high.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Hawaiian lava usually gushes out in red-hot fountains a few hundred feet high that feed lava rivers or lakes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q017","read_aloud":"What is magma called when it reaches Earth\u0027s surface? A. lava B. ash C. steam D. rock","excerpt":"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.","stem":"What is magma called when it reaches Earth\u0027s surface?","choices":{"A":"lava","B":"ash","C":"steam","D":"rock"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says when magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q018","read_aloud":"Where do most volcanoes erupt? A. where two tectonic plates meet B. in the middle of large oceans C. on top of the highest mountains D. in desert areas with little rain","excerpt":"Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.","stem":"Where do most volcanoes erupt?","choices":{"A":"where two tectonic plates meet","B":"in the middle of large oceans","C":"on top of the highest mountains","D":"in desert areas with little rain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that most volcanoes erupt where two tectonic plates meet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q019","read_aloud":"How does this detail show the relationship between destruction and renewal in nature? A. ecosystems can recover and adapt after volcanic disturbances B. volcanic eruptions permanently destroy all life in an area C. only animals can return after an eruption, not plants D. humans must always rebuild after volcanic eruptions","excerpt":"After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself.","stem":"How does this detail show the relationship between destruction and renewal in nature?","choices":{"A":"ecosystems can recover and adapt after volcanic disturbances","B":"volcanic eruptions permanently destroy all life in an area","C":"only animals can return after an eruption, not plants","D":"humans must always rebuild after volcanic eruptions"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that while eruptions cause destruction, nature has the ability to renew itself over time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After a volcano erupts, everything is buried under lava or ash. Plants and animals are nowhere to be found. But in a few short months, life renews itself."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q020","read_aloud":"Why is this a powerful way to end an informational text about volcanoes? A. it leaves readers with a balanced view of volcanoes\u0027 power to destroy and create B. it suggests volcanoes are only dangerous and should be feared C. it argues that scientists should stop studying volcanoes D. it complains that volcanoes are too unpredictable to understand","excerpt":"Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes.","stem":"Why is this a powerful way to end an informational text about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"it leaves readers with a balanced view of volcanoes\u0027 power to destroy and create","B":"it suggests volcanoes are only dangerous and should be feared","C":"it argues that scientists should stop studying volcanoes","D":"it complains that volcanoes are too unpredictable to understand"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ending with this statement emphasizes that volcanoes have both destructive and creative powers, giving readers a complete understanding of their role on Earth. Section A - Text Information Title: Volcanoes (excerpt)Author: Seymour Simon","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many good things can come from the fiery explosions of volcanoes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q021","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these sentences? A. Magma is cold. B. Volcanoes form when magma rises through cracks in the crust. C. Earth has only one layer. D. Volcanoes are not important.","excerpt":"\"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. … Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through cracks in Earth\u0027s crust.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"Magma is cold.","B":"Volcanoes form when magma rises through cracks in the crust.","C":"Earth has only one layer.","D":"Volcanoes are not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains how volcanoes form.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our planet is made up of many layers of rock. … Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through cracks in Earth\u0027s crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q022","read_aloud":"How destructive was the Mount St. Helens eruption? A. It caused no damage. B. It was the most destructive in U.S. history, with loss of life and property. C. It was a small eruption. D. It only damaged roads.","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives.\"","stem":"How destructive was the Mount St. Helens eruption?","choices":{"A":"It caused no damage.","B":"It was the most destructive in U.S. history, with loss of life and property.","C":"It was a small eruption.","D":"It only damaged roads."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it was the most destructive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States. Sixty people lost their lives.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q023","read_aloud":"What is a volcano? A. A hole in the ground B. A hill or mountain formed by erupted material piling up C. A type of earthquake D. A river of lava","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"What is a volcano?","choices":{"A":"A hole in the ground","B":"A hill or mountain formed by erupted material piling up","C":"A type of earthquake","D":"A river of lava"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives this definition.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q024","read_aloud":"How are magma and lava related? A. Magma is lava that has cooled. B. Magma is called lava when it reaches the surface. C. Lava is underground; magma is on the surface. D. They are the same thing.","excerpt":"\"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava. … A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"How are magma and lava related?","choices":{"A":"Magma is lava that has cooled.","B":"Magma is called lava when it reaches the surface.","C":"Lava is underground; magma is on the surface.","D":"They are the same thing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines magma underground and lava on the surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava. … A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q025","read_aloud":"Do you think it is worth living near a volcano for the benefits? Why? A. No, because the danger is too great. B. Yes, because the soil is good for farming and the land is beautiful. C. Both; people must weigh the risks and benefits. D. Neither; volcanoes have no benefits.","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\"","stem":"Do you think it is worth living near a volcano for the benefits? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because the danger is too great.","B":"Yes, because the soil is good for farming and the land is beautiful.","C":"Both; people must weigh the risks and benefits.","D":"Neither; volcanoes have no benefits."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text presents both destruction and creation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q026","read_aloud":"(from the previous week\u0027s text, but this theme applies.) Write one sentence predicting what scientists might learn about volcanoes in the future. A. \"Scientists will learn nothing new.\" B. \"Scientists might learn how to predict eruptions more accurately and save more lives.\" C. \"Scientists will stop studying volcanoes.\" D. \"Scientists will make volcanoes erupt on purpose.\"","excerpt":"What will we discover next?","stem":"(from the previous week\u0027s text, but this theme applies.) Write one sentence predicting what scientists might learn about volcanoes in the future.","choices":{"A":"\"Scientists will learn nothing new.\"","B":"\"Scientists might learn how to predict eruptions more accurately and save more lives.\"","C":"\"Scientists will stop studying volcanoes.\"","D":"\"Scientists will make volcanoes erupt on purpose.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Future research could improve prediction and safety. Section A - Text information Title: Volcanoes Author: Seymour Simon","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: What will we discover next?"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q027","read_aloud":"What does reclaim mean? A. To lose B. To find C. To take back D. To sell","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island...\"","stem":"What does reclaim mean?","choices":{"A":"To lose","B":"To find","C":"To take back","D":"To sell"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"To reclaim means to take back something that was yours.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q028","read_aloud":"Where do most volcanoes form? A. In the center of plates B. Where plates meet C. Under lakes D. In the sky","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates. Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\"","stem":"Where do most volcanoes form?","choices":{"A":"In the center of plates","B":"Where plates meet","C":"Under lakes","D":"In the sky"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that most volcanoes erupt where plates meet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates. Most of the world\u0027s volcanoes erupt in places where two plates meet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q029","read_aloud":"What caused the crater on Mount St. Helens? A. An earthquake broke the ground. B. The top of the mountain slid away during an eruption. C. People dug a hole. D. A flood washed the dirt away.","excerpt":"\"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away. In its place is a huge volcanic crater.\"","stem":"What caused the crater on Mount St. Helens?","choices":{"A":"An earthquake broke the ground.","B":"The top of the mountain slid away during an eruption.","C":"People dug a hole.","D":"A flood washed the dirt away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the top slid away due to the eruption force, leaving a crater.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away. In its place is a huge volcanic crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q030","read_aloud":"How are the rocks named \"aa\" and \"pahoehoe\" different? A. Aa is smooth; pahoehoe is sharp. B. Aa is sharp and rough; pahoehoe is smooth. C. Both rocks are exactly the same. D. Aa is liquid; pahoehoe is solid.","excerpt":"\"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa... The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption.\"","stem":"How are the rocks named \"aa\" and \"pahoehoe\" different?","choices":{"A":"Aa is smooth; pahoehoe is sharp.","B":"Aa is sharp and rough; pahoehoe is smooth.","C":"Both rocks are exactly the same.","D":"Aa is liquid; pahoehoe is solid."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes aa as sharp/rough and pahoehoe as smooth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The largest Hawaiian volcano is Mauna Loa... The kinds of rocks formed are clues to the kind of eruption.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q031","read_aloud":"How has our understanding of volcanoes changed since early times? A. We know less now than before. B. We still think gods cause eruptions. C. We use science to understand how they work. D. We can stop all eruptions now.","excerpt":"\"In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes. They still don\u0027t know all the answers, but they know much about how a volcano works.\"","stem":"How has our understanding of volcanoes changed since early times?","choices":{"A":"We know less now than before.","B":"We still think gods cause eruptions.","C":"We use science to understand how they work.","D":"We can stop all eruptions now."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Early people used legends (gods); now scientists study how volcanoes actually work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In modern times, scientists began to study volcanoes. They still don\u0027t know all the answers, but they know much about how a volcano works.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q032","read_aloud":"Why is it useful for scientists to group volcanoes into types? A. To give them names B. To understand how they erupt and form C. To make them look nice D. To count them easily","excerpt":"\"Shield volcanoes... have broad, gentle slopes... Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand... Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash... Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava...\"","stem":"Why is it useful for scientists to group volcanoes into types?","choices":{"A":"To give them names","B":"To understand how they erupt and form","C":"To make them look nice","D":"To count them easily"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Classifying helps scientists understand the different ways volcanoes are built and how they behave.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Shield volcanoes... have broad, gentle slopes... Cinder cone volcanoes look like piles of dry sand... Stratovolcanoes are formed by the lava, cinders, and ash... Dome volcanoes have thick, slow-moving lava...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q033","read_aloud":"Why might people in Hawaii feel safer than people near Mount St. Helens? A. Hawaiian volcanoes are usually less violent. B. Hawaii has no volcanoes. C. Mount St. Helens is dormant. D. Hawaii is not on Earth\u0027s crust.","excerpt":"\"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens. Only rarely does a Hawaiian volcano throw out rock and high clouds of ash.\"","stem":"Why might people in Hawaii feel safer than people near Mount St. Helens?","choices":{"A":"Hawaiian volcanoes are usually less violent.","B":"Hawaii has no volcanoes.","C":"Mount St. Helens is dormant.","D":"Hawaii is not on Earth\u0027s crust."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states Hawaiian eruptions are \"less violently\" and rarely throw out rock and ash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Hawaiian volcanoes erupt much less violently than did Surtsey or Mount St. Helens. Only rarely does a Hawaiian volcano throw out rock and high clouds of ash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q034","read_aloud":"What message does the author want you to remember about volcanoes? A. Volcanoes are scary and should be avoided. B. Volcanoes are only destructive. C. Volcanoes create new beginnings and land. D. Volcanoes are cold and wet.","excerpt":"\"Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks. Insects and other animals return. Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\"","stem":"What message does the author want you to remember about volcanoes?","choices":{"A":"Volcanoes are scary and should be avoided.","B":"Volcanoes are only destructive.","C":"Volcanoes create new beginnings and land.","D":"Volcanoes are cold and wet."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author ends by emphasizing renewal and the creation of new land, showing the positive side of volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plants grow in the cracks between the rocks. Insects and other animals return. Volcanoes do not just destroy. They bring new mountains, new islands, and new soil to the land.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q035","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q036","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. To break out or burst forth, B. To grow very slowly, C. To hide in a hole, D. To freeze into ice","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"To break out or burst forth,","B":"To grow very slowly,","C":"To hide in a hole,","D":"To freeze into ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To erupt means to burst forth, which is what lava and rock do during a volcanic event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a mountain or hill with a crater or vent. During a volcanic eruption, lava, gas, and bits of rock erupt through the crater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q037","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. An extinct volcano B. A dormant volcano C. An active volcano D. A cold mountain","excerpt":"\"Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years. Kilauea is still an active volcano.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"An extinct volcano","B":"A dormant volcano","C":"An active volcano","D":"A cold mountain"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly states that Kilauea is still an active volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though the islanders tried to please Pele, she burst forth every few years. Kilauea is still an active volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q038","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Water B. Magma C. Trees D. Wind","excerpt":"\"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Water","B":"Magma","C":"Trees","D":"Wind"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that magma pushing up through cracks forms volcanoes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Volcanoes are formed when magma pushes its way up through the cracks in Earth\u0027s crust.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q039","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. The front or surface of the mountain B. A person\u0027s expression C. A clock D. The bottom of the ocean","excerpt":"\"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"The front or surface of the mountain","B":"A person\u0027s expression","C":"A clock","D":"The bottom of the ocean"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Here, face refers to the outer surface or side of the volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The top of the volcano and a large segment of its north face slid away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q040","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Crust B. Magma C. Lava D. Ash","excerpt":"\"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Crust","B":"Magma","C":"Lava","D":"Ash"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that melted rock on the surface is called lava.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When magma pours forth on the surface, it is called lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q041","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. It melts. B. It becomes gas. C. It hardens into rock. D. It turns into water.","excerpt":"\"As lava cools, it hardens to form rock that is also called lava.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"It melts.","B":"It becomes gas.","C":"It hardens into rock.","D":"It turns into water."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says that cooling lava hardens to form rock.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As lava cools, it hardens to form rock that is also called lava.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q042","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. By water washing up sand B. By erupted material piling up C. By trees growing tall D. By wind blowing dirt","excerpt":"\"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"By water washing up sand","B":"By erupted material piling up","C":"By trees growing tall","D":"By wind blowing dirt"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that erupted material piles up to form the hill or mountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A volcano is a hill or mountain formed by erupted material that piles up around the vent.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q043","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Sand B. Trees C. Ice D. Lava","excerpt":"\"Mount Rainier in the state of Washington is an ice-covered volcano that last erupted in the nineteenth century.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Sand","B":"Trees","C":"Ice","D":"Lava"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes Mount Rainier as an ice-covered volcano.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mount Rainier in the state of Washington is an ice-covered volcano that last erupted in the nineteenth century.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q044","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. To leave behind B. To take back C. To sell D. To destroy","excerpt":"\"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"To leave behind","B":"To take back","C":"To sell","D":"To destroy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To reclaim means to take something back or return to claim it again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After a year\u0027s time, the people of Heimaey came back to reclaim their island with its new 735-foot volcano.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q045","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. 7:00 A.M. B. 8:32 A.M. C. 12:00 P.M. D. 5:00 P.M.","excerpt":"\"Sunday, May 18, dawned bright and clear. The mountain seemed much the same as it had been for the past month. Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"7:00 A.M.","B":"8:32 A.M.","C":"12:00 P.M.","D":"5:00 P.M."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives the specific time of the eruption as 8:32 A.M.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sunday, May 18, dawned bright and clear. The mountain seemed much the same as it had been for the past month. Suddenly, at 8:32 A.M., Mount St. Helens erupted with incredible force.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q046","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Ten million tons of dynamite B. A small firecracker C. A lightning bolt D. A nuclear bomb","excerpt":"\"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Ten million tons of dynamite","B":"A small firecracker","C":"A lightning bolt","D":"A nuclear bomb"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author uses the comparison of ten million tons of dynamite to describe the force.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The energy released in the eruption was equal to ten million tons of dynamite.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q047","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. Lava flowed down the street. B. Ash fell on the houses. C. Small earthquakes shook the mountain. D. The top of the mountain fell off.","excerpt":"\"In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"Lava flowed down the street.","B":"Ash fell on the houses.","C":"Small earthquakes shook the mountain.","D":"The top of the mountain fell off."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists small earthquakes as the first sign that the volcano was waking up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In March 1980, Mount St. Helens awakened from its long sleep. First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q048","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. It was the biggest noise ever. B. It caused the most damage and loss. C. It lasted the longest time. D. It was the first eruption ever.","excerpt":"\"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"It was the biggest noise ever.","B":"It caused the most damage and loss.","C":"It lasted the longest time.","D":"It was the first eruption ever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Destructive means causing much damage. The text lists lives lost, houses destroyed, and forests blown down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The eruption of Mount St. Helens was the most destructive in the history of the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q049","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 513. A. Back B. Hide C. Side D. Cover","excerpt":"\"The cinder cone on Pacaya volcano in Guatemala, Central America, has had frequent eruptions.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 513.","choices":{"A":"Back","B":"Hide","C":"Side","D":"Cover"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"A face of a mountain is often called a side. \"Side\" is a synonym for the surface or face of an object like a mountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The cinder cone on Pacaya volcano in Guatemala, Central America, has had frequent eruptions.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w2-volcanoes-std-q050","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 514. A. Eggshells B. Plates C. Islands D. Magma","excerpt":"\"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 514.","choices":{"A":"Eggshells","B":"Plates","C":"Islands","D":"Magma"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text compares the crust to an eggshell but names the pieces \"plates.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Earth\u0027s crust is broken into huge sections like a giant cracked eggshell. The pieces of the crust are called plates.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste","grade":4,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":5,"week":3,"title":"The Top 10 Ways You Can Reduce Waste","author":"Nick Winnick","genre":"Informational Text","essential_question":"How can people protect Earth\u0027s resources?","weekly_question":"What actions can people take to reduce waste?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["emissions","carbon footprint","recycle","reduce","pollution"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"The Top 10 Ways You Can Reduce Waste. What actions can people take to reduce waste?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027emissions\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options: A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027emissions\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q002","read_aloud":"What is a carbon footprint? Options: A. A mark made by a shoe, B. The amount of greenhouse gases humans create, C. A way to paint a picture, D. The number of trees in a forest","excerpt":"\"You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.\"","stem":"What is a carbon footprint? Options:","choices":{"A":"A mark made by a shoe,","B":"The amount of greenhouse gases humans create,","C":"A way to paint a picture,","D":"The number of trees in a forest"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines a carbon footprint as the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q003","read_aloud":"According to the text, what is one way to reduce your carbon footprint? Options: A. Riding in a car all day, B. Walking or riding a bike, C. Buying more things you do not need, D. Leaving all the lights on","excerpt":"\"There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car.\"","stem":"According to the text, what is one way to reduce your carbon footprint? Options:","choices":{"A":"Riding in a car all day,","B":"Walking or riding a bike,","C":"Buying more things you do not need,","D":"Leaving all the lights on"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text specifically suggests walking or riding a bike instead of using a car to help the planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q004","read_aloud":"What does the author suggest doing when you leave a room? Options: A. Turning off the lights, B. Leaving the door open, C. Turning on the TV, D. Buying a new lamp","excerpt":"\"You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste. Reusing plastic shopping bags to carry other items is another way to help the environment.\"","stem":"What does the author suggest doing when you leave a room? Options:","choices":{"A":"Turning off the lights,","B":"Leaving the door open,","C":"Turning on the TV,","D":"Buying a new lamp"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author tells readers to turn off lights when leaving a room to help reduce energy waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste. Reusing plastic shopping bags to carry other items is another way to help the environment.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the author want people to recycle newspaper? Options: A. To make the trash look nice, B. To save trees from being chopped down, C. To get more space in the garage, D. To build a new house","excerpt":"\"You can recycle newspaper so that fewer trees are chopped down to make new paper.\"","stem":"Why does the author want people to recycle newspaper? Options:","choices":{"A":"To make the trash look nice,","B":"To save trees from being chopped down,","C":"To get more space in the garage,","D":"To build a new house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Recycling newspaper saves trees because fewer of them need to be cut down to make new paper.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You can recycle newspaper so that fewer trees are chopped down to make new paper.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"emissions\" mean in this sentence? A. things that are eaten B. substances released or given off C. places where people live D. types of animals","excerpt":"\"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What does \"emissions\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"things that are eaten","B":"substances released or given off","C":"places where people live","D":"types of animals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines emissions as substances released or anything given off by something else. Carbon emissions are gases released into the air.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is this paragraph mostly about? A. how to plant trees B. how to help the planet by reducing waste C. how to build houses D. how to drive cars","excerpt":"\"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint.\"","stem":"What is this paragraph mostly about?","choices":{"A":"how to plant trees","B":"how to help the planet by reducing waste","C":"how to build houses","D":"how to drive cars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph asks how to make the world greener and answers that you can help by reducing your carbon footprint. This is about helping the planet by reducing waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What is one of the biggest causes of climate change? A. oxygen in the air B. carbon dioxide C. clean water D. fresh soil","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide.\"","stem":"What is one of the biggest causes of climate change?","choices":{"A":"oxygen in the air","B":"carbon dioxide","C":"clean water","D":"fresh soil"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that one of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What do people burn fossil fuels for? A. for cooking food only B. for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles C. for making toys D. for growing plants","excerpt":"\"People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.\"","stem":"What do people burn fossil fuels for?","choices":{"A":"for cooking food only","B":"for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles","C":"for making toys","D":"for growing plants"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly lists three uses: electricity, heating, and powering vehicles. These are the main reasons people burn fossil fuels.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q010","read_aloud":"What is a carbon footprint? A. a mark made by a shoe B. a measure of greenhouse gases from human activities C. a type of animal track D. a way to measure weight","excerpt":"\"A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.\"","stem":"What is a carbon footprint?","choices":{"A":"a mark made by a shoe","B":"a measure of greenhouse gases from human activities","C":"a type of animal track","D":"a way to measure weight"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines a carbon footprint as the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities. It is not a real footprint but a way to measure pollution.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does the word \"emissions\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. substances released into the air B. clean water in rivers C. trees planted in forests D. rocks found underground","excerpt":"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.","stem":"What does the word \"emissions\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"substances released into the air","B":"clean water in rivers","C":"trees planted in forests","D":"rocks found underground"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions means substances released into the air. The text says carbon emissions are damaging pollution, which matches this meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is one way to reduce your carbon footprint? A. walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car B. drive a bigger car C. use more electricity at home D. buy more plastic bags","excerpt":"There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car.","stem":"What is one way to reduce your carbon footprint?","choices":{"A":"walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car","B":"drive a bigger car","C":"use more electricity at home","D":"buy more plastic bags"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says walking or riding a bike instead of driving helps reduce your carbon footprint.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What is one easy way to help the environment? A. reducing waste B. buying more things C. using more plastic D. throwing away food","excerpt":"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it.","stem":"What is one easy way to help the environment?","choices":{"A":"reducing waste","B":"buying more things","C":"using more plastic","D":"throwing away food"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that reducing waste is one of the easiest ways to help the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q014","read_aloud":"Why should you think before buying something? A. to avoid creating too much waste B. to spend more money C. to buy bigger items D. to use more packaging","excerpt":"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, consider the waste the purchase will produce.","stem":"Why should you think before buying something?","choices":{"A":"to avoid creating too much waste","B":"to spend more money","C":"to buy bigger items","D":"to use more packaging"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that buying unneeded items creates excessive waste, so thinking first helps avoid waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, consider the waste the purchase will produce."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. The world is not green. B. You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. C. Carbon footprints are only made by factories. D. Greenhouse gases are not a problem.","excerpt":"\"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"The world is not green.","B":"You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint.","C":"Carbon footprints are only made by factories.","D":"Greenhouse gases are not a problem."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text asks a question and answers it: reduce your carbon footprint.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What are three things people use fossil fuels for? A. Cooking, sleeping, and reading B. Electricity, heating, and powering vehicles C. Running, jumping, and swimming D. Planting trees, recycling, and composting","excerpt":"\"Greenhouse gases are created by burning fossil fuels. People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.\"","stem":"What are three things people use fossil fuels for?","choices":{"A":"Cooking, sleeping, and reading","B":"Electricity, heating, and powering vehicles","C":"Running, jumping, and swimming","D":"Planting trees, recycling, and composting"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Greenhouse gases are created by burning fossil fuels. People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What is one way to reduce your carbon footprint mentioned in the text? A. Ride in a car more often B. Walk or ride a bike C. Leave lights on all day D. Buy more plastic bottles","excerpt":"\"There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car.\"","stem":"What is one way to reduce your carbon footprint mentioned in the text?","choices":{"A":"Ride in a car more often","B":"Walk or ride a bike","C":"Leave lights on all day","D":"Buy more plastic bottles"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says walking or biking instead of riding in a car helps.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q018","read_aloud":"Why does recycling newspaper help trees? A. It uses more trees. B. Fewer trees need to be cut down for new paper. C. Trees grow faster. D. It has nothing to do with trees.","excerpt":"\"You can recycle newspaper so that fewer trees are chopped down to make new paper.\"","stem":"Why does recycling newspaper help trees?","choices":{"A":"It uses more trees.","B":"Fewer trees need to be cut down for new paper.","C":"Trees grow faster.","D":"It has nothing to do with trees."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Recycling newspaper means less new paper is needed, so fewer trees are cut.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You can recycle newspaper so that fewer trees are chopped down to make new paper.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What does the word emissions mean in this sentence? A. Things that are bought in a store B. Substances released into the air C. Lights that save energy D. Plants that grow in a garden","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What does the word emissions mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Things that are bought in a store","B":"Substances released into the air","C":"Lights that save energy","D":"Plants that grow in a garden"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Emissions are substances, like gases, that are released or given off into the air.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q020","read_aloud":"According to the text, what are two ways to reduce your carbon footprint? A. Drive a car and leave lights on B. Walk or ride a bike and turn off lights C. Buy new things and throw away old ones D. Use more electricity and heat","excerpt":"\"One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car. You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste.\"","stem":"According to the text, what are two ways to reduce your carbon footprint?","choices":{"A":"Drive a car and leave lights on","B":"Walk or ride a bike and turn off lights","C":"Buy new things and throw away old ones","D":"Use more electricity and heat"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists walking, biking, and turning off lights as ways to help.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car. You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q021","read_aloud":"Why do people burn fossil fuels? A. To create water B. To make the air clean C. For electricity, heating, and power D. To grow plants","excerpt":"\"Greenhouse gases are created by burning fossil fuels. People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.\"","stem":"Why do people burn fossil fuels?","choices":{"A":"To create water","B":"To make the air clean","C":"For electricity, heating, and power","D":"To grow plants"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that people burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Greenhouse gases are created by burning fossil fuels. People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027excessive\u0027 mean? Options:? A. Very little, B. Exactly the right amount, C. A lot, or more than necessary, D. Something that is broken","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases... consider the waste the purchase will produce.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027excessive\u0027 mean? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Very little,","B":"Exactly the right amount,","C":"A lot, or more than necessary,","D":"Something that is broken"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Excessive means having more than is needed or a large amount that is unnecessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases... consider the waste the purchase will produce.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of paragraph 5? Options:? A. The world is getting smaller, B. We need to figure out how to support more people while helping the environment, C. Everyone should move to a different planet, D. The population is decreasing","excerpt":"\"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment?\"","stem":"What is the main idea of paragraph 5? Options:?","choices":{"A":"The world is getting smaller,","B":"We need to figure out how to support more people while helping the environment,","C":"Everyone should move to a different planet,","D":"The population is decreasing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph discusses the challenge of a growing population and the need to protect the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q024","read_aloud":"What detail supports the claim that the human population is growing? Options:? A. There are seven billion people, B. People do not like to recycle, C. People live in houses, D. The earth is round","excerpt":"The text notes there are nearly seven billion people on Earth, which supports the idea that the population is large and growing.","stem":"What detail supports the claim that the human population is growing? Options:?","choices":{"A":"There are seven billion people,","B":"People do not like to recycle,","C":"People live in houses,","D":"The earth is round"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The correct answer is supported by the details in the excerpt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text notes there are nearly seven billion people on Earth, which supports the idea that the population is large and growing."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l01-q025","read_aloud":"Why are energy-efficient light bulbs a good choice? Options:? A. They do not give off any light, B. They use less electricity and last longer, C. They are very expensive to buy, D. They can only be used once","excerpt":"\"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs.\"","stem":"Why are energy-efficient light bulbs a good choice? Options:?","choices":{"A":"They do not give off any light,","B":"They use less electricity and last longer,","C":"They are very expensive to buy,","D":"They can only be used once"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that these bulbs use less electricity and last longer than regular bulbs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027excessive\u0027 mean? Options: A. Very little, B. Exactly the right amount, C. A lot, or more than necessary, D. Something that is broken","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases... consider the waste the purchase will produce.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027excessive\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Very little,","B":"Exactly the right amount,","C":"A lot, or more than necessary,","D":"Something that is broken"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Excessive means having more than is needed or a large amount that is unnecessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases... consider the waste the purchase will produce.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of paragraph 5? Options: A. The world is getting smaller, B. We need to figure out how to support more people while helping the environment, C. Everyone should move to a different planet, D. The population is decreasing","excerpt":"\"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment?\"","stem":"What is the main idea of paragraph 5? Options:","choices":{"A":"The world is getting smaller,","B":"We need to figure out how to support more people while helping the environment,","C":"Everyone should move to a different planet,","D":"The population is decreasing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph discusses the challenge of a growing population and the need to protect the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What detail supports the claim that the human population is growing? Options: A. There are seven billion people, B. People do not like to recycle, C. People live in houses, D. The earth is round","excerpt":"The text notes there are nearly seven billion people on Earth, which supports the idea that the population is large and growing.","stem":"What detail supports the claim that the human population is growing? Options:","choices":{"A":"There are seven billion people,","B":"People do not like to recycle,","C":"People live in houses,","D":"The earth is round"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The correct answer is supported by the details in the excerpt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text notes there are nearly seven billion people on Earth, which supports the idea that the population is large and growing."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q004","read_aloud":"Why are energy-efficient light bulbs a good choice? Options: A. They do not give off any light, B. They use less electricity and last longer, C. They are very expensive to buy, D. They can only be used once","excerpt":"\"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs.\"","stem":"Why are energy-efficient light bulbs a good choice? Options:","choices":{"A":"They do not give off any light,","B":"They use less electricity and last longer,","C":"They are very expensive to buy,","D":"They can only be used once"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that these bulbs use less electricity and last longer than regular bulbs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What does the author suggest you do with things you no longer need? Options: A. Throw them in the trash, B. Bury them in the backyard, C. Donate them to charity, D. Hide them in a closet","excerpt":"\"Before throwing away an item, think about whether it could be donated to charity.\"","stem":"What does the author suggest you do with things you no longer need? Options:","choices":{"A":"Throw them in the trash,","B":"Bury them in the backyard,","C":"Donate them to charity,","D":"Hide them in a closet"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author specifically recommends donating unwanted items to charity instead of throwing them away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Before throwing away an item, think about whether it could be donated to charity.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"excessive\" mean in this sentence? A. a small amount B. a lot, or more than necessary C. exactly the right amount D. none at all","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, consider the waste the purchase will produce.\"","stem":"What does \"excessive\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a small amount","B":"a lot, or more than necessary","C":"exactly the right amount","D":"none at all"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines excessive as a lot, or more than necessary. Buying more than you need creates more waste than necessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, consider the waste the purchase will produce.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. The mountain exploded. B. Small earthquakes shook the mountain. C. Ash fell everywhere. D. The mountain became a monument.","excerpt":"\"First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain. Then, on March 27, Mount St. Helens began to spout ashes and steam.\"","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"The mountain exploded.","B":"Small earthquakes shook the mountain.","C":"Ash fell everywhere.","D":"The mountain became a monument."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text uses \"first\" and \"then\" to show order. First, small earthquakes shook the mountain. Then the mountain began to spout ashes and steam.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"First there were a few small earthquakes that shook the mountain. Then, on March 27, Mount St. Helens began to spout ashes and steam.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What happens when you turn off lights? A. You waste more energy. B. You reduce energy waste. C. The room gets brighter. D. The lights break.","excerpt":"\"You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste.\"","stem":"What happens when you turn off lights?","choices":{"A":"You waste more energy.","B":"You reduce energy waste.","C":"The room gets brighter.","D":"The lights break."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that turning off lights when you leave a room reduces energy waste. This is a simple way to help the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q009","read_aloud":"How can reusing plastic bags help? A. It creates more trash. B. It helps the environment. C. It makes bags weaker. D. It costs more money.","excerpt":"\"Reusing plastic shopping bags to carry other items is another way to help the environment.\"","stem":"How can reusing plastic bags help?","choices":{"A":"It creates more trash.","B":"It helps the environment.","C":"It makes bags weaker.","D":"It costs more money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that reusing plastic shopping bags is another way to help the environment. Using something again means less waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Reusing plastic shopping bags to carry other items is another way to help the environment.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why does recycling newspaper help trees? A. because trees like newspaper B. because fewer trees need to be chopped down for new paper C. because newspaper grows on trees D. because trees can read","excerpt":"\"You can recycle newspaper so that fewer trees are chopped down to make new paper.\"","stem":"Why does recycling newspaper help trees?","choices":{"A":"because trees like newspaper","B":"because fewer trees need to be chopped down for new paper","C":"because newspaper grows on trees","D":"because trees can read"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that recycling newspaper means fewer trees are chopped down. Old paper is used to make new paper, so we do not need as many new trees.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You can recycle newspaper so that fewer trees are chopped down to make new paper.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q011","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"excessive\"? A. a lot, or more than necessary B. very small amounts C. just the right amount D. nothing at all","excerpt":"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, whether you are buying food or a new piece of electronic equipment, consider the waste the purchase will produce.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"excessive\"?","choices":{"A":"a lot, or more than necessary","B":"very small amounts","C":"just the right amount","D":"nothing at all"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Excessive means a lot or more than necessary. The text warns about waste that is excessive or too much.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, whether you are buying food or a new piece of electronic equipment, consider the waste the purchase will produce."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What should you ask about food packaging? A. if it is recyclable or made from recycled materials B. if it is the most colorful C. if it is the heaviest D. if it is the most expensive","excerpt":"Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? If it does have packaging, is that packaging recyclable or made from recycled materials?","stem":"What should you ask about food packaging?","choices":{"A":"if it is recyclable or made from recycled materials","B":"if it is the most colorful","C":"if it is the heaviest","D":"if it is the most expensive"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text suggests asking if packaging is recyclable or made from recycled materials.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? If it does have packaging, is that packaging recyclable or made from recycled materials?"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What is connected to supporting more people and the environment? A. reducing waste B. using more plastic C. building bigger cities D. driving more cars","excerpt":"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment? The answer has a great deal to do with reducing waste.","stem":"What is connected to supporting more people and the environment?","choices":{"A":"reducing waste","B":"using more plastic","C":"building bigger cities","D":"driving more cars"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the answer to supporting more people while helping the environment has to do with reducing waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment? The answer has a great deal to do with reducing waste."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What does every person on Earth produce? A. waste B. clean air C. new trees D. fresh water","excerpt":"Think About People. Currently, there are nearly seven billion people on Earth. The population continues to grow, and every person on the planet produces waste.","stem":"What does every person on Earth produce?","choices":{"A":"waste","B":"clean air","C":"new trees","D":"fresh water"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states that every person on the planet produces waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Think About People. Currently, there are nearly seven billion people on Earth. The population continues to grow, and every person on the planet produces waste."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q015","read_aloud":"Why are energy-efficient light bulbs a good choice? A. they use less energy but work as well or better B. they cost more money to use C. they break more easily D. they give off less light","excerpt":"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs.","stem":"Why are energy-efficient light bulbs a good choice?","choices":{"A":"they use less energy but work as well or better","B":"they cost more money to use","C":"they break more easily","D":"they give off less light"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that efficient products use less energy while working as well or better than what they replace.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What should you do first before buying something? A. Buy the item immediately. B. Consider the waste the purchase will produce. C. Throw away the packaging. D. Ignore the amount of packaging.","excerpt":"\"Before making purchases, whether you are buying food or a new piece of electronic equipment, consider the waste the purchase will produce. Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? … Do you need a new TV, or could you have an old one fixed or buy a used one?\"","stem":"What should you do first before buying something?","choices":{"A":"Buy the item immediately.","B":"Consider the waste the purchase will produce.","C":"Throw away the packaging.","D":"Ignore the amount of packaging."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"Before making purchases … consider the waste.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Before making purchases, whether you are buying food or a new piece of electronic equipment, consider the waste the purchase will produce. Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? … Do you need a new TV, or could you have an old one fixed or buy a used one?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q017","read_aloud":"What is one effect of more people on the planet? A. Less waste is produced. B. More waste is produced. C. Waste disappears. D. Recycling becomes easier.","excerpt":"\"The population continues to grow, and every person on the planet produces waste. However, there are many simple ways that each person can cut back on the waste he or she produces.\"","stem":"What is one effect of more people on the planet?","choices":{"A":"Less waste is produced.","B":"More waste is produced.","C":"Waste disappears.","D":"Recycling becomes easier."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says every person produces waste, so more people mean more waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The population continues to grow, and every person on the planet produces waste. However, there are many simple ways that each person can cut back on the waste he or she produces.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What are three benefits of energy-efficient light bulbs? A. They are cheaper, brighter, and smaller. B. They last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled. C. They are heavier, hotter, and harder to find. D. They break easily, waste energy, and cannot be recycled.","excerpt":"\"Energy-efficient light bulbs … last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\"","stem":"What are three benefits of energy-efficient light bulbs?","choices":{"A":"They are cheaper, brighter, and smaller.","B":"They last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.","C":"They are heavier, hotter, and harder to find.","D":"They break easily, waste energy, and cannot be recycled."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists these three benefits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Energy-efficient light bulbs … last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q019","read_aloud":"If you wanted to become less wasteful, what could you do today? A. Throw away all your old toys. B. Turn off lights when you leave a room. C. Leave the water running while brushing your teeth. D. Buy everything new instead of repairing.","excerpt":"\"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives.\"","stem":"If you wanted to become less wasteful, what could you do today?","choices":{"A":"Throw away all your old toys.","B":"Turn off lights when you leave a room.","C":"Leave the water running while brushing your teeth.","D":"Buy everything new instead of repairing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Turning off lights reduces energy waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What does excessive mean? A. The right amount B. Very little C. Too much or more than needed D. Just enough","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\"","stem":"What does excessive mean?","choices":{"A":"The right amount","B":"Very little","C":"Too much or more than needed","D":"Just enough"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Excessive means more than what is necessary or too much.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q021","read_aloud":"What does it mean to \"precycle\"? A. To buy things without thinking B. To plan purchases with recycling in mind C. To throw everything away D. To ride a bicycle","excerpt":"\"Another way to reduce waste is to precycle. Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind.\"","stem":"What does it mean to \"precycle\"?","choices":{"A":"To buy things without thinking","B":"To plan purchases with recycling in mind","C":"To throw everything away","D":"To ride a bicycle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines precycling as planning purchases with recycling in mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Another way to reduce waste is to precycle. Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q022","read_aloud":"Which container is better for the environment? A. The Styrofoam container B. The cardboard container C. The plastic container D. The metal container","excerpt":"\"For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. They are the same price, but one comes in a Styrofoam container, and the other in a cardboard container.\"","stem":"Which container is better for the environment?","choices":{"A":"The Styrofoam container","B":"The cardboard container","C":"The plastic container","D":"The metal container"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that cardboard can be recycled or will break down, unlike Styrofoam.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. They are the same price, but one comes in a Styrofoam container, and the other in a cardboard container.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q023","read_aloud":"Why is Styrofoam a bad choice for the environment? A. It breaks down very quickly. B. It is good for plants. C. It lasts for a very long time in landfills. D. It is made of paper.","excerpt":"\"It is not known exactly how long it takes for Styrofoam to break down, but it will last for at least 100 years.\"","stem":"Why is Styrofoam a bad choice for the environment?","choices":{"A":"It breaks down very quickly.","B":"It is good for plants.","C":"It lasts for a very long time in landfills.","D":"It is made of paper."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Styrofoam lasts at least 100 years and does not break down easily.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is not known exactly how long it takes for Styrofoam to break down, but it will last for at least 100 years.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q024","read_aloud":"Why is refilling a water bottle better than throwing it away? A. It costs less money and creates less waste. B. It makes the water taste better. C. It is a new trend. D. It takes up more space.","excerpt":"\"A water bottle might be recyclable, but it could be refilled and reused instead of buying another bottle of water.\"","stem":"Why is refilling a water bottle better than throwing it away?","choices":{"A":"It costs less money and creates less waste.","B":"It makes the water taste better.","C":"It is a new trend.","D":"It takes up more space."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Refilling the bottle means you do not have to buy a new one, which saves money and reduces waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A water bottle might be recyclable, but it could be refilled and reused instead of buying another bottle of water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027emissions\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027emissions\u0027 mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the sentence, what does \u0027underlie\u0027 mean? Options: A. To hide underneath a rug, B. To form the foundation of something, C. To change quickly, D. To break into pieces","excerpt":"\"It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\"","stem":"Based on the sentence, what does \u0027underlie\u0027 mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"To hide underneath a rug,","B":"To form the foundation of something,","C":"To change quickly,","D":"To break into pieces"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To underlie means to be the basis or foundation that supports something else, like a lifestyle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What are the \"Three Rs\" mentioned in the text? Options: A. Run, Race, Read, B. Reduce, Reuse, Recycle, C. Return, Repair, Refresh, D. Real, Right, Ready","excerpt":"\"The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\"","stem":"What are the \"Three Rs\" mentioned in the text? Options:","choices":{"A":"Run, Race, Read,","B":"Reduce, Reuse, Recycle,","C":"Return, Repair, Refresh,","D":"Real, Right, Ready"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that the three Rs stand for Reduce, Reuse, and Recycle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What is the result of buying items you do not need? Options: A. It saves money, B. It creates a lot of waste, C. It helps the planet, D. It cleans the house","excerpt":"\"Before you buy any item, ask yourself whether you really need it. A great deal of waste is created when people buy items they do not need or cannot use.\"","stem":"What is the result of buying items you do not need? Options:","choices":{"A":"It saves money,","B":"It creates a lot of waste,","C":"It helps the planet,","D":"It cleans the house"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that buying unnecessary items leads to a \"great deal of waste\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Before you buy any item, ask yourself whether you really need it. A great deal of waste is created when people buy items they do not need or cannot use.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q004","read_aloud":"Why are eggs in a cardboard container a better choice than Styrofoam? Options: A. Cardboard is cheaper, B. Cardboard can be recycled or is biodegradable, C. Cardboard tastes better, D. Styrofoam is too heavy","excerpt":"\"Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. ... The cardboard can be recycled... The Styrofoam would have to be thrown away.\"","stem":"Why are eggs in a cardboard container a better choice than Styrofoam? Options:","choices":{"A":"Cardboard is cheaper,","B":"Cardboard can be recycled or is biodegradable,","C":"Cardboard tastes better,","D":"Styrofoam is too heavy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that cardboard is better because it is recyclable or biodegradable, unlike Styrofoam which must be thrown away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. ... The cardboard can be recycled... The Styrofoam would have to be thrown away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q005","read_aloud":"How does growing your own food help the planet? Options: A. It creates a lot of packaging waste, B. It creates very little waste, C. It makes you spend more money at the store, D. It helps the grocery store","excerpt":"\"Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.\"","stem":"How does growing your own food help the planet? Options:","choices":{"A":"It creates a lot of packaging waste,","B":"It creates very little waste,","C":"It makes you spend more money at the store,","D":"It helps the grocery store"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author states that growing your own food creates very little waste, unlike buying store-bought items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"underlie\" mean in this sentence? A. form the foundation of B. float above C. disappear from D. ignore completely","excerpt":"\"Our personal consumer choices have ecological, social, and spiritual consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\"","stem":"What does \"underlie\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"form the foundation of","B":"float above","C":"disappear from","D":"ignore completely"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines underlie as form the foundation of. The notions that underlie our lifestyles are the basic ideas that support how we live.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our personal consumer choices have ecological, social, and spiritual consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What is one benefit of energy-efficient light bulbs? A. They are more expensive. B. They use less electricity. C. They break easily. D. They cannot be recycled.","excerpt":"\"A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\"","stem":"What is one benefit of energy-efficient light bulbs?","choices":{"A":"They are more expensive.","B":"They use less electricity.","C":"They break easily.","D":"They cannot be recycled."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists several benefits. One of them is that energy-efficient light bulbs use less electricity. They also last longer and can be recycled.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q008","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s opinion on packaging? A. The author thinks all packaging is good. B. The author thinks less packaging and recyclable packaging are better. C. The author does not care about packaging. D. The author thinks packaging should be bigger.","excerpt":"\"Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? If it does have packaging, is that packaging recyclable or made from recycled materials?\"","stem":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s opinion on packaging?","choices":{"A":"The author thinks all packaging is good.","B":"The author thinks less packaging and recyclable packaging are better.","C":"The author does not care about packaging.","D":"The author thinks packaging should be bigger."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author asks readers to think about whether packaging is excessive and whether it is recyclable. This shows the author believes less packaging and recyclable packaging are better for the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? If it does have packaging, is that packaging recyclable or made from recycled materials?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What are the three Rs? A. Read, Write, and Arithmetic B. Reduce, Reuse, and Recycle C. Run, Rest, and Relax D. Red, Blue, and Green","excerpt":"\"The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\"","stem":"What are the three Rs?","choices":{"A":"Read, Write, and Arithmetic","B":"Reduce, Reuse, and Recycle","C":"Run, Rest, and Relax","D":"Red, Blue, and Green"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that the three Rs are \"Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\" These are three ways to help the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q010","read_aloud":"Why is reducing waste important for the future? A. because the population will grow and more people will create more waste B. because people will disappear C. because the environment does not matter D. because waste is good for Earth","excerpt":"\"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment?\"","stem":"Why is reducing waste important for the future?","choices":{"A":"because the population will grow and more people will create more waste","B":"because people will disappear","C":"because the environment does not matter","D":"because waste is good for Earth"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the world\u0027s population will grow larger. More people means more waste. Reducing waste now helps prepare for a future with more people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"underlie\" most likely mean based on this context? A. form the foundation of something B. float on top of water C. move very quickly D. make something louder","excerpt":"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways.","stem":"What does \"underlie\" most likely mean based on this context?","choices":{"A":"form the foundation of something","B":"float on top of water","C":"move very quickly","D":"make something louder"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Underlie means to form the foundation. The text shows that small changes form the foundation for bigger benefits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What question should you ask before buying something? A. whether you really need it B. whether it is the newest model C. whether your friends have one D. whether it comes in many colors","excerpt":"Think Twice. Before you buy any item, ask yourself whether you really need it. A great deal of waste is created when people buy items they do not need or cannot use.","stem":"What question should you ask before buying something?","choices":{"A":"whether you really need it","B":"whether it is the newest model","C":"whether your friends have one","D":"whether it comes in many colors"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text advises asking yourself whether you really need an item before buying it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Think Twice. Before you buy any item, ask yourself whether you really need it. A great deal of waste is created when people buy items they do not need or cannot use."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What can happen when you spend free time shopping? A. you may buy items you do not really need B. you will always save money C. you will make more friends D. you will learn new skills","excerpt":"Try a New Activity. Do you spend a great deal of time shopping with your friends? Some people think of shopping as a fun, leisure activity or as a hobby. One result of spending free time shopping may be buying items when you do not really need them.","stem":"What can happen when you spend free time shopping?","choices":{"A":"you may buy items you do not really need","B":"you will always save money","C":"you will make more friends","D":"you will learn new skills"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that spending free time shopping may lead to buying unneeded items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Try a New Activity. Do you spend a great deal of time shopping with your friends? Some people think of shopping as a fun, leisure activity or as a hobby. One result of spending free time shopping may be buying items when you do not really need them."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What does precycling mean? A. planning purchases with recycling in mind B. buying things before you need them C. recycling things after you use them D. throwing away old items quickly","excerpt":"Precycle. Another way to reduce waste is to precycle. Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs.","stem":"What does precycling mean?","choices":{"A":"planning purchases with recycling in mind","B":"buying things before you need them","C":"recycling things after you use them","D":"throwing away old items quickly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines precycling as planning purchases with recycling in mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Precycle. Another way to reduce waste is to precycle. Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the \"Three Rs\" from this sentence? A. Reduce is the least important. B. Reduce is very important. C. Reuse and recycle are not important. D. There are four Rs.","excerpt":"\"Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the \"Three Rs\" from this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Reduce is the least important.","B":"Reduce is very important.","C":"Reuse and recycle are not important.","D":"There are four Rs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author says reducing is one of the most important parts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q016","read_aloud":"How is this text organized? A. As a story with a beginning, middle, and end B. As a list of numbered tips or ways to reduce waste C. As a poem D. As a letter to a friend","excerpt":"The text has numbered sections such as \"Think Twice,\" \"Precycle,\" \"Try a New Activity,\" and \"Repair or Donate.\"","stem":"How is this text organized?","choices":{"A":"As a story with a beginning, middle, and end","B":"As a list of numbered tips or ways to reduce waste","C":"As a poem","D":"As a letter to a friend"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The title says \"10 Ways\" and the sections are numbered tips.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text has numbered sections such as \"Think Twice,\" \"Precycle,\" \"Try a New Activity,\" and \"Repair or Donate.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q017","read_aloud":"Which egg container is better for the environment? A. Styrofoam container B. Plastic container C. Cardboard container D. Metal container","excerpt":"\"Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. … The eggs in the cardboard container are the better choice for the environment.\"","stem":"Which egg container is better for the environment?","choices":{"A":"Styrofoam container","B":"Plastic container","C":"Cardboard container","D":"Metal container"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The cardboard container can be recycled and is biodegradable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. … The eggs in the cardboard container are the better choice for the environment.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q018","read_aloud":"Why does gardening reduce waste? A. It creates a lot of trash. B. Growing your own food creates little waste and avoids packaging. C. It uses many plastic containers. D. It requires buying many new tools.","excerpt":"\"Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.\"","stem":"Why does gardening reduce waste?","choices":{"A":"It creates a lot of trash.","B":"Growing your own food creates little waste and avoids packaging.","C":"It uses many plastic containers.","D":"It requires buying many new tools."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Homegrown tomatoes produce little waste compared to storebought ones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What does the word underlie mean? A. To hide under a bed B. To form the foundation of something C. To forget about something D. To sleep","excerpt":"\"Our personal consumer choices have ecological, social, and spiritual consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\"","stem":"What does the word underlie mean?","choices":{"A":"To hide under a bed","B":"To form the foundation of something","C":"To forget about something","D":"To sleep"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To underlie means to be the foundation or basis for something, like our habits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our personal consumer choices have ecological, social, and spiritual consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q020","read_aloud":"When should you ask these questions? A. Before buying food B. Before throwing an item away C. After you buy something new D. When you are at school","excerpt":"\"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\"","stem":"When should you ask these questions?","choices":{"A":"Before buying food","B":"Before throwing an item away","C":"After you buy something new","D":"When you are at school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests asking these questions when you are thinking about throwing an item away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. Plastic items can only be used once. B. Plastic items are very expensive. C. You can find new uses for disposable items. D. You should buy new plastic items.","excerpt":"\"Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Plastic items can only be used once.","B":"Plastic items are very expensive.","C":"You can find new uses for disposable items.","D":"You should buy new plastic items."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The paragraph gives examples of how to reuse plastic items instead of throwing them away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q022","read_aloud":"What happens to items donated to charities? A. They are thrown in the trash. B. They are given to people who need them. C. They are recycled into new bottles. D. They are sold for high prices.","excerpt":"\"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\"","stem":"What happens to items donated to charities?","choices":{"A":"They are thrown in the trash.","B":"They are given to people who need them.","C":"They are recycled into new bottles.","D":"They are sold for high prices."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Charities make sure donated items get to people in need.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q023","read_aloud":"Why might you want to repair a broken item? A. To make it look new again B. Because it is often cheaper than buying a new one C. To give it to a friend D. To practice building","excerpt":"\"Repairing a damaged item can often be cheaper than replacing it.\"","stem":"Why might you want to repair a broken item?","choices":{"A":"To make it look new again","B":"Because it is often cheaper than buying a new one","C":"To give it to a friend","D":"To practice building"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says repairing an item can be cheaper than replacing it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Repairing a damaged item can often be cheaper than replacing it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l03-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for the word \u0027innovative\u0027? Options: A. Old-fashioned, B. Boring, C. Creative, D. Difficult","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"What is a synonym for the word \u0027innovative\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"Old-fashioned,","B":"Boring,","C":"Creative,","D":"Difficult"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Innovative means using new or creative ideas and methods to solve problems.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q002","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s suggestion when an electronic item breaks? Options: A. Throw it away and buy a new one, B. Try to have it repaired, C. Never use electronics, D. Hide it in a box","excerpt":"\"If a cell phone or a camera breaks, it may be possible to have it repaired rather than buying a new one.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s suggestion when an electronic item breaks? Options:","choices":{"A":"Throw it away and buy a new one,","B":"Try to have it repaired,","C":"Never use electronics,","D":"Hide it in a box"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author encourages repairing items as a way to avoid waste instead of replacing them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If a cell phone or a camera breaks, it may be possible to have it repaired rather than buying a new one.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q003","read_aloud":"How do charities like Goodwill help the environment? Options: A. By making people buy new clothes, B. By making sure used items are reused by others, C. By building more landfills, D. By selling food","excerpt":"\"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\"","stem":"How do charities like Goodwill help the environment? Options:","choices":{"A":"By making people buy new clothes,","B":"By making sure used items are reused by others,","C":"By building more landfills,","D":"By selling food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By helping distribute donated goods, these charities ensure items are reused rather than thrown away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q004","read_aloud":"Why would a person use a power strip to \"slay\" energy vampires? Options: A. Because it looks cool, B. Because it is easier to turn off power to many devices at once, C. Because the power strip uses more energy, D. Because it makes devices run faster","excerpt":"\"Many people choose to plug their devices into a power strip or bar. ... They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\"","stem":"Why would a person use a power strip to \"slay\" energy vampires? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because it looks cool,","B":"Because it is easier to turn off power to many devices at once,","C":"Because the power strip uses more energy,","D":"Because it makes devices run faster"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Using a power strip allows people to cut power to all plugged-in items easily, preventing energy waste when devices are not in use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many people choose to plug their devices into a power strip or bar. ... They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q005","read_aloud":"Why is good insulation a smart choice for a family? Options: A. It makes the house look bigger, B. It helps the house stay at a comfortable temperature using less energy, C. It makes the house very loud, D. It requires no maintenance","excerpt":"\"In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation. This means that less energy and less money is needed.\"","stem":"Why is good insulation a smart choice for a family? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the house look bigger,","B":"It helps the house stay at a comfortable temperature using less energy,","C":"It makes the house very loud,","D":"It requires no maintenance"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Good insulation keeps the home at the right temperature longer, which saves money and energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation. This means that less energy and less money is needed.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"innovative\" mean in this sentence? A. boring and old B. creative, using new ideas or methods C. difficult and confusing D. expensive and fancy","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"What does \"innovative\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"boring and old","B":"creative, using new ideas or methods","C":"difficult and confusing","D":"expensive and fancy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines innovative as creative, using new ideas or methods. People are finding new and clever ways to save water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author suggest thinking before buying? A. because buying things is always bad B. because unnecessary purchases create waste C. because stores are closed D. because money is not important","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, whether you are buying food or a new piece of electronic equipment, consider the waste the purchase will produce.\"","stem":"Why does the author suggest thinking before buying?","choices":{"A":"because buying things is always bad","B":"because unnecessary purchases create waste","C":"because stores are closed","D":"because money is not important"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says buying more than you need leads to excessive waste. The author wants readers to think about waste before purchasing to avoid creating unnecessary trash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, whether you are buying food or a new piece of electronic equipment, consider the waste the purchase will produce.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What should you ask yourself before buying a new TV? A. What color is the TV? B. Could I fix my old one or buy a used one instead? C. How many buttons does it have? D. Does the TV have a remote?","excerpt":"\"Do you need a new TV, or could you have an old one fixed or buy a used one?\"","stem":"What should you ask yourself before buying a new TV?","choices":{"A":"What color is the TV?","B":"Could I fix my old one or buy a used one instead?","C":"How many buttons does it have?","D":"Does the TV have a remote?"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests asking whether you need a new TV or could fix an old one or buy a used one. This helps reduce waste by avoiding unnecessary new purchases.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Do you need a new TV, or could you have an old one fixed or buy a used one?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q009","read_aloud":"Why does the author mention charities like Goodwill? A. to show where to buy new clothes B. to give readers a way to help others while reducing waste C. to prove that charities are bad D. to describe fashion trends","excerpt":"\"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\"","stem":"Why does the author mention charities like Goodwill?","choices":{"A":"to show where to buy new clothes","B":"to give readers a way to help others while reducing waste","C":"to prove that charities are bad","D":"to describe fashion trends"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author mentions charities as a way to reuse items. Instead of throwing things away, you can donate them. This helps people in need and keeps items out of landfills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"watt\" most likely measure based on this text? A. electrical power or energy use B. the weight of light bulbs C. the color of light D. the size of a room","excerpt":"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb.","stem":"What does \"watt\" most likely measure based on this text?","choices":{"A":"electrical power or energy use","B":"the weight of light bulbs","C":"the color of light","D":"the size of a room"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Watt is a unit for measuring electrical power. The text discusses energy-efficient bulbs that use less power.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q011","read_aloud":"How can gardening help reduce waste? A. growing your own food creates little waste B. gardening uses lots of plastic bags C. gardens need many new tools D. gardening requires buying more things","excerpt":"Try a New Activity. Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.","stem":"How can gardening help reduce waste?","choices":{"A":"growing your own food creates little waste","B":"gardening uses lots of plastic bags","C":"gardens need many new tools","D":"gardening requires buying more things"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that growing your own food, like tomatoes, creates very little waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Try a New Activity. Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q012","read_aloud":"Why is cardboard a better choice than Styrofoam? A. cardboard can be recycled and breaks down naturally B. cardboard is always cheaper C. cardboard holds more eggs D. cardboard looks more colorful","excerpt":"Precycle. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. They are the same price, but one comes in a Styrofoam container, and the other in a cardboard container. The cardboard can be recycled, and even if it should be thrown out, cardboard is biodegradable.","stem":"Why is cardboard a better choice than Styrofoam?","choices":{"A":"cardboard can be recycled and breaks down naturally","B":"cardboard is always cheaper","C":"cardboard holds more eggs","D":"cardboard looks more colorful"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states cardboard can be recycled and is biodegradable, unlike Styrofoam.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Precycle. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. They are the same price, but one comes in a Styrofoam container, and the other in a cardboard container. The cardboard can be recycled, and even if it should be thrown out, cardboard is biodegradable."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q013","read_aloud":"If you have an empty water bottle, what could you do based on this text? A. refill and reuse it instead of buying a new one B. throw it away immediately C. give it to someone who does not want it D. use it only once and then recycle it","excerpt":"Putting Items to New Uses. Reusing can be thought of as rescuing things that would otherwise be wasted. A water bottle might be recyclable, but it could be refilled and reused instead of buying another bottle of water.","stem":"If you have an empty water bottle, what could you do based on this text?","choices":{"A":"refill and reuse it instead of buying a new one","B":"throw it away immediately","C":"give it to someone who does not want it","D":"use it only once and then recycle it"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the idea of reusing by refilling a water bottle instead of buying new.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Putting Items to New Uses. Reusing can be thought of as rescuing things that would otherwise be wasted. A water bottle might be recyclable, but it could be refilled and reused instead of buying another bottle of water."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q014","read_aloud":"How does asking these questions help reduce waste? A. it helps you find ways to use items instead of throwing them away B. it makes you buy more new things C. it helps you throw things away faster D. it makes items last a shorter time","excerpt":"Ways to Reuse Items. Ask Questions. Take a close look at an item you are thinking about throwing away. Maybe it is a bicycle with a broken gear shift or an old shirt that no longer fits. Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027could someone else use this?\u0027","stem":"How does asking these questions help reduce waste?","choices":{"A":"it helps you find ways to use items instead of throwing them away","B":"it makes you buy more new things","C":"it helps you throw things away faster","D":"it makes items last a shorter time"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that asking if you or others can use an item helps find ways to reuse instead of waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Ways to Reuse Items. Ask Questions. Take a close look at an item you are thinking about throwing away. Maybe it is a bicycle with a broken gear shift or an old shirt that no longer fits. Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027could someone else use this?\u0027"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What does a watt measure? A. the weight of electricity B. the speed of electricity C. the amount of electrical power D. the temperature of a light bulb","excerpt":"\"Many families in the United States have saved money and energy by installing a power meter called a KillAWatt. … Watt unit of measurement for electrical power.\"","stem":"What does a watt measure?","choices":{"A":"the weight of electricity","B":"the speed of electricity","C":"the amount of electrical power","D":"the temperature of a light bulb"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"watt unit of measurement for electrical power.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many families in the United States have saved money and energy by installing a power meter called a KillAWatt. … Watt unit of measurement for electrical power.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q016","read_aloud":"How are wellinsulated homes different from poorly insulated homes? A. They are colder. B. They get warm faster and stay warm longer. C. They cost more to heat. D. They waste more energy.","excerpt":"\"In cold weather, wellinsulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation. This means that less energy and less money is needed to heat wellinsulated homes.\"","stem":"How are wellinsulated homes different from poorly insulated homes?","choices":{"A":"They are colder.","B":"They get warm faster and stay warm longer.","C":"They cost more to heat.","D":"They waste more energy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states these differences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In cold weather, wellinsulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation. This means that less energy and less money is needed to heat wellinsulated homes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q017","read_aloud":"What effect does putting a brick in the toilet tank have? A. It breaks the toilet. B. It reduces the amount of water used per flush. C. It makes the toilet flush louder. D. It increases water use.","excerpt":"\"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank. The toilet will keep the same level of water in the tank without using as much water with each flush.\"","stem":"What effect does putting a brick in the toilet tank have?","choices":{"A":"It breaks the toilet.","B":"It reduces the amount of water used per flush.","C":"It makes the toilet flush louder.","D":"It increases water use."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The brick takes up space, so less water is needed to refill the tank.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank. The toilet will keep the same level of water in the tank without using as much water with each flush.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q018","read_aloud":"Why does good insulation save money? A. Because it makes the house look nicer. B. Because less energy is needed to heat the house, so heating bills are lower. C. Because insulation is free. D. Because it makes the house smaller.","excerpt":"\"The same idea is true for homes. In cold weather, wellinsulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation. This means that less energy and less money is needed to heat wellinsulated homes.\"","stem":"Why does good insulation save money?","choices":{"A":"Because it makes the house look nicer.","B":"Because less energy is needed to heat the house, so heating bills are lower.","C":"Because insulation is free.","D":"Because it makes the house smaller."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Less energy needed means lower heating bills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The same idea is true for homes. In cold weather, wellinsulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation. This means that less energy and less money is needed to heat wellinsulated homes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q019","read_aloud":"If you saw that your family\u0027s energy use was very high on the meter, what could you do? A. Ignore the meter. B. Turn off lights and electronics that are not needed. C. Use more appliances. D. Leave everything running.","excerpt":"\"Many families in the United States have saved money and energy by installing a power meter called a KillAWatt. These meters display how much energy is being used and how much this energy costs.\"","stem":"If you saw that your family\u0027s energy use was very high on the meter, what could you do?","choices":{"A":"Ignore the meter.","B":"Turn off lights and electronics that are not needed.","C":"Use more appliances.","D":"Leave everything running."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Reducing energy use would lower the meter reading and save money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many families in the United States have saved money and energy by installing a power meter called a KillAWatt. These meters display how much energy is being used and how much this energy costs.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q020","read_aloud":"What is a watt? A. A unit to measure water B. A unit to measure electrical power C. A type of light bulb D. A way to save money","excerpt":"\"Watt: unit of measurement for electrical power.\"","stem":"What is a watt?","choices":{"A":"A unit to measure water","B":"A unit to measure electrical power","C":"A type of light bulb","D":"A way to save money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A watt is a unit of measurement for electrical power.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Watt: unit of measurement for electrical power.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q021","read_aloud":"Why are some devices called \"vampires\"? A. They look scary. B. They suck energy even when turned off. C. They only work at night. D. They make a loud noise.","excerpt":"\"Some devices use power whenever they are plugged in, whether they are turned on or not. These energy-sucking devices are sometimes referred to as \u0027vampires.\u0027\"","stem":"Why are some devices called \"vampires\"?","choices":{"A":"They look scary.","B":"They suck energy even when turned off.","C":"They only work at night.","D":"They make a loud noise."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They are called vampires because they \"suck\" or use energy even when they are turned off.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some devices use power whenever they are plugged in, whether they are turned on or not. These energy-sucking devices are sometimes referred to as \u0027vampires.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How can a power strip help save energy? A. It makes devices work faster. B. It helps you plug in more things. C. It can cut power to many devices at once. D. It uses less water.","excerpt":"\"Power strips have several outlets with a single plug. They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\"","stem":"How can a power strip help save energy?","choices":{"A":"It makes devices work faster.","B":"It helps you plug in more things.","C":"It can cut power to many devices at once.","D":"It uses less water."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Power strips have switches to easily cut off power to devices plugged into them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Power strips have several outlets with a single plug. They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does insulation help a home? A. It keeps the home cool in the winter. B. It keeps the home warm and saves energy. C. It lets fresh air inside. D. It stops the wind from blowing.","excerpt":"\"In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation.\"","stem":"How does insulation help a home?","choices":{"A":"It keeps the home cool in the winter.","B":"It keeps the home warm and saves energy.","C":"It lets fresh air inside.","D":"It stops the wind from blowing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Insulation keeps heat inside the home, so it stays warm and uses less energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q024","read_aloud":"Why is insulation a smart decision? A. It looks nice. B. It helps the environment and saves money. C. It is easy to do alone. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\"","stem":"Why is insulation a smart decision?","choices":{"A":"It looks nice.","B":"It helps the environment and saves money.","C":"It is easy to do alone.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Insulation saves energy, which helps the environment and lowers bills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l04-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is a \u0027watt\u0027? Options: A. A type of spoiled food, B. A unit used to measure electrical power, C. A container for garbage, D. A tool for the garden","excerpt":"\"Most families throw this kind of waste into the garbage. It is possible, however, to find a use for many types of spoiled or uneaten food. ... watt unit of measurement for electrical power.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is a \u0027watt\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"A type of spoiled food,","B":"A unit used to measure electrical power,","C":"A container for garbage,","D":"A tool for the garden"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text provides a clear definition: a watt is a unit of measurement for electrical power.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most families throw this kind of waste into the garbage. It is possible, however, to find a use for many types of spoiled or uneaten food. ... watt unit of measurement for electrical power.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q002","read_aloud":"What is this an example of? Options: A. Wasting water, B. Reusing graywater, C. Buying a new shower, D. Using less soap","excerpt":"\"Try collecting the water that runs in the shower while the water gets hot and then using it to water plants.\"","stem":"What is this an example of? Options:","choices":{"A":"Wasting water,","B":"Reusing graywater,","C":"Buying a new shower,","D":"Using less soap"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Collecting water that would otherwise go down the drain to use on plants is a form of reusing graywater.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Try collecting the water that runs in the shower while the water gets hot and then using it to water plants.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q003","read_aloud":"Why does putting a brick in the toilet tank save water? Options: A. It makes the toilet flush faster, B. It takes up space so less water is needed to fill the tank, C. It makes the water cleaner, D. It breaks the toilet","excerpt":"\"Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank. The toilet will keep the same level of water in the tank without using as much water with each flush.\"","stem":"Why does putting a brick in the toilet tank save water? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the toilet flush faster,","B":"It takes up space so less water is needed to fill the tank,","C":"It makes the water cleaner,","D":"It breaks the toilet"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because the object takes up space, the tank fills with less water, which saves that amount of water every time it flushes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank. The toilet will keep the same level of water in the tank without using as much water with each flush.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q004","read_aloud":"How do these materials become helpful to plants? Options: A. They turn into solid rock, B. They break down into a soil-like material that acts as fertilizer, C. They disappear completely, D. They stay exactly the same forever","excerpt":"\"In addition to spoiled food, people put garden trimmings and parts of food that cannot be eaten, such as cornhusks and eggshells, into a container in their garden.\"","stem":"How do these materials become helpful to plants? Options:","choices":{"A":"They turn into solid rock,","B":"They break down into a soil-like material that acts as fertilizer,","C":"They disappear completely,","D":"They stay exactly the same forever"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Composting causes food and plant scraps to break down, creating nutrient-rich material that helps plants grow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In addition to spoiled food, people put garden trimmings and parts of food that cannot be eaten, such as cornhusks and eggshells, into a container in their garden.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Why is vermiculture a good choice for people living in apartments? Options: A. Because they have large backyards, B. Because they don\u0027t have space for outdoor composting, C. Because they don\u0027t eat food, D. Because they don\u0027t like worms","excerpt":"\"In many cases, people who wish to compost indoors use vermiculture. Vermiculture uses a colony of worms, such as earthworms, to break down food that would otherwise be wasted.\"","stem":"Why is vermiculture a good choice for people living in apartments? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they have large backyards,","B":"Because they don\u0027t have space for outdoor composting,","C":"Because they don\u0027t eat food,","D":"Because they don\u0027t like worms"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since apartment dwellers lack outdoor garden space, vermiculture allows them to compost food scraps indoors using worms.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In many cases, people who wish to compost indoors use vermiculture. Vermiculture uses a colony of worms, such as earthworms, to break down food that would otherwise be wasted.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What is a \"watt\"? A. a type of light bulb B. a unit of measurement for electrical power C. a kind of battery D. a color of light","excerpt":"\"These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\"","stem":"What is a \"watt\"?","choices":{"A":"a type of light bulb","B":"a unit of measurement for electrical power","C":"a kind of battery","D":"a color of light"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines watt as a unit of measurement for electrical power. It helps measure how much electricity something uses.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q007","read_aloud":"Why do people use power strips? A. because they look pretty B. to easily turn off multiple devices and stop \"vampire\" energy use C. because they are required by law D. to make devices use more energy","excerpt":"\"Many people choose to plug their devices into a power strip or bar. Power strips have several outlets with a single plug. They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\"","stem":"Why do people use power strips?","choices":{"A":"because they look pretty","B":"to easily turn off multiple devices and stop \"vampire\" energy use","C":"because they are required by law","D":"to make devices use more energy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says some devices use power even when turned off. These are called \"vampires.\" Power strips let you cut power to all devices at once, stopping this waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many people choose to plug their devices into a power strip or bar. Power strips have several outlets with a single plug. They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author start with a question? A. to confuse readers B. to get readers thinking about how they can help the environment C. because the author does not know the answer D. to make the text shorter","excerpt":"\"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint.\"","stem":"Why does the author start with a question?","choices":{"A":"to confuse readers","B":"to get readers thinking about how they can help the environment","C":"because the author does not know the answer","D":"to make the text shorter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Starting with a question engages readers and makes them think. The author wants readers to consider their own actions and how they can make the world greener.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q009","read_aloud":"What can you do with water that runs while waiting for the shower to get hot? A. let it go down the drain B. collect it and use it to water plants C. pour it on the floor D. ignore it completely","excerpt":"\"Try collecting the water that runs in the shower while the water gets hot and then using it to water plants.\"","stem":"What can you do with water that runs while waiting for the shower to get hot?","choices":{"A":"let it go down the drain","B":"collect it and use it to water plants","C":"pour it on the floor","D":"ignore it completely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests collecting this water and using it to water plants. This is a simple way to reuse water that would otherwise be wasted.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Try collecting the water that runs in the shower while the water gets hot and then using it to water plants.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q010","read_aloud":"How does pooling resources help the community? A. It creates more trash. B. It helps people earn money, share items, and reduce waste. C. It makes people buy more new things. D. It forces people to keep items they do not need.","excerpt":"\"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\"","stem":"How does pooling resources help the community?","choices":{"A":"It creates more trash.","B":"It helps people earn money, share items, and reduce waste.","C":"It makes people buy more new things.","D":"It forces people to keep items they do not need."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists three benefits: earning money, providing items to neighbors, and keeping items from being thrown away. Pooling resources helps everyone while reducing waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"innovative\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. creative; using new ideas or methods B. old-fashioned and traditional C. slow and careful D. expensive and difficult","excerpt":"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water. Modern homes and businesses can use a great deal of fresh water, and, often, much of this water is wasted.","stem":"What does \"innovative\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"creative; using new ideas or methods","B":"old-fashioned and traditional","C":"slow and careful","D":"expensive and difficult"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Innovative means creative or using new ideas. The text describes people finding new ways to save water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water. Modern homes and businesses can use a great deal of fresh water, and, often, much of this water is wasted."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What is one way to reuse plastic shopping bags? A. use them as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste B. throw them away after one use C. burn them to make heat D. give them to stores for money","excerpt":"Find New Uses. Many disposable products can be used multiple times before they are thrown away or recycled. Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste.","stem":"What is one way to reuse plastic shopping bags?","choices":{"A":"use them as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste","B":"throw them away after one use","C":"burn them to make heat","D":"give them to stores for money"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text lists using plastic bags as trash liners or for picking up pet waste as reuse ideas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Find New Uses. Many disposable products can be used multiple times before they are thrown away or recycled. Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What is one benefit of repairing items? A. it can often be cheaper than replacing them B. it always takes less time than buying new C. it makes items look brand new D. it requires no tools or skills","excerpt":"Repair or Donate. Repairing a damaged item can often be cheaper than replacing it. If you do not have a family member who knows how to do this, consider calling the store where you purchased the item for advice about having it fixed.","stem":"What is one benefit of repairing items?","choices":{"A":"it can often be cheaper than replacing them","B":"it always takes less time than buying new","C":"it makes items look brand new","D":"it requires no tools or skills"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that repairing items can often cost less than buying replacements.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Repair or Donate. Repairing a damaged item can often be cheaper than replacing it. If you do not have a family member who knows how to do this, consider calling the store where you purchased the item for advice about having it fixed."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q014","read_aloud":"If you have devices that use power when plugged in, what could you do? A. plug them into a power strip and turn it off when not in use B. leave them plugged in all the time C. buy more of the same devices D. use them only at night","excerpt":"Use Power Strips. Did you know that some devices use power whenever they are plugged in, whether they are turned on or not? These energy-sucking devices are sometimes referred to as \u0027vampires.\u0027 Cell phone chargers, DVD players, microwave ovens, and coffee makers can be \u0027vampires.\u0027","stem":"If you have devices that use power when plugged in, what could you do?","choices":{"A":"plug them into a power strip and turn it off when not in use","B":"leave them plugged in all the time","C":"buy more of the same devices","D":"use them only at night"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This applies the text\u0027s suggestion to use power strips to cut power to devices that waste energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Use Power Strips. Did you know that some devices use power whenever they are plugged in, whether they are turned on or not? These energy-sucking devices are sometimes referred to as \u0027vampires.\u0027 Cell phone chargers, DVD players, microwave ovens, and coffee makers can be \u0027vampires.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q015","read_aloud":"How does the thermos example help explain home insulation? A. it shows how insulation keeps heat from escaping in both cases B. it proves that thermoses are better than cups for all drinks C. it suggests that homes should not have windows D. it shows that insulation only works in summer","excerpt":"Keep Insulated. Think about the difference between hot chocolate in a cup and hot chocolate in a thermos. The liquid in the thermos stays hot longer because the thermos is insulated. The same idea is true for homes. In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation.","stem":"How does the thermos example help explain home insulation?","choices":{"A":"it shows how insulation keeps heat from escaping in both cases","B":"it proves that thermoses are better than cups for all drinks","C":"it suggests that homes should not have windows","D":"it shows that insulation only works in summer"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text uses the thermos comparison to help readers understand how insulation keeps heat inside homes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Keep Insulated. Think about the difference between hot chocolate in a cup and hot chocolate in a thermos. The liquid in the thermos stays hot longer because the thermos is insulated. The same idea is true for homes. In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose in writing this text? A. To entertain readers with funny stories about waste B. To persuade readers to reduce waste by giving them practical tips C. To describe the history of recycling D. To tell a story about a family who wasted everything","excerpt":"The text includes many tips such as \"Use Power Strips,\" \"Try KillAWatt,\" \"Keep Insulated,\" and \"Collect Rainwater.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose in writing this text?","choices":{"A":"To entertain readers with funny stories about waste","B":"To persuade readers to reduce waste by giving them practical tips","C":"To describe the history of recycling","D":"To tell a story about a family who wasted everything"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text is persuasive and gives actionable advice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes many tips such as \"Use Power Strips,\" \"Try KillAWatt,\" \"Keep Insulated,\" and \"Collect Rainwater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s attitude toward saving water? A. He thinks it is impossible. B. He thinks it is important and possible with simple methods. C. He thinks only rich people can save water. D. He thinks water is unlimited.","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s attitude toward saving water?","choices":{"A":"He thinks it is impossible.","B":"He thinks it is important and possible with simple methods.","C":"He thinks only rich people can save water.","D":"He thinks water is unlimited."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He gives examples of simple, innovative ways to save water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Is this a practical suggestion for most people? Why? A. No, because compost buckets are too expensive. B. Yes, because the buckets are inexpensive and many gardeners would welcome free compost. C. No, because composting is too hard. D. Yes, because everyone has a garden.","excerpt":"\"If you do not have a use for compost at your home, ask your friends and family to see if anyone would like extra compost. … Small compost buckets are inexpensive, can be kept in the house or garage, and are easy to transport.\"","stem":"Is this a practical suggestion for most people? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because compost buckets are too expensive.","B":"Yes, because the buckets are inexpensive and many gardeners would welcome free compost.","C":"No, because composting is too hard.","D":"Yes, because everyone has a garden."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says buckets are inexpensive and gardeners would be happy to get compost.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If you do not have a use for compost at your home, ask your friends and family to see if anyone would like extra compost. … Small compost buckets are inexpensive, can be kept in the house or garage, and are easy to transport.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q019","read_aloud":"What does innovative mean? A. Using new ideas or methods B. Doing things the old way C. Being very lazy D. Buying expensive items","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"What does innovative mean?","choices":{"A":"Using new ideas or methods","B":"Doing things the old way","C":"Being very lazy","D":"Buying expensive items"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Innovative means using new ideas or creative methods to solve a problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q020","read_aloud":"What is one use for a rain barrel? A. To store drinking water B. To collect rainwater for the garden C. To keep leaves in the yard D. To catch bugs","excerpt":"\"Inexpensive rain barrels are available at most hardware stores. Most of these barrels have a screen that keeps out leaves and other debris.\"","stem":"What is one use for a rain barrel?","choices":{"A":"To store drinking water","B":"To collect rainwater for the garden","C":"To keep leaves in the yard","D":"To catch bugs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rain barrels collect rainwater, which can be used to water gardens.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Inexpensive rain barrels are available at most hardware stores. Most of these barrels have a screen that keeps out leaves and other debris.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q021","read_aloud":"How can you reduce water used by a toilet? A. Flush it more often. B. Put a brick in the tank to use less water. C. Use more toilet paper. D. Buy a new house.","excerpt":"\"A great deal of the water used in any home is flushed down the toilet.\"","stem":"How can you reduce water used by a toilet?","choices":{"A":"Flush it more often.","B":"Put a brick in the tank to use less water.","C":"Use more toilet paper.","D":"Buy a new house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests putting a brick or container in the tank to reduce water use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A great deal of the water used in any home is flushed down the toilet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q022","read_aloud":"Why does this trick work? A. It cleans the toilet. B. It makes the water cold. C. The tank fills with less water. D. It stops the toilet from flushing.","excerpt":"\"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\"","stem":"Why does this trick work?","choices":{"A":"It cleans the toilet.","B":"It makes the water cold.","C":"The tank fills with less water.","D":"It stops the toilet from flushing."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The brick takes up space, so the tank holds less water but still works the same way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q023","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q024","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l05-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Before buying food B. Before throwing an item away C. After you buy something new D. When you are at school","excerpt":"\"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Before buying food","B":"Before throwing an item away","C":"After you buy something new","D":"When you are at school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests asking these questions when you are thinking about throwing an item away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \u0027insulated\u0027 mean in this context? Options: A. Wrapped or protected to prevent the loss of heat, B. Left out in the cold air, C. Made of cold metal, D. Filled with ice","excerpt":"\"Think about the difference between hot chocolate in a cup and hot chocolate in a thermos. The liquid in the thermos stays hot longer because the thermos is insulated.\"","stem":"What does the word \u0027insulated\u0027 mean in this context? Options:","choices":{"A":"Wrapped or protected to prevent the loss of heat,","B":"Left out in the cold air,","C":"Made of cold metal,","D":"Filled with ice"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Insulated materials, like a thermos, help keep contents at their temperature by preventing heat from escaping.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Think about the difference between hot chocolate in a cup and hot chocolate in a thermos. The liquid in the thermos stays hot longer because the thermos is insulated.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q002","read_aloud":"How can a bottle drive benefit both a group and the environment? Options: A. It creates more trash, B. The group earns money and the items get recycled, C. It makes streets dirtier, D. It causes more trucks to drive","excerpt":"\"Bottle drives are a great way to earn money and help the environment. In a bottle drive, people go to homes and businesses in a community and ask residents to donate bottles and cans.\"","stem":"How can a bottle drive benefit both a group and the environment? Options:","choices":{"A":"It creates more trash,","B":"The group earns money and the items get recycled,","C":"It makes streets dirtier,","D":"It causes more trucks to drive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Bottle drives allow groups to collect money through recycling, ensuring the items are processed properly rather than thrown away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bottle drives are a great way to earn money and help the environment. In a bottle drive, people go to homes and businesses in a community and ask residents to donate bottles and cans.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Why is pooling resources for a yard sale a \"green\" idea? Options: A. It forces people to buy new clothes, B. It keeps usable items from being thrown away, C. It wastes a lot of time, D. It costs too much money","excerpt":"\"Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need. ... If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\"","stem":"Why is pooling resources for a yard sale a \"green\" idea? Options:","choices":{"A":"It forces people to buy new clothes,","B":"It keeps usable items from being thrown away,","C":"It wastes a lot of time,","D":"It costs too much money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By working together to sell old items, people keep them in use and out of the trash, which is better for the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need. ... If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author recommend choosing activities other than shopping? Options: A. Because shopping is not allowed, B. Because shopping often leads to buying things we don\u0027t need, C. Because gardening is too hard, D. Because shopping is very cheap","excerpt":"\"Some people think of shopping as a fun, leisure activity or as a hobby. ... Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste.\"","stem":"Why does the author recommend choosing activities other than shopping? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because shopping is not allowed,","B":"Because shopping often leads to buying things we don\u0027t need,","C":"Because gardening is too hard,","D":"Because shopping is very cheap"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author suggests that when shopping is treated as a hobby, people are more likely to buy unnecessary things, so choosing other activities reduces that waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some people think of shopping as a fun, leisure activity or as a hobby. ... Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Why might someone use vermiculture? A. because they have too many worms B. because they live in an apartment and cannot compost outdoors C. because worms are pets D. because outdoor composting is too easy","excerpt":"\"In many cases, people who wish to compost indoors use vermiculture. Vermiculture uses a colony of worms, such as earthworms, to break down food that would otherwise be wasted.\"","stem":"Why might someone use vermiculture?","choices":{"A":"because they have too many worms","B":"because they live in an apartment and cannot compost outdoors","C":"because worms are pets","D":"because outdoor composting is too easy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says not everyone can compost outdoors. People in apartments might not have outdoor space. Vermiculture lets them compost indoors using worms.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In many cases, people who wish to compost indoors use vermiculture. Vermiculture uses a colony of worms, such as earthworms, to break down food that would otherwise be wasted.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q006","read_aloud":"Why does the author mention Nick Winnick\u0027s other books? A. to prove that Winnick only writes about waste B. to show that Winnick has experience writing about environmental topics C. to make the text longer D. to describe animals","excerpt":"\"Nick Winnick has published books about a variety of topics, including animals, seasons, and green living. In the Being Green series, Winnick gives readers tips about forming eco-friendly habits.\"","stem":"Why does the author mention Nick Winnick\u0027s other books?","choices":{"A":"to prove that Winnick only writes about waste","B":"to show that Winnick has experience writing about environmental topics","C":"to make the text longer","D":"to describe animals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mentioning the Being Green series shows that Winnick has written about eco-friendly topics before. This helps readers trust his advice because he has experience with green living.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Nick Winnick has published books about a variety of topics, including animals, seasons, and green living. In the Being Green series, Winnick gives readers tips about forming eco-friendly habits.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q007","read_aloud":"Why is improving insulation both a financial and environmental decision? A. because it costs a lot of money and wastes energy B. because it saves money on heating and uses less energy C. because it makes the house look bigger D. because it requires more fossil fuels","excerpt":"\"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\"","stem":"Why is improving insulation both a financial and environmental decision?","choices":{"A":"because it costs a lot of money and wastes energy","B":"because it saves money on heating and uses less energy","C":"because it makes the house look bigger","D":"because it requires more fossil fuels"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer. This means less energy and less money is needed for heating. It helps both the environment and the family\u0027s budget.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why does putting a brick in the toilet tank save water? A. because bricks make water cleaner B. because the tank holds less water, so less is used with each flush C. because bricks are heavy D. because toilets need bricks to work","excerpt":"\"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\"","stem":"Why does putting a brick in the toilet tank save water?","choices":{"A":"because bricks make water cleaner","B":"because the tank holds less water, so less is used with each flush","C":"because bricks are heavy","D":"because toilets need bricks to work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The brick takes up space in the tank. This means the tank fills with less water but still works the same. Each flush uses less water, which saves water over time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q009","read_aloud":"How does understanding \"emissions\" help readers understand the author\u0027s main argument? A. it shows that released substances harm the planet and should be reduced B. it proves that all pollution is the same C. it suggests that emissions are helpful for Earth D. it means emissions only affect cars","excerpt":"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution. There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint.","stem":"How does understanding \"emissions\" help readers understand the author\u0027s main argument?","choices":{"A":"it shows that released substances harm the planet and should be reduced","B":"it proves that all pollution is the same","C":"it suggests that emissions are helpful for Earth","D":"it means emissions only affect cars"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Understanding emissions as harmful released substances supports the author\u0027s argument that we should reduce them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution. There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q010","read_aloud":"What is graywater? A. water used for cooking, bathing, cleaning, and laundry B. water that comes from rain only C. water that is safe to drink D. water found only in oceans","excerpt":"Reuse Graywater. There are three major \u0027types\u0027 of water in a modern home. They are drinking water, waste disposal water, and the water used for cooking, bathing, cleaning, and laundry, which is called graywater. Most of the water used in any home will become graywater.","stem":"What is graywater?","choices":{"A":"water used for cooking, bathing, cleaning, and laundry","B":"water that comes from rain only","C":"water that is safe to drink","D":"water found only in oceans"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines graywater as water used for household tasks like bathing and cleaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Reuse Graywater. There are three major \u0027types\u0027 of water in a modern home. They are drinking water, waste disposal water, and the water used for cooking, bathing, cleaning, and laundry, which is called graywater. Most of the water used in any home will become graywater."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What are two ways to collect rainwater mentioned in the text? A. draining gutters into a bucket or using a filtered pump system B. buying bottled water or digging a well C. using a hose or turning on sprinklers D. boiling water or freezing it for later","excerpt":"Collect Rainwater. Many homes supplement their water intake by collecting rainwater. This can be as simple as draining your home\u0027s gutters into a bucket for watering the garden, or as sophisticated as a system that filters and pumps water into the home.","stem":"What are two ways to collect rainwater mentioned in the text?","choices":{"A":"draining gutters into a bucket or using a filtered pump system","B":"buying bottled water or digging a well","C":"using a hose or turning on sprinklers","D":"boiling water or freezing it for later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes both simple bucket collection and sophisticated filtered systems for rainwater.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Collect Rainwater. Many homes supplement their water intake by collecting rainwater. This can be as simple as draining your home\u0027s gutters into a bucket for watering the garden, or as sophisticated as a system that filters and pumps water into the home."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q012","read_aloud":"If your family has an older toilet, what could you do based on this text? A. place a sealed container of water in the tank to use less water per flush B. flush the toilet more often to save water C. stop using the toilet completely D. replace all pipes in the house","excerpt":"Modify Toilets. A great deal of the water used in any home is flushed down the toilet. However, there are ways to reduce the amount of water lost down the drain in your home. New low-flush toilets use much less water than older models, and many have an option to flush with more water when needed.","stem":"If your family has an older toilet, what could you do based on this text?","choices":{"A":"place a sealed container of water in the tank to use less water per flush","B":"flush the toilet more often to save water","C":"stop using the toilet completely","D":"replace all pipes in the house"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This applies the text\u0027s tip about placing a container in the toilet tank to reduce water use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Modify Toilets. A great deal of the water used in any home is flushed down the toilet. However, there are ways to reduce the amount of water lost down the drain in your home. New low-flush toilets use much less water than older models, and many have an option to flush with more water when needed."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q013","read_aloud":"How does composting connect to the author\u0027s overall message about reducing waste? A. it shows how food scraps can become useful instead of being wasted B. it proves that all food should be thrown away C. it suggests that composting creates more waste D. it shows that only professionals can compost","excerpt":"Use Compost Containers. Fungi and bacteria can cause food to spoil. Most of the time, this spoiled food is thrown away. However, keeping some types of food in a special container can turn it into compost. Most composting is done outdoors. In addition to spoiled food, people put garden trimmings and parts of food that cannot be eaten, such as cornhusks and eggshells, into a container in their garden.","stem":"How does composting connect to the author\u0027s overall message about reducing waste?","choices":{"A":"it shows how food scraps can become useful instead of being wasted","B":"it proves that all food should be thrown away","C":"it suggests that composting creates more waste","D":"it shows that only professionals can compost"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text presents composting as a way to turn food scraps into something useful, supporting the message to reduce waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Use Compost Containers. Fungi and bacteria can cause food to spoil. Most of the time, this spoiled food is thrown away. However, keeping some types of food in a special container can turn it into compost. Most composting is done outdoors. In addition to spoiled food, people put garden trimmings and parts of food that cannot be eaten, such as cornhusks and eggshells, into a container in their garden."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q014","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for excessive? A. too little B. too much C. just right D. none","excerpt":"\"Excessive waste is a problem. Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for excessive?","choices":{"A":"too little","B":"too much","C":"just right","D":"none"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Excessive means more than necessary, or too much.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Excessive waste is a problem. Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q015","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s claim? A. Reducing waste is difficult. B. Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways to help the environment. C. Only adults can reduce waste. D. Reducing waste does not help.","excerpt":"\"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s claim?","choices":{"A":"Reducing waste is difficult.","B":"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways to help the environment.","C":"Only adults can reduce waste.","D":"Reducing waste does not help."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author states this claim directly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q016","read_aloud":"How do the photographs help the reader? A. They show what the items look like and make the tips easier to understand. B. They are only for decoration. C. They replace the need to read the text. D. They make the text longer.","excerpt":"The text includes photographs of a light bulb, a power strip, a rain barrel, a lowflush toilet, and a compost bucket.","stem":"How do the photographs help the reader?","choices":{"A":"They show what the items look like and make the tips easier to understand.","B":"They are only for decoration.","C":"They replace the need to read the text.","D":"They make the text longer."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Visuals help readers understand the suggested items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes photographs of a light bulb, a power strip, a rain barrel, a lowflush toilet, and a compost bucket."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Why is it important to know about graywater? A. Because it can be reused for purposes like watering plants instead of being wasted. B. Because it is dangerous to drink. C. Because it is the only type of water in a home. D. Because it cannot be saved.","excerpt":"\"There are three major \u0027types\u0027 of water in a modern home. They are drinking water, waste disposal water, and the water used for cooking, bathing, cleaning, and laundry, which is called graywater.\"","stem":"Why is it important to know about graywater?","choices":{"A":"Because it can be reused for purposes like watering plants instead of being wasted.","B":"Because it is dangerous to drink.","C":"Because it is the only type of water in a home.","D":"Because it cannot be saved."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Reusing graywater reduces water waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There are three major \u0027types\u0027 of water in a modern home. They are drinking water, waste disposal water, and the water used for cooking, bathing, cleaning, and laundry, which is called graywater.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q018","read_aloud":"Do you agree with this statement? Why? A. No, because only factories can reduce waste. B. Yes, because individuals can make many small changes that add up to big effects. C. No, because it is impossible to reduce waste. D. Yes, but only if you have a lot of money.","excerpt":"\"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands.\"","stem":"Do you agree with this statement? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because only factories can reduce waste.","B":"Yes, because individuals can make many small changes that add up to big effects.","C":"No, because it is impossible to reduce waste.","D":"Yes, but only if you have a lot of money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists many individual actions that reduce waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Which word from the text means \"substances released into the air\"? A. Garbage B. Emissions C. Trash D. Resources","excerpt":"\"This growing mountain of garbage and trash represents not only an attitude of indifference toward valuable natural resources, but also a serious economic and public health problem.\"","stem":"Which word from the text means \"substances released into the air\"?","choices":{"A":"Garbage","B":"Emissions","C":"Trash","D":"Resources"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Emissions are substances released into the air, like pollution.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This growing mountain of garbage and trash represents not only an attitude of indifference toward valuable natural resources, but also a serious economic and public health problem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q020","read_aloud":"What is compost made of? A. Plastic and metal B. Spoiled food and plant trimmings C. Glass and paper D. Old clothes","excerpt":"\"Keeping some types of food in a special container can turn it into compost.\"","stem":"What is compost made of?","choices":{"A":"Plastic and metal","B":"Spoiled food and plant trimmings","C":"Glass and paper","D":"Old clothes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Compost is made from spoiled food, garden trimmings, and other natural waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Keeping some types of food in a special container can turn it into compost.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Why is compost good for plants? A. It looks like soil and helps them grow. B. It smells very good. C. It keeps bugs away. D. It is free.","excerpt":"\"As these materials break down, they turn into a soil-like material that is helpful to plants.\"","stem":"Why is compost good for plants?","choices":{"A":"It looks like soil and helps them grow.","B":"It smells very good.","C":"It keeps bugs away.","D":"It is free."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Compost becomes a soil-like material that acts as fertilizer for plants.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As these materials break down, they turn into a soil-like material that is helpful to plants.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What items should not be put in a compost pile? A. Leaves and grass B. Apple cores and banana peels C. Meat and cheese D. Corn husks and eggshells","excerpt":"\"Keep in mind that meat and dairy products cannot be composted.\"","stem":"What items should not be put in a compost pile?","choices":{"A":"Leaves and grass","B":"Apple cores and banana peels","C":"Meat and cheese","D":"Corn husks and eggshells"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says meat and dairy products cannot be composted.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Keep in mind that meat and dairy products cannot be composted.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q023","read_aloud":"What is one challenge of vermiculture? A. The worms are expensive. B. The worms need specific heat and moisture. C. The worms eat too much. D. The worms are dangerous.","excerpt":"\"Vermiculture can be difficult to use because the worms\u0027 habitat must be kept at a certain temperature and humidity level.\"","stem":"What is one challenge of vermiculture?","choices":{"A":"The worms are expensive.","B":"The worms need specific heat and moisture.","C":"The worms eat too much.","D":"The worms are dangerous."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Vermiculture can be difficult because the worms need a specific temperature and humidity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Vermiculture can be difficult to use because the worms\u0027 habitat must be kept at a certain temperature and humidity level.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l06-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is \u0027caulking\u0027? Options: A. A type of paint for walls, B. A material used to seal gaps and prevent air leaks, C. A tool for cutting wood, D. A type of light bulb","excerpt":"\"Sources of heat loss can be sealed with foam, caulking, or weatherstripping.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is \u0027caulking\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"A type of paint for walls,","B":"A material used to seal gaps and prevent air leaks,","C":"A tool for cutting wood,","D":"A type of light bulb"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions caulking as a way to seal heat loss, which indicates it is a sealing material used for gaps.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sources of heat loss can be sealed with foam, caulking, or weatherstripping.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q002","read_aloud":"What does the ENERGY STAR logo tell a shopper? Options: A. The product is very expensive, B. The product uses less energy than similar products, C. The product is made of glass, D. The product is only for schools","excerpt":"\"When your family is buying a new appliance, look for the ENERGY STAR logo. This logo identifies products that have been certified by the U. S. Environmental Protection Agency to be energy-efficient.\"","stem":"What does the ENERGY STAR logo tell a shopper? Options:","choices":{"A":"The product is very expensive,","B":"The product uses less energy than similar products,","C":"The product is made of glass,","D":"The product is only for schools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that the logo marks products that have been certified to be energy-efficient.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When your family is buying a new appliance, look for the ENERGY STAR logo. This logo identifies products that have been certified by the U. S. Environmental Protection Agency to be energy-efficient.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What is the benefit of replacing old bulbs with CFLs? Options: A. They are very bright, B. They save electricity and money, C. They make the air smell better, D. They are made of cardboard","excerpt":"\"Replacing older incandescent bulbs... with CFLs, which are very energy efficient, will reduce your family\u0027s electric bill.\"","stem":"What is the benefit of replacing old bulbs with CFLs? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are very bright,","B":"They save electricity and money,","C":"They make the air smell better,","D":"They are made of cardboard"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says that using CFLs instead of older bulbs reduces the family\u0027s electric bill.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Replacing older incandescent bulbs... with CFLs, which are very energy efficient, will reduce your family\u0027s electric bill.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How does the author use this statistic to support the argument for changing light bulbs? Options: A. To show that it is a very big, important change, B. To say that it is too hard to do, C. To show that light bulbs are dangerous, D. To say that 5 billion tons is a small number","excerpt":"\"If everyone in the United States made this change [to CFLs], the reduced need for electricity could mean that more than 5 billion tons of greenhouse gases would not enter the atmosphere.\"","stem":"How does the author use this statistic to support the argument for changing light bulbs? Options:","choices":{"A":"To show that it is a very big, important change,","B":"To say that it is too hard to do,","C":"To show that light bulbs are dangerous,","D":"To say that 5 billion tons is a small number"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The huge amount of gas saved shows the massive positive impact that a simple change in light bulbs can have on the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If everyone in the United States made this change [to CFLs], the reduced need for electricity could mean that more than 5 billion tons of greenhouse gases would not enter the atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the author call this one of the \"smartest\" decisions a family can make? Options: A. Because it saves both money and helps the environment, B. Because it makes the house look beautiful, C. Because it is only for rich people, D. Because it is a very easy, one-minute task","excerpt":"\"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\"","stem":"Why does the author call this one of the \"smartest\" decisions a family can make? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because it saves both money and helps the environment,","B":"Because it makes the house look beautiful,","C":"Because it is only for rich people,","D":"Because it is a very easy, one-minute task"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author highlights both financial savings and environmental protection, making it a very high-value choice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q006","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"innovative\" the same way as the excerpt? A. The innovative student found a new way to solve the math problem. B. The innovative rock sat in the garden. C. She innovative her lunch by eating it. D. The innovative cat slept all day.","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"innovative\" the same way as the excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The innovative student found a new way to solve the math problem.","B":"The innovative rock sat in the garden.","C":"She innovative her lunch by eating it.","D":"The innovative cat slept all day."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"In the excerpt, \"innovative\" means creative and using new ideas. A student finding a new way to solve a problem is also being creative. The other choices do not use \"innovative\" correctly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q007","read_aloud":"If everyone in your family switched to energy-efficient bulbs, what would likely happen? A. Your electricity bill would go up. B. You would use less electricity and the bulbs would last longer. C. The house would be darker. D. You would need to buy bulbs more often.","excerpt":"\"Energy-efficient light bulbs... give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\"","stem":"If everyone in your family switched to energy-efficient bulbs, what would likely happen?","choices":{"A":"Your electricity bill would go up.","B":"You would use less electricity and the bulbs would last longer.","C":"The house would be darker.","D":"You would need to buy bulbs more often."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says energy-efficient bulbs use less electricity and last longer. If your family switched, you would likely save electricity and replace bulbs less often.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Energy-efficient light bulbs... give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the number 5 billion tons? A. to make the text longer B. to show how much one small change can help on a large scale C. to prove that light bulbs are heavy D. to describe the weight of garbage","excerpt":"\"Replacing older incandescent bulbs with CFLs... If everyone in the United States made this change, the reduced need for electricity could mean that more than 5 billion tons of greenhouse gases would not enter the atmosphere.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the number 5 billion tons?","choices":{"A":"to make the text longer","B":"to show how much one small change can help on a large scale","C":"to prove that light bulbs are heavy","D":"to describe the weight of garbage"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"5 billion tons is an enormous number. The author uses it to show that if many people make a small change, the total effect is huge. This helps readers see that their actions matter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Replacing older incandescent bulbs with CFLs... If everyone in the United States made this change, the reduced need for electricity could mean that more than 5 billion tons of greenhouse gases would not enter the atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q009","read_aloud":"How does the word \"underlie\" connect to the idea that small actions matter? A. it suggests that small actions form the foundation for bigger changes B. it means that only big actions can make a difference C. it shows that waste cannot be reduced D. it suggests that changes happen without any effort","excerpt":"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways.","stem":"How does the word \"underlie\" connect to the idea that small actions matter?","choices":{"A":"it suggests that small actions form the foundation for bigger changes","B":"it means that only big actions can make a difference","C":"it shows that waste cannot be reduced","D":"it suggests that changes happen without any effort"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Underlie means to form a foundation. The text shows that small personal changes form the foundation for larger environmental benefits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q010","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use to explain composting for others? A. problem and solution: no garden but know someone who does B. chronological order of composting steps C. compare and contrast of different compost types D. cause and effect of composting on weather","excerpt":"Make Compost for Others. Many people do not have gardens, but almost everyone knows someone who does. If you do not have a use for compost at your home, ask your friends and family to see if anyone would like extra compost. Many gardeners would be happy for the help, and you could use some of your home\u0027s waste to make compost for them.","stem":"What text structure does the author use to explain composting for others?","choices":{"A":"problem and solution: no garden but know someone who does","B":"chronological order of composting steps","C":"compare and contrast of different compost types","D":"cause and effect of composting on weather"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author presents the problem (no garden) and solution (share compost with someone who gardens).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Make Compost for Others. Many people do not have gardens, but almost everyone knows someone who does. If you do not have a use for compost at your home, ask your friends and family to see if anyone would like extra compost. Many gardeners would be happy for the help, and you could use some of your home\u0027s waste to make compost for them."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What can you infer about vermiculture from this passage? A. it is a composting option for people without outdoor space B. it only works in very cold climates C. it requires a large garden to be effective D. it is more expensive than outdoor composting","excerpt":"Try Vermiculture. Not everyone can compost outdoors. People who live in apartments, for example, might not have this option. In many cases, people who wish to compost indoors use vermiculture. Vermiculture uses a colony of worms, such as earthworms, to break down food that would otherwise be wasted.","stem":"What can you infer about vermiculture from this passage?","choices":{"A":"it is a composting option for people without outdoor space","B":"it only works in very cold climates","C":"it requires a large garden to be effective","D":"it is more expensive than outdoor composting"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states vermiculture is for people who cannot compost outdoors, like apartment dwellers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Try Vermiculture. Not everyone can compost outdoors. People who live in apartments, for example, might not have this option. In many cases, people who wish to compost indoors use vermiculture. Vermiculture uses a colony of worms, such as earthworms, to break down food that would otherwise be wasted."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q012","read_aloud":"If you have a few items to sell but not enough for your own yard sale, what could you do? A. join with friends or neighbors to hold a sale together B. throw the items away immediately C. keep the items forever even if you do not need them D. buy more items to have a bigger sale","excerpt":"Pool Resources. One of the greenest ways to help your community is to keep items from being wasted in the first place. Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need. You may not have enough to hold a yard sale of your own, but perhaps you can hold one with friends or neighbors.","stem":"If you have a few items to sell but not enough for your own yard sale, what could you do?","choices":{"A":"join with friends or neighbors to hold a sale together","B":"throw the items away immediately","C":"keep the items forever even if you do not need them","D":"buy more items to have a bigger sale"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This applies the text\u0027s suggestion to pool resources with others when you do not have enough for your own sale.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pool Resources. One of the greenest ways to help your community is to keep items from being wasted in the first place. Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need. You may not have enough to hold a yard sale of your own, but perhaps you can hold one with friends or neighbors."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q013","read_aloud":"How does the bottle drive example support the author\u0027s purpose for writing this text? A. it shows a practical way individuals can earn money while helping the environment B. it proves that recycling is too difficult for most people C. it suggests that only states with bottle laws can reduce waste D. it shows that earning money is more important than helping Earth","excerpt":"Hold Bottle Drives. In some states, people may receive money for turning in empty bottles and cans for recycling. The payment is 5 or 10 cents per can or bottle, which will add up over time. Bottle drives are a great way to earn money and help the environment.","stem":"How does the bottle drive example support the author\u0027s purpose for writing this text?","choices":{"A":"it shows a practical way individuals can earn money while helping the environment","B":"it proves that recycling is too difficult for most people","C":"it suggests that only states with bottle laws can reduce waste","D":"it shows that earning money is more important than helping Earth"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The bottle drive example supports the author\u0027s persuasive purpose by showing a practical, rewarding way to reduce waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Hold Bottle Drives. In some states, people may receive money for turning in empty bottles and cans for recycling. The payment is 5 or 10 cents per can or bottle, which will add up over time. Bottle drives are a great way to earn money and help the environment."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q014","read_aloud":"How are lowflush toilets and the brick trick similar? A. Both use more water. B. Both reduce the amount of water used per flush. C. Both are expensive. D. Both require a plumber.","excerpt":"\"New lowflush toilets use much less water than older models, and many have an option to flush with more water when needed. If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank … and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\"","stem":"How are lowflush toilets and the brick trick similar?","choices":{"A":"Both use more water.","B":"Both reduce the amount of water used per flush.","C":"Both are expensive.","D":"Both require a plumber."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both methods reduce water use per flush.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"New lowflush toilets use much less water than older models, and many have an option to flush with more water when needed. If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank … and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s purpose in mentioning this challenge? A. To discourage readers from trying to reduce waste B. To introduce composting as a solution for food waste C. To say that food waste cannot be reduced D. To argue that recycling is useless","excerpt":"\"Some types of waste can be harder to reduce than others. You cannot add spoiled food or old teabags to a recycling bin.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s purpose in mentioning this challenge?","choices":{"A":"To discourage readers from trying to reduce waste","B":"To introduce composting as a solution for food waste","C":"To say that food waste cannot be reduced","D":"To argue that recycling is useless"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The next sections discuss composting as a solution.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some types of waste can be harder to reduce than others. You cannot add spoiled food or old teabags to a recycling bin.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q016","read_aloud":"Why is a bottle drive a good way to help the environment and the community? A. It only helps the environment. B. It reduces waste by recycling bottles and cans and also raises money for good causes. C. It creates more waste. D. It is only for businesses.","excerpt":"\"In a bottle drive, people go to homes and businesses in a community and ask residents to donate bottles and cans. Many groups, such as sports teams and charity organizations, use this method to earn money for their activities.\"","stem":"Why is a bottle drive a good way to help the environment and the community?","choices":{"A":"It only helps the environment.","B":"It reduces waste by recycling bottles and cans and also raises money for good causes.","C":"It creates more waste.","D":"It is only for businesses."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It recycles waste and raises money for community groups.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a bottle drive, people go to homes and businesses in a community and ask residents to donate bottles and cans. Many groups, such as sports teams and charity organizations, use this method to earn money for their activities.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q017","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses excessive correctly? A. The excessive rain flooded the streets. B. The excessive boy walked to school. C. She drank an excessive amount of air. D. He made an excessive sound.","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses excessive correctly?","choices":{"A":"The excessive rain flooded the streets.","B":"The excessive boy walked to school.","C":"She drank an excessive amount of air.","D":"He made an excessive sound."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Excessive means too much. Flooding streets shows too much rain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q018","read_aloud":"What happens during a bottle drive? A. People throw bottles in the trash. B. People buy new bottles. C. People collect bottles to recycle them. D. People break bottles.","excerpt":"\"In a bottle drive, people go to homes and businesses in a community and ask residents to donate bottles and cans.\"","stem":"What happens during a bottle drive?","choices":{"A":"People throw bottles in the trash.","B":"People buy new bottles.","C":"People collect bottles to recycle them.","D":"People break bottles."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"During a bottle drive, people collect bottles and cans to recycle them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a bottle drive, people go to homes and businesses in a community and ask residents to donate bottles and cans.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Why might you hold a yard sale with friends? A. To buy new clothes B. To sell more items together C. To clean your house D. To meet new people","excerpt":"\"Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need. You may not have enough to hold a yard sale of your own, but perhaps you can hold one with friends or neighbors.\"","stem":"Why might you hold a yard sale with friends?","choices":{"A":"To buy new clothes","B":"To sell more items together","C":"To clean your house","D":"To meet new people"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pooling resources means you have more items to sell, which is better than having a sale alone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need. You may not have enough to hold a yard sale of your own, but perhaps you can hold one with friends or neighbors.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q020","read_aloud":"What are three benefits of pooling resources for a yard sale? A. Earning money, helping others, and reducing waste B. Buying new things, driving cars, and eating food C. Recycling plastic, glass, and paper D. Saving water, energy, and gas","excerpt":"\"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\"","stem":"What are three benefits of pooling resources for a yard sale?","choices":{"A":"Earning money, helping others, and reducing waste","B":"Buying new things, driving cars, and eating food","C":"Recycling plastic, glass, and paper","D":"Saving water, energy, and gas"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text lists earning money, providing items to others, and keeping items out of the trash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q021","read_aloud":"How does a bottle drive help the environment? A. It creates new glass. B. It keeps bottles out of landfills. C. It cleans the streets. D. It saves electricity.","excerpt":"\"Bottle drives are a great way to earn money and help the environment.\"","stem":"How does a bottle drive help the environment?","choices":{"A":"It creates new glass.","B":"It keeps bottles out of landfills.","C":"It cleans the streets.","D":"It saves electricity."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Collecting bottles ensures they 2/2 complete please Thought Process","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bottle drives are a great way to earn money and help the environment.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q022","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q023","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q024","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Before buying food B. Before throwing an item away C. After you buy something new D. When you are at school","excerpt":"\"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Before buying food","B":"Before throwing an item away","C":"After you buy something new","D":"When you are at school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests asking these questions when you are thinking about throwing an item away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l07-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Plastic items can only be used once. B. Plastic items are very expensive. C. You can find new uses for disposable items. D. You should buy new plastic items.","excerpt":"\"Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Plastic items can only be used once.","B":"Plastic items are very expensive.","C":"You can find new uses for disposable items.","D":"You should buy new plastic items."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The paragraph gives examples of how to reuse plastic items instead of throwing them away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What are \u0027green contractors\u0027? Options: A. People who only paint houses green, B. Builders who specialize in eco-friendly construction, C. People who only build parks, D. People who don\u0027t know how to build","excerpt":"\"Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies. Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems and other technologies.\"","stem":"What are \u0027green contractors\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"People who only paint houses green,","B":"Builders who specialize in eco-friendly construction,","C":"People who only build parks,","D":"People who don\u0027t know how to build"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines them as builders who use eco-friendly products and technologies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies. Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems and other technologies.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main point of debate described in paragraph 49? Options: A. Whether we should recycle at all, B. Whether cities should pay for door-to-door recycling pickup, C. Whether we should stop building trucks, D. Whether taxpayers have enough money","excerpt":"\"Should a city\u0027s taxpayers, for instance, pay for door-to-door collection of recyclable materials? Should the city save that money and depend on people to drop off recyclable materials on their own?\"","stem":"What is the main point of debate described in paragraph 49? Options:","choices":{"A":"Whether we should recycle at all,","B":"Whether cities should pay for door-to-door recycling pickup,","C":"Whether we should stop building trucks,","D":"Whether taxpayers have enough money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the debate is specifically about funding methods for recycling collection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Should a city\u0027s taxpayers, for instance, pay for door-to-door collection of recyclable materials? Should the city save that money and depend on people to drop off recyclable materials on their own?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q003","read_aloud":"What is one \"Pro\" or positive reason for door-to-door recycling? Options: A. It makes the streets louder, B. It encourages more people to recycle, C. It makes taxes go down, D. It is unattractive","excerpt":"\"PROS: 1. Much less potentially recyclable material will be sent to landfills. 2. Easier participation will encourage more people to take part...\"","stem":"What is one \"Pro\" or positive reason for door-to-door recycling? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the streets louder,","B":"It encourages more people to recycle,","C":"It makes taxes go down,","D":"It is unattractive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that easier participation will encourage more people to take part in local recycling.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"PROS: 1. Much less potentially recyclable material will be sent to landfills. 2. Easier participation will encourage more people to take part...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think the author presents a fair debate? Why? Options: A. No, because he only talks about the pros, B. Yes, because he lists both the benefits and the costs/concerns for the city, C. No, because he hates trucks, D. Yes, because he says taxes should always go up","excerpt":"\"CONS: 1. Door-to-door collection will increase taxes for property owners. ... 2. There is an additional environmental cost in the form of more large trucks on the city\u0027s streets.\"","stem":"Do you think the author presents a fair debate? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, because he only talks about the pros,","B":"Yes, because he lists both the benefits and the costs/concerns for the city,","C":"No, because he hates trucks,","D":"Yes, because he says taxes should always go up"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By providing a list of pros and cons, the author shows both sides of the issue so the reader can decide.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"CONS: 1. Door-to-door collection will increase taxes for property owners. ... 2. There is an additional environmental cost in the form of more large trucks on the city\u0027s streets.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Imagine you are a city leader. Which of these two concerns would be harder to solve? Options: A. Taxes, because they are easy to change whenever you want, B. The trucks, because you need them to pick up the materials, C. Neither is a problem, D. Taxes are not a concern","excerpt":"\"Door-to-door collection will increase taxes for property owners. ... There is an additional environmental cost in the form of more large trucks on the city\u0027s streets.\"","stem":"Imagine you are a city leader. Which of these two concerns would be harder to solve? Options:","choices":{"A":"Taxes, because they are easy to change whenever you want,","B":"The trucks, because you need them to pick up the materials,","C":"Neither is a problem,","D":"Taxes are not a concern"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Solving the environmental cost of the trucks is difficult because the trucks are required for the service, making this a complex trade-off.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Door-to-door collection will increase taxes for property owners. ... There is an additional environmental cost in the form of more large trucks on the city\u0027s streets.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q006","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"emissions\"? A. releases B. absorptions C. gases D. pollutants","excerpt":"\"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"emissions\"?","choices":{"A":"releases","B":"absorptions","C":"gases","D":"pollutants"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Emissions\" means substances released or given off. The opposite would be absorptions, which means taking in rather than releasing. Emissions put things out; absorptions take things in.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why might the author use the word \"tips\" instead of \"rules\"? A. because tips are suggestions, which feel friendlier and easier to follow than strict rules B. because rules are not real C. because tips are harder to understand D. because the author does not care about the environment","excerpt":"\"Nick Winnick gives readers tips about forming eco-friendly habits.\"","stem":"Why might the author use the word \"tips\" instead of \"rules\"?","choices":{"A":"because tips are suggestions, which feel friendlier and easier to follow than strict rules","B":"because rules are not real","C":"because tips are harder to understand","D":"because the author does not care about the environment"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Tips\" sounds friendly and optional. \"Rules\" sounds strict and demanding. The author wants to persuade readers, not boss them around. Using \"tips\" makes the advice feel more welcoming and doable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Nick Winnick gives readers tips about forming eco-friendly habits.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author say reducing is the most important of the three Rs? A. because reducing comes first in the list B. because if you reduce waste, there is less to reuse and recycle C. because reusing and recycling do not matter D. because reducing is the easiest","excerpt":"\"Think about all the times that you have heard people refer to the \u0027Three Rs.\u0027 The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\"","stem":"Why does the author say reducing is the most important of the three Rs?","choices":{"A":"because reducing comes first in the list","B":"because if you reduce waste, there is less to reuse and recycle","C":"because reusing and recycling do not matter","D":"because reducing is the easiest"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author emphasizes reducing because it stops waste before it happens. If you buy less and create less waste, you have less to deal with later. Reducing is the first and most effective step.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Think about all the times that you have heard people refer to the \u0027Three Rs.\u0027 The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q009","read_aloud":"If more people grew their own food, how might communities change? A. There would be more packaging waste. B. There would be less packaging waste and people might eat healthier food. C. People would stop buying all food. D. Gardens would replace all stores.","excerpt":"\"Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.\"","stem":"If more people grew their own food, how might communities change?","choices":{"A":"There would be more packaging waste.","B":"There would be less packaging waste and people might eat healthier food.","C":"People would stop buying all food.","D":"Gardens would replace all stores."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Growing your own food means less packaging from stores. The text also mentions that foods with less packaging are often more healthful. Communities might have less waste and healthier eating habits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q010","read_aloud":"How does understanding \"watt\" help readers make informed choices about light bulbs? A. it helps them compare how much energy different bulbs use B. it helps them choose the brightest bulb only C. it helps them pick the cheapest bulb regardless of energy use D. it helps them avoid using any light bulbs","excerpt":"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb.","stem":"How does understanding \"watt\" help readers make informed choices about light bulbs?","choices":{"A":"it helps them compare how much energy different bulbs use","B":"it helps them choose the brightest bulb only","C":"it helps them pick the cheapest bulb regardless of energy use","D":"it helps them avoid using any light bulbs"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Understanding watts as a measure of energy use helps readers compare bulbs and choose efficient ones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q011","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about using the Web for waste reduction? A. online platforms can help people exchange items and keep them out of landfills B. the Web is only useful for buying new products C. online sites create more waste than they reduce D. only nonprofits can use the Web for waste reduction","excerpt":"Go Online. The Web can be a great resource for waste reduction. The Freecycle Network is a nonprofit group devoted to exchanging free items and keeping objects out of landfills. Some community sites have free classified sections where people can list items that they no longer need.","stem":"What is the main idea about using the Web for waste reduction?","choices":{"A":"online platforms can help people exchange items and keep them out of landfills","B":"the Web is only useful for buying new products","C":"online sites create more waste than they reduce","D":"only nonprofits can use the Web for waste reduction"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The passage\u0027s main idea is that websites like Freecycle help people exchange items instead of wasting them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Go Online. The Web can be a great resource for waste reduction. The Freecycle Network is a nonprofit group devoted to exchanging free items and keeping objects out of landfills. Some community sites have free classified sections where people can list items that they no longer need."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q012","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use in this section? A. problem and solution: air leaks cause heat loss, sealing fixes it B. chronological order of home building C. compare and contrast of different house types D. cause and effect of weather on homes","excerpt":"10 Ways to Make Your Home Green. Stop Air Leaks. Heat is lost very quickly through air leaks. Windows, doors, light switches, and electrical outlets may be letting warm air escape. This means that more energy has to be used to heat the house. Sources of heat loss can be sealed with foam, caulking, or weatherstripping.","stem":"What text structure does the author use in this section?","choices":{"A":"problem and solution: air leaks cause heat loss, sealing fixes it","B":"chronological order of home building","C":"compare and contrast of different house types","D":"cause and effect of weather on homes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author presents the problem (air leaks waste heat) and solution (seal leaks with foam, caulking, or weatherstripping).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: 10 Ways to Make Your Home Green. Stop Air Leaks. Heat is lost very quickly through air leaks. Windows, doors, light switches, and electrical outlets may be letting warm air escape. This means that more energy has to be used to heat the house. Sources of heat loss can be sealed with foam, caulking, or weatherstripping."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q013","read_aloud":"- David Suzuki, biologist and environmentalistDo you think the author includes this quotation effectively to support the argument? Why or why not? A. yes, because it adds expert authority and connects personal choices to bigger impacts B. no, because quotations should not appear in argumentative texts C. yes, but only if the reader already knows who David Suzuki is D. no, because the quotation is too short to be meaningful","excerpt":"Our personal consumer choices have ecological, social, and spiritual consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.","stem":"- David Suzuki, biologist and environmentalistDo you think the author includes this quotation effectively to support the argument? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because it adds expert authority and connects personal choices to bigger impacts","B":"no, because quotations should not appear in argumentative texts","C":"yes, but only if the reader already knows who David Suzuki is","D":"no, because the quotation is too short to be meaningful"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The quotation from an expert biologist strengthens the argument by linking personal choices to larger consequences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Our personal consumer choices have ecological, social, and spiritual consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q014","read_aloud":"If you wanted to create a new waste-reducing activity for your school, what might you suggest based on this text? A. start a school garden where students grow food to reduce packaging waste B. organize a shopping trip to buy more school supplies C. plan a party with disposable plates and cups D. create a contest to see who can throw away the most","excerpt":"Try a New Activity. Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself.","stem":"If you wanted to create a new waste-reducing activity for your school, what might you suggest based on this text?","choices":{"A":"start a school garden where students grow food to reduce packaging waste","B":"organize a shopping trip to buy more school supplies","C":"plan a party with disposable plates and cups","D":"create a contest to see who can throw away the most"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This creative response applies the text\u0027s idea that growing your own food reduces waste to a school setting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Try a New Activity. Trying a new activity, such as a sport or gardening, can reduce waste. There is very little waste created by a tomato that you have grown yourself."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q015","read_aloud":"How does the word underlie help you understand the quote? A. It shows that our beliefs are the foundation of how we live. B. It means our beliefs are unimportant. C. It means our lifestyles have no foundation. D. It means we should ignore our beliefs.","excerpt":"\"It is time to reexamine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\"","stem":"How does the word underlie help you understand the quote?","choices":{"A":"It shows that our beliefs are the foundation of how we live.","B":"It means our beliefs are unimportant.","C":"It means our lifestyles have no foundation.","D":"It means we should ignore our beliefs."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Underlie means form the foundation of; our beliefs support our actions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is time to reexamine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q016","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s overall message about reducing waste? A. It is too difficult for one person. B. Individuals and communities can take many small actions to reduce waste. C. Only governments can reduce waste. D. Reducing waste is not important.","excerpt":"The text gives tips on reducing waste at home (insulation, CFLs, power strips) and in the community (bottle drives, composting, pooling resources).","stem":"What is the author\u0027s overall message about reducing waste?","choices":{"A":"It is too difficult for one person.","B":"Individuals and communities can take many small actions to reduce waste.","C":"Only governments can reduce waste.","D":"Reducing waste is not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives many examples of individual and community actions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text gives tips on reducing waste at home (insulation, CFLs, power strips) and in the community (bottle drives, composting, pooling resources)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q017","read_aloud":"Is \"pooling resources\" for a yard sale a good idea? Why? A. No, because it is too much work. B. Yes, because it helps multiple families reduce waste, earn money, and share items. C. No, because yard sales are not environmentally friendly. D. Yes, but only if you sell everything.","excerpt":"\"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\"","stem":"Is \"pooling resources\" for a yard sale a good idea? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because it is too much work.","B":"Yes, because it helps multiple families reduce waste, earn money, and share items.","C":"No, because yard sales are not environmentally friendly.","D":"Yes, but only if you sell everything."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists three benefits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Create one new tip for reducing waste that is not already in the text. A. \"Leave all lights on 24 hours a day.\" B. \"Use a reusable water bottle instead of buying plastic bottles.\" C. \"Throw away all your old clothes.\" D. \"Drive everywhere instead of walking.\"","excerpt":"\"Here are 10 simple ways to make a home more efficient.\"","stem":"Create one new tip for reducing waste that is not already in the text.","choices":{"A":"\"Leave all lights on 24 hours a day.\"","B":"\"Use a reusable water bottle instead of buying plastic bottles.\"","C":"\"Throw away all your old clothes.\"","D":"\"Drive everywhere instead of walking.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The tip should reduce waste, such as reusing a bottle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Here are 10 simple ways to make a home more efficient.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for emissions in the context of pollution? A. Releases B. Outputs C. Absorptions D. Gases","excerpt":"\"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for emissions in the context of pollution?","choices":{"A":"Releases","B":"Outputs","C":"Absorptions","D":"Gases"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Emissions are things sent out. Absorptions are things taken in, making them opposites.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q020","read_aloud":"What problem does this sentence solve? A. Losing heat through air leaks B. Paying high water bills C. Buying too many items D. Cleaning the house","excerpt":"\"Sources of heat loss can be sealed with foam, caulking, or weatherstripping.\"","stem":"What problem does this sentence solve?","choices":{"A":"Losing heat through air leaks","B":"Paying high water bills","C":"Buying too many items","D":"Cleaning the house"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says heat is lost through leaks, and sealing them solves this problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sources of heat loss can be sealed with foam, caulking, or weatherstripping.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What materials do green artists use? A. New paint and canvas B. Expensive diamonds C. Recycled materials like glass and fibers D. Rare metals","excerpt":"\"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment. These artists may sculpt with recycled materials, create weavings with recycled fibers, design jewelry made from used glass, or find any other way to create art without harming Earth.\"","stem":"What materials do green artists use?","choices":{"A":"New paint and canvas","B":"Expensive diamonds","C":"Recycled materials like glass and fibers","D":"Rare metals"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists recycled materials like fibers, glass, and used items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment. These artists may sculpt with recycled materials, create weavings with recycled fibers, design jewelry made from used glass, or find any other way to create art without harming Earth.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q022","read_aloud":"Why might someone choose to be a green artist? A. To become rich and famous B. To make art that helps the planet C. To use as much paint as possible D. To throw things away","excerpt":"\"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment.\"","stem":"Why might someone choose to be a green artist?","choices":{"A":"To become rich and famous","B":"To make art that helps the planet","C":"To use as much paint as possible","D":"To throw things away"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Green artists have a passion for the environment and want to create art without harming Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How is a green contractor different from a regular contractor? A. A green contractor builds faster. B. A green contractor uses eco-friendly technologies. C. A green contractor costs less money. D. A regular contractor uses solar panels.","excerpt":"\"Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies.\"","stem":"How is a green contractor different from a regular contractor?","choices":{"A":"A green contractor builds faster.","B":"A green contractor uses eco-friendly technologies.","C":"A green contractor costs less money.","D":"A regular contractor uses solar panels."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Green contractors specialize in products that are good for the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l08-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What does a \u0027green artist\u0027 do? Options: A. Uses recycled materials to create art, B. Only paints trees, C. Does not believe in art, D. Only uses green paint","excerpt":"\"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment. These artists may sculpt with recycled materials...\"","stem":"What does a \u0027green artist\u0027 do? Options:","choices":{"A":"Uses recycled materials to create art,","B":"Only paints trees,","C":"Does not believe in art,","D":"Only uses green paint"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that they use things like recycled fibers or glass to make art without harming the Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment. These artists may sculpt with recycled materials...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q002","read_aloud":"What is a way artists use their work to help the environment? Options: A. By creating fashion from natural fabrics, B. By destroying old clothes, C. By only making paintings, D. By using only new plastic","excerpt":"\"Some green artists work in fashion design, creating clothing from organic cotton and other natural fabrics.\"","stem":"What is a way artists use their work to help the environment? Options:","choices":{"A":"By creating fashion from natural fabrics,","B":"By destroying old clothes,","C":"By only making paintings,","D":"By using only new plastic"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text identifies fashion designers who use natural fabrics as a way to be eco-friendly artists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some green artists work in fashion design, creating clothing from organic cotton and other natural fabrics.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q003","read_aloud":"How do artists contribute to the environment besides making art? Options: A. They teach others about environmental issues, B. They clean the ocean, C. They only work for money, D. They stop other people from making art","excerpt":"\"Many green artists use their work to educate others about various environmental issues.\"","stem":"How do artists contribute to the environment besides making art? Options:","choices":{"A":"They teach others about environmental issues,","B":"They clean the ocean,","C":"They only work for money,","D":"They stop other people from making art"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text notes that these artists use their work as a tool for educating others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many green artists use their work to educate others about various environmental issues.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think art is a good way to teach people about the environment? Why? Options: A. No, art is only for museums, B. Yes, because art can share a message in a way that catches people\u0027s attention, C. No, people only learn from books, D. Yes, because it is always very cheap","excerpt":"\"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment. ... Many green artists use their work to educate others about various environmental issues.\"","stem":"Do you think art is a good way to teach people about the environment? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, art is only for museums,","B":"Yes, because art can share a message in a way that catches people\u0027s attention,","C":"No, people only learn from books,","D":"Yes, because it is always very cheap"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Art can convey emotional and important messages effectively, making it a powerful way to raise awareness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green artists combine their love of art with a passion for the environment. ... Many green artists use their work to educate others about various environmental issues.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q005","read_aloud":"Why might it be better to hire a \"green contractor\" than a regular contractor? Options: A. Because they are only for show, B. Because they know how to make homes more efficient, C. Because regular contractors are never good, D. Because they are always free","excerpt":"\"Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies. ... Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems...\"","stem":"Why might it be better to hire a \"green contractor\" than a regular contractor? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they are only for show,","B":"Because they know how to make homes more efficient,","C":"Because regular contractors are never good,","D":"Because they are always free"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They have the specialized knowledge and skills to install energy-saving systems that a standard builder might not focus on.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies. ... Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q006","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"excessive\" correctly? A. The excessive rain caused flooding in the streets. B. She excessive her homework before dinner. C. The excessive cat slept on the couch. D. He excessive the book by reading it.","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"excessive\" correctly?","choices":{"A":"The excessive rain caused flooding in the streets.","B":"She excessive her homework before dinner.","C":"The excessive cat slept on the couch.","D":"He excessive the book by reading it."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Excessive\" means more than necessary. Too much rain causing flooding is excessive. The other choices do not use \"excessive\" correctly because it is an adjective describing nouns, not a verb.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author call devices \"vampires\" and say you can \"slay\" them? A. to scare readers B. to make saving energy sound fun and memorable C. to prove that devices are alive D. to describe real vampires","excerpt":"\"Cell phone chargers, DVD players, microwave ovens, and coffee makers can be \u0027vampires.\u0027 There are a couple of different ways that you can slay these vampires.\"","stem":"Why does the author call devices \"vampires\" and say you can \"slay\" them?","choices":{"A":"to scare readers","B":"to make saving energy sound fun and memorable","C":"to prove that devices are alive","D":"to describe real vampires"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Vampires suck blood, and these devices suck energy. The comparison makes a boring topic fun and easy to remember. \"Slay\" adds a playful, heroic feeling to saving energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Cell phone chargers, DVD players, microwave ovens, and coffee makers can be \u0027vampires.\u0027 There are a couple of different ways that you can slay these vampires.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author include information about green careers? A. to give readers hope that they can make a difference through their future jobs B. to prove that only adults can help the environment C. to make the text longer D. to describe construction work","excerpt":"\"Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems, and other technologies designed to make homes more energy efficient and environmentally friendly.\"","stem":"Why does the author include information about green careers?","choices":{"A":"to give readers hope that they can make a difference through their future jobs","B":"to prove that only adults can help the environment","C":"to make the text longer","D":"to describe construction work"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Including green careers shows readers that helping the environment can be part of their future. It connects reducing waste to real jobs and gives readers a positive vision for how they can contribute as adults.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems, and other technologies designed to make homes more energy efficient and environmentally friendly.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q009","read_aloud":"- Buckminster Fuller Do you think this quotation is always true? Why or why not? A. Yes, because all pollution can be turned into useful resources. B. No, because some pollution is truly harmful and cannot be safely reused. C. Both a and b can be argued. D. The quotation does not make sense.","excerpt":"Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value.","stem":"- Buckminster Fuller Do you think this quotation is always true? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because all pollution can be turned into useful resources.","B":"No, because some pollution is truly harmful and cannot be safely reused.","C":"Both a and b can be argued.","D":"The quotation does not make sense."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While some waste can be recycled or composted, some pollution is too dangerous to reuse. Toxic chemicals and radioactive waste are harmful to people and the environment. Not all pollution can be safely harvested as a resource.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q010","read_aloud":"If a family forgot to use power strips and never unplugged devices, what might happen? A. They would save a lot of energy. B. They would waste energy and pay more for electricity without realizing it. C. Their devices would break immediately. D. The power company would give them free electricity.","excerpt":"\"The simplest way is to unplug the devices. Many people choose to plug their devices into a power strip or bar.\"","stem":"If a family forgot to use power strips and never unplugged devices, what might happen?","choices":{"A":"They would save a lot of energy.","B":"They would waste energy and pay more for electricity without realizing it.","C":"Their devices would break immediately.","D":"The power company would give them free electricity."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says devices use power whenever plugged in, even when off. Without power strips or unplugging, this \"vampire\" energy would continue. The family would waste energy and pay for electricity they are not actually using.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The simplest way is to unplug the devices. Many people choose to plug their devices into a power strip or bar.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q011","read_aloud":"Which sentence best shows \"innovative\" using context clues? A. people are finding creative new methods to save water B. people are using the same old ways to waste water C. people are ignoring water problems completely D. people are making water use more complicated","excerpt":"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water. Modern homes and businesses can use a great deal of fresh water, and, often, much of this water is wasted.","stem":"Which sentence best shows \"innovative\" using context clues?","choices":{"A":"people are finding creative new methods to save water","B":"people are using the same old ways to waste water","C":"people are ignoring water problems completely","D":"people are making water use more complicated"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context shows people finding \"simple and innovative ways,\" meaning creative new methods to solve water waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water. Modern homes and businesses can use a great deal of fresh water, and, often, much of this water is wasted."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this passage? A. drinkable water is limited, so wasting it is a serious problem B. Earth has unlimited water so waste does not matter C. only businesses waste water, not homes D. drinking water is not important for survival","excerpt":"Ways to Reduce Water Use. Earth may be covered by water, but only a small portion of that water is drinkable. Since all humans must drink water to survive, it is important not to waste this resource. Modern homes and businesses can use a great deal of fresh water, and, often, much of this water is wasted.","stem":"What is the main idea of this passage?","choices":{"A":"drinkable water is limited, so wasting it is a serious problem","B":"Earth has unlimited water so waste does not matter","C":"only businesses waste water, not homes","D":"drinking water is not important for survival"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The passage emphasizes that drinkable water is scarce and wasting it is problematic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Ways to Reduce Water Use. Earth may be covered by water, but only a small portion of that water is drinkable. Since all humans must drink water to survive, it is important not to waste this resource. Modern homes and businesses can use a great deal of fresh water, and, often, much of this water is wasted."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about green contractors from this passage? A. they help make homes more energy efficient and eco-friendly B. they only work on very old buildings C. they avoid using any new technologies D. they focus only on making homes look beautiful","excerpt":"Green Contractor. Career: Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies. Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems, and other technologies designed to make homes more energy efficient and environmentally friendly.","stem":"What can you infer about green contractors from this passage?","choices":{"A":"they help make homes more energy efficient and eco-friendly","B":"they only work on very old buildings","C":"they avoid using any new technologies","D":"they focus only on making homes look beautiful"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes green contractors as specialists in eco-friendly technologies that improve home efficiency.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Green Contractor. Career: Green contractors are builders and tradespeople who specialize in eco-friendly products and technologies. Green contractors install insulation, solar panels, graywater systems, and other technologies designed to make homes more energy efficient and environmentally friendly."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q014","read_aloud":"- Benjamin Franklin, statesman, scientist, inventor, and authorDo you think this quotation is effective in the section about reducing water use? Why or why not? A. yes, because it uses a memorable saying to emphasize water\u0027s value before it is gone B. no, because quotations from historical figures are not relevant today C. yes, but only for readers who already know who Benjamin Franklin was D. no, because the quotation is too long and confusing","excerpt":"When the well is dry, we know the worth of water.","stem":"- Benjamin Franklin, statesman, scientist, inventor, and authorDo you think this quotation is effective in the section about reducing water use? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because it uses a memorable saying to emphasize water\u0027s value before it is gone","B":"no, because quotations from historical figures are not relevant today","C":"yes, but only for readers who already know who Benjamin Franklin was","D":"no, because the quotation is too long and confusing"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Franklin\u0027s quotation effectively uses a well-known saying to highlight the importance of conserving water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When the well is dry, we know the worth of water."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q015","read_aloud":"If you could design a community program to reduce waste, what might it include based on this text? A. a neighborhood item-swap event where people exchange things they no longer need B. a contest to see who can buy the most new items C. a program that encourages throwing away old things quickly D. a service that delivers new products to every home","excerpt":"Pool Resources. One of the greenest ways to help your community is to keep items from being wasted in the first place. Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need.","stem":"If you could design a community program to reduce waste, what might it include based on this text?","choices":{"A":"a neighborhood item-swap event where people exchange things they no longer need","B":"a contest to see who can buy the most new items","C":"a program that encourages throwing away old things quickly","D":"a service that delivers new products to every home"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This creative response applies the text\u0027s idea of pooling resources to a community item-swap program.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pool Resources. One of the greenest ways to help your community is to keep items from being wasted in the first place. Imagine that you have old clothes, books, or sports equipment that you no longer need."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of emissions? A. releases B. absorption (taking in) C. gases D. pollution","excerpt":"\"Emissions from factories and cars pollute the air. Reducing these emissions helps fight climate change.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym of emissions?","choices":{"A":"releases","B":"absorption (taking in)","C":"gases","D":"pollution"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Emissions are things given off; absorption is taking in.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Emissions from factories and cars pollute the air. Reducing these emissions helps fight climate change.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the author use short, active headings? A. To make the text longer B. To grab attention and clearly tell the reader what each section is about C. To hide the main ideas D. To confuse the reader","excerpt":"The author uses headings like \"Think Twice,\" \"Precycle,\" \"Try a New Activity,\" \"Repair or Donate,\" and \"Use Power Strips.\"","stem":"Why does the author use short, active headings?","choices":{"A":"To make the text longer","B":"To grab attention and clearly tell the reader what each section is about","C":"To hide the main ideas","D":"To confuse the reader"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Headings organize and guide the reader.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The author uses headings like \"Think Twice,\" \"Precycle,\" \"Try a New Activity,\" \"Repair or Donate,\" and \"Use Power Strips.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q018","read_aloud":"(Composting) How is composting different from recycling? A. Composting handles food and plant waste; recycling handles materials like paper, glass, and plastic. B. They are exactly the same. C. Composting is only for plastic. D. Recycling is only for food.","excerpt":"Some types of waste can be harder to reduce than others. … It is possible, however, to find a use for many types of spoiled or uneaten food.","stem":"(Composting) How is composting different from recycling?","choices":{"A":"Composting handles food and plant waste; recycling handles materials like paper, glass, and plastic.","B":"They are exactly the same.","C":"Composting is only for plastic.","D":"Recycling is only for food."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says food waste cannot go in recycling bins but can be composted.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some types of waste can be harder to reduce than others. … It is possible, however, to find a use for many types of spoiled or uneaten food."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Write one sentence describing a group project your class could do to reduce waste. A. \"My class could ignore waste problems.\" B. \"My class could start a recycling competition with other classes.\" C. \"My class could throw away all paper.\" D. \"My class could use more plastic.\"","excerpt":"\"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results.\"","stem":"Write one sentence describing a group project your class could do to reduce waste.","choices":{"A":"\"My class could ignore waste problems.\"","B":"\"My class could start a recycling competition with other classes.\"","C":"\"My class could throw away all paper.\"","D":"\"My class could use more plastic.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Group actions can have a larger impact.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q020","read_aloud":"How does the author explain the meaning of watt in the text? A. As a unit of measurement for electrical power B. As a type of battery C. As a way to save water D. As a tool for gardening","excerpt":"\"Kill-A-Watt meters display how much energy is being used and how much this energy costs. With this information, many people find it easier to keep track of how many watts they use.\"","stem":"How does the author explain the meaning of watt in the text?","choices":{"A":"As a unit of measurement for electrical power","B":"As a type of battery","C":"As a way to save water","D":"As a tool for gardening"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines a watt as a unit of measurement for electrical power.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kill-A-Watt meters display how much energy is being used and how much this energy costs. With this information, many people find it easier to keep track of how many watts they use.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q021","read_aloud":"What is the \"debate\" about in this section? A. Whether people should recycle at all B. How cities should collect recyclables C. If recycling costs too much money D. If bottles are useful","excerpt":"\"Most people would agree that reducing waste is a good idea. However, there are many different ways to do so, and these specifics are often topics for heated debate.\"","stem":"What is the \"debate\" about in this section?","choices":{"A":"Whether people should recycle at all","B":"How cities should collect recyclables","C":"If recycling costs too much money","D":"If bottles are useful"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains the debate is about how cities collect recyclable materials.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most people would agree that reducing waste is a good idea. However, there are many different ways to do so, and these specifics are often topics for heated debate.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q022","read_aloud":"According to the text, why is door-to-door collection a \"Pro\"? A. It costs less money. B. It encourages more people to participate. C. It reduces traffic. D. It creates more jobs.","excerpt":"\"Easier participation will encourage more people to take part in local recycling programs.\"","stem":"According to the text, why is door-to-door collection a \"Pro\"?","choices":{"A":"It costs less money.","B":"It encourages more people to participate.","C":"It reduces traffic.","D":"It creates more jobs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"Pros\" list says easier participation will encourage more people to take part.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Easier participation will encourage more people to take part in local recycling programs.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q023","read_aloud":"Why might some people vote against door-to-door recycling? A. They do not want to pay higher taxes. B. They do not like recycling. C. They want more trucks on the street. D. They think bins are pretty.","excerpt":"\"Door-to-door collection will increase taxes for property owners.\"","stem":"Why might some people vote against door-to-door recycling?","choices":{"A":"They do not want to pay higher taxes.","B":"They do not like recycling.","C":"They want more trucks on the street.","D":"They think bins are pretty."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The \"Cons\" list says this option will increase taxes, which people might dislike.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Door-to-door collection will increase taxes for property owners.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q024","read_aloud":"Is the appearance of bins a strong argument against recycling? A. Yes, because ugly bins stop people from recycling. B. No, because the environmental benefit is more important than looks. C. Yes, because bins should always look new. D. No, because bins are always hidden.","excerpt":"\"The bins used for recycling collection are unattractive.\"","stem":"Is the appearance of bins a strong argument against recycling?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because ugly bins stop people from recycling.","B":"No, because the environmental benefit is more important than looks.","C":"Yes, because bins should always look new.","D":"No, because bins are always hidden."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This is an opinion question. Helping the Earth is usually seen as more important than how a bin looks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The bins used for recycling collection are unattractive.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l09-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q001","read_aloud":"What does it mean for a contractor to be \u0027licensed\u0027? Options: A. They have passed a test and have permission to work, B. They are just starting to learn, C. They are not allowed to build, D. They only work in one house","excerpt":"\"All U.S. states require contractors to be licensed. The details of these licenses vary by state, but most licensed contractors must pass a multiple-choice exam.\"","stem":"What does it mean for a contractor to be \u0027licensed\u0027? Options:","choices":{"A":"They have passed a test and have permission to work,","B":"They are just starting to learn,","C":"They are not allowed to build,","D":"They only work in one house"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Being licensed means they have met specific requirements, like passing an exam, to show they are qualified for the job.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"All U.S. states require contractors to be licensed. The details of these licenses vary by state, but most licensed contractors must pass a multiple-choice exam.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q002","read_aloud":"What is the trend for new homes regarding water? Options: A. Developers are ignoring water waste, B. Developers are adding systems to treat and reuse graywater, C. Developers are making houses without water, D. Developers are only building houses near rivers","excerpt":"\"Most of the water used in any home will become graywater. Many developers have begun installing graywater treatment systems in homes.\"","stem":"What is the trend for new homes regarding water? Options:","choices":{"A":"Developers are ignoring water waste,","B":"Developers are adding systems to treat and reuse graywater,","C":"Developers are making houses without water,","D":"Developers are only building houses near rivers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text highlights that it is becoming common for developers to install treatment systems to reuse water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the water used in any home will become graywater. Many developers have begun installing graywater treatment systems in homes.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q003","read_aloud":"What is the purpose of suggesting a trick for older toilets? Options: A. To make the toilet look fancy, B. To save water if the family cannot buy a new low-flush model, C. To get rid of the brick, D. To break the toilet on purpose","excerpt":"\"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\"","stem":"What is the purpose of suggesting a trick for older toilets? Options:","choices":{"A":"To make the toilet look fancy,","B":"To save water if the family cannot buy a new low-flush model,","C":"To get rid of the brick,","D":"To break the toilet on purpose"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This trick is a solution for families who have older, less efficient toilets and want to save water without buying a new one.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q004","read_aloud":"How does this quote by Jimmy Carter support the author\u0027s argument? Options: A. It shows that trash is just a small, unimportant issue, B. It shows that trash is a serious problem for our health and money, C. It says everyone is doing a great job, D. It suggests we should move to a new planet","excerpt":"\"This growing mountain of garbage and trash represents not only an attitude of indifference toward valuable natural resources, but also a serious economic and public health problem.\"","stem":"How does this quote by Jimmy Carter support the author\u0027s argument? Options:","choices":{"A":"It shows that trash is just a small, unimportant issue,","B":"It shows that trash is a serious problem for our health and money,","C":"It says everyone is doing a great job,","D":"It suggests we should move to a new planet"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote underscores the seriousness of the waste problem, reinforcing why individual and community action is necessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This growing mountain of garbage and trash represents not only an attitude of indifference toward valuable natural resources, but also a serious economic and public health problem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q005","read_aloud":"What does the author mean by a \"ripple effect\"? Options: A. That small actions by one person can inspire others and lead to bigger changes, B. That actions make no difference at all, C. That only big, expensive changes matter, D. That changes happen only in water","excerpt":"\"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways.\"","stem":"What does the author mean by a \"ripple effect\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"That small actions by one person can inspire others and lead to bigger changes,","B":"That actions make no difference at all,","C":"That only big, expensive changes matter,","D":"That changes happen only in water"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Just like a stone thrown in water, one person\u0027s positive choice can spread out and lead to more people making similar choices.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q006","read_aloud":"Which word could replace \"watt\" in a sentence about light bulbs without changing the meaning much? A. unit of power B. type of bulb C. color of light D. size of bulb","excerpt":"\"These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb.\"","stem":"Which word could replace \"watt\" in a sentence about light bulbs without changing the meaning much?","choices":{"A":"unit of power","B":"type of bulb","C":"color of light","D":"size of bulb"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"A watt is a unit of measurement for electrical power. In a sentence about light bulbs, \"unit of power\" explains what a watt measures. The other choices do not describe what a watt is.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q007","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s main message about reducing waste? A. Only one person can save the environment. B. Individual actions matter, but working together as a community creates bigger change. C. The environment cannot be saved. D. People should not bother trying.","excerpt":"\"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s main message about reducing waste?","choices":{"A":"Only one person can save the environment.","B":"Individual actions matter, but working together as a community creates bigger change.","C":"The environment cannot be saved.","D":"People should not bother trying."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author says individual action is a great start but a large group sees faster results. The message is that while personal choices matter, community action multiplies the effect. Working together is more powerful than acting alone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author use \"we\" and \"our\" throughout the text? A. to distance himself from readers B. to build a relationship and show that everyone shares responsibility for the environment C. to prove that he is better than readers D. to confuse readers about who is speaking","excerpt":"\"Nick Winnick uses the first-person point of view... to remind readers that he and they live in the same world.\"","stem":"Why does the author use \"we\" and \"our\" throughout the text?","choices":{"A":"to distance himself from readers","B":"to build a relationship and show that everyone shares responsibility for the environment","C":"to prove that he is better than readers","D":"to confuse readers about who is speaking"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Using \"we\" and \"our\" makes readers feel included. It shows the author and readers are in this together. This builds trust and makes readers more likely to accept the author\u0027s argument and take action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Nick Winnick uses the first-person point of view... to remind readers that he and they live in the same world.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q009","read_aloud":"If schools required students to compost food waste, how might that change students\u0027 habits at home? A. Students would forget about composting completely. B. Students might teach their families about composting and start composting at home. C. Students would refuse to eat at school. D. Composting would have no effect on anyone.","excerpt":"\"In order to have a clean and healthy world in the future, we need to start working toward it now.\"","stem":"If schools required students to compost food waste, how might that change students\u0027 habits at home?","choices":{"A":"Students would forget about composting completely.","B":"Students might teach their families about composting and start composting at home.","C":"Students would refuse to eat at school.","D":"Composting would have no effect on anyone."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If students learn to compost at school, they might bring those habits home. They could teach parents and siblings what they learned. School habits often influence family behavior, creating a ripple effect of positive change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In order to have a clean and healthy world in the future, we need to start working toward it now.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q010","read_aloud":"How does understanding \"underlie\" deepen our view of the text\u0027s message about personal responsibility? A. it shows that our daily choices form the foundation for larger environmental change B. it suggests that only governments can reduce waste C. it means that personal actions do not matter D. it shows that waste reduction happens without any effort","excerpt":"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways.","stem":"How does understanding \"underlie\" deepen our view of the text\u0027s message about personal responsibility?","choices":{"A":"it shows that our daily choices form the foundation for larger environmental change","B":"it suggests that only governments can reduce waste","C":"it means that personal actions do not matter","D":"it shows that waste reduction happens without any effort"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Understanding underlie as \"forming the foundation\" reinforces the message that personal choices are the foundation for bigger change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands. Many people have started to make changes to become less wasteful in their everyday lives. These changes can have a ripple effect that benefits the world in many ways."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q011","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the entire selection, supported by this opening? A. argumentative texts can persuade readers to take action by providing practical ways to reduce waste B. all texts about the environment are only for scientists C. reducing waste is impossible for ordinary people D. fossil fuels are the only cause of environmental problems","excerpt":"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities. Greenhouse gases are created by burning fossil fuels. People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles.","stem":"What is the main idea of the entire selection, supported by this opening?","choices":{"A":"argumentative texts can persuade readers to take action by providing practical ways to reduce waste","B":"all texts about the environment are only for scientists","C":"reducing waste is impossible for ordinary people","D":"fossil fuels are the only cause of environmental problems"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The opening introduces the problem (carbon footprint) and the text provides practical solutions, showing how argumentative texts can persuade action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities. Greenhouse gases are created by burning fossil fuels. People burn fossil fuels for electricity, heating, and powering vehicles."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q012","read_aloud":"How does the question-and-answer format help readers understand the text\u0027s purpose? A. it engages readers by presenting a problem and then offering solutions B. it confuses readers by asking too many questions C. it suggests that there are no real answers to environmental problems D. it shows that only experts can solve these questions","excerpt":"In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment? The answer has a great deal to do with reducing waste.","stem":"How does the question-and-answer format help readers understand the text\u0027s purpose?","choices":{"A":"it engages readers by presenting a problem and then offering solutions","B":"it confuses readers by asking too many questions","C":"it suggests that there are no real answers to environmental problems","D":"it shows that only experts can solve these questions"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The question-and-answer format engages readers and clearly presents the text\u0027s persuasive purpose: reducing waste solves future challenges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In the future, the world\u0027s population will likely grow much larger than it is today. How can the world support more people, yet still be kinder to the environment? The answer has a great deal to do with reducing waste."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q013","read_aloud":"- Buckminster Fuller, architect and inventorDo you think the author fairly presents the relationship between pollution and wasted resources? Why or why not? A. yes, it shows that what we call pollution is often valuable resources we fail to use wisely B. no, it suggests that all pollution can be easily turned into resources C. yes, but only for readers who already agree with the author D. no, because pollution and resources are completely different things","excerpt":"Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value.","stem":"- Buckminster Fuller, architect and inventorDo you think the author fairly presents the relationship between pollution and wasted resources? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, it shows that what we call pollution is often valuable resources we fail to use wisely","B":"no, it suggests that all pollution can be easily turned into resources","C":"yes, but only for readers who already agree with the author","D":"no, because pollution and resources are completely different things"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The quotation fairly presents that many pollutants are actually valuable resources we fail to capture and reuse.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q014","read_aloud":"(Adapted from text theme)If Nick Winnick could send one message to young people today about reducing waste, what might it be based on his text? A. \"Start small, think creatively, and remember that your choices today shape the world of tomorrow.\" B. \"Only experts can make a difference in reducing waste.\" C. \"Wait until you are older to worry about the environment.\" D. \"Buy as much as you want because waste does not really matter.\"","excerpt":"After all, experience is the greatest teacher.","stem":"(Adapted from text theme)If Nick Winnick could send one message to young people today about reducing waste, what might it be based on his text?","choices":{"A":"\"Start small, think creatively, and remember that your choices today shape the world of tomorrow.\"","B":"\"Only experts can make a difference in reducing waste.\"","C":"\"Wait until you are older to worry about the environment.\"","D":"\"Buy as much as you want because waste does not really matter.\""},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Winnick\u0027s text emphasizes practical, creative actions individuals can take, making this message authentic to his argument.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After all, experience is the greatest teacher."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q015","read_aloud":"Why is the word emissions important in understanding climate change? A. It means taking in gases, which helps the climate. B. It refers to the release of harmful gases that trap heat and warm the planet. C. It means recycling gases. D. It means creating new gases.","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Why is the word emissions important in understanding climate change?","choices":{"A":"It means taking in gases, which helps the climate.","B":"It refers to the release of harmful gases that trap heat and warm the planet.","C":"It means recycling gases.","D":"It means creating new gases."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Carbon emissions are harmful gases released into the air.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q016","read_aloud":"What evidence does the author give to support his claim that reducing waste is possible? A. He says it is impossible. B. He lists specific, doable actions like walking, biking, and turning off lights. C. He only talks about problems. D. He gives no evidence.","excerpt":"\"There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car. You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste.\"","stem":"What evidence does the author give to support his claim that reducing waste is possible?","choices":{"A":"He says it is impossible.","B":"He lists specific, doable actions like walking, biking, and turning off lights.","C":"He only talks about problems.","D":"He gives no evidence."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author gives concrete examples of actions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint. One way is to walk or ride your bike instead of riding in a car. You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q017","read_aloud":"What conclusion can you draw about the author\u0027s view on who can reduce waste? A. Only governments can reduce waste. B. Everyone-individuals, families, and communities-can take action to reduce waste. C. Only factories can reduce waste. D. , at stores (precycling, buying less), and in the community (bottle drives, yard sales, composting).","excerpt":"The text covers reducing waste at home (energy, water, foo","stem":"What conclusion can you draw about the author\u0027s view on who can reduce waste?","choices":{"A":"Only governments can reduce waste.","B":"Everyone-individuals, families, and communities-can take action to reduce waste.","C":"Only factories can reduce waste.","D":", at stores (precycling, buying less), and in the community (bottle drives, yard sales, composting)."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text addresses actions for all levels.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text covers reducing waste at home (energy, water, foo"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q018","read_aloud":"Write one new sentence that could be added to the conclusion of this text, encouraging readers to take action. A. \"It is too late to help the environment.\" B. \"Start with one small change today, and together we can make a big difference.\" C. \"Only adults should worry about waste.\" D. \"Reducing waste is a waste of time.\"","excerpt":"\"How can you make the world a greener place?\"","stem":"Write one new sentence that could be added to the conclusion of this text, encouraging readers to take action.","choices":{"A":"\"It is too late to help the environment.\"","B":"\"Start with one small change today, and together we can make a big difference.\"","C":"\"Only adults should worry about waste.\"","D":"\"Reducing waste is a waste of time.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A good conclusion inspires action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"How can you make the world a greener place?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q019","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses innovative correctly? A. The old car was innovative because it broke down. B. She had an innovative idea to use less plastic. C. The innovative sandwich tasted good. D. He felt innovative when he was tired.","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses innovative correctly?","choices":{"A":"The old car was innovative because it broke down.","B":"She had an innovative idea to use less plastic.","C":"The innovative sandwich tasted good.","D":"He felt innovative when he was tired."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Innovative means using new ideas. Finding a new way to save plastic fits the meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q020","read_aloud":"Who is the intended audience for this text? A. Scientists only B. Young students and their families C. Government officials D. Construction workers","excerpt":"\"Think about ways that you could use what you have learned about reducing waste to help your community.\"","stem":"Who is the intended audience for this text?","choices":{"A":"Scientists only","B":"Young students and their families","C":"Government officials","D":"Construction workers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses simple language and gives tips that students and families can do at home or school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Think about ways that you could use what you have learned about reducing waste to help your community.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q021","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose for writing this text? A. To entertain readers with funny stories B. To persuade readers to reduce waste C. To inform readers about the history of trash D. To sell new light bulbs","excerpt":"\"In order to have a clean and healthy world in the future, we need to start working toward it now.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose for writing this text?","choices":{"A":"To entertain readers with funny stories","B":"To persuade readers to reduce waste","C":"To inform readers about the history of trash","D":"To sell new light bulbs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author gives reasons and tips to convince readers to change their habits and reduce waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In order to have a clean and healthy world in the future, we need to start working toward it now.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q022","read_aloud":"What does the author mean by this sentence? A. We need to wash our hands. B. We are responsible for making changes. C. We cannot do anything to help. D. Waste is too heavy to lift.","excerpt":"\"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands.\"","stem":"What does the author mean by this sentence?","choices":{"A":"We need to wash our hands.","B":"We are responsible for making changes.","C":"We cannot do anything to help.","D":"Waste is too heavy to lift."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It means individuals have the ability and responsibility to make a difference.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q023","read_aloud":"If you wrote a letter to your mayor, which tip from the text would be the best one to suggest for the whole town? A. Starting a vermiculture worm bin in every home B. Installing a Kill-A-Watt meter in every home C. Starting a city-wide bottle drive D. Buying a new water heater","excerpt":"(The whole text)","stem":"If you wrote a letter to your mayor, which tip from the text would be the best one to suggest for the whole town?","choices":{"A":"Starting a vermiculture worm bin in every home","B":"Installing a Kill-A-Watt meter in every home","C":"Starting a city-wide bottle drive","D":"Buying a new water heater"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"A bottle drive involves the community and raises money, making it a good town project.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: (The whole text)"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-l10-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"emissions\" mean? A. things that are eaten B. substances released or given off C. places where people live D. types of animals","excerpt":"\"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What does \"emissions\" mean?","choices":{"A":"things that are eaten","B":"substances released or given off","C":"places where people live","D":"types of animals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines emissions as substances released or anything given off. Carbon emissions are gases released into the air by burning fossil fuels.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q002","read_aloud":"What does \"excessive\" mean? A. a small amount B. a lot, or more than necessary C. exactly the right amount D. none at all","excerpt":"\"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\"","stem":"What does \"excessive\" mean?","choices":{"A":"a small amount","B":"a lot, or more than necessary","C":"exactly the right amount","D":"none at all"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines excessive as a lot, or more than necessary. Buying more than you need creates more waste than is necessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q003","read_aloud":"What does \"innovative\" mean? A. boring and old B. creative, using new ideas or methods C. difficult and confusing D. expensive and fancy","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"What does \"innovative\" mean?","choices":{"A":"boring and old","B":"creative, using new ideas or methods","C":"difficult and confusing","D":"expensive and fancy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines innovative as creative, using new ideas or methods. People are finding new and clever ways to save water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this section? A. how to build cars B. how to help the planet by reducing waste C. how to grow trees D. how to make money","excerpt":"\"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this section?","choices":{"A":"how to build cars","B":"how to help the planet by reducing waste","C":"how to grow trees","D":"how to make money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The section introduces ways to make the world greener by reducing your carbon footprint. The main idea is about helping the planet through waste reduction.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"How can you make the world a greener place? You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. There are many ways you can reduce your carbon footprint.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q005","read_aloud":"What is one effect of turning off lights? A. more energy waste B. reduced energy waste C. brighter rooms D. broken light bulbs","excerpt":"\"You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste. Reusing plastic shopping bags to carry other items is another way to help the environment.\"","stem":"What is one effect of turning off lights?","choices":{"A":"more energy waste","B":"reduced energy waste","C":"brighter rooms","D":"broken light bulbs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that turning off lights reduces energy waste. This is a simple action with a clear positive effect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"You can turn off lights when you leave a room to reduce energy waste. Reusing plastic shopping bags to carry other items is another way to help the environment.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q006","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s opinion? A. The author thinks all packaging is good. B. The author thinks less packaging and recyclable packaging are better choices. C. The author does not care about packaging. D. The author thinks packaging should be bigger.","excerpt":"\"Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? If it does have packaging, is that packaging recyclable or made from recycled materials?\"","stem":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s opinion?","choices":{"A":"The author thinks all packaging is good.","B":"The author thinks less packaging and recyclable packaging are better choices.","C":"The author does not care about packaging.","D":"The author thinks packaging should be bigger."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author asks readers to consider whether packaging is excessive and whether it is recyclable. This shows the author believes less and recyclable packaging are better for the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Does the food item have an excessive amount of packaging? If it does have packaging, is that packaging recyclable or made from recycled materials?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q007","read_aloud":"What are the three Rs? A. Read, Write, and Arithmetic B. Reduce, Reuse, and Recycle C. Run, Rest, and Relax D. Red, Blue, and Green","excerpt":"\"The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\"","stem":"What are the three Rs?","choices":{"A":"Read, Write, and Arithmetic","B":"Reduce, Reuse, and Recycle","C":"Run, Rest, and Relax","D":"Red, Blue, and Green"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that the three Rs are \"Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\" These are three key ways to help the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The three Rs are \u0027Reduce, Reuse, Recycle.\u0027 Reducing is one of the most important parts of being green.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q008","read_aloud":"Why are energy-efficient bulbs popular? A. They are more expensive. B. They last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled. C. They break easily. D. They cannot be found in stores.","excerpt":"\"A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\"","stem":"Why are energy-efficient bulbs popular?","choices":{"A":"They are more expensive.","B":"They last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.","C":"They break easily.","D":"They cannot be found in stores."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists three reasons: they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled. These benefits make them popular with people who want to save energy and money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs. These bulbs have become popular because they give off the same amount of light as an incandescent light bulb. However, they last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q009","read_aloud":"Why does the author say a large group will see faster results? A. because one person cannot do anything B. because when many people work together, their combined actions create bigger change C. because groups are always noisy D. because the environment does not need help","excerpt":"\"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results. Think about ways that you could use what you have learned about reducing waste to help your community.\"","stem":"Why does the author say a large group will see faster results?","choices":{"A":"because one person cannot do anything","B":"because when many people work together, their combined actions create bigger change","C":"because groups are always noisy","D":"because the environment does not need help"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author believes individual action is good but limited. When many people in a community work together, their combined efforts multiply. More people reducing waste means less total waste and faster positive results.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results. Think about ways that you could use what you have learned about reducing waste to help your community.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q010","read_aloud":"Why do you think the author chose to write this book for young readers? A. because young readers cannot understand science B. because young readers can form good habits early and influence their families C. because adults do not care about the environment D. because young readers have more money","excerpt":"\"Nick Winnick gives readers tips about forming eco-friendly habits... He attributes his direct, conversational approach to his twenty-three years as a science teacher.\"","stem":"Why do you think the author chose to write this book for young readers?","choices":{"A":"because young readers cannot understand science","B":"because young readers can form good habits early and influence their families","C":"because adults do not care about the environment","D":"because young readers have more money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses a friendly, conversational style suitable for young readers. Young people can start eco-friendly habits early and teach their families. The author believes that reaching young readers creates lasting change that spreads to homes and communities. Section A - Text Information Title: The Top 10 Ways You Can Reduce WasteAuthor: Nick WinnickText Type: Argumentative TextPreview Vocabulary Words: emissions, excessive, underlie, watt, innovative","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Nick Winnick gives readers tips about forming eco-friendly habits... He attributes his direct, conversational approach to his twenty-three years as a science teacher.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"emissions\" mean in this sentence? A. substances released into the air B. clean water in rivers C. trees planted in forests D. rocks found underground","excerpt":"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.","stem":"What does \"emissions\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"substances released into the air","B":"clean water in rivers","C":"trees planted in forests","D":"rocks found underground"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions means substances released into the air. The text says carbon emissions are damaging pollution.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q012","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"excessive\"? A. a lot, or more than necessary B. very small amounts C. just the right amount D. nothing at all","excerpt":"Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, consider the waste the purchase will produce.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"excessive\"?","choices":{"A":"a lot, or more than necessary","B":"very small amounts","C":"just the right amount","D":"nothing at all"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Excessive means a lot or more than necessary. The text warns about waste that is excessive or too much.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Buying more items than you actually need can lead to excessive waste. Before making purchases, consider the waste the purchase will produce."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"innovative\" mean in this sentence? A. creative; using new ideas or methods B. old-fashioned and traditional C. slow and careful D. expensive and difficult","excerpt":"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.","stem":"What does \"innovative\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"creative; using new ideas or methods","B":"old-fashioned and traditional","C":"slow and careful","D":"expensive and difficult"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Innovative means creative or using new ideas. The text describes people finding new ways to save water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is a carbon footprint? A. the measure of greenhouse gases from human activities B. the size of a person\u0027s feet C. the number of trees in a forest D. the amount of water in oceans","excerpt":"You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.","stem":"What is a carbon footprint?","choices":{"A":"the measure of greenhouse gases from human activities","B":"the size of a person\u0027s feet","C":"the number of trees in a forest","D":"the amount of water in oceans"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states a carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: You can help the planet by reducing your carbon footprint. A carbon footprint is the measure of greenhouse gases produced by human activities."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q015","read_aloud":"What text structure helps explain why efficient products are a good choice? A. compare and contrast: efficient products use less energy but work as well or better B. chronological order of product development C. cause and effect of energy use on weather D. problem and solution for building factories","excerpt":"Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs.","stem":"What text structure helps explain why efficient products are a good choice?","choices":{"A":"compare and contrast: efficient products use less energy but work as well or better","B":"chronological order of product development","C":"cause and effect of energy use on weather","D":"problem and solution for building factories"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author compares efficient products to regular ones, showing they use less energy while performing equally well.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Efficient energy products use less energy, but they work as well as, or better than, the items they replace. A good example is energy-efficient light bulbs."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q016","read_aloud":"What is one easy way to help the environment? A. reducing waste B. buying more things C. using more plastic D. throwing away food","excerpt":"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment.","stem":"What is one easy way to help the environment?","choices":{"A":"reducing waste","B":"buying more things","C":"using more plastic","D":"throwing away food"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that reducing waste is one of the easiest ways to help the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q017","read_aloud":"Why is precycling a helpful practice? A. it helps you choose packaging that can be recycled or breaks down naturally B. it makes you spend more money on products C. it encourages buying items with more packaging D. it suggests that all packaging is the same","excerpt":"Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. They are the same price, but one comes in a Styrofoam container, and the other in a cardboard container.","stem":"Why is precycling a helpful practice?","choices":{"A":"it helps you choose packaging that can be recycled or breaks down naturally","B":"it makes you spend more money on products","C":"it encourages buying items with more packaging","D":"it suggests that all packaging is the same"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that precycling helps you choose recyclable or biodegradable packaging.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. They are the same price, but one comes in a Styrofoam container, and the other in a cardboard container."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q018","read_aloud":"- Benjamin FranklinHow does this quotation support the section about reducing water use? A. it uses a memorable saying to emphasize that we often do not value water until it is scarce B. it suggests that water is not important until it is gone C. it proves that wells are the only source of water D. it shows that Benjamin Franklin invented water conservation","excerpt":"When the well is dry, we know the worth of water.","stem":"- Benjamin FranklinHow does this quotation support the section about reducing water use?","choices":{"A":"it uses a memorable saying to emphasize that we often do not value water until it is scarce","B":"it suggests that water is not important until it is gone","C":"it proves that wells are the only source of water","D":"it shows that Benjamin Franklin invented water conservation"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Franklin\u0027s quotation emphasizes that people often do not appreciate water\u0027s value until it becomes scarce, supporting the argument to conserve it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When the well is dry, we know the worth of water."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q019","read_aloud":"- Buckminster FullerWhy is this a powerful way to end an argumentative text about reducing waste? A. it challenges readers to rethink what they consider \"waste\" and see potential value in resources B. it suggests that pollution is not a real problem C. it argues that only scientists should worry about resources D. it complains that recycling is too difficult","excerpt":"Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value.","stem":"- Buckminster FullerWhy is this a powerful way to end an argumentative text about reducing waste?","choices":{"A":"it challenges readers to rethink what they consider \"waste\" and see potential value in resources","B":"it suggests that pollution is not a real problem","C":"it argues that only scientists should worry about resources","D":"it complains that recycling is too difficult"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Ending with this quotation challenges readers to see waste as unused resources, reinforcing the text\u0027s persuasive message to reduce waste. Section A - Text Information Title: The Top 10 Ways You Can Reduce Waste (excerpt)Author: Nick Winnick","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q020","read_aloud":"What are emissions? A. things that are recycled B. things given off, such as gases C. things that are buried D. things that are eaten","excerpt":"\"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"What are emissions?","choices":{"A":"things that are recycled","B":"things given off, such as gases","C":"things that are buried","D":"things that are eaten"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Emissions are things given off, like gases.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q021","read_aloud":"What does a watt measure? A. the weight of electricity B. the amount of electrical power C. the temperature of a light bulb D. the speed of light","excerpt":"\"Many families have saved money and energy by installing a power meter called a KillAWatt.\"","stem":"What does a watt measure?","choices":{"A":"the weight of electricity","B":"the amount of electrical power","C":"the temperature of a light bulb","D":"the speed of light"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A watt is a unit of electrical power.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many families have saved money and energy by installing a power meter called a KillAWatt.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this passage? A. Reducing waste is hard. B. Reducing waste is easy and there are many ways to do it. C. Only factories can reduce waste. D. Waste cannot be reduced.","excerpt":"\"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this passage?","choices":{"A":"Reducing waste is hard.","B":"Reducing waste is easy and there are many ways to do it.","C":"Only factories can reduce waste.","D":"Waste cannot be reduced."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author states that reducing waste is easy and provides many ways.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q023","read_aloud":"What are three benefits of energyefficient light bulbs? A. They are cheaper, brighter, and smaller. B. They last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled. C. They are heavier, hotter, and harder to find. D. They break easily and waste energy.","excerpt":"\"Energy-efficient light bulbs … last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\"","stem":"What are three benefits of energyefficient light bulbs?","choices":{"A":"They are cheaper, brighter, and smaller.","B":"They last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.","C":"They are heavier, hotter, and harder to find.","D":"They break easily and waste energy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists these three benefits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Energy-efficient light bulbs … last longer, use less electricity, and can be recycled.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q024","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s purpose in mentioning this? A. To discourage readers B. To introduce composting as a solution for food waste C. To say that food waste cannot be reduced D. To argue that recycling is useless","excerpt":"\"Some types of waste can be harder to reduce than others. You cannot add spoiled food or old teabags to a recycling bin.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the author\u0027s purpose in mentioning this?","choices":{"A":"To discourage readers","B":"To introduce composting as a solution for food waste","C":"To say that food waste cannot be reduced","D":"To argue that recycling is useless"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The next sections discuss composting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some types of waste can be harder to reduce than others. You cannot add spoiled food or old teabags to a recycling bin.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q025","read_aloud":"Which egg container is the better choice for the environment? A. Styrofoam container B. Plastic container C. Cardboard container D. Metal container","excerpt":"\"Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. … The eggs in the cardboard container are the better choice for the environment.\"","stem":"Which egg container is the better choice for the environment?","choices":{"A":"Styrofoam container","B":"Plastic container","C":"Cardboard container","D":"Metal container"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Cardboard can be recycled and is biodegradable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Precycling refers to planning purchases with recycling in mind. For example, you may have a choice between two brands of eggs. … The eggs in the cardboard container are the better choice for the environment.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q026","read_aloud":"Do you agree with this statement? Why? A. No, because only governments can help. B. Yes, because individuals can make many small changes that add up to big effects. C. No, because it is impossible to reduce waste. D. Yes, but only if you have a lot of money.","excerpt":"\"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands.\"","stem":"Do you agree with this statement? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because only governments can help.","B":"Yes, because individuals can make many small changes that add up to big effects.","C":"No, because it is impossible to reduce waste.","D":"Yes, but only if you have a lot of money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists many individual actions that reduce waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The power to reduce waste lies in our own hands.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q027","read_aloud":"Write one sentence describing a group project your school could do to reduce waste. A. \"My school could ignore waste problems.\" B. \"My school could start a recycling program and a compost bin for lunch scraps.\" C. \"My school could throw away all paper.\" D. \"My school could use more plastic.\"","excerpt":"\"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results.\"","stem":"Write one sentence describing a group project your school could do to reduce waste.","choices":{"A":"\"My school could ignore waste problems.\"","B":"\"My school could start a recycling program and a compost bin for lunch scraps.\"","C":"\"My school could throw away all paper.\"","D":"\"My school could use more plastic.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Group actions can have a larger impact. Section A - Text information Title: The Top 10 Ways You Can Reduce Waste Author: Nick Winnick","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Protecting the environment is a big job. Taking individual action is a great start, but a large group will see faster results.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q028","read_aloud":"What does underlie mean? A. To lie down on the floor B. To hide under a bed C. To form the foundation of something D. To sleep late","excerpt":"\"Our personal consumer choices have ecological consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\"","stem":"What does underlie mean?","choices":{"A":"To lie down on the floor","B":"To hide under a bed","C":"To form the foundation of something","D":"To sleep late"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"To underlie means to be the foundation or basis for something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our personal consumer choices have ecological consequences. It is time to re-examine some of our deeply held notions that underlie our lifestyles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q029","read_aloud":"What benefit does the author predict if everyone uses CFL bulbs? A. Electric bills will stay the same. B. People will buy more lamps. C. Less greenhouse gas will enter the atmosphere. D. Old bulbs will become valuable.","excerpt":"\"Replacing older incandescent bulbs with CFLs, which are very energy efficient, will reduce your family\u0027s electric bill. If everyone in the United States made this change, the reduced need for electricity could mean that more than 5 billion tons (4.5 billion metric tons) of greenhouse gases would not enter the atmosphere.\"","stem":"What benefit does the author predict if everyone uses CFL bulbs?","choices":{"A":"Electric bills will stay the same.","B":"People will buy more lamps.","C":"Less greenhouse gas will enter the atmosphere.","D":"Old bulbs will become valuable."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that reduced electricity need would mean billions of tons of greenhouse gases would not enter the atmosphere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Replacing older incandescent bulbs with CFLs, which are very energy efficient, will reduce your family\u0027s electric bill. If everyone in the United States made this change, the reduced need for electricity could mean that more than 5 billion tons (4.5 billion metric tons) of greenhouse gases would not enter the atmosphere.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q030","read_aloud":"What is the benefit of \"pooling resources\" for a yard sale? A. You have fewer items to sell. B. You can earn money and help others reuse items. C. You can throw more things away. D. You do not have to talk to neighbors.","excerpt":"\"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\"","stem":"What is the benefit of \"pooling resources\" for a yard sale?","choices":{"A":"You have fewer items to sell.","B":"You can earn money and help others reuse items.","C":"You can throw more things away.","D":"You do not have to talk to neighbors."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says pooling resources helps you earn money and keeps items out of the trash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If all of you pool your resources and hold a sale together, you can earn money, provide your friends and neighbors with items they might need, and keep items from being thrown away.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q031","read_aloud":"According to the text, why are carbon emissions a problem? A. They help plants grow faster. B. They are a major cause of climate change. C. They make the air smell good. D. They cool down the Earth.","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"According to the text, why are carbon emissions a problem?","choices":{"A":"They help plants grow faster.","B":"They are a major cause of climate change.","C":"They make the air smell good.","D":"They cool down the Earth."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that carbon dioxide from emissions is a big cause of climate change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q032","read_aloud":"What is the first step to helping the environment according to the text? A. Buying new things B. Deciding to reduce waste C. Moving to a new city D. Turning on all the lights","excerpt":"\"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it.\"","stem":"What is the first step to helping the environment according to the text?","choices":{"A":"Buying new things","B":"Deciding to reduce waste","C":"Moving to a new city","D":"Turning on all the lights"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says that once you decide to reduce waste, you can learn ways to do it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Reducing waste is one of the easiest ways you can help the environment. Once you decide to reduce the amount of waste you produce, you can learn many different ways to do it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q033","read_aloud":"What does the author say about reducing waste? A. Everyone agrees on the best way to do it. B. People often debate the specific ways to do it. C. It is a bad idea to reduce waste. D. It is too hard to do.","excerpt":"\"Most people would agree that reducing waste is a good idea. However, there are many different ways to do so, and these specifics are often topics for heated debate.\"","stem":"What does the author say about reducing waste?","choices":{"A":"Everyone agrees on the best way to do it.","B":"People often debate the specific ways to do it.","C":"It is a bad idea to reduce waste.","D":"It is too hard to do."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author says that while people agree on the general idea, they often debate the specifics.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most people would agree that reducing waste is a good idea. However, there are many different ways to do so, and these specifics are often topics for heated debate.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q034","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s final message to the reader? A. Wait until tomorrow to start helping. B. We must act now to help the planet. C. Only adults can save the world. D. The future is not important.","excerpt":"\"In order to have a clean and healthy world in the future, we need to start working toward it now.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s final message to the reader?","choices":{"A":"Wait until tomorrow to start helping.","B":"We must act now to help the planet.","C":"Only adults can save the world.","D":"The future is not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The correct answer is supported by the details in the excerpt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In order to have a clean and healthy world in the future, we need to start working toward it now.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q035","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q036","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. Things that are given off or released, B. A type of healthy food, C. A way to grow new trees, D. A tool used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"Things that are given off or released,","B":"A type of healthy food,","C":"A way to grow new trees,","D":"A tool used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Emissions are substances that are released or given off by something, such as gases from vehicles or factories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One of the biggest causes of climate change is the greenhouse gas known as carbon dioxide. Many scientists believe that carbon emissions are more damaging to Earth than any other kind of pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q037","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. Before buying food B. Before throwing an item away C. After you buy something new D. When you are at school","excerpt":"\"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"Before buying food","B":"Before throwing an item away","C":"After you buy something new","D":"When you are at school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests asking these questions when you are thinking about throwing an item away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ask yourself the following questions. \u0027Can I still use this?\u0027 and \u0027Could someone else use this?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q038","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Plastic items can only be used once. B. Plastic items are very expensive. C. You can find new uses for disposable items. D. You should buy new plastic items.","excerpt":"\"Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Plastic items can only be used once.","B":"Plastic items are very expensive.","C":"You can find new uses for disposable items.","D":"You should buy new plastic items."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The paragraph gives examples of how to reuse plastic items instead of throwing them away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic knives and forks can be washed and re-used for school lunches. Plastic shopping bags can be used as trash can liners or to pick up dog waste.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q039","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. They are thrown in the trash. B. They are given to people who need them. C. They are recycled into new bottles. D. They are sold for high prices.","excerpt":"\"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"They are thrown in the trash.","B":"They are given to people who need them.","C":"They are recycled into new bottles.","D":"They are sold for high prices."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Charities make sure donated items get to people in need.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many charities, such as Goodwill and the Salvation Army, can make sure that donated clothing and household goods get to people in need.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q040","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. To make it look new again B. Because it is often cheaper than buying a new one C. To give it to a friend D. To practice building","excerpt":"\"Repairing a damaged item can often be cheaper than replacing it.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"To make it look new again","B":"Because it is often cheaper than buying a new one","C":"To give it to a friend","D":"To practice building"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says repairing an item can be cheaper than replacing it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Repairing a damaged item can often be cheaper than replacing it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q041","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. A unit to measure water B. A unit to measure electrical power C. A type of light bulb D. A way to save money","excerpt":"\"Watt: unit of measurement for electrical power.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"A unit to measure water","B":"A unit to measure electrical power","C":"A type of light bulb","D":"A way to save money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A watt is a unit of measurement for electrical power.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Watt: unit of measurement for electrical power.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q042","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. They look scary. B. They suck energy even when turned off. C. They only work at night. D. They make a loud noise.","excerpt":"\"Some devices use power whenever they are plugged in, whether they are turned on or not. These energy-sucking devices are sometimes referred to as \u0027vampires.\u0027\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"They look scary.","B":"They suck energy even when turned off.","C":"They only work at night.","D":"They make a loud noise."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They are called vampires because they \"suck\" or use energy even when they are turned off.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some devices use power whenever they are plugged in, whether they are turned on or not. These energy-sucking devices are sometimes referred to as \u0027vampires.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q043","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It makes devices work faster. B. It helps you plug in more things. C. It can cut power to many devices at once. D. It uses less water.","excerpt":"\"Power strips have several outlets with a single plug. They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It makes devices work faster.","B":"It helps you plug in more things.","C":"It can cut power to many devices at once.","D":"It uses less water."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Power strips have switches to easily cut off power to devices plugged into them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Power strips have several outlets with a single plug. They have switches that can be used to easily cut off power to every device plugged into the strip.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q044","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. It keeps the home cool in the winter. B. It keeps the home warm and saves energy. C. It lets fresh air inside. D. It stops the wind from blowing.","excerpt":"\"In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"It keeps the home cool in the winter.","B":"It keeps the home warm and saves energy.","C":"It lets fresh air inside.","D":"It stops the wind from blowing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Insulation keeps heat inside the home, so it stays warm and uses less energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In cold weather, well-insulated homes get warm faster and stay warm longer than homes with poor insulation.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q045","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. It looks nice. B. It helps the environment and saves money. C. It is easy to do alone. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"It looks nice.","B":"It helps the environment and saves money.","C":"It is easy to do alone.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Insulation saves energy, which helps the environment and lowers bills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Improving a home\u0027s insulation by sealing drafts and properly insulating the roof, walls, and floor, can be one of smartest financial and environmental decisions a family can make.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q046","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Using new ideas or methods B. Doing things the old way C. Being very lazy D. Buying expensive items","excerpt":"\"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Using new ideas or methods","B":"Doing things the old way","C":"Being very lazy","D":"Buying expensive items"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Innovative means using new ideas or creative methods to solve a problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Around the world, people are finding simple and innovative ways to save water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q047","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. To store drinking water B. To collect rainwater for the garden C. To keep leaves in the yard D. To catch bugs","excerpt":"\"Inexpensive rain barrels are available at most hardware stores. Most of these barrels have a screen that keeps out leaves and other debris.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"To store drinking water","B":"To collect rainwater for the garden","C":"To keep leaves in the yard","D":"To catch bugs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rain barrels collect rainwater, which can be used to water gardens.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Inexpensive rain barrels are available at most hardware stores. Most of these barrels have a screen that keeps out leaves and other debris.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q048","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. Flush it more often. B. Put a brick in the tank to use less water. C. Use more toilet paper. D. Buy a new house.","excerpt":"\"A great deal of the water used in any home is flushed down the toilet.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"Flush it more often.","B":"Put a brick in the tank to use less water.","C":"Use more toilet paper.","D":"Buy a new house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text suggests putting a brick or container in the tank to reduce water use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A great deal of the water used in any home is flushed down the toilet.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q049","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 513. A. It cleans the toilet. B. It makes the water cold. C. The tank fills with less water. D. It stops the toilet from flushing.","excerpt":"\"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 513.","choices":{"A":"It cleans the toilet.","B":"It makes the water cold.","C":"The tank fills with less water.","D":"It stops the toilet from flushing."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The brick takes up space, so the tank holds less water but still works the same way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If your family does not have a new toilet, you can try this simple trick instead. Open the back tank of your toilet, and place a brick or a sealed container of water in the tank.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w3-reduce-waste-std-q050","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 514. A. Garbage B. Emissions C. Trash D. Resources","excerpt":"\"This growing mountain of garbage and trash represents not only an attitude of indifference toward valuable natural resources, but also a serious economic and public health problem.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 514.","choices":{"A":"Garbage","B":"Emissions","C":"Trash","D":"Resources"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Emissions are substances released into the air, like pollution.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This growing mountain of garbage and trash represents not only an attitude of indifference toward valuable natural resources, but also a serious economic and public health problem.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas","grade":4,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":5,"week":4,"title":"The Himalayas","author":"Charles W. Maynard","genre":"Informational Text","essential_question":"How do landforms affect people and places?","weekly_question":"What makes the Himalayas important and unique?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["abode","range","peak","Sanskrit","central Asia"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"The Himalayas. What makes the Himalayas important and unique?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"abode\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options: A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"What does the word \"abode\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options: A. There are fourteen mountains in the world, B. The Himalayas have the world\u0027s tallest mountains, C. Mountains are very hard to climb, D. The Himalayas are 1,550 miles long","excerpt":"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet above sea level.","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options:","choices":{"A":"There are fourteen mountains in the world,","B":"The Himalayas have the world\u0027s tallest mountains,","C":"Mountains are very hard to climb,","D":"The Himalayas are 1,550 miles long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph focuses on how the Himalayas contain the highest peaks, which is the main idea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet above sea level."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q003","read_aloud":"According to the text, which country is NOT mentioned as part of the Himalayas\u0027 path? Options: A. China, B. India, C. Japan, D. Nepal","excerpt":"The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia. From China\u0027s border, they travel through Burma, Nepal, Tibet, and Bhutan, dip south to India, and spread west, ending in Afghanistan.","stem":"According to the text, which country is NOT mentioned as part of the Himalayas\u0027 path? Options:","choices":{"A":"China,","B":"India,","C":"Japan,","D":"Nepal"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists China, Burma, Nepal, Tibet, Bhutan, India, and Afghanistan, but it does not mention Japan.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia. From China\u0027s border, they travel through Burma, Nepal, Tibet, and Bhutan, dip south to India, and spread west, ending in Afghanistan."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q004","read_aloud":"What is the name of the highest mountain in the world? Options: A. The Himalayas, B. Mount Everest, C. The Rooftop of the World, D. Sir George Everest","excerpt":"The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m).","stem":"What is the name of the highest mountain in the world? Options:","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas,","B":"Mount Everest,","C":"The Rooftop of the World,","D":"Sir George Everest"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that Mount Everest is the highest peak in the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q005","read_aloud":"What does the word \"Himalaya\" mean? Options: A. House of snow, B. Highest peak, C. Rooftop of Earth, D. Ancient language","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"What does the word \"Himalaya\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"House of snow,","B":"Highest peak,","C":"Rooftop of Earth,","D":"Ancient language"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that the name Himalaya comes from words that mean \"house of snow.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"survey\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. a type of mountain B. a careful study and measurement of an area C. a picture of the land D. a trip for fun","excerpt":"\"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.\"","stem":"What does the word \"survey\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a type of mountain","B":"a careful study and measurement of an area","C":"a picture of the land","D":"a trip for fun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text tells us that Sir George Everest led a study of India. A survey means to carefully measure and study an area of land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The Himalayas are in Asia. B. The Himalayas have the tallest mountains on Earth. C. Sir George Everest climbed the mountains. D. The mountains are very old.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas are in Asia.","B":"The Himalayas have the tallest mountains on Earth.","C":"Sir George Everest climbed the mountains.","D":"The mountains are very old."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt focuses on how the Himalayan peaks are the highest in the world, which tells us the main idea is about their great height.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q008","read_aloud":"Which country is NOT mentioned as part of the Himalayas in this excerpt? A. Nepal B. India C. Afghanistan D. Japan","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia. From China\u0027s border, they travel through Burma, Nepal, Tibet, and Bhutan, dip south to India, and spread west, ending in Afghanistan.\"","stem":"Which country is NOT mentioned as part of the Himalayas in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Nepal","B":"India","C":"Afghanistan","D":"Japan"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The excerpt lists Burma, Nepal, Tibet, Bhutan, India, and Afghanistan. Japan is not mentioned in the list.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia. From China\u0027s border, they travel through Burma, Nepal, Tibet, and Bhutan, dip south to India, and spread west, ending in Afghanistan.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What does the name \"Himalaya\" mean? A. house of wind B. house of snow C. house of rocks D. house of rivers","excerpt":"\"The name \u0027Himalaya\u0027 comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.\"","stem":"What does the name \"Himalaya\" mean?","choices":{"A":"house of wind","B":"house of snow","C":"house of rocks","D":"house of rivers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that Himalaya means \"abode, or house, of snow\" in the ancient Sanskrit language.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The name \u0027Himalaya\u0027 comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why is Mount Everest called the highest peak \"in the world\"? A. Because it is the oldest mountain. B. Because it is the tallest mountain on Earth. C. Because it is in the most countries. D. Because it has the most snow.","excerpt":"\"The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m).\"","stem":"Why is Mount Everest called the highest peak \"in the world\"?","choices":{"A":"Because it is the oldest mountain.","B":"Because it is the tallest mountain on Earth.","C":"Because it is in the most countries.","D":"Because it has the most snow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says Mount Everest is the highest peak in the Himalayas \"and thus in the world,\" which means it is the tallest mountain anywhere on Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m).\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q011","read_aloud":"How far do the Himalayas stretch? A. 1,550 miles B. 2,000 miles C. 1,000 miles D. 3,000 miles","excerpt":"The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.","stem":"How far do the Himalayas stretch?","choices":{"A":"1,550 miles","B":"2,000 miles","C":"1,000 miles","D":"3,000 miles"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states the Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles in central Asia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is the highest peak in the world? A. Mount Everest B. Mount Kilimanjaro C. Mount Fuji D. Mount McKinley","excerpt":"The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m).","stem":"What is the highest peak in the world?","choices":{"A":"Mount Everest","B":"Mount Kilimanjaro","C":"Mount Fuji","D":"Mount McKinley"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states Mount Everest is the highest peak in the Himalayas and in the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q013","read_aloud":"Why are the Himalayas called the Rooftop of the World? A. they have the highest mountains on Earth B. they are the oldest mountains in the world C. they have the most snow of any mountains D. they are the widest mountain range","excerpt":"Because the highest mountains on Earth are in the Himalayas, these amazing mountains are also called the Rooftop of the World.","stem":"Why are the Himalayas called the Rooftop of the World?","choices":{"A":"they have the highest mountains on Earth","B":"they are the oldest mountains in the world","C":"they have the most snow of any mountains","D":"they are the widest mountain range"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains the Himalayas are called the Rooftop of the World because they have the highest mountains on Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Because the highest mountains on Earth are in the Himalayas, these amazing mountains are also called the Rooftop of the World."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. The Himalayas are the longest mountain range in the world. B. The Himalayas include the highest peaks and stretch across central Asia. C. The Himalayas are only in Nepal. D. The Himalayas have no snow.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level. The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas are the longest mountain range in the world.","B":"The Himalayas include the highest peaks and stretch across central Asia.","C":"The Himalayas are only in Nepal.","D":"The Himalayas have no snow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph gives facts about height and length.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level. The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What does the word \"Himalaya\" mean? A. house of fire B. house of snow C. high mountain D. roof of the world","excerpt":"\"The name \u0027Himalaya\u0027 comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow. Sanskrit is an ancient language that was spoken in India.\"","stem":"What does the word \"Himalaya\" mean?","choices":{"A":"house of fire","B":"house of snow","C":"high mountain","D":"roof of the world"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it means \"abode, or house, of snow.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The name \u0027Himalaya\u0027 comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow. Sanskrit is an ancient language that was spoken in India.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q016","read_aloud":"Which mountain range is older, the Himalayas or the Appalachians? A. The Himalayas B. The Appalachians C. They are the same age. D. Neither is older.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old.\"","stem":"Which mountain range is older, the Himalayas or the Appalachians?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas","B":"The Appalachians","C":"They are the same age.","D":"Neither is older."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The Appalachians are 250-300 million years old; the Himalayas are only 60-65 million years old.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What caused the Himalayas to form? A. Volcanic eruptions B. The Indian subcontinent bumping into Eurasia C. Glaciers carving valleys D. Wind erosion","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. … About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia. That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas.\"","stem":"What caused the Himalayas to form?","choices":{"A":"Volcanic eruptions","B":"The Indian subcontinent bumping into Eurasia","C":"Glaciers carving valleys","D":"Wind erosion"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The collision of the Indian subcontinent with Eurasia pushed up the mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. … About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia. That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What does the word survey mean in this sentence? A. A type of mountain climb B. A measurement of land C. A kind of heavy rock D. A fast river trip","excerpt":"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.","stem":"What does the word survey mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"A type of mountain climb","B":"A measurement of land","C":"A kind of heavy rock","D":"A fast river trip"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A survey is a way to measure and map an area of land. Sir George Everest led this work in India.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q019","read_aloud":"Which detail tells how tall Mount Everest is? A. It is the highest peak in the world. B. It is 29,028 feet high. C. It is on the border of Nepal. D. It was named after a man.","excerpt":"The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m).","stem":"Which detail tells how tall Mount Everest is?","choices":{"A":"It is the highest peak in the world.","B":"It is 29,028 feet high.","C":"It is on the border of Nepal.","D":"It was named after a man."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text specifically lists the height of Mount Everest as 29,028 feet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q020","read_aloud":"Where are the Himalayas located? A. In North America B. In central Asia C. Near the ocean D. In Great Britain","excerpt":"The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia. From China\u0027s border, they travel through Burma, Nepal, Tibet, and Bhutan...","stem":"Where are the Himalayas located?","choices":{"A":"In North America","B":"In central Asia","C":"Near the ocean","D":"In Great Britain"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first sentence directly states that the Himalayas are in central Asia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia. From China\u0027s border, they travel through Burma, Nepal, Tibet, and Bhutan..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q021","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is a \"subcontinent\"? Options:? A. A very small island, B. A large region that is part of a continent, C. The highest mountain peak, D. A flat area of land","excerpt":"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia...","stem":"Based on the text, what is a \"subcontinent\"? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A very small island,","B":"A large region that is part of a continent,","C":"The highest mountain peak,","D":"A flat area of land"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines a subcontinent as a \"large region that is part of a continent.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What happens when these plates bump into each other? Options:? A. The Earth stays the same, B. It forms mountains, C. The plates stop moving, D. The ocean floor gets deeper","excerpt":"The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates. These plates have moved slowly over millions of years, sometimes bumping into each other.","stem":"What happens when these plates bump into each other? Options:?","choices":{"A":"The Earth stays the same,","B":"It forms mountains,","C":"The plates stop moving,","D":"The ocean floor gets deeper"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that when plates bump together, the crust is pushed up to form mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates. These plates have moved slowly over millions of years, sometimes bumping into each other."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What caused the Himalayas to form? Options:? A. The Indian subcontinent hitting Eurasia, B. Strong winds blowing on the land, C. Many years of heavy rain, D. Large rivers carving valleys","excerpt":"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia... That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas.","stem":"What caused the Himalayas to form? Options:?","choices":{"A":"The Indian subcontinent hitting Eurasia,","B":"Strong winds blowing on the land,","C":"Many years of heavy rain,","D":"Large rivers carving valleys"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that the collision between the Indian subcontinent and Eurasia caused the land to wrinkle and form the mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia... That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q024","read_aloud":"Which of these is true about the Himalayas? Options:? A. They are only in India, B. They are found in many countries, C. They are not in Asia, D. They stop growing after many years","excerpt":"The Himalayan mountains are part of the land in many countries, from China to Afghanistan.","stem":"Which of these is true about the Himalayas? Options:?","choices":{"A":"They are only in India,","B":"They are found in many countries,","C":"They are not in Asia,","D":"They stop growing after many years"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the mountains are part of the land in many countries, stretching from China to Afghanistan.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayan mountains are part of the land in many countries, from China to Afghanistan."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l01-q025","read_aloud":"How much do the Himalayas grow every five years? Options:? A. 10 inches, B. 5 inches, C. 1 inch, D. 2 inches","excerpt":"Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing. The Himalayas are getting taller by about 1 inch (2.5 cm) every five years.","stem":"How much do the Himalayas grow every five years? Options:?","choices":{"A":"10 inches,","B":"5 inches,","C":"1 inch,","D":"2 inches"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The \"Mountain Fact\" box clearly states the mountains grow by 1 inch every five years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing. The Himalayas are getting taller by about 1 inch (2.5 cm) every five years."}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is a \"subcontinent\"? Options: A. A very small island, B. A large region that is part of a continent, C. The highest mountain peak, D. A flat area of land","excerpt":"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia...","stem":"Based on the text, what is a \"subcontinent\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"A very small island,","B":"A large region that is part of a continent,","C":"The highest mountain peak,","D":"A flat area of land"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines a subcontinent as a \"large region that is part of a continent.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What happens when these plates bump into each other? Options: A. The Earth stays the same, B. It forms mountains, C. The plates stop moving, D. The ocean floor gets deeper","excerpt":"The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates. These plates have moved slowly over millions of years, sometimes bumping into each other.","stem":"What happens when these plates bump into each other? Options:","choices":{"A":"The Earth stays the same,","B":"It forms mountains,","C":"The plates stop moving,","D":"The ocean floor gets deeper"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that when plates bump together, the crust is pushed up to form mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates. These plates have moved slowly over millions of years, sometimes bumping into each other."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What caused the Himalayas to form? Options: A. The Indian subcontinent hitting Eurasia, B. Strong winds blowing on the land, C. Many years of heavy rain, D. Large rivers carving valleys","excerpt":"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia... That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas.","stem":"What caused the Himalayas to form? Options:","choices":{"A":"The Indian subcontinent hitting Eurasia,","B":"Strong winds blowing on the land,","C":"Many years of heavy rain,","D":"Large rivers carving valleys"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that the collision between the Indian subcontinent and Eurasia caused the land to wrinkle and form the mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia... That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q004","read_aloud":"Which of these is true about the Himalayas? Options: A. They are only in India, B. They are found in many countries, C. They are not in Asia, D. They stop growing after many years","excerpt":"The Himalayan mountains are part of the land in many countries, from China to Afghanistan.","stem":"Which of these is true about the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are only in India,","B":"They are found in many countries,","C":"They are not in Asia,","D":"They stop growing after many years"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the mountains are part of the land in many countries, stretching from China to Afghanistan.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayan mountains are part of the land in many countries, from China to Afghanistan."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q005","read_aloud":"How much do the Himalayas grow every five years? Options: A. 10 inches, B. 5 inches, C. 1 inch, D. 2 inches","excerpt":"Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing. The Himalayas are getting taller by about 1 inch (2.5 cm) every five years.","stem":"How much do the Himalayas grow every five years? Options:","choices":{"A":"10 inches,","B":"5 inches,","C":"1 inch,","D":"2 inches"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The \"Mountain Fact\" box clearly states the mountains grow by 1 inch every five years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing. The Himalayas are getting taller by about 1 inch (2.5 cm) every five years."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"subcontinent\" mean in this sentence? A. a small island in the ocean B. a large region that is part of a continent C. a country with no people D. a type of rock","excerpt":"\"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia.\"","stem":"What does \"subcontinent\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a small island in the ocean","B":"a large region that is part of a continent","C":"a country with no people","D":"a type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the Indian subcontinent bumped into Eurasia. A subcontinent is a large region that is part of a bigger continent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. The Indian subcontinent bumped into Eurasia. B. The Himalayas began forming. C. Mount Everest was named. D. People started climbing the mountains.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago... About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia.\"","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"The Indian subcontinent bumped into Eurasia.","B":"The Himalayas began forming.","C":"Mount Everest was named.","D":"People started climbing the mountains."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the Himalayas began forming 60 to 65 million years ago, and the Indian subcontinent bumped into Eurasia about 50 million years ago. So the mountains began forming first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago... About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q008","read_aloud":"How are the Himalayas different from the Appalachian range? A. The Appalachians are older than the Himalayas. B. The Himalayas are in the United States. C. The Appalachians are taller than the Himalayas. D. Both are the same age.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old.\"","stem":"How are the Himalayas different from the Appalachian range?","choices":{"A":"The Appalachians are older than the Himalayas.","B":"The Himalayas are in the United States.","C":"The Appalachians are taller than the Himalayas.","D":"Both are the same age."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the Appalachians are 250 to 300 million years old, while the Himalayas began forming only 60 to 65 million years ago. This means the Appalachians are much older.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q009","read_aloud":"How are the Himalayas changing today? A. They are getting smaller. B. They are staying the same height. C. They are getting taller. D. They are moving to a new place.","excerpt":"\"Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing. The Himalayas are getting taller by about 1 inch (2.5 cm) every five years.\"","stem":"How are the Himalayas changing today?","choices":{"A":"They are getting smaller.","B":"They are staying the same height.","C":"They are getting taller.","D":"They are moving to a new place."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says the tectonic plates are still moving and the Himalayas are \"still growing\" and \"getting taller\" every five years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing. The Himalayas are getting taller by about 1 inch (2.5 cm) every five years.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q010","read_aloud":"What is \"plate tectonics\"? A. the study of dinner plates B. the movement of Earth\u0027s crust C. a type of mountain rock D. a way to map the ocean","excerpt":"\"Scientists call the movement of Earth\u0027s crust plate tectonics.\"","stem":"What is \"plate tectonics\"?","choices":{"A":"the study of dinner plates","B":"the movement of Earth\u0027s crust","C":"a type of mountain rock","D":"a way to map the ocean"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly defines plate tectonics as the movement of Earth\u0027s crust, which is made of huge slabs of rock called plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists call the movement of Earth\u0027s crust plate tectonics.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q011","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"subcontinent\"? A. large region that is part of a continent B. small island in the ocean C. deep valley between mountains D. flat land near the sea","excerpt":"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"subcontinent\"?","choices":{"A":"large region that is part of a continent","B":"small island in the ocean","C":"deep valley between mountains","D":"flat land near the sea"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Subcontinent means a large region that is part of a continent. The text describes India as a subcontinent that moved into Eurasia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What happens when tectonic plates bump together? A. the crust is pushed up and forms mountains B. the ocean water rises and floods land C. the weather becomes colder and snowier D. the rivers dry up and disappear","excerpt":"When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains.","stem":"What happens when tectonic plates bump together?","choices":{"A":"the crust is pushed up and forms mountains","B":"the ocean water rises and floods land","C":"the weather becomes colder and snowier","D":"the rivers dry up and disappear"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says when plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and forms mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What are the Himalayas called based on how they formed? A. fold mountains B. volcanic mountains C. block mountains D. dome mountains","excerpt":"That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas. These huge wrinkles are called fold mountains.","stem":"What are the Himalayas called based on how they formed?","choices":{"A":"fold mountains","B":"volcanic mountains","C":"block mountains","D":"dome mountains"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains the Himalayas are called fold mountains because they formed when the land mass wrinkled.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas. These huge wrinkles are called fold mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q014","read_aloud":"When did the Himalayas begin forming? A. 60 to 65 million years ago B. 100 to 150 million years ago C. 10 to 20 million years ago D. 250 to 300 million years ago","excerpt":"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago.","stem":"When did the Himalayas begin forming?","choices":{"A":"60 to 65 million years ago","B":"100 to 150 million years ago","C":"10 to 20 million years ago","D":"250 to 300 million years ago"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states the Himalayas began forming 60 to 65 million years ago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q015","read_aloud":"How do the Himalayas compare to the Appalachian Mountains? A. the Himalayas are younger than the Appalachians B. the Himalayas are older than the Appalachians C. both mountain ranges are the same age D. the Appalachians are still growing taller","excerpt":"The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old.","stem":"How do the Himalayas compare to the Appalachian Mountains?","choices":{"A":"the Himalayas are younger than the Appalachians","B":"the Himalayas are older than the Appalachians","C":"both mountain ranges are the same age","D":"the Appalachians are still growing taller"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the Himalayas are 60-65 million years old while the Appalachians are 250-300 million years old, making the Himalayas younger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What does subcontinent mean? A. a small island B. a large region that is part of a continent C. a type of mountain D. a deep ocean trench","excerpt":"\"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia.\"","stem":"What does subcontinent mean?","choices":{"A":"a small island","B":"a large region that is part of a continent","C":"a type of mountain","D":"a deep ocean trench"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"subcontinent large region that is part of a continent.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q017","read_aloud":"What happens right after two plates bump together? A. They stop moving. B. The crust is pushed up and forms mountains. C. The crust melts. D. The ocean floods the land.","excerpt":"\"The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates. These plates have moved slowly over millions of years, sometimes bumping into each other. When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains.\"","stem":"What happens right after two plates bump together?","choices":{"A":"They stop moving.","B":"The crust is pushed up and forms mountains.","C":"The crust melts.","D":"The ocean floods the land."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says when plates bump, the crust is pushed up and forms mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates. These plates have moved slowly over millions of years, sometimes bumping into each other. When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q018","read_aloud":"Why is limestone found high in the Himalayas? A. Because sea creatures climbed the mountains. B. Because the ocean floor was pushed up into mountains. C. Because people carried it there. D. Because limestone is formed by wind.","excerpt":"\"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago. Plate tectonic forces pushed the sea floors into high mountains. Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\"","stem":"Why is limestone found high in the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"Because sea creatures climbed the mountains.","B":"Because the ocean floor was pushed up into mountains.","C":"Because people carried it there.","D":"Because limestone is formed by wind."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The ocean floor (with sea creature fossils) was pushed up into mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago. Plate tectonic forces pushed the sea floors into high mountains. Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q019","read_aloud":"Are the Himalayas still growing today? A. No, they finished growing millions of years ago. B. Yes, they get about 1 inch taller every five years. C. They are shrinking. D. They stay the same height.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. … EVEN TODAY, THE TECTONIC PLATES ARE STILL MOVING, AND THE HIMALAYAS ARE STILL GROWING. THE HIMALAYAS ARE GETTING TALLER BY ABOUT 1 INCH (2.5 CM) EVERY FIVE YEARS.\"","stem":"Are the Himalayas still growing today?","choices":{"A":"No, they finished growing millions of years ago.","B":"Yes, they get about 1 inch taller every five years.","C":"They are shrinking.","D":"They stay the same height."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact box says the plates are still moving and the Himalayas are still growing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. … EVEN TODAY, THE TECTONIC PLATES ARE STILL MOVING, AND THE HIMALAYAS ARE STILL GROWING. THE HIMALAYAS ARE GETTING TALLER BY ABOUT 1 INCH (2.5 CM) EVERY FIVE YEARS.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q020","read_aloud":"If you found a fossil of a sea creature on top of a very high mountain, what could you infer? A. The mountain was once under the ocean. B. The sea creature climbed the mountain. C. The fossil was planted there by people. D. The sea creature could fly.","excerpt":"\"Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures that lived and died millions of years ago.\"","stem":"If you found a fossil of a sea creature on top of a very high mountain, what could you infer?","choices":{"A":"The mountain was once under the ocean.","B":"The sea creature climbed the mountain.","C":"The fossil was planted there by people.","D":"The sea creature could fly."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Limestone fossils show the area was once ocean floor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures that lived and died millions of years ago.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q021","read_aloud":"How does the age of the Himalayas compare to the Appalachian range? A. The Himalayas are much older. B. Both ranges are the same age. C. The Himalayas are much younger. D. The Appalachians are very young.","excerpt":"The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old.","stem":"How does the age of the Himalayas compare to the Appalachian range?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas are much older.","B":"Both ranges are the same age.","C":"The Himalayas are much younger.","D":"The Appalachians are very young."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The numbers show that the Appalachians are much older (250-300 million years) than the Himalayas (60-65 million years).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range in the eastern United States is from 250 to 300 million years old."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q022","read_aloud":"What causes mountains to form according to the text? A. The plates bump together. B. The oceans get deeper. C. The wind blows hard. D. The snow falls on top.","excerpt":"When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains. Scientists call the movement of Earth\u0027s crust plate tectonics.","stem":"What causes mountains to form according to the text?","choices":{"A":"The plates bump together.","B":"The oceans get deeper.","C":"The wind blows hard.","D":"The snow falls on top."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says that when plates bump together, the crust is pushed up to form mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains. Scientists call the movement of Earth\u0027s crust plate tectonics."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q023","read_aloud":"How were the Himalayas formed? A. By volcanoes exploding B. By land wrinkling up C. By rivers drying out D. By heavy rain falling","excerpt":"That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas. These huge wrinkles are called fold mountains.","stem":"How were the Himalayas formed?","choices":{"A":"By volcanoes exploding","B":"By land wrinkling up","C":"By rivers drying out","D":"By heavy rain falling"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the land mass wrinkled, which formed the fold mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: That event caused part of the Eurasian land mass to wrinkle, forming the Himalayas. These huge wrinkles are called fold mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What is happening to the Himalayas right now? A. They are getting smaller. B. They are not moving. C. They are getting taller. D. They are sinking down.","excerpt":"Mountain Fact Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing.","stem":"What is happening to the Himalayas right now?","choices":{"A":"They are getting smaller.","B":"They are not moving.","C":"They are getting taller.","D":"They are sinking down."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says the mountains are still growing because the plates are moving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Mountain Fact Even today, the tectonic plates are still moving, and the Himalayas are still growing."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What does the word \"abode\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"What does the word \"abode\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the context of the Himalayas, what is a \"plateau\"? Options: A. A deep hole in the ground, B. A large, high, flat area of land, C. A small hill covered in trees, D. The bottom of the ocean","excerpt":"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.","stem":"Based on the context of the Himalayas, what is a \"plateau\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"A deep hole in the ground,","B":"A large, high, flat area of land,","C":"A small hill covered in trees,","D":"The bottom of the ocean"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines a plateau as a \"large, high, flat area of land.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What do the limestone fossils tell us about the history of the Himalayas? Options: A. The mountains were once covered by the ocean, B. Sea creatures still live there today, C. The mountains were always very tall, D. Limestone is the only rock on the peaks","excerpt":"Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures that lived and died millions of years ago.","stem":"What do the limestone fossils tell us about the history of the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"The mountains were once covered by the ocean,","B":"Sea creatures still live there today,","C":"The mountains were always very tall,","D":"Limestone is the only rock on the peaks"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Because fossils of sea creatures are found high up, it shows that those peaks were once part of the ocean floor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures that lived and died millions of years ago."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What is one force that works to \"wear down\" the mountains? Options: A. Moving tectonic plates, B. The growing of new trees, C. Large glaciers, D. Farmers planting crops","excerpt":"As the Himalayas rise, other forces are working to wear them down. Over millions of years, gigantic glaciers slowly carve large valleys through the high mountains.","stem":"What is one force that works to \"wear down\" the mountains? Options:","choices":{"A":"Moving tectonic plates,","B":"The growing of new trees,","C":"Large glaciers,","D":"Farmers planting crops"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly states that \"gigantic glaciers\" are a force working to carve valleys and wear the mountains down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As the Himalayas rise, other forces are working to wear them down. Over millions of years, gigantic glaciers slowly carve large valleys through the high mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q004","read_aloud":"Where would you find forests and fertile valleys? Options: A. In the Great Himalayas, B. In the Lesser Himalayas, C. On the Outer Himalayas only, D. On the very highest peaks","excerpt":"The highest snow-covered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas. The Lesser Himalayas have peaks between 6,000 and 15,000 feet (1,829-4,572 m) tall and are covered with forests and fertile valleys.","stem":"Where would you find forests and fertile valleys? Options:","choices":{"A":"In the Great Himalayas,","B":"In the Lesser Himalayas,","C":"On the Outer Himalayas only,","D":"On the very highest peaks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that the Lesser Himalayas are the ones covered with forests and fertile valleys.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest snow-covered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas. The Lesser Himalayas have peaks between 6,000 and 15,000 feet (1,829-4,572 m) tall and are covered with forests and fertile valleys."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q005","read_aloud":"What is another name for the Outer Himalayas? Options: A. Great peaks, B. Foothills, C. Plateau, D. Temperate zones","excerpt":"The lowest, southernmost peaks are the Outer Himalayas. They are called foothills, and they have wide valleys and rivers.","stem":"What is another name for the Outer Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"Great peaks,","B":"Foothills,","C":"Plateau,","D":"Temperate zones"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Paragraph 8 mentions that the lowest peaks, the Outer Himalayas, are called foothills.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The lowest, southernmost peaks are the Outer Himalayas. They are called foothills, and they have wide valleys and rivers."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"altitude\" mean? A. the age of a mountain B. the height or distance above sea level C. the type of rock in a mountain D. the speed of wind","excerpt":"\"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago... Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\"","stem":"What does \"altitude\" mean?","choices":{"A":"the age of a mountain","B":"the height or distance above sea level","C":"the type of rock in a mountain","D":"the speed of wind"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines altitude as \"height or distance above sea level or Earth\u0027s surface.\" It tells us how high something is.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago... Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q007","read_aloud":"How does the heading \"When Continents Collide\" help the reader? A. It tells a funny story. B. It gives a clue about what the section will explain. C. It lists all the animals in the Himalayas. D. It shows the temperature of the mountains.","excerpt":"[Heading] \"When Continents Collide\" followed by \"The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates.\"","stem":"How does the heading \"When Continents Collide\" help the reader?","choices":{"A":"It tells a funny story.","B":"It gives a clue about what the section will explain.","C":"It lists all the animals in the Himalayas.","D":"It shows the temperature of the mountains."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The heading \"When Continents Collide\" tells the reader that this section will explain how continents bump into each other to form mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: [Heading] \"When Continents Collide\" followed by \"The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q008","read_aloud":"How many climate zones do the Himalayas have? A. two B. three C. four D. five","excerpt":"\"The highest snow-covered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas. The Lesser Himalayas have peaks between 6,000 and 15,000 feet... The lowest, southernmost peaks are the Outer Himalayas.\"","stem":"How many climate zones do the Himalayas have?","choices":{"A":"two","B":"three","C":"four","D":"five"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes three zones: the Great Himalayas (highest), the Lesser Himalayas (middle), and the Outer Himalayas (lowest). That makes three climate zones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The highest snow-covered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas. The Lesser Himalayas have peaks between 6,000 and 15,000 feet... The lowest, southernmost peaks are the Outer Himalayas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What does \"sacred\" mean in this sentence? A. very old B. very dirty C. holy and special D. very wide","excerpt":"\"The Ganges River in India was formed by a glacier, high in the Himalayas. The Ganges is sacred for people of the Hindu religion.\"","stem":"What does \"sacred\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"very old","B":"very dirty","C":"holy and special","D":"very wide"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text tells us the Ganges River is sacred for people of the Hindu religion. Sacred means something is holy, special, and greatly respected.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Ganges River in India was formed by a glacier, high in the Himalayas. The Ganges is sacred for people of the Hindu religion.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"plateau\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. large, high, flat area of land B. deep valley with steep sides C. tall mountain with a sharp peak D. wide plain near the ocean","excerpt":"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.","stem":"What does \"plateau\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"large, high, flat area of land","B":"deep valley with steep sides","C":"tall mountain with a sharp peak","D":"wide plain near the ocean"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Plateau means a large, high, flat area of land. The text describes the Tibetan plateau as lying north of the Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q011","read_aloud":"Where are the highest snow-covered peaks located? A. in the Great Himalayas B. in the Lesser Himalayas C. in the Outer Himalayas D. in the Tibetan plateau","excerpt":"The highest snow-covered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas.","stem":"Where are the highest snow-covered peaks located?","choices":{"A":"in the Great Himalayas","B":"in the Lesser Himalayas","C":"in the Outer Himalayas","D":"in the Tibetan plateau"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the highest snow-covered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest snow-covered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What stays on the ground year-round in the Great Himalayas? A. snow and ice B. green grass and flowers C. sand and desert plants D. rivers and lakes","excerpt":"The peaks of the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round.","stem":"What stays on the ground year-round in the Great Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"snow and ice","B":"green grass and flowers","C":"sand and desert plants","D":"rivers and lakes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states snow and ice stay on the ground year-round in the Great Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The peaks of the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q013","read_aloud":"Why is it difficult to live at the top of Mt. Everest? A. the oxygen in the air is only one-third of sea level B. there is too much rain and flooding C. the ground is too soft for building D. there are too many dangerous animals","excerpt":"Atop Mt. Everest the oxygen in the air is only one-third of that at sea level. It is difficult for plants, animals, and humans to live there.","stem":"Why is it difficult to live at the top of Mt. Everest?","choices":{"A":"the oxygen in the air is only one-third of sea level","B":"there is too much rain and flooding","C":"the ground is too soft for building","D":"there are too many dangerous animals"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains it is difficult to live atop Mt. Everest because the oxygen is only one-third of sea level.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Atop Mt. Everest the oxygen in the air is only one-third of that at sea level. It is difficult for plants, animals, and humans to live there."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What does plateau mean? A. a deep valley B. a large, high, flat area of land C. a fastflowing river D. a type of glacier","excerpt":"\"India\u0027s and Nepal\u0027s great plains lie south of the range. The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\"","stem":"What does plateau mean?","choices":{"A":"a deep valley","B":"a large, high, flat area of land","C":"a fastflowing river","D":"a type of glacier"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"plateau large, high, flat area of land.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"India\u0027s and Nepal\u0027s great plains lie south of the range. The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how altitude affects climate? A. Higher altitudes are always hot and rainy. B. Higher altitudes are colder and have snow; lower altitudes are warmer. C. Altitude has no effect on climate. D. Lower altitudes are always colder.","excerpt":"\"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there. The valleys of the Outer Himalayas … are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate. … The highest snowcovered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas.\"","stem":"What can you infer about how altitude affects climate?","choices":{"A":"Higher altitudes are always hot and rainy.","B":"Higher altitudes are colder and have snow; lower altitudes are warmer.","C":"Altitude has no effect on climate.","D":"Lower altitudes are always colder."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Higher peaks are snowcovered; lower valleys are warmer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there. The valleys of the Outer Himalayas … are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate. … The highest snowcovered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q016","read_aloud":"How do the photograph and map help you understand the text? A. They show what the mountains look like and where they are located. B. They replace the need to read the text. C. They are only for decoration. D. They show the animals that live there.","excerpt":"The text includes a photograph of Mount Everest and a map showing where the Himalayas are located.","stem":"How do the photograph and map help you understand the text?","choices":{"A":"They show what the mountains look like and where they are located.","B":"They replace the need to read the text.","C":"They are only for decoration.","D":"They show the animals that live there."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Photos and maps provide visual information that supports the text.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes a photograph of Mount Everest and a map showing where the Himalayas are located."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q017","read_aloud":"Why do trees not grow above the tree line in the Great Himalayas? A. There is too much rain. B. The altitude is too high and it is too cold. C. There is no soil. D. Animals eat all the trees.","excerpt":"\"The altitudes and climates in the Himalayas support many types of plant life. … Pine, oak, and poplar trees grow in the Lesser Himalayas. … The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.\"","stem":"Why do trees not grow above the tree line in the Great Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"There is too much rain.","B":"The altitude is too high and it is too cold.","C":"There is no soil.","D":"Animals eat all the trees."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states trees will not grow above that level because of high altitude and cold.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The altitudes and climates in the Himalayas support many types of plant life. … Pine, oak, and poplar trees grow in the Lesser Himalayas. … The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q018","read_aloud":"Why are tree roots important on steep mountainsides? A. They make the mountain look pretty. B. They hold the soil in place and prevent erosion. C. They provide food for animals. D. They make the trees grow faster.","excerpt":"\"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\"","stem":"Why are tree roots important on steep mountainsides?","choices":{"A":"They make the mountain look pretty.","B":"They hold the soil in place and prevent erosion.","C":"They provide food for animals.","D":"They make the trees grow faster."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Roots keep soil from washing or blowing away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What is a plateau? A. A deep valley with rivers B. A high, flat area of land C. A very tall pointed mountain D. A thick forest with trees","excerpt":"India\u0027s and Nepal\u0027s great plains lie south of the range. The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.","stem":"What is a plateau?","choices":{"A":"A deep valley with rivers","B":"A high, flat area of land","C":"A very tall pointed mountain","D":"A thick forest with trees"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes the Tibetan plateau as high land lying to the north, which fits the definition of a high, flat area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: India\u0027s and Nepal\u0027s great plains lie south of the range. The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q020","read_aloud":"What does this detail explain about the mountains? A. They used to be under water. B. They are made of sand. C. They are very wet today. D. They have many fish.","excerpt":"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago. Plate tectonic forces pushed the sea floors into high mountains.","stem":"What does this detail explain about the mountains?","choices":{"A":"They used to be under water.","B":"They are made of sand.","C":"They are very wet today.","D":"They have many fish."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the peaks were part of the ocean floor long ago.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago. Plate tectonic forces pushed the sea floors into high mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q021","read_aloud":"Why are there fossils in the rocks? A. Animals climbed the mountains. B. Sea creatures lived there when it was underwater. C. Scientists brought them there. D. The wind blew them to the top.","excerpt":"Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures...","stem":"Why are there fossils in the rocks?","choices":{"A":"Animals climbed the mountains.","B":"Sea creatures lived there when it was underwater.","C":"Scientists brought them there.","D":"The wind blew them to the top."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that limestone is made of fossils from sea creatures, and the land used to be the ocean floor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q022","read_aloud":"What do glaciers do to the mountains? A. They make the mountains taller. B. They carve large valleys. C. They cover the mountains in grass. D. They melt and make deserts.","excerpt":"Over millions of years, gigantic glaciers slowly carve large valleys through the high mountains.","stem":"What do glaciers do to the mountains?","choices":{"A":"They make the mountains taller.","B":"They carve large valleys.","C":"They cover the mountains in grass.","D":"They melt and make deserts."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that glaciers carve large valleys through the mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Over millions of years, gigantic glaciers slowly carve large valleys through the high mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How is the description of the Lesser Himalayas different from the highest peaks? A. The Lesser Himalayas are covered in ice. B. The Lesser Himalayas have forests. C. The Lesser Himalayas have no valleys. D. The Lesser Himalayas are higher.","excerpt":"The Lesser Himalayas have peaks between 6,000 and 15,000 feet... and are covered with forests and fertile valleys.","stem":"How is the description of the Lesser Himalayas different from the highest peaks?","choices":{"A":"The Lesser Himalayas are covered in ice.","B":"The Lesser Himalayas have forests.","C":"The Lesser Himalayas have no valleys.","D":"The Lesser Himalayas are higher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the Lesser Himalayas are covered with forests, while the highest peaks are frozen.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Lesser Himalayas have peaks between 6,000 and 15,000 feet... and are covered with forests and fertile valleys."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q024","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l03-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"altitude\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. How high something is above the surface, B. The temperature of the air, C. The amount of rain, D. The speed of the wind","excerpt":"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.","stem":"What does \"altitude\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"How high something is above the surface,","B":"The temperature of the air,","C":"The amount of rain,","D":"The speed of the wind"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Altitude refers to the height or distance above sea level or the Earth\u0027s surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q002","read_aloud":"How do the mountains change the climate of the areas around them? Options: A. By making it rain every day, B. By blocking certain types of weather, C. By cooling the air with snow, D. By moving the monsoon winds","excerpt":"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.","stem":"How do the mountains change the climate of the areas around them? Options:","choices":{"A":"By making it rain every day,","B":"By blocking certain types of weather,","C":"By cooling the air with snow,","D":"By moving the monsoon winds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the mountains act as a wall, \"blocking cold weather\" and \"humid weather.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q003","read_aloud":"When do the monsoon winds bring the most rain? Options: A. During the winter months, B. Between June and September, C. Only in the eastern parts, D. Throughout the whole year","excerpt":"Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds from June through September.","stem":"When do the monsoon winds bring the most rain? Options:","choices":{"A":"During the winter months,","B":"Between June and September,","C":"Only in the eastern parts,","D":"Throughout the whole year"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says that most of the year\u0027s rainfall comes with the monsoon winds \"from June through September.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds from June through September."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q004","read_aloud":"Why do the Outer Himalayas have a subtropical climate? Options: A. Because they are at a lower altitude, B. Because they are very close to the North Pole, C. Because they have no rivers, D. Because the wind never blows there","excerpt":"The valleys of the Outer Himalayas, such as those in India and Burma, are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain.","stem":"Why do the Outer Himalayas have a subtropical climate? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they are at a lower altitude,","B":"Because they are very close to the North Pole,","C":"Because they have no rivers,","D":"Because the wind never blows there"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text establishes earlier that different altitudes create different climates, and the lower valleys are hotter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The valleys of the Outer Himalayas, such as those in India and Burma, are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q005","read_aloud":"What is the climate like on the Plateau of Tibet? Options: A. Hot and wet, B. Tropical and rainy, C. Dry and dusty, D. Sunny and mild","excerpt":"The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long.","stem":"What is the climate like on the Plateau of Tibet? Options:","choices":{"A":"Hot and wet,","B":"Tropical and rainy,","C":"Dry and dusty,","D":"Sunny and mild"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly describes the Plateau of Tibet as being \"dry and dusty.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"erosion\" mean in this paragraph? A. the process of planting new trees B. the process of wearing away or breaking down land over time C. the process of building new mountains D. the process of making soil richer","excerpt":"\"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides.\"","stem":"What does \"erosion\" mean in this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"the process of planting new trees","B":"the process of wearing away or breaking down land over time","C":"the process of building new mountains","D":"the process of making soil richer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines erosion as \"process of wearing away or breaking down land over time.\" When trees are cut down, soil washes away in rain, which is erosion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about climbing Mount Everest? A. It is easy for everyone to do. B. It is dangerous because of low oxygen and freezing cold. C. It is best done in summer only. D. It requires no special equipment.","excerpt":"\"Even the valleys are cold and desertlike, with no trees and few plants. Atop Mt. Everest the oxygen in the air is only one-third of that at sea level. It is difficult for plants, animals, and humans to live there.\"","stem":"What can you infer about climbing Mount Everest?","choices":{"A":"It is easy for everyone to do.","B":"It is dangerous because of low oxygen and freezing cold.","C":"It is best done in summer only.","D":"It requires no special equipment."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says oxygen is only one-third of normal and it is difficult for humans to live there. This means climbing is dangerous because of the low oxygen and cold.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even the valleys are cold and desertlike, with no trees and few plants. Atop Mt. Everest the oxygen in the air is only one-third of that at sea level. It is difficult for plants, animals, and humans to live there.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The Himalayas have many different climates because of different heights. B. All parts of the Himalayas are freezing cold. C. The Outer Himalayas get the most rain. D. There are no plants in the Himalayas.","excerpt":"\"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there. The valleys of the Outer Himalayas... are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate... The highest snow-covered peaks... are frozen worlds.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas have many different climates because of different heights.","B":"All parts of the Himalayas are freezing cold.","C":"The Outer Himalayas get the most rain.","D":"There are no plants in the Himalayas."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The first sentence states that \"wide differences of altitude create the many climates.\" The rest of the paragraph gives examples of these different climates at different heights.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there. The valleys of the Outer Himalayas... are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate... The highest snow-covered peaks... are frozen worlds.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q009","read_aloud":"Why do farmers in the Lesser Himalayas need to worry about cutting down too many trees? A. The trees might fall on their houses. B. Without tree roots, soil will wash away and erosion will happen. C. The trees are needed for shade only. D. Cutting trees makes the mountains taller.","excerpt":"\"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\"","stem":"Why do farmers in the Lesser Himalayas need to worry about cutting down too many trees?","choices":{"A":"The trees might fall on their houses.","B":"Without tree roots, soil will wash away and erosion will happen.","C":"The trees are needed for shade only.","D":"Cutting trees makes the mountains taller."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that tree roots keep soil from washing away in rain. If too many trees are cut down, the soil will erode, which hurts farming.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q010","read_aloud":"How has human activity changed the Outer Himalayas? A. People have made the mountains taller. B. People have cut down forests to use the land for farming and grazing. C. People have built cities on top of the peaks. D. People have added more trees to the area.","excerpt":"\"The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested. The land is now either farmed or used to graze goats and other livestock.\"","stem":"How has human activity changed the Outer Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"People have made the mountains taller.","B":"People have cut down forests to use the land for farming and grazing.","C":"People have built cities on top of the peaks.","D":"People have added more trees to the area."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the Outer Himalayas \"once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested.\" Now the land is used for farming or grazing animals. This shows how human activity changed the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested. The land is now either farmed or used to graze goats and other livestock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"altitude\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. height or distance above sea level B. the width of a mountain range C. the temperature of the air D. the amount of rainfall in an area","excerpt":"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.","stem":"What does \"altitude\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"height or distance above sea level","B":"the width of a mountain range","C":"the temperature of the air","D":"the amount of rainfall in an area"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Altitude means height or distance above sea level. The text says differences in altitude create different climates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q012","read_aloud":"What is the climate like in the Outer Himalayas valleys? A. subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain B. frozen with snow all year long C. dry desert with almost no rain D. cold tundra with short summers","excerpt":"The valleys of the Outer Himalayas, such as those in India and Burma, are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain.","stem":"What is the climate like in the Outer Himalayas valleys?","choices":{"A":"subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain","B":"frozen with snow all year long","C":"dry desert with almost no rain","D":"cold tundra with short summers"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes the Outer Himalayas valleys as subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The valleys of the Outer Himalayas, such as those in India and Burma, are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What do the different altitudes and climates support? A. many types of plant life B. only one type of tree C. no plants at all D. only desert cacti","excerpt":"The altitudes and climates in the Himalayas support many types of plant life.","stem":"What do the different altitudes and climates support?","choices":{"A":"many types of plant life","B":"only one type of tree","C":"no plants at all","D":"only desert cacti"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states the altitudes and climates support many types of plant life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The altitudes and climates in the Himalayas support many types of plant life."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q014","read_aloud":"If you were planting trees on a steep hillside, why would this be helpful? A. tree roots keep soil from washing away in rain B. trees make the hillside look more colorful C. trees attract more birds to the area D. trees provide shade for people hiking","excerpt":"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides.","stem":"If you were planting trees on a steep hillside, why would this be helpful?","choices":{"A":"tree roots keep soil from washing away in rain","B":"trees make the hillside look more colorful","C":"trees attract more birds to the area","D":"trees provide shade for people hiking"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the text\u0027s information about tree roots preventing erosion to a new situation about planting on hillsides.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q015","read_aloud":"How do these three factors work together to affect plant life? A. they determine which plants can survive in each area B. they make all plants grow at the same speed C. they cause plants to change color with the seasons D. they help plants grow taller than in other places","excerpt":"Rainfall, temperatures, and oxygen all affect the species of trees and plants that live in the mountains and in the valleys.","stem":"How do these three factors work together to affect plant life?","choices":{"A":"they determine which plants can survive in each area","B":"they make all plants grow at the same speed","C":"they cause plants to change color with the seasons","D":"they help plants grow taller than in other places"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows how rainfall, temperatures, and oxygen work together to determine which plant species can live in different areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Rainfall, temperatures, and oxygen all affect the species of trees and plants that live in the mountains and in the valleys."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What does altitude mean? A. the width of a mountain B. height or distance above sea level or Earth\u0027s surface C. the depth of a valley D. the speed of wind","excerpt":"\"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.\"","stem":"What does altitude mean?","choices":{"A":"the width of a mountain","B":"height or distance above sea level or Earth\u0027s surface","C":"the depth of a valley","D":"the speed of wind"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"altitude height or distance above sea level or Earth\u0027s surface.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q017","read_aloud":"How is the climate of the Outer Himalayas different from the Great Himalayas? A. The Outer Himalayas are colder. B. The Outer Himalayas are warmer with more rain; the Great Himalayas are cold and snowy. C. Both have the same climate. D. The Great Himalayas are hot and rainy.","excerpt":"\"The Outer Himalayas … are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate. … The highest snowcovered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas.\"","stem":"How is the climate of the Outer Himalayas different from the Great Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"The Outer Himalayas are colder.","B":"The Outer Himalayas are warmer with more rain; the Great Himalayas are cold and snowy.","C":"Both have the same climate.","D":"The Great Himalayas are hot and rainy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes different climate zones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Outer Himalayas … are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate. … The highest snowcovered peaks lie in the Great Himalayas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q018","read_aloud":"What causes most of the rainfall in the Himalayas? A. Snow melting B. Monsoon winds C. Ocean currents D. Earthquakes","excerpt":"\"Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds from June through September. The eastern Himalayas receive more rain.\"","stem":"What causes most of the rainfall in the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"Snow melting","B":"Monsoon winds","C":"Ocean currents","D":"Earthquakes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says rainfall comes with monsoon winds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds from June through September. The eastern Himalayas receive more rain.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q019","read_aloud":"How do the Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia? A. They make it colder and wetter. B. They block cold northern air and humid southern air. C. They have no effect. D. They cause earthquakes.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.\"","stem":"How do the Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia?","choices":{"A":"They make it colder and wetter.","B":"They block cold northern air and humid southern air.","C":"They have no effect.","D":"They cause earthquakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states they block cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q020","read_aloud":"What does altitude mean in this sentence? A. The temperature of the air B. The amount of rain falling C. The height above sea level D. The size of the mountain","excerpt":"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.","stem":"What does altitude mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"The temperature of the air","B":"The amount of rain falling","C":"The height above sea level","D":"The size of the mountain"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Altitude measures how high something is above the Earth\u0027s surface or sea level.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What kind of climate do the Outer Himalayas have? A. Cold and snowy B. Dry and dusty C. Hot and rainy D. Windy and cool","excerpt":"The valleys of the Outer Himalayas... are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain.","stem":"What kind of climate do the Outer Himalayas have?","choices":{"A":"Cold and snowy","B":"Dry and dusty","C":"Hot and rainy","D":"Windy and cool"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes the Outer Himalayas as subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The valleys of the Outer Himalayas... are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How do the mountains change the climate? A. They block cold and humid weather. B. They make the whole area very hot. C. They stop all the wind from blowing. D. They cause it to rain every day.","excerpt":"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.","stem":"How do the mountains change the climate?","choices":{"A":"They block cold and humid weather.","B":"They make the whole area very hot.","C":"They stop all the wind from blowing.","D":"They cause it to rain every day."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the mountains block cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q023","read_aloud":"Why would many people live in the Kathmandu valley? A. It is at the very top of the mountains. B. It is too cold for trees to grow. C. It has a good climate for farming. D. It is covered by thick glaciers.","excerpt":"The Kathmandu valley of Nepal, in the temperate zone, is populated with many farms and several cities.","stem":"Why would many people live in the Kathmandu valley?","choices":{"A":"It is at the very top of the mountains.","B":"It is too cold for trees to grow.","C":"It has a good climate for farming.","D":"It is covered by thick glaciers."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The valley is in the temperate zone and has many farms, so the climate is good for growing food.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Kathmandu valley of Nepal, in the temperate zone, is populated with many farms and several cities."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q024","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why is the Plateau of Tibet dry? A. The mountains block humid weather from the south. B. It is too high for water to exist. C. There are too many trees there. D. The sun is too hot.","excerpt":"The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long.","stem":"Based on the text, why is the Plateau of Tibet dry?","choices":{"A":"The mountains block humid weather from the south.","B":"It is too high for water to exist.","C":"There are too many trees there.","D":"The sun is too hot."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text earlier says the Himalayas block humid weather from the south, which explains why the area to the north is dry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l04-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the context, what is \"erosion\"? Options: A. Planting new flowers, B. The wearing away of land, C. Keeping soil in one place, D. Cutting down trees","excerpt":"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides.","stem":"Based on the context, what is \"erosion\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Planting new flowers,","B":"The wearing away of land,","C":"Keeping soil in one place,","D":"Cutting down trees"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines erosion as the process of wearing away or breaking down land over time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q002","read_aloud":"What happens to the soil when trees are removed? Options: A. It gets harder and stronger, B. It stays in the same place, C. It is more likely to wash or blow away, D. It grows more wildflowers","excerpt":"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.","stem":"What happens to the soil when trees are removed? Options:","choices":{"A":"It gets harder and stronger,","B":"It stays in the same place,","C":"It is more likely to wash or blow away,","D":"It grows more wildflowers"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that roots keep the soil in place; without them, the soil is not protected from rain and wind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q003","read_aloud":"What is the main reason trees do not grow at the very top of the Great Himalayas? Options: A. There is not enough soil, B. The altitude is too high and cold, C. People have cut them all down, D. There is too much oxygen","excerpt":"Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.","stem":"What is the main reason trees do not grow at the very top of the Great Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"There is not enough soil,","B":"The altitude is too high and cold,","C":"People have cut them all down,","D":"There is too much oxygen"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says trees cannot grow above the tree line due to the \"high altitude and the cold.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q004","read_aloud":"How has human activity changed the Outer Himalayas? Options: A. They made the forests grow bigger, B. They changed the forest land into farms, C. They added more trees to the slopes, D. They stopped all farming there","excerpt":"The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested. The land is now either farmed or used to graze goats and other livestock.","stem":"How has human activity changed the Outer Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"They made the forests grow bigger,","B":"They changed the forest land into farms,","C":"They added more trees to the slopes,","D":"They stopped all farming there"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions that forests were harvested and the land is now used for farming or grazing animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested. The land is now either farmed or used to graze goats and other livestock."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q005","read_aloud":"What can be found on the mountainsides even where there are no trees? Options: A. Large animals like tigers, B. Beautiful wildflowers, C. Thick tropical forests, D. Deep, frozen lakes","excerpt":"Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides. Orchids, lilies, anemones, poppies, and rhododendron flowers flourish among the mountains.","stem":"What can be found on the mountainsides even where there are no trees? Options:","choices":{"A":"Large animals like tigers,","B":"Beautiful wildflowers,","C":"Thick tropical forests,","D":"Deep, frozen lakes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions that wildflowers like orchids and lilies \"flourish\" on the slopes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides. Orchids, lilies, anemones, poppies, and rhododendron flowers flourish among the mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q006","read_aloud":"How have the animals of the Outer Himalayas changed? A. The same animals live there now as before. B. Fewer types of animals live there because forests have been cut down. C. More animals live there now than before. D. All the animals have moved to the Great Himalayas.","excerpt":"\"Leopards, tigers, deer, and Indian rhinoceroses were once plentiful in the forests of the Outer Himalayas... Black bears, leopards and other cats, and the muntjac... now live in the few existing forests.\"","stem":"How have the animals of the Outer Himalayas changed?","choices":{"A":"The same animals live there now as before.","B":"Fewer types of animals live there because forests have been cut down.","C":"More animals live there now than before.","D":"All the animals have moved to the Great Himalayas."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says large animals like tigers and rhinos \"were once plentiful\" but now only smaller animals like black bears and muntjac live in the \"few existing forests.\" This shows fewer animal types live there now.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Leopards, tigers, deer, and Indian rhinoceroses were once plentiful in the forests of the Outer Himalayas... Black bears, leopards and other cats, and the muntjac... now live in the few existing forests.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use in this excerpt? A. cause and effect B. problem and solution C. description D. compare and contrast","excerpt":"\"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate. People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat.\"","stem":"What text structure does the author use in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"cause and effect","B":"problem and solution","C":"description","D":"compare and contrast"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author describes what a yak is, where it lives, what climate it likes, and how people use it. This is a description text structure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate. People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q008","read_aloud":"If you were planning a trip to the eastern Himalayas, when might you want to bring an umbrella? A. December through February B. March through May C. June through September D. October through November","excerpt":"\"Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds from June through September. The eastern Himalayas receive more rain.\"","stem":"If you were planning a trip to the eastern Himalayas, when might you want to bring an umbrella?","choices":{"A":"December through February","B":"March through May","C":"June through September","D":"October through November"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says most rainfall comes from June through September with monsoon winds. The eastern Himalayas get even more rain, so you would need an umbrella during these months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds from June through September. The eastern Himalayas receive more rain.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q009","read_aloud":"How do the Himalayas act like a wall? A. They stop weather from moving across Asia. B. They keep all rain from falling anywhere. C. They make the whole continent cold. D. They cause earthquakes in China.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south. The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty.\"","stem":"How do the Himalayas act like a wall?","choices":{"A":"They stop weather from moving across Asia.","B":"They keep all rain from falling anywhere.","C":"They make the whole continent cold.","D":"They cause earthquakes in China."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the Himalayas block cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south. Like a wall, they stop weather from moving freely across the region.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south. The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"erosion\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. process of wearing away or breaking down land over time B. process of building up new land with fresh soil C. process of planting new trees in empty areas D. process of measuring the height of mountains","excerpt":"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion.","stem":"What does \"erosion\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"process of wearing away or breaking down land over time","B":"process of building up new land with fresh soil","C":"process of planting new trees in empty areas","D":"process of measuring the height of mountains"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Erosion means the process of wearing away or breaking down land over time. The text links tree cutting to erosion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What do tree roots keep soil from doing? A. washing away in rain or blowing away in wind B. turning into rocks over many years C. becoming too wet for plants to grow D. freezing during the winter months","excerpt":"They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.","stem":"What do tree roots keep soil from doing?","choices":{"A":"washing away in rain or blowing away in wind","B":"turning into rocks over many years","C":"becoming too wet for plants to grow","D":"freezing during the winter months"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states tree roots keep soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What colors the mountainsides even without trees? A. beautiful wildflowers B. green moss and ferns C. bright red berries D. golden autumn leaves","excerpt":"Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides.","stem":"What colors the mountainsides even without trees?","choices":{"A":"beautiful wildflowers","B":"green moss and ferns","C":"bright red berries","D":"golden autumn leaves"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides even where trees have been cut down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q013","read_aloud":"If you planted a pine tree at 18,000 feet in the Great Himalayas, what would likely happen? A. it would not grow because of high altitude and cold B. it would grow very tall and strong C. it would produce extra pine cones D. it would change color with the seasons","excerpt":"The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.","stem":"If you planted a pine tree at 18,000 feet in the Great Himalayas, what would likely happen?","choices":{"A":"it would not grow because of high altitude and cold","B":"it would grow very tall and strong","C":"it would produce extra pine cones","D":"it would change color with the seasons"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the text\u0027s information about the tree line to predict what would happen to a tree planted above that line.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q014","read_aloud":"What does the variety of flowers tell you about the Lesser Himalayas environment? A. it has conditions that support many different plant types B. it is too cold for most plants to survive C. it has very little rainfall throughout the year D. it is covered with ice and snow most of the time","excerpt":"Orchids, lilies, anemones, poppies, and rhododendron flowers flourish among the mountains and valleys of the Lesser Himalayas.","stem":"What does the variety of flowers tell you about the Lesser Himalayas environment?","choices":{"A":"it has conditions that support many different plant types","B":"it is too cold for most plants to survive","C":"it has very little rainfall throughout the year","D":"it is covered with ice and snow most of the time"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text lists many types of flowers that flourish, showing the environment supports diverse plant life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Orchids, lilies, anemones, poppies, and rhododendron flowers flourish among the mountains and valleys of the Lesser Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What does erosion mean? A. the process of building up land B. the process of wearing away or breaking down land over time C. the process of freezing water D. the process of planting trees","excerpt":"\"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion.\"","stem":"What does erosion mean?","choices":{"A":"the process of building up land","B":"the process of wearing away or breaking down land over time","C":"the process of freezing water","D":"the process of planting trees"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"erosion process of wearing away or breaking down land over time.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What can you infer happens when trees are cut down on steep mountainsides? A. The soil stays in place. B. Erosion increases because nothing holds the soil. C. The trees grow back immediately. D. The mountains become taller.","excerpt":"\"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\"","stem":"What can you infer happens when trees are cut down on steep mountainsides?","choices":{"A":"The soil stays in place.","B":"Erosion increases because nothing holds the soil.","C":"The trees grow back immediately.","D":"The mountains become taller."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Without roots, soil washes or blows away (erosion).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q017","read_aloud":"Do you think the yak is an important animal for people in the Himalayas? Why? A. No, because it is only one animal. B. Yes, because it provides transportation, food, and materials for clothing and rope. C. No, because it is dangerous. D. Yes, but only for its milk.","excerpt":"\"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. … People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat. Yak hair is woven to make rope and cloth, and yak skin is used for leather.\"","stem":"Do you think the yak is an important animal for people in the Himalayas? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because it is only one animal.","B":"Yes, because it provides transportation, food, and materials for clothing and rope.","C":"No, because it is dangerous.","D":"Yes, but only for its milk."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists many uses of the yak.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. … People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat. Yak hair is woven to make rope and cloth, and yak skin is used for leather.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q018","read_aloud":"What is erosion in this context? A. Planting new trees on a mountain B. Soil washing or blowing away C. Heavy rain falling down D. Rocks breaking into sand","excerpt":"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place...","stem":"What is erosion in this context?","choices":{"A":"Planting new trees on a mountain","B":"Soil washing or blowing away","C":"Heavy rain falling down","D":"Rocks breaking into sand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says roots keep soil in place, so erosion happens when the soil washes or blows away because trees are gone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Why can\u0027t trees grow above 16,000 feet? A. There is not enough sunlight. B. It is too high and cold. C. There is too much snow. D. People cut them all down.","excerpt":"The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.","stem":"Why can\u0027t trees grow above 16,000 feet?","choices":{"A":"There is not enough sunlight.","B":"It is too high and cold.","C":"There is too much snow.","D":"People cut them all down."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that trees will not grow there because of the high altitude and the cold.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q020","read_aloud":"What happened to the tropical forest in the Outer Himalayas? A. It grew much larger. B. It was cut down. C. It burned in a fire. D. It turned into a desert.","excerpt":"The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested.","stem":"What happened to the tropical forest in the Outer Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"It grew much larger.","B":"It was cut down.","C":"It burned in a fire.","D":"It turned into a desert."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Harvested\" in this context means the trees were cut down by people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q021","read_aloud":"What would happen if all the trees were removed from a mountainside? A. The soil would stay in place. B. More flowers would grow. C. The soil would wash away. D. The mountain would get taller.","excerpt":"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain...","stem":"What would happen if all the trees were removed from a mountainside?","choices":{"A":"The soil would stay in place.","B":"More flowers would grow.","C":"The soil would wash away.","D":"The mountain would get taller."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says roots keep soil from washing away, so removing trees would cause the soil to wash away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q022","read_aloud":"How does the author show that nature is still beautiful in the Lesser Himalayas? A. By describing the colorful wildflowers B. by talking about the tall trees C. By explaining how deep the rivers are D. By listing the types of animals","excerpt":"Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides. Orchids, lilies, anemones, poppies, and rhododendron flowers flourish...","stem":"How does the author show that nature is still beautiful in the Lesser Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"By describing the colorful wildflowers","B":"by talking about the tall trees","C":"By explaining how deep the rivers are","D":"By listing the types of animals"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author lists beautiful wildflowers like orchids and poppies that grow there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides. Orchids, lilies, anemones, poppies, and rhododendron flowers flourish..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q023","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q024","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l05-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. plain B. valley (low are C. mountain D. glacier","excerpt":"\"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"plain","B":"valley (low are","C":"mountain","D":"glacier"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A plateau is a high, flat area; a valley is a low area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"plentiful\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. Very hard to find, B. Existing in large numbers, C. Moving to a new place, D. Living in very cold areas","excerpt":"Leopards, tigers, deer, and Indian rhinoceroses were once plentiful in the forests of the Outer Himalayas.","stem":"What does the word \"plentiful\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Very hard to find,","B":"Existing in large numbers,","C":"Moving to a new place,","D":"Living in very cold areas"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Plentiful\" means there was a large supply or number of those animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Leopards, tigers, deer, and Indian rhinoceroses were once plentiful in the forests of the Outer Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q002","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship described here? Options: A. More trees caused more animals to arrive, B. Cutting down trees caused the forest and animal life to change, C. Animals cutting trees caused the forest to grow, D. The number of animals changed before the trees were cut","excerpt":"When people cut down the trees for lumber, the forests changed and so did the types and numbers of animals that lived in them.","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship described here? Options:","choices":{"A":"More trees caused more animals to arrive,","B":"Cutting down trees caused the forest and animal life to change,","C":"Animals cutting trees caused the forest to grow,","D":"The number of animals changed before the trees were cut"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that human actions (cutting trees) resulted in environmental changes (the forests and animal populations).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When people cut down the trees for lumber, the forests changed and so did the types and numbers of animals that lived in them."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Why is the yak well-suited for living in the Himalayas? Options: A. It enjoys hot and rainy weather, B. It likes the cold, dry climate of the mountains, C. It only eats trees from the forest, D. It does not like to live on plateaus","excerpt":"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate.","stem":"Why is the yak well-suited for living in the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"It enjoys hot and rainy weather,","B":"It likes the cold, dry climate of the mountains,","C":"It only eats trees from the forest,","D":"It does not like to live on plateaus"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that the yak \"likes the cold, dry climate,\" which matches its mountain home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q004","read_aloud":"In what way do the people of the Himalayas rely on the yak? Options: A. For only meat and milk, B. For many things including work, food, and clothing, C. To protect them from other animals, D. To act as their only guides in the snow","excerpt":"People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat. Yak hair is woven to make rope and cloth, and yak skin is used for leather.","stem":"In what way do the people of the Himalayas rely on the yak? Options:","choices":{"A":"For only meat and milk,","B":"For many things including work, food, and clothing,","C":"To protect them from other animals,","D":"To act as their only guides in the snow"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists several ways the yak helps: carrying loads, pulling carts, providing food, and making materials like rope and leather.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat. Yak hair is woven to make rope and cloth, and yak skin is used for leather."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q005","read_aloud":"How are the muntjac and the common deer different? Options: A. The muntjac lives in water, B. The muntjac makes a barking sound, C. The muntjac is much larger, D. Common deer do not live in forests","excerpt":"Black bears, leopards and other cats, and the muntjac, a deer known for making a barking sound, now live in the few existing forests.","stem":"How are the muntjac and the common deer different? Options:","choices":{"A":"The muntjac lives in water,","B":"The muntjac makes a barking sound,","C":"The muntjac is much larger,","D":"Common deer do not live in forests"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes the muntjac specifically as \"a deer known for making a barking sound.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Black bears, leopards and other cats, and the muntjac, a deer known for making a barking sound, now live in the few existing forests."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q006","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"altitude\" help explain? A. why rivers form B. why different plants grow at different heights C. why the mountains are growing D. why people climb mountains","excerpt":"\"As the snow and ice of the peaks melt, they form rivers. India\u0027s great Ganges River begins in the Himalayas.\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"altitude\" help explain?","choices":{"A":"why rivers form","B":"why different plants grow at different heights","C":"why the mountains are growing","D":"why people climb mountains"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that altitude (height) creates different climates. Different altitudes have different temperatures and rainfall, which explains why different plants grow at different heights.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As the snow and ice of the peaks melt, they form rivers. India\u0027s great Ganges River begins in the Himalayas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q007","read_aloud":"Why are Sherpas good guides for climbers? A. They have lived in the steep mountain valleys for a long time. B. They are the tallest people in the world. C. They have special climbing equipment no one else has. D. They do not need oxygen to breathe.","excerpt":"\"The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas. The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas. Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.\"","stem":"Why are Sherpas good guides for climbers?","choices":{"A":"They have lived in the steep mountain valleys for a long time.","B":"They are the tallest people in the world.","C":"They have special climbing equipment no one else has.","D":"They do not need oxygen to breathe."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Sherpas \"settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas.\" Because they have lived there for a long time, they know the mountains well and make the best guides.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas. The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas. Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the story of Mallory and Irvine? A. To show that climbing Everest is easy. B. To show that exploring the Himalayas is dangerous and difficult. C. To tell a funny story about climbers. D. To explain how to use oxygen tanks.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas were some of the last mountains on Earth to be explored... After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned.\"","stem":"Why does the author include the story of Mallory and Irvine?","choices":{"A":"To show that climbing Everest is easy.","B":"To show that exploring the Himalayas is dangerous and difficult.","C":"To tell a funny story about climbers.","D":"To explain how to use oxygen tanks."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author tells us the Himalayas were \"some of the last mountains on Earth to be explored\" and that Mallory and Irvine \"never returned.\" This shows how dangerous and difficult exploring these mountains was.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas were some of the last mountains on Earth to be explored... After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q009","read_aloud":"What does the word \"However\" show in this sentence? A. The author is changing to a new topic. B. The author is showing two different ideas: danger and success. C. The author is giving a definition. D. The author is telling a joke.","excerpt":"\"Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen. However, hundreds have reached Everest\u0027s peak.\"","stem":"What does the word \"However\" show in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"The author is changing to a new topic.","B":"The author is showing two different ideas: danger and success.","C":"The author is giving a definition.","D":"The author is telling a joke."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"However\" is a signal word that shows contrast. The author first tells us many climbers died, but then uses \"However\" to show that despite the danger, hundreds also succeeded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen. However, hundreds have reached Everest\u0027s peak.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q010","read_aloud":"Why is it important that the expedition found Mallory\u0027s body at 25,000 feet? A. It proves that climbing is safe. B. It shows how dangerous and deadly the high altitude can be. C. It means Mallory reached the top of Everest. D. It shows that bodies do not decay in cold weather.","excerpt":"\"In 1999, an expedition searched for clues to the 1924 disappearance of George Mallory and Andrew Irvine. The team found George Mallory\u0027s body at more than 25,000 feet (7,620 m).\"","stem":"Why is it important that the expedition found Mallory\u0027s body at 25,000 feet?","choices":{"A":"It proves that climbing is safe.","B":"It shows how dangerous and deadly the high altitude can be.","C":"It means Mallory reached the top of Everest.","D":"It shows that bodies do not decay in cold weather."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Finding Mallory\u0027s body at 25,000 feet, below the summit, shows that even experienced climbers can die from the extreme conditions. It proves how dangerous the high altitude is.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1999, an expedition searched for clues to the 1924 disappearance of George Mallory and Andrew Irvine. The team found George Mallory\u0027s body at more than 25,000 feet (7,620 m).\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q011","read_aloud":"How does the word \"plateaus\" help you understand where yaks live? A. it tells you yaks live on high, flat areas of land B. it tells you yaks live in deep ocean waters C. it tells you yaks live in hot desert areas D. it tells you yaks live in thick tropical forests","excerpt":"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate.","stem":"How does the word \"plateaus\" help you understand where yaks live?","choices":{"A":"it tells you yaks live on high, flat areas of land","B":"it tells you yaks live in deep ocean waters","C":"it tells you yaks live in hot desert areas","D":"it tells you yaks live in thick tropical forests"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Plateaus are high, flat areas of land. The text says yaks live on high plateaus, helping readers picture their habitat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What are two ways people use yaks? A. to carry heavy loads and as a source of milk and meat B. to pull sleds and to make warm clothing C. to guard homes and to pull farm plows D. to race in competitions and for their fur","excerpt":"People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat.","stem":"What are two ways people use yaks?","choices":{"A":"to carry heavy loads and as a source of milk and meat","B":"to pull sleds and to make warm clothing","C":"to guard homes and to pull farm plows","D":"to race in competitions and for their fur"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states people raise yaks to carry loads and pull carts, and they provide milk and meat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q013","read_aloud":"What can be made from yak hair and skin? A. rope, cloth, and leather B. tents, shoes, and blankets C. tools, weapons, and baskets D. paint, ink, and paper","excerpt":"Yak hair is woven to make rope and cloth, and yak skin is used for leather.","stem":"What can be made from yak hair and skin?","choices":{"A":"rope, cloth, and leather","B":"tents, shoes, and blankets","C":"tools, weapons, and baskets","D":"paint, ink, and paper"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says yak hair is woven into rope and cloth, and yak skin is used for leather.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Yak hair is woven to make rope and cloth, and yak skin is used for leather."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q014","read_aloud":"If you were raising animals in a cold, high-altitude area, why might you choose yaks? A. they are adapted to cold, dry, high-altitude climates B. they grow very quickly and reproduce often C. they can live on very little food and water D. they are gentle and easy to train for shows","excerpt":"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate.","stem":"If you were raising animals in a cold, high-altitude area, why might you choose yaks?","choices":{"A":"they are adapted to cold, dry, high-altitude climates","B":"they grow very quickly and reproduce often","C":"they can live on very little food and water","D":"they are gentle and easy to train for shows"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply information about yak adaptations to decide why they would be good for high-altitude farming.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q015","read_aloud":"How does cutting down trees affect animal populations? A. it changes the habitat so different animals can live there B. it makes all animals move to warmer climates C. it causes animals to grow larger and stronger D. it helps animals find more food and water","excerpt":"Leopards, tigers, deer, and Indian rhinoceroses were once plentiful in the forests of the Outer Himalayas. When people cut down the trees for lumber, the forests changed and so did the types and numbers of animals that lived in them.","stem":"How does cutting down trees affect animal populations?","choices":{"A":"it changes the habitat so different animals can live there","B":"it makes all animals move to warmer climates","C":"it causes animals to grow larger and stronger","D":"it helps animals find more food and water"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that when forests change due to tree cutting, the types and numbers of animals also change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Leopards, tigers, deer, and Indian rhinoceroses were once plentiful in the forests of the Outer Himalayas. When people cut down the trees for lumber, the forests changed and so did the types and numbers of animals that lived in them."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for altitude? A. depth B. height C. width D. temperature","excerpt":"\"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for altitude?","choices":{"A":"depth","B":"height","C":"width","D":"temperature"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Altitude means height above sea level.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q017","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose in writing The Himalayas? A. To persuade readers to climb Mount Everest B. To inform readers about the geography, climate, life, and history of the Himalayas C. To tell a story about a family living in the mountains D. To argue that the Himalayas are not important","excerpt":"The text includes facts about the height, formation, climate, plants, animals, people, and climbing history of the Himalayas.","stem":"What is the author\u0027s main purpose in writing The Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"To persuade readers to climb Mount Everest","B":"To inform readers about the geography, climate, life, and history of the Himalayas","C":"To tell a story about a family living in the mountains","D":"To argue that the Himalayas are not important"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text is informational, giving many facts about the Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes facts about the height, formation, climate, plants, animals, people, and climbing history of the Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the Great Himalayas from this passage? A. Many people live there. B. Very few people live there, but animals have adapted to the harsh conditions. C. No animals live there. D. The weather is warm and rainy.","excerpt":"\"The Great Himalayas, a land of few people, are home to wolves, snow leopards, small, bushytailed marmots, and musk deer. A kind of tiny black spider lives as high as 22,500 feet (6,858 m).\"","stem":"What can you infer about the Great Himalayas from this passage?","choices":{"A":"Many people live there.","B":"Very few people live there, but animals have adapted to the harsh conditions.","C":"No animals live there.","D":"The weather is warm and rainy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"a land of few people\" but lists many animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Great Himalayas, a land of few people, are home to wolves, snow leopards, small, bushytailed marmots, and musk deer. A kind of tiny black spider lives as high as 22,500 feet (6,858 m).\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Why are Sherpas valued as guides for climbing the Himalayas? A. They are good cooks. B. They know the mountains well from living there for generations. C. They are the only people allowed to climb. D. They are afraid of the mountains.","excerpt":"\"The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas. The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steepsided valleys of the Himalayas. Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.\"","stem":"Why are Sherpas valued as guides for climbing the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"They are good cooks.","B":"They know the mountains well from living there for generations.","C":"They are the only people allowed to climb.","D":"They are afraid of the mountains."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Their knowledge of the terrain makes them excellent guides.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas. The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steepsided valleys of the Himalayas. Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Which word describes where the yak lives? A. Subcontinent B. Plateau C. Valley D. Foothill","excerpt":"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate.","stem":"Which word describes where the yak lives?","choices":{"A":"Subcontinent","B":"Plateau","C":"Valley","D":"Foothill"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the yak lives on high plateaus.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q021","read_aloud":"What was the effect of people cutting down trees? A. More animals moved in. B. The animals stayed the same. C. The types of animals changed. D. The forests became thicker.","excerpt":"When people cut down the trees for lumber, the forests changed and so did the types and numbers of animals that lived in them.","stem":"What was the effect of people cutting down trees?","choices":{"A":"More animals moved in.","B":"The animals stayed the same.","C":"The types of animals changed.","D":"The forests became thicker."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says the forests changed, which caused the types and numbers of animals to change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When people cut down the trees for lumber, the forests changed and so did the types and numbers of animals that lived in them."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q022","read_aloud":"Which animal lives in the Great Himalayas? A. Indian rhinoceros B. Snow leopard C. Tiger D. Indian elephant","excerpt":"The Great Himalayas, a land of few people, are home to wolves, snow leopards, small, bushy-tailed marmots, and musk deer.","stem":"Which animal lives in the Great Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"Indian rhinoceros","B":"Snow leopard","C":"Tiger","D":"Indian elephant"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The list of animals in the Great Himalayas includes the snow leopard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Great Himalayas, a land of few people, are home to wolves, snow leopards, small, bushy-tailed marmots, and musk deer."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How do people use yaks? (Choose the best answer). A. They use them for food and work. B. They keep them as house pets. C. They use them to hunt tigers. D. They race them for sport.","excerpt":"People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat.","stem":"How do people use yaks? (Choose the best answer).","choices":{"A":"They use them for food and work.","B":"They keep them as house pets.","C":"They use them to hunt tigers.","D":"They race them for sport."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says yaks carry loads, pull carts, and provide milk and meat.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People raise yaks to carry heavy loads and to pull carts. Yaks are a source of milk and meat."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q024","read_aloud":"What conclusion can you make about the tiny spider? A. It needs warm weather to live. B. It cannot survive very high up. C. It can survive in extreme conditions. D. It is the largest animal in the mountains.","excerpt":"A kind of tiny black spider lives as high as 22,500 feet (6,858 m).","stem":"What conclusion can you make about the tiny spider?","choices":{"A":"It needs warm weather to live.","B":"It cannot survive very high up.","C":"It can survive in extreme conditions.","D":"It is the largest animal in the mountains."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Living at 22,500 feet is very high and cold, so the spider can survive in extreme conditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A kind of tiny black spider lives as high as 22,500 feet (6,858 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l06-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"settled\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. Climbed to the top, B. Moved to a place to live, C. Looked for new food, D. Left their homes behind","excerpt":"The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas.","stem":"What does the word \"settled\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Climbed to the top,","B":"Moved to a place to live,","C":"Looked for new food,","D":"Left their homes behind"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To \"settle\" in a place means to make that location your permanent home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q002","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is the most common way people in the Himalayas make a living? Options: A. Mining for gold, B. Building large cities, C. Farming and herding, D. Climbing mountains for money","excerpt":"Most people of the Himalayas are farmers who grow fruits and grains and who herd livestock.","stem":"Based on the text, what is the most common way people in the Himalayas make a living? Options:","choices":{"A":"Mining for gold,","B":"Building large cities,","C":"Farming and herding,","D":"Climbing mountains for money"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly states that \"most people\" are farmers who grow food and herd animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most people of the Himalayas are farmers who grow fruits and grains and who herd livestock."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q003","read_aloud":"Why might someone climbing the Himalayas want to hire a Sherpa? Options: A. Because Sherpas are the only ones who live in Nepal, B. Because Sherpas know the mountains very well, C. Because Sherpas want to grow fruits and grains, D. Because Sherpas are the only people who herd yaks","excerpt":"Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.","stem":"Why might someone climbing the Himalayas want to hire a Sherpa? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because Sherpas are the only ones who live in Nepal,","B":"Because Sherpas know the mountains very well,","C":"Because Sherpas want to grow fruits and grains,","D":"Because Sherpas are the only people who herd yaks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since they are known as the \"best guides,\" it implies they have the expertise needed to navigate the difficult terrain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How does the religion of the people change as you move north from India? Options: A. Everyone remains Hindu, B. The religion changes from Hindu to Buddhist, C. People stop practicing religion entirely, D. Everyone changes to a new, unnamed religion","excerpt":"Many of the people who live in the southern countries of the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas are of Indian origin and practice the Hindu religion. North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist.","stem":"How does the religion of the people change as you move north from India? Options:","choices":{"A":"Everyone remains Hindu,","B":"The religion changes from Hindu to Buddhist,","C":"People stop practicing religion entirely,","D":"Everyone changes to a new, unnamed religion"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts the people in the south (Hindu) with the Tibetan people in the north (Buddhist).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many of the people who live in the southern countries of the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas are of Indian origin and practice the Hindu religion. North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q005","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about the people of Nepal based on this fact? Options: A. They are all exactly the same, B. They come from many different backgrounds, C. They all speak the same language, D. They do not live near each other","excerpt":"Nepal has 35 separate ethnic groups.","stem":"What can you conclude about the people of Nepal based on this fact? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are all exactly the same,","B":"They come from many different backgrounds,","C":"They all speak the same language,","D":"They do not live near each other"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Having 35 separate groups shows that the population is very diverse and made of many different cultures.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Nepal has 35 separate ethnic groups."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"erosion\" have to do with the tree line? A. Erosion happens more above the tree line because there are no roots to hold soil. B. Erosion does not happen in the Great Himalayas. C. The tree line causes erosion to stop completely. D. Trees above the tree line grow faster.","excerpt":"\"The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.\"","stem":"What does \"erosion\" have to do with the tree line?","choices":{"A":"Erosion happens more above the tree line because there are no roots to hold soil.","B":"Erosion does not happen in the Great Himalayas.","C":"The tree line causes erosion to stop completely.","D":"Trees above the tree line grow faster."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that tree roots keep soil in place. Above the tree line, no trees grow, so there are no roots to prevent soil from washing away. This means erosion can happen more easily.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q007","read_aloud":"Why do yaks need thick, heavy coats? A. to look pretty for tourists B. to stay warm in the cold, high-altitude climate C. to protect them from falling rocks D. to help them run faster","excerpt":"\"The wild yak is a huge animal with long, brown-black hair forming a thick coat. Male yaks can be 6 1/2 feet (2 m) tall at the shoulders. They can weigh more than 2,000 pounds (907 kg).\"","stem":"Why do yaks need thick, heavy coats?","choices":{"A":"to look pretty for tourists","B":"to stay warm in the cold, high-altitude climate","C":"to protect them from falling rocks","D":"to help them run faster"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says yaks live in cold, dry climates on high plateaus. Their thick coats help them survive in the freezing temperatures of high altitudes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The wild yak is a huge animal with long, brown-black hair forming a thick coat. Male yaks can be 6 1/2 feet (2 m) tall at the shoulders. They can weigh more than 2,000 pounds (907 kg).\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Which detail supports the idea that the Himalayas are important for human life? A. The mountains are very tall. B. Millions of people live there and farm the land. C. The mountains are still growing. D. There are many glaciers.","excerpt":"\"About 40 million people live in the Himalayas... Most people of the Himalayas are farmers who grow fruits and grains and who herd livestock.\"","stem":"Which detail supports the idea that the Himalayas are important for human life?","choices":{"A":"The mountains are very tall.","B":"Millions of people live there and farm the land.","C":"The mountains are still growing.","D":"There are many glaciers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact that 40 million people live in the Himalayas and most are farmers shows that these mountains support human life and provide food for many people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"About 40 million people live in the Himalayas... Most people of the Himalayas are farmers who grow fruits and grains and who herd livestock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q009","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt tell us about the people of the Himalayas? A. They all follow the same religion. B. They are all from one ethnic group. C. They are diverse, with different religions and ethnic groups. D. They all speak the same language.","excerpt":"\"North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist. Nepal has 35 separate ethnic groups.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt tell us about the people of the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"They all follow the same religion.","B":"They are all from one ethnic group.","C":"They are diverse, with different religions and ethnic groups.","D":"They all speak the same language."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text tells us that Tibetans are mostly Buddhist, while Nepal has 35 separate ethnic groups. This shows the people of the Himalayas are diverse, meaning they have many different backgrounds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist. Nepal has 35 separate ethnic groups.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q010","read_aloud":"How has technology changed the exploration of the Himalayas? A. Technology has made it impossible to visit the mountains. B. Technology has made mapping easier and more exact than before. C. Technology has made the mountains shorter. D. Technology has removed all the snow.","excerpt":"\"One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks. Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible.\"","stem":"How has technology changed the exploration of the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"Technology has made it impossible to visit the mountains.","B":"Technology has made mapping easier and more exact than before.","C":"Technology has made the mountains shorter.","D":"Technology has removed all the snow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts early mapping challenges with today\u0027s technology. Aircraft and satellites now make \"exact maps possible,\" which means technology has improved exploration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks. Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q011","read_aloud":"How does knowing the number of people help you understand the text? A. it shows the Himalayas support a large human population B. it proves the Himalayas are the most crowded place on Earth C. it tells you most people there are farmers D. it explains why there are so many animals there","excerpt":"About 40 million people live in the Himalayas.","stem":"How does knowing the number of people help you understand the text?","choices":{"A":"it shows the Himalayas support a large human population","B":"it proves the Himalayas are the most crowded place on Earth","C":"it tells you most people there are farmers","D":"it explains why there are so many animals there"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The number 40 million shows the Himalayas can support a large human population, which is important for understanding the region.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 40 million people live in the Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q012","read_aloud":"What religion do many people in the southern Himalayas practice? A. Hindu B. Buddhist C. Christian D. Islamic","excerpt":"Many of the people who live in the southern countries of the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas are of Indian origin and practice the Hindu religion.","stem":"What religion do many people in the southern Himalayas practice?","choices":{"A":"Hindu","B":"Buddhist","C":"Christian","D":"Islamic"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states many people in the southern Himalayas practice the Hindu religion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many of the people who live in the southern countries of the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas are of Indian origin and practice the Hindu religion."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q013","read_aloud":"What religion do most Tibetan people practice? A. Buddhist B. Hindu C. Christian D. Islamic","excerpt":"North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist.","stem":"What religion do most Tibetan people practice?","choices":{"A":"Buddhist","B":"Hindu","C":"Christian","D":"Islamic"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states most Tibetan people are Buddhist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q014","read_aloud":"If you were planning to climb a Himalayan mountain, why might you hire a Sherpa guide? A. they have special knowledge of the mountains and climbing B. they charge less money than other guides C. they speak more languages than other guides D. they carry heavier loads than other guides","excerpt":"Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.","stem":"If you were planning to climb a Himalayan mountain, why might you hire a Sherpa guide?","choices":{"A":"they have special knowledge of the mountains and climbing","B":"they charge less money than other guides","C":"they speak more languages than other guides","D":"they carry heavier loads than other guides"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply the text\u0027s information about Sherpas being the best guides to explain why climbers would hire them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q015","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about how people have moved through the Himalayas over time? A. people have migrated and settled in different areas of the mountains B. people have always lived in the same places without moving C. people only live in the lowest valleys, never higher up D. people avoid the mountains and live only on the coasts","excerpt":"The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas. The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas.","stem":"What does this tell you about how people have moved through the Himalayas over time?","choices":{"A":"people have migrated and settled in different areas of the mountains","B":"people have always lived in the same places without moving","C":"people only live in the lowest valleys, never higher up","D":"people avoid the mountains and live only on the coasts"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Sherpas came from Tibet and settled in Himalayan valleys, showing human migration through the region.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas. The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q016","read_aloud":"How is the land of the Outer Himalayas different from its original state? A. It is now a desert. B. It was once forested and is now used for farming and grazing. C. It was always farmland. D. It is now underwater.","excerpt":"\"The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested. The land is now either farmed or used to graze goats and other livestock.\"","stem":"How is the land of the Outer Himalayas different from its original state?","choices":{"A":"It is now a desert.","B":"It was once forested and is now used for farming and grazing.","C":"It was always farmland.","D":"It is now underwater."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The original forest was replaced by farmland and grazing land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Outer Himalayas, once covered with a rich, tropical forest, have been harvested. The land is now either farmed or used to graze goats and other livestock.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the difficulty of exploring the Himalayas? A. They were easy to explore. B. They were very difficult to explore due to high altitude, cold, and rugged terrain. C. They were explored before any other mountains. D. No one ever tried to explore them.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas were some of the last mountains on Earth to be explored.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the difficulty of exploring the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"They were easy to explore.","B":"They were very difficult to explore due to high altitude, cold, and rugged terrain.","C":"They were explored before any other mountains.","D":"No one ever tried to explore them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being the last to be explored suggests they were very challenging.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas were some of the last mountains on Earth to be explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q018","read_aloud":"Why is it important to protect areas of the Himalayas? A. To keep people from climbing the mountains B. To save endangered plants and animals and preserve the natural environment C. To build more hotels D. To cut down more trees","excerpt":"\"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved. The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort.\"","stem":"Why is it important to protect areas of the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"To keep people from climbing the mountains","B":"To save endangered plants and animals and preserve the natural environment","C":"To build more hotels","D":"To cut down more trees"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Protection helps endangered species and preserves nature.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved. The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Write one sentence explaining why a tourist might want to visit the Himalayas even if they do not climb to the top. A. \"Tourists would not want to visit because it is too cold.\" B. \"Tourists can enjoy the beautiful scenery, glaciers, valleys, and unique culture from lower elevations.\" C. \"Tourists only come to climb.\" D. \"Tourists come to cut down trees.\"","excerpt":"\"Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers.\"","stem":"Write one sentence explaining why a tourist might want to visit the Himalayas even if they do not climb to the top.","choices":{"A":"\"Tourists would not want to visit because it is too cold.\"","B":"\"Tourists can enjoy the beautiful scenery, glaciers, valleys, and unique culture from lower elevations.\"","C":"\"Tourists only come to climb.\"","D":"\"Tourists come to cut down trees.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says people come to look with wonder at the scenery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q020","read_aloud":"The word subcontinent refers to India. What does the prefix \"sub-\" likely mean? A. Under or part of B. Very big C. Near the water D. On top of","excerpt":"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia...","stem":"The word subcontinent refers to India. What does the prefix \"sub-\" likely mean?","choices":{"A":"Under or part of","B":"Very big","C":"Near the water","D":"On top of"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"A subcontinent is a large part of a continent. \"Sub-\" often means under or part of something larger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q021","read_aloud":"What does this paragraph mainly tell us? A. The names of the mountains. B. The height of the mountains. C. Where the people live. D. The animals in the mountains.","excerpt":"About 40 million people live in the Himalayas. The Himalayas pass through the Indian states. The Himalayas also lie in the kingdoms of Nepal and Bhutan, as well as in Tibet.","stem":"What does this paragraph mainly tell us?","choices":{"A":"The names of the mountains.","B":"The height of the mountains.","C":"Where the people live.","D":"The animals in the mountains."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The paragraph focuses on the people and the places they live in the Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 40 million people live in the Himalayas. The Himalayas pass through the Indian states. The Himalayas also lie in the kingdoms of Nepal and Bhutan, as well as in Tibet."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q022","read_aloud":"Which religion is common in the southern parts of the Himalayas? A. Buddhism B. Hinduism C. Christianity D. Islam","excerpt":"Many of the people who live in the southern countries of the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas are of Indian origin and practice the Hindu religion.","stem":"Which religion is common in the southern parts of the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"Buddhism","B":"Hinduism","C":"Christianity","D":"Islam"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that people in the southern countries practice the Hindu religion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many of the people who live in the southern countries of the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas are of Indian origin and practice the Hindu religion."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q023","read_aloud":"Why are Sherpas good guides for climbers? A. They live in the steep valleys and know the mountains. B. They are the only people who live there. C. They have the most money. D. They built the roads up the mountains.","excerpt":"The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas. Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.","stem":"Why are Sherpas good guides for climbers?","choices":{"A":"They live in the steep valleys and know the mountains.","B":"They are the only people who live there.","C":"They have the most money.","D":"They built the roads up the mountains."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says they settled in the steep valleys, so they know the land well, making them the best guides.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Sherpas are tribespeople who came from Tibet and settled in the steep-sided valleys of the Himalayas. Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the culture change as you go north in the Himalayas? A. People stop farming animals. B. People become Buddhist. C. People move to the cities. D. People speak Sanskrit.","excerpt":"North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist.","stem":"How does the culture change as you go north in the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"People stop farming animals.","B":"People become Buddhist.","C":"People move to the cities.","D":"People speak Sanskrit."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts the Hindu south with the Buddhist north, so the religion changes to Buddhism.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: North of India, most Tibetan people are Buddhist."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l07-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q001","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does the word \"scale\" mean? Options: A. To weigh something, B. To climb to the top, C. To measure the size, D. To get very cold","excerpt":"Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen.","stem":"In this sentence, what does the word \"scale\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"To weigh something,","B":"To climb to the top,","C":"To measure the size,","D":"To get very cold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In the context of mountain climbing, \"to scale\" means to climb up or reach the top.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q002","read_aloud":"What happened to Mallory and Irvine? Options: A. They reached the top and returned home, B. They decided to stop climbing, C. They disappeared during their attempt, D. They became famous guides","excerpt":"After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned.","stem":"What happened to Mallory and Irvine? Options:","choices":{"A":"They reached the top and returned home,","B":"They decided to stop climbing,","C":"They disappeared during their attempt,","D":"They became famous guides"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"They never returned,\" which indicates they disappeared while climbing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q003","read_aloud":"Who were the first two people confirmed to reach the top of Mount Everest? Options: A. George Mallory and Andrew Irvine, B. Tenzing Norgay and Edmund Hillary, C. Sir George Everest and a Spanish priest, D. The team from 1999","excerpt":"On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.","stem":"Who were the first two people confirmed to reach the top of Mount Everest? Options:","choices":{"A":"George Mallory and Andrew Irvine,","B":"Tenzing Norgay and Edmund Hillary,","C":"Sir George Everest and a Spanish priest,","D":"The team from 1999"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly identifies these two men as the first to reach the peak.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Why is climbing Mount Everest dangerous? Options: A. Because it is too crowded with people, B. Because there are no maps to follow, C. Because of the extreme cold and lack of oxygen, D. Because the mountains are not tall enough","excerpt":"Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen.","stem":"Why is climbing Mount Everest dangerous? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because it is too crowded with people,","B":"Because there are no maps to follow,","C":"Because of the extreme cold and lack of oxygen,","D":"Because the mountains are not tall enough"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly lists \"freezing temperatures\" and \"low oxygen\" as the causes of death for climbers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Why do you think a map was important for the early exploration of the Himalayas? Options: A. It helped explorers see the routes and avoid getting lost, B. It made the mountains grow faster, C. It helped the priest reach the top of Everest, D. It proved that the mountains were not real","excerpt":"A Spanish priest drew one of the first maps of the area in 1590.","stem":"Why do you think a map was important for the early exploration of the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"It helped explorers see the routes and avoid getting lost,","B":"It made the mountains grow faster,","C":"It helped the priest reach the top of Everest,","D":"It proved that the mountains were not real"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Maps are tools used to understand new territory and navigate, which would have been necessary for early explorers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A Spanish priest drew one of the first maps of the area in 1590."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q006","read_aloud":"If a scientist is studying \"erosion\" in the Himalayas, what question might they ask? A. How fast is the soil washing away on mountainsides without trees? B. What color are the snow leopards? C. How tall is Mount Everest? D. What language do Sherpas speak?","excerpt":"\"Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better.\"","stem":"If a scientist is studying \"erosion\" in the Himalayas, what question might they ask?","choices":{"A":"How fast is the soil washing away on mountainsides without trees?","B":"What color are the snow leopards?","C":"How tall is Mount Everest?","D":"What language do Sherpas speak?"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Erosion is the wearing away of land. A scientist studying erosion would ask about soil washing away, especially on steep mountainsides where trees have been cut down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author mention the \"spice and silk trade routes\"? A. To show that people have used the Himalayas for thousands of years. B. To list items for sale in the mountains. C. To explain how to cook with spices. D. To describe modern highways.","excerpt":"\"Ancient spice and silk trade routes between China and India wound through the high mountain passes between India and Tibet. A Spanish priest drew one of the first maps of the area in 1590.\"","stem":"Why does the author mention the \"spice and silk trade routes\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that people have used the Himalayas for thousands of years.","B":"To list items for sale in the mountains.","C":"To explain how to cook with spices.","D":"To describe modern highways."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author mentions ancient trade routes to show that the Himalayas were important to people long ago. This helps readers understand that the mountains have a long history of human use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ancient spice and silk trade routes between China and India wound through the high mountain passes between India and Tibet. A Spanish priest drew one of the first maps of the area in 1590.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Is protecting the Himalayas a good idea? Use text evidence. A. No, because no animals live there. B. Yes, because endangered plants and animals need to be saved. C. No, because people should cut down all the trees. D. Yes, because climbers need more places to climb.","excerpt":"\"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved. The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort.\"","stem":"Is protecting the Himalayas a good idea? Use text evidence.","choices":{"A":"No, because no animals live there.","B":"Yes, because endangered plants and animals need to be saved.","C":"No, because people should cut down all the trees.","D":"Yes, because climbers need more places to climb."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says protection helps \"endangered plants and animals will be saved.\" This is a good reason to protect the area, as endangered species are at risk of disappearing forever.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved. The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Why do you think the author calls the peaks \"mysterious\"? A. Because no one has ever seen them. B. Because they are beautiful, powerful, and not fully understood. C. Because they are covered in gold. D. Because they move around at night.","excerpt":"\"Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers.\"","stem":"Why do you think the author calls the peaks \"mysterious\"?","choices":{"A":"Because no one has ever seen them.","B":"Because they are beautiful, powerful, and not fully understood.","C":"Because they are covered in gold.","D":"Because they move around at night."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author describes the peaks as \"mysterious\" because they are grand and awe-inspiring. Even with modern technology, these extreme mountains still hold secrets and challenges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Do you agree that the Himalayas are \"wonderful and extreme\"? Use two details from the text. A. No, because they are just small hills. B. Yes, because they have the world\u0027s highest peaks and many different climates and animals. C. No, because they are too dangerous to visit. D. Yes, because they are the oldest mountains on Earth.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful and extreme places.\"","stem":"Do you agree that the Himalayas are \"wonderful and extreme\"? Use two details from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because they are just small hills.","B":"Yes, because they have the world\u0027s highest peaks and many different climates and animals.","C":"No, because they are too dangerous to visit.","D":"Yes, because they are the oldest mountains on Earth."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text supports this view with many details: Mount Everest is the highest peak, there are three climate zones, and unique animals like snow leopards and yaks live there. These facts show the Himalayas are both wonderful and extreme.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful and extreme places.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"challenge\" mean in this context? A. something difficult that must be overcome B. a fun game people play together C. a type of mountain climbing equipment D. a special map of snowy mountains","excerpt":"One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks.","stem":"What does \"challenge\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"something difficult that must be overcome","B":"a fun game people play together","C":"a type of mountain climbing equipment","D":"a special map of snowy mountains"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Challenge means something difficult that must be overcome. The text says mapping the peaks was an early challenge for explorers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q012","read_aloud":"How do modern tools help with mapping the Himalayas? A. aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible B. they help climbers reach the peaks faster C. they predict when snowstorms will happen D. they measure the temperature of the peaks","excerpt":"Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible.","stem":"How do modern tools help with mapping the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible","B":"they help climbers reach the peaks faster","C":"they predict when snowstorms will happen","D":"they measure the temperature of the peaks"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states aircraft and satellites make exact maps of the Himalayas possible today.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q013","read_aloud":"What are scientists still doing in the Himalayas? A. working to understand the region better B. building new roads for tourists C. planting trees to stop erosion D. counting all the animals that live there","excerpt":"Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better.","stem":"What are scientists still doing in the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"working to understand the region better","B":"building new roads for tourists","C":"planting trees to stop erosion","D":"counting all the animals that live there"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says scientists are still working to understand the Himalayas better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Do you think protecting areas of the Himalayas is important? Why or why not? A. yes, because it helps save endangered plants and animals B. no, because people should be able to use all the land C. yes, but only for animals, not for plants D. no, because the mountains are too big to protect","excerpt":"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.","stem":"Do you think protecting areas of the Himalayas is important? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because it helps save endangered plants and animals","B":"no, because people should be able to use all the land","C":"yes, but only for animals, not for plants","D":"no, because the mountains are too big to protect"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text supports that protecting areas helps save endangered species, which is an important reason for conservation efforts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q015","read_aloud":"If you could design a new national park in the Himalayas, what might you include to protect both nature and people? A. areas for wildlife and paths for safe hiking by local people B. only areas for tourists with no access for locals C. only research stations with no public access D. only farming areas with no protected wildlife zones","excerpt":"The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort. The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m).","stem":"If you could design a new national park in the Himalayas, what might you include to protect both nature and people?","choices":{"A":"areas for wildlife and paths for safe hiking by local people","B":"only areas for tourists with no access for locals","C":"only research stations with no public access","D":"only farming areas with no protected wildlife zones"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to creatively apply conservation ideas to design a park that balances protecting nature with allowing human use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort. The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why was a survey of India important for understanding the Himalayas? A. Surveys measure land and help create maps, which were needed to identify the highest peaks. B. Surveys are only for building roads. C. Surveys have nothing to do with mountains. D. Surveys are for counting people.","excerpt":"\"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.\"","stem":"Why was a survey of India important for understanding the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"Surveys measure land and help create maps, which were needed to identify the highest peaks.","B":"Surveys are only for building roads.","C":"Surveys have nothing to do with mountains.","D":"Surveys are for counting people."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Surveys measure land and were used to map the mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q017","read_aloud":"What conclusion can you draw about the relationship between plate tectonics and the Himalayas? A. Plate tectonics have nothing to do with the Himalayas. B. The Himalayas were formed by plate movement and continue to be shaped by it. C. Plate tectonics only affect volcanoes. D. The Himalayas formed without any plate movement.","excerpt":"The text explains that the Himalayas formed when the Indian subcontinent collided with Eurasia, that they are still growing, and that they contain fossils of sea creatures.","stem":"What conclusion can you draw about the relationship between plate tectonics and the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"Plate tectonics have nothing to do with the Himalayas.","B":"The Himalayas were formed by plate movement and continue to be shaped by it.","C":"Plate tectonics only affect volcanoes.","D":"The Himalayas formed without any plate movement."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that plate movement created and still affects the Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text explains that the Himalayas formed when the Indian subcontinent collided with Eurasia, that they are still growing, and that they contain fossils of sea creatures."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Do you think the deaths of Mallory and Irvine were worth it to eventually reach the summit? Why? A. No, because no goal is worth losing lives. B. Yes, because their efforts helped pave the way for later successful climbs and exploration. C. No, because climbing is not important. D. Yes, because they became famous.","excerpt":"\"After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned. On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.\"","stem":"Do you think the deaths of Mallory and Irvine were worth it to eventually reach the summit? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because no goal is worth losing lives.","B":"Yes, because their efforts helped pave the way for later successful climbs and exploration.","C":"No, because climbing is not important.","D":"Yes, because they became famous."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Exploration often involves risk, and early attempts inform later successes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned. On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Write one sentence suggesting a new rule for visitors to Sagarmatha National Park to help protect the environment. A. \"Visitors should be allowed to litter.\" B. \"Visitors must carry out all trash and stay on marked trails.\" C. \"Visitors should cut down trees for firewood.\" D. \"Visitors should feed the wild animals.\"","excerpt":"\"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery.\"","stem":"Write one sentence suggesting a new rule for visitors to Sagarmatha National Park to help protect the environment.","choices":{"A":"\"Visitors should be allowed to litter.\"","B":"\"Visitors must carry out all trash and stay on marked trails.\"","C":"\"Visitors should cut down trees for firewood.\"","D":"\"Visitors should feed the wild animals.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Protecting the park requires rules that reduce human impact.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q020","read_aloud":"What does the word located mean? A. Found or placed B. Built up C. Moved away D. Climbed up","excerpt":"The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m).","stem":"What does the word located mean?","choices":{"A":"Found or placed","B":"Built up","C":"Moved away","D":"Climbed up"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Located\" tells where something is found or placed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q021","read_aloud":"Why were the mountain passes important long ago? A. They were used for trade. B. They were used for farming. C. They were used for skiing. D. They were used for hunting.","excerpt":"Ancient spice and silk trade routes between China and India wound through the high mountain passes between India and Tibet.","stem":"Why were the mountain passes important long ago?","choices":{"A":"They were used for trade.","B":"They were used for farming.","C":"They were used for skiing.","D":"They were used for hunting."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text mentions that trade routes for spice and silk went through the passes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Ancient spice and silk trade routes between China and India wound through the high mountain passes between India and Tibet."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q022","read_aloud":"What are two dangers of climbing Mt. Everest? A. High heat and too much air B. Freezing cold and low oxygen C. Wild animals and deep rivers D. Too many trees and heavy rain","excerpt":"Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen.","stem":"What are two dangers of climbing Mt. Everest?","choices":{"A":"High heat and too much air","B":"Freezing cold and low oxygen","C":"Wild animals and deep rivers","D":"Too many trees and heavy rain"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists freezing temperatures and low oxygen as causes of death for climbers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q023","read_aloud":"Why was this event important? A. It proved airplanes could fly high. B. It was the first time people reached the top. C. It showed that the mountain was small. D. It helped scientists find fossils.","excerpt":"On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.","stem":"Why was this event important?","choices":{"A":"It proved airplanes could fly high.","B":"It was the first time people reached the top.","C":"It showed that the mountain was small.","D":"It helped scientists find fossils."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they were the \"first to reach Everest\u0027s peak,\" which makes the event historically important.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q024","read_aloud":"Based on this text, what is a likely reason they did not return? A. They got lost in a forest. B. They decided to stay on the mountain. C. The conditions were too dangerous. D. They found a secret city.","excerpt":"After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned.","stem":"Based on this text, what is a likely reason they did not return?","choices":{"A":"They got lost in a forest.","B":"They decided to stay on the mountain.","C":"The conditions were too dangerous.","D":"They found a secret city."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Since the text says they never returned and mentions others died from freezing and low oxygen, we can infer the conditions were dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: After several attempts, George Mallory and Andrew Irvine set out to climb Mt. Everest on June 8, 1924. They never returned."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l08-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"endangered\" mean? Options: A. Being in danger of disappearing forever, B. Being very common in many places, C. Being able to live anywhere, D. Being safe from any harm","excerpt":"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.","stem":"What does \"endangered\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Being in danger of disappearing forever,","B":"Being very common in many places,","C":"Being able to live anywhere,","D":"Being safe from any harm"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Endangered species are those that are at risk of becoming extinct, so they need protection to be saved.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q002","read_aloud":"How has technology changed the way scientists study the Himalayas? Options: A. It makes the mountains grow slower, B. It makes mapping the area easier and more accurate, C. It has stopped all exploration, D. It has replaced the need for geologists","excerpt":"Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible. Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better.","stem":"How has technology changed the way scientists study the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the mountains grow slower,","B":"It makes mapping the area easier and more accurate,","C":"It has stopped all exploration,","D":"It has replaced the need for geologists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says aircraft and satellites make \"exact maps possible,\" which helps scientists understand the area better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible. Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q003","read_aloud":"Why did Nepal create the Sagarmatha National Park? Options: A. To build more cities for people, B. To make it harder for people to travel, C. To protect the natural environment and animals, D. To find more gold and spice routes","excerpt":"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery. The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park.","stem":"Why did Nepal create the Sagarmatha National Park? Options:","choices":{"A":"To build more cities for people,","B":"To make it harder for people to travel,","C":"To protect the natural environment and animals,","D":"To find more gold and spice routes"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that the park was created to save the animals, plants, and the scenery of the mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery. The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why might the Himalayas have been some of the \"last mountains on Earth to be explored\"? Options: A. People were not interested in them, B. They were too easy to climb, C. The environment was too harsh and difficult to map, D. There were no animals or plants there","excerpt":"One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks.","stem":"Based on the text, why might the Himalayas have been some of the \"last mountains on Earth to be explored\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"People were not interested in them,","B":"They were too easy to climb,","C":"The environment was too harsh and difficult to map,","D":"There were no animals or plants there"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Because the mountains were difficult to map and had such challenging conditions (like snow-covered peaks), they were hard to explore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q005","read_aloud":"Why do people continue to visit the Himalayas even if they don\u0027t climb them? Options: A. To hunt the animals, B. To appreciate their beauty and wonder, C. To build new farms, D. To take apart the glaciers","excerpt":"Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys...","stem":"Why do people continue to visit the Himalayas even if they don\u0027t climb them? Options:","choices":{"A":"To hunt the animals,","B":"To appreciate their beauty and wonder,","C":"To build new farms,","D":"To take apart the glaciers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says people come to \"look with wonder\" at the peaks, valleys, and rivers because they are wonderful places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"altitude\" connect to \"frozen worlds\"? A. High altitude means it is always cold and frozen at the peaks. B. Altitude makes the snow melt faster. C. Frozen worlds happen only in valleys. D. Altitude has nothing to do with temperature.","excerpt":"\"The highest peaks in the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round.\"","stem":"How does the word \"altitude\" connect to \"frozen worlds\"?","choices":{"A":"High altitude means it is always cold and frozen at the peaks.","B":"Altitude makes the snow melt faster.","C":"Frozen worlds happen only in valleys.","D":"Altitude has nothing to do with temperature."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that the highest peaks are frozen year-round. High altitude means higher elevation, where temperatures are colder. This is why snow and ice never melt at the highest peaks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The highest peaks in the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q007","read_aloud":"How does knowing about the author help you understand the text? A. It tells you the author likes mountains and wants to share that with young people. B. It tells you the author has never visited mountains. C. It tells you the author only writes about oceans. D. It tells you the author does not like national parks.","excerpt":"\"Charles W. Maynard believes in the importance of wilderness. His more than forty publications include a series of books for young readers about the great mountain ranges of the world.\"","stem":"How does knowing about the author help you understand the text?","choices":{"A":"It tells you the author likes mountains and wants to share that with young people.","B":"It tells you the author has never visited mountains.","C":"It tells you the author only writes about oceans.","D":"It tells you the author does not like national parks."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Knowing the author believes in wilderness and writes books for young readers about mountains helps us understand he cares about nature and wants to teach children about it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Charles W. Maynard believes in the importance of wilderness. His more than forty publications include a series of books for young readers about the great mountain ranges of the world.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q008","read_aloud":"How does this information change how you think about mountains? A. It shows that mountains can come from the bottom of the ocean. B. It shows that oceans are not real. C. It shows that sea creatures still live on Mount Everest. D. It shows that limestone is a type of animal.","excerpt":"\"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago... Some rocks near the highest peaks... are limestone... made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\"","stem":"How does this information change how you think about mountains?","choices":{"A":"It shows that mountains can come from the bottom of the ocean.","B":"It shows that oceans are not real.","C":"It shows that sea creatures still live on Mount Everest.","D":"It shows that limestone is a type of animal."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text reveals that the highest mountains were once underwater. This surprising fact shows that Earth\u0027s surface changes over millions of years, and mountains can rise from ocean floors.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago... Some rocks near the highest peaks... are limestone... made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Why is it important that a Sherpa and a foreign climber reached the top together? A. It shows that teamwork between local people and visitors can achieve great things. B. It shows that Sherpas are not good climbers. C. It shows that New Zealand is part of the Himalayas. D. It shows that climbing alone is always better.","excerpt":"\"On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.\"","stem":"Why is it important that a Sherpa and a foreign climber reached the top together?","choices":{"A":"It shows that teamwork between local people and visitors can achieve great things.","B":"It shows that Sherpas are not good climbers.","C":"It shows that New Zealand is part of the Himalayas.","D":"It shows that climbing alone is always better."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text highlights that Tenzing Norgay (a local Sherpa who knew the mountains) and Edmund Hillary (a visitor from New Zealan d) worked together. This shows teamwork between local experts and others can lead to success.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q010","read_aloud":"If you could add one more rule to protect Sagarmatha National Park, what would it be and why? A. Allow unlimited tree cutting so more people can visit. B. Limit the number of climbers to reduce trash and protect the environment. C. Build a shopping mall on Mount Everest. D. Remove all the Sherpa people from the park.","excerpt":"\"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery. The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park.\"","stem":"If you could add one more rule to protect Sagarmatha National Park, what would it be and why?","choices":{"A":"Allow unlimited tree cutting so more people can visit.","B":"Limit the number of climbers to reduce trash and protect the environment.","C":"Build a shopping mall on Mount Everest.","D":"Remove all the Sherpa people from the park."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the park protects \"animals, plants, and mountain scenery.\" Limiting climbers would help keep the park clean and protect the environment, which matches the park\u0027s purpose.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery. The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q011","read_aloud":"How does \"set aside\" help you understand what the government did? A. it means the government reserved land for protection B. it means the government sold the land to developers C. it means the government ignored the area completely D. it means the government built cities on the land","excerpt":"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery.","stem":"How does \"set aside\" help you understand what the government did?","choices":{"A":"it means the government reserved land for protection","B":"it means the government sold the land to developers","C":"it means the government ignored the area completely","D":"it means the government built cities on the land"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Set aside means to reserve or designate for a special purpose. The text shows Nepal reserved land to protect nature.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Why do people visit the Himalayas even if they don\u0027t climb? A. to look with wonder at the mysterious high peaks B. to mine for valuable metals and stones C. to hunt the rare animals that live there D. to build new roads and towns","excerpt":"Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks.","stem":"Why do people visit the Himalayas even if they don\u0027t climb?","choices":{"A":"to look with wonder at the mysterious high peaks","B":"to mine for valuable metals and stones","C":"to hunt the rare animals that live there","D":"to build new roads and towns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says people come from around the world to look with wonder at the high peaks, even without climbing them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q013","read_aloud":"What is the main idea about the Himalayas in this sentence? A. they remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places B. they are the most dangerous mountains to visit C. they are too cold for most people to enjoy D. they are only important to scientists","excerpt":"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.","stem":"What is the main idea about the Himalayas in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"they remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places","B":"they are the most dangerous mountains to visit","C":"they are too cold for most people to enjoy","D":"they are only important to scientists"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sentence\u0027s main idea is that the Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Is it fair to allow local people to live in a protected national park? Why or why not? A. yes, because local people have lived there for generations and can help protect it B. no, because no people should live in any national park C. yes, but only if they pay to live there D. no, because they might harm the animals","excerpt":"The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park.","stem":"Is it fair to allow local people to live in a protected national park? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because local people have lived there for generations and can help protect it","B":"no, because no people should live in any national park","C":"yes, but only if they pay to live there","D":"no, because they might harm the animals"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Sherpas have lived in the Himalayas long-term, and allowing them to stay can support both cultural preservation and conservation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q015","read_aloud":"If you were writing a travel brochure about the Himalayas, what three features would you highlight to attract visitors? A. mysterious high peaks, steep valleys, and swift rivers B. busy cities, shopping centers, and amusement parks C. hot beaches, tropical forests, and coral reefs D. flat plains, wide rivers, and grassy fields","excerpt":"People come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers.","stem":"If you were writing a travel brochure about the Himalayas, what three features would you highlight to attract visitors?","choices":{"A":"mysterious high peaks, steep valleys, and swift rivers","B":"busy cities, shopping centers, and amusement parks","C":"hot beaches, tropical forests, and coral reefs","D":"flat plains, wide rivers, and grassy fields"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to creatively select the most appealing features from the text to promote Himalayan tourism.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of plateau? a) A. plain B. valley (low are C. mountain D. glacier","excerpt":"\"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym of plateau? a)","choices":{"A":"plain","B":"valley (low are","C":"mountain","D":"glacier"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A plateau is a high, flat area; a valley is a low area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q017","read_aloud":"How does the Himalayas\u0027 blocking of humid air affect the Plateau of Tibet? A. It makes the plateau wet and rainy. B. It makes the plateau dry and dusty. C. It has no effect. D. It makes the plateau hot.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south. The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long.\"","stem":"How does the Himalayas\u0027 blocking of humid air affect the Plateau of Tibet?","choices":{"A":"It makes the plateau wet and rainy.","B":"It makes the plateau dry and dusty.","C":"It has no effect.","D":"It makes the plateau hot."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The plateau is dry because the mountains block humid air from the south.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south. The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q018","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s attitude toward the Himalayas? A. He thinks they are boring. B. He thinks they are wonderful and worth protecting. C. He thinks they are dangerous and should be avoided. D. He thinks they are not important.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s attitude toward the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"He thinks they are boring.","B":"He thinks they are wonderful and worth protecting.","C":"He thinks they are dangerous and should be avoided.","D":"He thinks they are not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author calls them \"wonderful.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Do you think protecting the Himalayas is more important than using the land for farming? Why? A. No, because people need food. B. Yes, because unique plants and animals could become extinct, and the environment is irreplaceable. C. No, because farming is always more important. D. Yes, because animals are cuter than plants.","excerpt":"\"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.\"","stem":"Do you think protecting the Himalayas is more important than using the land for farming? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because people need food.","B":"Yes, because unique plants and animals could become extinct, and the environment is irreplaceable.","C":"No, because farming is always more important.","D":"Yes, because animals are cuter than plants."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"There is a balance between conservation and human needs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q020","read_aloud":"Imagine you are an explorer in the 1800s. Write one sentence about what you hope to find in the Himalayas. A. \"I hope to find a shopping mall.\" B. \"I hope to discover the highest peak and learn about the plants and animals there.\" C. \"I hope to cut down all the trees.\" D. \"I hope to build a hotel.\"","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas were some of the last mountains on Earth to be explored.\"","stem":"Imagine you are an explorer in the 1800s. Write one sentence about what you hope to find in the Himalayas.","choices":{"A":"\"I hope to find a shopping mall.\"","B":"\"I hope to discover the highest peak and learn about the plants and animals there.\"","C":"\"I hope to cut down all the trees.\"","D":"\"I hope to build a hotel.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Explorers seek knowledge and discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas were some of the last mountains on Earth to be explored.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q021","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for altitude? A. Depth B. Height C. Width D. Weight","excerpt":"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.","stem":"Which word is a synonym for altitude?","choices":{"A":"Depth","B":"Height","C":"Width","D":"Weight"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Altitude refers to how high something is, so height is a synonym.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q022","read_aloud":"Why are governments protecting parts of the Himalayas? A. To build new cities B. To save plants and animals C. To make more roads D. To stop people from visiting","excerpt":"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.","stem":"Why are governments protecting parts of the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"To build new cities","B":"To save plants and animals","C":"To make more roads","D":"To stop people from visiting"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states the purpose is to save endangered plants and animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q023","read_aloud":"What is special about Sagarmatha National Park? A. It is at a very high altitude. B. It is near the ocean. C. It is located in a desert. D. It is the largest park in the world.","excerpt":"The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort. The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m).","stem":"What is special about Sagarmatha National Park?","choices":{"A":"It is at a very high altitude.","B":"It is near the ocean.","C":"It is located in a desert.","D":"It is the largest park in the world."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text mentions the park is located above 9,700 feet, which is very high.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Sagarmatha National Park of Nepal is one example of this effort. The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q024","read_aloud":"Do you think it is a good idea to let Sherpas live in the park? A. No, because they might cut down all the trees. B. Yes, because it is their home and they know the land. C. No, because animals need all the space. D. Yes, because they can build big cities there.","excerpt":"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery. The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park.","stem":"Do you think it is a good idea to let Sherpas live in the park?","choices":{"A":"No, because they might cut down all the trees.","B":"Yes, because it is their home and they know the land.","C":"No, because animals need all the space.","D":"Yes, because they can build big cities there."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since Sherpas have lived there for a long time and are good guides, allowing them to stay respects their home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery. The Sherpa people are allowed to live in the national park."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l09-q025","read_aloud":"Why do scientists keep studying the Himalayas? A. To find gold and silver. B. To understand the world better. C. To build houses on the peaks. D. To cut down more trees.","excerpt":"Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better.","stem":"Why do scientists keep studying the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"To find gold and silver.","B":"To understand the world better.","C":"To build houses on the peaks.","D":"To cut down more trees."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they are working to \"understand the Rooftop of the World better.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better."}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q001","read_aloud":"In this context, what is a \"peak\"? Options: A. The base of the mountain, B. The sharpest point or top of a mountain, C. A deep valley in the middle, D. A flat field of ice","excerpt":"...hundreds have reached Everest\u0027s peak, the top of the high Himalayas.","stem":"In this context, what is a \"peak\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"The base of the mountain,","B":"The sharpest point or top of a mountain,","C":"A deep valley in the middle,","D":"A flat field of ice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A peak refers specifically to the highest point or summit of a mountain.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: ...hundreds have reached Everest\u0027s peak, the top of the high Himalayas."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q002","read_aloud":"Which statement best summarizes how the Himalayas formed? Options: A. Glaciers carved the mountains over time, B. Earth\u0027s plates moved and pushed the land upward, C. People built the mountains from piles of rock, D. The ocean floor rose because of the wind","excerpt":"Scientists call the movement of Earth\u0027s crust plate tectonics. About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia...","stem":"Which statement best summarizes how the Himalayas formed? Options:","choices":{"A":"Glaciers carved the mountains over time,","B":"Earth\u0027s plates moved and pushed the land upward,","C":"People built the mountains from piles of rock,","D":"The ocean floor rose because of the wind"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Plate tectonics explains that the bumping of plates pushes crust up, which is exactly how the text describes the formation of these mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists call the movement of Earth\u0027s crust plate tectonics. About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author characterize the environment of the Great Himalayas? Options: A. As a warm and tropical forest, B. As a busy place full of people and cities, C. As a harsh and cold \"frozen world,\" D. As a wet place with monsoon winds","excerpt":"The highest peaks in the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round. Even the valleys are cold and desertlike, with no trees and few plants.","stem":"How does the author characterize the environment of the Great Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"As a warm and tropical forest,","B":"As a busy place full of people and cities,","C":"As a harsh and cold \"frozen world,\"","D":"As a wet place with monsoon winds"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The \"Mountain Fact\" box clearly calls it a \"frozen world\" where it is difficult for plants and animals to live.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest peaks in the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round. Even the valleys are cold and desertlike, with no trees and few plants."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Based on the information in the text, why is it important to keep studying the Himalayas? Options: A. Because we already know everything about them, B. Because they are always changing and we want to protect them, C. Because we want to make them shorter, D. Because it is easy to do","excerpt":"Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better.","stem":"Based on the information in the text, why is it important to keep studying the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because we already know everything about them,","B":"Because they are always changing and we want to protect them,","C":"Because we want to make them shorter,","D":"Because it is easy to do"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since the mountains are still moving/growing and we need to save endangered species, there is still much to learn and protect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Geologists, geographers, and other scientists are still working to understand the Rooftop of the World better."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q005","read_aloud":"How would the Himalayas be different today if the government of Nepal had not created a national park? Options: A. More people would be able to climb the peaks, B. Endangered animals and plants might be in greater danger of disappearing, C. The mountains would stop growing taller, D. The climate would become tropical","excerpt":"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery.","stem":"How would the Himalayas be different today if the government of Nepal had not created a national park? Options:","choices":{"A":"More people would be able to climb the peaks,","B":"Endangered animals and plants might be in greater danger of disappearing,","C":"The mountains would stop growing taller,","D":"The climate would become tropical"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because the park exists to protect the environment, the opposite-fewer protections-would likely put the plants and animals at higher risk.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q006","read_aloud":"Using your understanding of \"altitude,\" why do you think the park starts at 9,700 feet? A. Because that is where the land becomes flat. B. Because that high altitude is where special mountain plants and animals need protection. C. Because there are no people above that height. D. Because the weather is always warm there.","excerpt":"\"The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m).\"","stem":"Using your understanding of \"altitude,\" why do you think the park starts at 9,700 feet?","choices":{"A":"Because that is where the land becomes flat.","B":"Because that high altitude is where special mountain plants and animals need protection.","C":"Because there are no people above that height.","D":"Because the weather is always warm there."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the park protects \"endangered plants and animals.\" High altitude areas have unique, fragile environments that need special protection, which is why the park starts at 9,700 feet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The entire park is located above 9,700 feet (2,957 m).\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Why did the author use these headings? A. To make the text longer. B. To help readers find information and understand how the text is organized. C. To hide important facts. D. To make the text more confusing.","excerpt":"The text has headings like \"Rooftop of the World,\" \"When Continents Collide,\" \"Mountains Build Up and Wear Away,\" \"A Land of Contrasts,\" \"Amazing Animals,\" \"Many Mountain Cultures,\" \"On Top of the World,\" and \"Mapping and Protecting the Himalayas.\"","stem":"Why did the author use these headings?","choices":{"A":"To make the text longer.","B":"To help readers find information and understand how the text is organized.","C":"To hide important facts.","D":"To make the text more confusing."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Informational texts use headings to organize ideas. These headings tell the reader what each section is about, making it easier to find information and follow the structure.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text has headings like \"Rooftop of the World,\" \"When Continents Collide,\" \"Mountains Build Up and Wear Away,\" \"A Land of Contrasts,\" \"Amazing Animals,\" \"Many Mountain Cultures,\" \"On Top of the World,\" and \"Mapping and Protecting the Himalayas.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q008","read_aloud":"If the Himalayas did not exist, how might Asia\u0027s climate be different? A. It would be exactly the same. B. Cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south would mix more freely. C. There would be no rain anywhere in Asia. D. All of Asia would become a desert.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.\"","stem":"If the Himalayas did not exist, how might Asia\u0027s climate be different?","choices":{"A":"It would be exactly the same.","B":"Cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south would mix more freely.","C":"There would be no rain anywhere in Asia.","D":"All of Asia would become a desert."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the Himalayas block weather from moving. Without the mountains, there would be no wall to stop cold and humid air from moving across the continent, so weather patterns would mix more.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q009","read_aloud":"Should tourism in the Himalayas be encouraged or limited? Use evidence from the text. A. Encouraged without limits, because more tourists means more money. B. Limited, because too many tourists could harm the protected plants, animals, and scenery. C. Banned completely, because no one should ever visit. D. Encouraged only for scientists, because regular people cannot appreciate beauty.","excerpt":"\"People come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers.\"","stem":"Should tourism in the Himalayas be encouraged or limited? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"Encouraged without limits, because more tourists means more money.","B":"Limited, because too many tourists could harm the protected plants, animals, and scenery.","C":"Banned completely, because no one should ever visit.","D":"Encouraged only for scientists, because regular people cannot appreciate beauty."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the park was created to protect \"animals, plants, and mountain scenery.\" Too many tourists could damage these protected things. Limiting tourism helps balance visiting with protection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks and their steep valleys, large glaciers, and swift rivers.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q010","read_aloud":"How could studying the Himalayas help people in the future? A. It could help us understand how extreme environments work and how to protect them. B. It could help us build taller buildings. C. It could help us find ways to remove all mountains. D. It could help us prove that mountains are not important.","excerpt":"\"To preserve biodiversity in parks for future generations, we must first discover the breadth of life forms that exist.\"","stem":"How could studying the Himalayas help people in the future?","choices":{"A":"It could help us understand how extreme environments work and how to protect them.","B":"It could help us build taller buildings.","C":"It could help us find ways to remove all mountains.","D":"It could help us prove that mountains are not important."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says we must \"discover the breadth of life forms\" to preserve biodiversity. Studying extreme environments like the Himalayas teaches us how life survives in harsh conditions, which helps us protect these places and maybe other extreme environments too.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To preserve biodiversity in parks for future generations, we must first discover the breadth of life forms that exist.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q011","read_aloud":"How does understanding \"blocking\" help you see the Himalayas\u0027 role in weather? A. it shows the mountains act like a barrier that changes weather patterns B. it shows the mountains make all weather warmer C. it shows the mountains cause more rain everywhere D. it shows the mountains have no effect on weather","excerpt":"The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.","stem":"How does understanding \"blocking\" help you see the Himalayas\u0027 role in weather?","choices":{"A":"it shows the mountains act like a barrier that changes weather patterns","B":"it shows the mountains make all weather warmer","C":"it shows the mountains cause more rain everywhere","D":"it shows the mountains have no effect on weather"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Blocking means acting as a barrier. The text shows the Himalayas block weather systems, affecting central Asia\u0027s climate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q012","read_aloud":"What is the climate like on the Tibetan Plateau? A. dry and dusty with cold, long winters B. wet and rainy with mild, short winters C. hot and humid with no winter at all D. windy and stormy with mild temperatures","excerpt":"The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long.","stem":"What is the climate like on the Tibetan Plateau?","choices":{"A":"dry and dusty with cold, long winters","B":"wet and rainy with mild, short winters","C":"hot and humid with no winter at all","D":"windy and stormy with mild temperatures"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes the Tibetan Plateau as dry, dusty, with cold and long winters.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The high Plateau of Tibet, to the north in China, is dry and dusty. The winters there are cold and long."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q013","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use in this concluding sentence? A. descriptive text structure to leave a lasting impression B. chronological order to show time passing C. cause-and-effect to explain mountain formation D. problem-and-solution to fix environmental issues","excerpt":"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.","stem":"What text structure does the author use in this concluding sentence?","choices":{"A":"descriptive text structure to leave a lasting impression","B":"chronological order to show time passing","C":"cause-and-effect to explain mountain formation","D":"problem-and-solution to fix environmental issues"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The concluding sentence uses descriptive structure to emphasize the Himalayas\u0027 beauty and leave readers with a strong final impression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q014","read_aloud":"(Adapted from similar text structure)Do you think the author fairly presents both the challenges and wonders of the Himalayas? Why or why not? A. yes, the text shows both dangers like erosion and wonders like diverse life B. no, the text only focuses on the dangers of the mountains C. yes, but only for scientists who study the region D. no, because the mountains are too remote to matter","excerpt":"Scientists think this trait is one reason that the echidna has managed to survive. But it\u0027s just one of the adaptations that makes the tiny, spiny echidna one of the most amazing creatures on Earth.","stem":"(Adapted from similar text structure)Do you think the author fairly presents both the challenges and wonders of the Himalayas? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, the text shows both dangers like erosion and wonders like diverse life","B":"no, the text only focuses on the dangers of the mountains","C":"yes, but only for scientists who study the region","D":"no, because the mountains are too remote to matter"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text presents both challenges (erosion, harsh climates) and wonders (diverse life, beauty), giving a balanced view of the Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists think this trait is one reason that the echidna has managed to survive. But it\u0027s just one of the adaptations that makes the tiny, spiny echidna one of the most amazing creatures on Earth."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q015","read_aloud":"(Adapted from similar text ending)If Charles W. Maynard could send one message to young explorers today, what might it be based on his text? A. \"Stay curious, ask questions, and keep exploring our amazing planet.\" B. \"Only study mountains that are near your home.\" C. \"Believe only what ancient maps say about Earth.\" D. \"Wait for others to make discoveries before you try.\"","excerpt":"Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?","stem":"(Adapted from similar text ending)If Charles W. Maynard could send one message to young explorers today, what might it be based on his text?","choices":{"A":"\"Stay curious, ask questions, and keep exploring our amazing planet.\"","B":"\"Only study mountains that are near your home.\"","C":"\"Believe only what ancient maps say about Earth.\"","D":"\"Wait for others to make discoveries before you try.\""},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Maynard\u0027s text shows ongoing discovery and scientific curiosity, making this message authentic to his purpose of inspiring exploration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Exploration continues to expand. People once thought Earth was the center of the universe. What will we discover next?"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q016","read_aloud":"How does the word subcontinent help you understand the size of India? A. It means India is a very small country. B. It means India is a large region that is part of the continent of Asia. C. It means India is an island. D. It means India is under the ocean.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. … About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia.\"","stem":"How does the word subcontinent help you understand the size of India?","choices":{"A":"It means India is a very small country.","B":"It means India is a large region that is part of the continent of Asia.","C":"It means India is an island.","D":"It means India is under the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A subcontinent is a large region that is part of a continent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges in the world. … About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia, which formed Europe and Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q017","read_aloud":"What does the author want readers to understand about the Himalayas? A. That they are only important for climbing. B. That they are a complex, important, and wonderful part of Earth with geology, ecology, and human history. C. That they are a dangerous place to avoid. D. That they are only interesting to scientists.","excerpt":"The text describes how the Himalayas formed, their climate zones, plant and animal life, human cultures, and conservation efforts.","stem":"What does the author want readers to understand about the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"That they are only important for climbing.","B":"That they are a complex, important, and wonderful part of Earth with geology, ecology, and human history.","C":"That they are a dangerous place to avoid.","D":"That they are only interesting to scientists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author covers many aspects of the Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text describes how the Himalayas formed, their climate zones, plant and animal life, human cultures, and conservation efforts."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q018","read_aloud":"What is the root word inside erosion? A. Rose B. Erode C. Error D. Rise","excerpt":"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion.","stem":"What is the root word inside erosion?","choices":{"A":"Rose","B":"Erode","C":"Error","D":"Rise"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Erosion comes from the word \"erode,\" which means to wear away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How has mapping changed over time? A. It is now done with planes and satellites. B. It is no longer necessary. C. It is harder to do today. D. It is done by climbing every peak.","excerpt":"One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks. Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible.","stem":"How has mapping changed over time?","choices":{"A":"It is now done with planes and satellites.","B":"It is no longer necessary.","C":"It is harder to do today.","D":"It is done by climbing every peak."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text contrasts early challenges with today\u0027s use of aircraft and satellites for mapping.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One early challenge to exploring the Himalayas was mapping its many high, snow-covered peaks. Today aircraft and satellites make exact maps possible."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q020","read_aloud":"Why do people visit the Himalayas? A. To climb the mountains. B. To look at the beautiful scenery. C. To find gold in the rivers. D. To live in the large cities.","excerpt":"Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks...","stem":"Why do people visit the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"To climb the mountains.","B":"To look at the beautiful scenery.","C":"To find gold in the rivers.","D":"To live in the large cities."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says people come to \"look with wonder\" at the peaks and valleys.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q021","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s purpose for writing this text? A. To tell a funny story about animals. B. To explain how to climb mountains. C. To inform us about the Himalayas. D. To scare us about dangerous weather.","excerpt":"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.","stem":"What is the author\u0027s purpose for writing this text?","choices":{"A":"To tell a funny story about animals.","B":"To explain how to climb mountains.","C":"To inform us about the Himalayas.","D":"To scare us about dangerous weather."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text gives facts and details to teach the reader about the mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q022","read_aloud":"If the Himalayas were completely flat, how would life in Asia be different? A. It would be exactly the same. B. There would be no rivers starting there. C. More people would live there. D. The weather would be colder.","excerpt":"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.","stem":"If the Himalayas were completely flat, how would life in Asia be different?","choices":{"A":"It would be exactly the same.","B":"There would be no rivers starting there.","C":"More people would live there.","D":"The weather would be colder."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that glaciers melt to form rivers like the Ganges. Without mountains, these rivers would not form the same way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q023","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q024","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-l10-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. plain B. valley (low are C. mountain D. glacier","excerpt":"\"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"plain","B":"valley (low are","C":"mountain","D":"glacier"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A plateau is a high, flat area; a valley is a low area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q001","read_aloud":"If a hiker travels to an \"altitude\" of 8,000 meters, what are they doing? Options: A. Walking along the ocean floor, B. Climbing to a very high level above sea level, C. Moving to a lower valley, D. Digging a hole in the ground","excerpt":"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world... fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level.","stem":"If a hiker travels to an \"altitude\" of 8,000 meters, what are they doing? Options:","choices":{"A":"Walking along the ocean floor,","B":"Climbing to a very high level above sea level,","C":"Moving to a lower valley,","D":"Digging a hole in the ground"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Altitude is the distance above sea level, so being at 8,000 meters means being very high up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world... fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q002","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is a \"subcontinent\"? Options: A. A small city, B. A massive ocean, C. A large part of a continent, D. A thin layer of ice","excerpt":"The Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia...","stem":"Based on the text, what is a \"subcontinent\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"A small city,","B":"A massive ocean,","C":"A large part of a continent,","D":"A thin layer of ice"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text defines a subcontinent as a large region that is part of a continent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q003","read_aloud":"Why is \"erosion\" bad for a mountainside? Options: A. It makes the trees grow faster, B. It takes away the soil that plants need to grow, C. It makes the mountains colder, D. It helps the yaks find more food","excerpt":"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds... this has caused erosion.","stem":"Why is \"erosion\" bad for a mountainside? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the trees grow faster,","B":"It takes away the soil that plants need to grow,","C":"It makes the mountains colder,","D":"It helps the yaks find more food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Erosion removes the soil that plants depend on, which causes harm to the mountain environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds... this has caused erosion."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the most accurate way to describe the size of the Himalayas? Options: A. They are a very small range in one country, B. They are the largest mountains on Earth, C. They are only found in India, D. They have no effect on the climate","excerpt":"The highest peaks in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest... The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.","stem":"What is the most accurate way to describe the size of the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are a very small range in one country,","B":"They are the largest mountains on Earth,","C":"They are only found in India,","D":"They have no effect on the climate"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes them as having the highest peaks in the world, making them the largest mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest peaks in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest... The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q005","read_aloud":"How does plate tectonics explain the formation of the Himalayas? Options: A. Rain caused the land to rise up, B. The moving of Earth\u0027s plates caused the land to lift, C. Animals pushed the earth into piles, D. The sun\u0027s heat made the land expand","excerpt":"The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates... When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains.","stem":"How does plate tectonics explain the formation of the Himalayas? Options:","choices":{"A":"Rain caused the land to rise up,","B":"The moving of Earth\u0027s plates caused the land to lift,","C":"Animals pushed the earth into piles,","D":"The sun\u0027s heat made the land expand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly identifies \"plate tectonics\" as the movement of plates that bumps land together to create mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The surface of Earth, called the crust, is made of huge slabs of rock called plates... When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q006","read_aloud":"What is the main way the Himalayas influence the climate of the region? Options: A. By creating giant glaciers, B. By acting as a barrier to weather systems, C. By trapping all the heat from the sun, D. By bringing rain only in the winter","excerpt":"Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds... The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south.","stem":"What is the main way the Himalayas influence the climate of the region? Options:","choices":{"A":"By creating giant glaciers,","B":"By acting as a barrier to weather systems,","C":"By trapping all the heat from the sun,","D":"By bringing rain only in the winter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By blocking both cold and humid air, the mountains change the weather on either side.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of the year\u0027s rainfall of 60 inches (152 cm) comes with monsoon winds... The Himalayas affect the climate of central Asia by blocking cold weather from the north and humid weather from the south."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q007","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why would a yak survive better in the Himalayas than a tiger? Options: A. A tiger needs tropical forests, while a yak likes cold, dry plateaus, B. A tiger is too large to walk on mountains, C. A yak is faster than a tiger, D. Tigers eat too much food","excerpt":"The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate.","stem":"Based on the text, why would a yak survive better in the Himalayas than a tiger? Options:","choices":{"A":"A tiger needs tropical forests, while a yak likes cold, dry plateaus,","B":"A tiger is too large to walk on mountains,","C":"A yak is faster than a tiger,","D":"Tigers eat too much food"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Tigers were plentiful in the forest, but yaks are described as liking the cold, dry climate of the high, treeless mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The yak is a Tibetan ox that lives on high plateaus and in the mountains. It likes the cold, dry climate."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q008","read_aloud":"How does the author show the relationship between human actions and nature? Options: A. By showing that humans always improve nature, B. By explaining how human actions like cutting trees can hurt the land, C. By saying that plants do not need soil to grow, D. By saying trees are not important at all","excerpt":"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place... Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides.","stem":"How does the author show the relationship between human actions and nature? Options:","choices":{"A":"By showing that humans always improve nature,","B":"By explaining how human actions like cutting trees can hurt the land,","C":"By saying that plants do not need soil to grow,","D":"By saying trees are not important at all"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text connects the cutting of trees to erosion, showing a negative impact on the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place... Even though many of the steep slopes no longer have trees, beautiful wildflowers color the mountainsides."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q009","read_aloud":"Why do you think people are still interested in the 1924 climbing attempt? Options: A. They want to keep the mountain empty, B. They want to learn from the history of exploring such a difficult place, C. They want to hide the mountain from others, D. They think the mountain is haunted","excerpt":"In 1999, an expedition searched for clues to the 1924 disappearance of George Mallory and Andrew Irvine.","stem":"Why do you think people are still interested in the 1924 climbing attempt? Options:","choices":{"A":"They want to keep the mountain empty,","B":"They want to learn from the history of exploring such a difficult place,","C":"They want to hide the mountain from others,","D":"They think the mountain is haunted"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Exploring the mountains is difficult, and learning from past attempts helps us understand the history and challenges of these extreme places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1999, an expedition searched for clues to the 1924 disappearance of George Mallory and Andrew Irvine."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q010","read_aloud":"Do you think it is a good idea for governments to protect national parks in the Himalayas? Why or why not? Options: A. No, because people should be allowed to cut down all the trees, B. Yes, because protecting the environment saves plants and animals for the future, C. No, because it is too expensive to look after the mountains, D. Yes, because it makes the mountains smaller and easier to climb","excerpt":"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.","stem":"Do you think it is a good idea for governments to protect national parks in the Himalayas? Why or why not? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, because people should be allowed to cut down all the trees,","B":"Yes, because protecting the environment saves plants and animals for the future,","C":"No, because it is too expensive to look after the mountains,","D":"Yes, because it makes the mountains smaller and easier to climb"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Protecting the environment ensures that species do not go extinct and that the natural beauty is preserved for future generations, which is the goal mentioned in the text. Section A - Text Information Title: The HimalayasAuthor: Charles W. MaynardGenre: Informational TextSource: Pages 546-559, Student Interactive U5 Week 4 Preview Vocabulary: survey, subcontinent, plateau, altitude, erosion","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"survey\" mean? A. a quick glance at something B. a careful measurement and study of land C. a type of mountain animal D. a weather pattern","excerpt":"\"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.\"","stem":"What does \"survey\" mean?","choices":{"A":"a quick glance at something","B":"a careful measurement and study of land","C":"a type of mountain animal","D":"a weather pattern"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In the text, a survey means to carefully measure and study an area of land. Sir George Everest was studying and mapping India.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q012","read_aloud":"What is a \"subcontinent\"? A. a small ocean B. a large region that is part of a continent C. a type of rock formation D. a country in Europe","excerpt":"\"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia.\"","stem":"What is a \"subcontinent\"?","choices":{"A":"a small ocean","B":"a large region that is part of a continent","C":"a type of rock formation","D":"a country in Europe"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that India is a large region that is part of the continent of Asia. A subcontinent is a big area that is part of an even larger continent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q013","read_aloud":"What is \"erosion\"? A. the process of planting trees B. the process of wearing away or breaking down land C. the process of building mountains D. the process of making it rain","excerpt":"\"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\"","stem":"What is \"erosion\"?","choices":{"A":"the process of planting trees","B":"the process of wearing away or breaking down land","C":"the process of building mountains","D":"the process of making it rain"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines erosion as the \"process of wearing away or breaking down land over time.\" Without tree roots, soil erodes by washing or blowing away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away in rain or blowing away in high winds.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The Himalayas are a long mountain range with the world\u0027s tallest peaks. B. The Himalayas are in Europe. C. Only one peak in the Himalayas is tall. D. The Himalayas are getting smaller.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level. The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas are a long mountain range with the world\u0027s tallest peaks.","B":"The Himalayas are in Europe.","C":"Only one peak in the Himalayas is tall.","D":"The Himalayas are getting smaller."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt gives two key facts: the Himalayas have the highest peaks and stretch for 1,550 miles. The main idea combines these facts about the range\u0027s height and length.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. Fourteen of the peaks rise more than 26,247 feet (8,000 m) above sea level. The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about why climbers use oxygen tanks? A. because they are heavy B. because there is not enough oxygen in the air C. because the tanks look cool D. because the tanks keep them warm","excerpt":"\"Atop Mt. Everest the oxygen in the air is only one-third of that at sea level. It is difficult for plants, animals, and humans to live there.\"","stem":"What can you infer about why climbers use oxygen tanks?","choices":{"A":"because they are heavy","B":"because there is not enough oxygen in the air","C":"because the tanks look cool","D":"because the tanks keep them warm"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says oxygen is only one-third of normal at the top of Everest. This means there is very little oxygen, so climbers need tanks to help them breathe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Atop Mt. Everest the oxygen in the air is only one-third of that at sea level. It is difficult for plants, animals, and humans to live there.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q016","read_aloud":"What structure does the author use here? A. problem and solution B. compare and contrast C. cause and effect D. sequence","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges... The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range... is from 250 to 300 million years old.\"","stem":"What structure does the author use here?","choices":{"A":"problem and solution","B":"compare and contrast","C":"cause and effect","D":"sequence"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author compares the age of the Himalayas (60-65 million years) with the age of the Appalachians (250-300 million years) to show how they are different.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas are young compared to other mountain ranges... The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago. The Appalachian range... is from 250 to 300 million years old.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q017","read_aloud":"What language does the name \"Himalaya\" come from? A. English B. Spanish C. Sanskrit D. Chinese","excerpt":"\"The name \u0027Himalaya\u0027 comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.\"","stem":"What language does the name \"Himalaya\" come from?","choices":{"A":"English","B":"Spanish","C":"Sanskrit","D":"Chinese"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly states that the name comes from \"Sanskrit,\" which is an ancient language spoken in India.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The name \u0027Himalaya\u0027 comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q018","read_aloud":"Why do the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas have different climates? A. Because they are at different altitudes. B. Because they are in different countries. C. Because one gets more wind. D. Because one has more people.","excerpt":"\"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there. The valleys of the Outer Himalayas... are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate.\"","stem":"Why do the Outer Himalayas and Lesser Himalayas have different climates?","choices":{"A":"Because they are at different altitudes.","B":"Because they are in different countries.","C":"Because one gets more wind.","D":"Because one has more people."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The first sentence states that \"wide differences of altitude create the many climates.\" The Outer and Lesser Himalayas are at different heights, which causes their different climates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there. The valleys of the Outer Himalayas... are subtropical with hot days and plenty of rain. The valleys of the Lesser Himalayas have a temperate climate.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q019","read_aloud":"Why does the author include information about Sherpas? A. To show that local people have important knowledge about the mountains. B. To show that only Sherpas can visit Nepal. C. To explain how to become a Sherpa. D. To list all the foods Sherpas eat.","excerpt":"\"The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas... Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.\"","stem":"Why does the author include information about Sherpas?","choices":{"A":"To show that local people have important knowledge about the mountains.","B":"To show that only Sherpas can visit Nepal.","C":"To explain how to become a Sherpa.","D":"To list all the foods Sherpas eat."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author includes Sherpas to show that people who have lived in the mountains for generations have valuable knowledge. Sherpas are \"the best guides\" because they know the mountains so well.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Sherpa people live in Nepal\u0027s Great Himalayas... Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q020","read_aloud":"Why are the Himalayas worth protecting? Give two reasons from the text. A. They are tall and old. B. They are home to endangered species and inspire wonder in people around the world. C. They block all weather from moving. D. They are easy to climb.","excerpt":"\"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved... Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks.\"","stem":"Why are the Himalayas worth protecting? Give two reasons from the text.","choices":{"A":"They are tall and old.","B":"They are home to endangered species and inspire wonder in people around the world.","C":"They block all weather from moving.","D":"They are easy to climb."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text gives two reasons for protection: (1) endangered plants and animals live there and need to be saved, and (2) people from all over the world feel wonder when they see the peaks. Both reasons show the Himalayas are valuable and worth protecting. Section A - Text Information Title: The HimalayasAuthor: Charles W. MaynardText Type: Informational TextPreview Vocabulary Words: survey, subcontinent, plateau, altitude, erosion","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved... Although only a few people will ever climb the mountains, people come from all over the world to look with wonder at these mysterious high peaks.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q021","read_aloud":"What does \"survey\" mean in this sentence? A. measurement of an area of land B. a type of mountain climbing gear C. a map drawn by ancient people D. the highest point of a mountain","excerpt":"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.","stem":"What does \"survey\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"measurement of an area of land","B":"a type of mountain climbing gear","C":"a map drawn by ancient people","D":"the highest point of a mountain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Survey means measurement of an area of land. The text says Sir George Everest led the survey of India.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q022","read_aloud":"What does \"subcontinent\" mean here? A. large region that is part of a continent B. small island in the ocean C. deep valley between mountains D. flat land near the sea","excerpt":"About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia.","stem":"What does \"subcontinent\" mean here?","choices":{"A":"large region that is part of a continent","B":"small island in the ocean","C":"deep valley between mountains","D":"flat land near the sea"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Subcontinent means a large region that is part of a continent. The text describes India as a subcontinent.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: About 50 million years ago, the Indian subcontinent began to bump into a land mass called Eurasia."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q023","read_aloud":"What does \"erosion\" mean in this context? A. process of wearing away or breaking down land over time B. process of building up new land with fresh soil C. process of planting new trees in empty areas D. process of measuring the height of mountains","excerpt":"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion.","stem":"What does \"erosion\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"process of wearing away or breaking down land over time","B":"process of building up new land with fresh soil","C":"process of planting new trees in empty areas","D":"process of measuring the height of mountains"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Erosion means the process of wearing away or breaking down land over time. The text links tree cutting to erosion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q024","read_aloud":"How far do the Himalayas stretch? A. 1,550 miles B. 2,000 miles C. 1,000 miles D. 3,000 miles","excerpt":"The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.","stem":"How far do the Himalayas stretch?","choices":{"A":"1,550 miles","B":"2,000 miles","C":"1,000 miles","D":"3,000 miles"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states the Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles in central Asia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q025","read_aloud":"What happens when tectonic plates bump together? A. the crust is pushed up and forms mountains B. the ocean water rises and floods land C. the weather becomes colder and snowier D. the rivers dry up and disappear","excerpt":"When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains.","stem":"What happens when tectonic plates bump together?","choices":{"A":"the crust is pushed up and forms mountains","B":"the ocean water rises and floods land","C":"the weather becomes colder and snowier","D":"the rivers dry up and disappear"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says when plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and forms mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q026","read_aloud":"What creates the many climates in the Himalayas? A. wide differences of altitude B. the number of people living there C. the types of animals that live there D. the ancient trade routes through the mountains","excerpt":"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.","stem":"What creates the many climates in the Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"wide differences of altitude","B":"the number of people living there","C":"the types of animals that live there","D":"the ancient trade routes through the mountains"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states wide differences of altitude create the many climates found in the Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q027","read_aloud":"What is the highest peak in the world? A. Mount Everest B. Mount Kilimanjaro C. Mount Fuji D. Mount McKinley","excerpt":"The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m).","stem":"What is the highest peak in the world?","choices":{"A":"Mount Everest","B":"Mount Kilimanjaro","C":"Mount Fuji","D":"Mount McKinley"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states Mount Everest is the highest peak in the Himalayas and in the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest at 29,028 feet (8,848 m)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q028","read_aloud":"What stays on the ground year-round in the Great Himalayas? A. snow and ice B. green grass and flowers C. sand and desert plants D. rivers and lakes","excerpt":"The peaks of the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round.","stem":"What stays on the ground year-round in the Great Himalayas?","choices":{"A":"snow and ice","B":"green grass and flowers","C":"sand and desert plants","D":"rivers and lakes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states snow and ice stay on the ground year-round in the Great Himalayas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The peaks of the Great Himalayas are frozen worlds. Snow and ice stay on the ground year-round."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q029","read_aloud":"How do these factors work together to affect plant life? A. they determine which plants can survive in each area B. they make all plants grow at the same speed C. they cause plants to change color with the seasons D. they help plants grow taller than in other places","excerpt":"Rainfall, temperatures, and oxygen all affect the species of trees and plants that live in the mountains and in the valleys.","stem":"How do these factors work together to affect plant life?","choices":{"A":"they determine which plants can survive in each area","B":"they make all plants grow at the same speed","C":"they cause plants to change color with the seasons","D":"they help plants grow taller than in other places"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows how rainfall, temperatures, and oxygen work together to determine which plant species can live in different areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Rainfall, temperatures, and oxygen all affect the species of trees and plants that live in the mountains and in the valleys."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q030","read_aloud":"Why might protecting areas of the Himalayas be important for the future? A. it helps save endangered plants and animals for future generations B. it makes the mountains taller and more impressive C. it allows more people to climb the highest peaks D. it changes the climate to be warmer everywhere","excerpt":"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.","stem":"Why might protecting areas of the Himalayas be important for the future?","choices":{"A":"it helps save endangered plants and animals for future generations","B":"it makes the mountains taller and more impressive","C":"it allows more people to climb the highest peaks","D":"it changes the climate to be warmer everywhere"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text supports that protecting areas helps save endangered species, which preserves biodiversity for the future. Section A - Text Information Title: The Himalayas (excerpt)Author: Charles W. Maynard","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q031","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this passage? A. The Himalayas are the longest mountain range. B. The Himalayas are the highest and stretch across central Asia. C. The Himalayas are in Europe. D. The Himalayas have no peaks.","excerpt":"\"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. … The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this passage?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas are the longest mountain range.","B":"The Himalayas are the highest and stretch across central Asia.","C":"The Himalayas are in Europe.","D":"The Himalayas have no peaks."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph gives facts about height and length.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayan mountain range includes the highest peaks in the world. … The Himalayas stretch for 1,550 miles (2,494 km) in central Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q032","read_aloud":"What evidence shows that the Himalayas were once under the ocean? A. There are rivers there. B. Limestone with sea creature fossils is found near the peaks. C. People have found whale skeletons. D. The mountains are wet.","excerpt":"\"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago. … Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\"","stem":"What evidence shows that the Himalayas were once under the ocean?","choices":{"A":"There are rivers there.","B":"Limestone with sea creature fossils is found near the peaks.","C":"People have found whale skeletons.","D":"The mountains are wet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Limestone with fossils proves the area was once ocean floor.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The peaks of the Himalayas were part of the ocean floor millions of years ago. … Some rocks near the highest peaks of the Himalayas are limestone. Limestone is a kind of rock that is made up of the fossils of sea creatures.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q033","read_aloud":"What can you infer about plant life above 16,000 feet? A. Forests are thick. B. Only small plants like mosses or no plants may grow there. C. Fruit trees grow there. D. There are many flowers.","excerpt":"\"The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.\"","stem":"What can you infer about plant life above 16,000 feet?","choices":{"A":"Forests are thick.","B":"Only small plants like mosses or no plants may grow there.","C":"Fruit trees grow there.","D":"There are many flowers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Trees cannot grow; only small, hardy plants might survive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The tree line in the Great Himalayas is about 16,000 feet (4,877 m). Trees will not grow above this level because of the high altitude and the cold.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q034","read_aloud":"Who were the first two people to reach the summit of Mount Everest? A. George Mallory and Andrew Irvine B. Tenzing Norgay and Edmund Hillary C. Sir George Everest and his team D. A Spanish priest and a British surveyor","excerpt":"\"On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.\"","stem":"Who were the first two people to reach the summit of Mount Everest?","choices":{"A":"George Mallory and Andrew Irvine","B":"Tenzing Norgay and Edmund Hillary","C":"Sir George Everest and his team","D":"A Spanish priest and a British surveyor"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states they were the first to reach the peak.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"On May 29, 1953, Tenzing Norgay, a Sherpa, and Edmund Hillary, of New Zealand, became the first to reach Everest\u0027s peak.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q035","read_aloud":"What is the relationship between cutting down trees and erosion? A. Cutting trees stops erosion. B. Cutting trees removes the roots that hold soil, leading to erosion. C. There is no relationship. D. Cutting trees creates new soil.","excerpt":"\"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides.\"","stem":"What is the relationship between cutting down trees and erosion?","choices":{"A":"Cutting trees stops erosion.","B":"Cutting trees removes the roots that hold soil, leading to erosion.","C":"There is no relationship.","D":"Cutting trees creates new soil."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Roots hold soil; without them, soil erodes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People have cut down many of these trees, which has caused erosion. Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q036","read_aloud":"Do you think creating national parks is a good way to protect the Himalayas? Why? A. No, because parks cost too much money. B. Yes, because they limit harmful activities and preserve nature for the future. C. No, because people should be allowed to do anything. D. Yes, because parks make money from tourists.","excerpt":"\"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery.\"","stem":"Do you think creating national parks is a good way to protect the Himalayas? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because parks cost too much money.","B":"Yes, because they limit harmful activities and preserve nature for the future.","C":"No, because people should be allowed to do anything.","D":"Yes, because parks make money from tourists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"National parks protect nature and wildlife.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The government of Nepal set aside this special place to protect animals, plants, and mountain scenery.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q037","read_aloud":"Write one sentence telling what you would most want to see if you visited the Himalayas. A. \"I would want to see a shopping mall.\" B. \"I would want to see the high snowcovered peaks, glaciers, and maybe a snow leopard.\" C. \"I would want to stay inside a hotel.\" D. \"I would not want to see anything.\"","excerpt":"\"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.\"","stem":"Write one sentence telling what you would most want to see if you visited the Himalayas.","choices":{"A":"\"I would want to see a shopping mall.\"","B":"\"I would want to see the high snowcovered peaks, glaciers, and maybe a snow leopard.\"","C":"\"I would want to stay inside a hotel.\"","D":"\"I would not want to see anything.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes mountains, glaciers, and animals like snow leopards. Section A - Text information Title: The Himalayas Author: Charles W. Maynard","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q038","read_aloud":"What does a survey involve? A. Measuring and mapping land B. Climbing high mountains C. Hunting for animals D. Digging for fossils","excerpt":"Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843.","stem":"What does a survey involve?","choices":{"A":"Measuring and mapping land","B":"Climbing high mountains","C":"Hunting for animals","D":"Digging for fossils"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"A survey is defined earlier in the text as a measurement of an area of land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Everest (1790-1866) led the survey of India from 1830 to 1843."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q039","read_aloud":"What does altitude measure? A. How deep the water is B. How hot the sun is C. How high the land is D. How wide the valley is","excerpt":"Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there.","stem":"What does altitude measure?","choices":{"A":"How deep the water is","B":"How hot the sun is","C":"How high the land is","D":"How wide the valley is"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Altitude is defined as height above sea level.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Wide differences of altitude in the Himalayas create the many climates found there."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q040","read_aloud":"What happens during erosion? A. New trees grow quickly. B. Rocks turn into lava. C. Soil wears away or washes off. D. Water freezes into ice.","excerpt":"Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away... caused erosion.","stem":"What happens during erosion?","choices":{"A":"New trees grow quickly.","B":"Rocks turn into lava.","C":"Soil wears away or washes off.","D":"Water freezes into ice."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Erosion is the process of wearing away or breaking down land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Tree roots are necessary for keeping soil in place on steep mountainsides. They keep the soil from washing away... caused erosion."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which sentence best summarizes the text? A. The Himalayas are cold mountains with no animals. B. The Himalayas are young mountains that are growing. C. The Himalayas are the highest mountains in the world. D. The Himalayas are located in North America.","excerpt":"The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest... The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago.","stem":"Which sentence best summarizes the text?","choices":{"A":"The Himalayas are cold mountains with no animals.","B":"The Himalayas are young mountains that are growing.","C":"The Himalayas are the highest mountains in the world.","D":"The Himalayas are located in North America."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"This sentence covers the main point that they are the highest mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The highest peak in the Himalayas, and thus in the world, is Mount Everest... The Himalayas began forming from 60 to 65 million years ago."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q042","read_aloud":"What is the cause of mountains forming? A. Plates bumping together B. Glaciers melting C. Rivers flowing down D. Wind blowing hard","excerpt":"When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains.","stem":"What is the cause of mountains forming?","choices":{"A":"Plates bumping together","B":"Glaciers melting","C":"Rivers flowing down","D":"Wind blowing hard"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that plates bumping together pushes the crust up to form mountains.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When the plates bump together, the crust is pushed up and it forms mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q043","read_aloud":"Why would a climber hire a Sherpa? A. To carry their luggage at the airport B. To guide them safely up the mountain C. To teach them how to swim D. To translate English into Sanskrit","excerpt":"Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains.","stem":"Why would a climber hire a Sherpa?","choices":{"A":"To carry their luggage at the airport","B":"To guide them safely up the mountain","C":"To teach them how to swim","D":"To translate English into Sanskrit"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text identifies Sherpas as the best guides for climbers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sherpas are known as the best guides for climbers of these mountains."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q044","read_aloud":"How does a yak\u0027s fur help it survive? A. It helps it run faster. B. It helps it hide in the snow. C. It keeps it warm in the cold. D. It helps it swim in rivers.","excerpt":"The wild yak is a huge animal with long, brown-black hair forming a thick coat.","stem":"How does a yak\u0027s fur help it survive?","choices":{"A":"It helps it run faster.","B":"It helps it hide in the snow.","C":"It keeps it warm in the cold.","D":"It helps it swim in rivers."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says yaks like the cold, dry climate and have thick coats, which implies the coat keeps them warm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The wild yak is a huge animal with long, brown-black hair forming a thick coat."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q045","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about climbing Mt. Everest? A. It is a safe and easy trip. B. It is a dangerous and difficult task. C. It takes only one day to finish. D. It requires no special equipment.","excerpt":"Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen.","stem":"What can you conclude about climbing Mt. Everest?","choices":{"A":"It is a safe and easy trip.","B":"It is a dangerous and difficult task.","C":"It takes only one day to finish.","D":"It requires no special equipment."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions climbers dying, freezing temperatures, and low oxygen, showing it is dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Since then, many climbers who have tried to scale this mountain have died from the freezing temperatures and the low oxygen."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q046","read_aloud":"Is protecting these areas a good idea? A. Yes, because it saves nature for the future. B. No, because people need more places to build houses. C. Yes, because it will stop the rain from falling. D. No, because animals do not need protection.","excerpt":"Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved.","stem":"Is protecting these areas a good idea?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it saves nature for the future.","B":"No, because people need more places to build houses.","C":"Yes, because it will stop the rain from falling.","D":"No, because animals do not need protection."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Protecting areas helps save endangered plants and animals, which is good for the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some areas of the Himalayas are being protected by several governments so that endangered plants and animals will be saved."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q047","read_aloud":"If you could create a new national park in the Himalayas, what would you name it? Use details from the text. A. Snow Leopard Park B. High Glacier Park C. The Great Fossil Park D. All of the above are good names.","excerpt":"The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places.","stem":"If you could create a new national park in the Himalayas, what would you name it? Use details from the text.","choices":{"A":"Snow Leopard Park","B":"High Glacier Park","C":"The Great Fossil Park","D":"All of the above are good names."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"All the options use details from the text (snow leopards, glaciers, fossils), so any would be a good name.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Himalayas remain among Earth\u0027s most wonderful places."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q048","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q049","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. A snowy mountain, B. A place to live, C. A cold language, D. A type of rock","excerpt":"The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"A snowy mountain,","B":"A place to live,","C":"A cold language,","D":"A type of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says \"abode, or house,\" which tells us that an abode is a place where someone lives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The name \"Himalaya\" comes from Sanskrit words that mean abode, or house, of snow."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w4-the-himalayas-std-q050","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. plain B. valley (low are C. mountain D. glacier","excerpt":"\"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"plain","B":"valley (low are","C":"mountain","D":"glacier"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A plateau is a high, flat area; a valley is a low area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The high Tibetan plateau lies to the north.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise","grade":4,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":5,"week":5,"title":"Trashing Paradise","author":"Rukhsana Khan","genre":"Informational Text","essential_question":"How can human choices affect natural places?","weekly_question":"How has trash changed Bali, and what can people do about it?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["marred","biodegradable","decomposed","pollution","paradise"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Trashing Paradise. How has trash changed Bali, and what can people do about it?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"marred\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options: A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"What does the word \"marred\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q002","read_aloud":"What is the author trying to help the reader do in this paragraph? Options: A. buy a ticket to Bali, B. learn how to surf, C. picture the beauty of Bali, D. find a map of Indonesia","excerpt":"\"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder.\"","stem":"What is the author trying to help the reader do in this paragraph? Options:","choices":{"A":"buy a ticket to Bali,","B":"learn how to surf,","C":"picture the beauty of Bali,","D":"find a map of Indonesia"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author asks the reader to close their eyes and picture things to help the reader imagine what the island looks like.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What did the Balinese people use for food wrappings long ago? Options: A. plastic bags, B. plastic plates, C. natural items like leaves, D. metal containers","excerpt":"\"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\"","stem":"What did the Balinese people use for food wrappings long ago? Options:","choices":{"A":"plastic bags,","B":"plastic plates,","C":"natural items like leaves,","D":"metal containers"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says they used \"banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items\" for their food.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q004","read_aloud":"Based on the paragraph, what does \"biodegradable\" mean? Options: A. it stays forever, B. it rots naturally, C. it is made of plastic, D. it is very strong","excerpt":"\"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted. It didn\u0027t create pollution.\"","stem":"Based on the paragraph, what does \"biodegradable\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"it stays forever,","B":"it rots naturally,","C":"it is made of plastic,","D":"it is very strong"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that biodegradable means it \"decomposed, or rotted,\" which means it breaks down naturally.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted. It didn\u0027t create pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q005","read_aloud":"What was Bali like before there was a lot of trash? Options: A. It was a dirty place, B. It was a clean paradise, C. It was a place with no trees, D. It was a busy city","excerpt":"\"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash.\"","stem":"What was Bali like before there was a lot of trash? Options:","choices":{"A":"It was a dirty place,","B":"It was a clean paradise,","C":"It was a place with no trees,","D":"It was a busy city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author states that Bali \"really was a paradise\" and the people created little or no trash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"marred\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. made beautiful B. damaged or made ugly C. covered in flowers D. protected from harm","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"What does the word \"marred\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"made beautiful","B":"damaged or made ugly","C":"covered in flowers","D":"protected from harm"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines marred as \"damaged; made ugly; marked.\" Trash piled on roadsides makes Bali look ugly and damaged.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is this excerpt describing? A. a snowy mountain B. the beautiful island of Bali before trash became a problem C. a city in the United States D. an underwater world","excerpt":"\"Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder. The smell of orchids and coconuts mingles with a gentle breeze from the Indian Ocean.\"","stem":"What is this excerpt describing?","choices":{"A":"a snowy mountain","B":"the beautiful island of Bali before trash became a problem","C":"a city in the United States","D":"an underwater world"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Bali with blue skies, palm trees, white sand, and ocean breezes. This is the paradise Bali used to be before trash became a problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder. The smell of orchids and coconuts mingles with a gentle breeze from the Indian Ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What did the Balinese people use to carry their things? A. plastic bags B. cloth bags C. paper boxes D. metal cans","excerpt":"\"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\"","stem":"What did the Balinese people use to carry their things?","choices":{"A":"plastic bags","B":"cloth bags","C":"paper boxes","D":"metal cans"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that the Balinese people \"used cloth bags to carry what they needed\" before plastic became common.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q009","read_aloud":"According to the text, what was Bali like for most of its history? A. full of trash and pollution B. a paradise with little or no trash C. covered in plastic bags D. a place with no people","excerpt":"\"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash.\"","stem":"According to the text, what was Bali like for most of its history?","choices":{"A":"full of trash and pollution","B":"a paradise with little or no trash","C":"covered in plastic bags","D":"a place with no people"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise\" and that the people \"created little or no trash.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"biodegradable\" mean? A. something that never breaks down B. something that decomposes or rots naturally C. something made of plastic D. something that is poisonous","excerpt":"\"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted. It didn\u0027t create pollution.\"","stem":"What does \"biodegradable\" mean?","choices":{"A":"something that never breaks down","B":"something that decomposes or rots naturally","C":"something made of plastic","D":"something that is poisonous"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that biodegradable means it \"decomposed, or rotted\" and \"didn\u0027t create pollution.\" This means it breaks down naturally in the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted. It didn\u0027t create pollution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What do people do in Bali according to this sentence? A. swim, surf, snorkel, and relax B. work, study, cook, and clean C. drive, fly, sail, and hike D. shop, eat, sleep, and watch","excerpt":"People swim, surf, snorkel, and soak in the tropical vibes.","stem":"What do people do in Bali according to this sentence?","choices":{"A":"swim, surf, snorkel, and relax","B":"work, study, cook, and clean","C":"drive, fly, sail, and hike","D":"shop, eat, sleep, and watch"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text lists activities people enjoy in Bali: swimming, surfing, snorkeling, and relaxing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: People swim, surf, snorkel, and soak in the tropical vibes."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this sentence? A. Plastic garbage is harming Bali\u0027s environment B. Bali has beautiful beaches and oceans C. Tourists love to visit tropical islands D. Flowers smell nice in Bali","excerpt":"Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare.","stem":"What is the main idea of this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Plastic garbage is harming Bali\u0027s environment","B":"Bali has beautiful beaches and oceans","C":"Tourists love to visit tropical islands","D":"Flowers smell nice in Bali"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sentence says plastic waste is turning Bali into an environmental problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What did the Balinese people create in the past? A. little or no trash B. lots of plastic bags C. many factories D. big shopping malls","excerpt":"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash.","stem":"What did the Balinese people create in the past?","choices":{"A":"little or no trash","B":"lots of plastic bags","C":"many factories","D":"big shopping malls"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says long ago, Balinese people made very little trash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q014","read_aloud":"Why did the Balinese use banana leaves and coconut shells? A. to wrap and serve their food B. to build houses and boats C. to make clothes and shoes D. to create art and music","excerpt":"They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.","stem":"Why did the Balinese use banana leaves and coconut shells?","choices":{"A":"to wrap and serve their food","B":"to build houses and boats","C":"to make clothes and shoes","D":"to create art and music"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says they used natural items like banana leaves as wrappings and plates for food.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this passage? A. Bali is a beautiful island with no problems. B. Bali used to be a paradise, but now it is damaged by trash. C. Bali has always been full of garbage. D. Bali is too hot to visit.","excerpt":"\"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. … That\u0027s the Bali many people see in their mind\u0027s eye. It\u0027s the Bali that existed for most of the island\u0027s history. Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this passage?","choices":{"A":"Bali is a beautiful island with no problems.","B":"Bali used to be a paradise, but now it is damaged by trash.","C":"Bali has always been full of garbage.","D":"Bali is too hot to visit."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts the beautiful past with the trashfilled present.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. … That\u0027s the Bali many people see in their mind\u0027s eye. It\u0027s the Bali that existed for most of the island\u0027s history. Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What natural items did the Balinese use as wrappings and plates? A. Plastic bags and bottles B. Banana leaves and coconut shells C. Paper and cardboard D. Metal and glass","excerpt":"\"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\"","stem":"What natural items did the Balinese use as wrappings and plates?","choices":{"A":"Plastic bags and bottles","B":"Banana leaves and coconut shells","C":"Paper and cardboard","D":"Metal and glass"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists banana leaves and coconut shells.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What does \"convenience came to Bali\" mean in this sentence? A. People started using easy, disposable plastic items instead of natural materials. B. Life became harder for the Balinese. C. The Balinese stopped using any containers. D. The island became cleaner.","excerpt":"\"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"What does \"convenience came to Bali\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"People started using easy, disposable plastic items instead of natural materials.","B":"Life became harder for the Balinese.","C":"The Balinese stopped using any containers.","D":"The island became cleaner."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Convenience\" refers to easytouse plastic items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What does the word marred mean in this sentence? A. Made dirty or damaged B. Made clean and new C. Painted with bright colors D. Hidden from view","excerpt":"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.","stem":"What does the word marred mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Made dirty or damaged","B":"Made clean and new","C":"Painted with bright colors","D":"Hidden from view"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the version of Bali is \"marred by trash,\" which means the trash made the island look ugly or damaged.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? A. The trash problem in Bali. B. The beautiful setting of Bali. C. The hotels in Indonesia. D. The surfing conditions.","excerpt":"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees.","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"The trash problem in Bali.","B":"The beautiful setting of Bali.","C":"The hotels in Indonesia.","D":"The surfing conditions."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The paragraph asks the reader to imagine the beautiful tropical island with blue skies and palm trees.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q020","read_aloud":"Where is the waste found in this version of Bali? A. Only in the forests. B. Only in the cities. C. On roadsides and beaches. D. In the hotels.","excerpt":"Waste is piled high on roadsides. It floats in the aqua ocean and washes up on the white-sand beaches.","stem":"Where is the waste found in this version of Bali?","choices":{"A":"Only in the forests.","B":"Only in the cities.","C":"On roadsides and beaches.","D":"In the hotels."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says waste is piled on roadsides and washes up on beaches.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Waste is piled high on roadsides. It floats in the aqua ocean and washes up on the white-sand beaches."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What was Bali like for most of its history? A. It was a dirty place. B. It was a paradise. C. It was full of trash. D. It was a scary place.","excerpt":"That\u0027s the Bali many people see in their mind\u0027s eye. It\u0027s the Bali that existed for most of the island\u0027s history.","stem":"What was Bali like for most of its history?","choices":{"A":"It was a dirty place.","B":"It was a paradise.","C":"It was full of trash.","D":"It was a scary place."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author describes the \"mind\u0027s eye\" view as a paradise with blue skies and palm trees.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: That\u0027s the Bali many people see in their mind\u0027s eye. It\u0027s the Bali that existed for most of the island\u0027s history."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What is happening to Bali today? A. It is becoming a paradise. B. It is getting cleaner. C. It is turning into a nightmare. D. It is empty of people.","excerpt":"Unfortunately, this is the reality of Bali today. Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare.","stem":"What is happening to Bali today?","choices":{"A":"It is becoming a paradise.","B":"It is getting cleaner.","C":"It is turning into a nightmare.","D":"It is empty of people."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that garbage is turning the paradise into an environmental nightmare.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Unfortunately, this is the reality of Bali today. Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What does \"crude oil\" mean in this passage? Options:? A. a type of cooking oil, B. a liquid found underground, C. a solid rock found on beaches, D. a chemical used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals.\"","stem":"What does \"crude oil\" mean in this passage? Options:?","choices":{"A":"a type of cooking oil,","B":"a liquid found underground,","C":"a solid rock found on beaches,","D":"a chemical used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Crude oil is defined in the text as \"unrefined liquid petroleum\" found deep inside the ground.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q024","read_aloud":"According to the text, what brought a lot of plastic to Bali? Options:? A. a change in the weather, B. a move toward convenience, C. a law passed by the government, D. a need for more food","excerpt":"\"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"According to the text, what brought a lot of plastic to Bali? Options:?","choices":{"A":"a change in the weather,","B":"a move toward convenience,","C":"a law passed by the government,","D":"a need for more food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that \"convenience came to Bali\" in the form of plastic items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l01-q025","read_aloud":"Which of these is a reason why trash is a problem on Bali? Options:? A. the island is very large, B. there are too many recycling centers, C. the island is small, D. people do not have enough food","excerpt":"\"Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place. Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground.\"","stem":"Which of these is a reason why trash is a problem on Bali? Options:?","choices":{"A":"the island is very large,","B":"there are too many recycling centers,","C":"the island is small,","D":"people do not have enough food"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author points out that because Bali is a small island, \"trash can pile up quickly\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place. Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"crude oil\" mean in this passage? Options: A. a type of cooking oil, B. a liquid found underground, C. a solid rock found on beaches, D. a chemical used for cleaning","excerpt":"\"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals.\"","stem":"What does \"crude oil\" mean in this passage? Options:","choices":{"A":"a type of cooking oil,","B":"a liquid found underground,","C":"a solid rock found on beaches,","D":"a chemical used for cleaning"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Crude oil is defined in the text as \"unrefined liquid petroleum\" found deep inside the ground.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q002","read_aloud":"According to the text, what brought a lot of plastic to Bali? Options: A. a change in the weather, B. a move toward convenience, C. a law passed by the government, D. a need for more food","excerpt":"\"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"According to the text, what brought a lot of plastic to Bali? Options:","choices":{"A":"a change in the weather,","B":"a move toward convenience,","C":"a law passed by the government,","D":"a need for more food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that \"convenience came to Bali\" in the form of plastic items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q003","read_aloud":"Which of these is a reason why trash is a problem on Bali? Options: A. the island is very large, B. there are too many recycling centers, C. the island is small, D. people do not have enough food","excerpt":"\"Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place. Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground.\"","stem":"Which of these is a reason why trash is a problem on Bali? Options:","choices":{"A":"the island is very large,","B":"there are too many recycling centers,","C":"the island is small,","D":"people do not have enough food"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author points out that because Bali is a small island, \"trash can pile up quickly\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place. Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q004","read_aloud":"Why was it okay to drop banana leaves in the past? Options: A. they are made of plastic, B. they break down into the soil, C. animals eat them immediately, D. they are very hard to see","excerpt":"\"When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down and mixes with the soil. A dropped plastic container won\u0027t.\"","stem":"Why was it okay to drop banana leaves in the past? Options:","choices":{"A":"they are made of plastic,","B":"they break down into the soil,","C":"animals eat them immediately,","D":"they are very hard to see"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that unlike plastic, a banana leaf will decompose and mix with the soil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down and mixes with the soil. A dropped plastic container won\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when saying \"few knew... about the consequences\"? Options: A. not many people knew how to make plastic, B. people didn\u0027t know about the problems plastic would cause, C. people were already using plastic bags, D. it was too expensive to ask questions","excerpt":"\"Almost overnight, plastic bags became a basic convenience of modern life. Few knew about or took the time to ask about the consequences of convenience.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when saying \"few knew... about the consequences\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"not many people knew how to make plastic,","B":"people didn\u0027t know about the problems plastic would cause,","C":"people were already using plastic bags,","D":"it was too expensive to ask questions"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"consequences\" refer to the bad results of using plastic, which most people were not thinking about at the time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Almost overnight, plastic bags became a basic convenience of modern life. Few knew about or took the time to ask about the consequences of convenience.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"disposable\" mean in this sentence? A. designed to last forever B. single-use; designed to be thrown away C. made of metal D. very expensive","excerpt":"\"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"What does \"disposable\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"designed to last forever","B":"single-use; designed to be thrown away","C":"made of metal","D":"very expensive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines disposable as \"single-use; designed to be thrown away.\" These plastic items were made to be used once and then thrown away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. People started using plastic bottles. B. Bali was a paradise with little trash. C. Tourists stopped visiting Bali. D. The government banned plastic bags.","excerpt":"\"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise... Then convenience came to Bali... Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles.\"","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"People started using plastic bottles.","B":"Bali was a paradise with little trash.","C":"Tourists stopped visiting Bali.","D":"The government banned plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise\" before \"convenience came to Bali.\" So being a paradise with little trash happened first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise... Then convenience came to Bali... Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q008","read_aloud":"How are banana leaves different from plastic containers? A. Banana leaves are nonbiodegradable. B. Plastic containers break down quickly in nature. C. Banana leaves are natural and biodegradable, but plastic is not. D. They are exactly the same.","excerpt":"\"They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food... Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"How are banana leaves different from plastic containers?","choices":{"A":"Banana leaves are nonbiodegradable.","B":"Plastic containers break down quickly in nature.","C":"Banana leaves are natural and biodegradable, but plastic is not.","D":"They are exactly the same."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says banana leaves and coconut shells are natural items, while plastic is \"nonbiodegradable.\" Natural items break down, but plastic does not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food... Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q009","read_aloud":"Why did people like using plastic? A. It was heavy and broke easily. B. It was durable, lightweight, and waterproof. C. It was very expensive. D. It was hard to find in stores.","excerpt":"\"Plastic, in particular, proved hard to resist. It\u0027s durable, lightweight, and waterproof.\"","stem":"Why did people like using plastic?","choices":{"A":"It was heavy and broke easily.","B":"It was durable, lightweight, and waterproof.","C":"It was very expensive.","D":"It was hard to find in stores."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states three reasons people liked plastic: it is \"durable, lightweight, and waterproof.\" These features made it convenient to use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic, in particular, proved hard to resist. It\u0027s durable, lightweight, and waterproof.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"consequences\" mean in this sentence? A. good things that happen B. results or effects of an action C. types of plastic D. ways to recycle","excerpt":"\"Few knew about or took the time to ask about the consequences of convenience.\"","stem":"What does \"consequences\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"good things that happen","B":"results or effects of an action","C":"types of plastic","D":"ways to recycle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Consequences means the results or effects of something. The text says people didn\u0027t think about what would happen as a result of using so much plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Few knew about or took the time to ask about the consequences of convenience.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q011","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"disposable\"? A. single-use; meant to be thrown away B. very expensive and valuable C. made from natural materials D. strong and long-lasting","excerpt":"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"disposable\"?","choices":{"A":"single-use; meant to be thrown away","B":"very expensive and valuable","C":"made from natural materials","D":"strong and long-lasting"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Disposable means single-use or designed to be thrown away after one use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What happens to biodegradable items? A. they rot and break down naturally B. they stay the same forever C. they turn into plastic D. they float in the ocean","excerpt":"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted. It didn\u0027t create pollution.","stem":"What happens to biodegradable items?","choices":{"A":"they rot and break down naturally","B":"they stay the same forever","C":"they turn into plastic","D":"they float in the ocean"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that biodegradable things decompose or rot, so they don\u0027t cause pollution.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted. It didn\u0027t create pollution."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What happened after convenience came to Bali? A. people started using plastic bottles and bags B. people stopped buying chewing gum C. store clerks lost their jobs D. plastic bottles became expensive","excerpt":"Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles. Store clerks were putting even the smallest purchase-say, a pack of chewing gum-into its own plastic bag.","stem":"What happened after convenience came to Bali?","choices":{"A":"people started using plastic bottles and bags","B":"people stopped buying chewing gum","C":"store clerks lost their jobs","D":"plastic bottles became expensive"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says after convenience arrived, people began using plastic bottles and bags for purchases.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles. Store clerks were putting even the smallest purchase-say, a pack of chewing gum-into its own plastic bag."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What is plastic made from? A. chemicals from crude oil B. banana leaves and coconuts C. cloth and natural fibers D. water and sunlight","excerpt":"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground.","stem":"What is plastic made from?","choices":{"A":"chemicals from crude oil","B":"banana leaves and coconuts","C":"cloth and natural fibers","D":"water and sunlight"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that plastic is made from chemicals taken from crude oil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q015","read_aloud":"Why is plastic a problem for nature? A. it takes a very long time to break down B. it smells bad when it rots C. it is too heavy to move D. it costs too much to make","excerpt":"That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade.","stem":"Why is plastic a problem for nature?","choices":{"A":"it takes a very long time to break down","B":"it smells bad when it rots","C":"it is too heavy to move","D":"it costs too much to make"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains plastic doesn\u0027t break down easily and can last hundreds or thousands of years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What is the first step in making plastic? A. Melting pellets into a thin film B. Taking chemicals from crude oil C. Cutting the film into bags D. Making polyurethane","excerpt":"\"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic.\"","stem":"What is the first step in making plastic?","choices":{"A":"Melting pellets into a thin film","B":"Taking chemicals from crude oil","C":"Cutting the film into bags","D":"Making polyurethane"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists take chemicals from crude oil first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q017","read_aloud":"Why does plastic take so long to break down? A. Because it is natural. B. Because it is different from anything in nature, so nature cannot easily break it. C. Because it is too heavy. D. Because it is made of banana leaves.","excerpt":"\"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade.\"","stem":"Why does plastic take so long to break down?","choices":{"A":"Because it is natural.","B":"Because it is different from anything in nature, so nature cannot easily break it.","C":"Because it is too heavy.","D":"Because it is made of banana leaves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Plastic is not natural, so nature cannot easily break it down.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What does \"more harshly and more visibly\" mean? A. The effects of plastic are worse and easier to see in Bali. B. The effects are the same everywhere. C. Bali has no plastic problems. D. The effects are hidden.","excerpt":"\"For several reasons, Bali has felt the effects of this increase in the use of plastic more harshly and more visibly than many other places.\"","stem":"What does \"more harshly and more visibly\" mean?","choices":{"A":"The effects of plastic are worse and easier to see in Bali.","B":"The effects are the same everywhere.","C":"Bali has no plastic problems.","D":"The effects are hidden."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The trash problem is worse and more obvious in Bali.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For several reasons, Bali has felt the effects of this increase in the use of plastic more harshly and more visibly than many other places.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q019","read_aloud":"If trash piles up quickly on a small island, what might be a solution? A. Make the island larger. B. Reduce the amount of trash created and improve waste collection. C. Ignore the trash. D. Throw trash into the ocean.","excerpt":"\"One reason is that Bali is a small island. … Someone could easily drive around the whole island in a day. Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place.\"","stem":"If trash piles up quickly on a small island, what might be a solution?","choices":{"A":"Make the island larger.","B":"Reduce the amount of trash created and improve waste collection.","C":"Ignore the trash.","D":"Throw trash into the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Reducing waste and better collection would help solve the problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One reason is that Bali is a small island. … Someone could easily drive around the whole island in a day. Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q020","read_aloud":"How did the Balinese people carry things in the past? A. They used plastic bags. B. They used cloth bags. C. They used paper boxes. D. They carried items by hand.","excerpt":"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","stem":"How did the Balinese people carry things in the past?","choices":{"A":"They used plastic bags.","B":"They used cloth bags.","C":"They used paper boxes.","D":"They carried items by hand."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q021","read_aloud":"What happens to biodegradable trash? A. It stays forever. B. It turns into plastic. C. It decomposes or rots. D. It becomes poisonous.","excerpt":"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted.","stem":"What happens to biodegradable trash?","choices":{"A":"It stays forever.","B":"It turns into plastic.","C":"It decomposes or rots.","D":"It becomes poisonous."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text defines biodegradable as things that decompose or rot.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q022","read_aloud":"Why did the Balinese use banana leaves and coconut shells? A. To make the food taste better. B. To create more trash. C. To wrap their food naturally. D. To sell to tourists.","excerpt":"They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.","stem":"Why did the Balinese use banana leaves and coconut shells?","choices":{"A":"To make the food taste better.","B":"To create more trash.","C":"To wrap their food naturally.","D":"To sell to tourists."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains they used natural items as wrappings and plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q023","read_aloud":"What does the word \"marred\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"What does the word \"marred\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What is the author trying to help the reader do in this paragraph? Options:? A. buy a ticket to Bali, B. learn how to surf, C. picture the beauty of Bali, D. find a map of Indonesia","excerpt":"\"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder.\"","stem":"What is the author trying to help the reader do in this paragraph? Options:?","choices":{"A":"buy a ticket to Bali,","B":"learn how to surf,","C":"picture the beauty of Bali,","D":"find a map of Indonesia"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author asks the reader to close their eyes and picture things to help the reader imagine what the island looks like.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What did the Balinese people use for food wrappings long ago? Options:? A. plastic bags, B. plastic plates, C. natural items like leaves, D. metal containers","excerpt":"\"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\"","stem":"What did the Balinese people use for food wrappings long ago? Options:?","choices":{"A":"plastic bags,","B":"plastic plates,","C":"natural items like leaves,","D":"metal containers"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says they used \"banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items\" for their food.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"dispose\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. to clean up, B. to throw away, C. to hide, D. to sell","excerpt":"\"R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympic-size swimming pools.\"","stem":"What does the word \"dispose\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"to clean up,","B":"to throw away,","C":"to hide,","D":"to sell"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To dispose of something means to get rid of it or throw it away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympic-size swimming pools.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What is a main problem with trash collection in Bali? Options: A. the services do not have enough trucks, B. the services cannot handle the amount of trash, C. people refuse to pay the service, D. there are no roads for the trucks","excerpt":"\"According to one source, 75 percent of rubbish isn\u0027t picked up by any trash service. Bali\u0027s refuse collection and disposal services simply can\u0027t keep up with all the garbage produced by residents and tourists.\"","stem":"What is a main problem with trash collection in Bali? Options:","choices":{"A":"the services do not have enough trucks,","B":"the services cannot handle the amount of trash,","C":"people refuse to pay the service,","D":"there are no roads for the trucks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that the disposal services \"can\u0027t keep up with all the garbage produced\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"According to one source, 75 percent of rubbish isn\u0027t picked up by any trash service. Bali\u0027s refuse collection and disposal services simply can\u0027t keep up with all the garbage produced by residents and tourists.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q003","read_aloud":"According to the text, is burning trash a good way to get rid of it? Options: A. yes, it is the safest way, B. no, it is not a safe solution, C. yes, it is unique to Bali, D. no, it is too expensive","excerpt":"\"Bali isn\u0027t unique in this practice; experts estimate that 40 percent of the world\u0027s waste is eliminated through burning. To put it mildly, that\u0027s not a safe solution.\"","stem":"According to the text, is burning trash a good way to get rid of it? Options:","choices":{"A":"yes, it is the safest way,","B":"no, it is not a safe solution,","C":"yes, it is unique to Bali,","D":"no, it is too expensive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author specifically says that burning waste is \"not a safe solution\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali isn\u0027t unique in this practice; experts estimate that 40 percent of the world\u0027s waste is eliminated through burning. To put it mildly, that\u0027s not a safe solution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What happens when plastic is burned? Options: A. it disappears completely, B. it turns into water, C. it releases harmful toxins, D. it helps the plants grow","excerpt":"\"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\"","stem":"What happens when plastic is burned? Options:","choices":{"A":"it disappears completely,","B":"it turns into water,","C":"it releases harmful toxins,","D":"it helps the plants grow"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that burning plastic releases \"toxic chemicals called dioxins\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Why is burning plastic dangerous to people and animals? Options: A. it makes the air too cold, B. it causes serious illnesses, C. it makes too much noise, D. it creates too much light","excerpt":"\"These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.\"","stem":"Why is burning plastic dangerous to people and animals? Options:","choices":{"A":"it makes the air too cold,","B":"it causes serious illnesses,","C":"it makes too much noise,","D":"it creates too much light"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author links the toxins released by burning plastic to \"illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What is \"crude oil\"? A. a type of plastic bag B. unrefined liquid petroleum found deep in the ground C. a clean energy source D. a type of ocean animal","excerpt":"\"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground.\"","stem":"What is \"crude oil\"?","choices":{"A":"a type of plastic bag","B":"unrefined liquid petroleum found deep in the ground","C":"a clean energy source","D":"a type of ocean animal"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines crude oil as \"unrefined liquid petroleum\" that is \"found deep inside the ground.\" This is the raw material used to make plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What do scientists use to make plastic? A. water and sand B. chemicals from crude oil C. banana leaves D. ocean water","excerpt":"\"Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic.\"","stem":"What do scientists use to make plastic?","choices":{"A":"water and sand","B":"chemicals from crude oil","C":"banana leaves","D":"ocean water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says scientists take chemicals from crude oil and change them to make plastic. This shows that crude oil is the starting material for making plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q008","read_aloud":"How do the bullet points help the reader? A. They make the text longer. B. They list examples clearly so readers can see what trash is in the ocean. C. They hide important information. D. They tell a story about one person.","excerpt":"[Heading] \"The Trouble with Ocean Trash\" and bullet points listing: microplastics, plastic beverage bottles, plastic bags, disposable utensils and plates, straws and stirrers.","stem":"How do the bullet points help the reader?","choices":{"A":"They make the text longer.","B":"They list examples clearly so readers can see what trash is in the ocean.","C":"They hide important information.","D":"They tell a story about one person."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Bullet points are a text feature that lists items clearly. They help readers quickly see the different types of trash commonly found in the ocean.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: [Heading] \"The Trouble with Ocean Trash\" and bullet points listing: microplastics, plastic beverage bottles, plastic bags, disposable utensils and plates, straws and stirrers."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q009","read_aloud":"Why does plastic stay in the environment for so long? A. Because nature cannot easily break it down. B. Because animals eat it quickly. C. Because it melts in the rain. D. Because it turns into soil right away.","excerpt":"\"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade.\"","stem":"Why does plastic stay in the environment for so long?","choices":{"A":"Because nature cannot easily break it down.","B":"Because animals eat it quickly.","C":"Because it melts in the rain.","D":"Because it turns into soil right away."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says plastics are \"different from anything that occurs in nature\" and \"nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down.\" This is why plastic lasts for hundreds or thousands of years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q010","read_aloud":"Why is Bali\u0027s small size a problem for trash? A. Small islands have more trees. B. Trash can pile up quickly in a small place. C. Small islands have no people. D. Small islands are always cold.","excerpt":"\"One reason is that Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware.\"","stem":"Why is Bali\u0027s small size a problem for trash?","choices":{"A":"Small islands have more trees.","B":"Trash can pile up quickly in a small place.","C":"Small islands have no people.","D":"Small islands are always cold."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place.\" Because Bali is small, the trash becomes a bigger problem faster than it would in a larger area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One reason is that Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What is \"crude oil\" based on this sentence? A. unrefined liquid petroleum from underground B. a type of plastic bag C. a natural plant that grows in Bali D. a kind of ocean wave","excerpt":"Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground.","stem":"What is \"crude oil\" based on this sentence?","choices":{"A":"unrefined liquid petroleum from underground","B":"a type of plastic bag","C":"a natural plant that grows in Bali","D":"a kind of ocean wave"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Crude oil is unrefined liquid petroleum that comes from deep underground.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q012","read_aloud":"Why does trash pile up quickly in Bali? A. because it is a small island with limited space B. because tourists don\u0027t like to recycle C. because the weather is always sunny D. because plastic is very light","excerpt":"Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware. Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place.","stem":"Why does trash pile up quickly in Bali?","choices":{"A":"because it is a small island with limited space","B":"because tourists don\u0027t like to recycle","C":"because the weather is always sunny","D":"because plastic is very light"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Bali is small, so trash can build up fast in a limited area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware. Trash can pile up quickly in such a small place."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q013","read_aloud":"How did people in Bali used to throw things away? A. by dropping them on the ground B. by putting them in recycling bins C. by burning them in fires D. by burying them deep underground","excerpt":"Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground. When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine.","stem":"How did people in Bali used to throw things away?","choices":{"A":"by dropping them on the ground","B":"by putting them in recycling bins","C":"by burning them in fires","D":"by burying them deep underground"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Balinese people were used to dropping things on the ground, which worked when they used banana leaves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground. When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q014","read_aloud":"How many tourists visit Bali each year? A. more than 3 million B. about 1 million C. less than 500,000 D. exactly 10 million","excerpt":"More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year. They account for a large percentage of the hundreds of tons of plastic waste the island produces each day.","stem":"How many tourists visit Bali each year?","choices":{"A":"more than 3 million","B":"about 1 million","C":"less than 500,000","D":"exactly 10 million"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states more than 3 million tourists visit Bali yearly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year. They account for a large percentage of the hundreds of tons of plastic waste the island produces each day."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q015","read_aloud":"Why might tourists not help keep Bali clean? A. they don\u0027t live there permanently B. they don\u0027t know how to recycle C. they don\u0027t like the beaches D. they don\u0027t speak the language","excerpt":"Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean.","stem":"Why might tourists not help keep Bali clean?","choices":{"A":"they don\u0027t live there permanently","B":"they don\u0027t know how to recycle","C":"they don\u0027t like the beaches","D":"they don\u0027t speak the language"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains tourists may not feel responsible because they don\u0027t live on Bali.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the Balinese people\u0027s habits before plastic? A. They created a lot of trash. B. They used natural, reusable items and created very little waste. C. They had no way to carry things. D. They used only metal containers.","excerpt":"\"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. … Then convenience came to Bali. … Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the Balinese people\u0027s habits before plastic?","choices":{"A":"They created a lot of trash.","B":"They used natural, reusable items and created very little waste.","C":"They had no way to carry things.","D":"They used only metal containers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They used banana leaves and cloth bags, which are natural and reusable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. … Then convenience came to Bali. … Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q017","read_aloud":"How is this text organized? A. As a story with a beginning, middle, and end B. As a problemandsolution text C. As a poem D. As a set of instructions","excerpt":"The text describes the problem of trash in Bali, gives reasons for the problem (small island, habits, tourists, poor waste management), and then presents solutions (the Wijsensisters\u0027 campaign).","stem":"How is this text organized?","choices":{"A":"As a story with a beginning, middle, and end","B":"As a problemandsolution text","C":"As a poem","D":"As a set of instructions"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text identifies a problem and then explains solutions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text describes the problem of trash in Bali, gives reasons for the problem (small island, habits, tourists, poor waste management), and then presents solutions (the Wijsensisters\u0027 campaign)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q018","read_aloud":"About how many tourists visit Bali each year? A. 1 million B. 2 million C. 3 million D. 10 million","excerpt":"\"Tourists are a third reason for the trash problem-a huge reason. More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year. They account for a large percentage of the hundreds of tons of plastic waste the island produces each day.\"","stem":"About how many tourists visit Bali each year?","choices":{"A":"1 million","B":"2 million","C":"3 million","D":"10 million"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says more than 3 million tourists visit each year.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tourists are a third reason for the trash problem-a huge reason. More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year. They account for a large percentage of the hundreds of tons of plastic waste the island produces each day.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q019","read_aloud":"How is plastic made according to the text? A. By picking it from trees. B. By changing chemicals from crude oil. C. By recycling old bags. D. By mixing water and sand.","excerpt":"Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic.","stem":"How is plastic made according to the text?","choices":{"A":"By picking it from trees.","B":"By changing chemicals from crude oil.","C":"By recycling old bags.","D":"By mixing water and sand."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that scientists change chemicals from crude oil to make plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q020","read_aloud":"What is the main problem with plastic? A. It is too expensive. B. Nature cannot break it down easily. C. It is too heavy to carry. D. It melts in the rain.","excerpt":"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down.","stem":"What is the main problem with plastic?","choices":{"A":"It is too expensive.","B":"Nature cannot break it down easily.","C":"It is too heavy to carry.","D":"It melts in the rain."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break down plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q021","read_aloud":"How long does it take for plastic to biodegrade? A. A few days. B. One year. C. Hundreds or thousands of years. D. It happens instantly.","excerpt":"It can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade. And in some cases, it never does.","stem":"How long does it take for plastic to biodegrade?","choices":{"A":"A few days.","B":"One year.","C":"Hundreds or thousands of years.","D":"It happens instantly."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states it can take hundreds or thousands of years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade. And in some cases, it never does."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q022","read_aloud":"What happens first in making plastic bags? A. Pellets are melted. B. Film is cut into bags. C. Polyurethane is formed into pellets. D. The bags are sold.","excerpt":"To make plastic bags, polyurethane is formed into pellets. Then the pellets are melted into a thin film.","stem":"What happens first in making plastic bags?","choices":{"A":"Pellets are melted.","B":"Film is cut into bags.","C":"Polyurethane is formed into pellets.","D":"The bags are sold."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The process describes forming pellets first, then melting them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: To make plastic bags, polyurethane is formed into pellets. Then the pellets are melted into a thin film."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q023","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q024","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l03-q025","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They used plastic bags. B. They used cloth bags. C. They used paper boxes. D. They carried items by hand.","excerpt":"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","stem":"What should readers understand about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They used plastic bags.","B":"They used cloth bags.","C":"They used paper boxes.","D":"They carried items by hand."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed."}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q001","read_aloud":"In this text, what does \"marine life\" refer to? Options: A. plants on land, B. animals that live in the ocean, C. birds that fly, D. people who live on islands","excerpt":"\"Trash has a deadly effect on marine life. Plastic is the worst offender by far. Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean.\"","stem":"In this text, what does \"marine life\" refer to? Options:","choices":{"A":"plants on land,","B":"animals that live in the ocean,","C":"birds that fly,","D":"people who live on islands"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The passage discusses birds and fish getting sick from plastic in the ocean, which means marine life refers to creatures living in the sea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Trash has a deadly effect on marine life. Plastic is the worst offender by far. Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Why are leatherback sea turtles endangered? Options: A. they eat too much jellyfish, B. they mistake plastic bags for food, C. they cannot swim in deep water, D. there are no more eggs to lay","excerpt":"\"Many animals mistake larger pieces of plastic for food too. Leatherback sea turtles are one example. These turtles have been around for more than 100 million years, but today they are endangered...\"","stem":"Why are leatherback sea turtles endangered? Options:","choices":{"A":"they eat too much jellyfish,","B":"they mistake plastic bags for food,","C":"they cannot swim in deep water,","D":"there are no more eggs to lay"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains they are endangered partially because \"they mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many animals mistake larger pieces of plastic for food too. Leatherback sea turtles are one example. These turtles have been around for more than 100 million years, but today they are endangered...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q003","read_aloud":"What is the result of birds eating plastic pieces? Options: A. they get too heavy to fly, B. they become stronger, C. they stop eating real food and starve, D. they learn to eat other things","excerpt":"\"Sometimes the birds\u0027 stomachs fill up with plastic. This signals to the birds that they are full, so they stop eating real food. Then they starve.\"","stem":"What is the result of birds eating plastic pieces? Options:","choices":{"A":"they get too heavy to fly,","B":"they become stronger,","C":"they stop eating real food and starve,","D":"they learn to eat other things"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that the plastic makes birds feel full, so they \"stop eating real food\" and \"starve\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sometimes the birds\u0027 stomachs fill up with plastic. This signals to the birds that they are full, so they stop eating real food. Then they starve.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q004","read_aloud":"How does the weather change the amount of trash on the beach? Options: A. rain makes the trash go away forever, B. winter winds bring the trash back to shore, C. the sun burns the trash on the sand, D. the rainy season creates no new trash","excerpt":"\"During Bali\u0027s rainy season, much of the island\u0027s trash washes out to sea. Then, during the winter season... wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore.\"","stem":"How does the weather change the amount of trash on the beach? Options:","choices":{"A":"rain makes the trash go away forever,","B":"winter winds bring the trash back to shore,","C":"the sun burns the trash on the sand,","D":"the rainy season creates no new trash"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The passage explains the cycle where trash washes out and then is driven \"back to shore\" by winter winds and waves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"During Bali\u0027s rainy season, much of the island\u0027s trash washes out to sea. Then, during the winter season... wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q005","read_aloud":"Why do the people on Bali call the winter \"trash season\"? Options: A. it is when they throw out the most trash, B. the ocean brings lots of trash back to the beaches, C. it is the time they clean the streets, D. they like to collect trash during the winter","excerpt":"\"Because Bali is a tropical island, it\u0027s greatly affected by the tides and by seasonal weather patterns. ... That\u0027s why winter in Bali has come to be known as \u0027trash season.\u0027\"","stem":"Why do the people on Bali call the winter \"trash season\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"it is when they throw out the most trash,","B":"the ocean brings lots of trash back to the beaches,","C":"it is the time they clean the streets,","D":"they like to collect trash during the winter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It is called \"trash season\" because that is when the winter weather and currents \"drive the trash back to shore\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because Bali is a tropical island, it\u0027s greatly affected by the tides and by seasonal weather patterns. ... That\u0027s why winter in Bali has come to be known as \u0027trash season.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"toxic\" mean? A. helpful and healthy B. poisonous C. colorful D. expensive","excerpt":"\"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\"","stem":"What does \"toxic\" mean?","choices":{"A":"helpful and healthy","B":"poisonous","C":"colorful","D":"expensive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines toxic as \"poisonous.\" Toxic chemicals like dioxins are harmful and can make people and animals sick.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q007","read_aloud":"Why is dropping plastic on the ground now a problem? A. Because plastic does not break down like banana leaves did. B. Because plastic is too heavy to pick up. C. Because the ground is too hard. D. Because people don\u0027t like the color of plastic.","excerpt":"\"The Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground. When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down and mixes with the soil. A dropped plastic container won\u0027t.\"","stem":"Why is dropping plastic on the ground now a problem?","choices":{"A":"Because plastic does not break down like banana leaves did.","B":"Because plastic is too heavy to pick up.","C":"Because the ground is too hard.","D":"Because people don\u0027t like the color of plastic."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that banana leaves \"soon break down and mix with the soil,\" but \"a dropped plastic container won\u0027t.\" This old habit is now a problem because plastic stays in the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground. When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down and mixes with the soil. A dropped plastic container won\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Tourists create a large amount of plastic waste in Bali. B. Bali has no tourists. C. Tourists only visit in winter. D. Tourists help clean up the beaches.","excerpt":"\"Tourists are a third reason for the trash problem-a huge reason. More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year. They account for a large percentage of the hundreds of tons of plastic waste the island produces each day.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Tourists create a large amount of plastic waste in Bali.","B":"Bali has no tourists.","C":"Tourists only visit in winter.","D":"Tourists help clean up the beaches."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The first sentence states that tourists are \"a third reason for the trash problem-a huge reason.\" The details about 3 million tourists and hundreds of tons of waste support this main idea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tourists are a third reason for the trash problem-a huge reason. More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year. They account for a large percentage of the hundreds of tons of plastic waste the island produces each day.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q009","read_aloud":"If tourists felt more responsibility, what might change? A. They might throw away more trash. B. They might take better care of the island and produce less waste. C. They might stop visiting completely. D. They might bring more plastic bags.","excerpt":"\"Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean.\"","stem":"If tourists felt more responsibility, what might change?","choices":{"A":"They might throw away more trash.","B":"They might take better care of the island and produce less waste.","C":"They might stop visiting completely.","D":"They might bring more plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says tourists feel \"no responsibility\" now. If they felt more responsible, they would likely take better care of Bali and not leave so much trash behind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q010","read_aloud":"Why can\u0027t Bali\u0027s trash services keep up? A. Because there is too much garbage being produced. B. Because the services are closed on weekends. C. Because people don\u0027t want to work. D. Because the trucks are too new.","excerpt":"\"75 percent of rubbish isn\u0027t picked up by any trash service. Bali\u0027s refuse collection and disposal services simply can\u0027t keep up with all the garbage.\"","stem":"Why can\u0027t Bali\u0027s trash services keep up?","choices":{"A":"Because there is too much garbage being produced.","B":"Because the services are closed on weekends.","C":"Because people don\u0027t want to work.","D":"Because the trucks are too new."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the services \"can\u0027t keep up with all the garbage produced by residents and tourists.\" This means there is simply too much trash for the services to handle.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"75 percent of rubbish isn\u0027t picked up by any trash service. Bali\u0027s refuse collection and disposal services simply can\u0027t keep up with all the garbage.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"toxic\" most likely mean here? A. poisonous or harmful to living things B. helpful and healthy for plants C. colorful and bright looking D. expensive and hard to find","excerpt":"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.","stem":"What does \"toxic\" most likely mean here?","choices":{"A":"poisonous or harmful to living things","B":"helpful and healthy for plants","C":"colorful and bright looking","D":"expensive and hard to find"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Toxic means poisonous. The text says these chemicals can contaminate land and water, which is harmful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q012","read_aloud":"What can happen when toxins get into the environment? A. they can cause illnesses in animals and people B. they can make flowers grow faster C. they can clean the ocean water D. they can help fish swim better","excerpt":"These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.","stem":"What can happen when toxins get into the environment?","choices":{"A":"they can cause illnesses in animals and people","B":"they can make flowers grow faster","C":"they can clean the ocean water","D":"they can help fish swim better"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text links toxins to serious health problems for both wildlife and humans.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q013","read_aloud":"How are banana leaves and plastic containers different? A. banana leaves break down; plastic does not B. banana leaves are heavy; plastic is light C. banana leaves cost money; plastic is free D. banana leaves are colorful; plastic is plain","excerpt":"A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down and mixes with the soil. A dropped plastic container won\u0027t.","stem":"How are banana leaves and plastic containers different?","choices":{"A":"banana leaves break down; plastic does not","B":"banana leaves are heavy; plastic is light","C":"banana leaves cost money; plastic is free","D":"banana leaves are colorful; plastic is plain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text contrasts how banana leaves decompose naturally while plastic does not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down and mixes with the soil. A dropped plastic container won\u0027t."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q014","read_aloud":"If you owned a hotel in Bali, what would be a better choice than burning plastic? A. find a proper waste disposal service B. throw trash in the ocean C. bury plastic in the beach sand D. leave trash on the roadside","excerpt":"Many Bali businesses, such as hotels and restaurants, burn litter, including plastics, in public places.","stem":"If you owned a hotel in Bali, what would be a better choice than burning plastic?","choices":{"A":"find a proper waste disposal service","B":"throw trash in the ocean","C":"bury plastic in the beach sand","D":"leave trash on the roadside"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This asks students to apply knowledge that burning plastic is harmful, so proper disposal would be better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many Bali businesses, such as hotels and restaurants, burn litter, including plastics, in public places."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q015","read_aloud":"How does burning trash connect to a bigger global problem? A. it adds carbon dioxide that may cause climate change B. it makes the air smell like flowers C. it helps plants grow taller and stronger D. it cools down the Earth\u0027s temperature","excerpt":"Burning waste also releases carbon dioxide into the air. Studies link high levels of carbon dioxide to climate change.","stem":"How does burning trash connect to a bigger global problem?","choices":{"A":"it adds carbon dioxide that may cause climate change","B":"it makes the air smell like flowers","C":"it helps plants grow taller and stronger","D":"it cools down the Earth\u0027s temperature"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students analyze the connection between burning waste, carbon dioxide, and climate change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Burning waste also releases carbon dioxide into the air. Studies link high levels of carbon dioxide to climate change."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What does toxic mean in this sentence? A. harmless B. poisonous C. helpful D. natural","excerpt":"\"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\"","stem":"What does toxic mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"harmless","B":"poisonous","C":"helpful","D":"natural"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"toxic poisonous.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q017","read_aloud":"What is one effect of burning plastic? A. It makes the air cleaner. B. It releases toxic chemicals that cause illness. C. It creates more plastic. D. It helps plants grow.","excerpt":"\"Plastic products are made of polyethylene, a type of gas. Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air … These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.\"","stem":"What is one effect of burning plastic?","choices":{"A":"It makes the air cleaner.","B":"It releases toxic chemicals that cause illness.","C":"It creates more plastic.","D":"It helps plants grow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states burning plastic releases toxins linked to illnesses.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic products are made of polyethylene, a type of gas. Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air … These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q018","read_aloud":"How is Bali\u0027s waste management problem similar to that of many other places? A. Bali is the only place with waste problems. B. Many places around the world also lack good waste management systems. C. Other places have perfect waste management. D. Bali has the best waste management.","excerpt":"\"For the most part, the Balinese-like many other people around the world-have not developed adequate systems for waste management. Instead, they hide or eliminate trash in any way they can.\"","stem":"How is Bali\u0027s waste management problem similar to that of many other places?","choices":{"A":"Bali is the only place with waste problems.","B":"Many places around the world also lack good waste management systems.","C":"Other places have perfect waste management.","D":"Bali has the best waste management."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"like many other people around the world.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For the most part, the Balinese-like many other people around the world-have not developed adequate systems for waste management. Instead, they hide or eliminate trash in any way they can.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q019","read_aloud":"How does plastic in the ocean affect people who eat seafood? A. It makes seafood taste better. B. People can get sick from eating fish that have eaten plastic. C. It has no effect on people. D. It makes the fish grow larger.","excerpt":"\"If people eat the fish that consume the plastic, they can get sick too.\"","stem":"How does plastic in the ocean affect people who eat seafood?","choices":{"A":"It makes seafood taste better.","B":"People can get sick from eating fish that have eaten plastic.","C":"It has no effect on people.","D":"It makes the fish grow larger."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that people can get sick from eating fish that have consumed plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If people eat the fish that consume the plastic, they can get sick too.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for disposable? A. Throwaway B. Reusable C. Single-use D. Plastic","excerpt":"It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for disposable?","choices":{"A":"Throwaway","B":"Reusable","C":"Single-use","D":"Plastic"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Disposable\" means designed to be thrown away, so \"reusable\" is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q021","read_aloud":"Why does trash pile up quickly in Bali? A. The island is very large. B. The island is small. C. There are no roads. D. People do not eat food.","excerpt":"One reason is that Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware.","stem":"Why does trash pile up quickly in Bali?","choices":{"A":"The island is very large.","B":"The island is small.","C":"There are no roads.","D":"People do not eat food."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that because Bali is a small island, trash can pile up quickly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One reason is that Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q022","read_aloud":"Compare a banana leaf and a plastic container. A. Both break down quickly. B. The leaf breaks down; the plastic does not. C. The plastic breaks down; the leaf does not. D. Both last forever.","excerpt":"When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down... A dropped plastic container won\u0027t.","stem":"Compare a banana leaf and a plastic container.","choices":{"A":"Both break down quickly.","B":"The leaf breaks down; the plastic does not.","C":"The plastic breaks down; the leaf does not.","D":"Both last forever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts the banana leaf, which breaks down, with plastic, which does not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down... A dropped plastic container won\u0027t."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q023","read_aloud":"Why do Balinese people drop trash on the ground? A. They want to hurt the island. B. They are used to doing this with natural items. C. There are no trash cans. D. The government told them to do it.","excerpt":"Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground.","stem":"Why do Balinese people drop trash on the ground?","choices":{"A":"They want to hurt the island.","B":"They are used to doing this with natural items.","C":"There are no trash cans.","D":"The government told them to do it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it is a longstanding habit from when they used banana leaves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How do tourists affect the trash problem? A. They clean the beaches every day. B. They bring trash cans with them. C. They add a lot of trash and do not clean up. D. They stop coming to the island.","excerpt":"Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean.","stem":"How do tourists affect the trash problem?","choices":{"A":"They clean the beaches every day.","B":"They bring trash cans with them.","C":"They add a lot of trash and do not clean up.","D":"They stop coming to the island."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says tourists produce tons of waste and often dispose of it thoughtlessly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l04-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"phenomenon\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. a human-made machine, B. an event that can be observed, C. a type of dangerous trash, D. a broken rule","excerpt":"\"The Balinese government was slow to address the island\u0027s trash problem. It was also seemingly slow to understand the causes. Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027\"","stem":"What does \"phenomenon\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"a human-made machine,","B":"an event that can be observed,","C":"a type of dangerous trash,","D":"a broken rule"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A phenomenon is an occurrence or event that people can study or observe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Balinese government was slow to address the island\u0027s trash problem. It was also seemingly slow to understand the causes. Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q002","read_aloud":"Why is the trash problem bad for Bali\u0027s economy? Options: A. tourists don\u0027t want to visit dirty beaches, B. the government spends all its money on cleaning, C. hotels are too expensive to build, D. surfers are using too much plastic","excerpt":"\"No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy.\"","stem":"Why is the trash problem bad for Bali\u0027s economy? Options:","choices":{"A":"tourists don\u0027t want to visit dirty beaches,","B":"the government spends all its money on cleaning,","C":"hotels are too expensive to build,","D":"surfers are using too much plastic"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that people do not want to visit \"trash-infested\" places, which lowers tourism.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q003","read_aloud":"How does the trash problem affect people who fish? Options: A. they catch more fish than before, B. they have to buy new boats, C. they cannot sell or eat the fish they catch, D. they have to fish in different oceans","excerpt":"\"Those who fish-whether to feed their families or to make a living-suffer from the trash problem too. Anyone aware of the effects of plastic on fish will hesitate to eat seafood from the waters surrounding Bali.\"","stem":"How does the trash problem affect people who fish? Options:","choices":{"A":"they catch more fish than before,","B":"they have to buy new boats,","C":"they cannot sell or eat the fish they catch,","D":"they have to fish in different oceans"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"People hesitate to eat the fish because of the plastic, and the trash also tangles nets and damages boat parts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Those who fish-whether to feed their families or to make a living-suffer from the trash problem too. Anyone aware of the effects of plastic on fish will hesitate to eat seafood from the waters surrounding Bali.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q004","read_aloud":"Why did the governor\u0027s explanation for the trash problem fail to solve the issue? Options: A. he didn\u0027t look at the source of the trash, B. he didn\u0027t know how to swim, C. he told people to stop visiting Bali, D. he made the trash increase","excerpt":"\"The Balinese government was slow to address the island\u0027s trash problem... [The governor] blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.\"","stem":"Why did the governor\u0027s explanation for the trash problem fail to solve the issue? Options:","choices":{"A":"he didn\u0027t look at the source of the trash,","B":"he didn\u0027t know how to swim,","C":"he told people to stop visiting Bali,","D":"he made the trash increase"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"By only blaming the tides, the governor ignored that humans were creating the trash in the first place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Balinese government was slow to address the island\u0027s trash problem... [The governor] blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why is it important for people to understand their role in creating the trash? Options: A. so they can blame the tourists, B. to stop the government from taxing them, C. to realize they need to change their habits, D. to prove that trash is a natural phenomenon","excerpt":"\"To bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem. And they had to understand their role in creating it.\"","stem":"Based on the text, why is it important for people to understand their role in creating the trash? Options:","choices":{"A":"so they can blame the tourists,","B":"to stop the government from taxing them,","C":"to realize they need to change their habits,","D":"to prove that trash is a natural phenomenon"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Change only happens when people realize their own actions contribute to the problem and decide to act differently.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem. And they had to understand their role in creating it.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"phenomenon\" mean? A. something that can be studied or observed; an event B. a type of plastic bag C. a person who cleans beaches D. a kind of ocean animal","excerpt":"\"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again.\"","stem":"What does \"phenomenon\" mean?","choices":{"A":"something that can be studied or observed; an event","B":"a type of plastic bag","C":"a person who cleans beaches","D":"a kind of ocean animal"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines phenomenon as \"something that can be studied or observed; event.\" The governor called the trash cycle a natural event, though the text suggests he was not addressing the real cause.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q007","read_aloud":"How are burning trash and dumping trash similar? A. Both are safe ways to get rid of garbage. B. Both are harmful ways that people use to eliminate trash. C. Both help the environment. D. Both are approved by the government.","excerpt":"\"Many Bali businesses, such as hotels and restaurants, burn litter, including plastics, in public places... Other businesses and individuals in Bali simply dump trash in rivers or on the side of the road.\"","stem":"How are burning trash and dumping trash similar?","choices":{"A":"Both are safe ways to get rid of garbage.","B":"Both are harmful ways that people use to eliminate trash.","C":"Both help the environment.","D":"Both are approved by the government."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says burning trash releases toxic chemicals, and dumping trash in rivers pollutes water. Both are unsafe, harmful ways people try to get rid of garbage because there are no good options.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many Bali businesses, such as hotels and restaurants, burn litter, including plastics, in public places... Other businesses and individuals in Bali simply dump trash in rivers or on the side of the road.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q008","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use in this excerpt? A. problem and solution B. cause and effect C. compare and contrast D. description","excerpt":"\"Trash has a deadly effect on marine life. Plastic is the worst offender by far. Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean... When birds or fish consume these plastic bits, they can get sick and die.\"","stem":"What text structure does the author use in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"problem and solution","B":"cause and effect","C":"compare and contrast","D":"description"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author explains that plastic in the ocean (cause) leads to birds and fish getting sick and dying (effect). This is a cause and effect structure showing what happens when animals eat plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Trash has a deadly effect on marine life. Plastic is the worst offender by far. Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean... When birds or fish consume these plastic bits, they can get sick and die.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q009","read_aloud":"If you lived near where trash was burned, why should you be worried? A. Because the smoke might smell good. B. Because the toxic chemicals could cause serious illnesses. C. Because the fire might be too small. D. Because the trash might be valuable.","excerpt":"\"These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.\"","stem":"If you lived near where trash was burned, why should you be worried?","choices":{"A":"Because the smoke might smell good.","B":"Because the toxic chemicals could cause serious illnesses.","C":"Because the fire might be too small.","D":"Because the trash might be valuable."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says toxins from burning plastic are linked to \"cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders.\" People living nearby could get sick from breathing these poisonous chemicals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare trash to Olympic swimming pools? A. To show that the amount of trash is enormous and hard to imagine. B. To tell people to go swimming. C. To explain how to build a swimming pool. D. To say that trash is good for swimming.","excerpt":"\"R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympic-size swimming pools.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare trash to Olympic swimming pools?","choices":{"A":"To show that the amount of trash is enormous and hard to imagine.","B":"To tell people to go swimming.","C":"To explain how to build a swimming pool.","D":"To say that trash is good for swimming."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author uses the swimming pool comparison to help readers understand just how much 530,000 cubic feet of trash really is. Most people have seen a swimming pool, so this makes the huge amount easier to picture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympic-size swimming pools.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"phenomenon\" mean in this context? A. something that can be observed or studied B. a type of plastic bag C. a famous tourist attraction D. a traditional Balinese dance","excerpt":"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027","stem":"What does \"phenomenon\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"something that can be observed or studied","B":"a type of plastic bag","C":"a famous tourist attraction","D":"a traditional Balinese dance"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Phenomenon means an observable event. The governor was describing the trash issue as something observable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main point of these sentences? A. Bali produces a huge amount of trash every day B. Olympic pools are very large C. Roadways are good places for trash D. Swimming pools need cleaning often","excerpt":"R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympic-size swimming pools.","stem":"What is the main point of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"Bali produces a huge amount of trash every day","B":"Olympic pools are very large","C":"Roadways are good places for trash","D":"Swimming pools need cleaning often"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The comparison to six Olympic pools emphasizes the massive daily trash amount in Bali.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympic-size swimming pools."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about burying trash in beach sand? A. it doesn\u0027t solve the trash problem; it moves it to the ocean B. it is the best way to handle waste on beaches C. it makes the beach look cleaner forever D. it helps sea animals find food more easily","excerpt":"Beachside hotels often bury trash under the sand. Soon the tide comes up and washes the trash into the ocean.","stem":"What can you infer about burying trash in beach sand?","choices":{"A":"it doesn\u0027t solve the trash problem; it moves it to the ocean","B":"it is the best way to handle waste on beaches","C":"it makes the beach look cleaner forever","D":"it helps sea animals find food more easily"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students infer that burying trash just moves the problem to the ocean when tides come in.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Beachside hotels often bury trash under the sand. Soon the tide comes up and washes the trash into the ocean."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q014","read_aloud":"If you found small plastic pieces on a beach, what might you conclude? A. they came from larger plastic items that broke apart B. they grew naturally from the sand C. they were always that small size D. they will disappear in a few days","excerpt":"Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean. Sunlight and waves break some plastic items into smaller and smaller pieces, but they never disappear entirely.","stem":"If you found small plastic pieces on a beach, what might you conclude?","choices":{"A":"they came from larger plastic items that broke apart","B":"they grew naturally from the sand","C":"they were always that small size","D":"they will disappear in a few days"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students apply the text\u0027s information that plastic breaks into smaller pieces but doesn\u0027t disappear.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean. Sunlight and waves break some plastic items into smaller and smaller pieces, but they never disappear entirely."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q015","read_aloud":"How does plastic in the ocean affect different living things? A. it can harm birds, fish, and even people through the food chain B. it only affects birds that fly over the ocean C. it helps fish grow bigger and stronger D. it has no effect on people who live on land","excerpt":"When birds or fish consume these plastic bits, they can get sick and die. If people eat the fish that consume the plastic, they can get sick too.","stem":"How does plastic in the ocean affect different living things?","choices":{"A":"it can harm birds, fish, and even people through the food chain","B":"it only affects birds that fly over the ocean","C":"it helps fish grow bigger and stronger","D":"it has no effect on people who live on land"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students analyze how plastic moves through the food chain affecting multiple species including humans.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When birds or fish consume these plastic bits, they can get sick and die. If people eat the fish that consume the plastic, they can get sick too."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What does phenomenon mean in this sentence? A. a strange monster B. something that can be studied or observed; an event C. a type of plastic D. a kind of fish","excerpt":"\"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangkau Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again.\"","stem":"What does phenomenon mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a strange monster","B":"something that can be studied or observed; an event","C":"a type of plastic","D":"a kind of fish"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"phenomenon something that can be studied or observed; event.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangkau Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Melati and Isabel from their actions? A. They are lazy and do nothing. B. They are determined, creative, and hardworking. C. They are afraid of plastic. D. They want more plastic bags.","excerpt":"\"The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. … They created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness. They spoke at markets and festivals. They held beach cleanup events.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Melati and Isabel from their actions?","choices":{"A":"They are lazy and do nothing.","B":"They are determined, creative, and hardworking.","C":"They are afraid of plastic.","D":"They want more plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"They took many active steps to solve the problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. … They created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness. They spoke at markets and festivals. They held beach cleanup events.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q018","read_aloud":"What effect did the Wijsensisters\u0027 campaign have beyond Bali? A. It only affected Bali. B. It spread to other Indonesian cities, which started eliminating plastic bags or charging fees. C. It made plastic bags more popular. D. It had no effect.","excerpt":"\"Melati and Isabel\u0027s project spread from Bali to other parts of Indonesia. Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags. In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store.\"","stem":"What effect did the Wijsensisters\u0027 campaign have beyond Bali?","choices":{"A":"It only affected Bali.","B":"It spread to other Indonesian cities, which started eliminating plastic bags or charging fees.","C":"It made plastic bags more popular.","D":"It had no effect."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The campaign spread and led to changes in other cities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Melati and Isabel\u0027s project spread from Bali to other parts of Indonesia. Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags. In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Melati tells others who want to make a difference. Do you think young people can make a difference like Melati and Isabel? Why? A. No, because only adults can change laws. B. Yes, because they started a successful campaign and inspired others even though they were young. C. No, because young people have no ideas. D. Yes, but only if they are rich.","excerpt":"Don\u0027t ever let anyone tell you that you\u0027re too young,","stem":"Melati tells others who want to make a difference. Do you think young people can make a difference like Melati and Isabel? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because only adults can change laws.","B":"Yes, because they started a successful campaign and inspired others even though they were young.","C":"No, because young people have no ideas.","D":"Yes, but only if they are rich."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Melati and Isabel proved that young people can create change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Don\u0027t ever let anyone tell you that you\u0027re too young,"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q020","read_aloud":"What does toxic mean? A. Safe to breathe B. Good for plants C. Poisonous D. Clean","excerpt":"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.","stem":"What does toxic mean?","choices":{"A":"Safe to breathe","B":"Good for plants","C":"Poisonous","D":"Clean"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text definition says toxic means poisonous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q021","read_aloud":"What is the problem with trash services in Bali? A. They pick up too much trash. B. They cannot keep up with the garbage. C. They are too expensive. D. They work too fast.","excerpt":"75 percent of rubbish isn\u0027t picked up by any trash service. Bali\u0027s refuse collection and disposal services simply can\u0027t keep up...","stem":"What is the problem with trash services in Bali?","choices":{"A":"They pick up too much trash.","B":"They cannot keep up with the garbage.","C":"They are too expensive.","D":"They work too fast."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the services \"simply can\u0027t keep up with all the garbage.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: 75 percent of rubbish isn\u0027t picked up by any trash service. Bali\u0027s refuse collection and disposal services simply can\u0027t keep up..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q022","read_aloud":"What is a result of burning plastic? A. It cleans the air. B. It makes the air safe. C. It causes illnesses. D. It helps plants grow.","excerpt":"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air... These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders...","stem":"What is a result of burning plastic?","choices":{"A":"It cleans the air.","B":"It makes the air safe.","C":"It causes illnesses.","D":"It helps plants grow."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text links the toxins from burning plastic to cancer and breathing disorders.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air... These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q023","read_aloud":"Why do people dump trash illegally? A. They want to save money on fees. B. They think it is good for the fish. C. They have nowhere else to put it. D. The rivers are made of trash.","excerpt":"Other businesses and individuals in Bali simply dump trash in rivers or on the side of the road.","stem":"Why do people dump trash illegally?","choices":{"A":"They want to save money on fees.","B":"They think it is good for the fish.","C":"They have nowhere else to put it.","D":"The rivers are made of trash."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that people don\u0027t want to pay the fees for legal dumping.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Other businesses and individuals in Bali simply dump trash in rivers or on the side of the road."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How do hotels add to the ocean trash? A. They throw trash into the ocean directly. B. They bury it, and the tide washes it away. C. They burn the trash on the beach. D. They recycle all their trash.","excerpt":"Beachside hotels often bury trash under the sand. Soon the tide comes up and washes the trash into the ocean.","stem":"How do hotels add to the ocean trash?","choices":{"A":"They throw trash into the ocean directly.","B":"They bury it, and the tide washes it away.","C":"They burn the trash on the beach.","D":"They recycle all their trash."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that hotels bury trash, but the tide washes it into the ocean.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Beachside hotels often bury trash under the sand. Soon the tide comes up and washes the trash into the ocean."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l05-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"appalled\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. very happy, B. shocked and disgusted, C. confused and lost, D. excited to play","excerpt":"\"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They were appalled by the plastic waste piling up and washing up around them.\"","stem":"What does \"appalled\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"very happy,","B":"shocked and disgusted,","C":"confused and lost,","D":"excited to play"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sisters were \"appalled\" because they saw the terrible amount of waste around them and wanted to fix it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They were appalled by the plastic waste piling up and washing up around them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q002","read_aloud":"Why did the sisters choose to focus on plastic bags? Options: A. they were easy to collect, B. they were deadly and unnecessary, C. the governor told them to, D. they were the only kind of trash","excerpt":"\"At first they weren\u0027t sure how to tackle such an enormous issue. Then the girls decided to focus on one crucial part of the problem: plastic bags. In Melati and Isabel\u0027s view, the bags were not only deadly but also entirely unnecessary.\"","stem":"Why did the sisters choose to focus on plastic bags? Options:","choices":{"A":"they were easy to collect,","B":"they were deadly and unnecessary,","C":"the governor told them to,","D":"they were the only kind of trash"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text specifically notes that the girls viewed the bags as \"deadly\" and \"entirely unnecessary\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At first they weren\u0027t sure how to tackle such an enormous issue. Then the girls decided to focus on one crucial part of the problem: plastic bags. In Melati and Isabel\u0027s view, the bags were not only deadly but also entirely unnecessary.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q003","read_aloud":"What is one way the sisters raised awareness about their project? Options: A. they wrote books, B. they made educational presentations, C. they made new laws, D. they burned trash safely","excerpt":"\"They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them. Then they created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness. They spoke at markets and festivals.\"","stem":"What is one way the sisters raised awareness about their project? Options:","choices":{"A":"they wrote books,","B":"they made educational presentations,","C":"they made new laws,","D":"they burned trash safely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The passage states they \"developed educational presentations\" to inform others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them. Then they created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness. They spoke at markets and festivals.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q004","read_aloud":"Why did the sisters meet with people like the head of the United Nations? Options: A. to learn how to organize and spread their message, B. to ask for money to buy more bags, C. to go on vacation to London, D. to learn how to swim better","excerpt":"\"The sisters talked to the head of the United Nations and to Jane Goodall, who gave advice about how to grow a network of followers and activists.\"","stem":"Why did the sisters meet with people like the head of the United Nations? Options:","choices":{"A":"to learn how to organize and spread their message,","B":"to ask for money to buy more bags,","C":"to go on vacation to London,","D":"to learn how to swim better"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Jane Goodall specifically gave them advice on how to build a network of followers to support their cause.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sisters talked to the head of the United Nations and to Jane Goodall, who gave advice about how to grow a network of followers and activists.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q005","read_aloud":"How did charging a fee for plastic bags affect shoppers? Options: A. they started buying more plastic bags, B. they stopped shopping at stores, C. they brought their own cloth or recycled bags, D. they stopped paying for food","excerpt":"\"Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags. In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective...\"","stem":"How did charging a fee for plastic bags affect shoppers? Options:","choices":{"A":"they started buying more plastic bags,","B":"they stopped shopping at stores,","C":"they brought their own cloth or recycled bags,","D":"they stopped paying for food"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that this \"policy has proved very effective\" in getting people to bring their own bags.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags. In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective...\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q006","read_aloud":"Which word is the opposite of \"marred\"? A. damaged B. ugly C. beautiful or unharmed D. dirty","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.\"","stem":"Which word is the opposite of \"marred\"?","choices":{"A":"damaged","B":"ugly","C":"beautiful or unharmed","D":"dirty"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Marred means \"damaged; made ugly.\" The opposite would be something that is beautiful or not harmed. The first version of Bali in the text was a paradise, which is the opposite of marred.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q007","read_aloud":"Why are plastic bags especially dangerous for sea turtles? A. Because turtles like to play with them. B. Because turtles mistake them for food and suffocate. C. Because plastic bags are too small to see. D. Because turtles are allergic to the color of plastic bags.","excerpt":"\"Leatherback sea turtles have been around for more than 100 million years, but today they are endangered, partially because they mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food.\"","stem":"Why are plastic bags especially dangerous for sea turtles?","choices":{"A":"Because turtles like to play with them.","B":"Because turtles mistake them for food and suffocate.","C":"Because plastic bags are too small to see.","D":"Because turtles are allergic to the color of plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says turtles \"mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food.\" When they try to swallow the bags, they suffocate. This is why plastic bags are so dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Leatherback sea turtles have been around for more than 100 million years, but today they are endangered, partially because they mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this detail about mother birds? A. To show that birds are bad parents. B. To show how plastic harms animals in heartbreaking ways. C. To tell a funny story about birds. D. To explain how birds build nests.","excerpt":"\"Mother birds even mistakenly feed plastic pieces to their babies. Sometimes the birds\u0027 stomachs fill up with plastic. This signals to the birds that they are full, so they stop eating real food. Then they starve.\"","stem":"Why does the author include this detail about mother birds?","choices":{"A":"To show that birds are bad parents.","B":"To show how plastic harms animals in heartbreaking ways.","C":"To tell a funny story about birds.","D":"To explain how birds build nests."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author describes mother birds feeding plastic to their babies to show the sad and serious effects of plastic pollution. This detail helps readers understand why plastic in the ocean is so dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mother birds even mistakenly feed plastic pieces to their babies. Sometimes the birds\u0027 stomachs fill up with plastic. This signals to the birds that they are full, so they stop eating real food. Then they starve.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q009","read_aloud":"Why has winter in Bali become known as \"trash season\"? A. Because it snows trash in Bali. B. Because trash that washed out to sea returns to shore during winter. C. Because people only throw trash away in winter. D. Because winter is when tourists visit.","excerpt":"\"During Bali\u0027s rainy season, much of the island\u0027s trash washes out to sea. Then, during the winter season, from December to February or March, wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore.\"","stem":"Why has winter in Bali become known as \"trash season\"?","choices":{"A":"Because it snows trash in Bali.","B":"Because trash that washed out to sea returns to shore during winter.","C":"Because people only throw trash away in winter.","D":"Because winter is when tourists visit."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that during the rainy season, trash washes out to sea. Then in winter, \"wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore.\" This cycle makes winter \"trash season\" because the beaches become covered in garbage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"During Bali\u0027s rainy season, much of the island\u0027s trash washes out to sea. Then, during the winter season, from December to February or March, wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q010","read_aloud":"What is the problem the author describes here? A. Trash hurts tourism, but tourism also helps Bali\u0027s economy. B. Tourists love swimming in trash. C. Bali has too few tourists. D. The beaches have no trash at all.","excerpt":"\"No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy.\"","stem":"What is the problem the author describes here?","choices":{"A":"Trash hurts tourism, but tourism also helps Bali\u0027s economy.","B":"Tourists love swimming in trash.","C":"Bali has too few tourists.","D":"The beaches have no trash at all."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author explains a difficult situation: trash keeps tourists away, but tourists bring money that supports businesses. Less tourism would mean less trash but also less money for the island. This is a tricky problem with no easy answer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q011","read_aloud":"How does the word \"marred\" help you understand the author\u0027s message about Bali? A. it shows trash has damaged Bali\u0027s beauty B. it suggests Bali has always been dirty C. it means tourists enjoy the trash piles D. it shows trash makes Bali more popular","excerpt":"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.","stem":"How does the word \"marred\" help you understand the author\u0027s message about Bali?","choices":{"A":"it shows trash has damaged Bali\u0027s beauty","B":"it suggests Bali has always been dirty","C":"it means tourists enjoy the trash piles","D":"it shows trash makes Bali more popular"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Marred\" emphasizes that trash has damaged or ruined Bali\u0027s natural beauty.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What is the correct order of what happens to ocean trash? A. trash enters ocean → floats away → may reach garbage patch → some washes back to shore B. trash disappears → becomes food for fish → helps coral grow → cleans the water C. trash sinks to bottom → turns into sand → becomes part of beach → disappears D. trash is eaten by whales → becomes whale food → helps whales grow → saves the ocean","excerpt":"Much of the trash eventually washes back onto the shore. Some of it will float far from the island, perhaps ending up in the Indian Ocean Garbage Patch in the North Pacific Ocean.","stem":"What is the correct order of what happens to ocean trash?","choices":{"A":"trash enters ocean → floats away → may reach garbage patch → some washes back to shore","B":"trash disappears → becomes food for fish → helps coral grow → cleans the water","C":"trash sinks to bottom → turns into sand → becomes part of beach → disappears","D":"trash is eaten by whales → becomes whale food → helps whales grow → saves the ocean"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes the sequence: trash enters ocean, floats, may reach garbage patches, and some returns to shore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Much of the trash eventually washes back onto the shore. Some of it will float far from the island, perhaps ending up in the Indian Ocean Garbage Patch in the North Pacific Ocean."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q013","read_aloud":"What is the effect of plastic bags on ocean life? A. they can trap animals and harm coral B. they provide homes for small fish C. they help coral grow faster and stronger D. they make the ocean water cleaner","excerpt":"Plastic bags also wrap around these sea animals so they can\u0027t swim. Bags even suffocate the beautiful living coral on the floor of the Indian Ocean.","stem":"What is the effect of plastic bags on ocean life?","choices":{"A":"they can trap animals and harm coral","B":"they provide homes for small fish","C":"they help coral grow faster and stronger","D":"they make the ocean water cleaner"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes how plastic bags physically harm sea animals and coral by trapping and suffocating them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Plastic bags also wrap around these sea animals so they can\u0027t swim. Bags even suffocate the beautiful living coral on the floor of the Indian Ocean."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q014","read_aloud":"Do you think the governor\u0027s approach of not blaming any one group is effective? Why or why not? A. yes, because change requires everyone to be aware and work together B. no, because only tourists should be responsible for the trash C. yes, because trash is not really a serious problem D. no, because hotels should pay for all cleanup","excerpt":"Understandably, he didn\u0027t want to point the finger of blame at tourists, or hotels, or restaurants, or any one group. However, to bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem.","stem":"Do you think the governor\u0027s approach of not blaming any one group is effective? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because change requires everyone to be aware and work together","B":"no, because only tourists should be responsible for the trash","C":"yes, because trash is not really a serious problem","D":"no, because hotels should pay for all cleanup"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text suggests that awareness and collective action from everyone is needed for change, supporting option a.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Understandably, he didn\u0027t want to point the finger of blame at tourists, or hotels, or restaurants, or any one group. However, to bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q015","read_aloud":"What relationship does this excerpt show between tourism and Bali\u0027s environment? A. tourism helps the economy but can increase environmental problems B. tourism has no effect on either the economy or environment C. tourism only helps the environment and hurts the economy D. tourism solves all of Bali\u0027s trash problems","excerpt":"A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy. Much of Bali\u0027s economy is based on tourist dollars.","stem":"What relationship does this excerpt show between tourism and Bali\u0027s environment?","choices":{"A":"tourism helps the economy but can increase environmental problems","B":"tourism has no effect on either the economy or environment","C":"tourism only helps the environment and hurts the economy","D":"tourism solves all of Bali\u0027s trash problems"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students analyze the complex relationship: tourism brings money but also contributes to waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy. Much of Bali\u0027s economy is based on tourist dollars."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for marred? A. beautified B. damaged C. cleaned D. hidden","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides. It floats in the aqua ocean and washes up on the whitesand beaches.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for marred?","choices":{"A":"beautified","B":"damaged","C":"cleaned","D":"hidden"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means damaged or made ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides. It floats in the aqua ocean and washes up on the whitesand beaches.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q017","read_aloud":"Why did plastic become popular so quickly around the world? A. Because it is expensive. B. Because it is durable, lightweight, and waterproof. C. Because it biodegrades quickly. D. Because it is made of banana leaves.","excerpt":"\"The same thing was happening all around the world, of course, including the United States. Plastic, in particular, proved hard to resist. It\u0027s durable, lightweight, and waterproof.\"","stem":"Why did plastic become popular so quickly around the world?","choices":{"A":"Because it is expensive.","B":"Because it is durable, lightweight, and waterproof.","C":"Because it biodegrades quickly.","D":"Because it is made of banana leaves."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists those attractive qualities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The same thing was happening all around the world, of course, including the United States. Plastic, in particular, proved hard to resist. It\u0027s durable, lightweight, and waterproof.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q018","read_aloud":"Why did Melati and Isabel take action? A. Because the government asked them to. B. Because the government was not solving the problem, so they felt they had to. C. Because they wanted to be famous. D. Because they were paid to do it.","excerpt":"\"Because the government wasn\u0027t doing anything, it was up to individuals to take action. In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island.\"","stem":"Why did Melati and Isabel take action?","choices":{"A":"Because the government asked them to.","B":"Because the government was not solving the problem, so they felt they had to.","C":"Because they wanted to be famous.","D":"Because they were paid to do it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The government\u0027s inaction led them to act.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because the government wasn\u0027t doing anything, it was up to individuals to take action. In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Why was getting the governor\u0027s support important? A. He could pass laws and enforce changes. B. He could ignore the problem. C. He was against the campaign. D. He could make more plastic bags.","excerpt":"\"Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plasticbag free by 2018.\"","stem":"Why was getting the governor\u0027s support important?","choices":{"A":"He could pass laws and enforce changes.","B":"He could ignore the problem.","C":"He was against the campaign.","D":"He could make more plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Government support can lead to official policies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plasticbag free by 2018.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses toxic correctly? A. The toxic water was safe to drink. B. The toxic waste made the river dangerous. C. The toxic candy tasted very sweet. D. The toxic air smelled like flowers.","excerpt":"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air...","stem":"Which sentence uses toxic correctly?","choices":{"A":"The toxic water was safe to drink.","B":"The toxic waste made the river dangerous.","C":"The toxic candy tasted very sweet.","D":"The toxic air smelled like flowers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Toxic\" means poisonous or dangerous, so toxic waste makes the river dangerous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q021","read_aloud":"How does trash get into the ocean according to this paragraph? A. Only tourists throw it there. B. Tides wash buried trash, and rivers carry trash. C. Fish bring the trash to the ocean. D. Helicopters drop the trash.","excerpt":"Beachside hotels often bury trash under the sand. Soon the tide comes up and washes the trash into the ocean. River trash often heads out to sea too.","stem":"How does trash get into the ocean according to this paragraph?","choices":{"A":"Only tourists throw it there.","B":"Tides wash buried trash, and rivers carry trash.","C":"Fish bring the trash to the ocean.","D":"Helicopters drop the trash."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains two ways: tides wash buried trash, and river trash flows out to sea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Beachside hotels often bury trash under the sand. Soon the tide comes up and washes the trash into the ocean. River trash often heads out to sea too."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What happens to plastic in the ocean? A. It turns into food for fish. B. It dissolves into water. C. It breaks into smaller pieces but stays plastic. D. It sinks to the bottom and vanishes.","excerpt":"Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean. Sunlight and waves break some plastic items into smaller and smaller pieces, but they never disappear entirely.","stem":"What happens to plastic in the ocean?","choices":{"A":"It turns into food for fish.","B":"It dissolves into water.","C":"It breaks into smaller pieces but stays plastic.","D":"It sinks to the bottom and vanishes."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says plastic breaks into smaller pieces but never disappears entirely.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean. Sunlight and waves break some plastic items into smaller and smaller pieces, but they never disappear entirely."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q023","read_aloud":"Why do turtles suffocate? A. They are allergic to plastic. B. They think plastic bags are jellyfish and eat them. C. The water is too cold. D. They cannot swim fast enough.","excerpt":"Leatherback sea turtles... mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food. When they try to swallow a plastic bag, they suffocate.","stem":"Why do turtles suffocate?","choices":{"A":"They are allergic to plastic.","B":"They think plastic bags are jellyfish and eat them.","C":"The water is too cold.","D":"They cannot swim fast enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The turtles mistake plastic bags for food, swallow them, and suffocate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Leatherback sea turtles... mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food. When they try to swallow a plastic bag, they suffocate."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does plastic cause birds to starve? A. The plastic tastes bad. B. The plastic fills their stomachs so they do not eat real food. C. The plastic wraps around their wings. D. The plastic makes them too heavy to fly.","excerpt":"Sometimes the birds\u0027 stomachs fill up with plastic. This signals to the birds that they are full, so they stop eating real food. Then they starve.","stem":"How does plastic cause birds to starve?","choices":{"A":"The plastic tastes bad.","B":"The plastic fills their stomachs so they do not eat real food.","C":"The plastic wraps around their wings.","D":"The plastic makes them too heavy to fly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the plastic makes birds feel full, so they stop eating and starve.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sometimes the birds\u0027 stomachs fill up with plastic. This signals to the birds that they are full, so they stop eating real food. Then they starve."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l06-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"alternatives\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. different choices, B. more trash, C. better machines, D. expensive items","excerpt":"\"The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags and other plastic products.\"","stem":"What does \"alternatives\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"different choices,","B":"more trash,","C":"better machines,","D":"expensive items"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Alternatives are other choices or options you can use instead of the original items.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags and other plastic products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q002","read_aloud":"Which groups are helping to clean up the beaches? Options: A. the government only, B. only children, C. surfers and companies that sell surfing gear, D. tourists who visit for one day","excerpt":"\"Many other individuals and organizations are now taking action too. For example, groups of surfers and companies that sell surfing equipment have organized regular beach-cleanup days on Bali.\"","stem":"Which groups are helping to clean up the beaches? Options:","choices":{"A":"the government only,","B":"only children,","C":"surfers and companies that sell surfing gear,","D":"tourists who visit for one day"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text specifically mentions that groups of surfers and surfing equipment companies are organizing cleanup days.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many other individuals and organizations are now taking action too. For example, groups of surfers and companies that sell surfing equipment have organized regular beach-cleanup days on Bali.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What is the goal of the organization Bali Fokus? Options: A. to stop surfing, B. to free Bali from plastic, C. to increase the number of tourists, D. to sell more plastic bags","excerpt":"\"Other organizations, such as the nonprofit group Bali Fokus, are sharing the message \u0027Free Bali from plastic.\u0027 They\u0027re encouraging both residents and tourists to find alternatives to waste products.\"","stem":"What is the goal of the organization Bali Fokus? Options:","choices":{"A":"to stop surfing,","B":"to free Bali from plastic,","C":"to increase the number of tourists,","D":"to sell more plastic bags"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Their message, \"Free Bali from plastic,\" explains their goal of reducing plastic waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Other organizations, such as the nonprofit group Bali Fokus, are sharing the message \u0027Free Bali from plastic.\u0027 They\u0027re encouraging both residents and tourists to find alternatives to waste products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author say Bali\u0027s future depends on \"cooperation\"? Options: A. one person can fix the whole island by themselves, B. everyone-residents and visitors-must work together, C. the government will force people to clean, D. the weather will eventually fix the problem","excerpt":"\"Bali\u0027s future depends on the work of these individuals and groups. It also depends on the cooperation of Bali\u0027s residents and its visitors.\"","stem":"Why does the author say Bali\u0027s future depends on \"cooperation\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"one person can fix the whole island by themselves,","B":"everyone-residents and visitors-must work together,","C":"the government will force people to clean,","D":"the weather will eventually fix the problem"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Cooperation means working together, and the text says the future depends on both residents and visitors working together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali\u0027s future depends on the work of these individuals and groups. It also depends on the cooperation of Bali\u0027s residents and its visitors.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q005","read_aloud":"How can tourists help make Bali cleaner? Options: A. by bringing more plastic bottles, B. by throwing trash in the ocean, C. by staying in hotels that have water dispensers, D. by ignoring the trash problem","excerpt":"\"Environmentalists now urge tourists to plan ahead to make their visit as eco-friendly as possible. ... [they] should also check to see whether hotels have dispensers for boiled water, which is safe to drink.\"","stem":"How can tourists help make Bali cleaner? Options:","choices":{"A":"by bringing more plastic bottles,","B":"by throwing trash in the ocean,","C":"by staying in hotels that have water dispensers,","D":"by ignoring the trash problem"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Using water dispensers allows tourists to \"avoid buying bottle after bottle of water,\" which reduces plastic waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Environmentalists now urge tourists to plan ahead to make their visit as eco-friendly as possible. ... [they] should also check to see whether hotels have dispensers for boiled water, which is safe to drink.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q006","read_aloud":"If something is \"toxic,\" why should you avoid touching or breathing it? A. Because it is poisonous and can make you sick. B. Because it is very expensive. C. Because it is too soft. D. Because it changes colors.","excerpt":"\"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air.\"","stem":"If something is \"toxic,\" why should you avoid touching or breathing it?","choices":{"A":"Because it is poisonous and can make you sick.","B":"Because it is very expensive.","C":"Because it is too soft.","D":"Because it changes colors."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines toxic as \"poisonous.\" Toxic chemicals like dioxins can cause illnesses such as cancer and breathing disorders, so you should avoid them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q007","read_aloud":"What does \"appalled\" mean, and why were the sisters appalled? A. They were happy about the trash. B. They were shocked and upset by all the plastic waste. C. They were bored with the beach. D. They were excited to buy more plastic.","excerpt":"\"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They were appalled by the plastic waste piling up and washing up around them.\"","stem":"What does \"appalled\" mean, and why were the sisters appalled?","choices":{"A":"They were happy about the trash.","B":"They were shocked and upset by all the plastic waste.","C":"They were bored with the beach.","D":"They were excited to buy more plastic."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Appalled\" means shocked and upset. The sisters were appalled because they saw plastic waste \"piling up and washing up around them\" on their island. This made them want to take action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They were appalled by the plastic waste piling up and washing up around them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Which detail shows that the sisters worked with others? A. They worked alone and told no one. B. They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them. C. They only talked to adults. D. They moved to another country.","excerpt":"\"The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them. Then they created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness.\"","stem":"Which detail shows that the sisters worked with others?","choices":{"A":"They worked alone and told no one.","B":"They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them.","C":"They only talked to adults.","D":"They moved to another country."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the sisters \"found a group of like-minded kids to work with them.\" This shows they did not work alone-they built a team of other kids who cared about the same problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them. Then they created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q009","read_aloud":"Why does Melati think education is important? A. Because educated people can understand problems and make better choices. B. Because education is required by law. C. Because schools need more students. D. Because education makes plastic disappear.","excerpt":"\"Melati noted, \u0027Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Melati think education is important?","choices":{"A":"Because educated people can understand problems and make better choices.","B":"Because education is required by law.","C":"Because schools need more students.","D":"Because education makes plastic disappear."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Melati believes that if people understand the problem, they can make changes. Education helps people learn about pollution and waste, so they can make better choices to protect the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Melati noted, \u0027Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q010","read_aloud":"Why did the governor sign a pledge to ban plastic bags? A. Because Melati and Isabel convinced him that plastic bags were a serious problem. B. Because he wanted more plastic bags on the island. C. Because plastic bags are good for the ocean. D. Because tourists demanded more plastic bags.","excerpt":"\"He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018. In 2016, officials at Bali\u0027s airport started making sure that tourists weren\u0027t bringing plastic bags to the island.\"","stem":"Why did the governor sign a pledge to ban plastic bags?","choices":{"A":"Because Melati and Isabel convinced him that plastic bags were a serious problem.","B":"Because he wanted more plastic bags on the island.","C":"Because plastic bags are good for the ocean.","D":"Because tourists demanded more plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the sisters \"got the governor of Bali on their side\" after talking to important people and raising awareness. The governor signed the pledge because the sisters showed him how harmful plastic bags were.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018. In 2016, officials at Bali\u0027s airport started making sure that tourists weren\u0027t bringing plastic bags to the island.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q011","read_aloud":"Why might \"disposable\" products be a problem for an island like Bali? A. they are used once and thrown away, creating ongoing waste B. they are too expensive for most people to buy C. they break down too quickly in the environment D. they are only available in certain stores","excerpt":"It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products. Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles.","stem":"Why might \"disposable\" products be a problem for an island like Bali?","choices":{"A":"they are used once and thrown away, creating ongoing waste","B":"they are too expensive for most people to buy","C":"they break down too quickly in the environment","D":"they are only available in certain stores"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Disposable items create continuous waste because they\u0027re used once then discarded, which is problematic on a small island.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products. Soon everyone was drinking from plastic bottles."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q012","read_aloud":"What can you infer about plastic pollution from this information? A. plastic pollution is a global ocean problem, not just Bali\u0027s B. plastic only pollutes the Indian Ocean C. ocean garbage patches are mostly made of natural materials D. plastic pollution is decreasing in Earth\u0027s oceans","excerpt":"The patch is one of five spread across Earth\u0027s oceans. About 90 percent of it is plastic.","stem":"What can you infer about plastic pollution from this information?","choices":{"A":"plastic pollution is a global ocean problem, not just Bali\u0027s","B":"plastic only pollutes the Indian Ocean","C":"ocean garbage patches are mostly made of natural materials","D":"plastic pollution is decreasing in Earth\u0027s oceans"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Five garbage patches across Earth\u0027s oceans, mostly plastic, shows this is a worldwide issue.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The patch is one of five spread across Earth\u0027s oceans. About 90 percent of it is plastic."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q013","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s purpose in ending with this sentence? A. to encourage readers to take action, no matter how small B. to tell readers that only big changes matter C. to suggest that nothing can be done about trash D. to convince readers to avoid visiting Bali","excerpt":"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.","stem":"What is the author\u0027s purpose in ending with this sentence?","choices":{"A":"to encourage readers to take action, no matter how small","B":"to tell readers that only big changes matter","C":"to suggest that nothing can be done about trash","D":"to convince readers to avoid visiting Bali"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author emphasizes that both small and large actions can help, encouraging reader participation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q014","read_aloud":"Was it fair that young girls had to lead the effort to reduce plastic waste? Support your answer. A. no, but their actions show that anyone can make a difference regardless of age B. yes, because adults don\u0027t care about the environment C. no, because children should focus only on school D. yes, because the government asked them to lead","excerpt":"Because the government wasn\u0027t doing anything, it was up to individuals to take action. In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island.","stem":"Was it fair that young girls had to lead the effort to reduce plastic waste? Support your answer.","choices":{"A":"no, but their actions show that anyone can make a difference regardless of age","B":"yes, because adults don\u0027t care about the environment","C":"no, because children should focus only on school","D":"yes, because the government asked them to lead"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"While ideally adults/government should lead, the text shows young people can drive change when needed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Because the government wasn\u0027t doing anything, it was up to individuals to take action. In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q015","read_aloud":"How did the Wijsen sisters use multiple strategies to address the plastic bag problem? A. they combined education, community events, and direct action to raise awareness B. they only focused on talking to government officials C. they waited for adults to solve the problem for them D. they only cleaned beaches without educating others","excerpt":"They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them. Then they created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness. They spoke at markets and festivals. They held beach cleanup events.","stem":"How did the Wijsen sisters use multiple strategies to address the plastic bag problem?","choices":{"A":"they combined education, community events, and direct action to raise awareness","B":"they only focused on talking to government officials","C":"they waited for adults to solve the problem for them","D":"they only cleaned beaches without educating others"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students analyze how the sisters used various approaches: petitions, presentations, speeches, and cleanups.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them. Then they created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness. They spoke at markets and festivals. They held beach cleanup events."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q016","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of toxic? A. poisonous B. harmless C. dangerous D. deadly","excerpt":"\"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym of toxic?","choices":{"A":"poisonous","B":"harmless","C":"dangerous","D":"deadly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Toxic means poisonous; harmless is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q017","read_aloud":"How is the Bali of the past different from Bali today? A. The past had more plastic. B. The past had little trash and used natural materials; today has a huge trash problem. C. Both are the same. D. The past had more tourists.","excerpt":"\"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags … banana leaves, coconut shells … Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.\"","stem":"How is the Bali of the past different from Bali today?","choices":{"A":"The past had more plastic.","B":"The past had little trash and used natural materials; today has a huge trash problem.","C":"Both are the same.","D":"The past had more tourists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The past was clean; today is polluted.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags … banana leaves, coconut shells … Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about burning trash as a global practice? A. It is a rare practice. B. It is a common practice (40% of world\u0027s waste). C. It is completely safe. D. It is only done in Bali.","excerpt":"\"Many Bali businesses, such as hotels and restaurants, burn litter, including plastics, in public places. Bali isn\u0027t unique in this practice; experts estimate that 40 percent of the world\u0027s waste is eliminated through burning.\"","stem":"What can you infer about burning trash as a global practice?","choices":{"A":"It is a rare practice.","B":"It is a common practice (40% of world\u0027s waste).","C":"It is completely safe.","D":"It is only done in Bali."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"40% is a large percentage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many Bali businesses, such as hotels and restaurants, burn litter, including plastics, in public places. Bali isn\u0027t unique in this practice; experts estimate that 40 percent of the world\u0027s waste is eliminated through burning.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Does this statistic help you understand the size of the problem? Why? A. No, because it is confusing. B. Yes, because comparing trash to swimming pools makes it easier to picture. C. No, because numbers are not important. D. Yes, but only for scientists.","excerpt":"\"R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympicsize swimming pools.\"","stem":"Does this statistic help you understand the size of the problem? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because it is confusing.","B":"Yes, because comparing trash to swimming pools makes it easier to picture.","C":"No, because numbers are not important.","D":"Yes, but only for scientists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparisons help readers visualize large amounts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"R.O.L.E. reports that every 24 hours, the Balinese dispose of almost 530,000 cubic feet of trash along roadways and at illegal dump sites. That\u0027s enough waste to fill six Olympicsize swimming pools.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Write one sentence explaining why an educational book for elementary students is a good idea. A. \"Elementary students are too young to learn about pollution.\" B. \"Teaching young children about waste can create lifelong good habits and spread awareness to families.\" C. \"Books are oldfashioned and useless.\" D. \"Only adults should learn about pollution.\"","excerpt":"\"The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags.\"","stem":"Write one sentence explaining why an educational book for elementary students is a good idea.","choices":{"A":"\"Elementary students are too young to learn about pollution.\"","B":"\"Teaching young children about waste can create lifelong good habits and spread awareness to families.\"","C":"\"Books are oldfashioned and useless.\"","D":"\"Only adults should learn about pollution.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Early education can lead to lasting change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q021","read_aloud":"Which item is made from crude oil? A. A wooden chair B. A glass bottle C. A plastic bag D. A paper plate","excerpt":"Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground.","stem":"Which item is made from crude oil?","choices":{"A":"A wooden chair","B":"A glass bottle","C":"A plastic bag","D":"A paper plate"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that chemicals from crude oil are used to make plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q022","read_aloud":"What brings the trash back to the shore in winter? A. The rain B. The tourists C. The wind and currents D. The fishing boats","excerpt":"During Bali\u0027s rainy season, much of the island\u0027s trash washes out to sea. Then, during the winter season... wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore.","stem":"What brings the trash back to the shore in winter?","choices":{"A":"The rain","B":"The tourists","C":"The wind and currents","D":"The fishing boats"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: During Bali\u0027s rainy season, much of the island\u0027s trash washes out to sea. Then, during the winter season... wind, waves, and strong currents drive the trash back to shore."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q023","read_aloud":"What is the effect of trash on tourism? A. More people want to visit. B. Tourists stop coming to the beaches. C. Tourists bring more money. D. People swim in the trash.","excerpt":"No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy.","stem":"What is the effect of trash on tourism?","choices":{"A":"More people want to visit.","B":"Tourists stop coming to the beaches.","C":"Tourists bring more money.","D":"People swim in the trash."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says no one wants to swim or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q024","read_aloud":"Why might people stop eating seafood in Bali? A. The fish are too expensive. B. The fish are dangerous due to plastic. C. The restaurants are closed. D. The fish taste like bananas.","excerpt":"Anyone aware of the effects of plastic on fish will hesitate to eat seafood from the waters surrounding Bali.","stem":"Why might people stop eating seafood in Bali?","choices":{"A":"The fish are too expensive.","B":"The fish are dangerous due to plastic.","C":"The restaurants are closed.","D":"The fish taste like bananas."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"People hesitate to eat seafood because they know plastic affects the fish.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Anyone aware of the effects of plastic on fish will hesitate to eat seafood from the waters surrounding Bali."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does plastic affect fishermen? A. It helps them catch more fish. B. It breaks their equipment. C. It makes the boats go faster. D. It cleans the ocean.","excerpt":"Plastic gets tangled in fishing nets. It also damages boat propellers and other equipment.","stem":"How does plastic affect fishermen?","choices":{"A":"It helps them catch more fish.","B":"It breaks their equipment.","C":"It makes the boats go faster.","D":"It cleans the ocean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions plastic damages propellers and other equipment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Plastic gets tangled in fishing nets. It also damages boat propellers and other equipment."}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"like-minded\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. children who are all the same age, B. people who think the same way, C. people who like to travel, D. kids who have never met","excerpt":"\"The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them.\"","stem":"What does \"like-minded\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"children who are all the same age,","B":"people who think the same way,","C":"people who like to travel,","D":"kids who have never met"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being like-minded means sharing the same ideas or goals about a topic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. They found a group of like-minded kids to work with them.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q002","read_aloud":"How did the sisters\u0027 video help them reach more people? Options: A. it got them a job in a store, B. it led to a speaking opportunity in London, C. it made them move away from Bali, D. it taught them how to make plastic","excerpt":"\"The nonprofit organization TED (which stands for Technology, Entertainment, and Design) saw the video. They contacted the girls and asked them to give a talk in London.\"","stem":"How did the sisters\u0027 video help them reach more people? Options:","choices":{"A":"it got them a job in a store,","B":"it led to a speaking opportunity in London,","C":"it made them move away from Bali,","D":"it taught them how to make plastic"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The TED organization saw the video and asked the girls to come to London to talk about it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The nonprofit organization TED (which stands for Technology, Entertainment, and Design) saw the video. They contacted the girls and asked them to give a talk in London.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q003","read_aloud":"What action did airport officials take to help reduce plastic? Options: A. they started selling plastic bags, B. they searched luggage for plastic bags, C. they made tourists pay a fee for air travel, D. they closed the airport","excerpt":"\"In 2016, officials at Bali\u0027s airport started making sure that tourists weren\u0027t bringing plastic bags to the island.\"","stem":"What action did airport officials take to help reduce plastic? Options:","choices":{"A":"they started selling plastic bags,","B":"they searched luggage for plastic bags,","C":"they made tourists pay a fee for air travel,","D":"they closed the airport"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they started \"making sure that tourists weren\u0027t bringing plastic bags to the island,\" which implies they checked what tourists were bringing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 2016, officials at Bali\u0027s airport started making sure that tourists weren\u0027t bringing plastic bags to the island.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Why does Melati believe education is necessary for change? Options: A. it is the only way to get money, B. people need to know about the problem before they will fix it, C. schools require students to learn about trash, D. it makes people stay inside their houses","excerpt":"\"Melati noted, \u0027Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Melati believe education is necessary for change? Options:","choices":{"A":"it is the only way to get money,","B":"people need to know about the problem before they will fix it,","C":"schools require students to learn about trash,","D":"it makes people stay inside their houses"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If people are not aware or educated about why something is harmful, they are unlikely to make the effort to change their behavior.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Melati noted, \u0027Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q005","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s main message in this final paragraph? Options: A. only big changes like new buildings matter, B. refusing a straw is too small to help, C. every action, big or small, helps create a better environment, D. it is too late to save the island","excerpt":"\"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s main message in this final paragraph? Options:","choices":{"A":"only big changes like new buildings matter,","B":"refusing a straw is too small to help,","C":"every action, big or small, helps create a better environment,","D":"it is too late to save the island"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author emphasizes that all efforts, \"small or large,\" contribute to making the island cleaner.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q006","read_aloud":"Why is calling trash a \"natural phenomenon\" not the best description? A. Because the trash comes from human choices, not nature. B. Because rain and tides are not real. C. Because trash is good for the environment. D. Because the governor was a scientist.","excerpt":"\"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again.\"","stem":"Why is calling trash a \"natural phenomenon\" not the best description?","choices":{"A":"Because the trash comes from human choices, not nature.","B":"Because rain and tides are not real.","C":"Because trash is good for the environment.","D":"Because the governor was a scientist."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the governor \"didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.\" Trash is caused by people using plastic and throwing it away, not by nature. Calling it \"natural\" ignores that humans created the problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why does the author start with \"Close your eyes and imagine\"? A. To help readers picture Bali as a beautiful paradise before explaining the trash problem. B. To tell readers to go to sleep. C. To describe a movie. D. To list facts about weather.","excerpt":"\"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder.\"","stem":"Why does the author start with \"Close your eyes and imagine\"?","choices":{"A":"To help readers picture Bali as a beautiful paradise before explaining the trash problem.","B":"To tell readers to go to sleep.","C":"To describe a movie.","D":"To list facts about weather."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author wants readers to imagine beautiful Bali first. This helps readers feel the loss when they later read about the trash problem. It makes the problem more real and emotional.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Close your eyes and imagine yourself on the tropical island of Bali, in Indonesia. Picture blue skies and palm trees. Think of white sand that runs through your fingers like powder.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Is charging a fee for plastic bags a good idea? Use text evidence. A. No, because people should get free plastic bags. B. Yes, because it has proved very effective at reducing plastic bag use. C. No, because cloth bags are too expensive. D. Yes, because stores make more money.","excerpt":"\"In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective in getting people to bring their own cloth or recycled bags when they shop.\"","stem":"Is charging a fee for plastic bags a good idea? Use text evidence.","choices":{"A":"No, because people should get free plastic bags.","B":"Yes, because it has proved very effective at reducing plastic bag use.","C":"No, because cloth bags are too expensive.","D":"Yes, because stores make more money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says this policy \"has proved very effective in getting people to bring their own cloth or recycled bags.\" This means fewer plastic bags are used, which helps the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective in getting people to bring their own cloth or recycled bags when they shop.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think the author\u0027s advice to tourists is helpful? Why or why not? A. No, because tourists should buy more plastic bottles. B. Yes, because it gives tourists ways to reduce plastic waste while staying safe. C. No, because tourists should not visit Bali at all. D. Yes, because hotels should be free.","excerpt":"\"Tourists should check to make sure their hotel follows proper waste-management procedures... they should also check to see whether hotels have dispensers for boiled water, which is safe to drink. That way they can avoid buying bottle after bottle of water.\"","stem":"Do you think the author\u0027s advice to tourists is helpful? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because tourists should buy more plastic bottles.","B":"Yes, because it gives tourists ways to reduce plastic waste while staying safe.","C":"No, because tourists should not visit Bali at all.","D":"Yes, because hotels should be free."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author suggests tourists choose hotels with good waste management and water dispensers. This helps tourists avoid buying many plastic bottles, which reduces waste while keeping tourists healthy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tourists should check to make sure their hotel follows proper waste-management procedures... they should also check to see whether hotels have dispensers for boiled water, which is safe to drink. That way they can avoid buying bottle after bottle of water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the author mention both small choices and large changes? A. To show that everyone can help, no matter what they are able to do. B. To say that small choices don\u0027t matter. C. To prove that only governments can fix the problem. D. To list things that are too hard to do.","excerpt":"\"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\"","stem":"Why does the author mention both small choices and large changes?","choices":{"A":"To show that everyone can help, no matter what they are able to do.","B":"To say that small choices don\u0027t matter.","C":"To prove that only governments can fix the problem.","D":"To list things that are too hard to do."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author includes both \"refusing a plastic drinking straw\" (small) and \"building a new waste-treatment facility\" (large) to show that every person and every action counts. Big or small, everyone can help make Bali cleaner.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q011","read_aloud":"Why might calling trash buildup a \"natural phenomenon\" be problematic? A. it suggests the problem is natural rather than human-caused, which may prevent solutions B. it accurately describes how trash naturally appears on beaches C. it helps tourists understand why beaches are dirty D. it encourages people to produce more trash","excerpt":"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.","stem":"Why might calling trash buildup a \"natural phenomenon\" be problematic?","choices":{"A":"it suggests the problem is natural rather than human-caused, which may prevent solutions","B":"it accurately describes how trash naturally appears on beaches","C":"it helps tourists understand why beaches are dirty","D":"it encourages people to produce more trash"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Calling human-created trash a \"natural phenomenon\" may mislead people about the real cause and delay action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q012","read_aloud":"How strong is the evidence that burning plastic is harmful? A. strong, because specific serious illnesses are linked to the toxins B. weak, because no illnesses are mentioned C. strong, because it only affects wildlife, not people D. weak, because the toxins are harmless","excerpt":"These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people.","stem":"How strong is the evidence that burning plastic is harmful?","choices":{"A":"strong, because specific serious illnesses are linked to the toxins","B":"weak, because no illnesses are mentioned","C":"strong, because it only affects wildlife, not people","D":"weak, because the toxins are harmless"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text provides strong evidence by naming specific serious health problems linked to the toxins.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: These toxins are linked to illnesses such as cancer, birth defects, and breathing disorders in both wildlife and people."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Why might charging for plastic bags be an effective solution? A. it creates a financial reason for people to change their behavior B. it makes plastic bags more popular and widely used C. it forces stores to give away free bags instead D. it has no effect on how people shop","excerpt":"In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective in getting people to bring their own cloth or recycled bags when they shop.","stem":"Why might charging for plastic bags be an effective solution?","choices":{"A":"it creates a financial reason for people to change their behavior","B":"it makes plastic bags more popular and widely used","C":"it forces stores to give away free bags instead","D":"it has no effect on how people shop"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students evaluate that a fee creates motivation for behavior change, which the text confirms is effective.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective in getting people to bring their own cloth or recycled bags when they shop."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q014","read_aloud":"- Melati WijsenDo you agree with Melati\u0027s statement? Use evidence from the text to support your opinion. A. yes, because education led to awareness and action that reduced plastic bag use in Bali B. no, because education has no effect on people\u0027s choices C. yes, because only children need to learn about the environment D. no, because laws alone can solve problems without education","excerpt":"Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.","stem":"- Melati WijsenDo you agree with Melati\u0027s statement? Use evidence from the text to support your opinion.","choices":{"A":"yes, because education led to awareness and action that reduced plastic bag use in Bali","B":"no, because education has no effect on people\u0027s choices","C":"yes, because only children need to learn about the environment","D":"no, because laws alone can solve problems without education"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows education through the sisters\u0027 presentations helped create change, supporting the quote.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q015","read_aloud":"If you could create one new rule for tourists visiting Bali, what would it be and why? A. require tourists to bring reusable bags and water bottles to reduce single-use plastic waste B. ban all tourists from visiting Bali\u0027s beaches C. require tourists to pay extra fees for everything they buy D. allow tourists to bring any amount of plastic they want","excerpt":"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place.","stem":"If you could create one new rule for tourists visiting Bali, what would it be and why?","choices":{"A":"require tourists to bring reusable bags and water bottles to reduce single-use plastic waste","B":"ban all tourists from visiting Bali\u0027s beaches","C":"require tourists to pay extra fees for everything they buy","D":"allow tourists to bring any amount of plastic they want"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This creative question asks students to apply the text\u0027s message that individual choices matter, with option a being a practical, text-supported solution.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author use sensory details (sight, smell) in this description? A. To make the problem feel real and vivid to the reader. B. To make the story longer. C. To confuse the reader. D. To sell souvenirs.","excerpt":"\"Waste is piled high on roadsides. It floats in the aqua ocean and washes up on the whitesand beaches. The smell of garbage replaces the scent of flowers.\"","stem":"Why does the author use sensory details (sight, smell) in this description?","choices":{"A":"To make the problem feel real and vivid to the reader.","B":"To make the story longer.","C":"To confuse the reader.","D":"To sell souvenirs."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Sensory details help the reader imagine the scene.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Waste is piled high on roadsides. It floats in the aqua ocean and washes up on the whitesand beaches. The smell of garbage replaces the scent of flowers.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q017","read_aloud":"What does this text show about solving environmental problems? A. Only governments can solve them. B. Individuals, groups, and governments all have roles to play. C. Problems cannot be solved. D. Only tourists can solve problems.","excerpt":"The text describes the causes of the trash problem (small island, habits, tourists, poor waste management) and then the solutions (Wijsensisters, beach cleanups, bans).","stem":"What does this text show about solving environmental problems?","choices":{"A":"Only governments can solve them.","B":"Individuals, groups, and governments all have roles to play.","C":"Problems cannot be solved.","D":"Only tourists can solve problems."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Multiple groups took action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text describes the causes of the trash problem (small island, habits, tourists, poor waste management) and then the solutions (Wijsensisters, beach cleanups, bans)."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Was the Wijsensisters\u0027 campaign successful? Why? A. No, because Bali still has trash. B. Yes, because it spread to other cities and led to plastic bag fees and bans. C. No, because nothing changed. D. Yes, because they became famous.","excerpt":"\"Melati and Isabel\u0027s project spread from Bali to other parts of Indonesia. Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags.\"","stem":"Was the Wijsensisters\u0027 campaign successful? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because Bali still has trash.","B":"Yes, because it spread to other cities and led to plastic bag fees and bans.","C":"No, because nothing changed.","D":"Yes, because they became famous."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The campaign led to measurable changes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Melati and Isabel\u0027s project spread from Bali to other parts of Indonesia. Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Write one sentence suggesting a small change a tourist could make to help Bali. A. \"Tourists should throw trash on the beach.\" B. \"Tourists should bring their own reusable water bottle and refuse plastic straws.\" C. \"Tourists should buy more plastic souvenirs.\" D. \"Tourists should ignore the trash.\"","excerpt":"\"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new wastetreatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place.\"","stem":"Write one sentence suggesting a small change a tourist could make to help Bali.","choices":{"A":"\"Tourists should throw trash on the beach.\"","B":"\"Tourists should bring their own reusable water bottle and refuse plastic straws.\"","C":"\"Tourists should buy more plastic souvenirs.\"","D":"\"Tourists should ignore the trash.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Small individual actions add up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new wastetreatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q020","read_aloud":"What is a phenomenon? A. Something that is planned by people B. Something that is studied or observed C. Something that is very small D. Something that is dangerous to touch","excerpt":"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \"natural phenomenon.\"","stem":"What is a phenomenon?","choices":{"A":"Something that is planned by people","B":"Something that is studied or observed","C":"Something that is very small","D":"Something that is dangerous to touch"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The definition in the text says a phenomenon is something that can be studied or observed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \"natural phenomenon.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What did the governor fail to address? A. The movement of the tides. B. The amount of rain falling. C. The source of the trash. D. The size of the island.","excerpt":"He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.","stem":"What did the governor fail to address?","choices":{"A":"The movement of the tides.","B":"The amount of rain falling.","C":"The source of the trash.","D":"The size of the island."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text notes he didn\u0027t address where the trash came from.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q022","read_aloud":"What was necessary for change to happen? A. The government needed more money. B. The tourists needed to leave. C. Everyone needed to understand their role. D. The rains needed to stop.","excerpt":"However, to bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem. And they had to understand their role in creating it.","stem":"What was necessary for change to happen?","choices":{"A":"The government needed more money.","B":"The tourists needed to leave.","C":"Everyone needed to understand their role.","D":"The rains needed to stop."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says everyone had to understand their role in creating the problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: However, to bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem. And they had to understand their role in creating it."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q023","read_aloud":"Do you think the governor was right to avoid blaming groups? A. Yes, because blaming might stop people from helping. B. No, because the tourists are the only problem. C. Yes, because the trash is not a real problem. D. No, because the rains are the main cause.","excerpt":"Understandably, he didn\u0027t want to point the finger of blame at tourists, or hotels, or restaurants, or any one group.","stem":"Do you think the governor was right to avoid blaming groups?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because blaming might stop people from helping.","B":"No, because the tourists are the only problem.","C":"Yes, because the trash is not a real problem.","D":"No, because the rains are the main cause."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Blaming groups can make them angry or unwilling to help solve the problem together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Understandably, he didn\u0027t want to point the finger of blame at tourists, or hotels, or restaurants, or any one group."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q024","read_aloud":"Why did individuals have to take action? A. The government refused to do anything. B. The government was too slow to act. C. The individuals were paid to do it. D. The tourists asked them to help.","excerpt":"Because the government wasn\u0027t doing anything, it was up to individuals to take action.","stem":"Why did individuals have to take action?","choices":{"A":"The government refused to do anything.","B":"The government was too slow to act.","C":"The individuals were paid to do it.","D":"The tourists asked them to help."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text implies the government was slow, so individuals stepped up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Because the government wasn\u0027t doing anything, it was up to individuals to take action."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l08-q025","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What is \"environmental degradation\"? Options: A. the process of improving nature, B. the damage or worsening of the natural environment, C. the study of weather patterns, D. a type of island holiday","excerpt":"\"Bali\u0027s trash crisis has sparked a wave of activism that has inspired people far beyond the island\u0027s shores. It has become a global case study for how a community can confront environmental degradation.\"","stem":"What is \"environmental degradation\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"the process of improving nature,","B":"the damage or worsening of the natural environment,","C":"the study of weather patterns,","D":"a type of island holiday"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Degradation refers to the act of lowering the quality or condition of something, in this case, the environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali\u0027s trash crisis has sparked a wave of activism that has inspired people far beyond the island\u0027s shores. It has become a global case study for how a community can confront environmental degradation.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q002","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when they say youth-led initiatives \"can influence government policy\"? Options: A. young people can force governments to change rules, B. governments ignore what young people think, C. young people only care about laws, D. governments make laws to stop young people","excerpt":"\"The success of \u0027Bye Bye Plastic Bags\u0027 demonstrates that youth-led initiatives can influence government policy. By pressuring local leaders, the students helped change laws regarding plastic bag distribution.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when they say youth-led initiatives \"can influence government policy\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"young people can force governments to change rules,","B":"governments ignore what young people think,","C":"young people only care about laws,","D":"governments make laws to stop young people"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The success of the sisters shows that when young people take action and pressure leaders, they can actually change how policies are made.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The success of \u0027Bye Bye Plastic Bags\u0027 demonstrates that youth-led initiatives can influence government policy. By pressuring local leaders, the students helped change laws regarding plastic bag distribution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q003","read_aloud":"According to the text, why are laws not enough to fix the trash problem? Options: A. the laws are too strict, B. the laws are too expensive, C. not everyone follows or enforces them, D. there are no stores in Bali","excerpt":"\"Even with new laws, the challenge remains to enforce them. Some stores still provide bags, and some citizens continue to discard trash illegally, showing that laws alone are not enough.\"","stem":"According to the text, why are laws not enough to fix the trash problem? Options:","choices":{"A":"the laws are too strict,","B":"the laws are too expensive,","C":"not everyone follows or enforces them,","D":"there are no stores in Bali"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author notes that despite new laws, some people continue to break them and stores still give out bags, proving that compliance is also necessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even with new laws, the challenge remains to enforce them. Some stores still provide bags, and some citizens continue to discard trash illegally, showing that laws alone are not enough.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main argument of the \"critics\" mentioned in the text? Options: A. plastic bags are perfectly fine, B. Bali should only focus on food waste, C. focusing only on bags ignores the bigger problem of total waste, D. children should not be involved in environmental issues","excerpt":"\"Critics sometimes argue that focusing on plastic bags is too narrow. They suggest that the broader issue of total waste management-including food waste and dangerous chemicals-needs more attention.\"","stem":"What is the main argument of the \"critics\" mentioned in the text? Options:","choices":{"A":"plastic bags are perfectly fine,","B":"Bali should only focus on food waste,","C":"focusing only on bags ignores the bigger problem of total waste,","D":"children should not be involved in environmental issues"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Critics feel that while bags are a problem, they are only one small part of the overall waste management crisis on the island.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Critics sometimes argue that focusing on plastic bags is too narrow. They suggest that the broader issue of total waste management-including food waste and dangerous chemicals-needs more attention.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q005","read_aloud":"How has the culture of Bali changed regarding trash? Options: A. people no longer care about convenience, B. sustainability has become a regular part of people\u0027s conversations, C. everyone has stopped using plastic entirely, D. people have moved away from Bali","excerpt":"\"The movement has forced a shift in the local culture. Where once convenience was the priority, sustainability is now a topic of daily conversation.\"","stem":"How has the culture of Bali changed regarding trash? Options:","choices":{"A":"people no longer care about convenience,","B":"sustainability has become a regular part of people\u0027s conversations,","C":"everyone has stopped using plastic entirely,","D":"people have moved away from Bali"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text indicates that the conversation has shifted from \"convenience\" being the main priority to \"sustainability\" being discussed daily.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The movement has forced a shift in the local culture. Where once convenience was the priority, sustainability is now a topic of daily conversation.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q006","read_aloud":"How does \"disposable\" connect to Bali\u0027s trash problem? A. Disposable items are used once and thrown away, creating lots of waste. B. Disposable items last forever. C. Disposable items are never used. D. Disposable items clean up the environment.","excerpt":"\"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"How does \"disposable\" connect to Bali\u0027s trash problem?","choices":{"A":"Disposable items are used once and thrown away, creating lots of waste.","B":"Disposable items last forever.","C":"Disposable items are never used.","D":"Disposable items clean up the environment."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Disposable means \"single-use; designed to be thrown away.\" When millions of people use disposable items every day, the waste piles up quickly because each item is only used once before becoming trash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q007","read_aloud":"How does knowing about the author help you understand \"Trashing Paradise\"? A. It shows she wants to help people understand problems and work together. B. It shows she only writes funny stories. C. It shows she doesn\u0027t care about the environment. D. It shows she lives in Bali.","excerpt":"\"Rukhsana Khan is a children\u0027s author and storyteller... Her greatest hope is that her stories help create understanding among cultures and reduce conflict in the world.\"","stem":"How does knowing about the author help you understand \"Trashing Paradise\"?","choices":{"A":"It shows she wants to help people understand problems and work together.","B":"It shows she only writes funny stories.","C":"It shows she doesn\u0027t care about the environment.","D":"It shows she lives in Bali."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author hopes her stories \"help create understanding\" and \"reduce conflict.\" This helps us understand that she wrote \"Trashing Paradise\" to help readers understand the trash problem and maybe inspire them to take action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Rukhsana Khan is a children\u0027s author and storyteller... Her greatest hope is that her stories help create understanding among cultures and reduce conflict in the world.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q008","read_aloud":"Why does the author mention the United States? A. To show that plastic pollution is not just Bali\u0027s problem-it is global. B. To say that the United States is worse than Bali. C. To list all the states in America. D. To describe a trip to New York.","excerpt":"\"The same thing was happening all around the world, of course, including the United States.\"","stem":"Why does the author mention the United States?","choices":{"A":"To show that plastic pollution is not just Bali\u0027s problem-it is global.","B":"To say that the United States is worse than Bali.","C":"To list all the states in America.","D":"To describe a trip to New York."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"By mentioning the United States, the author shows that plastic pollution is a problem everywhere, not just on one small island. This helps readers understand that everyone shares this problem and must work together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The same thing was happening all around the world, of course, including the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Why is it important that the sisters\u0027 project spread to other cities? A. Because it shows that kids can make a big difference. B. Because Bali is the only place with trash. C. Because the sisters wanted to be famous. D. Because other cities have no problems.","excerpt":"\"Melati and Isabel\u0027s project spread from Bali to other parts of Indonesia. Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags.\"","stem":"Why is it important that the sisters\u0027 project spread to other cities?","choices":{"A":"Because it shows that kids can make a big difference.","B":"Because Bali is the only place with trash.","C":"Because the sisters wanted to be famous.","D":"Because other cities have no problems."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sisters started as two kids on one island, but their project grew to help many cities. This shows that even young people can create big changes when they work hard and care about a problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Melati and Isabel\u0027s project spread from Bali to other parts of Indonesia. Today, many Indonesian cities are working to eliminate plastic bags.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q010","read_aloud":"If you wanted to reduce plastic waste in your own community, what is one action you could take? A. Use more plastic bags every day. B. Bring a reusable cloth bag when shopping and refuse plastic straws. C. Throw all trash in the ocean. D. Ignore the problem and hope it goes away.","excerpt":"\"Individuals can join together and work to make a positive change in the world.\"","stem":"If you wanted to reduce plastic waste in your own community, what is one action you could take?","choices":{"A":"Use more plastic bags every day.","B":"Bring a reusable cloth bag when shopping and refuse plastic straws.","C":"Throw all trash in the ocean.","D":"Ignore the problem and hope it goes away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that small changes help. Bringing a reusable bag and refusing plastic straws are actions that reduce plastic waste, just like the sisters\u0027 project in Bali.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Individuals can join together and work to make a positive change in the world.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q011","read_aloud":"How does understanding that toxins can travel \"short or long distances\" change how we think about burning plastic? A. it shows the harm isn\u0027t just local; burning plastic can affect areas far away B. it means toxins only stay where they are released C. it suggests burning plastic is safe if done far from cities D. it proves that wind always carries toxins back to the source","excerpt":"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.","stem":"How does understanding that toxins can travel \"short or long distances\" change how we think about burning plastic?","choices":{"A":"it shows the harm isn\u0027t just local; burning plastic can affect areas far away","B":"it means toxins only stay where they are released","C":"it suggests burning plastic is safe if done far from cities","D":"it proves that wind always carries toxins back to the source"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Understanding toxins travel shows burning plastic has widespread impacts, not just local ones.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q012","read_aloud":"How does plastic pollution affect Bali\u0027s fishing industry in multiple ways? A. it reduces fish populations, scares away customers, and damages fishing equipment B. it only makes fishing nets heavier and easier to use C. it helps fish grow faster, benefiting fishermen D. it has no real impact on fishing or seafood sales","excerpt":"Those who fish-whether to feed their families or to make a living-suffer from the trash problem too. Anyone aware of the effects of plastic on fish will hesitate to eat seafood from the waters surrounding Bali. In addition, plastic gets tangled in fishing nets. It also damages boat propellers and other equipment.","stem":"How does plastic pollution affect Bali\u0027s fishing industry in multiple ways?","choices":{"A":"it reduces fish populations, scares away customers, and damages fishing equipment","B":"it only makes fishing nets heavier and easier to use","C":"it helps fish grow faster, benefiting fishermen","D":"it has no real impact on fishing or seafood sales"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students synthesize multiple effects: fewer fish, consumer hesitation, and equipment damage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Those who fish-whether to feed their families or to make a living-suffer from the trash problem too. Anyone aware of the effects of plastic on fish will hesitate to eat seafood from the waters surrounding Bali. In addition, plastic gets tangled in fishing nets. It also damages boat propellers and other equipment."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q013","read_aloud":"What is the author doing by presenting these two questions? A. showing there are different approaches to waste management that communities must consider B. telling readers that recycling doesn\u0027t work anywhere C. arguing that cities should never spend money on trash collection D. suggesting that individuals should handle all waste without help","excerpt":"Should cities fund door-to-door collection of materials for recycling programs? Should the city save that money and depend on people to drop off recyclable materials on their own?","stem":"What is the author doing by presenting these two questions?","choices":{"A":"showing there are different approaches to waste management that communities must consider","B":"telling readers that recycling doesn\u0027t work anywhere","C":"arguing that cities should never spend money on trash collection","D":"suggesting that individuals should handle all waste without help"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author presents competing viewpoints to show the complexity of waste management decisions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Should cities fund door-to-door collection of materials for recycling programs? Should the city save that money and depend on people to drop off recyclable materials on their own?"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Is the author\u0027s hopeful ending realistic based on the evidence in the text? Why or why not? A. yes, because the text shows individuals and groups are already making positive changes B. no, because the trash problem is too big for anyone to solve C. yes, because tourists will stop visiting Bali soon D. no, because plastic cannot be recycled anywhere","excerpt":"If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise.","stem":"Is the author\u0027s hopeful ending realistic based on the evidence in the text? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because the text shows individuals and groups are already making positive changes","B":"no, because the trash problem is too big for anyone to solve","C":"yes, because tourists will stop visiting Bali soon","D":"no, because plastic cannot be recycled anywhere"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text provides evidence of successful actions by the Wijsen sisters and others, making hope realistic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q015","read_aloud":"If you were helping the Wijsen sisters write their book, what three topics would you include and why? A. how plastic is made, how it harms animals, and what alternatives exist-because knowledge leads to change B. how to make more plastic products, where to buy them, and why they\u0027re convenient C. why trash is not a real problem, how to ignore it, and where to hide waste D. how to burn plastic safely, why recycling is hard, and why tourists should come anyway","excerpt":"The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags and other plastic products.","stem":"If you were helping the Wijsen sisters write their book, what three topics would you include and why?","choices":{"A":"how plastic is made, how it harms animals, and what alternatives exist-because knowledge leads to change","B":"how to make more plastic products, where to buy them, and why they\u0027re convenient","C":"why trash is not a real problem, how to ignore it, and where to hide waste","D":"how to burn plastic safely, why recycling is hard, and why tourists should come anyway"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"This creative question asks students to apply the text\u0027s themes: understanding problems and solutions leads to action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags and other plastic products."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Why is calling the trash problem a \"natural phenomenon\" misleading? A. The trash itself is not natural; it comes from human activities. B. The tides are unnatural. C. It is a correct scientific term. D. The governor was lying on purpose.","excerpt":"\"Bali\u0027s governor … called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.\"","stem":"Why is calling the trash problem a \"natural phenomenon\" misleading?","choices":{"A":"The trash itself is not natural; it comes from human activities.","B":"The tides are unnatural.","C":"It is a correct scientific term.","D":"The governor was lying on purpose."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The problem is caused by human waste, not nature alone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali\u0027s governor … called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s opinion about the governor\u0027s approach? A. The author thinks the governor was right not to blame anyone. B. The author thinks awareness and accepting responsibility are necessary for change. C. The author thinks the governor should have done nothing. D. The author thinks tourists are completely to blame.","excerpt":"\"Understandably, he [the governor] didn\u0027t want to point the finger of blame at tourists, or hotels, or restaurants, or any one group. However, to bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s opinion about the governor\u0027s approach?","choices":{"A":"The author thinks the governor was right not to blame anyone.","B":"The author thinks awareness and accepting responsibility are necessary for change.","C":"The author thinks the governor should have done nothing.","D":"The author thinks tourists are completely to blame."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author says everyone must be aware and understand their role.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Understandably, he [the governor] didn\u0027t want to point the finger of blame at tourists, or hotels, or restaurants, or any one group. However, to bring about change, everyone on the island had to become aware of the problem.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q018","read_aloud":"(Text) How is the sisters\u0027 approach in the text similar to their approach in the video \"Bye Bye Plastic Bags on Bali\"? A. They both focused on blaming tourists. B. They both used education, awareness, and advocacy to change behavior. C. They both ignored the problem. D. They both built factories.","excerpt":"The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. … They created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness.","stem":"(Text) How is the sisters\u0027 approach in the text similar to their approach in the video \"Bye Bye Plastic Bags on Bali\"?","choices":{"A":"They both focused on blaming tourists.","B":"They both used education, awareness, and advocacy to change behavior.","C":"They both ignored the problem.","D":"They both built factories."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Both texts show education and advocacy as key strategies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The sisters named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags. … They created petitions and developed educational presentations to raise awareness."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Why is it especially dangerous that plastic breaks into tiny pieces? A. Because the pieces become invisible. B. Because sea creatures mistake them for food (plankton) and eat them. C. Because the pieces turn into algae. D. Because the pieces float away.","excerpt":"\"Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean. Sunlight and waves break some plastic items into smaller and smaller pieces, but they never disappear entirely. These tiny pieces are about the size of the plankton and algae that many sea creatures feed on.\"","stem":"Why is it especially dangerous that plastic breaks into tiny pieces?","choices":{"A":"Because the pieces become invisible.","B":"Because sea creatures mistake them for food (plankton) and eat them.","C":"Because the pieces turn into algae.","D":"Because the pieces float away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Animals eat the tiny pieces, thinking they are food.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic doesn\u0027t biodegrade in the ocean. Sunlight and waves break some plastic items into smaller and smaller pieces, but they never disappear entirely. These tiny pieces are about the size of the plankton and algae that many sea creatures feed on.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q020","read_aloud":"- Melati Wijsen Write one sentence about what you could teach younger students about plastic pollution. A. \"Plastic is good for the environment.\" B. \"Plastic bags can harm sea turtles, so we should use reusable bags.\" C. \"Burning plastic is the best way to get rid of it.\" D. \"Trash should always be thrown into the ocean.\"","excerpt":"Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.","stem":"- Melati Wijsen Write one sentence about what you could teach younger students about plastic pollution.","choices":{"A":"\"Plastic is good for the environment.\"","B":"\"Plastic bags can harm sea turtles, so we should use reusable bags.\"","C":"\"Burning plastic is the best way to get rid of it.\"","D":"\"Trash should always be thrown into the ocean.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Education is key to changing behavior.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q021","read_aloud":"Which is an example of a natural phenomenon? A. A plastic bag in a tree. B. A sunset over the ocean. C. A car driving on the road. D. A house built on the beach.","excerpt":"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \"natural phenomenon.\"","stem":"Which is an example of a natural phenomenon?","choices":{"A":"A plastic bag in a tree.","B":"A sunset over the ocean.","C":"A car driving on the road.","D":"A house built on the beach."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A sunset is a natural event that can be observed, fitting the definition.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \"natural phenomenon.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q022","read_aloud":"What motivated the sisters to act? A. They wanted to be famous. B. They were appalled by the plastic waste. C. They needed money for school. D. They lost their trash can.","excerpt":"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They were appalled by the plastic waste piling up...","stem":"What motivated the sisters to act?","choices":{"A":"They wanted to be famous.","B":"They were appalled by the plastic waste.","C":"They needed money for school.","D":"They lost their trash can."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they were appalled by the plastic waste, which made them want to help.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They were appalled by the plastic waste piling up..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q023","read_aloud":"What solution did the sisters offer for plastic bags? A. They burned the plastic bags. B. They gave out bags made of recycled newspaper. C. They buried the plastic bags. D. They sold plastic bags.","excerpt":"They gave out net bags and bags made of recycled newspaper and other organic materials to replace plastic.","stem":"What solution did the sisters offer for plastic bags?","choices":{"A":"They burned the plastic bags.","B":"They gave out bags made of recycled newspaper.","C":"They buried the plastic bags.","D":"They sold plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sisters gave out alternatives like newspaper bags to replace plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They gave out net bags and bags made of recycled newspaper and other organic materials to replace plastic."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q024","read_aloud":"Was the sisters\u0027 project successful? A. No, the governor ignored them. B. No, they stopped working after one year. C. Yes, the governor signed a pledge. D. Yes, all the trash disappeared instantly.","excerpt":"Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018.","stem":"Was the sisters\u0027 project successful?","choices":{"A":"No, the governor ignored them.","B":"No, they stopped working after one year.","C":"Yes, the governor signed a pledge.","D":"Yes, all the trash disappeared instantly."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text highlights their success by mentioning the governor signed a pledge.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l09-q025","read_aloud":"Do you agree with Melati\u0027s statement? A. No, people can change without knowing why. B. Yes, people need to learn about a problem to fix it. C. No, education makes problems worse. D. Yes, schools are the only place to learn.","excerpt":"Melati noted, \"Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\"","stem":"Do you agree with Melati\u0027s statement?","choices":{"A":"No, people can change without knowing why.","B":"Yes, people need to learn about a problem to fix it.","C":"No, education makes problems worse.","D":"Yes, schools are the only place to learn."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Education helps people understand problems so they can make better choices to fix them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Melati noted, \"Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q001","read_aloud":"What is a \"testament\" in this context? Options: A. a secret plan, B. a piece of proof or evidence, C. a type of legal document, D. an expensive reward","excerpt":"\"Ultimately, the story of Bali is a testament to the fact that environmental problems can be overcome when communities are willing to adapt their daily habits.\"","stem":"What is a \"testament\" in this context? Options:","choices":{"A":"a secret plan,","B":"a piece of proof or evidence,","C":"a type of legal document,","D":"an expensive reward"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Here, \"testament\" means the story serves as evidence or proof that progress is possible.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ultimately, the story of Bali is a testament to the fact that environmental problems can be overcome when communities are willing to adapt their daily habits.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q002","read_aloud":"How can a tourist act in an \"aware\" way? Options: A. by only staying in the largest hotels, B. by choosing businesses that care about the environment, C. by not visiting Bali at all, D. by bringing as much plastic as they need","excerpt":"\"For travelers, the lesson is clear: being a \u0027good\u0027 tourist means being an aware one. By choosing businesses that prioritize the environment, tourists contribute directly to the solution.\"","stem":"How can a tourist act in an \"aware\" way? Options:","choices":{"A":"by only staying in the largest hotels,","B":"by choosing businesses that care about the environment,","C":"by not visiting Bali at all,","D":"by bringing as much plastic as they need"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being aware means choosing businesses that focus on helping the environment rather than hurting it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For travelers, the lesson is clear: being a \u0027good\u0027 tourist means being an aware one. By choosing businesses that prioritize the environment, tourists contribute directly to the solution.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q003","read_aloud":"What does the author mean by \"reclaiming its status\"? Options: A. it is becoming a natural paradise again, B. it is losing all its trees, C. it is renaming the island, D. it is fighting a war","excerpt":"\"While Bali still struggles with its waste, the progress made in the last decade is undeniable. From beach cleanups to legislative change, the island is slowly reclaiming its status as a natural paradise.\"","stem":"What does the author mean by \"reclaiming its status\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"it is becoming a natural paradise again,","B":"it is losing all its trees,","C":"it is renaming the island,","D":"it is fighting a war"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Reclaiming\" implies getting back something that was lost, meaning Bali is returning to the clean state it was in before the trash problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"While Bali still struggles with its waste, the progress made in the last decade is undeniable. From beach cleanups to legislative change, the island is slowly reclaiming its status as a natural paradise.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author describe these as \"pillars\"? Options: A. they are physical buildings, B. they are the essential parts that support the whole effort, C. they are names of laws, D. they are things that tourists should not worry about","excerpt":"\"Education, policy, and personal responsibility are the three pillars of Bali\u0027s fight against trash. One cannot be successful without the others.\"","stem":"Why does the author describe these as \"pillars\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"they are physical buildings,","B":"they are the essential parts that support the whole effort,","C":"they are names of laws,","D":"they are things that tourists should not worry about"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Pillars hold up a roof; similarly, these three concepts are the essential elements that hold up and support the success of the environmental effort.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Education, policy, and personal responsibility are the three pillars of Bali\u0027s fight against trash. One cannot be successful without the others.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q005","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s final point about the reader\u0027s potential impact? Options: A. only adults can change the world, B. you are too young to make a difference, C. your actions matter regardless of your age, D. the world is already perfect","excerpt":"\"As Melati and Isabel have shown, age is not a barrier to change. Whether you are ten or one hundred, your actions have an impact on the world around you.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s final point about the reader\u0027s potential impact? Options:","choices":{"A":"only adults can change the world,","B":"you are too young to make a difference,","C":"your actions matter regardless of your age,","D":"the world is already perfect"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author uses the example of the sisters to show that everyone, regardless of age, has the power to affect the world through their actions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As Melati and Isabel have shown, age is not a barrier to change. Whether you are ten or one hundred, your actions have an impact on the world around you.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q006","read_aloud":"Why did the governor use the word \"phenomenon\" instead of \"problem\"? A. Because he wanted to avoid blaming people for creating the trash. B. Because he didn\u0027t know what phenomenon meant. C. Because phenomenon means the same as solution. D. Because he wanted more tourists to visit.","excerpt":"\"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027\"","stem":"Why did the governor use the word \"phenomenon\" instead of \"problem\"?","choices":{"A":"Because he wanted to avoid blaming people for creating the trash.","B":"Because he didn\u0027t know what phenomenon meant.","C":"Because phenomenon means the same as solution.","D":"Because he wanted more tourists to visit."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the governor \"blamed the rains and the tides\" and \"didn\u0027t want to point the finger of blame at tourists, or hotels, or restaurants.\" Calling it a \"phenomenon\" made it sound like a natural event rather than a human-caused problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Why did the author organize the weekly launch with these questions as headings? A. To confuse readers. B. To guide readers through understanding the problem and finding solutions. C. To make the text shorter. D. To hide important facts.","excerpt":"The text has headings like \"The Trouble with Ocean Trash,\" \"What Is in the Ocean?\", \"How Does It Get There?\", and \"What Can We Do?\"","stem":"Why did the author organize the weekly launch with these questions as headings?","choices":{"A":"To confuse readers.","B":"To guide readers through understanding the problem and finding solutions.","C":"To make the text shorter.","D":"To hide important facts."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The questions as headings help readers follow a clear path: first learn what trash is in the ocean, then how it gets there, and finally what can be done. This structure helps readers understand and feel empowered to act.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text has headings like \"The Trouble with Ocean Trash,\" \"What Is in the Ocean?\", \"How Does It Get There?\", and \"What Can We Do?\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q008","read_aloud":"If everyone does NOT work together, what might happen to Bali? A. The trash problem will get worse, and Bali may never recover. B. The trash will magically disappear. C. Bali will become the cleanest place on Earth. D. Tourists will stop visiting, which will solve everything.","excerpt":"\"If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise.\"","stem":"If everyone does NOT work together, what might happen to Bali?","choices":{"A":"The trash problem will get worse, and Bali may never recover.","B":"The trash will magically disappear.","C":"Bali will become the cleanest place on Earth.","D":"Tourists will stop visiting, which will solve everything."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says \"If everyone works together,\" Bali can become a paradise again. The opposite is also true: if people don\u0027t work together, the trash will keep piling up, and Bali\u0027s environment and economy will suffer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q009","read_aloud":"Why was it important that the sisters\u0027 talk was viewed around the world? A. Because it spread their message to more people who could help. B. Because they wanted to become movie stars. C. Because London is the only city that cares about trash. D. Because videos are always funny.","excerpt":"\"The nonprofit organization TED saw the video. They contacted the girls and asked them to give a talk in London. The talk was recorded and viewed by people around the world.\"","stem":"Why was it important that the sisters\u0027 talk was viewed around the world?","choices":{"A":"Because it spread their message to more people who could help.","B":"Because they wanted to become movie stars.","C":"Because London is the only city that cares about trash.","D":"Because videos are always funny."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"When the talk was viewed around the world, more people learned about Bali\u0027s plastic problem. This global attention helped spread the sisters\u0027 message and inspired others to take action in their own communities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The nonprofit organization TED saw the video. They contacted the girls and asked them to give a talk in London. The talk was recorded and viewed by people around the world.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q010","read_aloud":"Should other communities organize beach cleanups too? Use evidence from the text. A. No, because cleaning beaches is a waste of time. B. Yes, because cleanups remove trash and protect marine life, animals, and tourism. C. No, because only kids should clean beaches. D. Yes, because cleanups make the sand hotter.","excerpt":"\"Groups of surfers and companies that sell surfing equipment have organized regular beach-cleanup days on Bali. In one recent event, they cleaned up more than 1 million pounds of trash from Bali\u0027s beaches.\"","stem":"Should other communities organize beach cleanups too? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because cleaning beaches is a waste of time.","B":"Yes, because cleanups remove trash and protect marine life, animals, and tourism.","C":"No, because only kids should clean beaches.","D":"Yes, because cleanups make the sand hotter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that trash harms marine life, animals, and tourism. Beach cleanups remove this harmful trash. The surfers\u0027 cleanup removed \"more than 1 million pounds of trash,\" which helps protect the environment and keep beaches beautiful for everyone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Groups of surfers and companies that sell surfing equipment have organized regular beach-cleanup days on Bali. In one recent event, they cleaned up more than 1 million pounds of trash from Bali\u0027s beaches.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q011","read_aloud":"What is the author implying by noting what the governor did NOT address? A. that focusing on natural causes may distract from human responsibility for creating the trash B. that the governor is completely wrong about everything C. that rain and tides are not real forces in Bali D. that trash appears naturally without human help","excerpt":"Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place.","stem":"What is the author implying by noting what the governor did NOT address?","choices":{"A":"that focusing on natural causes may distract from human responsibility for creating the trash","B":"that the governor is completely wrong about everything","C":"that rain and tides are not real forces in Bali","D":"that trash appears naturally without human help"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author implies that blaming nature alone overlooks the human choices that create the waste problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bali\u0027s governor, Made Mangku Pastika, called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027 He blamed the rains and the tides for the repeated cycle of trash washing out and back in again, but he didn\u0027t address the problem of where the trash came from in the first place."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q012","read_aloud":"Based on \"Trashing Paradise,\" do you think plastic waste could be viewed as a \"resource we are not harvesting\"? Why or why not? A. yes, because plastic can be recycled into new products if we collect and process it properly B. no, because plastic has no value and should never be used C. yes, because burning plastic is the best way to use it D. no, because all waste should be buried underground forever","excerpt":"Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value.","stem":"Based on \"Trashing Paradise,\" do you think plastic waste could be viewed as a \"resource we are not harvesting\"? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"yes, because plastic can be recycled into new products if we collect and process it properly","B":"no, because plastic has no value and should never be used","C":"yes, because burning plastic is the best way to use it","D":"no, because all waste should be buried underground forever"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text mentions recycling and alternatives, supporting the idea that plastic could be a resource if managed properly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Pollution is nothing but the resources we are not harvesting. We allow them to disperse because we\u0027ve been ignorant of their value."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Which vocabulary word best describes the effect of plastic on Bali\u0027s beauty? A. disposable B. marred C. crude oil D. initiative","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. … Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals … Bali\u0027s governor called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027\"","stem":"Which vocabulary word best describes the effect of plastic on Bali\u0027s beauty?","choices":{"A":"disposable","B":"marred","C":"crude oil","D":"initiative"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means damaged or made ugly, which describes the effect on beauty.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. … Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals … Bali\u0027s governor called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the author end with this focus on education? A. To show that the work is done. B. To show that education is the foundation for longterm change. C. To advertise a book. D. To confuse the reader.","excerpt":"\"The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags and other plastic products. Melati noted, \u0027Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does the author end with this focus on education?","choices":{"A":"To show that the work is done.","B":"To show that education is the foundation for longterm change.","C":"To advertise a book.","D":"To confuse the reader."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Education leads to awareness and action.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sisters are now focused on creating an educational book for elementary school students. It will be filled with information about pollution, waste management, and alternatives to plastic bags and other plastic products. Melati noted, \u0027Change doesn\u0027t happen if no one is educated.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q015","read_aloud":"Write one sentence describing a new rule your school could adopt to reduce plastic waste. A. \"My school should throw all trash on the playground.\" B. \"My school could ban plastic straws in the cafeteria and encourage reusable water bottles.\" C. \"My school should use more plastic bags.\" D. \"My school should burn all trash.\"","excerpt":"\"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new wastetreatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\"","stem":"Write one sentence describing a new rule your school could adopt to reduce plastic waste.","choices":{"A":"\"My school should throw all trash on the playground.\"","B":"\"My school could ban plastic straws in the cafeteria and encourage reusable water bottles.\"","C":"\"My school should use more plastic bags.\"","D":"\"My school should burn all trash.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Small changes at school can reduce waste and educate students.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new wastetreatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q016","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses marred correctly? A. The beautiful view was marred by the storm. B. The beautiful view was marred by the sunshine. C. The beautiful view was marred by the flowers. D. The beautiful view was marred by the clouds.","excerpt":"This one is marred by trash.","stem":"Which sentence uses marred correctly?","choices":{"A":"The beautiful view was marred by the storm.","B":"The beautiful view was marred by the sunshine.","C":"The beautiful view was marred by the flowers.","D":"The beautiful view was marred by the clouds."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Marred\" means damaged or made ugly, and a storm can damage a view.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: This one is marred by trash."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q017","read_aloud":"Why do places charge a fee for plastic bags? A. To make people angry. B. To make money for the store. C. To encourage people to bring their own bags. D. To make shopping harder.","excerpt":"In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective in getting people to bring their own cloth or recycled bags...","stem":"Why do places charge a fee for plastic bags?","choices":{"A":"To make people angry.","B":"To make money for the store.","C":"To encourage people to bring their own bags.","D":"To make shopping harder."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says the policy is effective in getting people to bring their own bags.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In a number of places, people must pay a fee to get a plastic bag at a store. This policy has proved very effective in getting people to bring their own cloth or recycled bags..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q018","read_aloud":"What are organizations encouraging people to do? A. Use more plastic. B. Find alternatives to waste. C. Burn their trash. D. Visit the island more often.","excerpt":"Other organizations... are encouraging both residents and tourists to find alternatives to waste products.","stem":"What are organizations encouraging people to do?","choices":{"A":"Use more plastic.","B":"Find alternatives to waste.","C":"Burn their trash.","D":"Visit the island more often."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says organizations are encouraging people to find alternatives.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Other organizations... are encouraging both residents and tourists to find alternatives to waste products."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How could a tourist be more eco-friendly? A. By buying many plastic bottles. B. By using a refillable water bottle. C. By leaving trash on the beach. D. By using plastic bags for souvenirs.","excerpt":"Environmentalists now urge tourists to plan ahead to make their visit as eco-friendly as possible.","stem":"How could a tourist be more eco-friendly?","choices":{"A":"By buying many plastic bottles.","B":"By using a refillable water bottle.","C":"By leaving trash on the beach.","D":"By using plastic bags for souvenirs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Using a refillable bottle reduces plastic waste, which is eco-friendly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Environmentalists now urge tourists to plan ahead to make their visit as eco-friendly as possible."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q020","read_aloud":"What is the main message of this text? A. Bali is a hopeless place. B. Tourists should stop visiting Bali. C. People working together can solve the trash problem. D. Plastic is the best material to use.","excerpt":"If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise.","stem":"What is the main message of this text?","choices":{"A":"Bali is a hopeless place.","B":"Tourists should stop visiting Bali.","C":"People working together can solve the trash problem.","D":"Plastic is the best material to use."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The ending emphasizes that working together can restore the island.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q022","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q023","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They used plastic bags. B. They used cloth bags. C. They used paper boxes. D. They carried items by hand.","excerpt":"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They used plastic bags.","B":"They used cloth bags.","C":"They used paper boxes.","D":"They carried items by hand."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q024","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It stays forever. B. It turns into plastic. C. It decomposes or rots. D. It becomes poisonous.","excerpt":"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted.","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It stays forever.","B":"It turns into plastic.","C":"It decomposes or rots.","D":"It becomes poisonous."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text defines biodegradable as things that decompose or rot.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-l10-q025","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To make the food taste better. B. To create more trash. C. To wrap their food naturally. D. To sell to tourists.","excerpt":"They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To make the food taste better.","B":"To create more trash.","C":"To wrap their food naturally.","D":"To sell to tourists."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains they used natural items as wrappings and plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food."}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"marred\" mean? A. made more beautiful B. damaged or made ugly C. covered in flowers D. protected from harm","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"What does \"marred\" mean?","choices":{"A":"made more beautiful","B":"damaged or made ugly","C":"covered in flowers","D":"protected from harm"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines marred as \"damaged; made ugly; marked.\" Trash piled on roadsides makes Bali look ugly and damaged.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q002","read_aloud":"What does \"disposable\" mean? A. designed to last forever B. single-use; designed to be thrown away C. made of metal D. very expensive","excerpt":"\"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"What does \"disposable\" mean?","choices":{"A":"designed to last forever","B":"single-use; designed to be thrown away","C":"made of metal","D":"very expensive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines disposable as \"single-use; designed to be thrown away.\" These plastic items were made to be used once and then thrown away.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q003","read_aloud":"What does \"toxic\" mean? A. helpful and healthy B. poisonous C. colorful D. expensive","excerpt":"\"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\"","stem":"What does \"toxic\" mean?","choices":{"A":"helpful and healthy","B":"poisonous","C":"colorful","D":"expensive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines toxic as \"poisonous.\" Toxic chemicals like dioxins are harmful and can make people and animals sick.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air, which carries them short or long distances to contaminate both land and water.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Bali was always covered in trash. B. Bali changed from a clean paradise to a place with serious plastic pollution. C. Plastic was never used in Bali. D. Tourists have always kept Bali clean.","excerpt":"\"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash... Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Bali was always covered in trash.","B":"Bali changed from a clean paradise to a place with serious plastic pollution.","C":"Plastic was never used in Bali.","D":"Tourists have always kept Bali clean."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt contrasts Bali\u0027s past as a paradise with little trash and its present after disposable plastic arrived. The main idea is that Bali changed from clean to polluted because of plastic waste.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"For most of its history, Bali really was a paradise. The Balinese people created little or no trash... Then convenience came to Bali. It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q005","read_aloud":"What can you infer about why sea turtles are endangered? A. Because they eat too much real food. B. Because plastic pollution in the ocean harms them. C. Because they don\u0027t like jellyfish anymore. D. Because they have lived too long.","excerpt":"\"Leatherback sea turtles have been around for more than 100 million years, but today they are endangered, partially because they mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food.\"","stem":"What can you infer about why sea turtles are endangered?","choices":{"A":"Because they eat too much real food.","B":"Because plastic pollution in the ocean harms them.","C":"Because they don\u0027t like jellyfish anymore.","D":"Because they have lived too long."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says turtles mistake plastic bags for jellyfish and suffocate. This shows that plastic pollution in the ocean is one reason these ancient animals are now endangered.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Leatherback sea turtles have been around for more than 100 million years, but today they are endangered, partially because they mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q006","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use here? A. problem and solution B. cause and effect C. compare and contrast D. sequence","excerpt":"\"One reason is that Bali is a small island... Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground... Tourists are a third reason for the trash problem... Then again, there really isn\u0027t any good way to dispose of garbage on the island. That\u0027s the fourth reason.\"","stem":"What text structure does the author use here?","choices":{"A":"problem and solution","B":"cause and effect","C":"compare and contrast","D":"sequence"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author lists reasons (causes) why Bali has a trash problem: small size, old habits, tourists, and no good disposal system. Each reason explains why the trash problem exists (effect).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One reason is that Bali is a small island... Another reason is that the Balinese are used to disposing of things by simply dropping them on the ground... Tourists are a third reason for the trash problem... Then again, there really isn\u0027t any good way to dispose of garbage on the island. That\u0027s the fourth reason.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q007","read_aloud":"How old were Melati and Isabel when they started their project? A. 5 and 7 B. 10 and 13 C. 18 and 20 D. 25 and 30","excerpt":"\"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags.\"","stem":"How old were Melati and Isabel when they started their project?","choices":{"A":"5 and 7","B":"10 and 13","C":"18 and 20","D":"25 and 30"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that Melati was 13 and Isabel was 10 when they started their project in 2013.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island. They named their project Bye Bye Plastic Bags.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q008","read_aloud":"Why is plastic bad for the environment? A. Because it breaks down too quickly. B. Because nature cannot easily break it down, so it lasts for hundreds of years. C. Because it is too soft. D. Because animals don\u0027t see it.","excerpt":"\"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade.\"","stem":"Why is plastic bad for the environment?","choices":{"A":"Because it breaks down too quickly.","B":"Because nature cannot easily break it down, so it lasts for hundreds of years.","C":"Because it is too soft.","D":"Because animals don\u0027t see it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that plastics are \"different from anything that occurs in nature,\" so nature cannot break them down easily. Plastic can last for \"hundreds or thousands of years,\" which means it pollutes the environment for a very long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down. In fact, it can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q009","read_aloud":"Why was getting the governor\u0027s support important? A. Because the governor could make official rules to ban plastic bags. B. Because the governor was the sisters\u0027 father. C. Because the governor could give them money. D. Because the governor liked plastic bags.","excerpt":"\"Melati and Isabel got people to pay attention. That was the first, crucial step to making real change in Bali... Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018.\"","stem":"Why was getting the governor\u0027s support important?","choices":{"A":"Because the governor could make official rules to ban plastic bags.","B":"Because the governor was the sisters\u0027 father.","C":"Because the governor could give them money.","D":"Because the governor liked plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The governor has the power to make laws and rules for the island. When he signed the pledge, it meant the government would work to make Bali plastic-bag free. Official rules help make sure everyone follows the new policies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Melati and Isabel got people to pay attention. That was the first, crucial step to making real change in Bali... Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q010","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s main message in this conclusion? A. Only big changes can help Bali. B. Only governments can fix the trash problem. C. Everyone\u0027s actions, big or small, matter, and working together can restore Bali. D. Bali will never be clean again.","excerpt":"\"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live. If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s main message in this conclusion?","choices":{"A":"Only big changes can help Bali.","B":"Only governments can fix the trash problem.","C":"Everyone\u0027s actions, big or small, matter, and working together can restore Bali.","D":"Bali will never be clean again."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author says \"every choice and every change, small or large\" can help, and \"if everyone works together,\" Bali can become a paradise again. The main message is that everyone has a role to play, and teamwork can solve the problem. Section A - Text Information Title: Trashing ParadiseAuthor: Rukhsana KhanText Type: Informational TextPreview Vocabulary Words: marred, disposable, crude oil, toxic, phenomenon","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live. If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"marred\" mean in this context? A. damaged or made less beautiful B. improved and made better C. visited by many people D. protected from harm","excerpt":"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.","stem":"What does \"marred\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"damaged or made less beautiful","B":"improved and made better","C":"visited by many people","D":"protected from harm"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Marred means damaged. The text contrasts beautiful Bali with trash-marred Bali.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q012","read_aloud":"Which best describes \"disposable\" products? A. designed for one use then thrown away B. meant to last for many years C. made from natural materials only D. too expensive for most people","excerpt":"It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.","stem":"Which best describes \"disposable\" products?","choices":{"A":"designed for one use then thrown away","B":"meant to last for many years","C":"made from natural materials only","D":"too expensive for most people"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Disposable means single-use items intended to be discarded after use.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q013","read_aloud":"What is a \"phenomenon\"? A. an observable event or occurrence B. a type of plastic container C. a traditional Balinese festival D. a method of recycling","excerpt":"Bali\u0027s governor called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027","stem":"What is a \"phenomenon\"?","choices":{"A":"an observable event or occurrence","B":"a type of plastic container","C":"a traditional Balinese festival","D":"a method of recycling"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Phenomenon means an observable event. The governor was describing the trash cycle as observable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Bali\u0027s governor called the issue a \u0027natural phenomenon.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the selection? A. Plastic pollution is harming Bali\u0027s environment and economy B. Bali has always been a perfect paradise with no problems C. Tourists should avoid all tropical islands D. Plastic is the best material for packaging","excerpt":"Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare.","stem":"What is the main idea of the selection?","choices":{"A":"Plastic pollution is harming Bali\u0027s environment and economy","B":"Bali has always been a perfect paradise with no problems","C":"Tourists should avoid all tropical islands","D":"Plastic is the best material for packaging"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text focuses on how plastic waste is damaging Bali\u0027s environment and affecting its future.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q015","read_aloud":"What is the chain of effects described here? A. plastic enters ocean → animals eat it → animals get sick → people who eat those animals can get sick B. plastic helps fish grow → fish taste better → people eat more fish → oceans stay clean C. plastic disappears in water → animals never find it → oceans become healthier → tourism increases D. plastic sinks to bottom → becomes sand → helps coral grow → attracts more tourists","excerpt":"When birds or fish consume these plastic bits, they can get sick and die. If people eat the fish that consume the plastic, they can get sick too.","stem":"What is the chain of effects described here?","choices":{"A":"plastic enters ocean → animals eat it → animals get sick → people who eat those animals can get sick","B":"plastic helps fish grow → fish taste better → people eat more fish → oceans stay clean","C":"plastic disappears in water → animals never find it → oceans become healthier → tourism increases","D":"plastic sinks to bottom → becomes sand → helps coral grow → attracts more tourists"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes how plastic moves through the food chain, affecting multiple levels of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When birds or fish consume these plastic bits, they can get sick and die. If people eat the fish that consume the plastic, they can get sick too."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q016","read_aloud":"What can you infer about solving Bali\u0027s trash problem? A. solutions must include educating tourists about their impact B. tourists should be banned from visiting Bali C. only local residents need to change their habits D. trash problems will solve themselves over time","excerpt":"Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean.","stem":"What can you infer about solving Bali\u0027s trash problem?","choices":{"A":"solutions must include educating tourists about their impact","B":"tourists should be banned from visiting Bali","C":"only local residents need to change their habits","D":"trash problems will solve themselves over time"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"If tourists don\u0027t feel responsible, education and awareness efforts targeting them would be important.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Because they don\u0027t live on Bali, many tourists feel no responsibility to keep the island clean."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q017","read_aloud":"According to the text, how many tourists visit Bali annually? A. more than 3 million B. about 1 million C. exactly 500,000 D. less than 100,000","excerpt":"More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year.","stem":"According to the text, how many tourists visit Bali annually?","choices":{"A":"more than 3 million","B":"about 1 million","C":"exactly 500,000","D":"less than 100,000"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states more than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: More than 3 million tourists visit Bali each year."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q018","read_aloud":"How did traditional Balinese practices help the environment? A. they used natural materials that break down and don\u0027t create lasting waste B. they used plastic containers that lasted for years C. they burned all waste in large fires D. they shipped trash to other islands","excerpt":"They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.","stem":"How did traditional Balinese practices help the environment?","choices":{"A":"they used natural materials that break down and don\u0027t create lasting waste","B":"they used plastic containers that lasted for years","C":"they burned all waste in large fires","D":"they shipped trash to other islands"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Natural materials like banana leaves decompose, unlike plastic that lasts for centuries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q019","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt reveal about environmental problems? A. they often involve trade-offs between different important goals B. they can always be solved by doing just one simple thing C. they only affect the environment, not the economy D. they are impossible to understand or address","excerpt":"A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy.","stem":"What does this excerpt reveal about environmental problems?","choices":{"A":"they often involve trade-offs between different important goals","B":"they can always be solved by doing just one simple thing","C":"they only affect the environment, not the economy","D":"they are impossible to understand or address"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Students analyze that environmental issues often require balancing competing needs like economy and ecology.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q020","read_aloud":"Based on the entire selection, what is the most important message the author wants readers to take away? A. everyone can contribute to solving environmental problems through their choices B. only governments can solve big problems like pollution C. individual actions don\u0027t matter for large-scale issues D. tourists should avoid Bali to protect its environment","excerpt":"Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place.","stem":"Based on the entire selection, what is the most important message the author wants readers to take away?","choices":{"A":"everyone can contribute to solving environmental problems through their choices","B":"only governments can solve big problems like pollution","C":"individual actions don\u0027t matter for large-scale issues","D":"tourists should avoid Bali to protect its environment"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text emphasizes both individual and collective action, ending with hope that everyone\u0027s choices matter. Section A - Text Information Title: Trashing Paradise (excerpt)Author: Rukhshana Khan","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Every choice and every change, small or large-from refusing a plastic drinking straw to building a new waste-treatment facility-can help make Bali a cleaner place."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q021","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the text? A. Bali is a perfect paradise with no problems. B. Plastic waste is damaging Bali\u0027s environment, but people are working to solve the problem. C. Only tourists cause problems in Bali. D. Bali has no trash problems.","excerpt":"\"Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of the text?","choices":{"A":"Bali is a perfect paradise with no problems.","B":"Plastic waste is damaging Bali\u0027s environment, but people are working to solve the problem.","C":"Only tourists cause problems in Bali.","D":"Bali has no trash problems."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text presents a problem and then solutions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Garbage, particularly in the form of plastic waste, is turning this onetime paradise into an environmental nightmare.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q022","read_aloud":"How does plastic affect leatherback sea turtles? A. They eat plastic bags thinking they are jellyfish and can suffocate. B. They use plastic bags to build nests. C. They are not affected. D. They eat more jellyfish.","excerpt":"\"Many animals mistake larger pieces of plastic for food too. Leatherback sea turtles … mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food. When they try to swallow a plastic bag, they suffocate.\"","stem":"How does plastic affect leatherback sea turtles?","choices":{"A":"They eat plastic bags thinking they are jellyfish and can suffocate.","B":"They use plastic bags to build nests.","C":"They are not affected.","D":"They eat more jellyfish."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Turtles mistake bags for jellyfish and can suffocate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many animals mistake larger pieces of plastic for food too. Leatherback sea turtles … mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food. When they try to swallow a plastic bag, they suffocate.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q023","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the Balinese people\u0027s values in the past? A. They valued convenience over nature. B. They valued using natural, reusable materials and avoiding waste. C. They did not care about the environment. D. They only used plastic.","excerpt":"\"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the Balinese people\u0027s values in the past?","choices":{"A":"They valued convenience over nature.","B":"They valued using natural, reusable materials and avoiding waste.","C":"They did not care about the environment.","D":"They only used plastic."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Their actions show respect for nature and waste reduction.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q024","read_aloud":"How old were the Wijsen sisters when they started their campaign? A. 20 and 17 B. 13 and 10 C. 8 and 5 D. 30 and 27","excerpt":"\"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island.\"","stem":"How old were the Wijsen sisters when they started their campaign?","choices":{"A":"20 and 17","B":"13 and 10","C":"8 and 5","D":"30 and 27"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they were 13 and 10.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 2013, a pair of sisters named Melati and Isabel Wijsen, then ages 13 and 10, stepped up to help their island.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q025","read_aloud":"Why is plastic so hard for nature to break down? A. Because it is made from banana leaves. B. Because it is made from chemicals not found in nature in that form. C. Because it is too heavy. D. Because it is too soft.","excerpt":"\"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. … The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down.\"","stem":"Why is plastic so hard for nature to break down?","choices":{"A":"Because it is made from banana leaves.","B":"Because it is made from chemicals not found in nature in that form.","C":"Because it is too heavy.","D":"Because it is too soft."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Plastic is different from natural materials, so nature cannot break it easily.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Plastic is made from chemicals. Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. … The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q026","read_aloud":"Melati tells others who want to make a difference with their actions. Do you think this message is important for young people? Why? A. No, because young people cannot change anything. B. Yes, because young people have energy, ideas, and can inspire others, as Melati and Isabel showed. C. No, because only adults have power. D. Yes, but only for boys.","excerpt":"Don\u0027t ever let anyone tell you that you\u0027re too young,","stem":"Melati tells others who want to make a difference with their actions. Do you think this message is important for young people? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because young people cannot change anything.","B":"Yes, because young people have energy, ideas, and can inspire others, as Melati and Isabel showed.","C":"No, because only adults have power.","D":"Yes, but only for boys."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Melati and Isabel proved that young people can create change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Don\u0027t ever let anyone tell you that you\u0027re too young,"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q027","read_aloud":"Write one sentence describing one small change you could make at home to reduce plastic waste. A. \"I could use more plastic bags.\" B. \"I could use a reusable water bottle instead of buying plastic bottles.\" C. \"I could throw all my trash on the ground.\" D. \"I could burn my trash in the backyard.\"","excerpt":"\"Every choice and every change, small or large … can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\"","stem":"Write one sentence describing one small change you could make at home to reduce plastic waste.","choices":{"A":"\"I could use more plastic bags.\"","B":"\"I could use a reusable water bottle instead of buying plastic bottles.\"","C":"\"I could throw all my trash on the ground.\"","D":"\"I could burn my trash in the backyard.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Small individual actions help reduce waste. Section A - Text information Title: Trashing Paradise Author: Rukhsana Khan","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Every choice and every change, small or large … can help make Bali a cleaner place to visit and to live.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q028","read_aloud":"Which word means the opposite of marred? A. Damaged B. Improved C. Broken D. Spoiled","excerpt":"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash.","stem":"Which word means the opposite of marred?","choices":{"A":"Damaged","B":"Improved","C":"Broken","D":"Spoiled"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Marred\" means damaged or made ugly, so \"improved\" is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q029","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for toxic? A. Safe B. Healthy C. Poisonous D. Clean","excerpt":"Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air...","stem":"What is a synonym for toxic?","choices":{"A":"Safe","B":"Healthy","C":"Poisonous","D":"Clean"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Toxic means poisonous, so poisonous is a synonym.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Burning plastic releases toxic chemicals called dioxins into the air..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q030","read_aloud":"What is the main ingredient used to make plastic? A. Banana leaves B. Crude oil C. Water D. Sand","excerpt":"Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals.","stem":"What is the main ingredient used to make plastic?","choices":{"A":"Banana leaves","B":"Crude oil","C":"Water","D":"Sand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that scientists use chemicals from crude oil to make plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground. Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q031","read_aloud":"What is the cause of the turtles suffocating? A. They cannot find jellyfish. B. The water is too deep. C. They swallow plastic bags thinking they are food. D. They are hunted by fishermen.","excerpt":"Leatherback sea turtles... mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food. When they try to swallow a plastic bag, they suffocate.","stem":"What is the cause of the turtles suffocating?","choices":{"A":"They cannot find jellyfish.","B":"The water is too deep.","C":"They swallow plastic bags thinking they are food.","D":"They are hunted by fishermen."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The turtles mistake plastic bags for jellyfish, eat them, and suffocate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Leatherback sea turtles... mistake plastic bags in the water for jellyfish, their favorite food. When they try to swallow a plastic bag, they suffocate."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q032","read_aloud":"What can the reader infer about the governor? A. He does not care about Bali. B. He was convinced by the sisters\u0027 hard work. C. He wanted to ban all tourists. D. He invented plastic bags.","excerpt":"Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018.","stem":"What can the reader infer about the governor?","choices":{"A":"He does not care about Bali.","B":"He was convinced by the sisters\u0027 hard work.","C":"He wanted to ban all tourists.","D":"He invented plastic bags."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since he signed the pledge after the sisters worked hard, it can be inferred he was convinced by their efforts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Finally, they even got the governor of Bali on their side. He signed a pledge that Bali would become plastic-bag free by 2018."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q033","read_aloud":"How was life in Bali different in the past compared to today? A. People used more plastic in the past. B. People created more trash in the past. C. People used natural materials and created little trash. D. People did not eat food in the past.","excerpt":"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves... as wrappings...","stem":"How was life in Bali different in the past compared to today?","choices":{"A":"People used more plastic in the past.","B":"People created more trash in the past.","C":"People used natural materials and created little trash.","D":"People did not eat food in the past."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text contrasts the past use of natural materials with the current use of plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed. They used banana leaves... as wrappings..."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q034","read_aloud":"Why is the trash problem a difficult challenge for Bali? A. Tourists like the trash. B. Cleaning up might hurt the economy. C. Trash helps the plants grow. D. The trash brings more money to the island.","excerpt":"No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy.","stem":"Why is the trash problem a difficult challenge for Bali?","choices":{"A":"Tourists like the trash.","B":"Cleaning up might hurt the economy.","C":"Trash helps the plants grow.","D":"The trash brings more money to the island."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If tourists stop coming, there is less trash, but the island loses money.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: No one wants to swim, snorkel, surf, or sunbathe at trash-infested beaches. A decrease in tourists might help slow the buildup of trash, but it would also damage the island\u0027s economy."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q035","read_aloud":"Melati tells others who want to make a difference with their actions. What is the best summary of Melati\u0027s message? A. Only adults can fix problems. B. Young people cannot make big changes. C. Age does not matter when you want to make a difference. D. Being young is a good reason to do nothing.","excerpt":"Don\u0027t ever let anyone tell you that you\u0027re too young,","stem":"Melati tells others who want to make a difference with their actions. What is the best summary of Melati\u0027s message?","choices":{"A":"Only adults can fix problems.","B":"Young people cannot make big changes.","C":"Age does not matter when you want to make a difference.","D":"Being young is a good reason to do nothing."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Melati believes that young people can make a difference just like adults can.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Don\u0027t ever let anyone tell you that you\u0027re too young,"},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q036","read_aloud":"Imagine you want to help Bali. What would be the best action to take? A. Visit Bali and leave your trash on the beach. B. Use reusable bags and bottles every day. C. Burn all your plastic trash in your backyard. D. Encourage your friends to buy more plastic.","excerpt":"If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise.","stem":"Imagine you want to help Bali. What would be the best action to take?","choices":{"A":"Visit Bali and leave your trash on the beach.","B":"Use reusable bags and bottles every day.","C":"Burn all your plastic trash in your backyard.","D":"Encourage your friends to buy more plastic."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Using reusable items reduces the amount of plastic waste, which helps solve the problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If everyone works together, one day the island may again become a real-life paradise."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q037","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q038","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. kept clean, B. damaged, C. built new, D. made better","excerpt":"\"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"kept clean,","B":"damaged,","C":"built new,","D":"made better"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Marred means that something has been damaged or made less beautiful, just like the trash makes the island look ugly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now picture another version of Bali. This one is marred by trash. Waste is piled high on roadsides.\""},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q039","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They used plastic bags. B. They used cloth bags. C. They used paper boxes. D. They carried items by hand.","excerpt":"The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They used plastic bags.","B":"They used cloth bags.","C":"They used paper boxes.","D":"They carried items by hand."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they used cloth bags to carry what they needed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Balinese people created little or no trash. They used cloth bags to carry what they needed."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q040","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It stays forever. B. It turns into plastic. C. It decomposes or rots. D. It becomes poisonous.","excerpt":"Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It stays forever.","B":"It turns into plastic.","C":"It decomposes or rots.","D":"It becomes poisonous."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text defines biodegradable as things that decompose or rot.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of what they threw out was biodegradable. That means it decomposed, or rotted."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q041","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To make the food taste better. B. To create more trash. C. To wrap their food naturally. D. To sell to tourists.","excerpt":"They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To make the food taste better.","B":"To create more trash.","C":"To wrap their food naturally.","D":"To sell to tourists."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains they used natural items as wrappings and plates.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They used banana leaves, coconut shells, and other natural items as wrappings and plates for their food."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q042","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. It was very expensive. B. It was easy to break. C. It was durable and lightweight. D. It was good for the earth.","excerpt":"Plastic, in particular, proved hard to resist. It\u0027s durable, lightweight, and waterproof.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"It was very expensive.","B":"It was easy to break.","C":"It was durable and lightweight.","D":"It was good for the earth."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists durable, lightweight, and waterproof as reasons plastic was hard to resist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Plastic, in particular, proved hard to resist. It\u0027s durable, lightweight, and waterproof."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q043","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. A type of plastic bag B. Unrefined liquid petroleum C. A kind of banana leaf D. Clean water","excerpt":"Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"A type of plastic bag","B":"Unrefined liquid petroleum","C":"A kind of banana leaf","D":"Clean water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The definition in the text states that crude oil is unrefined liquid petroleum.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Scientists take the chemicals from crude oil found deep inside the ground."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q044","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. By picking it from trees. B. By changing chemicals from crude oil. C. By recycling old bags. D. By mixing water and sand.","excerpt":"Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"By picking it from trees.","B":"By changing chemicals from crude oil.","C":"By recycling old bags.","D":"By mixing water and sand."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that scientists change chemicals from crude oil to make plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Then they change the chemicals through reactions with other chemicals. That\u0027s how they make polyurethane and other types of plastic."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q045","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It is too expensive. B. Nature cannot break it down easily. C. It is too heavy to carry. D. It melts in the rain.","excerpt":"The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It is too expensive.","B":"Nature cannot break it down easily.","C":"It is too heavy to carry.","D":"It melts in the rain."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break down plastic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The problem is that all plastics are different from anything that occurs in nature. That means nature doesn\u0027t have an easy way to break them down."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q046","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A few days. B. One year. C. Hundreds or thousands of years. D. It happens instantly.","excerpt":"It can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade. And in some cases, it never does.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A few days.","B":"One year.","C":"Hundreds or thousands of years.","D":"It happens instantly."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states it can take hundreds or thousands of years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It can take hundreds or thousands of years for plastic to biodegrade. And in some cases, it never does."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q047","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. Pellets are melted. B. Film is cut into bags. C. Polyurethane is formed into pellets. D. The bags are sold.","excerpt":"To make plastic bags, polyurethane is formed into pellets. Then the pellets are melted into a thin film.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"Pellets are melted.","B":"Film is cut into bags.","C":"Polyurethane is formed into pellets.","D":"The bags are sold."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The process describes forming pellets first, then melting them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: To make plastic bags, polyurethane is formed into pellets. Then the pellets are melted into a thin film."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q048","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Throwaway B. Reusable C. Single-use D. Plastic","excerpt":"It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Throwaway","B":"Reusable","C":"Single-use","D":"Plastic"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Disposable\" means designed to be thrown away, so \"reusable\" is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It came in the form of disposable plastic containers, plastic bags, and other nonbiodegradable products."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q049","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. The island is very large. B. The island is small. C. There are no roads. D. People do not eat food.","excerpt":"One reason is that Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"The island is very large.","B":"The island is small.","C":"There are no roads.","D":"People do not eat food."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that because Bali is a small island, trash can pile up quickly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: One reason is that Bali is a small island. At a little more than 2,000 square miles, it\u0027s about the size of the state of Delaware."},{"item_id":"g4-u5-w5-trashing-paradise-std-q050","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. Both break down quickly. B. The leaf breaks down; the plastic does not. C. The plastic breaks down; the leaf does not. D. Both last forever.","excerpt":"When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down... A dropped plastic container won\u0027t.","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"Both break down quickly.","B":"The leaf breaks down; the plastic does not.","C":"The plastic breaks down; the leaf does not.","D":"Both last forever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts the banana leaf, which breaks down, with plastic, which does not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When people carried food in banana leaves, this was fine. A dropped banana leaf soon breaks down... A dropped plastic container won\u0027t."}]}}]};const target=window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA||{selections:[]};const existingIds=new Set((target.selections||[]).map((selection)=>selection.selection_id));unit5Selections.selections.forEach((selection)=>{if(!existingIds.has(selection.selection_id)){target.selections.push(selection);}});window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA=target;})();
